<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUKE-RESEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., CITING SAFETY, SUSPENDS HUMAN RESEARCH AT DUKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page) (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government has suspended all federally financed
medical research on humans at the Duke University Medical Center
after determining that the center could not adequately guarantee
the safety of the subjects, a federal official said on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Gary B. Ellis, heads the Office for Protection
From Research Risks, whose inspectors found on repeated visits to
Duke that there were unacceptable lapses in procedures and
record-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said on Tuesday night that he and his agency colleagues
had been surprised at the center's slowness in moving to correct
the problems and that he had sent a letter to the medical center
conveying the agency's decision _ one that could cost the center in
Durham, N.C., some $175 million in federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   No research subjects have been made ill or harmed in any way,
the medical center said on Tuesday, characterizing the deficiencies
as housekeeping problems. Ellis conceded that no one had been
harmed, but he said there was nothing trivial about the problems
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``In medicine, all doctors know that if something isn't
documented in the medical records, it wasn't done,'' Ellis said.
``That's a good standard for medical research as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems cited by the agency in its letter include the
failure of a supervisory committee at the medical center to keep
track of human studies after they began _ the only way to make sure
the subjects are not unexpectedly harmed by the research _ and
failure to make sure that protections for children were in force,
as required by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's action against the prestigious Duke center, only
the fourth such move by the government in nearly a decade and
apparently the most significant in terms of the money at stake, was
reported in Wednesday's editions of The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper quoted Ralph Snyderman, Duke's chancellor for
health affairs, as saying, ``We're absolutely going to make certain
that anyone in a research protocol is going to be fully
protected.'' He and other Duke officials said they would do their
utmost to see that the shortcomings detected by the government were
corrected.
</P>
<P>
   People involved in the experiments run the gamut from the
desperately ill whose sickness does not respond to treatment to the
robustly healthy who take part out of a sense of altruism or
perhaps to aid an ailing relative, Ellis said in an interview on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Office for Protection From Research Risks is part of the
National Institutes of Health, which in turn is part of the
Department of Health and Human Services. The action against Duke
follows a similar one against a Los Angeles veterans' hospital in
March. Ellis said other disciplinary actions had been taken against
a Chicago hospital in 1998 and a Massachusetts eye-and-ear
treatment center in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said his agency's dissatisfaction with the Duke center
began with a random visit in December. Subsequent visits and
several exchanges of letters did not produce the expected
corrections, Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected the faults would be swiftly and sufficiently
corrected,'' he said. ``We were wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the failings dealt with the center's Institutional
Review Board, which reviews all proposed human research to insure
that it is appropriate, scientifically and ethically, The Post
reported, adding that it was sometimes difficult to tell from
records whether a quorum was present for meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
