<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-BRANAM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SACRIFICE FLY, BULLPEN SAVE CSUN IN 12
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ With this kind of opportunity, Jason Gorman
wasn't going to wait for another chance. He was going to swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is get the right pitch and execute,''
Gorman said after knocking in the winning run with a 12th-inning
sacrifice fly to give the Cal State Northridge baseball team a 6-5
victory over UC Santa Barbara Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Gorman's high fly ball to right field, which he hit on the first
pitch he got from Gauchos reliever Chris Quiroz, was deep enough to
score Michael Bumstead and give the Matadors (27-28) their second
consecutive extra-inning win at home.
</P>
<P>
   Gorman, a freshman from Palmdale High who started at third base,
was the right Matador to come to the plate in the 12th with the
bases loaded and one out; he had three hits in his first five
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN coach Mike Batesole said Gorman needed to swing at any high
fastball Quiroz offered. Gorman just happened to get it on the
first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is if you get one up, you have to do something with
it,'' Batesole said. ``(Gorman) did something with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quiroz (2-3) had only allowed one hit in four innings before
facing Gorman _ and that was J.T. Stott's infield single in the
previous at-bat. CSUN also received quality relief pitching from
Mike Frick, who gave up one run in 31/3 innings, Jose Vasquez, who
threw 21/3 shutout innings and Darryl Grant, who shut out UCSB over
the last 11/3 innings to get his first victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who started in left field, also hit a three-run homer in
the sixth to give the Matadors a 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we expected of (Grant) all along,'' Batesole said.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN closes its season at 2:30 p.m. today at home against Loyola
Marymount. The Matadors have won their last five games at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are taking a lot of pride in their work,'' Batesole
said. ``We played the full 12 (innings).''
</P>
<P>
   UCSB right fielder Brad Wright, who played at Agoura High and
Crespi, entered the game with a .390 batting average and went 1 for
6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
