<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0005 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3440 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WOLVES-SPURS-HNS &LR;      05-12 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLVES-SPURS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ Minnesota forward Kevin Garnett thought he let his
team down Sunday when he failed to score in the final 21 minutes of
the Timberwolves' Game 1 loss to the San Antonio Spurs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He wasn't about to let that happen twice. Garnett scored 10 of
his 23 points in the fourth quarter to help the Timberwolves hold
off a San Antonio comeback and defeat the Spurs 80-71 on Tuesday
night in front of a shocked crowd of 22,494 at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   It evens the best-of-five NBA opening-round series at a game
each as the teams travel to Minneapolis for Game 3 on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew everybody had given up on us,'' Garnett said. ``People
were saying sweep, and that was like a spit in the face to us.
We're competitors, and we can play, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Garnett made sure the Wolves stayed in front down the stretch,
but the death blow came from guard Anthony Peeler.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota led 74-67 with 1:20 to go when forward Joe Smith had
the ball in the low post as time was running out on the shot clock.
Smith was double-teamed, so he tossed the ball outside to Peeler,
who was 30 feet from the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler shot an off-balance fadeaway that went in with one second
on the shot clock, giving the Wolves a 77-67 lead and putting the
game out of reach for the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves are 3-3 against San Antonio this season. The
victory ended an 11-game road losing streak for Minnesota and
stopped a 15-game home winning streak for the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those games that was meant to be for us,'' said
Minnesota coach Flip Saunders. ``Now we have a series. We are
playing the best team in the NBA, but now we have home-court
advantage. I told our guys this was a breakthrough game for us and
a character-builder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wolves surprised San Antonio by winning the rebounding
46-40, including 19 offensive boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnesota came out and busted their butts and took the game
from us,'' said San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich. ``That was the
main reason for the outcome. It's pretty obvious that's what
happened when they have 19 offensive rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Garnett had 12 rebounds, Smith added 10 (including six
offensive), and center Dean Garrett had nine (five offensive).
</P>
<P>
   ``We started a bigger lineup tonight, and we wanted to crash the
boards,'' Garnett said. ``It was just a matter of who wanted it
more. The difference tonight was that we stayed aggressive for 48
minutes and we matched their intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota made a lineup change from Game 1 and started Garrett,
which proved wise. Garrett did an outstanding job defensively on
San Antonio center David Robinson, who took only six shots and
ended the game with 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring eight points in the first quarter, Robinson did
not make another shot until the last minute of the game after the
outcome had been decided. But Popovich placed some of the blame for
that on the poor outside shooting of the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make perimeter shots or our big men are going to
get double-teamed,'' Popovich said. ``Tonight we were pretty poor
from the perimeter when the ball was kicked outside.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio missed all eight 3-point shots it attempted. Tim
Duncan led the team with 18 points but failed to score in the
second and third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs led 21-19 at the end of the first quarter, thanks
mainly to 14 points inside from Duncan and Robinson. San Antonio
had 16 points in the lane in the first quarter; the Timberwolves
had two.
</P>
<P>
   But things changed dramatically in the second quarter when
neither Robinson nor Duncan scored and Minnesota held the Spurs to
a 10-point quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs led 23-20 before the Wolves had a 14-1 spurt to take a
34-24 lead after a jumper at the top of the key by Garnett.
Minnesota led 37-31 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-foot bank shot by Terrell Brandon, who had 18 points
and nine assists, gave Minnesota its biggest lead at 42-31 with
10:56 to go in the third quarter. The Wolves held a 60-51 lead
entering the final period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
