<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3448 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOGART-BOMB-BEIJING-7     05-12 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOGART-BOMB-BEIJING-725&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OF ALL THE EMBASSIES IN ALL THE CITIES...WE HAD TO HIT THAT ONE'  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This pithy ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE NEEDING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
CAN STAND IN 725 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 950 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By RUPERT CORNWELL  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To misquote Humphrey Bogart: ``Of all the embassies in all the
cities in all the world, we had to hit that one'' _ the mission in
Belgrade of China, the country, after Russia, whose consent is most
vital if a United Nations resolution imposing a Kosovo settlement
is to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   But, remarkably, the signs last night were that the diplomatic
destruction wrought by the misdirected bomb might be less
devastating than initially feared.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, on both sides of the Atlantic a damage limitation
exercise was in full swing, even as the air strikes continued
during the weekend, primarily against communications targets.
</P>
<P>
   As British Prime Minister Tony Blair sent a written apology to
Beijing for NATO's bombing blunder, diplomats labored to ensure
that the outline agreement for a settlement secured last week by
the foreign ministers of the leading Western powers and Russia was
not imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   The most hopeful note, perhaps, lay in what the Chinese
authorities did not say. For all their country's outrage at a ``war
crime'' in which at least three people died, Vice President Hu
Jintao insisted that China would maintain its policy of opening to
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   Above all he gave no hint whatsoever that China was
contemplating direct diplomatic retaliation related to Kosovo _ the
nightmare scenario which must have flashed across the minds of a
thousand Western officials when they first heard the calamitously
embarrassing news of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   All along it had been assumed that notwithstanding its right of
veto in the Security Council, Beijing had no desire to become
directly embroiled in a crisis 6,000 miles away, in which it had no
direct stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the deal's good enough for the Russians, it'll be good
enough for the Chinese,'' was the typical prediction of one NATO
official last week, after the outline plan agreed in Germany by the
G-8.
</P>
<P>
   But the embassy bombing threatened to change that calculation _
and indeed still might, if the measured official reaction in
Beijing fails to keep demonstrations against American and British
missions under control.
</P>
<P>
   If so, then the Chinese leadership might have no choice but to
be obstructive in the U.N. over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The hope however is that once the indignation subsides, the
Chinese will act according to their interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership wants a decent relationship with the U.S.,''
one diplomat said, ``not least because China badly wants to join
the World Trade Organization, something for which Washington's
support is essential.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally reassuring, Russia's commitment to the G-8 deal does not
seem to have been soured by the bombing, despite a predictably
scathing condemnation from Moscow, and the abrupt cancellation by
Igor Ivanov, the foreign minister, of a weekend trip to Britain for
talks with the Foreign Secretary Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
   After talks in Germany with Chancellor Gerhard Schroder on
Saturday, Moscow's envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin spoke by phone with
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The next step will be a meeting with Strobe Talbott, the U.S.
deputy secretary of state, in Moscow Tuesday, after which
Chernomyrdin said he would be taking ``concrete proposals'' to the
Yugoslav leader before the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``New, very important, developments connected to the Balkan
settlement'' had emerged, he cryptically declared on his return to
Moscow Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   All of which suggests that a draft U.N. resolution could still
be forthcoming within a fortnight, as diplomats had hoped before
the Chinese embassy uproar.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N.'s newly appointed envoy, the former Swedish Prime
Minister Carl Bildt, met Chernomyrdin in Germany. Sunday night he
met the French President Jacques Chirac in Paris, before holding
talks Monday in London with Cook.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the attempts to portray this activity as ``business
as usual,'' the incident will surely affect the dynamics of the
search for an agreed U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
   However fleetingly, President Milosevic's hand has been
strengthened. Public support in the West for the bombing campaign
may falter, and the standing of the Russians has been indirectly
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   These considerations may make it harder still to come up with a
formula which satisfies NATO, above all on the terms for a halt in
the bombing and on the makeup of the international force to enter
Kosovo to keep the peace and allow more than 700,000 refugees to
return home. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 725. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   For the alliance, the ``effective international civil and
security presences'' foreseen for Kosovo in the G-8 statement must
involve a well-armed force, with a NATO ``core'' and under NATO
command _ even though it may formally be under a U.N. aegis and
contain a substantial Russian contingent.
</P>
<P>
   That was spelled out again Sunday by Cook, who insisted U.S. and
British troops had to take part if the force was to be a credible
protector for the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Most distasteful for the allies, and above all for Britain, the
most hawkish of them, this weekend's developments make it more
likely that in some form or other NATO will at the end of the day
be obliged to negotiate with Milosevic, a man whom London openly
brands a war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Sunday, the Foreign Secretary insisted NATO's
objectives were non-negotiable.
</P>
<P>
   ```We are willing to reach a settlement tomorrow provided
Milosevic accepts those objectives...but this is not a negotiation,
and we will not make a compromise with him.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Cook made equally clear, a full-scale ground war is not in
the cards _ nor is any invasion other than a mopping-up operation
against a Serb resistance battered by months of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether, after the Chinese embassy debacle,
Western public opinion is ready to wait that long. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 950-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to
reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
