<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3449 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-FLOGS-ITSELF-725     05-12 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-FLOGS-ITSELF-725&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ENEMY WITHIN: NATO TURNS TO SELF-CRITICISM  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This insightful ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE NEEDING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
CAN STAND IN 725 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,050.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By STEPHEN CASTLE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ The question was serious, but the answer came back
with a full, shoulder-heaving laugh.
</P>
<P>
   No, replied the senior NATO diplomat, the alliance had not made
contact with dissident elements in Belgrade: ``Quite frankly,'' he
said, ``we are not that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost seven weeks into the bombing campaign a sudden outburst
of frankness has struck NATO's headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to avoid the self-criticism last week when the
organization's most senior military official, General Klaus
Naumann, sparked a debate about its frailties in an unusually blunt
farewell press conference.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, he said, had failed in its initial conflict aims,
squandered its chances of surprising the Yugoslav army and needed
``to find a way to reconcile the conditions of a coalition war with
the principles of military operations.''
</P>
<P>
   This profound soul-searching is, however, only half the picture.
NATO's top brass have not just admitted their weaknesses, but have
begun to address them.
</P>
<P>
   Caught up in an unexpectedly protracted air campaign, the
alliance's lethargic military bureaucracy has had to adapt to
survive. And NATO has done so by expanding its responsibilities,
beefing up its diplomacy and aiming to forge a new, transnational
political entity.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that, in the aftermath of the Cold War, the
alliance had been searching for a role and, ahead of last month's
Washington summit, the organization was busy debating its mission
statement, or ``strategic concept.''
</P>
<P>
   As one NATO diplomat put it: ``Suddenly Kosovo appears and
presents NATO with a hothouse flower. Theories had been going
around about what will be required in the Europe in the coming
century _ and then it presents itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Improvisation has proved more successful than theory. NATO's
immediate decision to assume humanitarian work was, in the words of
one senior diplomat, ``extraordinarily successful in responding
quickly to a situation which was overwhelming the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees and the other agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   But outside the public gaze, NATO embarked on an escalation of
diplomacy and a politicization which had not been foreseen before
the Kosovo campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   The central task was to keep the alliance together. Through
astute stewardship and skillful avoidance of the most divisive
issues, the 19 member states have stayed reasonably united _
despite the fact that in one of their number _ Greece _ 96 percent
of the population oppose the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If diplomacy has been active within the alliance, it has
extended well beyond it too. Javier Solana, NATO's secretary
general, was the first to hold high-profile meetings with
politicians from countries neighboring Yugoslavia, cajoling
Albania, Bulgaria and Romania into handing over their airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Since then there have been visits to the region from British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and
U.S. General Wesley Clark, the Supreme Allied Commander in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there are even some worries that Yugoslavia's neighbors
are experiencing ``VIP fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor has NATO been afraid to improvise on the diplomatic side,
particularly in the case of Macedonia. As one senior diplomat put
it: ``The Macedonian government has been very uncomfortable about
the volume of refugees it was receiving and worried about the
ethnic balance in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some worry about the presence of NATO troops in
Macedonia, but also a feeling that the country was not getting its
payoff in terms of cash, security guarantees and pledges on NATO
and EU membership.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the solution NATO installed its own representative in
Skopje, Hans Eiff, Bonn's former ambassador to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   On the global stage NATO has acted as a clearinghouse for
international efforts. Again the process has been pragmatic, with
the alliance's key member states applying pressure through the
different bodies to which they are affiliated.
</P>
<P>
   The oil embargo against Yugoslavia, for example, was initiated
by the European Union, thanks to British, French and Dutch
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to bind the Russians and the United Nations to a peace
proposal compatible with NATO's five conditions was brokered with
German help through the Group of Eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders are pursuing these plans through a variety of
forums,'' said one official, ``but the ideas are coming out of
NATO.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 725. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   All of this is part of a wider awakening. NATO was always a
marriage of military and political structures, but the civilian
side was muted during the Cold War because the objectives were
consensual ones. The case for the air bombardment has taken much
more selling.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently the media war has been given a new priority,
boosted by the influx of a new unit, equipping the alliance with
all the expertise now available to modern political parties when
they fight elections.
</P>
<P>
   A team of around seven full-time press officers and 23
back-office and technical staff has been augmented by another 30
personnel, linking the civilian and military machines and
coordinating with the important NATO capitals.
</P>
<P>
   And the pursuit of NATO's ``message'' has been taken to new
rhetorical heights. In the process the familiar separation in which
the military handle the weaponry and the politicians, who deploy
the rhetoric, has all but disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, this recent condemnation of Serbian President
Slobodan Milosevic: ``Those of us who have grown up in liberal
democracies have had a hard time truly appreciating what is
happening right now in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a grand combination of terror and ethnic cleansing on a
vast scale, it's being perpetrated largely against defenseless
civilians by the last vestige of a Communist dictatorship in
Europe. Man does not do this to his fellow man.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement was delivered not by a political leader but by
General Clark.
</P>
<P>
   While the military results in Kosovo may have been
disappointing, NATO as an organization has undoubtedly been
energized. The downside to this expanded new role is that the
stakes have been raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo has,'' said one diplomat last week, ``very much defined
the new NATO and this is why everyone is determined to see it
through. If this is what we say we are all about, and then we don't
do it, we will have proven our ineffectiveness.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,050-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to
reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
