<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3463 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-AZR &LR;      05-12 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA RELATIVES PREPARE FOR ARRIVAL OF REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS FISCUS AND CAROL SOWERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vjollca Berisha's mind sometimes flashes to her missing
brother-in-law and uncle in Kosovo. They lived just three miles
from a village that was burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   She hears of people being burned and worries, ``Maybe that might
have been them.''
</P>
<P>
   Berisha has filed papers so that 33 of her relatives _ &UR; including
her mother and three sisters, and her husband's parents and four
brothers _ can come to the Phoenix area and escape the tragedy that
is Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Berisha, an Albanian, doesn't know how many may come, or when
they will arrive. All she can do is imagine the day when their long
journey to freedom brings them to Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to touch them, hug them, just kind of look at
them to make sure they are alive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Kosovo refugees may be headed for the Phoenix area,
and at least 84 have local relatives, who are cleaning out spare
bedrooms and planning favorite meals.
</P>
<P>
   Berisha said that at first her family didn't want to leave for
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept saying, `We don't want to go anywhere.' We said,
`Just consider yourself a guest and you can go back when things get
better.' I think they're looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Berisha, who's over 40. She hasn't seen some relatives in
years, and wonders what they look like, how tall they are.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to explain the emotion, she says, the feeling of
relatives waiting to see whether their loved ones will be among
those brought to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what they went through before they got to Macedonia.
We kept in touch very closely by phone,'' she said, though they
once lost contact for about 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   There's celebration in knowing some relatives are alive, &UR; but
others have been missing since March.
</P>
<P>
   Even those that make the trip face many hurdles, from learning a
language to dealing with ``the horrible things they saw,'' Berisha
said.
</P>
<P>
   For Arben Rizvanolli, 35, an Albanian who has lived in Phoenix
for 12 years, it's the rumors and vague news reports coming out of
Kosovo that tear at his heart.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, he read on the Internet about a battle between the
Kosovo Liberation Army and the Serbs, and he wonders about the fate
of his missing 40-year-old brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he got killed,'' Rizvanolli said. ``Maybe he has joined
the KLA.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rizvanolli knows the plight of another brother, a cousin and
the man's wife and young children.
</P>
<P>
   In the earliest days of the war, they escaped Pristina, the
capital of Kosovo, with only the clothes on their backs and made it
to a home in Macedonia that they share with about 40 people.
</P>
<P>
   Rizvanolli says he expects them to be among the refugees headed
for the Phoenix area. For a time, they may all crowd into the
two-bedroom apartment Rizvanolli shares with his wife, Linda, son
and parents. Resettlement groups also have plans to temporarily
place refugees in apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just lucky they got out,'' Linda said of her
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   She and her mother-in-law plan to welcome three relatives with a
menu of rice and hamburger rolled up in cabbage and a
``checkerboard'' cake for dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Zuriya Amedovski, 44, of Phoenix, is cleaning out a bedroom and
planning to buy a bed for her cousin and the woman's two sons _
ages 13 and 16 _ who have been living in a Macedonian refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   She has not seen the cousin since she left Macedonia 18 years
ago, and knows little about what happened to them when the war
started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know her husband was killed by the Serbs,'' she said. ``But
she will tell me everything when she gets here.''
</P>
<P>
   Eager to introduce her family to freedom, she said: ``I will
teach them English. I will do everything they need and take them
everywhere they need to go. It is terrible what is happening over
there. It is the same like Hitler did.''
</P>
<P>
   While relatives are preparing for the refugees, so are
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   A Brownie troop is collecting toys. Businesses are donating new
clothes and kits of emergency supplies or hygiene products. Others
are offering jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian Cultural Center said Scottsdale City Council
representatives called and said the council will try to provide
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural center said there will be a meeting Sunday at 9:30
a.m. in Cactus Park, near Cactus Road and 35th Avenue. Anyone is
welcome to donate items or to hear about what help is needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mary Barolli of the cultural center said another gathering is
planned soon: a large picnic in the park after the refugees arrive
to welcome them to town. &QL; 
Chris Fiscus can be reached at (602) 444-7942 or at
chris.fiscus(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Carol Sowers can be reached at (602) 444-7482 or at
carol.sowers(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
