<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WNBA-SEATTLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE OFFERING INCENTIVES TO LAND WNBA TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY AND STEVEN GOLDSMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When the American Basketball League abruptly shut down
last December, women's basketball fans in Seattle had one glimmer
of hope: The WNBA might expand its league here.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, city officials confirmed that hope is alive _ with
conditions attached.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Paul Schell has sent a letter to The Ackerley Group,
owners of the Seattle SuperSonics National Basketball Association
team, confirming the city is willing to sweeten the KeyArena lease
to minimize start-up costs for a new women's pro team.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if The Ackerley Group thinks the city is
offering enough. The Sonics owners did not respond to requests for
comment on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not heard that we can pop the cork yet,'' said Seattle
Center Director Virginia Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's National Basketball Association is to announce four
expansion teams for the 2000 season before June 10, the start date
of the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA has supported Seattle's interest in obtaining a WNBA
franchise _ with the Sonics apparently high on the list for a new
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the league is very interested in Seattle,'' Anderson
said. ``We have a good building for basketball, and a good city for
supporting women's basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Schell sent The Ackerley Group a letter of support on Tuesday to
demonstrate the city's enthusiasm to the NBA, which controls the
women's league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have the support of my colleagues on the City Council
in saying that the city welcomes the opportunity to be partners
with (the Sonics' marketing group) Full House in bringing the WNBA
to Seattle,'' Schell wrote.
</P>
<P>
   To sweeten the deal, Schell offered:
</P>
<P>
   - Reduced rent for all WNBA home dates to actual operating costs
plus $2,500, about a tenth of that paid by the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   - Giving all ticket and concession revenue to Full House.
</P>
<P>
   - Granting priority scheduling to the women's team during its
summer season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the city would keep all parking and admission tax
revenue from WNBA games and control staffing.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Schell's letter gives the Sonics the green light to
tell WNBA officials that Seattle is ready for an expansion
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The city has long supported women's basketball, first at the
University of Washington and later with the American Basketball
League's pro team, the Reign. The Reign averaged about 3,900 fans
per game, with a record crowd of 7,358. The Sonics, by comparison,
commonly draw more than 18,000.
</P>
<P>
   However, while the city and the Sonics appear ready to partner
up for the new sports enterprise, city officials are concerned The
Ackerley Group is seeking something far more sweeping. All but four
of the 12 WNBA franchises have complete control of their arenas.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics owners have been negotiating, so far without success,
for complete year-round control of KeyArena in exchange for a
guaranteed return to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Full House has been jockeying for months to take control of
KeyArena, sources say, and to scrap the 5-year-old deal between the
team and the city made after Sonics owner Barry Ackerley lost his
bid to build a privately owned arena south of the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerley instead made a deal that renovated the deteriorated
Seattle Center Coliseum. To do it, the city sold $74 million in
bonds. Ackerley kicked in $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the city gets to keep most of the revenue, which so
far has covered the $7.5 million annual debt without a tax
increase. However, the NBA lockout this winter wiped out the city's
modest profit.
</P>
<P>
   If Ackerley is saying the city could have ``peace of mind'' in
handing over KeyArena in exchange for a guaranteed annual return,
city officials aren't buying it. City Councilwoman Tina Podlodowski
on Tuesday said any move in that direction would be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The City Council is very commited to bringing the WNBA,'' she
said. ``But if there are any other (conditions), we need to know
about them now.''
</P>
<P>
   Podlodowski said Full House has not formally requested full
control of KeyArena as a stipulation to start a WNBA franchise.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``in the past, what they have requested is the ability
to book and manage KeyArena for 365 days a year,'' Podlodowski
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the city ``did not build KeyArena for one tenant,'' and
added that the city has an interest in controlling the arena to
allow ``diversity in events'' there.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA spokesman Mark Pray said Tuesday that league officials have
not given any indication about where the new franchises will go. He
said at least 12 NBA teams have expressed interest in operating a
WNBA franchise, the Sonics among those.
</P>
</TEXT>
