<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-RIOTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TICKET BUYERS: FORCE IS WITH YOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ The force will be with Star Wars fans waiting
in line today to get the first tickets to ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _
The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burbank police force, that is. For the past week, police
have been working with the local AMC Theaters to cope with what is
expected to be a crush of fans lining up at ticket offices.
Although the movie does not open until May 19, tickets will go on
sale at noon today at theaters throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Department and Los Angeles County
Sheriff's Department have left the planning up to individual police
stations and have no special plans to cope with the lines, other
than to monitor them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll respond to incidents as they occur,'' said Sgt. Robert
Courtland of the LAPD's West Valley Division.
</P>
<P>
   In Canyon Country, a suburb north of Los Angeles, Edwards Cinema
officials plan to provide their own security to ensure crowds
expected to line up for the first screenings don't get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   In Burbank, AMC will have a security guard at each of its ticket
sale locations and extra parking attendants on hand to handle the
potential crowds. Burbank police will supplement their normal
patrols in the downtown area to help out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's obviously going to be a big rush at noon,'' said Capt.
Gordon Bowers of the department's Special Operations Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be ticketing and towing to keep things as orderly as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers in Burbank's Traffic Bureau have been asked not to take
any time off during the next week and a half so a full complement
of officers will be available to handle any problems in the
downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Public Works Department will be at the ready to close
down Palm Avenue to traffic if the crowds get too thick for
sidewalks in downtown Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers said the city worked out a plan with AMC because it will
be selling tickets at two of its three downtown locations, the AMC
14 on Palm Avenue and the AMC 6 on First Street. Because the
theaters are located in the city's crowded downtown area, the lines
are expected to stretch well beyond the property owned by the
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers said he is relieved that tickets are being sold in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way they are not struggling to get in to see the movie,
they're just struggling to get a ticket,'' Bowers said.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Brian Humphrey, a spokesman for the city Fire
Department, said stations have been alerted and are ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're well prepared for it. We're used to these kinds of
things,'' Humphrey said. ``Our people are ready to go as this
reaches its zenith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be concerned if there was a sudden change in the weather
with a sudden spike to over 90 degrees where people could become
ill or pass out.''
</P>
<P>
   In Canyon Country, Sheriff's Department officials are prepared
for the crowds that might gather at the new Edwards Cinemas, said
Sgt. Joe Efflandt of the Santa Clarita Valley station. The theater
chain will foot the bill for crowd control, either by hiring
private security guards or contracting with the Sheriff's
Department, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tieger, managing director at the AMC Theaters in Burbank,
said fans will be able to buy 12 tickets at once if they stand in
line and nine tickets at a time if they get through on a phone to a
movie ticket service.
</P>
<P>
   He expects that AMC will be selling tickets at least for the
first several days of the release of the movie. Decisions have not
yet been made about how far in advance the tickets can be sold and
many details were left unsettled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The first showings at the AMC theaters in Burbank will start at
12:01 a.m. May 19.
</P>
<P>
   Tieger said he is excited about the advance ticket sale today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most highly anticipated film of all time. This is
what we live for,'' Tieger said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Adamson, a spokesman for AMC, said the company's theaters
have been encouraged to sell concession stand items to those in
line and to even hire jugglers and mimes to entertain the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Burbank, ``Phantom Menace'' tickets will be available at
other AMC sites including the Promenade 16 in Woodland Hills, and
AMC theaters in Covina and Puente Hills. On May 19, the movie will
be shown on five screens at the Burbank sites and on five screens
at other AMC locations.
</P>
<P>
   Some theater chains Tuesday were still working out the details
for ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Brower, a spokeswoman for the Edwards chain, said as of
Tuesday that Edwards would be selling advance tickets only for the
first early morning shows May 19 but that the situation could
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' tickets will be on sale at several area
Edwards locations including Calabasas, Camarillo, Canyon Country
and Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   The Mann Theater chain will be selling advance tickets at the
following sites: the Chinese in Hollywood, the Village in Westwood,
the Mann 9 Granada Hills, the Mann 9 Valley West in Tarzana, the
Plant 16 in Van Nuys, Mann 8 in Agoura Hills, the Janss Marketplace
in Thousand Oaks, Mann 6 in Simi Valley and the Glendale Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman Fisher, a spokesman for Loews Complex Entertainment,
said the company's 18-screen theater at Universal Studios does not
expect a crowd control problem. Fisher expects many people will buy
their tickets through Moviefone.
</P>
<P>
   As for crowd control, there is already a Sheriff's Department
substation on the lot and Loews and Universal have plenty of
security in place. Unlike the theaters in Burbank, there is plenty
of room at Universal for people to wait in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can line up as many people as we want and not impede any
traffic flow or commerce,'' Fisher said. ``Obviously we're excited
by it. This is a phenomenon that is unequaled.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
