A3480 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-MARINERS-REDSOX-BOS     05-12 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DROP THE BALL
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-MARINERS-REDSOX-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By GORDON EDES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Headaches replaced history as the operative principle at Fenway
Park Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, when the Red Sox' five-game winning streak
disappeared as ingloriously as the fan who took a Seattle home run
off the coconut in the Mariners' 8-5 win before an irritated
gathering of 24,416.
</P>
<P>
   Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, in a muted encore to his
three-homer, two-grand slam, 10-RBI performance the night before,
came to bat four times with runners on base but came away with a
mere mortal's run-scoring double off Mariners winner Jamie Moyer
and a walk in five plate appearances. The hit extended his hitting
streak to 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight-reel material Tuesday night was the header by the
spectator, who was hardly culpable for the Sox loss compared to the
six Boston pitchers who combined to give up 14 hits and 10 walks
while throwing an absurd 204 pitches. Nonetheless, he did no favors
for Tim Wakefield, whose record dropped to 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield was in a 1-1 game until Tom Lampkin's fourth-inning
flyball down the right-field line caromed off a noggin in the
shadow of Pesky's Pole instead of coming to rest in the glove of
Sox outfielder Darren Lewis, who was preparing to make the catch.
</P>
<P>
   It was a classic case of knuckleball meeting knucklehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bead on it,'' Lewis said. ``I hit my ribs on the
fence, which dropped me pretty good, so I was just trying to get my
bearings. I could have sworn I had it, and somebody told me I could
have caught it if that guy hadn't jumped in front of me at the last
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows, he could have been a Mariners fan. Fans come out
there looking for souvenirs. You see it happen all the time. Just
the way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin's home run was one of three struck by the Mariners, who
lead the majors with 62 homers and hardly needed the audience
participation. But the fan, who was escorted from the premises
after trying to retrieve the ball that outfielder Damon Buford had
tossed to another fan, was not the last party to act generously
toward the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox bullpen did its part, too, as Rheal Cormier made a
damaging error in a four-run Mariner sixth that broke a 2-all tie
and Jim Corsi, whose sinker has been less bowling ball than
balloon, was touched in the seventh for two more runs, including a
home run by Butch Huskey that cleared the Monster.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthander Cormier, who had inherited nine runners in his
previous 11 appearances and stranded all nine, entered and induced
pinch hitter Dan Wilson to bounce into a double play as a run
scored, breaking a 2-all tie.
</P>
<P>
   But Domingo Cedeno, one of seven Mariners to play shortstop in
the absence of injured All-Star Alex Rodriguez, followed with a
run-scoring double to left, and Cormier then permitted Brian
Hunter's groundball to pass uncontested through the 5-hole for an
error as another run scored.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell, whose 10th home run had given the Mariners a 1-0
lead in the first, followed with a run-scoring single to make it
5-2, and Ken Griffey beat out an infield hit against an overshifted
infield for the sixth Seattle run.
</P>
<P>
   This being the Mariners, a team that came into the game with the
worst ERA in the majors, the Sox were still alive in the eighth,
when three singles off reliever Jose Paniagua, the last an RBI hit
by pinch hitter Reggie Jefferson, made it 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox brought the tying run to the plate in the ninth against
Mariners closer Jose Mesa, after a single by John Valentin, a walk
to Nomar Garciaparra, and a two-out throwing error by Bell made it
8-5 and left runners on second and third.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Frye's bid for a base hit instead caromed off Mesa
directly to shortstop Cedeno, who threw out Frye to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, a better finisher than starter these days, left after
loading the bases with none out in the sixth on a ground-rule
double by Huskey, a walk, and a single by Russ Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good,'' Wakefield said after a yield of nine
hits and three walks in his return from a successful four-day stint
in the bullpen. ``The numbers just didn't come out in my favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the hometown crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one of those years, maybe,'' Wakefield said, ``but I'll
keep taking the ball, every five days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
