<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT &LR;      05-12 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKIES DEFEAT METS, 8-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Other than their given and proper names, and their
current occupations, Robert Joseph Jones of the New York Mets and
Robert Mitchell Jones of the Colorado Rockies have frighteningly
little in common.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Mets' Bobby Jones had 63 major league victories
compared to only eight for his counterpart going into this unusual
matchup of starting pitchers _ the first this century in which both
starters shared the same first and last names _ it was the Mets'
right-hander who had trouble keeping up with the other Jones on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Helton blasted a pair of two-run home runs off the Mets'
Jones, who tied his career high in earned runs allowed with eight,
as the Mets dropped their third straight game and sixth in the last
seven with an 8-5 loss to the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for two pitches, it could have been a different game,''
Jones said of the hanging fastballs that Helton knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive game, a Mets' starter has either
equaled or surpassed his career high by allowing eight earned runs.
On Sunday, Rick Reed allowed eight runs to Arizona, the most in his
career. And on Monday night here, Al Leiter was pounded for eight
runs, a career high, too.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, it was Jones' turn. Two years ago, he allowed
10 runs in a start, but only 6 earned. The only other time he had
surrendered eight earned runs was on Aug. 21, 1993, the second
start of his major league career. The setting? About a mile
southwest at Mile High Stadium, where the Rockies used to play.
</P>
<P>
   The two home runs the Mets' Jones allowed on Tuesday night were
the first two he has allowed in seven starts this season. And
Helton is now 6 for 8 versus Jones in his career. But Coors Field
has never been kind to Bobby J. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a great lineup,'' said Jones (3-1). ``And I just
don't like pitching here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not putting any blame on the ball parks,'' said Bob
Apodaca, the pitching coach. ``Where they've hit it the last few
days, we wouldn't have caught it anyway. We're just not pitching
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday evening, Jones' 7.91 earned run average at Coors
Field, which opened in 1995, was sixth-highest among active
National League visiting pitchers. But considering that Bobby M.
Jones was lugging a 7.88 era into his seventh appearance of the
season _ and first start _ the game figured to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies did not disappoint. After the Mets scored an
unearned run in the first, Helton answered with his first two-run
homer in the bottom of the inning. Mike Lansing, who had four hits
in front of Helton, scored on a third-inning Dante Bichette
groundout to make it 3-1. And then Helton blasted his second
two-run shot of the game in the fifth to give the Rockies a 5-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby M. Jones, meanwhile, made his first start this season one
to remember, allowing four hits and just two runs, 1 earned in
five-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   The start was one to remember regardless of the outcome.
According to the Elias Sports Bureau, prior to 1900, there were
three major league games _ all in the National League _ in which
same-name starting pitchers opposed each other: April 16, 1899:
John B. Taylor of Cincinnati versus John W. Taylor of Chicago. And
twice in 1876, when George H. Bradley of Boston and George W.
Bradley of St. Louis squared off in the inaugural season of the
league.
</P>
<P>
   But in this century, no pitching namesakes had started against
one another until Tuesday night. Before the series, Bobby M. Jones
had said, ``There are not a lot of similarities outside of our
name.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the two pitch in the major leagues at the same time,
they are often confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get his stuff in the mail all the time,'' Bobby M. Jones
said. ``It baffles me, when I'm with the Rockies and he's with the
Mets. He's 6-4 and I'm 6-foot. He's white and I'm black. He's
right-handed and I'm left-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   But now the two Jones' have another thing in common this season:
After Tuesday night, each has one loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
