<SLUG> BC-LITTON-AVONDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVONDALE BOARD OKS TALKS WITH LITTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shipbuilder Avondale Industries Inc. said Tuesday
its board approved talks with Litton Industries Inc. regarding the
company's $38-per-share cash offer for Avondale.
</P>
<P>
   When Woodland Hills-based Litton made its offer for the
Avondale, La.-based company last week the deal was valued at about
$503.9 million. Avondale had earlier agreed to merge with Newport
News Shipbuilding.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Avondale issued a brief statement, saying its board
decided Litton's offer ``could lead to a proposal which is superior
to the terms of (the) agreement to merge with Newport News
Shipbuilding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to engage in a discussion in order to evaluate the
proposal so I could guess you could say this is the first step''
toward a deal, said Avondale spokesman Tom Kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   No timetable for the talks has been set but executives from the
two companies will likely meet sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all anxious to enter into meaningful discussions,'' said
Litton spokesman Randy Belote. ``This allows us to move to the next
step, to enter into formal discussions . . . and answer in-depth
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same day Litton offered to buy Avondale, it made a $1.25
billion offer for Newport News. At the time, Newport News directors
said they were willing to discuss the deal with Litton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our board authorized preliminary discussions with Litton to
review the offer but that by no means means acceptance,'' Newport
News spokeswoman Jerri Dickseski said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If Litton's acquisitions are approved by federal regulators, the
company would become the nation's largest builder of military
ships. Combined, the three companies would have revenue of about
$7.4 billion and more than 58,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   A combined Litton-Avondale-Newport News would create a company
able to build a wide range of military ships, including
nuclear-powered aircraft carriers and noncombat support ships.
</P>
<P>
   It would reduce the number of major players in the market from
four to two, with General Dynamics Corp. providing competition for
Litton. Regulators sunk General Dynamics' attempt to buy Newport
News because it would have concentrated too much construction and
research and development work with one company.
</P>
<P>
   But they also approved the Newport News combination with
Avondale.
</P>
<P>
   The Litton-Avondale-Newport News merger would spread the work
more evenly across the country and to different contractors and
subcontractors, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Litton's military warship work is done at its Pascagoula,
Miss.-based Ingalls Shipbuilding.
</P>
<P>
   Newport News, based in Newport News, Va., is the only U.S. maker
of nuclear-powered aircraft carriers. Avondale manufactures
amphibious assault vehicles and other military ships.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
