<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST UNCERTAIN ABOUT RETIREMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Jerry West won't say how much longer he'll
run the Lakers, but he will say this much: He's not trading his
Lakers gear for a Knicks jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' executive vice president once again hinted Tuesday
that he's considering retirement but wouldn't specify when or how
he plans to leave the organization he's helped define for the last
three decades. But he laughed when confronted with a persistent
rumor that he'll become general manager of the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fellas, I'm not going anywhere,'' West told reporters. ``I'm
not going anywhere. I'm gonna live in Los Angeles, period. I'm not
looking for another job. . . . This has been more than just a job
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's a job that continues to take a toll on West, who turns
61 this month. This is the second straight year he's openly
contemplated retirement, though the talk subsided last summer when
he signed a four-year contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   West won't say if he plans to fulfill that contract, which
begins next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I really don't know,'' he said. ``There's times
I think I'd maybe like to take a year off. When I signed that
contract, I had every intention of finishing that. But there are
times, as I mentioned, these jobs are very wearing. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this team more than anything. I care about this team so
much that sometimes it brings me a lot of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially this season, as the Lakers have gone through a
coaching change, a major trade and the Dennis Rodman drama while
underachieving on the court. West opposed the signing of Rodman,
but Lakers owner Jerry Buss insisted on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult for me, because I didn't think he was a good
fit for us,'' West said of Rodman. ``It put a terrible burden on
Kurt (Rambis) as a coach. I do think it's an experiment that
hopefully we would try to shy away from something like that in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   West said that has not affected his relationship with Buss but
implied that he regrets not taking a stronger stand against the
Rodman move.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Buss) owns this team, and if you want to criticize him,
criticize me because maybe I wasn't in there, holding onto his leg,
like Jeff Van Gundy was holding onto Alonzo Mourning's,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his future, West said he will discuss the matter with
Buss in the offseason. But he's got at least one, 330-pound reason
to stay awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have made some promises to one player in particular here,
Shaquille O'Neal,'' he said. ``I almost feel like he's a family
member for me now, someone who I care a lot about. . . . I told him
I'd be here.''
</P>
<P>
   For how long remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as my future, I think the most important thing for me
is to have the enthusiasm that's really necessary to do this job,''
West said. ``And sometimes when the walls seem like they're kind of
closing in on you, sometimes you really question that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Options open: For his part, O'Neal is slightly more
definitive on his future here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a 97 percent chance I'm gonna be back here next
year,'' said O'Neal, who can opt out of his contract this summer,
``but I'm not even thinking about that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   As for that other 3 percent, O'Neal said, ``I wouldn't worry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
