<SLUG> BC-WARNER-JUDGMENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER BROS., D.C. WIN DAMAGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A federal judge has ordered two Los Angeles toy
makers to pay $3.6million in fines and damages for counterfeiting
consumer products based on Warner Bros. and D.C. Comics characters.
</P>
<P>
   In his judgment against Los Angeles-based CBB Group Inc., U.S.
Federal District Judge Manuel Real ordered its two principals,
Raymond Hung and Hank Tsan, to stop importing any consumer retail
goods until they can show they have ended all counterfeiting
activities. Real also found the men in contempt of court for
violating two previous orders against counterfeiting and said they
could be fined up to $10,000 per day if they fail to comply with
the latest judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Both Warner Bros. and D.C. Comics are owned by Time Warner
Entertainment. Warner Bros. Consumer Products licenses the rights
to characters from properties including Looney Tunes, Batman,
Superman, Scooby-Doo and Wizard of Oz.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at CBB Group's downtown Los Angeles facility, Hung said
he knew nothing of the judge's Thursday order. ``I don't know what
you're talking about,'' Hung said Tuesday. ``I was out of town for
about a month at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsan could not be reached Tuesday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Warner Bros. said the judgment was a victory but
added they are skeptical they will ever see the large award.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make efforts, but whether the money is actually
collectible, I don't know,'' said Gary Simon, vice president of
legal affairs at Warner Bros.' consumer products division. &UR;  &QL; 
!dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
