<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL, BRYANT SHOW ROCKETS THE DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The vigorous rubbing sound reverberating in
the upper reaches of the Forum on Tuesday was an echo of the Lakers
furiously erasing doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts about their season, about their personnel, about their
ability to work together and stay together.
</P>
<P>
   All of it was wiped out with a few quick strokes across the
blackboard, and an etched-in-slate 110-98 victory over the stunned
Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers took a 2-0 lead in the best-of-five first-round
series, which heads to Houston for Game 3 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Enchanted evening as it was, the Lakers even got an assist from
Magic Johnson, who caught guard Derek Harper as he chased down a
loose ball and stumbled out of bounds in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal scored a game-high 28 points to go with nine
rebounds and seven assists. Kobe Bryant scored 19, and Derek Fisher
provided a scoring boost for the second straight game, adding 16.
</P>
<P>
   After squandering a 13-point lead in Game 1, the Lakers could
take nothing for granted Tuesday, so their 55-40 halftime lead
seemed anything but safe in context. They had already watched the
Rockets battle back from as much as a 23-point deficit in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis hoped the Lakers had ironed out the hitches
that nearly cost them Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some mistakes. We made some mistakes that cost us 12
points or more,'' he said of Sunday's game. ``And those are
mistakes that the team knows about and shouldn't have made. That's
the way I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston probably figured the Lakers' gaudy lead could be sliced
and diced again. And indeed, the Rockets had a run at them,
short-lived though it was.
</P>
<P>
   They opened the third quarter with five straight points to cut
the lead to 55-45, but they couldn't break the 10-point barrier.
The Lakers, with 3-pointers from Kobe Bryant, Derek Fisher and Glen
Rice, blew the game open again, and less than four minutes into the
quarter, they led by 21.
</P>
<P>
   Houston never threatened the lead again.
</P>
<P>
   Defense ruled early, as the Lakers held Houston to 12 points in
the first quarter, a season-low for an opponent. But the Rockets
won the second quarter to make it semi-respectable by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The strangest part of it all was that Charles Barkley was a
nonfactor for the first 24 minutes of the game. Coming off a
25-point effort in Game 1 _ and threatening to shoot the ball 25
times if the Lakers stuck to single-coverage _ Barkley sat the
entire second quarter following a poor opening period _ two points,
missing 3 of 4 shots.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't make a dent until the third, when he scored 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Down by 23 early in the second, the Rockets reeled off a 13-3
run amid a flurry of 3-pointers from Sam Mack and Brent Price,
cutting the lead to 40-27. Price and Mack continued their 3-point
assault in an 8-2 run that cut the Lakers' lead to single digits,
44-35, for the first time since early in the first.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers closed out the half with an 11-5 run, including
five points from Rice and four from Shaquille O'Neal, to make it
55-40 at halftime. O'Neal scored 11 points in the half, and Bryant
scored 14 as the Lakers shot 55.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher wasted no time proving that Sunday's 20-point game was no
fluke. He scored a team-leading 11 points in the first quarter as
the Lakers built an unbelievable 31-12 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers held a three-point lead early in the first when
Fisher hit the first in a trio of 3-pointers in the period. That
started the Lakers on a run that never seemed to end. After Houston
pulled within four, the Lakers outscored the Rockets 20-5 in the
last seven-plus minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The win also included a rejuvenated Lakers bench. After
contributing a season-low five points Sunday, the reserves scored a
combined 29 points Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've done a good job whenever we've played well, it's
different people stepping up at different times,'' Rambis said.
``Some nights it's the bench, sometimes it's the starters,
different starters different nights. It's just the nature of our
team, different people step it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
