<HEADER>
A3507 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HN     05-12 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Astro-nomical.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the farewell season of the Astrodome, it was only fitting
Tuesday night that the Astros turned in one of the most complete
offensive outbursts in their 35 years there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we begin?'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said after
the Astros tied a team scoring record with a 19-8 victory over the
Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   When the 3-hour, 22-minute marathon was complete, the numbers
were staggering: twenty-seven runs, 32 hits, 83 at-bats, 14 doubles
and 10 pitchers used between the two clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Things turned so lopsided that the Pirates sent a catcher, Keith
Osik, to pitch the eighth inning. And like the previous four
Pittsburgh hurlers, Osik had trouble getting anybody out.
</P>
<P>
   The 19 runs by the Astros tied a team record set against the
Chicago Cubs on June 25, 1995. They also had 10 doubles in the
game, eclipsing the old team mark of eight set in 1977. Carl
Everett, who entered the fourth inning in an 0-for-13 slump, wound
up matching a career high with five RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros broke open a close game by twice batting around
during five-run outbursts in the fourth and fifth innings. By the
end of the fifth, they led 14-3.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't finished. For that matter, neither were the
Pirates. The Astros added five more runs in their final two at-bats
and watched as Pittsburgh staged a mini-rally with a pair of home
runs off righthander Sean Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of an ugly game from both teams' standpoint,''
Dierker said. ``This is not the type of game I would have
preferred, but you certainly want to be on the winning end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven Astros had at least two hits, including three each by
Everett and Richard Hidalgo. Jeff Bagwell (three walks), Ken
Caminiti and Everett, the Astros' three through five hitters, were
a combined 7-for-11 with 13 RBIs and seven runs.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Bogar added three RBIs on a bases-loaded double in the
eighth to cap the scoring. Glen Barker grounded out with Bogar at
third as the Astros fell just short of scoring 20 runs for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Astros enjoyed one of their most productive nights
ever, Bergman was not at all pleased with his performance. It isn't
every game a pitcher is backed by 19 runs, but Bergman felt he
should have delivered the knockout punch after the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman (2-1) allowed six runs and 11 hits, including the two
home runs, over five-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense was definitely the story. The way I pitched was
unacceptable,'' Bergman said. ``We scored runs, and I should have
been able to get guys out. I didn't do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was a way for Pittsburgh to give away the game, the
Pirates found it. They had 14 hits but offset them with five errors
_ one short of the team record. Six of the Astros' 19 runs were
unearned.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Ritchie (2-2) was pounded for eight runs _ five earned _
and seven hits in 3 innings. Chris Peters gave up six runs _ three
earned _ and seven hits in 1 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we put our heads together like this, there's no telling how
many times we can do it,'' Everett said. ``It's a great club, and
everyone can hit. I think we were more anxious to try and get this
game over with. Your feet start hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied at 1, the Astros went up in the third when
Craig Biggio was hit by a pitch, Derek Bell reached on a fielding
blunder by shortstop Pat Meares and Bagwell hit a two-run double
into the left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, the Astros sent nine batters to the plate. With
one out, Biggio doubled, Bell reached on third baseman Ed Sprague's
throwing error to first base and Bagwell walked to load the bases.
Caminiti, who extended his hitting streak to 12 games, hit a
two-run double off Ritchie to put the Astros ahead 6-1. Everett
followed with a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   In almost a repeat of the fourth inning, the Astros tacked on
another five runs in the fifth. They had six hits in the inning,
the big blow being Bagwell's second two-run double of the game.
Everett and Paul Bako, who went 2-for-5, followed with RBI singles.
</P>
<P>
   In the Astros' four-run eighth, Osik became the first Pittsburgh
position player to pitch since outfielder John Cangelosi on May 3,
1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
