<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUINEI OVERDOSE FAR FROM ISOLATED; HEROIN DEATHS ON RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the field of substance abuse treatment, there is an
old acronym for the kind of person who most responds to help:
</P>
<P>
   YAVIS _ Young, attractive, verbal, insightful and successful.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, things are changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've begun to realize,'' said Dr. John Talmadge, ``it also can
be an acronym for a dead heroin user.''
</P>
<P>
   Latest example is Mark Tuinei, the popular, charismatic former
Dallas Cowboy lineman who accidentally killed himself May 6 with a
walloping drug cocktail of heroin and the amphetamine Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei's death at 39 and his choice of weapon is a shocker for
the Cowboys, where he was a 15-year fixture who retired in 1998, as
well as the sports nation.
</P>
<P>
   But for the town where he died, the wealthy Dallas suburb of
Plano, it was largely a sad case of same old, same old.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three years in the suburbs of Dallas and Fort Worth,
34 young people have died from heroin overdoses. While Tuinei is a
little older than the YAVIS profile, he still fits well the
cultural label: A guy the middle class would never suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the long string of high school deaths, Plano has been
the object of much media attention, including a major story in the
current issue of Rolling Stone magazine, ``Texas Heroin Massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   But the sprawling corporate 'burb is little different from its
counterparts throughout America. Especially in and around Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Heroin deaths in King County set a record in 1998: 144, six more
than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A compilation over the last three years of heroin deaths by the
county medical examiner's office disclosed that 83 percent of the
victims were white, and 13 percent were African-American. More than
80 percent were male and about half were in the 35-44 age group.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we typically find is that these people are mixing their
drugs,'' said Jon Nakagawara, the examiner's administrative
assistant. ``It's not uncommon to see heroin used with alcohol and
other drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Seattle menu is typically black tar heroin from Asia,
the Texas prep preference comes from Mexico in gel capsules and
leaves no tell-tale physical evidence, not even red eyes or runny
noses.
</P>
<P>
   The heroin, or chiva, as it's called in Mexico, is also cheap,
so that even the upper middle-class kids of Plano, much less
professional athletes, have no trouble indulging their fatal
pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible problem,'' said Talmadge, a Dallas M.D. with a
specialty in addiction psychiatry and medicine. ``A lot of
community energy is going into what amounts to a heroin epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   Where once Seattle was tagged by national media as the heroin
capital of America, the cursed label now falls to Plano, even
though the problem is countrywide. Tuinei's death has again brought
the spotlight, but much of the sports coverage is focused on
further damage to the Cowboys' already tattered reputation.
</P>
<P>
   That consequence is minimal compared to the larger problem,
particularly since heroin use among young people is growing instead
of shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I moved to Dallas 10 years ago, there were several good
treatment programs for high school-age kids,'' Talmadge said. ``The
troubled kids typically fell into two categories, users and
rehabbers. Each school had dozens involved in Alcoholics Anonymous,
or Narcotics Anonymous, or other kinds of counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there's really only one group _ users.''
</P>
<P>
   Talmadge said that use of rehab programs has fallen off
dramatically because most health insurers increasingly do not pay
for specialty care, particularly regarding mental problems and
addictive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the discrimination stems from a society that is
generally not sympathetic to problems of alcohol and drugs, as well
as the belief that abuse is a moral issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep dismantling the treatment system, what outcome can
be expected?'' he said. ``This is not a crime problem; it's a
public health problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had slain the moral issue in the '80s, when half
the cast of `Saturday Night Live,' along with Eric Clapton, Betty
Ford, and members of the McGovern and Dukakis families, accepted
treatment and started turning the corner on public perception.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, because treatment is fading, Talmadge said there are no
longer kids telling their stories about recoveries. He said that
1992 was the last year that extensive, insured treatment programs
were available to most Dallas-area students.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's unconscionable that insurance coverage is denying
treatment to kids,'' he said. ``It's a national tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're killing all the evangelists.''
</P>
<P>
   It's probable that Tuinei could have afforded any treatment.
What he didn't have, apparently, was knowledge that he either had a
problem or was toying with almost instant death.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is individual or societal, the root of the problem is
the same _ ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the shocking squandering of Tuinei's life might make a
few points that his athletic career never did.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, America's stupidity about drugs is an almost
unbeatable opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
