<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3519 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-12 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVEN SECOND CHANCE, MARINERS MAKE RED SOX PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With his spot likely slipping away a few time zones
over, Domingo Cedeno was losing time to make his first Mariner days
count. And if Boston Red Sox catcher Jason Varitek had held onto
his foul tip in the sixth inning Tuesday night, the
lightest-hitting Mariner might have left without a highlight.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox reliever Rheal Cormier had just gotten a bases-loaded
double-play ball, and though a run had scored, he seemed secure
with two strikes on Cedeno. But when Varitek dropped the foul tip,
it gave Cedeno another chance.
</P>
<P>
   He delivered, rapping a run-scoring double to left-center. It
was the pivotal hit in a four-run rally that sparked Seattle to an
8-5 win over the Red Sox and helped Jamie Moyer earn his second
victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just waiting for my pitch,'' said Cedeno, who added an
RBI single in the seventh. ``He threw me another changeup. I was
looking for it, he went a little bit up, and that's where you can
hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been 13 games since Cedeno's last start, and with a .225
average, he likely will be sent to the minors when Alex Rodriguez
returns on Friday. Rodriguez played shortstop in a rehab stint
Tuesday at Peoria, Ariz., with no reported problems.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's return from knee surgery will help the Mariners, who
have struggled to sustain offensive rallies. Their first two runs
Tuesday came on solo homers, and they left runners in scoring
position in the first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   But in the sixth inning, they scored four runs on five hits, a
walk and an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a young season, but I can't remember too many
times when we've come up with clutch hitting like we did tonight,''
said catcher Tom Lampkin, who was taken out for a pinch-hitter that
inning after hitting a double and a homer earlier. ``Cedeno had two
big hits, David Bell, Butch Huskey, Junior. ... It was
unbelievable, everybody that got in the game did something major to
contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two hits of the inning did not leave the infield. Bell
singled to second to bring in Cedeno, and Ken Griffey Jr. brought
in the last run, which gave the Mariners a 6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey one-hopped a ball to short, where Nomar Garciaparra had
to cross over second base to field it, and beat the throw. The Red
Sox had three infielders on the first-base side of the bag in a
``Ted Williams Shift,'' an increasingly popular strategy against
Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time that you do something to help your team, that's the
important thing,'' Griffey said. ``It doesn't matter what they do.
I'm not looking to hit the ball in the infield. I think it'd bother
me if they put four or five outfielders out there more than the
infielders putting the shift on. Boston started that last year, and
I hit .385 (.333) off them. If you're going to give me a hit, I'll
take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer will take his outing, in which he allowed three runs in
six innings to meet the minimum requirements for the so-called
quality start _ the first for Seattle in 12 games. The Mariners
needed the innings _ manager Lou Piniella wanted to save long
reliever John Halama for Wednesday night, and he is still
short-handed in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But Moyer walked four, and threw 52 balls among his 106 pitches.
A control specialist, he now has nine walks in his last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when you're locked in where you need to be,
and other times when you're just not there,'' Moyer said. ``I feel
great, I feel strong, and I felt good in the sixth inning. It's
something I'm not going to panic over or make something out of
nothing. Sooner or later, it's going to come. It's going to click
and be right back in stride. My feeling is there's no sense in
trying to force things to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But 50 balls in 100 pitches _ that's not good for my style of
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer's counterpart Tuesday was knuckleballer Tim Wakefield, who
is far different from Wednesday night's starter both in style and
performance. Boston will pitch the dominating Pedro Martinez
Wednesday, as the Mariners finish a nine-game road trip, and the
mention of his name soured Piniella's post-game press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll worry about Pedro tomorrow,'' said Piniella, whose team
has lost five times in eight games on this trip. ``Let me enjoy
this one tonight _ please.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
