<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG)__WRITETHOUGH </SLUG>
 
LAKERS GET AN `A' for `D' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The TV set at one end of the Los Angeles
Lakers' locker room played the same videotape over and over the
past few days, a tightly edited loop of Houston Rockets scoring
plays from the regular season, each flickering past as quickly as a
Kurt Rambis nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The tape wasn't merely a scouting tool, it was a scare tactic.
</P>
<P>
   There was Charles Barkley backing in for a layup. And Hakeem
Olajuwon hitting a jump shot. Barkley again. And Scottie Pippen
slashing through the lane. Barkley again. And Sam Mack nailing a
3-pointer. Barkley AGAIN. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   At that rate, the Rockets must have averaged 200 points a game
this year!
</P>
<P>
   Only in comparison to that rapid-fire video did the Lakers slow
down the Rockets in their series-opening victory the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they celebrated that one-point win, the Lakers knew
there was reason for worry, knew they wouldn't win many more
playoff games if they kept giving up 100. They had to improve their
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, they answered the challenge, improving their
``D'' to an ``A'' in a 110-98 victory at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The 98 is misleading. The game was over after the Lakers turned
in their best defensive quarter of the season to hold the Rockets
to 12 points and 23.5-percent shooting in the first 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was any magic to what we were doing,''
said Lakers guard Derek Fisher, who drew two charging fouls in a
stretch of three Rockets possessions in the early going. ``We just
came out with intensity and tried to set the tone. In basketball
you set the tone with defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the flawed Lakers team that squeaked by in Game 1,
raising the prospect of a hard-fought series, is not just in
control of the best-of-five at 2-0 but dominating the Rockets and
their three Hall of Famers.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, who had 25 in Game 1, was held to 19. Olajuwon was held
to 8, on 3- for-10 shooting. Pippen had 3, and was 0 for 7 from the
floor while guarded mostly by Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen more wins like this and some of us will be convinced
the Lakers are NBA-title material.
</P>
<P>
   Good defense can be hard to explain. Rarely can you put a face
on it, as Shaquille O'Neal did with his last-second block of a
Cuttino Mobley layup on Sunday and as Fisher had by diving for a
key steal seconds earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why it's hard to teach NBA players the importance
of defense. There's so little star potential in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense is a team thing,'' Rambis had said the other day.
``It's a developmental (practice) thing. Players have to learn to
trust that somebody is going to get their back.''
</P>
<P>
   But if good defense is hard to define, bad defense can be plain
to see.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up 100 points is a bad sign in this era of the incredible
shrinking NBA score.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' 101-100 victory Sunday made them the only team to
give up three figures and win in this NBA postseason. There won't
be many more.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up 100 has meant trouble for the Lakers: When they gave
up 100 or more in games against playoff-bound teams this season,
they went 2-11.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring 100 has meant success for the Rockets: When they put up
100 or more in games against playoff-bound teams this season, they
went 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   That summed up the Lakers' task Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Game-1 self-assessments of the defense had ranged from ``up
and down'' (Fisher) to ``pretty good'' (Glen Rice).
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't stop Barkley. They let the Rockets hit 52.1
percent of their shots.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, though, their interior defense improved and the Rockets
wound up under 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Shaq's game-saving block on Sunday persuaded the Lakers to
trust each other. Somebody DID have their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way we want to play defense,'' Rambis said
afterward. ``You take care of your business one-on-one and the
other four guys are there to help you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we stayed focused to our game plan tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' only breath all night came from their guards, who
hit five straight 3-pointers to briefly cut the Lakers' lead to
single figures in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, the Lakers made that Rockets videotape in the
locker room look like a work of fiction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
