<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3533 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKE2-LADN-(SLANG     05-12 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKE2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS DEFENSE RULES
</HEADLINE>
 - WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The vigorous swooshing sound reverberating
in the upper reaches of the Forum on Tuesday was an echo of the Los
Angeles Lakers furiously erasing doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts about their tumultuous season, about their personnel,
about their ability to work together, to stay together and to
somehow fuse all that talent into the dominant team billed as the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   All those doubts, and more, were wiped out with a few quick
strokes across the blackboard, and an etched-in-slate 110-98
victory over the stunned Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense was stifling, their offense as fine-tuned as a
Stradivarius _ and their confidence? It was somewhere in the
stratosphere after they took a 2-0 lead in the best-of-five
first-round series, which heads to Houston for Game 3 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're feeling very confident in ourselves, but it's good to
know where that's coming from _ the defensive end,'' said Kobe
Bryant in an understated tribute to the Lakers' newfound dominance.
</P>
<P>
   How shut down were the Rockets?
</P>
<P>
   They never led.
</P>
<P>
   They scored 12 points in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They shot 39.7 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   They trailed by double digits for all but five-and-a-half
minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen, he of a stamped Hall of Fame pass, scored 3
points and failed to hit a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon, himself Hall-bound, topped out at 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   And the third piece of the Hall trio, Charles Barkley, had two
points at halftime, scoring the rest of his 19 in a futile
second-half charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that when we go out and play aggressive defense and
stop them from doing the things they want to do, we feel the sky's
the limit,'' Glen Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   And as far as Bryant was concerned, the Lakers shouldn't even be
surprised at the havoc they wrought.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, ``because we're an explosive team.''
</P>
<P>
   Explosive, as in Shaquille O'Neal's 28 points, nine rebounds and
seven assists, to go with Bryant's 19 points and a
see-I-told-you-so 16 from new scoring whiz Derek Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   As enchanted an evening as it was, the Lakers even got an assist
from Magic Johnson _ who caught guard Derek Harper as he chased
down a loose ball and stumbled out of bounds in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   How's that for a good omen?
</P>
<P>
   And now the Lakers, confident and gaining momentum through six
straight wins, can close out the Rockets on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over yet and we realize that,'' Rice said. ``The
hardest fight is still ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly expected more fight Tuesday after squeaking out a
last-second victory in Game 1. But there was no need for an O'Neal
swat at the buzzer this time.
</P>
<P>
   After squandering a 13-point lead two days earlier, the Lakers
could take nothing for granted, so their 55-40 halftime lead seemed
anything but safe in context. And they had already watched the
Rockets battle back from as much as a 23-point deficit in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   But lessons learned Sunday stuck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned a lot,'' Rice said. ``We know when you get a good
veteran team down, you have to keep the pressure on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston probably figured the Lakers' gaudy lead could be sliced
and diced again. But the Rockets were not up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   They opened the third quarter with five straight points to cut
the lead to 55-45, but they couldn't break the 10-point barrier.
The Lakers, with 3-pointers from Bryant, Fisher and Rice, blew the
game open again, and less than four minutes into the quarter, they
led by 21.
</P>
<P>
   Houston never threatened the lead again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fully expected this game to be tougher than Game 1 was,''
Fisher said. ``We didn't expect to get out to such a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Houston coach Rudy Tomjanovich.
</P>
<P>
   ``One team came out chewing jock, one team came out for a day at
the beach,'' Tomjanovich said. ``They kick our (butts) right from
the gun. . . . I was disappointed, and I expected . . . a
competitive game. It was a collective, nonaggressive ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense ruled early _ the Lakers held Houston to 12 points in
the first quarter, a season low for an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher wasted no time proving that Sunday's 20-point game was no
fluke. He scored a team-leading 11 points in the quarter as the
Lakers built an unbelievable 19-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers, who sluggishly meandered through parts of the
regular season, were just waiting for the playoffs to peak, they've
timed it beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying for a while now, this team is coming
together, but we're still developing as a team,'' coach Kurt Rambis
said. ``We're still improving. We still haven't played our best
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   What they did Tuesday night was pretty darn close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 0243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3535 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-12 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ If an octopus had hands, there still wouldn't
be enough fingers to point at all that went wrong with the Rockets
this time.
</P>
<P>
   No breakdowns in the final minute. Just a train wreck from the
opening quarter. No game that got away. Just a team that never
showed up.
</P>
<P>
   No offense.
</P>
<P>
   No defense.
</P>
<P>
   No chance.
</P>
<P>
   No Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   Now no margin for error after the 110-98 thumping by the Lakers
on Tuesday night that was never that close.
</P>
<P>
   The last four minutes of this one found a lineup of Sam Mack,
Brent Price, Othella Harrington, Matt Bullard and Stanley Roberts
on the floor for the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Any questions?
</P>
<P>
   Just one: Why even bother?
</P>
<P>
   On a night when he had something to prove, Pippen scored just
three points. In a game when he had a reason to be inspired, Pippen
was limp, taking seven shots and missing every one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready to play after sitting around for two days,''
Pippen said. ``I know myself that I had spent enough time sitting
around thinking about the mistakes we made in the first game, the
things we didn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they didn't do them even more.
</P>
<P>
   So much for redemption
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be a night for redemption, a time to show
that the final horrific minute to Game 1 hadn't left the Rockets
physically and emotionally fractured from Pippen's comments that
were seen by most as selling out his teammate and good buddy
Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it came out was that I was throwing rocks at Charles,
and that's not what I was doing at all,'' Pippen said. ``I still
don't think it was a very smart play to foul Shaq with 28 seconds
left. All I was doing was giving my opinion on that one play.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it was the only play of the Rockets' collapse Pippen
singled out for dissection and conveniently omitted his own blunder
with 7.6 seconds to play when he fell down and had the ball stolen
by Derek Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that kind of season for Pippen, who signed his
five-year, $67 million contract at the end of the NBA lockout in
January and has struggled to fit into the Rockets' overall team
picture as either a savior or a perfect complementary part ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's travails began on opening night right here at the Great
Western Forum when Lakers phenom Kobe Bryant lit him up for 25
points while Scottie shot like a man wearing a blindfold, going
just 4-for-18 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   It was going to take a few weeks to feel comfortable, then a few
months, and now here is Pippen in his first playoffs wearing a
uniform other than the Chicago Bulls' and he has yet to find his
place among the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   His comments concerning Barkley's intentional foul on Shaquille
O'Neal with 28.4 seconds left in the game and the Rockets holding a
two-point lead could have provoked an explosive reaction from
within the team.
</P>
<P>
   However, Barkley uncharacteristically chose discretion and did
not allow the situation to escalate.
</P>
<P>
   Unaddressed topic at dinner
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Charles and Scottie went out to dinner together Sunday
night. But the subject never came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a word,'' said Barkley, ``and that's all right. I
understand that he said something that he probably shouldn't have
and didn't really mean. I also understand that he's under a lot of
pressure. And pressure can make people do funny things.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, the Rockets ought to be more laughs than a
barrel of monkeys for Game 3 on Thursday night, since all they have
to do is stop a runaway Lakers locomotive that is gaining
confidence and momentum with plenty of assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Like 4-for-17 shooting with six turnovers by the Rockets in the
first quarter. Which is how the Lakers managed to take a 37-14 lead
and the win almost before Jack Nicholson made it to his courtside
seat.
</P>
<P>
   As Jack might say, the Rockets couldn't handle the truth. Which
is that they flat-out didn't come to compete. And didn't really
have a chance when Hakeem Olajuwon picked up his third personal
foul just 14 minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, Antoine Carr and Barkley could not stop O'Neal's power
game inside. The Rockets couldn't stop Bryant anywhere, and nobody
in this series understands yet that you have to guard Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen drove and stumbled. He shot twice and stumbled at the
start. He struggled and spent most of the fourth quarter on the
bench, while his buddy fought and battled almost to the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game plan was to be aggressive,'' he said. ``I was going to
shoot the hell out of the ball tonight. But that plan only lasted
three or four minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, there were no fingers pointed. No friendships
betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles and I are the last thing you've got to worry about,''
Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least they are way down on a growing list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
