<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3536 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-12 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Rockets Rookies were as cute as they could
be a week ago, all dressed up and ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   They were looking all grown up with their wildly impressive
scoring performances, their hip talent, their speed, their
veterans' guile and their bright eyes beaming as their first
playoff experience fast approached.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuttino Mobley and Michael Dickerson are rookies. It's very
clear _ as clear as the Rockets' offense seems to be in a fog _
that they are rookies. And rookies they will remain until this
season is over, which might be any day now.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers 110, Rockets 98 Tuesday night at the Great Western Forum
turned into a yawner early and was a lot of things for a lot of
people.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant turned the floor into a personal playground,
bouncing around as if he had turbocharged his sneakers. Hakeem
Olajuwon turned into a fan for much of the first half, sitting on
the pine like just another beautiful person, thanks to too much
Shaquille O'Neal and too much foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal slammed down dunks seemingly at will, finishing with 28
points. Charles Barkley struggled to find any room for his burly
spins and barreling drives.
</P>
<P>
   And not to point fingers or anything, but Scottie Pippen could
just as well have raided the concession stand for goat-cheese sun
crackers like all the other onlookers. He was shut out on field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   But as difficult as the 2-0 deficit in this best-of-five series
against the Lakers might be to overcome, you have to believe coach
Rudy Tomjanovich and the Rockets' veterans will find a way to make
a few adjustments as the series heads to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   One thing, however, cannot be changed: Mobley and Dickerson are
rookies in this series. They always will be. And it's looking like
it will be as difficult to overcome as Pippen's search for the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets expected much production out of their young
backcourt against the Lakers, and there was every reason to believe
they would get it.
</P>
<P>
   There were those terrific late-season efforts by the rooks,
particularly Dickerson's back-to-back 31- and 27-point games in the
last week of the season. There was Dickerson's cool demeanor. There
was Mobley, with his free spirit and sweet game, looking every bit
like one of those rare first-year players who could remain unfazed
no matter the stakes. There even was a decent matchup against the
Lakers' underwhelming point guard, Derek Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   But the best Rockets backcourt combination that Tomjanovich put
on the floor Tuesday night was the one he didn't even have to begin
the year: Sam Mack and Brent Price.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, who arrived from Vancouver before the trading deadline,
scored 20 points. Price, who came off the injured list, showed
veteran experience on the way to 18 points and several nice
moments.
</P>
<P>
   When Price and Mack subbed for the rooks in the second quarter,
there even were brief thoughts that the Rockets might claw back
into this thing. Very brief.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Dickerson and Mobley showed only that they were
rookies.
</P>
<P>
   They succumbed to the immense pressure of the moment almost from
the opening tip, which rookies do in the playoffs. They never got
going, like most rookies in the playoffs. They got no calls, which
rookies rarely get in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no picture better illustrated the fate and status of
Mobley and Dickerson than an offensive foul called against Mobley
midway through the first quarter, when the Lakers were getting
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley drove toward the Lakers' free-throw line, much like
Bryant did in the critical and decisive final moments of Game 1.
Fisher, who finished with 16 points Tuesday and has looked like
Magic Johnson thus far, sprinted in front of Mobley.
</P>
<P>
   The two players bumped and became tangled in one another's feet
as the ball bounced away. It was a moment that looked like the
mirror image of Bryant's crash with Mack in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the call went against Mobley. Offensive foul.
Mobley screamed in agony and got a brief scolding from the
official.
</P>
<P>
   Don't talk back to me, Rook.
</P>
<P>
   The ball went the other way, and the Lakers kept running and
scoring. Thus, the hole dug early, when the Lakers built a 19-point
first-quarter lead, was far too much.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was nowhere. But the rookies were not enough, either. In
the first quarter, Dickerson and Mobley committed a combined five
turnovers and two fouls, with no assists on 1-of-5 shooting. They
both sat through the entire second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson ultimately finished with zero points on 0-of-8
shooting from the field. Mobley finished with six points, managing
just three field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Before this series began and the pressure of going to the
playoffs with a rookie backcourt was brought up, Barkley said of
Mobley and Dickerson, ``That's something we can't change. We have
confidence in them, but we can't change that they're rookies. We
have to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless things change, they'll have to die in this series because
of it, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
