<SLUG> BC-BBN-NEWDODGER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS BEAT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 -- WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers right fielder Raul Mondesi hit
two home runs, has four in his last two games and leads the major
leagues with 13 homers.
</P>
<P>
   That's it for the good signs from the Dodgers' 10-5 loss to the
Chicago Cubs at Dodger Stadium on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Onto the pressing concern regarding the Dodgers, and
particularly the plight of right-handed reliever Antonio Osuna. He
says he's well. Dodgers manager Davey Johnson isn't so sure, which
again throws a monkey-wrench into the never-stable bullpen
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna allowed four runs in just a third of an inning. In that
span the Cubs turned a 5-4 lead into a 10-4 laugher, and in the
process resurrected talk that Osuna may be too hurt to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little concerned about Osuna,'' Johnson said. ``He had
rest and didn't have his best stuff. I would imagine it's been a
while since he's been hit that hard. His fastball had no life on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna has a bone spur in his right elbow and Dodgers team
physician Dr. Frank Jobe recommended surgery three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, Osuna, who had a bone spur removed from the same spot
last September, spurned the bone spur surgery and said he wanted to
pitch with it since it wasn't causing him pain. Osuna was placed on
the disabled list April 21 (retroactive to April 18) for the second
time this season and told he would have to prove he could pitch
through the pain before he was activated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling good,'' Osuna said. ``I feel strong. I tried to
throw hard and the ball was up. I told them, `If you want to use me
today, I feel good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   How Osuna felt and how he pitched were very different, and
pitching coach Charlie Hough said it looked like Osuna lost
velocity on his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the Cubs' five-run seventh inning that broke the
game open was an RBI single by Chicago reliever Rodney Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of line drives for (Osuna) to be strong,''
Johnson said. ``I'm concerned. I'm concerned that he's healthy. I
need to find out. The first time he threw he had a lot of pop in
San Diego. Next time out it was a little bit less and this time out
it was a little less.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in four outings that Osuna has given up a
run, but since Johnson views the bullpen as one of the most
important part of a baseball team (the bench is included in that
group), and given Osuna's medical resume, there's a reason the
Dodgers will be anxious to see Osuna at the ballpark today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Osuna's inability to hold the Cubs at bay in the
seventh inning _ not to mention starter Carlos Perez's fourth loss
in five outings _ cost the Dodgers a chance for a winning
homestand. The best they can do is split the six-game stand.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs right fielder Sammy Sosa and shortstop Jose Hernandez
deserve the blame _ or credit _ for that. They combined for six of
the Cubs' 11 hits and each came within one hit of the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez needed only a single in his final at-bat but flied to
center. His third-inning homer gave the Cubs a 2-0 lead, which Mark
Grace extended to 3-0 with a homer. Sosa was missing a triple, but
he did deliver excitement in the form of his eighth homer of the
season. His solo shot in the sixth gave the Cubs a 5-2 lead but he
grounded to second in his last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Sammy to homer his last time up and miss the home
plate,'' said Grace, who hit for the cycle six years ago. ``They're
both trying to catch me, but I'm still the last one to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which, combined with Osuna's problems, more than
overshadowed Mondesi. He hit a two-run homer in the sixth to cut
the Cubs' lead to 5-4 and then hit a solo shot in the eighth to
make it 10-5. He has four homers in his last five at-bats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
