<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3538 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-LAKERS-HN     05-12 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Rockets had their extended Southern
California weekend, played some ball, saw some sights. They just
never had time for the beach.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That came Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The control of their Western Conference series that seemed
theirs until the final eight seconds two days earlier was proved to
be made of sand. Tuesday, the Lakers kicked the sand in the
Rockets' faces, manhandling them with embarrassing ease.
</P>
<P>
   Routed from the opening minutes, the Rockets only occasionally
earned their opponents' attention, with the Lakers easily brushing
aside the few brief Rockets runs before settling for a 110-98 win
not nearly that close.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I saw it, it was one team chewing on the jockstraps
and the other team coming out for a day at the beach,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``They kicked our butts from the start. The biggest
adjustment we've got to make is coming to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The win gave the Lakers a commanding 2-0 lead in the
best-of-five series, forcing the Rockets to win three straight
after having not beaten teams with winning records in three
consecutive games all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done it before,'' Lakers guard Kobe Bryant said of the
long-shot Rockets comeback chances. ``Not against us, but Rudy
Tomjanovich has experience with that. When we get down to Houston,
we have to take care of business like the series is 0-0.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets looked a long way from winning even once. And
that was just in the opening minutes when the game was already a
mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just kicked our butts,'' said Rockets forward Charles
Barkley, forced to team with Sam Mack and Brent Price to form the
revised but insufficient version of the Big Three. ``I can't say
what was wrong. Anything I say would be excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Barkley would not blame teammates or even the
disheartening loss Sunday, the reasons for Tuesday's debacle were
clear.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon, in immediate and unrelenting foul trouble,
never found the touch that he had going so well two days earlier.
He made just three of 10 shots and finished with eight points.
Without Olajuwon around to at least make him work on defense,
Shaquille O'Neal rolled to a game-high 28 points, nine rebounds,
seven assists and five blocked shots, while triggering the Lakers'
unstoppable offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go to Shaq, and it creates mismatches with his size,''
Olajuwon said. ``When he moves it around and passes the ball and
shoots the ball so well, we have to find a different way to defend
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what troubles Olajuwon had, he shined compared to
Scottie Pippen. Determined to attack the basket and make something
happen from the outset, Pippen was no more effective offensively
than when he fell Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen missed all seven of his field-goal attempts, finishing
with three first-half free throws, his three-point total bringing
howls from the Forum crowd when it was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get myself going early, but that sort of went to
hell,'' Pippen said. ``Those opportunities never came again. They
started to pull away, and we just never got ourselves back in the
game. It's pretty difficult. It was just one of those nights we
were never in the flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bryant) makes me expend a lot of energy. I got cross-matched
(defending Glen Rice). Now Rice is resting (on the other end). And
Kobe comes up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   With Pippen and Olajuwon absent without leave offensively, Mack
led the Rockets with 20 points, with Barkley getting 19 points and
13 rebounds, Price 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Mack and Price got into the game in the second
quarter, it was all they could do to try to force an improbable
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam and I have been giving a lift all year with scoring off
the bench,'' Price said. ``But when he and I are a couple of the
leading scorers in a game, we're in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to have the starters doing their thing. We have to
have the Big Three. They're veterans. They're our leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bench created the Rockets' only runs, their only moments
of respectability.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' last burst, completed with Barkley's second 3 of
the night, brought them to within 13 with 8:49 left. But that was
something of a fraud, as unlikely to last as a torrent of Barkley
3s.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was resting during that brief run, and when he returned
he put in four consecutive baskets to blow the lead back out to
100-79 with 6:31 left.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any doubt after the Lakers' fast start, it had long
since been put aside. The Lakers had built a 23-point lead in the
first half, let it slide to nine, then built it back to 23 in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, guard Derek Fisher, who made six of 11 shots,
including four of six 3s to finish with 16 points, burned the
Rockets for double-and triple-teaming O'Neal. Bryant finished with
19, Rice 14.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rockets had no answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They jumped on us,'' Barkley said. ``Fisher got off to another
great start, and Kobe got of to a great start. I'm not going to sit
here and dissect our team. We just got our butts kicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got killed, no excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Having left their day at the beach badly sunburned, the Rockets
were not ready to deal with such problems, anyway. Instead, they
watched the intensity and effort of Game 1 go out with the tide and
knew nothing would work until they got that back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected a hell of a competitive game,'' Tomjanovich said.
``It was a collective non-aggressive game. We have to go back and
regroup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
