<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKESIDE2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 WRITETHRU (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Point blank, Charles Barkley was asked a
simple question.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Houston Rockets ever have a chance against the Los
Angeles Lakers on Tuesday night?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Barkley replied.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets hope their stay in the NBA playoffs isn't as short
as Barkley's answer, but things are turning desperate after they
dropped Game 2 110-98 before 17,505 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   At least after Sunday's opener, the Rockets could talk big about
how they gave that one-point loss away. But there was no way to
rationalize this debacle, even for someone as skilled as Sir
Charles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got our butt kicked,'' Barkley said. ``I'm not going
to sit here and dissect our team, we just got our butts kicked.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had grand strategies for Game 2. None more than
those of forward Scottie Pippen, trying to atone for his turnover
at the end of Game 1 that probably cost the Rockets the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my game plan to come out and be aggressive and shoot
the hell out of the ball,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   The end result: Pippen had three points and missed all seven of
his shots from the field. He's made 5 of 20 shots in the series,
including 0 for 6 on 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen felt the Lakers' fast start took him out of the
offense more than any problems he's having shooting the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing well offensively; it took us out of what we
wanted to do,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   With Pippen looking less and less influential in this series,
maybe the Rockets could get a boost somewhere else, like rookie
shooting guard Michael Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson missed all eight of his shots and did not score a
point. It was the type of performance that allows critics to say
rookies are usually out of their league once the playoffs begin. A
point Dickerson vehemently denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no difference. I don't see any difference,'' Dickerson
said. ``I'm not frustrated. I'll bounce back. There's no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   With two starters going 0 for 15, it's a wonder the Rockets lost
by only 12 points. Did we mention that center Hakeem Olajuwon went
3 for 10 from the field and scored eight points? He's about had it
after two games, although his complaints are directed more at the
officials. Olajuwon picked up his first foul one minute into play
Tuesday and had two in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult,'' Olajuwon said. ``We just have to make the
necessary adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   But exactly what are those adjustments? The Rockets seem unable
to contain the Lakers inside (Shaquille O'Neal had 28 points) or
outside (Derek Fisher had 16).
</P>
<P>
   And offensively, they've gone AWOL with the exception of
Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gotta go back and regroup,'' Houston coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said. ``I just need to go back and look at everything. It will be a
hard one to watch (on tape). We just need to bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many ways Tomjanovich tries to adjust, however,
the Rockets are going nowhere unless Pippen starts playing a little
more as he did when he could rely on Michael Jordan to bail his
team out in pressure situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just playing,'' Pippen said. ``I'm trying to do whatever
it takes to win. It's not happening now. They're just overshadowing
whatever we're trying to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 0301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
