<HEADER>
A3564 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTHS-SEX-SFCHRON &LR;      05-12 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHS-SEX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOW INSECTS USE SEX TO PROTECT THEIR MATES FROM PREDATORS  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the wedding gifts that male animals can offer their
brides, the lovely rattlebox moth must surely be the most generous:
In the act of copulating, he gives his female partner lifelong
protection against being devoured by voracious spiders.
</P>
<P>
   The rattlebox isn't the only insect that mates so protectively.
The male queen butterfly, scientists have found, includes a
chemical with his package of sperm that protects the female
butterfly's hundreds of eggs against predatory ants, ladybird
beetles and mites as well as spiders.
</P>
<P>
   Studying these interactions in insects _ as well as other
curious relationships between chemistry and living organisms _ is
known as ``chemical ecology.'' A pioneer in the field is Thomas
Eisner of Cornell University, a noted biologist and specialist in
the protection of endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   To Eisner, a bug collector since he first learned to walk, the
male rattlebox moth's strategy for transmitting chemical defenses
against predators to his mate during sex offers a fascinating
insight into the complex ways that nature keeps the insect world
thriving.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner and a team of his graduate students describe the latest
insights into the helpful uses of sex among insects in the current
issue of the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences. The
story offers an intriguing glimpse of a world that few people
besides entomologists know about: the insect tribes that far
outnumber humans on planet Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Eisner said he has recently returned
from field work in Florida studying the rattlebox moth in greater
detail.
</P>
<P>
   The lovely pink, white and black females, he said, are about as
sexually active as any animal alive. They live for only a month,
but during that brief life span they mate as often as 10 times _
with 10 different males. In fact, Eisner said, he observed one
Florida female mating a total of 23 times _ most probably with 23
different males, although he couldn't be certain that the same male
didn't come back a second time in a few cases.
</P>
<P>
   Rattlebox moth copulation is a feat of endurance, he noted, for
once the moths start to mate, they remain coupled together for as
long as nine hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   According to Eisner and his colleagues, the male rattlebox moth,
known scientifically as Utetheisa ornatrix, feeds exclusively while
still a caterpillar on a bean plant that contains alkaloids called
pyrolizidines. Those chemicals, it seems, are totally repulsive to
at least two species of spiders _ orb weavers and wolf spiders _
and the male caterpillars retain the plant's alkaloids in their
bodies through the pupal stage of their lives and even after they
emerge from their cocoons as winged moths.
</P>
<P>
   When they copulate, the males include the alkaloids in their
``sperm packages,'' which are rich in both nutrients and the
protective alkaloids.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after mating, the female moths transfer the alkaloids to
their eggs and retain enough in their own bodies to make themselves
repulsive to spiders, Eisner said.
</P>
<P>
   When a hungry spider traps a female moth in its web, the Cornell
researchers observed, the moth secretes a disgusting chemical in a
froth of bubbles, and the spider promptly liberates the moth by
cutting the web away with its fangs and feelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a human bridegroom would buy life insurance for his
bride,'' Eisner told Cornell associates. ``This classy moth gives a
gift she can really use _ a life insurance policy, if you will _
that keeps paying off every time her life is in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   But the male moth gets his reward, too, for when the female
casts about to select a mate, she has a way of sensing which male
bodies are richest in the protective chemical she needs _ and those
are the ones she chooses.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner's colleagues during the team's most recent series of
moth-and-spider experiments, as well as during observations in the
wild, include his wife, research associate Maria Eisner, and his
graduate students, the husband-and-wife team of Andres Gonzalez and
Carmen Rossini. Gonzales is the lead author of their published
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 0340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
