<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 03:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3568 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-COELHO-SFCHRON &LR;      05-12 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-COELHO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EX-CALIFORNIA CONGRESSMAN TO HEAD GORE CAMPAIGN  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and ROBERT G. GUNNISON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., was named Tuesday as the
general chairman of Al Gore's 2000 presidential effort, in a move
designed to energize the vice president's lagging campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the appointment of Coelho, 56, the former head of the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, may also bring with it
controversy about financial dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho, who represented the Central Valley town of Merced in
Congress, is considered an energetic strategist and top-notch
fund-raiser who excelled in tapping ``soft money'' donations from
political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   But critics note that Coelho resigned suddenly from Congress in
1989 during an investigation into his personal finances, though no
charges were ever filed against him on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair game,'' Coelho said Tuesday, referring to questions
about his finances. ``I have been investigated . . . and vetted by
everybody,'' he said. ``The Reagan-Bush Justice Department
investigated me for two years, and they gave me a clean bill of
health.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho termed ``poppycock'' the questions already raised by some
watchdog groups: that his past money troubles could focus more
attention on Gore's fund-raising problems. ``There were no
violations on my part. . . . Obviously Al was cleared of anything
on his part,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho said he welcomes any questions about his past, saying
``there's nothing there, and all they have to do is look.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho, an investment banker and agricultural landowner in
California, said he has agreed to work for Gore without pay for the
next 18 months on the condition that the vice president will not
consider Coelho for, or even ask him to discuss, a job in a Gore
administration. ``I'm doing this because I believe in him,'' Coelho
said.
</P>
<P>
   He has also asked lawyers to review whether he should resign
from several business boards in California. ``I'll do whatever they
want me to do so there's no conflicts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho said he intends ``no shakeups'' in Gore's campaign
organization. The campaign, which has suffered from perceptions of
inertia, ``is in better shape than people think,'' he said. ``The
structure is there, the talent is there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see some perceptual change . . . and major
policy speeches'' in the next phase of the campaign, Coelho
promised. ``We're going to have fun, and get the job done and help
people understand what Al Gore is all about, what is his vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho declined to talk about Gore's state fund-raising goals,
but added, ``California is critical for us . . . for finances.''
</P>
<P>
   Some state political veterans say Coelho's appointment proves
Gore's campaign is on top of the game in crucial California. The
vice president has visited California more than 50 times, but polls
show him running virtually neck and neck with both Texas Governor
George W. Bush and Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony is a very significant asset. . . . If the ability to pick
raw talent is a measure of Gore's campaign, it was a very smart
move,'' said political consultant Richie Ross Tuesday. ``(Gore)
needed a major league move . . . and Tony Coelho brings a level of
energy. This is not some tired figurehead. He's a guy who will make
things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ross predicted, ``the campaign will roll _ or heads will
roll.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
