<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CARLOS-FRANCO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCO RIDES GOLF FROM DIRT POOR TO TOUR RICHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Perhaps a bit of Jack Nicklaus' magic rubbed off
last month at the Masters Tournament when he picked up Carlos
Franco's 5-iron during a practice round and hit an approach shot.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps golf fans in the United States simply didn't recognize
the potential of a PGA Tour rookie who grew up playing barefoot in
a country with only three golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Franco has stunned the PGA Tour since that
day at Augusta National Golf Club. The native of Paraguay followed
up a sixth-place tie in his Masters debut with last week's triumph
at the Compaq Classic of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, one of six golfing brothers from a family that shared
a one-room shack with a dirt floor heads into tomorrow's opening
round of the GTE Byron Nelson Classic with more earnings in his
brief career ($910,549) than Sam Snead ($620,126), who won a
tour-record 81 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Of Franco's total, $593,200 has come in his last two outings.
But the real eye-opener came in the aftermath of Sunday's victory
at New Orleans, when tournament officials treated Franco to his
first limousine ride, complete with champagne and five Colombian
cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Then, came the phone calls. Friends and relatives from five
different countries, roughly 15 in all, offered heartfelt kudos.
Franco, 33, was touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were so emotional, they were crying. They couldn't even
talk,'' said Franco, who joined Roberto DiVicenzo (Argentina) on
the short list of PGA Tour winners from South American countries.
``When you're crying and saying, `Congratulations,' it means a lot
more. You can tell it's genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   The outpouring of support, said Franco, caused him to reflect on
his humble beginnings. On the long odds he has beaten. From his
days of playing with borrowed equipment, Franco has become a
celebrity in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm better known there than Bill Clinton would be here,'' said
Franco, whose strong finish at the Masters triggered a parade in
his hometown of Asuncion. ``The people who drive the taxis stop and
wave. I like it. Everyone knows who Tiger Woods is, but the people
there think of me as the king of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of his 30 tournament victories worldwide, Franco has
eclipsed the celebrity status of a fellow Paraguayan athlete,
tennis star Victor Pecci, who lost to Bjorn Borg in the finals of
the 1979 French Open. But his initial PGA Tour triumph, Franco
said, has taken his fame to a new level and provided him confidence
that he can continue his roll this week at the Four Seasons Resort
and Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why not,'' said Hal Sutton, who finished five
strokes behind Franco in New Orleans. ``We've never been paired,
but he looked pretty good to me on TV when the heat was on.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco ranks among the top tier of touring pros in driving
distance, putting and sand saves. His scoring average (70.2) is
13th among tour participants in 1999. He is adjusting, he said, to
a new home in Miami, a city he selected ``because everyone speaks
Spanish and my wife doesn't speak English.''
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't plan to forget the folks who flooded him with
phone calls after Sunday's career-turning triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a champion on the PGA Tour, coming from where I've come
from, is one of the toughest things to do,'' Franco said. ``Having
so many people call me after I won in New Orleans showed it's
important to have ... a South American presence that will make more
people in South America want to understand and play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Another parade in Asuncion, now that he's a PGA Tour champion,
may not be out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just want to continue celebrating because I've had so
much success, so close together,'' Franco said. ``It makes me very
happy, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 0816EDT &QL; 
