<SLUG> BC-CAR-TEXAS-FENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MOTOR SPEEDWAY TO ADD HEIGHT TO FENCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The catch fencing at Texas Motor Speedway
likely will be raised by as much as 41/2 feet and the overhang
extended before the Pep Boys Indy Racing League's Longhorn 500 on
June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Gossage, TMS' executive vice president and general
manager, said he is anticipating those changes once engineers
employed by Speedway Motorsports Inc. complete their investigation
into the spectator fatalities and injuries that occurred during the
IRL's VisionAire 500 at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C., on
May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said the anticipated changes come on the heels of a
conversation he had with Bruton Smith, the chairman of the board of
SMI, on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to the engineers,'' Gossage said yesterday during
an Indianapolis 500 sendoff for IRL driver Greg Ray of Plano at The
Speedway Club. ``He \RSmith\S told me he felt like they were going
to come back with some recommendations on raising the height and
changing the design of the fences. Specifically `what' is in their
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what's going to happen with our track. We are going to
make some changes to the fence before the Longhorn 500. I would
suspect that Charlotte \RLMS\S would make changes before The
Winston, so we're talking about a lot of work in a very short
period. But it can be done. And we can do it here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's Motor Speedway is scheduled to play host to The Winston,
the all-star race of NASCAR's Winston Cup Series, on May 22. The
next points-race scheduled at LMS is NASCAR's Coca-Cola 600 on May
30.
</P>
<P>
   Three spectators were killed and eight injured at LMS when a
three-car crash sent a wheel and debris flying over a 15-foot-high
fence in Turn 4. LMS and TMS are sister 1.5-mile tracks and among
four Speedway Motorsports Inc.-owned facilities scheduled to play
host to five IRL races this season.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said the catch fencing at TMS, which also will play host
to the IRL's season-ender on Oct. 17, currently measures between
151/2 to 16 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be raised to as much as 20 feet tall,'' Gossage said,
``so we're talking about a tremendous addition.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said the current overhang fencing at TMS, which he
estimated at between three and four feet, also likely will be
extended. The overhang is designed to prevent debris from shooting
up and over the fence into the stands when a car makes contact with
the outside wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be other suggestions as well,'' Gossage said.
``There is the possibility they will say there's no reason to do
anything. But from the discussions we've had, I anticipate those
two changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray, of Team Menard, is scheduled to begin practice at the
2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Saturday. The IRL's premier
event, the 83rd Indy 500, is scheduled for May 30. Ray, who will
attempt to qualify for his third Indy 500 on May 22, called for the
IRL to accelerate its efforts to make open-wheeled cars safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to eliminate the danger completely. There is
risk involved,'' said Ray, who favors using tether straps to keep
wheels and tires attached to the car's tub section upon impact with
a wall. ``You can't put a Band-Aid on it. You can't do a quick fix.
What we have to do as a human race is look at it, use our
technology and our common sense to put more countermeasures in
there to protect not only the spectators but the participants.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 0817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
