<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, May 12, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIF-SURPLUS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California Gov. Gray Davis
wants to expand after-school and preschool programs with a fraction
of the huge budget surplus coming this year, administration sources
said. He is expected to announce Friday that California's booming
economy has put an unexpected $4 billion into the state's coffers.
By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   MARIN-HOUSING (Point Reyes Station, Calif.) _ In a jaw-dropping
display of citizen interest in an issue that has roiled the
community for almost a year, a quarter of the residents of West
Marin voted their opinion on a proposed affordable housing project
for Point Reyes Station: Yes. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-POLLUTION (San Francisco) _ MTBE, a controversial ingredient
added to gasoline to curb auto air pollution but blamed for
increases in water pollution, does little to reduce smog, according
to a study by the National Research Council. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JOB-CONFLICTS (San Francisco) _ Just about everybody gets
stressed out at work these days, and the natural reaction is to do
whatever it takes to avoid conflicts. Work is tough enough without
increasing the potential for arguments and more stress. But you can
have effective conflicts at work if you think before you act. By
DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ACTIVIST-HONORED (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Edith Coliver has watched
history from a front-row seat. As an analyst at the Nuremberg
Trials or a representative to developing democracies, Coliver has
been deeply involved in the international community for the past 50
years. Last week, she was named the 1999 International House Alumna
of the Year at UC-Berkeley for her half-century of service. By ERIC
DRUDIS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FUDGE-CAKE (Undated) _ Pillsbury finally did it. They've come up
with a new recipe for Tunnel of Fudge Cake. Just in time for the
50th anniversary of the Pillsbury Bake-Off, the company has
re-created its most requested recipe. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STARWARS-PROFILE (New York) _ Jake Lloyd, the 10-year-old
boy who plays Anakin Skywalker in ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace,'' talks about his Vader character. When I got the
part, I started yelling,'' he said. ``Then I took a deep breath and
thought, `Oh my gosh _ I got Star Wars!' Then I yelled some more.
Then I started crying.'' By BRUCE WESTBROOK
</P>
<P>
   GRATEFUL-DEAD (San Francisco) _ The Grateful Dead will keep on
truckin' _ over the World Wide Web _ for free. A lawyer for the
venerable Bay Area band has announced that fan- recorded live
concerts will be distributed at no charge on the Web. The
recordings will be posted in the controversial MP3 file format,
which lets users easily exchange near-CD quality songs over the
Internet. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A council of San Francisco's
press federation was invited for a Force feeding on Tuesday night,
a preview of the prequel, ``Star Wars: Episode I, The Phantom
Menace.'' If a bomb had gone off in the theater, PR people in San
Francisco would never have to give out freebies again. That's how
many of the freebie elite were there. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Like many pro athletes and some
politicians, cats don't always know when it's time to retire. When
Tiger was born, the president was Jimmy Carter. That president is
long gone. These days, when Tiger howls, I assure him that
everything is fine. After 20 years together, he always takes my
word for it. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   JESSE-JACKSON (San Antonio) _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson has a huge
opinion of himself and would love to have the power to stop wars.
But to accuse him of prolonging the Yugoslav war, as one
commentator did, exceeds logic. To lay at Jackson's feet a war that
has its roots in centuries-old conflicts and retaliations is
rhetorical overkill. By CARY CLACK.
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Piedmont, Calif.) _ In our boom economy that defies
the doomsayers, discussions about welfare have all but disappeared.
Politicians chortle with great satisfaction that the Welfare Reform
Act of 1996 has greatly reduced the welfare rolls. Before we all
become too smug about lifting millions of people out of poverty and
into productive work, listen to Doris Ng. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
