<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Ways to Speed Up Your Web Surfing  
 By David Einstein   
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  I recently saw a piece about speeding up Web surfing
as well as overall system performance by cleaning out old, unused
files. It mentioned deleting old program installation files, which
I assume are only used once when you install a program. It also
suggested cleaning out the Internet cache folder. How do I identify
these without deleting something I'll need later?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Unless you've installed dozens of programs, getting
rid of old installation files probably won't boost your system's
performance. But you might get a lift from emptying the browser's
cache folder, which can accumulate hundreds of little files over
time (these files are used to speed up the loading of Web pages
you've previously visited).
</P>
<P>
   Here's how to empty the cache: If you're using Internet
Explorer, choose Internet Options from the Tools menu. In the
section labeled Temporary Internet files, click Delete Files. If
you're using Netscape Navigator, choose Preferences from the Edit
menu. Click the plus mark next to Advanced in the directory on the
left. Choose Cache and then click the button labeled Clear Disk
Cache.
</P>
<P>
   Decoding MIME
</P>
<P>
   Q: I hope you can help: What does it mean when someone sends me
an attachment that I download, only to find it is a ``multipart
mime message''? I've tried various programs to open (Notebook,
Word, Excel) only to find Greek symbols instead of English text. I
have America Online.
</P>
<P>
   A: I know the feeling, because I had the same experience over
the weekend with some photos that someone sent to my AOL account.
AOL's Help section claims that ``When you receive a MIME-encoded
attached file from an Internet address, the AOL software will
decode the file for you _ invisibly and automatically.'' WRONG!
</P>
<P>
   I had the photos resent to another e-mail account and was able
to download them just fine using Outlook Express.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of MIME is to ensure that files can be sent over the
Internet and opened at the other end. But obviously that doesn't
always work with AOL. To decipher your files, you'll need a program
that can decode MIME. Two that come to mind are Winzip, a $29
shareware program that also happens to be great for compressing
files; and Wincode, which is free. Both can be downloaded from
www.hotfiles.com.
</P>
<P>
   No Upgrade
</P>
<P>
   Q: I use Microsoft Exchange 4.0 for e-mail. It came on my
computer nearly three years ago. Is there a free upgrade for this
program? If not, what alternatives are there?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is no upgrade for the consumer version of Exchange,
which is no longer being shipped with Windows. But several free
e-mail programs are available that might suit you. If you want to
stick with Microsoft, try Outlook Express, which comes with the
Internet Explorer browser. You can download it for free at
www.microsoft.com/ie.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is the Netscape Messenger, an e-mail client that
comes as part of Netscape Communicator. Also free, it can be
downloaded at www.netscape.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the Big Two, but there also are a couple of other
terrific free e-mail programs out there. One is Eudora Light from
Qualcomm, which you can get at www.eudora.com. The other is Pegasus
Mail, which is available at www.pegasus.usa.com.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Addresses
</P>
<P>
   Q: I can't find any file in America Online 4.0 dedicated to my
list of e-mail addresses. AOL 3.0 had such a list called
addrbk.lst. I just had a hard drive crash and had no backup for the
address list and am slowly recovering one name at a time. Is there
a way I can back up my address book?
</P>
<P>
   A: Indeed there is. AOL stores your addresses in a file that has
the same name as your screen name. You'll find it in the Organize
folder inside the America Online folder on your hard disk. To back
up the file, simply save it to another place on your hard drive, or
to a floppy or Zip disk.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the storage file also contains your Favorite Places
bookmarks, so you can also back them up by saving the file.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   You work at a company that doesn't let you access your corporate
e-mail when you're out of the office. Maybe they're paranoid, or
maybe they just don't have a way to get you around the firewall.
But if you use Microsoft Outlook at work, and your company uses
Microsoft Exchange, there is a way. Just set up a message rule that
forwards copies of your e-mail to another address _ either an
Internet account you have at home, or maybe a free Web-based e-mail
service like Hotmail.
</P>
<P>
   With your Outlook Inbox open, go to the Tools menu and choose
Rules Wizard. The wizard will guide you through the process of
setting up a rule that automatically forwards messages for you.
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   NYT-05-05-99 2048EDT &QL;
</P>
