<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. SHIMPI GOES TO CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some Internet publishers have millions of dollars to play with,
and some merely have a life-consuming passion. Never bet against
the fellow with a fire in his gut.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Time Warner Inc. announced it would shut down
Pathfinder, its ambitious effort to establish the first great
Internet portal. Time Warner began Pathfinder in 1994, when hardly
anybody else was even thinking about such a venture. And the
company spent $15 million a year in an effort to build an audience.
All for naught.
</P>
<P>
   How can the publisher of Time and People and Sports Illustrated
fail to attract Web users? By burying its most valuable properties
at the Pathfinder site, Time Warner failed to capitalize on the
appeal of its biggest brands.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a mistake made by my favorite Web 'zines. These
low-budget start-ups create their own brands through their sheer
fervent love of technology and good writing.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Anand Shimpi. He lived in Northampton till
1991, then moved with his family to Raleigh, N.C. A couple of years
ago, while taking a shower, Shimpi had an idea for a personal Web
site celebrating his passion for technology.
</P>
<P>
   Shimpi had little hope of becoming a Web celebrity. After all,
gearhead Web sites abound, from amateur efforts like his own to
major tech sites developed by major companies. Besides, Shimpi had
only one computer to write about _ his own. After all, he was only
a 14-year-old high school freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Shimpi took a month to design his site and write a review
of a new processor chip he'd bought. ``It wasn't the highest in
quality,'' Shimpi recalls.
</P>
<P>
   But back in 1997, Shimpi's site was good enough to attract a
stream of visitors, including the owner of a now-defunct computer
business who offered to provide sample parts in exchange for free
advertising. Soon, the site was truly worth visiting, crammed with
dozens of up-to-date hardware reviews, most of them written by
Shimpi himself at night, on weekends, and between classes.
</P>
<P>
   Today Shimpi has his own Internet domain, www.anandtech.com, a
couple of part-time employees, a steady stream of advertising
income and, he claims, 40,000 visitors a day.
</P>
<P>
   I applied another rough-and-ready test of Web-site popularity.
With the AltaVista search engine, you can see how many Web pages
contain links to a particular site. People link to someone else's
site if they like it and want others to visit it, so this is a good
popularity test. There are about 11,000 Web pages with links to
Salon, the red-hot Internet magazine backed by millions of Silicon
Valley bucks. Meanwhile, Anandtech, run out of Shimpi's bedroom and
relying on word of mouth, has built up over 4,000 links.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need to be a rocket scientist to do this,'' says
Shimpi. ``All you have to be, I think, is dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say _ he's planning to attend MIT. Then again,
maybe he's right. Ken Fisher is no rocket scientist. He's studying
ancient languages at Harvard Divinity School. But when he's not
reading Caesar's Commentaries, he becomes ``Caesar,'' self-taught
computer network administrator and technology buff.
</P>
<P>
   He and three of his Divinity School buddies run Ars Technica
(www.ars-technica.com), a relatively new, absolutely cool
technology site. Born in September of last year, Ars Technica takes
in only enough ad revenue to cover its Web hosting fees. But
already it's come to be regarded as an authoritative source of
information on the latest processors and graphics accelerators.
``We set out to make ours a biased news source,'' says Fisher.
``We're kidding ourselves if we try to say we're totally objective.
So we just set out to do this great thing, have a lot of fun, and
all of a sudden we're an authority.''
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of sites like Ars Technica and Anandtech out
there, assembled by dedicated amateurs with brains and attitude.
They're entering the game a lot later than Time Warner's
Pathfinder, and with a lot less money to burn _ just talent and
passion. And often, that's plenty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-06-99 1336EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
