<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEBACCESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Pretty Web Pages Can Be Ugly to the Disabled  
 By Benny Evangelista   
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The blazing 3-D graphics, video and sound that enliven
multimedia Web sites also can create barriers for people with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Web design is primarily driven by retinal chauvinists,'' said
Jerry Kuns, a visually impaired sales representative who uses
computer speech and Braille synthesizers to read information on the
Internet. ``Pictures are great, but they are stumbling blocks to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, audio clips can present a barrier for hearing
impaired people if no text translation is available.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a worldwide Internet standards body has just created
guidelines to help Web designers avoid problems that make their
sites cumbersome or unusable for people with physical or learning
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The World Web Web Consortium, called the W3C for short, released
its ``Web Content Accessibility Guidelines 1.0'' last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web has become a very visual medium,'' said Judy Brewer,
director of the W3C's Web Accessibility Initiative. ``It's a
wonderful way to exchange information. But if you have someone who
can't see that information, they wouldn't necessarily know what's
in that content.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, a button graphic on a company's Web site that links
a sighted person to products they can buy online may not be visible
to a person using software that converts text into speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone with sight might see `products, services, a business
plan, news,' but someone who can't see that would hear, `image,
image, image, image,''' Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   And sites that rely solely on mouse clicks for navigation may be
difficult for people with physical disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines ``take that into account, so a developer doesn't
have to think through all of that,'' Brewer said. For instance, she
said the guidelines say ``when you are putting in an image, add
alternative text.''
</P>
<P>
   The 300-member W3C also created a list of 10 tips for making
pages more accessible, such as always using the ``alt'' key to
display text that describes what visual elements like buttons do.
</P>
<P>
   Web accessibility is not just an issue of aesthetics, Brewer
said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 opinion written by the U.S. Department of Justice said
the 1990 Americans With Disabilities Act _ a sweeping bill that
mandates that buildings and services be made accessible to people
with disabilities _ also applies to companies and government
agencies offering products and services through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   However, the W3C also tried to create guidelines that could
bring about better Web designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are afraid an accessible page is dull or
boring, but multimedia can be effective support for
accessibility,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines are available at www.w3.org/wai. For a list of 10
quick design tips, go to www.w3.org /WAI/References/QuickTips.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-09-99 2010EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
