<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3871 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE11-COX &LR;      05-12 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE11-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
CYBERSCENE: Meet someone new via personal Web pages 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tucked between the Web pages that sell you books, urge you to
download music, and extol the virtues of Fords and Chevrolets are
some pages that have nothing to sell. For the most part, the
designer of the page and the owner are the same person.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, these are personal Web pages. For the most part, what you
read and see on them won't help you with a term paper or provide
you with information you need at work, but it may introduce you to
some interesting people. Almost all personal Web pages have links _
usually at the bottom of the page _ that let you send e-mail to the
creator. It's a nifty way to meet people around the world (this is
the World Wide Web, remember) and, worst case, you'll probably
enjoy the old-fashioned nature of a home page. Many of them are
filled with family snapshots and stories.
</P>
<P>
   How do you find random home pages? After all, it's not like
doing a search for the gross national product of Brazil. But there
are ways, and today we'll show you some of the keys that will get
you into home pages from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a start that may keep you busy for a few days. Yahoo!
(www.yahoo.com) has a section that includes 64,000 or so personal
home pages. Just go to
http://dir.yahoo.com/SocietyandCulture/People/PersonalHomePages/
and start clicking. You'll find that this directory is organized
alphabetically. And that leads us to one of the really entertaining
things that today's adventure into the personal offers us.
</P>
<P>
   Why not start the journey by looking up home pages by people
with your last name? Now for a person named Husted, that can be
especially entertaining. Most of the pages are in Denmark _ based
on the origin of the name _ so it offers a chance to learn about
that part of the family who stayed home. Admittedly, if you are a
Williams, Smith, Miller or Jones, the appeal may be less, but even
then you may find a distant relative in Des Moines. So click on a
letter of the alphabet and read the information that should include
the name of the page and a brief description of what it contains.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest repositories of personal home pages on the
Web is located at www.geocities.com. You can peruse the pages there
by starting at www.geocities.com/Avenues/PeopleandChat/. You'll
find that the vast GeoCities site is divided into neighborhoods.
It's very similar to real-world neighborhoods: Members select a
neighborhood area for their home page and build there.
</P>
<P>
   Since these are big neighborhoods _ true virtual cities _ you'll
need to use the search capability to find the sort of home pages
that interest you. For instance, let's say that you decide to visit
the College Park neighborhood at www.geocities.com/CollegePark/.
Then you can use the search function (it's on the left side of the
page) to type in a search word. The name ``Husted'' brings up a
list of sites that are either run by someone named Husted, or that
discuss that name. But you could just as easily search for
``skiing'' or ``pets'' or ``games.''
</P>
<P>
   Most search engines, including AltaVista (altavista.digital.com)
have the same sort of search functions you'll find at Yahoo! or
GeoCities. But you are not limited to formal collections of
personal home pages. You can also use any search engine, type in
search words that include ``home'' and ``page'' and ``personal,''
and search out the most specialized pages easily.
</P>
<P>
   If, after spending a lazy afternoon searching other home pages,
you find that you like the charm of visiting with real people from
around the world, remember that it's fairly easy to build your own
home page and join the fun. And sites such as GeoCities offer free
space for home pages so _ if you get the building urge _ you can
soon have a home on the Web of your own.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted's personal Web page is
www.mindspring.com/(tilde)bhusted/bills.htm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
