<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRILL-DRILL13-COX     05-12 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILL-DRILL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Avoid getting raked over coals: Clean grill
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ We're coming up on the first big grilling holiday
of the year (Memorial Day, May 31), and the retail trend of the
past decade seems to be continuing: It's easier to find a variety
of propane-gas grills than old-fashioned charcoal grills these
days.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got a grill you haven't used since last fall, now's
the time to drag it out and get it into shape for cooking. You have
to be especially careful about maintaining it because a poorly
maintained gas grill can be more dangerous than a charcoal grill.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few tips for getting the most out of the grill:
</P>
<P>
   GAS GRILLS
</P>
<P>
   The best time to give your gas grill its thorough annual
cleaning is at the end of the grilling season in the fall.
Otherwise, grease and dirt will have all winter to corrode the body
of the grill. Plus, hardened food by-products will be harder to
clean.
</P>
<P>
   But if you didn't clean up last fall, expect to spend an hour or
two cleaning up now before using the grill.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need some warm water with grease-cutting dish soap or
other mild detergent, a vinyl-bristle brush, a soft cloth,
toothpicks, sandpaper, a nonmetal bottle brush and your owner's
manual.
</P>
<P>
   Following the instructions in your owner's manual, disconnect
the hollow burner tubes through which the gas flows and use the
bottle brush to thoroughly clean the insides of the tubes. Grease
blobs and spider webs can clog the small gas ports in the burner
tubes. Clean them carefully with toothpicks.
</P>
<P>
   Before replacing the burner tubes, clean the inside and outside
of the grill housing with the vinyl brush. Use aluminum foil to
keep water from getting inside gas orifices.
</P>
<P>
   Areas with chipped paint must be sanded, primed and repainted
with heat-resistant paint. Paint only while the grill is cold and
allow time for the paint to dry before turning on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   Stove polish, a liquid or paste polish with black pigments, can
also help restore the grill's original, lustrous-black look.
</P>
<P>
   Check your gas line, line connections and propane tank before
restarting the grill. You can check the lines and connections by
turning on the gas and brushing the connections with soapy water.
Bubbles will form at the site of any leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes tightening a connection will stop a leak, but
sometimes you'll have to replace a hose or an O-ring.
</P>
<P>
   Although propane tanks will last as long as the grill, dented or
badly rusted tanks must be replaced immediately. Minor tank
corrosion can be fixed the same way chipped paint on the housing is
fixed.
</P>
<P>
   When you're sure the grill is ready to turn on, burn some of the
grease off the briquettes and cooking grids.
</P>
<P>
   Flip the briquettes so the greasy side faces the burner and
return the cooking grids to their usual positions. Light the grill,
close the lid and set the flame on high for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After the grill cools, remove the grids and briquettes and scrub
off any remaining grease with the vinyl brush and soapy water.
Rinse, towel dry and put them back in place.
</P>
<P>
   During the cooking season, flipping the briquettes over after
every use will help keep down the accumulation of grease.
</P>
<P>
   CHARCOAL GRILLS
</P>
<P>
   Read your owner's manual and follow its advice when it comes to
maintenance. Too many people who use charcoal grills base their
usage on family traditions and ignore the manufacturers' guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Charcoal grills should be cleaned thoroughly once a year, and,
again, fall is the best time. You'll need warm, soapy water, a
vinyl scrub brush, a scouring pad or pumice stone and a garden
hose.
</P>
<P>
   Start by emptying the ashes from past cookouts. It's a good idea
to have a metal trash can handy to dump used ashes, even if you
believe they're completely cool.
</P>
<P>
   Scrub the grill housing inside and out with the vinyl brush and
soapy water. Some enameled grills can stand up to household oven
cleaners, but check your owner's manual or call the manufacturer if
you're unsure. Rinse off the soap with the hose. Towel dry.
</P>
<P>
   Areas with chipped paint or rust should be sanded, primed and
painted with heat-resistant paint.
</P>
<P>
   The grilling grate can be cleaned with a scouring pad or a
pumice stone. Pumice stones are getting rather rare, but you should
be able to find them at hardware stores for a couple of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Before each use, clean the grate with a specially designed grill
brush or a piece of crumpled aluminum foil. Wipe with paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
