<HEADER>
A3901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPEYE-HOMETOWN13-COX     05-12 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPEYE-HOMETOWN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The home of Popeye
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITOR'S NOTE: This is Ron Wiggins' latest dispatch on his
trip, Into Thin Hair, to Alaska.)
</P>
<P>
   When helpful reader Don Armstrong of Lake Worth, Fla. said to be
sure and include the ``home of Popeye'' on my way to Alaska, and to
please buy him a Popeye doll to replace the beloved doll that he
lost, I didn't see how my route to Alaska would take me anywhere
near Chester, Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when I saw that my path through Tennessee almost grazed
Chester, I went back to his letter. Popeye? Popeye has fans?
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong had written: ``I'm in a Popeye skit where I perform at
small social events, which is why I'm interested in Popeye.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong woefully understates the case. He is Popeye. I learned
this when Popeye _ complete with gigantic forearms, pipe and sailor
hat _ showed up at my bon voyage party in The Palm Beach Post's
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   I promised to do my level best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Yam what I Yam,'' is what I think Popeye said, scrunching
his face, squinting one eye and keeping the corn cob pipe clenched
in his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The real name of the Popeye museum is Spinach Can Collectibles,
smack dab in the middle of Chester, the city which claims itself as
the home of Popeye's creator, Elzie C. Segar. Segar introduced the
spinach-powered sailor man in 1929 and died in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Spinach Can Collectibles is indeed a Popeye museum, with
memorabilia going back to the '30s. The owners also offer a web
site for fans: www.midwest.net/org/ace1
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more than 140 items,'' said Laurie Randall who, with
her husband Dave and partners Debbie and Mike Brooks, are probably
as nutty on the subject of Popeye as you can be without custodial
care.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have anything against Popeye, but what's to admire if
the guy can't remember to eat his spinach before tangling with
Bluto?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his take-me-as-I-am attitude,'' Randall explained. ``And
the way he says it is very important: `I Yam what I Yam and that's
all that I Yam.'''
</P>
<P>
   And after his arch-rival, the brutish Bluto, beats up Popeye and
then walks off with the beauteous Olive Oyl, Popeye becomes more
than he Yam by bolting a can of spinach, the greens' industry's
answer to methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   I still don't get it. Why did Olive Oyl even give Bluto the time
of day? He fought dirty, abused Popeye something fearful, and had a
beard you couldn't cut with metal shears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the eternal triangle,'' Randall explained patiently. ``I
think it's clear that Bluto was fond of Olive Oyl but that he dated
her more to get Popeye's goat than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Oops, what's this? A Popeye memorabilia store selling Betty Boop
pencils and wrist watches?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure this Betty Boop stuff belongs here?'' I asked.
Then I confessed: ``I used to have troubling thoughts about Betty
Boop when she alternated with Crusader Rabbit on Saturday morning.
Came on at 8 a.m., and I never missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall laughed. ``Betty has always been somewhat controversial.
And there was something of a scandal when frame art collectors
learned that the cartoonist would every once in a while sneak in a
nude frame of Betty.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding? That explains the impure thoughts. I always thought
it was the skirt and garter belt ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it flashed by too fast for anybody to detect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people,'' Randall continued, ``don't know that Popeye
made his movie debut in a Betty Boop cartoon. I think they dated
for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   That salty dog! No wonder Olive Oyl tormented him by flirting
with Bluto. I bought Donald Armstrong his doll and left Chester,
Ill. with an elevated respect for the sailor man and a rekindled
flame for Miss Boop.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
