<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What the real '60s panel would say about the decade
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with TEX-SIXTIES-SYMPOSIUM.)
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Let the LBJ Library have its stuffy symposium on
the '60s. We got to wondering what the ultimate assemblage of
intellectual candlepower on the decade might look like _ factors
such as death or dementia being no deterrent. Such as it is, here's
our dream team:
</P>
<P>
   Moderator: Jann Wenner , Rolling Stone founder and poster boy
for wanton boomer excess and self-indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   Panel: Timothy Leary , Harvard academic and LSD advocate; the
Maharishi Mahesh Yogi , leader of transcendental meditation
movement; Mama Cass , singer, the Mamas and the Papas; Hunter S.
Thompson , gonzo journalist; Malcolm X, civil rights activist and
subject of Spike Lee bio-flick; Janis Joplin, singer; Jimi Hendrix
, musician; Lee Harvey Oswald, got some 'splaining to do; Sly
Stone, singer (absent).
</P>
<P>
   Wenner: OK, before we getstarted can I get anybody a latte or a
subscription to Men's Journal?
</P>
<P>
   Thompson: Mrff ... glurg ... mescaline . . . BATS!
</P>
<P>
   Wenner: Genius, Hunter! We'll run it next issue. Dr. Leary,
you've been dead for three years now. What do the '60s mean to you?
</P>
<P>
   Leary: Dying is cool. It's the last, best trip. Unlock your
consciousness _ tune in, turn on, drop dead!
</P>
<P>
   Maharishi: Ah, but only by learning the unified field theory can
we embrace the oneness of all existence. Transcendental meditation
is the key to . . .
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm: You guys levitate, right?
</P>
<P>
   Maharishi: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm: So how come I just saw you get out of a cab?
</P>
<P>
   Mama Cass: I'd just like to say I don't think that one joke is
very funny. The one about how if I'd split that ham sandwich with
Karen Carpenter we'd both be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Joplin: I think it's time we admitted something: I was awful. If
I hadn't died, I'd be playing Monday nights on Sixth Street.
</P>
<P>
   Wenner: I've got no problem with that. Jimi?
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix: They're using ``Are You Experienced?'' to sell shoes,
man. Janis is pushing Mercedes and I got stinking jogging shoes?
</P>
<P>
   Wenner: We call it ``running.'' And Jimi, the '60s were being
commodified and repackaged by the spring of '68. It made me so much
money I need a truck to carry it around. You're just mad because
your estate was tied up in court for years.
</P>
<P>
   Wenner: Wenner.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix: Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Maharishi: Have I mentioned I know the Beatles?
</P>
<P>
   Cass: ``Revolution'' in a Nike commercial. More shoes. The
economy absorbed the counterculture, reverse-engineered the ethos
and then sold it back to us as nostalgia for our failed revolution.
You know who owns the '60s? Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix: Chick sounds like she's on public radio.
</P>
<P>
   Oswald: I am so tired of people defining me by just that one
day. I had a pretty interesting life, you know. But it's always,
``Lee Harvey Oswald, presidential assassin.'' It's just not fair.
And people are still mad.
</P>
<P>
   Wenner: Plus we know you didn't really do it.
</P>
<P>
   Oswald: No, it was me.
</P>
<P>
   Wenner: Was not.
</P>
<P>
   Oswald: Was too.
</P>
<P>
   Wenner: Uhhuh.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm: That's the chickens coming home to roost!
</P>
<P>
   Thompson: Mrphblb. . .Bad craziness. . .glub. . .ASSASSINS!
</P>
<P>
   Cass: Why does Johnny Depp think this guy is so cool?
</P>
<P>
   Oswald: My favorite part of the '60s was when Pete Townshend
bashed Abbie Hoffman's head in at Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   Wenner: I really, really hate myself.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix: You're a yuppie sellout, Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   Oswald: Yes?
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix (simultaneously): I'll have what he's having.
</P>
<P>
   Leary: They shot my ashes into space with Gene Roddenberry's!
I'm tripping through the stars!
</P>
<P>
   Cass: In point of fact, I had a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Beach writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
