<HEADER>
A3908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-SIXTIES-SYMPOSIUM     05-12 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-SIXTIES-SYMPOSIUM13-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Symposium on the Sixties promises to be, well, less freaked-out
than the decade it explores
</P>
<P>
   By Don McLeese
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ My good friend Jimmy slept with a pistol under
his pillow until 1977. Toward the end of the previous decade, he
had returned from a tour of duty as a Marine in Vietnam with a bad
case of the jitters and a penchant for barroom fistfights. It was
only when he was drunk that he'd talk about the war, until he
passed out, and it was only by passing out that he could sleep.
When he awoke with a start, he'd grab for his gun. Home from the
war, he was still fighting a war that was raging inside his head.
</P>
<P>
   That was his Legacy of the Sixties.
</P>
<P>
   I could never know exactly what he'd gone through, just as he
had only the faintest idea what he'd been missing back home. He
joked sardonically about catching up on some of that ``free love,''
but how to explain the long hair, the acid flashbacks, the street
protests, the infatuations with Buddha and Marx, the fashion
disasters of beads and bell-bottoms? How to explain the
inscrutable, amphetamine ravings of an electrified Bob Dylan, who
just a year or two earlier had been strumming protest songs on his
acoustic guitar?
</P>
<P>
   How had everything moved so far so fast? How had the passive
resistance of Martin Luther King Jr. escalated so quickly into the
aggressive militancy of the Black Panthers, the separatism of
Stokely Carmichael? How were ideals of peace transformed into the
``bringing the war home'' violence of the Weathermen's ``Days of
Rage''? How had universities become overrun by protestors who
seemed to be majoring in anarchy and minoring in hashish? Where was
the innocence of ``I Want To Hold Your Hand'' amid the marijuana
haze of ``Sgt. Pepper''?
</P>
<P>
   Was this the dawning of a new consciousness? Not the hokey ``Age
of Aquarius'' of ``Hair,'' but a shift in values more subversive
and pervasive, one that opened the doors of perception and threw
the very conception of reality up for grabs?
</P>
<P>
   Or was this a culture collapsing under the weight of a
collective nervous breakdown? A mass ``freak out,'' in the parlance
of the age, a time when ``blowing your mind'' was considered a good
thing. For the walking wounded of the psychedelic revolution, this
was another Legacy of the Sixties.
</P>
<P>
   One suspects that it's a different ``Legacy of the Sixties''
that will be explored through this week's symposium by that name at
the University of Texas. Sponsored by the LBJ Library and School of
Public Affairs, the event runs through Friday, with all of its
panels and speeches free and open to the public. Topics to be
discussed range from space exploration and foreign policy through
civil rights and the counter culture, with Pulitzer Prize-winning
historian Arthur Schlesinger, Jr., the NAACP's Julian Bond and
retired anchorman Walter Cronkite among the participating
luminaries.
</P>
<P>
   For all of its breadth of cultural concern and depth of academic
legitimacy, the event seems curiously at odds with the spirit of
the '60s, at least as this semi-blown mind remembers it. The
symposium will not, you can rest assured, be a ``freak out.'' It
will not be a ``happening.'' It will, instead, examine the
century's most culturally cataclysmic decade from the far side of
the generation gap, from the perspective of the institutions _
governmental, academic, journalistic _ that found themselves under
siege through that tumultuous era.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium is additionally serving as a reunion of the
Johnson administration (some 1,500 members have been invited),
which makes the '60s spin seem all the more peculiar. For the
Johnson alumni to celebrate the '60s is a little like Napoleon's
forces holding their homecoming at Waterloo. For if the '60s found
the American culture in a state of civil war _ and the images that
persist of tear gas, police dogs and the National Guard suggest
nothing less _ then the Johnson presidency was that war's most
notorious casualty. It could have withstood a political debate over
the war in Vietnam; what it couldn't survive was the daily chants
of ``Hey, hey, LBJ, how many kids did you kill today?''
</P>
<P>
   History already has been kinder to Johnson than the street mobs
were. As the symposium is sure to highlight, his presidency was far
more aggressive in its commitment to racial equality than the
federal government had ever been before (or since). The progressive
programs of the ``Great Society'' reinforce the impression that
Johnson could have been a great domestic president if he hadn't
fallen into the quagmire of Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, the aftershocks of the '60s continue to
reverberate _ from the fallout from the sexual revolution to calls
for censorship on entertainment to political campaigns with
candidates who either ``didn't inhale'' or dismiss such behavior as
youthful folly. With the return of the pendulum toward Puritanism,
there are those who continue to scapegoat the '60s as the decade
when the American dream turned to nightmare, when parental
permissiveness, artistic license, pharmaceutical experimentation
and spiritual restlessness all contributed to the decline of
Western civilization and the death of common decency as we know it.
Too much freedom, too much rebellion, too much '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, once opened, Pandora's Box is awfully hard to close. For
the '60s found a country that was forged in the spirit of freedom
pushing those freedoms to their limits, renewing its revolutionary
fervor. We've learned from the excesses and indulgences of the
decade; we've long since realized that free love carries a heavy
price and that heaven isn't likely to manifest itself through a tab
of mescaline. It was rumored during the '60s that the ingestion of
certain drugs would change our chromosomes and alter the genetic
makeup of our babies. Instead, the '60s themselves were what
changed the cultural DNA, altering the psyche of the nation in a
manner that made it impossible to return to ``Father Knows Best.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, those of us who questioned authority
throughout the '60s are learning from our babies how it feels to
have our own authority questioned. And parents raised on the rock
of the Doors and Jimi Hendrix now wring their hands over Marilyn
Manson.
</P>
<P>
   Don McLeese writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
