<HEADER>
A3909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WICCA-BELIEFS13-COX     05-12 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WICCA-BELIEFS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wicca Beliefs
 &HT;    (EDS: Sidebar to MILITARY-WITCHES)
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The groups that practice modern-day Wicca are autonomous, though
some may associate with umbrella organizations in the neo-pagan
movement.
</P>
<P>
   While their rituals can vary, they share some common beliefs,
such as:
</P>
<P>
   _Ethics. Wiccan groups have their own version of the Golden
Rule, called the Wiccan Rede, which states ``an it harm none, do
what you will,'' meaning you don't harm yourself or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   _Deities. Wiccans worship the sacred in nature and believe in
dual deities, the god and goddess, who often are personified in
Mother Earth and Father Sky.
</P>
<P>
   _Magic. The use of the psychic energies witches believe surround
all living things. They use rituals, dance, chants, visualization
and hypnosis to focus and direct the energy for healing, protecting
and aiding each other.
</P>
<P>
   _Text. They do not have a sacred text, like the Bible or Koran,
but most Wiccan groups have a book of rituals and lore called ``The
Book of Shadows.'' They often add new material.
</P>
<P>
   _Holidays. There are eight major holidays, solar festivals
called sabbats. The dates of some depend on the lunar calendar and
the observances vary. The celebrations are Samhain, the Celtic new
year on Oct. 31 celebrating the fall harvest; Yule, winter solstice
in December, usually around the 20th or 21st; Imbolc or Candlemas,
recognizing the growing warmth of the sun, the first sign of the
rebirth of spring, observed Feb. 1 or 2; Ostara, the spring equinox
in March, usually around the 21st; Beltane, the May 1 observance of
the marriage of the god and goddess; Litha, the summer solstice
that usually falls around June 21; Lammas or Lughnasadh, observing
the first harvest on Aug. 1; and Mabon, the autumn equinox, around
Sept. 21, recognizing the second harvest time.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
