<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WICCA-HISTORY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wicca History
 &HT;    (EDS: Sidebar to MILITARY-WITCHES)
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In ancient times, pagans were the people who
lived in the countryside, but by the Middle Ages the meaning had
changed as the Roman Catholic Church used the word to describe
anyone who was Jewish, Muslim or practiced an indigenous religion.
</P>
<P>
   Things got messy from there, with charges of paganism and
witchcraft used against church heretics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1486, two Dominican monks wrote a book, ``Malleus
Maleficarum'' (``Witches' Hammer''), espousing myths that have
transcended the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the book that really defined the stereotype of the
modern witch,'' said Derek Collins, an assistant professor of
classics in the University of Texas religious studies program.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the book, witches are described as mostly women who are
more susceptible to the influence of demons,'' Collins said. ``It
also talks about women using the fat of babies for an ointment to
help them fly to meetings on broomsticks and chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The women, the book's authors purport, go to group meetings
where they worship and have sex with demons.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are largely monkish fantasies,'' said Collins, who
teaches a course on the history of witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   The 16th-century Protestant Reformation brought some new ideas,
including the myths that demonic spirits can inhabit toads, frogs
and cats, and that witches carry the devil's mark: moles and
birthmarks.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that in the 16th and 17th centuries, 50,000 to
100,000 people, about three-quarters of them women, were killed
after being accused of witchcraft, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   While people today continue to spread the myths about paganism
and witchcraft, many scholars and religious leaders are keenly
aware that some paganistic rituals have become Christian
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The date of Jesus' birthday, Dec. 25, is believed by many
scholars to have a direct correlation to the pagan festival of
Yule, the celebration of the winter solstice. A lighted tree and
burning of the yule log symbolized the divine gift of fire to
humanity in many European pagan customs. Easter is associated with
the rabbit and eggs that were used by pagans in Ostara, the
celebration of the spring equinox, to represent fertility and
eternal life. Many of the saints' days commemorated by the Catholic
Church fall on the holidays of pagan gods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paganism as an idea really developed in the shadow of the
Roman Catholic Church, and as the Catholic Church conquered Europe,
it didn't reject the local pagan traditions _ it simply absorbed
them,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
