A3911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-EDITORIAL13-COX     05-12 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-EDITORIAL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: Guns and politics remain an incendiary mix
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gabfest on youth violence which occurred at the White House
this week was notable for the absence of two key players: the
National Rifle Association and top Hollywood executives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, President Clinton used the meeting to reiterate the
gun-control package he proposed immediately after the Columbine
High School shooting massacre in Littleton on April 20. And, while
the NRA wasn't invited, the president did get support for his plan
from three major gun manufacturers and the American Shooting Sports
Council.
</P>
<P>
   That's because some of it, but by no means all of it, makes
sense. In particular, it's highly appropriate to close loopholes
that make it easier for minors or criminals to obtain weapons
through gun shows than at retail stores. Additionally, establishing
a more efficient system of tracing guns found at crimes scenes
could be useful in tracking people who act as conduits for
criminals to obtain weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan also calls for prohibiting people from ever
owning weapons if they have been convicted of violent crimes as
juveniles. While that is logical, it is largely symbolic with
little practical effect. One need only look to the numbers of
convicted adult felons who cannot legally own weapons but still
obtain them illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision would hold parents criminally liable if their
juvenile children use weapons to commit crimes. That's reasonable
if parents are willfully negligent in allowing their children easy
access to guns but not if the parents took normal precautions such
as keeping their guns locked.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Clinton's plan would make it illegal for anyone under
age 21 to own guns of any kind. That's an overreaction. For
millions of normal and well-adjusted youngsters, getting that first
shotgun at age 16 or younger in order to sit in a duck blind at
dawn with Dad extends a time-honored American tradition. Moreover,
it seems a slap in the face to tell 18-year-olds they are old
enough to carry weapons, fight and possibly die for their country,
but they can't own a firearm in civilian life.
</P>
<P>
   On the cultural side, Clinton used the meeting to mildly upbraid
his buddies in Hollywood for churning out the violent nihilism
which is all too often emblematic of contemporay movie making. But
the only solid cultural proposal to come out of Monday's meeting
was an agreement with America Online and video-game manufacturers
to limit the availability of violent video games on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There is merit to portions of Clinton's gun-control plan. A part
of that merit is political _ it will allow the president and
Congress to say to the American people, ``See, we've done
something.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as the NRA said in absentia Monday, there is decidedly more
merit in most of the thousands of gun laws already on the books.
Better enforcement of those existing laws will do more to reduce
violence than adopting packages of new laws which are of little
practical value and only infrequently enforced.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in The Daily Sentinel, Grand Junction,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
