<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How about the '50 smartest people'?
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ `Jeffie, do you think I'm beautiful?''
Bernard Thomas asked as I pulled up to the pump at the corner
service station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, B.T.,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   My old high school classmate shook his head sadly, took the hose
from its socket and began pumping my gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's with the vanity, B.T.?'' I asked. ``Since when have you
made looks your priority? (No answer.) ``Beautiful? No . . . but
you're definitely not the ugliest bean in the soup. Can you live
with that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can,'' he sighed, ``but I've been wondering whether my
grandchildren can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``B.T., those children love you. They're not about to stop
because you can't win a beauty contest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be so sure, Jeffie. Teenagers look at things different.
Check out this week's People magazine for the list of ``The 50 Most
Beautiful People in the World.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have, and it's nothing new. They've been making that list a
cover story every year since 1990. It's mostly models and
entertainers. Don't be hurt you didn't make . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't make it, and neither did a lot of other people I
can think of.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're thinking about me, don't. The editors' strategy was
to figure out which celebrities will sell the most magazines, throw
in pictures of a few other good-lookers and stir up a little
controversy. I'm looking forward to the letters to the editor. The
beautiful people issue sells out, and the publishers laugh all the
way to the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm not laughing, not even a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see that, and I can't understand why.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You would if you coulda seen my grandchildren when the
magazine came in the mail. They musta argued over a hour about who
shoulda made the list and who shoulda been left off. They argued
about hunks and babes until I just about puked. A senator got
picked, not 'cause he's doing such a good job but 'cause he looks
pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to admit,'' I teased, ``being a hunk draws votes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeffie, that could mean how you look's more important than
what you do or how you do it.'' The more B.T. talked, the gloomier
he looked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give People credit. The list includes a little
something for everybody of every age, race and background.'' I said
to lighten the tone. ``That's good marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   My tactic didn't work. ``It's the 'marketing' what's got me
upset,'' B.T. said. ``Looks over substance. And we're buying it
everywhere. My grandchildren look like me, and I don't want them
thinking they got to be beautiful to be recognized for what they
do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they won't. Magazine covers emphasize physical beauty
because beauty sells. It's not supposed to be a values statement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe not to us, but I'm not so sure about the kids. I noticed
that this month when my Ebony magazine came. This singer, Lauryn
Hill, one of People's 50 beauties, was on the cover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have that issue. She was also on the cover of Time a few
weeks back for getting more Grammys than any other woman in a
single year. At 23, the sister's definitely more than just another
beautiful face.''
</P>
<P>
   ``True. But inside that Ebony was a story about a neurosurgeon
named Keith Richards. The brother's 41 and world-famous 'cause he
can slice a cancer out of a person's brain without disturbing the
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really? I've got the May issue at home. I've got to read about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you already read the cover story about this Miss Hill,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   I nodded, reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeffie, now you understand why I want to know how I measure up
in the looks department.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You take things too seriously, old friend. Just tell the
children our society judges people based on ability, not looks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold onto that thought, Jeffie.''
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
