</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP lawmaker letting freak flag fly
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Has state Rep. Talmadge Heflin let his brown
hair grow down to his shoulders because he's fixing to join the
World Wrestling Federation?
</P>
<P>
   Is the Houston Republican sporting this very un-GOPish hairdo
because he's going to begin a new life on the Drag?
</P>
<P>
   Or is he wearing a hairdo that would have gotten him thrown out
of third grade in Bastrop a few years ago because he is starting a
grunge band?
</P>
<P>
   It sure looks like any of those could explain why the
conservative Heflin is letting his freak flag fly.
</P>
<P>
   But Heflin says his newfound hairstyle has nothing to do with a
philosophical shift. Heflin, 59, in his ninth term in the House,
says he let his hair grow long because he got a bad haircut here in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   So he's gone from having a bad hair day to having a bad hair
life.
</P>
<P>
   Heflin says he hasn't cut his hair since last July or August. Up
until the bad haircut, Heflin wore a regular businessman's haircut.
But now he looks like a new man, and the new man looks like David
Crosby. It's getting to the point where it looks like Heflin is
about to ask you for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the truth of the matter is, back last year I got a
bad haircut,'' Heflin said. ``I was forced to change barbers
because my barber retired. The reference I got just gave me a very
bad haircut, and I just decided I didn't need to pay for (another)
very bad haircut. I just let it grow, and I suppose I got used to
it and my family got used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody has gotten used to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does seem to kind of nag on people around here, though,
'cause it seems out of character for me,'' Heflin said. ``I still
have people come up and comment that it's aggravating to them. I
don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   Heflin added that part of the reason he hasn't cut his hair is
that he hasn't ``taken the time to find another barber. I've had
two or three people say, 'I've got a really good barber; why don't
you let me make you an appointment?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Why not indeed? I told Heflin the name of my barber, and he
didn't seem interested.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because Heflin just likes looking like a hippie. He
says this is the first time in his life he's had long hair. Maybe
he just enjoys that Woodstock skinny dip look. Maybe next session
he'll be taking up the mandolin.
</P>
<P>
   You want to know how big Heflin's hair is? I'll tell you. I saw
Heflin on the House floor chatting with a woman Tuesday, and his
hair was bigger than hers.
</P>
<P>
   I should mention that on Ricky Williams Day back in late
January, Heflin had his hair done up in dreadlocks with rubber
bands by his administrative secretary, Jennifer Wilhite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real envious,'' said Rep. Glen Maxey, an Austin Democrat.
``Those of us who can't seem to grow any hair have to look every
day at this guy. He must be approaching the big 6-0, walking around
with hair way past his shoulders. It's pretty outrageous. It's
pretty radical. He could have entered the aging hippie contest at
Pease Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxey added that if he was trying to guess which lawmaker would
grow long hair, Heflin's name would not come up. ``He is the most,
let's just say, conservative curmudgeon you would ever find,''
Maxey said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the reason Heflin has taken on that leftist look is that
the magical vibes from Barton Springs are getting to his brain.
After all, Heflin has been in the House since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells you why you should have term limits,'' Maxey said.
``If you stay in Austin long enough, you turn into an Austinite.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
