A3916 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN13-COX     05-12 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A touch of fate, a date with greatness
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Every time I visit the Golden Lamb, I peek into
the Charles Dickens room on the second floor and dream of staying
there one night, soaking up the stray molecules of literary
brilliance, that, who knows, may still be wafting around after 157
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday night before Mother's Day seemed the perfect time.
I called the Golden Lamb and _ fate ordained it _ there had been a
cancellation: the Dickens room.
</P>
<P>
   What a perfect antidote to the rigors of the previous weekend,
when, along with hundreds of other journalists, I attended the
National Writers Workshop in Indianapolis _ all of us little names
lured by the big names (best-selling novelist Jacquelyn Mitchard,
three Pulitzer Prize winners, the works).
</P>
<P>
   One of the weekend's themes was ``Stealing from the Classics,''
or borrowing techniques from literary giants. A good idea, and a
humbling one, reminding us that even the finest newspaper writing
is a long way from Fitzgerald or Faulkner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would anybody be reading any of our stuff 50, 100 years from
now?'' I wondered. Surveying the assembled luminaries, I remembered
John F. Kennedy's 1962 speech at a dinner honoring American Nobel
Prize winners: ``I think this is the most extraordinary collection
of talent, of human knowledge, that has ever been gathered at the
White House, with the possible exception of when Thomas Jefferson
dined alone.''
</P>
<P>
   How do you reconcile ambition and humility, dreams with
practicality? What's the point of trying to achieve good work, if
you can't be guaranteed greatness?
</P>
<P>
   Most of the conference headliners exhibited a modesty in
refreshing contrast with some of the brash young
hand-me-the-world-on-a-platter wannabes. The charmingly
down-to-earth Mitchard, author of the first Oprah Book Club
selection, The Deep End of the Ocean, said her success was a fluke.
Until ``anointed by the hand of Oprah,'' she said, she was ``an
obscure but respectable first-time author from Madison, Wis.''
</P>
<P>
   If her success was incidental, what were the odds against
Charles Dickens, a debtor's son? You're have a far better chance of
being ``Oprah-fied,'' after all, than being touched by the hand of
genius as was Dickens.
</P>
<P>
   But, if you're lucky, you can book the genius' bedroom. The
Dickens room boasts a walnut Victorian bed with a death-defying
12-foot headboard. But alas, its namesake never actually stayed
there overnight. On April 20, 1842, Dickens hopped a stagecoach to
Xenia, Ohio after an apparently unsatisfactory dining experience at
the Golden Lamb. In American Notes he wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask for brandy; but it is a temperance hotel, and spirits
were not to be had for love or money. This preposterous forcing of
unpleasant drinks down the throats of reluctant travelers is not
uncommon in America. . . . Perhaps the plainest course for persons
of such tender conscience would be a total abstinence from
tavern-keeping.''
</P>
<P>
   He sounds awfully mortal, this immortal, cranky and weary after
a hard day's journey on stagecoach. But that first bad review
brought the Golden Lamb untold business, and the Dickens room is
requested far and away more than those of any of the 10 presidents
who stopped there.
</P>
<P>
   So what if the Dickens bedroom is the closest I get to
greatness? The National Writers Workshop reminded me: It's a
privilege to write for a living.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a good conference, inspiring, invigorating.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been the most extraordinary collection of literary
talent that has ever been gathered in the Midwest, with the
exception of when Charles Dickens dined at the Golden Lamb, alone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
