<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINOR-COLUMN13-COX     05-12 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Let sitting books lie
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I called my mother the other morning to
give her the bad news, a little something no good daughter should
do two days after Mother's Day, but I had no choice. I am, after
all, a fallen Catholic with substantial residual guilt.
</P>
<P>
   So I had to tell her.
</P>
<P>
   I had to tell her I was never going to make the cover of Cosmo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think you've got the bosom for it,'' she said in full
sincerity, proving in short order that all good mothers really are
nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom,'' I said, near tears. ``That's not the point. The point
is I've put my foot in my mouth. I've spoken out when I shouldn't
have. I've embarrassed myself and, thus, you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom,'' I said. ``I've ostracized Kate White.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kate Who?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And I hung up and wept with wild joy.
</P>
<P>
   Kate White is the editor-in-chief of Cosmopolitan magazine, a
big job which means she is in charge of instructing American women,
mostly white American women, how to do our hair, lose 10 pounds and
make ourselves more orgasmic. Not in that order, of course.
</P>
<P>
   She also writes books, two so far. The first one was called Why
Good Girls Don't Get Ahead ... but Gutsy Girls Do. I never read it
and, thus, have had only two promotions in the last five years as
opposed to the 35 she so slyly recommends.
</P>
<P>
   OK. I made that last part up, that part about the 35 promotions.
But this next part is true: The title of White's newest book is 9
Secrets of Women Who Get Everything They Want ($12, Three Rivers
Press). And the chapter titles are even, as White likes to say,
even more ``irreverent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people don't understand that,'' she admits.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 1: Covet They Neighbor's Things.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 2: Bite Off More Than You Can Chew. (I did this and it
took me straight to Chapter 5. See title below.)
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 3: Don't Wait for the Right Moment. (Not a problem.)
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 4: Wear Your Heart on Your Sleeve. (Got that one
covered.)
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 5: Be Too Big for Your Britches. (See Chapter 2.)
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 6: Never Mind Your Own Business. (Done, ask my husband.)
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 7: Keep Your Elbows on the Table.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 8: Don't Sit Tight.
</P>
<P>
   And the ninth secret: Rest on Your Laurels. (I'm a master at
this; ask my editor.)
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit, I didn't pick up White's book at first. Scared
maybe? All those empowering chapter titles. All that talk of new
shoes and corporate climbing.
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt from Chapter 3: To get what you want, you have to
feel you deserve it, and, unfortunately, pouncing and snatching
don't allow much time for working on your sense of entitlement. Try
this shortcut: Go out and buy something absolutely expensive and
wonderful to wear, and get a haircut that gives you a whole new
look. When you dress and act like a movie star, you often feel like
one.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful stuff.
</P>
<P>
   So when Kate White called, when I actually had her on the line,
when I'd actually gotten past Miriam, her personal assistant, and
Celeste, her substitute secretary on Monday, when I'd actually been
given 15 minutes of her time, I just lost control of my senses.
</P>
<P>
   Why does this book annoy me? I asked her.
</P>
<P>
   And that's how I blew the cover of Cosmo.
</P>
<P>
   So I swear to you. If tabloid editor Steve Coz ever writes a
book, I am not picking it up. Not even one time. I swear I won't
and if I do I will never, ever request an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmopolitan is one thing. But my mother will never forgive me
if I blow the cover of the National Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
