</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A new Basketball era has begun
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is Year 1 A.M. for the National Basketball Association
playoffs _ the first year After Michael _ and the verdict is in: We
miss him as much as the Bulls did.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you rooted for him or against him, Jordan was the focal
point of both the season and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If you avoided investing any emotional capital in this shortened
regular season, you chose wisely. Watching regular seasons that
lead to 16 playoff spots is like watching cars circling the parking
lot at a mall, waiting for a spot near the door. Eventually, only
the very bad or the very unlucky don't get one.
</P>
<P>
   I followed the regular season on two levels.
</P>
<P>
   Level One: How many days would go by between player arrests for
driving while impaired?
</P>
<P>
   Level Two: How would what Jordan called his ``supporting cast''
do without him?
</P>
<P>
   The latter was the more interesting because when Jordan retired,
there was a small but loud group of fans/experts/seriously-confused
folks who considered Jordan overrated, most of them being from the
extended family of Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   I've always liked Pippen, but he showed he was just another good
player in his failure to lift the Bulls in the 1 1/2 seasons when
Jordan was on his successful crusade to prove baseball is hard.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Pippen landed in Houston, surrounded by two other
future Hall of Famers _ Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley _ and
Pippen's leadership skills propelled the Rockets to a fine
fifth-place finish in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the ``supporting cast'' worked similar miracles.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Kukoc and Ron Harper stayed in Chicago and led the New
Bulls to a scintillating last-place finish in the East. Dennis
Rodman put in guest-appearances with Carmen Electra, Jay Leno and
the Lakers in that order, then retired after he couldn't find his
shoes and socks. Steve Kerr surfaced in San Antonio, where he is a
sub. Luc Longley went to Phoenix, got hurt and got a tan.
</P>
<P>
   Any other questions about how great Jordan was?
</P>
<P>
   Now we have reached the playoffs, and, with Jordan sharing
quality time with his family on a golf course somewhere, the table
has no centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA and its television arm, NBC, are doing their utmost to
give us substitute themes:
</P>
<P>
   Are Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant capable of sharing one
lockerroom in LA?
</P>
<P>
   Is this Houston's last hurrah with the aging foursome of Hakeem,
Sir Charles, Scottie and Dorian Gray?
</P>
<P>
   What's the over-under on the number of civil disturbances
between the Knicks and Heat?
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone and John Stockton: Just good enough to lose again?
</P>
<P>
   Whose dome do you like better on those frisky 76ers _ Alan
Iverson's or Matt Geiger's.
</P>
<P>
   This is the peak time of the year for couch potatoes, carrots
and beans of all persuasions.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to my yearly mantra: Another playoff is going on
and the games are usually better than the NBA's, even if you can't
name 10 players or pronounce their names. (Hint: Roy is pronounced
``Wah.'')
</P>
<P>
   Miniscule TV ratings aside, there is no more exciting game than
playoff hockey. Every game is like the World Wrestling Federation
on skates, complete with morality plays and blood.
</P>
<P>
   Watch a period one of these nights, and if you're not hooked,
I'll ask Claude Lemeiux (pronounced ``Game Misconduct'') to come to
your house and explain the finer points of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Year 1 A.M. should be good, too, as soon as I figure
out the story line.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
