</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-FERGUSON13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sprint to the finish
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ You'll have to forgive Debbie Ferguson if she has
barely noticed this week's SEC Track and Field Championships. It's
just that, lately, life has threatened to lap the fastest woman in
University of Georgia history.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ferguson had to study for finals and then take the
exams. Then, her family came up from the Bahamas for her
graduation, and she had to find places for them to stay. Next was
the graduation, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, we had to move out of the dorms,'' said the defending
SEC and NCAA champion in the 100 and 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much pressure on me to do well at the SECs and the
NCAAs, but I've had so much going on, I haven't really had time to
even think about them,'' Ferguson said. ``I'm trying to stay
focused, but. . . '' she said. ``Basically, I'm trying not to
panic.''
</P>
<P>
   One might wonder why she would. Ferguson, after all, has won
every notable race and every conceivable award in collegiate track
and field. She's a four-time NCAA champion, six-time SEC individual
titleist, 16-time All-American and the current Jackie Joyner-Kersee
Award recipient, which goes annually to the top female performer in
college track.
</P>
<P>
   So why is Ferguson so nervous about this week's meet, which is
going to be held in her own back yard on the familiar track at
UGA's Spec Towns Track?
</P>
<P>
   ``So much about this sport has to do with adrenaline,'' said
Ferguson, a 1996 Olympic silver medalist as part of the Bahamas 400
relay team in the '96 Atlanta Games. ``Being at home, I'm afraid
I'm going to be too relaxed. I want to be on the edge. That's when
I do well.''
</P>
<P>
   She has another distraction. With respect to the SECs, Ferguson
has been focusing all of her training this year on the Bahama
nationals and, ultimately, the World Championships in Seville,
Spain, in August. A semifinalist in last year's Worlds, Ferguson is
determined to win a medal this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very goal-oriented,'' the senior from Nassau said. ``I set
goals, then go out and try to achieve them. In college, basically
I've achieved them all. I've won the SECs and the NCAAs, and I
graduated last Saturday. My next goal is the World Championships,
and I'm really focused on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that defending her SEC 100- and 200-meter
titles is not important. On the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the problem I'm having right now. It is important to
me,'' Ferguson said. ``You want to be at your peak all the time,
but that's impossible. I'm not sure I'll be at my best. It's a
little frustrating, but I'll do my best and whatever happens,
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't count Georgia track coach John Mitchell among those
worried about Ferguson's performance this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be if it wasn't on our own track,'' said Mitchell, who
will retire after this season. ``She wants to win here, big-time;
she wants to win here major-league. And the girls she's got to beat
here, she's going to have to beat (at the NCAA Championships) in
Boise. She's a fierce competitor. She'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson will get all she can handle in the SEC field. Although
she owns last year's fastest 100-meter time _ 10.97 _ her personal
best of 11.09 this season ranks behind two of her conference
colleagues. Tennessee's Kelli White posted a wind-aided 10.96 and
LSU's Peta-Gaye Dowdie has run an 11.03.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson still ranks first in the 100 meters heading into next
month's NCAAs, with Dowdie second and White fourth. In the 200,
Dowdie's ranked No. 1, with Ferguson and White right behind.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson's focus on life after college is understandable. She
has made enormous financial sacrifices while remaining an amateur
the last couple of years. She gave up at least $30,000 in prize
money last year, not including potential endorsements. And she
passed on the $10,000 that was offered along with her Olympic
silver medal.
</P>
<P>
   But Ferguson hasn't exactly wasted her time in the interim. She
graduated last week with a 3.07 in biology. When her track career
is over, she plans to become a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My academics come first, then athletics,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   With her college career drawing near a close, those priorities
will reverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track is my life,'' Ferguson said. ``It's how I got my
education. It's allowed me to travel around the world, to meet
people and do things. It's affected my whole life. It's like a
religion _ I preach it, and I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   SEC TRACK CHAMPIONSHIPS
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Thursday through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Spec Towns Track, University of Georgia campus, Athens,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defending champions: Arkansas (men); Florida (women)
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
