<HEADER>
A3921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-PREVIEW13-CO     05-12 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-PREVIEW13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Star Wars' preview wows members of its cast; critics less
enthusiastic
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Liam Neeson likens watching the highly anticipated
first Star Wars prequel to being very hungry and presented with a
tray of all your favorite foods. ``You have time to just grab the
french fries before it's taken away,'' said Neeson, who stars in
Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace as Jedi Knight Qui-Gon
Jinn.
</P>
<P>
   The first chapter of George Lucas' phenomenally successful space
saga flies by faster than the jet-propelled Podracers featured in
one of the film's most thrilling sequences. Five concurrent story
lines, nearly 2,000 visual-effects shots and a universe of
painstakingly detailed characters, sets and costumes whiz past.
</P>
<P>
   Neeson, an Oscar nominee for Schindler's List, said he needed to
see the film a few more times ``to just digest it.'' The Phantom
Menace opens next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The $120-million movie was screened over the weekend in New York
City for members of the foreign, television, print and radio media.
Attending the Saturday night screening were film stars Samuel L.
Jackson (Mace Windu), Natalie Portman (Queen Amidala), Jake Lloyd
(Anakin Skywalker), Pernilla August (Shmi Skywalker) and Ahmed Best
(Jar Jar Binks), as well as celebrity shock jock Howard Stern
(Jerk).
</P>
<P>
   Journalists were offered as much as $200 for an extra ticket by
fans and paparazzi staking out the Union Square movie theater and
Midtown Manhattan hotel, where interviews were conducted. The
individually numbered screening passes were scanned with
ultraviolet light at one of five security checkpoints for an
invisible watermark to verify authenticity. Under no circumstances
were they to be sold. Anyone secretly videotaping the film was to
be reported to management. ``We wouldn't want to see this film on
the Internet,'' a 20th Century Fox spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   As the lights went down, the audience cheered the Fox and
Lucasfilm logos, as well as the title card, opening crawl and first
appearances by familiar characters such as R2-D2. The actors loudly
cheered their fellow cast members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really good,'' Jackson said later. ``It worked. The whole
thing worked.'' The Oscar nominee for Pulp Fiction wasn't aware of
Episode 1's full story until he saw the film for the first time on
Saturday. ``I really hadn't had time to go on the Internet and read
the script,'' he said, laughing. ``So I had no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas only completed The Phantom Menace six days earlier, on May
1, with the final effects shot of horn-headed villain Darth Maul
(Ray Park) testing an electronic barrier with his double-bladed
lightsaber.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was the second screening for Lloyd, a 10-year-old actor
who plays the future Darth Vader as an innocent slave boy who is
strong with the Force. ``You get to catch more of the story (the
second time), because the first time you're just looking at
yourself, seeing how you did,'' said Lloyd, who previously played
Arnold Schwarzenegger's son in Jingle All the Way. ``The second
time you try to get the story and the third time you get the
story.'' Lloyd loved the film.
</P>
<P>
   Critical reaction was less enthusiastic and widely mixed. While
many jaded critics cheered the exciting Podrace and battle
sequences and applauded the end of the film, others found the
biggest movie event of the decade to be a big disappointment. More
than a few naysayers felt that the film lacked romance and was
geared too much to younger children. They also had problems with
the performance of one of the film's digitally rendered characters.
``It took me out of the movie,'' said Rene Rodriguez, film critic
for the Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Star Wars films have gotten generally bad reviews,
Lucas said. ``They have mostly been trashed one way or another,
especially in the major media. So I certainly expect not to do well
critically. I never have.'' He expects to do better with The
Phantom Menace than with some of the other films he has directed or
produced, such as Howard the Duck.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the director's chair for the first time since the
original Star Wars 22 years ago, Lucas is pleased with the result _
largely because film technology has finally caught up with his
vision. ``This is the one time I was able to sit down and basically
let my imagination run wild and not be hampered by, `Oh, I can't to
this, I can't do that, I can't go to Coruscant, I'll never be able
to do the buildings, I can't do a Podrace because that's
impossible.' I could sort of dream up whatever I wanted and I was,
for the most part, able to pull it all off.'' Lucas plans to direct
Episodes 2 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   Best, a former Stomp performer who created the movements and
provided the voice for the amphibious Jar Jar, said he was so
jazzed watching the film for the first time earlier last week that
it all went by too fast. ``Also, the first night I was sitting next
to Harrison Ford _ that flipped me out _ and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   The original trilogy's Han Solo was on the edge of his seat,
according to Best, who divided his attention between Ford and the
screen. ``So I know I missed something, but that was like, I'm
watching Star Wars: Episode 1 and Han Solo is right there!''
</P>
<P>
   Best thoroughly enjoyed the film and said the same went for
Ford. ``It's like everything Star Wars is supposed to be: Great
action, great story, great effects.'' Echoing his co-stars, Jar
Jar's alter-ego said The Phantom Menace is also extremely
fast-paced. ``As soon as you sit down, it's like, `Take this,' and
everything just sets off.'' Lucasfilm certainly hopes that fans
will go back for second and third helpings of those fries.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Larsen writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
