<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3922 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MYTHS13-CO     05-12 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-MYTHS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Myths about Kosovo can be dangerous
 &HT;    (EDS: FREELANCE MATERIAL _ not for use by NYT subscribers.)
 &HT;    By John Price
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service3
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There is a great deal of ``information'' floating
around about Kosovo these days, much of it useful and
thought-provoking. There are also a fair number of pundits whose
solemn pronouncements have more to do with their points of view
than any real understanding of the area.
</P>
<P>
   I am not a Balkan scholar. However, as a U.S. State Department
official from 1989 to '96, I dealt daily with the ancient places
and forces at work in Kosovo. One of the lessons I learned was that
myths are dangerous weapons. As we make decisions about whether to
escalate our presence in the Balkans, we should be sure that those
decisions are grounded in reality rather than myths we ``know'' to
be true.
</P>
<P>
   Myth 1: Kosovo is the Serbs' Jerusalem; they have a right to it.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Kosovo has tremendous emotional importance for Serbs.
However, in the past two months, Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and his army have made the Serbs' emotional attachment to
Kosovo as irrelevant as English claims to Calais. The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution recently featured a column by a writer who
maintained that our folly in Yugoslavia was in not reading Serbian
history, in not understanding how important Kosovo is to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, clutching the dead hand of the long ago is the
very source of Yugoslavia's tragedy. I have witnessed the ways in
which history can be used to justify all manner of atrocities;
crimes I cannot fully imagine even though I have seen the evidence
and talked to the victims. At some point, the international
community must be allowed to say, ``Enough.'' When a government
sets out to murder its citizens in a gruesome homage to history and
ethnic purity, we mock our creed by ignoring it.
</P>
<P>
   Myth 2: Milosevic is Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   It can be politically useful to dress up our adversaries as
Satan. However, Milosevic is not evil. Not like Adolf Hitler or
Joseph Stalin, anyway. When you sit in a room with him, he does not
conjure up visions of history's great villains. Rather, one
imagines Michael Corleone with a bad haircut. The way to deal with
him is not as a larger-than-life figure but as a calculating thug.
He will not be coaxed out of Kosovo. By the same token, he will not
disappear into his bunker with a pistol while flames lick Belgrade.
If we demonstrate a willingness to ``go to the mat,'' he will
consider his options and make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Myth 3: This is simply none of our business.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever your opinion of this president and his foreign policy,
do not fool yourself. Our national interest is now inextricably
bound up with the Kosovars and their sad little war. To the world,
this is not President Clinton's war but NATO's war, America's war.
Consider the results if we fail to roll back Milosevic. Ignore the
immediate consequences _ a ratification of butchery that borders on
genocide. Think instead of the geopolitical consequences of a NATO
bug-out. Actually, in Washington they have been thinking about it
for years.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. foreign-policy planners long ago predicted that Serb
repression could lead to an armed conflict in Kosovo. This, they
forecast, would result in massive refugee outflow. (Any of this
sound familiar?) Hundreds of thousands of embittered refugees would
destabilize the region and imperil the new architecture of Europe.
This destabilization could easily spark a generalized conflict in
Central and Southern Europe. Are there any doubts that the United
States could remain aloof from such a conflict? Which leads us to
the final, most dangerous myth of all.
</P>
<P>
   Myth 4: The Cold War is over; NATO's success or failure is
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Before this century was even half over, the United States had
sent troops to fight and die in two European wars. But, in the
years after, we averted another, even more cataclysmic war before
it could begin and ended a second before it could spread. In both
the Cold War and the implementation of the Bosnian peace, NATO made
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Having been sheltered behind this mighty bulwark for so long, we
forgot the world that preceded it. The 21st century can be a return
to that world: Today, in 1999, people are being rounded up, pushed
onto trains. Their daughters are being raped. Their sons are being
shot. Their houses are being burned. All because they belong to the
group that doesn't have the most guns.
</P>
<P>
   Or, we can build on the progress of the past 50 years. The way
to do that is not to abandon the fortress that protects us. Rather,
it is to jealously guard NATO's credibility and defend this world
we have built.
</P>
<P>
   John Price is a former foreign service officer who attends
Georgia State University law school.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
