<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESSE-JACKSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESSE JACKSON'S NO WARMONGER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It's understandable that some people would mistake
the Rev. Jesse Jackson for a member of the legendary singing group
the Temptations.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Temps, Jackson is tall, mustachioed and fast on his
feet. But William Kristol, editor of the conservative Weekly
Standard magazine and a commentator on ABC's ``This Week With Sam
Donaldson and Cokie Roberts,'' obviously believes that Jackson
possesses the supernatural powers the Temptations boasted about in
song.
</P>
<P>
   Kristol is critical of Jackson's successful mission to
Yugoslavia to win the release of three American GIs. So much so
that on ``Larry King Live,'' Kristol said Jackson's action had
``prolonged the war'' against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, Jackson has a huge opinion of himself and would
love to have the power to stop all wars. But to accuse him of
prolonging the Yugoslav war exceeds the most strident criticisms
ever leveled against him.
</P>
<P>
   To lay at Jackson's feet a war that has its roots in
centuries-old conflicts and retaliations is rhetorical overkill at
best and contemptuous illogic at worst. (With what unit of
measurement will Kristol gauge just how long Jackson extended the
war?)
</P>
<P>
   Such is Jackson's power, obviously, that eventually we'll learn
he's to blame for tornadoes, the Y2K problem and blue M&AMP;Ms.
</P>
<P>
   Kristol reveals a fascinating reflection of Jackson's most
persistent critics: On one hand, they deem him an irrelevant
globe-trotting sideshow ``meddling'' in foreign affairs. On the
other hand, they attribute to him the ability to alter world events
to the detriment of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson confounds his critics and makes them say silly things
because they continue to underestimate him. He wasn't expected to
win the release of the three captive Americans, just as he wasn't
expected to win the release of Lt. Robert Goodman from Syria in
1983, just as he wasn't expected to be a serious presidential
candidate in 1984 and again in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, so serious was Jackson's presidential run in 1988 (in
which he vanquished Al Gore) that there was a moment, after his 2
to 1 victory over Michael Dukakis in the Michigan caucuses, when he
scared the Democratic Party establishment with the possibility he'd
win the nomination. (The Blame Jesse Game continued when, in 1995,
Dukakis campaign manager Susan Estrich wrote a USA Today column all
but putting Dukakis' defeat to George Bush on Jackson, ignoring the
fact that her candidate had the personality of plywood.)
</P>
<P>
   Jackson can be a caricature of himself. His love for the camera
can be both annoying and comical. But the essence of the man is
that since his days as a student activist at North Carolina A&AMP;T, he
has devoted his life to social justice, taking seriously the
nonviolence he learned from Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   No, Jesse Jackson can't turn gray skies blue.
</P>
<P>
   Neither can he prolong a war.
</P>
<P>
   But he has the imagination and courage to bring three soldiers
home to their families.
</P>
<P>
   That's good enough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
