<HEADLINE>
BILL OFFERS FREE COLLEGE FOR CAPTURED TEXAS GIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas soldier held captive in the Balkans
until his release early this month would be eligible for a free
education at a state-supported university plus a stipend to live
on, under legislation approved by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Senators gave a unanimous thumbs-up Tuesday and sent to the
House the bill that would apply at present only to Army Spc. Steven
Gonzales of Huntsville. If other Texans were to be held captive
during future U.S. military actions, they too would receive
benefits under the bill introduced by Sen. Eddie Lucio Jr.,
D-Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, 22, and two other soldiers were captured March 31 in
Macedonia by Serbian ground forces after NATO began a bombing
campaign in an effort to halt Serbian ``ethnic cleansing'' in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The three were released May 2 to the Rev. Jesse Jackson. While
Gonzales was in captivity, Huntsville was awash in yellow ribbons
in a gesture of support.
</P>
<P>
   Before enlisting in the Army in 1996, Gonzales attended Texas
A&AMP;M University in College Station. Shortly after his capture, his
parents said he hoped to return to the university after completing
his military service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll turn that yellow ribbon into a full scholarship _
hopefully at Texas A&AMP;M,'' said Sen. Steve Ogden, R-Bryan, whose
district includes both Huntsville and the College Station.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
