<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAY HAS DOS SANTOS SHOOTING TO FOREFRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Paulo Dos Santos sat on the bench for the New England
Revolution in 1996 before being selected by Tampa Bay in the '97
supplemental draft, but his status wasn't any different with the
Mutiny, who had numerous talented midfielders.
</P>
<P>
   Dos Santos hooked up with the Rhode Island Stingrays of the USL
last season, and found success as an attacking midfielder. So Dos
Santos, who moved to Brockton from Cape Verde at age 14, got
another with the Revolution last summer and made the team this year
after a tryout.
</P>
<P>
   He has played four games (156 minutes), including starting
against Colorado May 1. Then last Saturday, Dos Santos scored the
deciding goal in a 1-0 shootout victory against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say that I like shootouts, but it's part of the
game,'' said Dos Santos, having practiced his one-on-ones against
backup goalkeeper Jeff Causey the last two weeks. ``Growing up an
an old-fashioned soccer fan, I was never involved with shootouts
but times have changed and it's a new thing here, and you have to
adapt to new rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The key was Dos Santos's second touch. ``The goalie usually
waits for your second touch to see what you're going to do,'' he
said. ``He flew out and I thought about going around him but it was
too risky so I kept it simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confident that I had a good chance to make it and you
have to keep thinking positive,'' added Dos Santos, who whose goal
gave the Revolution a 3-2 verdict in the shootout and sparked a
celebration. ``I blocked everything out on the shot. It was a great
moment. It was stuff that you always dream of.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been a standout everywhere: Brockton High (an
All-Scholastic), Mount Ida Junior College (his team was unbeaten in
two seasons), and the University of Rhode Island (ranked sixth in
the country his senior year before losing to Virginia in the
opening round of the NCAAs).
</P>
<P>
   Now Dos Santos wants to become a starter with the Revolution.
``It's the coach's decision and all I can do is keep working and be
patient waiting for the opportunity,'' he said, often running six
miles four times a week.
</P>
<P>
   He's never gotten frustrated with trying to make Major League
Soccer. ``That first season with the Revolution was the toughest
part of my career,'' said Dos Santos, his confidence saved by the
Stingrays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to take people on when I play, just like playing for
the Stingrays, which allowed me quite a bit of freedom. I've always
thought I could make it in this league. It was just being in the
right situation. I've seen players from the A League and the USL
that I've had good success against and they did well in the MLS,
and I feel I could make it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Walter Zenga (groin), who didn't practice Tuesday
will probably play against Columbus Saturday, as might midfielder
John Harkes (knee) . . . Anthony Latronica, the Boston Bulldogs
keeper, is a spare with the Revolution and will travel to Columbus
. . . The Crew might be without forward Brian McBride, who broke
his cheek bone last weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
