<HEADER>
A4068 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AL-GORE-MONEY-NYTSF &LR;      05-12 2548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-GORE-MONEY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL GORE'S MONEY MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JILL ABRAMSON  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    The vice president stood before 40 wealthy Democrats in the
Fifth Avenue palazzo of the Lazard Freres executive Steven Rattner,
a stunning place with marble columns and a view over the
Metropolitan Museum.
 &HT;    The guests, bathed in candlelight, nibbled at apple crisp and
whipped cream. To be here, each had promised to raise at least
$35,000 for Al Gore's presidential quest.
 &HT;    Gore began by recognizing some of the more luminous luminaries
in the room _ Eugene Ludwig, the former comptroller of the
Currency; Richard Gardner, former ambassador to Spain and Italy;
and a raft of Wall Street heavyweights.
 &HT;    Then it was time for a joke: the one Gore tells at every
fund-raiser, about an 8-year-old boy in Minnesota who wrote Gore a
sort of fan letter that called him ``the greatest vice president of
my time.'' There was a polite titter.
 &HT;    As Gore moved on to his studiously rehearsed vision for the 21st
century, the overwhelming impression was of a marble candidate in a
marble setting.
 &HT;    So far in this young campaign, the issues that Gore loves _ from
his ``practical idealism'' to his ``electronic-privacy bill of
rights'' _ have lacked a certain electricity.
 &HT;    But that is not to say that the Gore 2000 effort is a listless
one. To the contrary, the candidate may still seem like the robot
caricature of a thousand late-night monologues, but his campaign's
fund-raising calls to mind a dizzyingly effective machine.
 &HT;    In the first three months of 1999 alone, Gore fund-raisers piled
up $8.9 million in contributions - easily a record, and a sum that
has scared off all challengers for the Democratic nomination except
Bill Bradley.
 &HT;    Between now and the Democratic convention in Los Angeles in
August 2000, Gore intends to raise a staggering $55 million. The
soul of this fund-raising machine is the candidate himself, with
his vast and assiduously built network of supporters stretching
from his native Tennessee to Wall Street and west to Silicon Valley
and Hollywood, his reputation as an outstanding bottom-line
salesman and his plain old tirelessness.
 &HT;    Gore will spend countless hours on the
free-range-chicken-and-Chardonnay circuit in the months ahead,
rolling out a green carpet leading (he hopes) straight to the
Democratic nomination.
 &HT;    A massive early war chest is more important in this election
than ever before because New York and California, both key,
expensive states, now have early primaries. Gore's facility with
total-immersion fund-raising, then, may be his greatest strength.
 &HT;    Yet it may also prove to be his greatest vulnerability. There is
the danger that Gore will ultimately focus too much on
fund-raising, because he's simply so good at it, instead of solving
his campaign's weaknesses _ such as finding the issues and the
message that broad swaths of voters can really get excited about.
 &HT;    If he does not do this, and thus move the story of his campaign
away from fund-raising, the defining impression left in the minds
of the electorate could simply be his ability to charm the
deep-pockets crowd. That could be disastrous at a moment when his
standing in the polls is anemic and campaign-finance reform is
popular.
 &HT;    Gore's opponents are no doubt aware of this potential weakness.
Before it's all over, there will almost certainly be attack ads
from foes recalling his role in the 1996 election as the Democratic
Party's ``solicitor in chief,'' cold-calling donors for cash, not
to mention his star turn with a chorus line of Buddhist nuns in
saffron robes.
 &HT;    ``Political money is the wrong game to monopolize in the year
2000,'' says Fred Wertheimer, a campaign-finance-reform advocate.
``That's particularly true for Gore,'' Wertheimer adds, because of
the 1996 scandals. ``By raising so much money, Gore has become
emblematic of the Washington money culture that the American people
find repugnant,'' Wertheimer continues. ``It's a high-risk
strategy.''
 &HT;    Even so, for Gore or any other candidate these days,
fund-raising remains a necessity, not an option. Gore declined to
speak with me on the record about fund-raising, but did allow me,
as his campaign kicked into high gear, to tag along and get a
firsthand look at events that are generally off-limits to the
press.
 &HT;    The day that ended at chez Rattner was a typical jumble of
official appearances sandwiched between unofficial schmooze
sessions with fat cats. It began in the Bronx at the Helen Keller
Elementary School in the heart of the Co-op City housing
development, where Gore read aloud to a second-grader dressed in a
neat uniform, who confided that she wants his job someday.
 &HT;    Then the motorcade rushed him to a private dining room at the
Four Seasons, where he joined rich Manhattan executives for a feast
of black bass with squid-ink risotto. In the afternoon, there were
private chats with other prominent New York Democrats.
 &HT;    For cocktails, Gore met with a group of African-American
business leaders who have each pledged to raise $5,000 for the
campaign, at an apartment on upper Park Avenue. Dinner, with a
$10,000-a-head bounty, was with a group of executives from the
communications industry at the trendy East Side restaurant Daniel.
And finally, dessert at Rattner's.
 &HT;    The day's take: an impressive $1.5 million.
 &HT;    What is Gore's appeal? David Geffen, sitting in his $47.5
million, nine-acre Beverly Hills estate, tells me that he finds
fund-raising ``time-consuming and irritating.'' But he intends to
spend a lot of time doing it for Gore.
 &HT;    ``I view this as an important election,'' says the Hollywood
mogul, clad in a white polo shirt, jeans and white sneakers.
``We're going to work very hard to elect Gore and replace the most
radical House and Senate in history.''
 &HT;    Seated next to Geffen is Andy Spahn, formerly Gary Hart's
national finance director and now a fund-raising and political
adviser to Geffen and his Dreamworks partners, Steven Spielberg and
Jeffrey Katzenberg. Geffen and Spahn say they will very likely hold
a dinner for Gore later in the campaign, much like the intimate
1996 meals Bill Clinton shared with Geffen and 15 or so Hollywood
execs, where $2 million was raised.
 &HT;    ``My biggest worry about the vice president between now and the
election is that he become the best communicator he can be,''
Geffen says. He worries that Gore does not have the sparkle that
his boss transmits so effortlessly. Some of Gore's other Hollywood
supporters voice the same concern. Famous directors such as
Spielberg and Rob Reiner are eager to race to Washington to give
their man some emergency speech coaching.
 &HT;    ``He's really funny, but he has a hard time letting his natural
personality emerge,'' frets Reiner, whose film ``An American
President,'' about a picture-perfect commander in chief, was made
with research help from Gore's staff.
 &HT;    The key to fund-raising is one-to-one networking, and Gore has
proven extremely effective at tapping connections from every phase
of his life. In Hollywood, for example, his longtime ambassador is
John Cooke, a Disney executive, who expects Gore's California
effort to raise millions. While Bradley has longstanding
friendships in Hollywood and is close to the Disney chairman,
Michael Eisner, as well as to Barry Diller, Gore has sewn up the
team from Dreamworks.
 &HT;    Farther up the coast are the executives in the high-tech
industry who have dubbed themselves the Gore Techs. During the
second Clinton-Gore inauguration, the vice president set aside two
hours to meet with a dozen executives from Silicon Valley.
 &HT;    The group, which included the high-tech venture capitalist John
Doerr, the Intuit chairman Scott Cook and the Marimba software
founder Kim Polese, were wowed by Gore's fluency with the New
Economy.
 &HT;    ``He really gets it,'' says Joe Kraus, the co-founder of Excite,
who has attended several Gore Tech meetings and has kicked in
$1,000 to Gore.
 &HT;    At a Gore fund-raiser last month at the Woodside, Calif.,
mansion of Janina Pawlowski, co-founder of E-Loan, his Silicon
Valley supporters raised $400,000 for their candidate.
 &HT;    Besides the nice turnout and breathtaking view, Gore had a rare
loose public moment. He and Tipper bopped with a band that included
two former members of the Grateful Dead; Tipper even played the
bongos. Then they repaired to dinner at Doerr's house with 30
Democratic donors, who raised $10,000 apiece.
 &HT;    John Tyson, an international business investor, is even raising
money from Gore's class at Harvard, where he was one of the future
vice president's roommates. He recalls long discussions with Gore
about Vietnam and civil rights as they lay in their bunk beds.
 &HT;    ``I always knew he'd be president,'' Tyson says. ``He does well
in an environment where there is a lot of pressure.'' At a recent
gala in Washington, Tyson solicited $20,000 from the class of '69,
and is now expanding his efforts to other classes.
 &HT;    Gore's prowess at the money game is one of the things that
attracted Bill Clinton in 1992. As magnetic as Clinton was on the
fund-raising circuit, he always hated actually asking for money.
Gore, in contrast, is known as the best ``closer'' in the business,
someone who can get contributors to commit to a specific amount and
write their checks on the spot.
 &HT;    When he was a senator, his family kept an apartment on Capitol
Hill that he used as a fund-raising safe house, where he could make
calls between votes. And he did not disappoint Clinton, helping
raise millions after he joined the ticket in 1992 and a staggering
$40 million for the party in 1996.
 &HT;    Add to the Gore network, then, some of Clinton's cash
constituencies. One is Wall Street, although there is some
lingering doubt over the vice president's environmentalism, which
some deem as antibusiness. Gore has strategically set his sights on
some of the party's younger financial powers _ such as his recent
host, Rattner.
 &HT;    During the 1996 campaign, he orchestrated a seat next to Rattner
at a fund-raising reception and subsequently called him to seek his
counsel on economic issues. When it came time to gear up the 2000
fund-raising effort, Rattner signed on to play his part in a
process that even he concedes ``could not possibly be what
Jefferson had in mind.''
 &HT;    While politicians pay lip service to the need for Congress to
pass campaign-finance reform, the bottom line is that in the
absence of such reforms, they will play by the rules of the game as
they exist, and play with a vengeance. Skyrocketing campaign costs
have sparked the fund-raising equivalent of a nuclear arms race,
and the 2000 election will be the most money-infused in history.
 &HT;    George W. Bush raised $7.6 million in the first three months of
1999, while Bradley managed to pull in a respectable $4.3 million.
 &HT;    Post-Watergate election-law reforms aside, the campaign-finance
system has become shot through with loopholes. Laws limiting
individuals to giving $1,000 during the primaries simply mean an
emphasis on rounding up donors who have lots of friends who can
also write $1,000 checks.
 &HT;    Candidates who accept federal matching funds must limit their
spending to $33.5 million in the primaries, but there are legal
ways to skirt the rules. Money spent on fund-raising and on legal
and accounting costs does not count toward the limit, and
candidates are allowed to establish separate funds for complying
with the arcane and complex federal election laws.
 &HT;    In the general election, there is a much bigger loophole to
exploit. Although the nominees don't raise any more private money
and receive $70 million in public funds for the general election,
parties can raise ``soft money'' _ unrestricted donations from
unions, wealthy individuals and corporations _ to help elect their
candidates. The two parties combined raised more than $250 million
in such contributions in 1996 _ and it was in the soft-money arena
that most of the campaign fund-raising abuses occurred.
 &HT;    The ghosts of past scandals loom over Gore's current efforts
more than anyone else's. ``There will be heightened scrutiny after
1996,'' says Lyn Utrecht, outside counsel to the Gore campaign. So
the vice president's finance and legal advisers have created an
unusually onerous set of fund-raising rules.
 &HT;    First and foremost, Gore will not personally solicit donors with
telephone calls, a practice he stopped in 1997. He has also vowed
not to use his official residence for ticketed fund-raising events.
 &HT;    Campaign lawyers have held more than 300 briefings on election
law for volunteer solicitors, and the campaign is scrutinizing the
backgrounds of all solicitors and any checks drawn on foreign bank
accounts. Campaign workers are told to follow even the smallest
rules, right down to making sure all solicitation letters go out on
campaign stationery.
 &HT;    Still, concedes Gore's campaign manager, Craig Smith, ``No
system is going to be perfect.'' In fact, there have already been a
few glitches. Some suspicious donations that came in money orders
may be returned. And the 850,000 pieces of direct mail sent out by
the campaign in February went to some donors whose checks the
campaign would not want.
 &HT;    Among the recipients: Johnny Chung, the California donor who
recently told federal investigators that some of the $400,000 he
had contributed to Democrats (since returned) came from the Chinese
military.
 &HT;    Some of Gore's longtime fund-raisers are clearly irritated with
the ``by the book'' mentality. A Miami solicitor complained that he
had to get the text of his thank-you notes to donors approved by
Washington. A solicitor in Los Angeles griped about being inactive
while a background check was run: ``I could have raised $100,000 in
those two weeks.''
 &HT;    But perhaps most critically, Gore, to maintain his front-runner
status, may concentrate too much on the money. That's what Gary
Koops thinks is happening, and his opinion is worth a listen. Now a
Washington public-relations consultant, Koops was an adviser to
Sen. Phil Gramm in 1996 _ when Gramm raised $8 million in the first
three months of 1995, setting a record that Gore has just beaten.
 &HT;    Gramm too was a powerful fund-raiser, and he didn't even make it
to the primaries. As Koops puts it: ``'We've got the money' isn't a
good campaign message.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Jill Abramson  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jill Abramson is Washington editor of The New York Times.) &LR;
</P>
