<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN CLUBS ARE NOW DOMINANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, Italy's Serie A was being stifled by
insularity and rocked by betting scandals. Now, the best foreign
players flock to Italy. And Lazio and Milan, both relegated after
it was determined one of their matches had been fixed in 1980, are
the country's top two teams.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has recovered from those dark days and president Sergio
Cragnotti has revitalized the club, even has it quoted on the Milan
stock exchange. Milan has thrived under Silvio Berlusconi, and
could begin a new cycle of success.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams will be in the Champions League next year, with the
field expanded to include four Italian clubs. Juventus will not
qualify, though only two weeks ago it was on the verge of
eliminating Manchester United in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Juventus was the first Italian club to adjust to FIFA's
3-points-for-a-win change, and has consistently been the country's
best team since 1994. But Juve's motives must be questioned after
the departure of several top players. Certainly, Juventus could
hardly refuse Atletico Madrid's $20 million offer for Cristian
Vieri in 1997. But Vieri soon returned to Italy; he scored the
clinching goal off a marvelous pass from Roberto Mancini in a 2-0
victory over Bologna that maintained Lazio's 1-point edge over
Milan.
</P>
<P>
   European soccer is changing. And merchandising, shareholding,
and television rights are joining gate receipts and player sales as
major sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United has grasped this better than most clubs.
United has avoided instability with the combination of a regular
revenue stream _ it is rated the world's most profitable club _ and
the resoluteness of coach Alex Ferguson. Unlike Juventus,
Manchester United has seldom sold players in recent years. United
has made few changes in recent years and is headed for a showdown
with Bayern Munich in the Champions League final in Barcelona May
26, its first appearance in the final since 1968 and the first by
an English club since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   A $1.06 billion takeover bid by Rupert Murdoch was successfully
resisted by Manchester United supporters, who want to retain their
input into the club and also maintain a balance between soccer and
spectacle. This is the best example of Manchester United's
statement of purpose, though the club's director, Martin Edwards,
disagrees. Of course, Edwards would have made an enormous profit
had Murdoch's offer been approved.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will Lazio or Milan likely dispense with their top players
after this season. They simply cannot risk missing out on the
Champions League.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Building an advantage
</P>
<P>
   Columbus Crew Stadium is alliterative but hardly seems a name to
rival Maracana or Bernabeu. But when the Crew meet the Revolution
in the stadium's opener Saturday, it could signal one of the most
significant events in professional soccer in the United States. The
22,500-seat stadium is the first built primarily for soccer in the
US since Fall River entrepreneur Samuel Mark constructed the
15,500-capacity Mark's Stadium in North Tiverton, R.I., in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Mark's Stadium drew capacity crowds for big matches involving
the Fall River Marksmen. But after the decline of the American
Soccer League in the 1930s, the stadium was abandoned. The Marksmen
won the ASL title six times, but Mark changed the name of the team
to the New York Yankees and moved the team to Yankee Stadium in
1931.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, professional soccer teams have seldom had control of
stadiums in the United States, almost insuring their demise. The
Boston Minutemen and New England Tea Men, for example, never had
dependable stadium setups in the 1970s. Though they often outdrew
the Red Sox, the Tea Men transferred to Jacksonville in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the aesthetics of the game, soccer, like baseball,
requires a specific stadium. The game thrives when performed on
wide, well-manicured fields, free from extraneous influences.
Soccer is also best viewed in relatively intimate surroundings,
with no running tracks surrounding the field, creating an
empathetic feel.
</P>
<P>
   This is among the most commendable of experiments conducted by
Major League Soccer and raises the question why other teams have
not built similar stadia.
</P>
<P>
   Le Stade Crew has a better chance of succeeding than Fort
Lauderdale's Lockhart Stadium because the Crew should have more
control of its use.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Hunt, the primary investor in the Crew, has often been
ahead of sports entrepreneurs in this country. Hunt suffered for
his vision, enduring some heavy resistance from fellow NFL owners
in the 1970s and '80s, whose policies were later determined to be
restraint of trade violations.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the sensibility of owners such as Hunt and the late
Joe Robbie, Hunt and others such as Phil Anschutz and the Kraft
family operate without having to fight for the right of
cross-ownership. This has opened the door to huge investments into
sport in the United States, and could lead to even more, especially
if the Columbus facility proves viable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
