<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLA-FIGHTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATCHED-UP KLA FIGHTERS AWAIT RETURN TO BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ The first shot did not stop him. Neither did
the second or the third. But by the twenty-third bullet Agron
Berisha was on the ground, awake and waiting to die.
</P>
<P>
   He lived.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 22-year-old soldier is recuperating in the six-room
alley apartment where the Kosovo Liberation Army sends its wounded
to heal. Open eight months, scores of foot soldiers and a few KLA
officers have been treated at what they call ``the hospital,''
where most of the medicine is dangerously outdated and the
intravenous stands are rusty with age.
</P>
<P>
   KLA doctors do visit daily, but surgery and other serious
medical procedures are performed at the Albanian military hospital
on the outskirts of Tirana. The one-bathroom apartment is for
afterward. Some soldiers stay for days, others for months. With two
dozen beds pushed against every available wall, they sometimes have
to double up.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers smoking on the long, narrow balcony or just staring
at the walls inside insist they do not mind. To them, the spare but
clean apartment is a place to ready themselves to fight again. Even
Berisha, injured nine months ago in an attack where the Serbs
outnumbered the KLA by two-to-one, hopes to return to the
battlefield one day. For now, though, he is limping on crutches and
using a colostomy bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that I'll be OK, and when I am OK, I am going right
back to fight,'' said the softspoken Berisha, who joined the KLA
last spring. ``I'm really mad now. When I get better, I am going
right to Kosovo to get my revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's commander, whose chiseled cheekbones and crinkly eyes
could get him cast in that exact role in a Hollywood war movie,
ordered them not to discuss battle strategies, arms strength or
anything else that could help the Serbs beat them back into
Albania. But speaking through a Kosovar interpreter, the soldiers
appeared to have few secrets to give away.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the beds that are the apartment's only furniture,
they spoke openly of being outnumbered but remaining optimistic, of
watching comrades die and greeting newcomers to war. From the
conversation, fatalities appeared to be high, injuries higher,
although no one could offer any numbers. Several did say that at
least 30 KLA fighters are being treated at the local military
hospital at any given time.
</P>
<P>
   As the soldiers explained, reports filtering back from Kosovo
indicate fighting in every corner of the country. No road, they
said, is safe for the civilian Kosovars still stuck there and the
fighters who chose to stay, some of them women. Many of the
soldiers have had no word of their own families' plight in the last
month and have been unable to get word to them that they are
injured but alive.
</P>
<P>
   Mustafa Bajraktari, the most veteran soldier among the wounded
and also the oldest at 40, said two of the four soldiers traveling
with him were killed during a late January ambush by Serbian
police. Shot three times, he was treated in the field, went back to
fighting, and waited two months to come to Tirana to see what could
be done about his left arm. From shoulder to elbow, the bone is
shattered; connected only by muscle, it jiggles like jelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 32 soldiers in my group, and I want to get back to
them,'' said Bajraktari, who described his rank as something like a
sergeant. ``I have been fighting a long time, and I am very proud
of how many people want to fight with us now.''
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers said they would like the chance to fight alongside
US Army troops, and they urged President Clinton to send them. As
Osman Musliu, a 30-year-old who suffered a severe concussion and
other injuries when he fell during a skirmish, put it, ``We want
American ground troops to finish this war once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   From the second-floor apartment at least, the soldiers seemed an
unlikely, disorganized band.
</P>
<P>
   No two described a similar training regime, with one saying he
had four months' worth and another saying he taught himself to
shoot using his own gun. They did agree that the recruits now
coming from as far away as America to sign up are spending as
little as 15 days in the KLA training camps around Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``This army is all volunteer; no one orders us there,'' said the
self-trained Shefqet Gashi, 28, who joined the KLA last May, was
injured in September when he fell during a firefight, and is
recovering from knee surgery. ``So we can fight because it comes
from the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, Gashi and the others wore cast-off uniforms that came
from one country or another or were sewn locally. In Tirana, they
wear donated clothes that this soldier may wear one day, that
soldier the next. They pass shoes around to find a good fit. A
soldier whose leg is in a cast must wash his foot in the bidet.
</P>
<P>
   In the medical supply room, where soldiers also sleep, several
huge boxes were filled to overflowing with bottles and packages of
drugs, almost all of them unusable. One sterile compress expired in
1992, a supply of amoxicillin in 1997. The X-ray machine was bound
together with heavy tape. The officer in charge of the facility
said he could think of no basic medical supplies _ from antibiotics
to bandages to crutches _ that the KLA had enough of, both at the
army's field hospitals and in the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, who asked to be identified only as Jashar, said the
KLA also needs foreign hospitals to care for its injured, since
there are no specialists or equipment in Albania to rebuild the
knees, elbows, and other joints shattered by bullets or bombs. The
other day, several were sent to Turkey. England took three and
Germany, two, Jashar said. Visas to other countries have proven
almost impossible to obtain, he added, noting that the KLA lacks
the money to transport the wounded overseas anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Jashar came to the apartment six months ago to recuperate. Years
ago, he said, he was shot. Next he was hit by an anti-tank mine and
hospitalized for three months. His most recent injury was also the
most serious: blinded by a grenade, he spent six weeks wondering
whether he would ever see again. Still, he said he will gladly
fight again when he is healthy and not needed in the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   None of the soldiers knew how he would be returned to the
border, and some expected they would walk. That is how Naim Tatari,
19, reached Albania after a grenade blast broke one of his ribs in
Kosovo on April 30: 12 hours alone by foot. To keep his mind off
the pain, he told himself over and over how lucky he was to be
alive. ``The first thing I thought when it happened was that I am
all in pieces,'' Tatari said.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, he has been eating at cheap restaurants around town
with the other soldiers and talking up the KLA to youngsters who
approach them. Many spoke of pats on the back from strangers who
identified themselves as Kosovar refugees. Tirana, like many
Albanian cities, is crowded with them now. Every so often, one of
them picks up the soldiers' meals. That is good enough for the
soldiers, who stressed that they do not expect every able Kosovar
to join their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every one of us is in a different kind of fight for
Kosovo,'' Berisha said as the others nodded. ``Even if they are not
in the KLA, we are all fighting in our own way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
