<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUDGE-CAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TUNNEL FUDGE CAKE IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pillsbury finally did it. They've come up with a new recipe for
Tunnel of Fudge Cake.
</P>
<P>
   The original recipe, which won second prize in the 17th
Pillsbury Bake-Off for Ella Helfrich of Houston in 1966, was so
popular that sales of bundt pans skyrocketed after the contest. At
the time, only one company, Northland Aluminum Products in
Minneapolis, Minn., made bundt pans and the factory had to go on a
24-hour production schedule to keep up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the original recipe called for a box of frosting
mix. Pillsbury phased out boxed frostings in the mid-1980s and ever
since, cooks have been clamoring for a new version of this cake. So
now, just in time for the 50th anniversary of the Pillsbury
Bake-Off, the company has re-created its most requested recipe. The
recipe is included in a booklet titled ``Best From 50 Years of
Bake-Off Contests,'' which came with the call for entries in the
next Pillsbury Bake-Off to be held Feb. 26-29 in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a theme for the next Bake-Off, it's fast cooking. All
four categories specify quick recipes, usually with time limits on
preparation. The Easy Weeknight Meals category, for instance,
require the recipe be prepared and assembled in 15 minutes or less
(not including cooking time) or the recipe be prepared completely
in 30 minutes or less. Ironically, the new Tunnel of Fudge recipe
takes longer than the original version. And, as always, entered
recipes must use one or more products from a list of Pillsbury,
Hungry Jack, Green Giant, Progresso and Old El Paso products.
</P>
<P>
   The rules and entry forms are available by calling 800-306-1111
through Sept. 30 or by checking the Bake-Off Web site at
www.bakeoff.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TUNNEL OF FUDGE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 16)
</P>
<P>
   Filling: 1 1/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 (3.4-ounce) package chocolate fudge pudding and pie filling
mix (not instant)
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) package chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Cake: 1 1/3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Glaze: 3/4 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 teaspoons milk
</P>
<P>
   Filling: In a medium saucepan, combine 1 1/2 cups milk and
pudding mix. Cook as directed on package. Add chocolate chips; stir
until melted. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cake: Heat oven to 350. Grease and flour a 12-cup bundt pan. In
a large bowl, combine sugar, butter and shortening; beat well until
light and fluffy. Add vanilla and eggs; mix well. Lightly spoon
flour into measuring cup; level off. Add flour, 1/2 cup cocoa,
baking powder, salt and milk; beat at low speed until moistened.
Beat 3 minutes at medium speed. Stir in walnuts. Reserve 2 cups of
the batter. Pour remaining batter into prepared pan. Spoon filling
in ring on top of batter, making sure it does not touch the sides
of the pan. Spoon reserved batter over filling. Bake for 50 to 60
minutes or until cake springs back when touched lightly in center.
Cool 1 hour. Remove from pan. Cook 1 1/2 more hours or until
completely cooled. Glaze: In a small bowl, blend ingredients,
adding enough milk for desired drizzling consistency. Spoon over
cake allowing some to run down the sides. Cut with a serrated
knife. Best served the same day; store remaining cake in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 570 calories (47 percent from fat), 30 grams fat,
80 milligrams cholesterol, 8 grams protein, 68 grams carbohydrates,
3 grams fiber, 230 milligrams sodium.
</P>
</TEXT>
