<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4081 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-MBAS-BOS &LR;      05-12 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MBAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD STUDENTS PLUGGING INTO ON-LINE CAREERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Youssef Ghazal, like many of his fellow Harvard
Business School students, thought he wanted to become a consultant.
He wanted the six-figure starting salary, the prestige that comes
from advising giant corporations, and a career on what has been one
of the hot job tracks of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But then he took a trip to Silicon Valley last summer, and
everything changed. Sitting around a beer-stained pool table in an
abandoned San Francisco honky-tonk that now serves as offices for
WebMethods, an Internet start-up company hoping to go public soon,
Ghazal, 31, experienced a revelation he calls ``the turning
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he realized that what he really wanted was a piece of
his own company. ``I realized it's not about the office you work
in, it's not about the salary. It's all about equity,'' The
Austrian native said of that moment.
</P>
<P>
   Ghazal ditched consulting and along with several other business
students is launching an on-line pharmacy in Europe. ``Those who
believe in the Internet will go far,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So many of Ghazal's classmates have arrived at the same
conclusion that few are planning to follow traditional business
paths when they graduate. In a frenzy that professors compare to
the Great Oklahoma Land Rush, graduates are turning down lucrative
offers to stake claims in the burgeoning on-line world by trying to
start Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 343 Harvard Business School graduates out of a class
of 880 say they plan either to launch high-tech start-ups or join
the venture capital firms that support them to cash in on the
Internet boom, according to a student poll. That's triple the
number four years ago. Also, the number of graduates taking
traditional consulting and Wall Street jobs has dropped by nearly
half, to 308.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be all about consulting and investment banking at
Harvard,'' says John Borchers, a Harvard business student who
recently cochaired the school's business plan competition,
dominated by proposals for new Internet companies. ``Now,
everybody's got a business plan under their arm. They're passing up
the big salaries and the security for $40,000 a year and a few
stock options.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift has been so sudden and severe that some consulting
firms could not recruit enough business students this year and
turned to Harvard law students, says Kirstin Moss, the business
school's director of career services.
</P>
<P>
   Moss says that even Fortune 500 companies, longtime outposts for
Harvard students, are struggling to fill positions. One student's
recent comments, she says, summed up the obsession with the
Internet. ``A student said to me, `The gold rush is on, and it's
not going to last very long.' They want to get out there while the
opportunities are still available.''
</P>
<P>
   The same trend is evident at other prestigious business schools,
including MIT's Sloan School of Management, the Wharton School at
the University of Pennsylvania, and the Stanford Graduate School of
Business. But at Harvard, whose august reputation and wood-paneled
corridors for so long nurtured captains of industry and fed the
nation's corporations, the change has been particularly stark.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the sudden enthusiasm for Internet enterprises are the
almost incomprehensible sums of money being pumped into new on-line
companies. A recent survey by PricewaterhouseCoopers found that
venture capitalists rained $14.3 billion on start-ups last year,
almost all of them Internet-related.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley alone, a record 787 Internet ventures sprouted
in 1998, the report said. Each received about $5.8 million. In New
England, which had the second-largest concentration of Internet
start-ups, 407 new companies got a record $2 billion in venture
capital funding.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of money, ``no brilliant idea should go wanting
for lack of funds,'' the report stated.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists who provide seed money to start-ups for a
piece of fledgling companies are ensuring that money is not a
problem. During recruiting season at Harvard, they invaded the
business school's Allston campus, handing out business cards to
students who one day might launch the next eBay or Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some fear that business students might be taking a big
gamble in passing up solid opportunities in corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about some of these kids,'' says Marco Iansiti, a
Harvard professor whose course on starting new ventures went from
an enrollment of 50 last year to 120 this year. ``There are some
who are going out there and doing very gutsy things. They're
turning down big offers and rolling the dice. It's a tougher world
out there than some of them think.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Harvard's hallways buzz with stories of recent
grads such as Stig Leschly, who two weeks ago sold his
seven-month-old start-up Exchange.com, an on-line seller of used
books and recordings, for a reported $200 million to Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the prospect of incredible sums of money, some say
students are motivated by a sense that the Internet represents a
vast frontier with unrivaled opportunities for making a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a time in contemporary history when there's
been a chance like this to leave your mark on the world,'' says
Anthony Tjan, a 1998 Harvard business graduate and cofounder of
Zefer, an Internet company specializing in business-to-business
communications. Last week, the company won $100 million in
financing from GTCR Golder Rauner LLC, a Chicago venture capital
firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industrial revolution produced Fords and Sloans,'' he
says. ``That's the opportunity we see in front of us now.''
</P>
<P>
   Such possibilities have inspired a near panic among student
entrepreneurs hoping to come up with the next big idea before
someone else does, students and professers say. In Harvard's annual
business plan contest, 80 student teams submitted entries for
companies they intend to launch this year, double the number in
1998. All but a few were ideas for Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the race to get started, many business students skipped
classes to make weekly pilgrimages to California and New York to
meet with potential investors. Some said they set up offices long
before they finished the spring semester.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people getting in on this that you can work
on an idea for a year only to find somebody else is trying to do
the same thing,'' says one student who asked not to be named
because financing arrangements for his Internet start-up are at a
delicate stage. ``There's nothing worse than being a minute too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the ever-present fear that investor enthusiasm for
Internet companies, which has driven initial stock offerings to
astronomical heights, will suddenly go flat and pop the Internet
balloon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to know when the music is going to stop,''
says Mike Roberts, a senior lecturer and director of
entrepreneurial studies at Harvard. ``Very few of these companies
are making money. It's largely driven by the capital markets at
this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the last 50 Internet public offerings nationwide, only one
has fizzled. But last week, a San Diego on-line real estate firm,
Comps.com, made headlines when its initial public offering opened
at $15 a share but finished three-fourths of a point lower by the
end of the trading day. In a world where it has become common for
new Internet offerings to jump dozens of points in a single day, it
was an ominous sign.
</P>
<P>
   Even venture capitalists who have staked fortunes on the
Internet's ability to generate huge gains can't peer very far into
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything could happen,'' says Klaus Koch, a 1997 Harvard
business graduate who works for the Los Angeles venture capital
firm Kleine, Hawkes &AMP; Co. ``I wouldn't be surprised if it goes on
for five years, and I wouldn't be surprised if it goes into the
toilet in three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But student entrepreneurs at Harvard such as Jason Palmer, who
says he's close to securing financing for Mascotnetwork (``a sort
of America Online for college campuses''), are banking on the
Internet's long-term viability as a place to make their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunities are still endless,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
