<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS LET HOLLYWOOD OFF TOO EASY ON VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senate hearings. House hearings. White House town halls. For all
of their frenzy in the wake of Littleton, they are already a
touchy-feely farce. To start, Senate majority leader Trent Lott is
feigning openness this week by allowing some debate on gun control
in hearings on juvenile justice at the same time he is saying gun
control will not happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think additional gun-control measures are probably not
needed,'' Lott said. ``The press and others may want this to turn
into gun control. That's not what this is about. That may be a
small part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun control is so small for Lott because gun money is so large
for his Republican Party. In the 1998 election cycle, the National
Rifle Association gave 83 percent of its congressional
contributions to Republicans, $1.35 million out of $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   This is no news by itself. The curiosity is the Democrats. While
Republicans are slaves to guns, the Democrats are in a state of
servitude to gun culture.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's youth violence town hall, President Clinton did
connect violent TV with real violence. But he stressed that ``We
are not here to place blame, but to shoulder responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   This is blamelessness to a fault, making Clinton as reassuring
for Hollywood as Lott is for the NRA. Hollywood figures are so
reassured that they can come to these hearings and insult our
intelligence. Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture
Association of America, said Hollywood is not part of the problem.
He said families should ``build a strong moral shield'' at ``church
and home and school.'' He said the surgeon general should study the
``why of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, the surgeon general did major surveys of data in
1972 and 1982 that concluded that violence on television
contributed to violent crime. This is proof that it is time to stop
pampering the likes of Valenti and start clamping down on his
industry with serious violence ratings, stringent restrictions on
advertising (I find a gun pointed in my face in ads as offensive as
the Marlboro Man), and new prime-time restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   But who will keep Valenti honest. Clinton? The Democrats? Not if
they are as afraid of offending their donors as are the
Republicans. Of the $16 million in political contributions that
flowed from the TV, movie, and music industry in the 1998 election
cycle, $10 million, or 63 percent, went to the Democrats, according
to federal data compiled by the nonpartisan Center for Responsive
Politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats did best in individual hard-money contributions to
candidates, party committees, and political action committees. Of
$7.2 million of such money, $5.3 million went to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   For example, individual contributions from people associated
with Universal Studios amounted to $206,600 for Democrats, compared
with $10,200 for Republicans. Contributions from people at Time
Warner and its many affiliates came to $419,007 to Democrats and
$60,800 to Republicans. Dreamworks individuals gave $108,300 to
Democrats and $4,500 to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti's group gave $55,975 to Democrats and $15,750 to
Republicans. Republicans do better in Hollywood through corporate
PACs or individual soft money for their party. After all, the
Disneys, Time Warners, and Universals need the Republicans to keep
business regulations lax and tax loopholes big.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no question who should shoulder the responsibility
when it comes to putting pressure on the industry to reel in the
guns and the gore. The top eight recipients in the Senate of
TV/movies/music contributions from 1993-98 are Democrats, led by
Barbara Boxer of Calfornia ($399,471) and immediately followed by
Ted Kennedy and John Kerry of Massachusetts ($330,024 and $323,440,
respectively), and Dianne Feinstein of California ($300,622). The
highest Republican recipient was Conrad Burns of Montana at
$186,609.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, the top five recipients of Hollywood money in the
1998 election cycle are Democrats, led by House minority leader
Richard Gephardt at $131,797. The highest Republican recipient was
Howard Coble of North Carolina at $54,611.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer and Kennedy have rightfully called for stronger gun
control. But they also have to stop being a doormat for Valenti. It
cannot be an accident that the toughest Democratic senator on media
violence, Connecticut's Joseph Lieberman, ranks only 33rd in
1993-98 contributions from Hollywood, at $71,800.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Kennedy said, ``We can work with the media to achieve
responsible programming for children and youth.'' Monday, Clinton
asked for a ``wholehearted participation'' by Hollywood in a
campaign to reduce youth violence. Clinton asked the makers of
violent movies, video games, and music to ``consider the
consequences'' of their products.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti's denial shows that Hollywood is not an industry that
can be ``worked with.'' There can be no mushy expectation that it
will ``consider'' a ``wholehearted participation'' in reducing
violence when violence is currently so profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has to be confronted. Gun control remains the top
priority after Littleton. But if Democrats fight only guns and not
our violent culture, they will find that most people are too numb
from the movies to get rid of the real thing. What we do know is
that this weekend, Clinton will not be on a mission to shame
Hollywood. He will be in Beverly Hills for a $1.5 million
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
