<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TRIPPIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRIPPIN' FALLS FLAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TRIPPIN' 
Directed by: David Raynr 
Written by: Gary Hardwick 
Starring: Deon Richmond, Donald Adeosun Faison, Maia Campbell, Guy
Torry, Countess Vaughn, Stoney Jackson 
Running time: 92 minutes 
Rated: R (sexual situations, adult language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What with the current, and mostly regrettable, deluge of teen
films clogging up valuable cineplex space, it was only a matter of
time before a hip-hop version of the trend found its way onto the
big screen. Hence, we have ``Trippin' ,'' which manages to prove
only that Hollywood finds black teens as inane, thick-headed,
uninspired, and sex-mad as their white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Reed (Deon Richmond) is known as ``G'' to his friends, and
that G might as well stand for goofball. A senior, he isn't as
interested in applying to college as he is in hooking up with any
number of young women. In fact, he spends most of his time
imagining himself as a babe magnet, forever wrapped in compromising
positions with lots of scantily clad women. He's a Walter Mitty-ish
boy in the 'hood, less concerned with heroics than hootchies.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he's like most of the students at Du Bois High
School where, suffice it to say, much of the student body would not
be included among those scholar W.E.B. Du Bois was considering when
he wrote of ``the Talented Tenth.'' Certainly not G's wastrel
buddies: June (Donald Adeosun Faison), a petty crook and a
self-styled ladies' man who doesn't seem to care if the ladies he's
pursuing already have a man. And Fish (Guy Torry) isn't any better.
He somehow thinks he can earn a living as a professional lover
bedding a different woman every night. Yes, this is a profession,
and it's called prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   G, when he isn't daydreaming of another menage a trois, has set
his sights on Cinny (Maia Campbell), who is, of course, the
smartest, prettiest girl in school. In real life, such a young
woman of promise wouldn't give a trifflin' no-count, wanna-be playa
like G the time of day. But since this movie is stoned on
teen-flick cliches, Cinny is falling for G faster than you can say
``She's All That.''
</P>
<P>
   Stupidly written by Gary Hardwick, flatly directed by David
Raynr, and poorly acted by all involved, the mind boggles to think
that someone somewhere thought this mess would work as a movie. And
I'm still trying to figure out the film's connection to LA Lakers
star Shaquille O'Neal, whose TWISM (which stands for ``The World Is
Mine) clothing line gets plenty of screen time. Still, its
inclusion in a film this terrible isn't likely to send sales
soaring. ``Trippin' '' is one trip to be avoided at the movies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
