<HEADER>
A4093 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-STARWARS-PROFILE     05-12 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STARWARS-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING YOUNG VADER ISN'T GOING TO CHANGE HIS LIFE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Meet Darth Vader, the 10-year-old kid and budding
comedian.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Lloyd was thrilled when he won the part of Anakin Skywalker
_ Vader as a boy _ in ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' which opens May 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vader's always been my favorite `Star Wars' character,'' said
an energetic and impish Jake, whose character is empowered by the
``Force'' found in creator George Lucas' universe and begins a
spiritual journey from darkness to redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vader's really a good guy,'' Jake insisted. ``He's the only
one who could destroy the emperor in the end (1983's ''Return of
the Jedi``).
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the part, I started yelling,'' he said. ``Then I
took a deep breath and thought, `Oh my gosh _ I got Star Wars!'
Then I yelled some more. Then I started crying.''
</P>
<P>
   His friends at school in Los Angeles weren't as impressed. Jake
recounted the conversation:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be in the new `Star Wars' film!''
</P>
<P>
   ``So?''
</P>
<P>
   ``But _ ''
</P>
<P>
   ``So?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``So-so.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, his schoolmates ``are OK with it. I don't think my
life will change that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he was a pro before ``The Phantom Menace.'' Jake worked
with Marisa Tomei in ``Unhook the Stars,'' had a recurring role on
``ER'' and played Arnold Schwarzenegger's son in ``Jingle All the
Way.''
</P>
<P>
   For a kid, you'd think working with Ah-nuld would be the
ultimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arnold was great,'' said Jake, a bubbly, quick-witted boy who
wore jeans and a DKNY 2000 T-shirt when meeting the press, along
with mop-top hair much like Anakin's.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was like, `OK, you've worked with Schwarzenegger. Are
you done now?' And I'm like, `No! I'm still up for `Star Wars!'''
</P>
<P>
   He got the part after a two-year casting search.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake was this wild little Tom Sawyer kid, which was just what
I was looking for,'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   A new actor will play the 16-year-old Anakin in ``Episode II,''
which is expected to be shot next year. But ``as long as it takes
them to cast these films, I just might have a chance,'' Jake said
wryly.
</P>
<P>
   He loved his ``Star Wars'' work in England and Tunisia, and
prefers any acting job to being in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only in this business because I enjoy it,'' he said,
``traveling all over, meeting such nice people.'' He paused and
said pointedly, kidding his questioners, ``No _ I'm talking about
the actors.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest thing about the new film? ``Leaving when the shoot
ended.''
</P>
<P>
   The best thing? ``All of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake said he hung out with his co-stars ``just like schoolmates.
I'd tell them riddles and not give the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   He stumped the press with a question: ``In which film does Luke
Skywalker's landspeeder make another cameo?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's this one,'' Jake said. ``When they first get to Mos Espa
(a city on Tatooine), there's a green landspeeder _ it's a
different color _ and it's his, the original.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake had done interviews for ``Jingle All the Way,'' so he was
prepared for a barrage of questions, not all of them smart.
</P>
<P>
   The ``stupidest'' question this time, he said, was, ``How do you
feel about being Christ?'' (Anakin is called ``the chosen one,''
and his birth is likened to an immaculate conception.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's not a bad thing being Christ, but I'm not
Christ, OK? Personally, there's Christ, Jesus, George (Lucas) and
so on,'' he said, motioning downward with his hand.
</P>
<P>
   The most hilarious question, he said, was, ``What do you look
for in women?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 10!'' Jake shouted. ``I don't look for women.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when not working, he rides his bike, plays with
friends, cares for his shih tzu (``You'll have to edit that part
out'') and tackles video games, especially a new ``Star Wars
Podracer'' game he received before its May 20 release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only kid in the world who has it,'' he said with
mischievous glee.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas also sent him a box of ``Phantom Menace'' toys and his
Jedi costume from the film.
</P>
<P>
   The downside, Jake said, is being recognized in public or
stalked by fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People waiting outside your hotel _ that's kind of scary.''
</P>
<P>
   He did visit fans lined up in front of a theater in Hollywood.
``They're doing it for a good cause _ every hour they spend means
money going to charity _ so what the heck. Make it worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   At home with his parents and sister _ who's 7 and has a bit part
in ``Phantom'' _ life is more normal. Jake watches ``The Family
Guy,'' prefers ``The Lord of the Rings'' to comic books, and loves
playing with his ``Star Wars'' toys. He's an ``A and B'' student
and will begin fifth grade this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he resists doing chores, and his mom has to remind him
he's not a movie star so much as a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that only comes up when we need to open both doors to put
my head through,'' Jake said, then added with a sly smile,
``Otherwise, I'm the perfect little angel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1348EDT &QL; 
