<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4096 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-12 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING _ AND LOVING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 10 months Martha Finney has been traveling around the
country in search of everyday people who love their work.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Finney, and at first glance her theory _ that there are
ordinary people who are truly happy at work _ seems naive,
especially in an era of rightsizings, downsizings, and skyrocketing
executive pay.
</P>
<P>
   But 20,000 miles after Finney hit the road, the 43-year-old
Maryland woman has managed to find many people motivated by the
intrinsic value they've found in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it really presumptuous to think that happiness is not
always determined by where you are on the organizational chart or
how much you make?'' Finney asked during an interview. ``What about
ordinary people who love what they do?''
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years ago, journalist Studs Terkel set out to
chronicle the work lives of regular men and women. Their comments
were published in a tome whose offerings foreshadowed some of the
discontent average working Americans have today.
</P>
<P>
   Terkel's interview subjects included prostitutes and bartenders,
salesmen and housekeepers, nurses and nannies _ people whose
stories rarely made the front page of any newspaper. The result was
a gritty account, not what anyone would call joyful but remarkably
real.
</P>
<P>
   Finney, co-author of the book, ``Find Your Calling; Love Your
Life,'' has different stories to tell. In addition to the book,
Finney has posted 20 upbeat profiles of working people on a Web
site (www.heartlandatwork.com). These people don't seem to be
worrying about where to find their next meal or their next job,
though a good number of them are, as Finney says, ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   During her travels, Finney talked to a worker at an animal
shelter, a carpenter, a beekeeper, a community relations
representative, a makeup artist at a department store, a mystery
writer, an occupational therapist, two innkeepers, and many others,
each time focusing on the satisfaction they've found doing what
they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studs Terkel painted the other side,'' Finney said when I
asked her about the many everyday people who labor under poor
conditions, or whose contributions go unrecognized. She noted,
however, that dissatisfaction with her own job as a human resources
management writer prompted her to quit and launch her cross-country
trek.
</P>
<P>
   While Finney might be criticized for ignoring low-wage workers
in deadend jobs, it appears that her goal was to find people doing
interesting, if not high-paying, work. But perhaps it's time for a
reality check. An animal lover who eschews higher pay to work in a
shelter because he or she loves animals has made a choice,
something a non-English-speaking maintenance worker struggling to
feed a family on $20,000 a year doesn't have.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is something refreshing about these
tales. Take Lori Risner, a thirtysomething occupational therapist
in Chicago who has been plying her trade for 11 years. When she
started, the pay was low _ about $18,000 _ but the personal rewards
were high. Today, occupational therapy graduates are in such demand
they are wooed with $10,000 sign-on bonuses and $40,000 salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I applied to the (training) program, you went into the
profession because you loved working with people,'' said Risner.
``Now, schools are keeping demand high by severely limiting the
number of students. Hospitals are offering bonuses, or they are
offering to pay the last year of tuition after a student
graduates.''
</P>
<P>
   That disturbs Risner, who says working with people not only
increased her self-confidence, it made the work worthwhile. ``The
students I get now are not people people,'' she told Finney. ``They
don't think about what they are saying to patients. They just focus
on the money.''
</P>
<P>
   What does it take to feel real dedication for work? Finney
believes workers must first respect the entity they work for and
its mission. Secondly, they must feel that they, too, have garnered
the respect of an employer who is interested in their growth on the
job. Thirdly, they must feel the work they do is important.
</P>
<P>
   Former carpenter Gordon ``Ike'' Brainerd, 64, of Branford,
Conn., found work that fit most of those criteria. Fifteen years
ago, he was walking in the woods with his wife when he discovered a
bee hive. Fascinated, he took it home. Brainerd had also befriended
a local beekeeper in his community who had cancer and could no
longer care for his hives. ``Doctors had told him to stay away from
the hives because they were concerned he would have an allergic
reaction if he was stung,'' recalled Brainerd. ``Six months later,
he died and left me nine hives, with about 60,000 bees.''
</P>
<P>
   When Finney visited Brainerd and his hives, he added another job
satisfaction criterium to the list. ``There always has to be a
mystery to a thing,'' he said. ``If you knew it all, there wouldn't
be a challenge anymore . . . There isn't any point in doing
anything anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   While some low-wage workers love their jobs, it's hard not to
add decent pay and benefits to the satisfaction criteria list.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Boston preschool teacher Kamalah Fletcher, then 22,
told me about her job at a day-care center. She said she loved the
children. She also said she was leaving. ``People don't value the
work we do with young children,'' said Fletcher, who was selling
sporting goods on weekends to supplement her $9.37 per hour wage.
``They see us as baby-sitters. There is a lot more to it than that,
but you can't live on the money. It just isn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher's work experience had made her think more seriously
about getting a degree in early childhood education. That way, she
reasoned, she could do work she loved and get the pay and
recognition she needs to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Extract from Fletcher's experience one more thing to add to
Finney's criteria: education plus training equals opportunity, more
options and, if you're lucky, real joy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Contact Diane E. Lewis at work(at)globe.com, or 617-929-2069.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
