<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS FACING A DIFFERENT KIND OF ON-LINE STOCK PROMOTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no way to start off a week like reading a piece of
electronic mail promising you the chance to make a quick buck.
</P>
<P>
   It caught our eyes Monday morning, the message promoting a stock
we never heard of called Rentech Inc. VSP Financial, another name
unfamiliar to us, said analysts predicted the stock could soar by
900 percent in the next few months and that regulators had
scheduled a May 20 meeting on a proposed Rentech stock promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Cold reality quickly set in. We were hardly the only people
receiving the message, e-mail that seemed to be spammed to half the
wired investing world. Worse, it was quickly being labeled in
Internet chat rooms as a sure P&AMP;D, short-hand for ``pump and
dump.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to a darker side of on-line investing. Like the days of
brokerage boiler rooms, stock touts, and hard-charging brokers,
it's hard to separate the illegal from the simply shady or just
plain aggressive sales practices that are rampant on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same scams, new medium,'' said David Levine, a senior advisor
to the US Securities and Exchange Commission's director of
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much new in terms of frauds you're seeing on the
Internet. It's just more cost effective to reach thousands of
people with a click of a mouse rather than incurring the cost of
running a boiler room,'' said Levine.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has twice conducted sweeps of Internet touts since last
October, rounding up people who allegedly promoted stocks on the
Web without disclosing they had been paid by those companies. Other
operators who simply try to inflate a stock by sending false claims
about a company to thousands of computer screens are another target
of enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   But a different kind of operator with just as much influence may
be beyond the grasp of regulatory action. They promote stocks via
e-mail or Web sites and disclose that they own shares or might hold
them. Those promoters presumably sell their investment at a profit
amid a sudden wave of demand from Internet day traders, the
so-called pump and dump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit like playing the dogs,'' said Matt Nestor,
chief of the Massachusetts Securities Division. ``If you catch it
right you might make some money. But clearly somebody at some point
is going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be a suspect practice, but disclosure is everything in
the trading world. Once existing investments are disclosed,
liabilities faced by promoters may be greatly diminished. VSP
Financial, promoters of Rentech stock, told us upfront via e-mail
that it owned 20,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   Some regulators disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disclosing you're about to commit market manipulation is no
defense,'' said Bill McDonald, chief of enforcement at the
California Department of Corporations. ``These are not going to be
easy cases to make and we're going to need some new laws. Some of
the old laws may not fit very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem: Are most of the wired buyers of an
electronically promoted stock really victims? Regulators and
securities lawyers privately concede that at least some of those
day traders aren't dupes, just gamblers who simply see a new game
beginning and believe they have the skill to get in and out quickly
enough to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   These are wired buyers and sellers who are too fast for the
day-trading moniker. They are known as minute traders and there is
a Web service that caters to them, recommending stock promotion
sites like Stock-Picks, Big-Picks, Great-Picks, and Hot-Picks,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   The Great-Picks site, like some others, announces days in
advance exactly when its next recommendation will be issued.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest loser in the Internet stock hype cycle is often the
company whose stock is being talked up. But even executives at
those businesses are not unanimous in their victim status.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Rentech, the company that had been electronically
promoted to us and others. Trading volume of those shares went wild
on Monday, about 14 times higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
   The trading was halted at midday and company officials said they
could not agree with any wild stock-appreciation forecasts. The big
May 20 regulatory meeting wasn't about a promotion, it was
scheduled to debate the planned delisting of Rentech stock because
the shares had traded below the minimum $1 for too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're trying to make it and do the right thing and you've got
people out there tearing up the market, literally tearing it up,''
said Mark Koenig, a Rentech spokesman. ``The regulators will tell
you their hands are tied. They don't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Many small businesses like Rentech say they don't want to be
seen as a hyped company because there are 10 other stocks an
investor can buy in the alternative. But others say it's so hard
for a small company to gain visibility with investors that they
will take their chances with cyber promoters.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Telident Inc., a Minneapolis high-tech company, were
among the leading small-stock gainers one day this spring when the
company was highlighted on Quiktrades, an Internet stock site, and
has since settled back to old price levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bring some notice of stocks where it might not otherwise
be,'' said Telident chief executive W. Edward McConaghay. ``Are
they buying ahead and then putting words out to capitalize on it? I
have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   A man who said he operated the Quiktrades site denied that it
was geared to minute-trading or that it had made money selling into
trading volume created by Quiktrade's own recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   The man, responding by phone to our e-mail query, declined to be
identified. He said he hoped to make money on Quiktrade by
eventually charging for research but predicted that most
minute-trading sites would disappear soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest has waned tremendously,'' he said. ``On the first one
I saw, stocks would go from 1 to 9. Now if you look at the
performance of these sites they're lucky to get a quarter point off
the recommendation.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record: Rentech shares, which doubled from 7/16 to 7/8
Monday, slipped back to 9/16 Tuesday. The company said it has
turned the case over to regulators.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
