A4104 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOB-CONFLICTS-HNS &LR;      05-12 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-CONFLICTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL CONFLICT IN THE OFFICE IS BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It seems as if everyone gets stressed out at
work these days, and the natural reaction is to do whatever you can
to avoid conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Work is tough enough without increasing the potential for
arguments and _ God forbid _ more stress. Besides, you can't lose
an argument if you don't have one.
</P>
<P>
   Can you? Of course you can. If people married never argue, it's
usually because one spouse gives in all the time. Resentment
builds, and the result is either an unhealthy marriage or a
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of people with healthy marriages owe part of their
success to knowing how to disagree _ and how to make up. You can
have effective conflict at work, too, if you follow these rules of
engagement:
</P>
<P>
   _ Appreciate the value of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Even Einstein wasn't brilliant at everything.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a good boss, you hired smart people. They didn't
suddenly become morons once you hired them.
</P>
<P>
   If people aren't coming to you with suggestions, it's a warning
signal. Think about how you reacted to earlier ideas. Did you
reject something without really trying to understand why the person
suggested it? Did an idea threaten your fragile ego? Did you try to
shape the idea into something that would work? Did you tell the
person why you rejected it? Any decently run company should have at
least an annual survey or some forum for workers to make
constructive suggestions, even if it's nothing more than an
old-fashioned suggestion box _ assuming someone in power actually
reads the suggestions. Labor unions should, too; otherwise union
leadership can lose touch with the needs of a changing work force.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be constructive.
</P>
<P>
   Don't go to your boss with problems. Go to your boss with
suggestions for resolving problems. Period.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to criticize an employee or co-worker, try to use it
as a teaching opportunity. Explain how things would be better next
time if they were done a different way.
</P>
<P>
   And whether you're a boss or employee, make sure you have all
the facts before you criticize. Even if you think you know the
answers, ask questions first. Why did the company implement this
policy? Did the employee understand what was expected? Are ulterior
motives involved?
</P>
<P>
   _ Pick your spots.
</P>
<P>
   If you get a reputation as a whiner, bosses aren't likely to
listen. If you constantly criticize employees, people get numb to
your suggestions. Think about the people you're criticizing, too.
</P>
<P>
   Are they generally good workers who deserve the benefit of the
doubt? If you embarrass people by criticizing them in front of
others, they'll remember the embarrassment (and anger toward you) a
lot longer than they'll remember the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Do you hand out a lot more praise than criticism? Do you let
people know that you appreciate their hard work? If your supervisor
does something that you like, do you say so? If you've shown that
you're generally supportive of people, they're more likely to
listen to criticism with an open mind instead of reacting
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   If you praise people every day for routine tasks, though, it can
backfire. You start sounding insincere. If you praise everybody for
everything, what do you have left for someone who does something
special?
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're wrong, admit it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hardest things to say is ``I screwed up.'' People try
to justify what they did or didn't do, which just makes the
conflict last longer. If you're a good worker and your company
fires you or disciplines you for making an honest mistake, you're
better off elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Apologies are like sushi: They're great when they're fresh, but
tend to smell funny after a few days.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't dwell on conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   No matter whether you have won or lost a conflict, don't keep
bringing it up unless the circumstances have changed dramatically.
You're either rubbing it in or whining, neither of which will do
you much good.
</P>
<P>
   Take it from one who obsesses on problems way too much: You're
better off if you can think about the conflict long enough to
present a good case, but then let it go and move on with your life.
If your job is 80 percent good and 20 percent bad, don't let the 20
percent dominate your thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   For therapy purposes only, you might consider buying ``Voodoo
Lou's Office Voodoo Kit'' for $9.95 from www.runningpress.com. Yes,
it does include a voodoo doll.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep it in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   How you handle conflicts is often more important than the
conflicts themselves. You won't win every fight or get every
promotion, but you can always earn respect.
</P>
<P>
   Issues come and go. Reputations endure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
