<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4114 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-IRAQ-SPI &LR;      05-12 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-IRAQ-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFE AND DEATH IN IRAQ: A nation sagging under the weight of
sanctions
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson, foreign editor of The Seattle Post-Intelligencer,
and Post-Intelligencer photographer Dan DeLong recently spent two
weeks in Iraq to report on the effect U.N. sanctions have had on
Iraq's people, most notably its children.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and DeLong traveled with a delegation called Washington
Physicians for Social Responsibility. They returned with a
compelling portrait of how the fabric of family life has been torn
as children are forced to drop out of school and find work and how
thousands of malnourished children are dying every month because of
a lack of medicine and food.
</P>
<P>
   And from Washington, D.C., Post-Intelligencer Washington
correspondent Michael Paulson explains how economic sanctions have
become increasing common _ and cotroversial. With innocent people
in the tareget countries and at home often bearing the brunt of
sanctions, Congress and the White House are poised to change U.S.
policies.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move this special
package with photos and graphics for clients of the NYTimes News
Service today for immediate or for weekend use. All stories,
whether datelined Baghdad or Washington, D.C., will move in the
``i'' category. If you have any questions on the stories, please
call Veronica Villarreal at (206) 448-8342, or Bob Schenet at (206)
448-8037. Other questions, call the N.Y. Times News Service at
(212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ART (Baghdad) _ At Al Mansour Pediatric Hospital,
malnourished children lay on stained mattresses. The hospital is
dark; electrical power is cut periodically each day to conserve
resources. Moving from bed to bed, Dr. Tarig Al-Shujairi lists the
illnesses: typhoid fever, pneumonia, leukemia, tuberculosis,
cholera. A nurse runs by carrying a small bottle of oxygen. Nemya,
a blond 2-year-old with meningitis is unable to breathe through the
fluid clogging her bronchial tubes. Her father and mother stand at
the side of her bed while the nurse covers Nemya's face with the
small oxygen mask. It is too late. Nemya's chest heaves, her body
shakes, and she dies. Her mother pulls her scarf close about her
face and cries silently. Her father looks at a visitor and touches
his chest over his heart. A fifty-cent tube could have saved her
life, but the hospital has none. Impossible to obtain under the
sanctions, Al-Shujairi says. Such is life _ and death _ in Iraq
under the sanctions imposed by the United Nations in the wake of
the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   By Larry Johnson. Photos by Dan DeLong.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-VIGNETTES-ART-2 TAKES (Undated) _ Walid, 14, and his
brother Ramy, 15, have been working the streets of Baghdad for
eight years, the same length of time sanctions have been in place.
They live in a dark two-room apartment with three younger
stepbrothers and their mother and father... At a school not far
from the Palestine Hotel last month, dozens of smiling students
welcomed American visitors warmly, then sang songs about Saddam
Hussein and about killing American invaders. Nothing personal was
intended; it was just the morning ritual...Star-dash anecdotes on
daily life in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   By Larry Johnson. Photos by Dan DeLong.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-FIXES (Washington) _ In Congress, the critics of sanctions
are pushing several pieces of legislation that would exempt food
and medicine from sanctions, or that would require congressional
approval and impose sunsets. From politicians to grass roots
activists, there are more and more calls to get rid of a program
that critics say does more harm to innocent people than achieves
its stated goals.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SANCTIONS (Washington) _ Since the end of the Cold War, the
U.S. and the U.N. have increasingly resorted to embargoes and trade
restrictions as a way of attempting to force change in countries
whose policies they don't like. The breadth of sanctions is
staggering: 42 percent of the world's population now lives in
sanctioned countries. Now, sanctions are coming under assault by
the business community and from those who argue sanctions hurt
civilians, not political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-DOCTORS (Undated) _ Gerri Haynes a nurse from Woodinville,
Wash., and executive board member of Washington Physicians for
Social Responsibility, said she saw the delegation's trip to
Baghdad ``as an awakening more than an act of civil disobedience.
We can go back to the United States and say to people that the
economic sanctions on Iraq are having a horrible effect.'' Capsules
on the 22-member delegation to Baghdad, which included doctors, a
veteran, a peace activist, a writer, an artist and a medical
student, and why they made the trip.
</P>
<P>
   By Larry Johnson. Photos by Dan DeLong.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-TRIP (Undated) _ A short explainer outlining the
circumstances of the trip, how it came about.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-TIMELINE (Undated) _ A timeline of key events in Iraq since
it invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-FACTS (Undated) _ Quick facts on its people, geography,
government.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-UN (Undated) _ What the U.N.'s oil-for-food resolution
allows Iraq to do and under what conditons.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-EFFECTS (Undated) _ The effects of the sanctions, at a
glance.
</P>
<P>
   BRIEF DESCRIPTIONS OF SOME OF THE ACCOMPANYING PHOTOS:
</P>
<P>
   A 4-year-old boy battling what doctors think is typhoid fever is
held in the arms of his weeping aunt in a Baghdad hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In the same hospital, a fly crawls on the face of a 19-month-old
Ahiam Fazel, one of the many malnourished youngsters at Al Mansour
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The father of 2-year-old Nemya grips her death certificate while
talking to a doctor moments after she died from meningitis in a
quarantined room at the hospital. A 50-cent tube could have saved
the youngster's life, one doctor says. But the hospital has none.
Impossible to obtain under the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the floor of a classroom, second-graders listen to a
lesson at Am Jad Al-Qadeseh, a primary school in Saddam City, the
poorest section of Baghdad. Many classrooms in Baghdad are
overcrowded, with two or three students sharing one desk and others
forced to sit on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   A tattered piece of corrugated cardboard serves as a book cover
for a young Iraqi student. Textbooks, paper and pencils are often
in short supply. Many children, forced to help their impoverished
families earn money, are dropping out of the educational system
much earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Yaiss Khther leaves the eastern bank of the Tigris River after
dropping off passengers. For 10 years, Khther has made a living
ferrying people across the Tigris with his small, gas-powered boat.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends dance and sing in joy at the marriage of a
Muslim couple as the newlyweds arrive at the Palestine Hotel in
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Gerri Haynes, who organized Washington Physicians for Social
Responsibility trip to Iraq, is confronted by Um-Hafiz Saleemah at
the Dijlah School, an all-girls school. Saleemah wanted to know how
Americans could sit comfortably in their homes and allow the
bombing of Iraq to continue.
</P>
<P>
   A young girl runs past a mural of an Iraqi soldier in a tank,
painted on the wall of the Dijlah all-girls school.
</P>
<P>
   GRAPHICS:
</P>
