</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-POOR-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 NO SHAME IN MY GAME
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Working Poor in the Inner City.
</P>
<P>
   By Katherine S. Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf/The Russell Sage Foundation. $27.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; FLIPPING BURGERS
</P>
<P>
   BY JASON DEPARLE
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Katherine S. Newman got the inspiration for this book in a
Harlem traffic jam. Crawling crosstown in the back of a cab, she
stared out at one of the country's most famous pockets of poverty
and saw throngs of people heading to work, just as in blue-collar
neighborhoods. As it happened, Newman, an anthropologist now at
Harvard, was on her way to a conference on the poor -- the jobless,
welfare-dependent poor who dominate public discussion. ``What do we
know about the others, the hard-working people of communities like
Harlem struggling to get to work?'' she wondered. ``Not much.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``No Shame in My Game,'' a study of Harlem fast-food workers,
Newman champions poor workers and seeks to reorient the poverty
debate. She wants to de-emphasize self-defeating behaviors like
teen-age pregnancy, and to stress what she sees as the larger
issues: the injustice of low wages and the apathy of more
prosperous citizens. These low-income workers ``are not people
whose values need re-engineering,'' she writes. ``They work hard at
jobs the rest of us would not want because they believe in the
dignity of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman's effort to recast the inner-city poor as neglected,
working-class heroes fails on two counts. Even her highly
sympathetic portraits make many of them seem less striving and more
party to their troubled circumstances than she realizes. And the
world is not as unaware of their economic woes as she believes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she is right to recognize that most poor people do work,
at least sporadically. The problem is that work alone often fails
to transform their lives. With tougher welfare laws sweeping the
country, this is a crucial point -- even programs that get people
into jobs may fail to uplift the ghettos. Newman argues that the
problem is mainly economics: low wages and scarce jobs. But her
findings suggest a more complicated set of issues. Newman and her
graduate students interviewed 300 workers and job applicants at a
fast-food franchise she calls ``Burger Barn.'' The students spent
four months working behind the counters, and the research team
followed 12 workers over a longer period. While Newman heralds the
``rich, detailed data that poured in,'' this is not a book of rich,
detailed portraits. The workers are known only by first names --
Jamal, Kyesha, Tiffany, Latoya -- and they blur together. There is
no narrative or human drama; the organization is topical.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Newman asks interesting questions, and some new
insights emerge. Examining the demeaned ``McJob,'' she finds it
more intellectually challenging and socially rewarding than most
outsiders would guess. Yes, abuse flows in from disgruntled
customers, including mocking peers. But the workers bond among
themselves to ``build a moral defense of their work.'' Yes, wages
are low and the work is hard. But the Burger Barn managers mix
profit motives with ``a missionary impulse'' toward rescuing
inner-city youth. ``The fast-food industry is actually very good
about internal promotion,'' Newman writes.
</P>
<P>
   This discovery of a management track is an interesting bit of
news, since these are supposed to be dead-end jobs. But like many
of Newman's findings, it is at odds with her larger view of a
class-bound society where opportunity is ``distressingly limited.''
She does not resolve -- often she does not even acknowledge -- such
contradictions. Newman argues that her Burger Barn workers are
filled with mainstream aspirations about school, work and family.
And she relays some uplifting stories of tenacity against the odds.
A particularly affecting tale involves William, a fat, bullied
teen-ager who takes refuge in his work despite the derision of
others his age.
</P>
<P>
   But Newman sees everyone she meets in a similarly flattering
light, as if she is afraid to make any judgments. ``Latoya does not
lack the desire to go to school, just the life circumstances that
would make more education feasible,'' Newman writes. What ``life
circumstances''? As a ``heavy partygoer,'' Latoya dropped out of
school at 16 and had a baby. Her mother said keep studying but,
Latoya said, ``I was like, 'Yeah, whatever.' ``She winds up with
three children by two or three men (the number of fathers is
unclear). Latoya is not even poor. While she earns about $15,000,
Jason, the father of her third child, is a union carpenter who
earns $15 an hour, or about $30,000 a year. Newman vigorously
defends the ``irregular social structures'' of the inner-city
family. But if Jason and Latoya would marry, their family income
would top $45,000. Finally they do marry -- and they escape
poverty. Jason's earnings are unusually high, but Latoya could
leave poverty even if Jason earned half as much. ``Irregular social
structures'' -- the lack of stable marriages -- are clearly part of
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Newman is particularly puzzling when she says American society
assigns low-wage workers ``the untouchable status of the Indian low
castes.'' In fact, support for low-wage workers has been growing at
a noteworthy pace. Two years ago, a Republican balanced-budget bill
found $24 billion over five years to subsidize health care for
low-income families. And that pales next to the $30 billion the
country now offers the working poor in annual wage supplements. The
program, called the earned income tax credit, provides annual cash
bonuses of more than $3,700 per family. This may or may not be
enough, but it is scarcely apathy or scorn. Newman races past the
program -- the centerpiece of policy toward low-wage workers -- in
two paragraphs.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the workers she meets, Jamal steals her heart. She is
impressed by the ``doting love he has for his young wife,'' Kathy,
and finds him ``something of a hero'' for boarding a bus to a
minimum-wage job each morning at 5. But as Newman goes on to
explain, Kathy is not his young wife -- she is his girlfriend. She
ran away from home to join him at 16, and soon they had a child.
The infant was put in foster care after Jamal apparently struck
her. His temper ``has its explosive side,'' and he has had problems
with cocaine. Newman sees Jamal as a striving worker blocked at
every turn. He has a less romantic view, describing himself as
``going from here to here to here, and doing this and that.'' It is
little wonder that he is adrift and depressed -- his mother is a
longtime crack addict, and he has never known his father.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Jamal has appealing qualities and untapped gifts; many
needy people do. No doubt better jobs would help. But as Newman
inadvertently shows, his problems stretch far past Burger Barn.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Jason DeParle, a national correspondent for The Times, writes
about poverty issues.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
