<HEADER>
A4136 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LIGHT-NYTSF     05-12 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LIGHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 CITY OF LIGHT
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Lauren Belfer.
</P>
<P>
   518 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   The Dial Press. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; OUT OF DARKNESS
</P>
<P>
   BY ELLEN FELDMAN
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   As man has progressed from the wheel to steam to silicon chips,
each generation has believed its technological revolution would
change the world and perfect it. History chronicles the changes;
perfection has proved more elusive. Human nature tends to be
techno-resistant, even in forward-looking, turn-of-the-last-century
Buffalo, the setting of ``City of Light,'' an ingenious first novel
by Lauren Belfer.
</P>
<P>
   Louisa Barrett, headmistress of the exclusive Macaulay School
for Girls, is a ``wise virgin,'' unmarried, dedicated to her work
and not above feigning a Boston marriage with an old college friend
to facilitate her movement among the powerful men of the city
without arousing the jealousy of their wives. Louisa is dedicated
to subverting the injustices of society by opening the minds and
inciting the ambitions of her young charges. But her real passion,
and therefore vulnerability, is her goddaughter, the 9-year-old
Grace Sinclair.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's mother has recently died, and Grace's father, Tom, who
has risen from an impoverished childhood in Ireland ``by his wits,
the gossips said -- and the way they said it was not entirely
complimentary,'' has buried his grief in his work as director of
the hydroelectric power project at Niagara Falls. Tom is a dreamer
as well as an entrepreneur. Once he has banished darkness by
bringing electric light to the masses, he explains to Louisa,
``people won't be afraid anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisa overhears an argument between Tom and one of the
``engineer heroes,'' as the newspapers have branded the breed, and
the engineer's body turns up beneath the ice of the Delaware Park
lake. She begins to suspect Tom is not the altruistic visionary he
seems. And when a visiting newspaperman turned art photographer,
who is connected to the city's elite but manages to look ``like a
tousled, world-weary Lord Byron,'' asks for her aid in following
``a trail of money, power and avarice,'' Louisa is torn between
exposing evil and protecting her goddaughter and herself, between
trusting a man to whom she is intimately connected and one she has
just met.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere Louisa turns, conflicting claims cloud her once-clear
vision. The Niagara Preservation Society asserts that God is on its
side in the battle against capitalist greed, but a young man, who
may or may not be a union agitator, asks Louisa, ``Isn't it God's
work we're doing here, by making light?'' White laborers on strike
for better conditions assault blacks who move in as scabs, the only
work they can get. And a high-strung young art teacher paints the
hydroelectric stations as ``cathedrals of power,'' what Louisa
terms ``symbols of the holiness of man's endeavors,'' but the
teacher bursts into tears at the thought of what Louisa calls ``a
future that turns the sublimity of Niagara into grinding wheels.''
Even electricity, she tells us, ``seemed like magic, but . . . was
science. Magic had become science, science had become magic,
anything was possible, and the future was ours.''
</P>
<P>
   In this spirit of optimism, the city gears up for the Pan
American Exposition, a monumental and ruinously expensive
celebration of technological advance and human progress. But as
President William McKinley arrives to throw the switch that will
put Powerhouse 3 on line, the kidnapping of one of Louisa's
students, a granddaughter of the leader of the local black
community, and a young Polish-American anarchist intent on
assassination threaten to turn the long-awaited exhibition into a
national embarrassment. With the future of the power station and
the prosperity of Buffalo hanging in the balance, the city fathers
close ranks to protect their investment and prerogatives. It is
not, Louisa learns, the first time they have taken the public good,
and her welfare, into their tainted hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Light'' rests on prodigious research. The novel teems
with arcane information and is alive with historical figures who
mingle seamlessly with the fictional characters. At its heart is a
brilliantly realized set piece starring Grover Cleveland that comes
as a complete surprise, yet has been carefully foreshadowed. It is
a small gem, almost a separate short story, that is wickedly
relevant to the headlines of that era, as well as to this one.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the machinery of the power station roars through the
pages of the book, so the mechanisms of the novel occasionally
clank noisily. Belfer seems to be moving the characters around to
accommodate a mystery plot that is more convoluted than involving.
Louisa keeps chanting her fears of deception and disaster in a
running monologue of Gothic foreboding. Moreover, the two men who
vie, albeit with halfhearted interest and at surprisingly
infrequent intervals, for Louisa's affections represent competing
worldviews; they are not convincing characters who might actually
be interested in snaring a feisty feminist schoolmarm. Perhaps
Belfer intended the triangle as a sendup of the romantic fiction of
that period (and this), but the love story lacks the ironic
undercurrent that would give bite to such a satire.
</P>
<P>
   Belfer's heart is clearly in the right place, on the side of the
oppressed immigrants, workers, and women of a century ago, but her
sensibilities occasionally slip into the wrong era. Louisa's
musings on what happens to lively little girls when they approach
puberty sound as if she had got her hands on an early draft of the
study by the American Association of University Women, and an aging
feminist's railings against her young counterparts, who take their
advantages for granted, are a slap at current postfeminist
sentiment. Occasional references to ``wheedling and dealing,'' a
child's need for help ``with her mourning,'' an ``upwardly mobile
life'' and ``disposable income'' are jarring anachronisms in a book
that evokes the clothing people wore, the buildings they inhabited
and the streets they walked in such rich and authentic detail.
</P>
<P>
   Though historical fiction, like the writing of history itself,
tells as much about the time in which it is written as the period
about which it writes, there are two approaches to the genre. One
plunges the reader into the past without conscious concession to
the present. The other draws obvious, if unexpressed, parallels
between the two periods. ``City of Light'' is an appealing and
authoritative example of the second school. A huge, sprawling
portrait of the United States at the turn of the last century,
illuminated by a dazzling image of light and progress, and
harboring a sly dark secret, the novel is didactic in the very best
sense of the word.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Feldman's most recent novel is ``God Bless the Child.''
She is working on a novel about Lucy Mercer and Franklin D.
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
