<HEADER>
A4137 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SURRENDER-NYT     05-12 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SURRENDER-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 SURRENDER, DOROTHY
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Meg Wolitzer.
</P>
<P>
   224 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Scribner. $22.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; A DEATH IN THE EXTENDED FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   BY SYLVIA BROWNRIGG
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The idea that friends are taking the place of family in people's
emotional lives has become widespread, as a wealth of literary and
cinematic productions attests. (See the sitcom ``Friends'' for
further reference.)
</P>
<P>
   Meg Wolitzer's previous novel, ``Friends for Life,'' traced the
relations among three women who'd been close since girlhood. Her
new novel departs from that scenario to ask: What happens to
friends for life if one of those lives abruptly ends?
</P>
<P>
   Wolitzer opens ``Surrender, Dorothy'' with an affectionate
portrait of the ``lofty and sacred'' relationship of 30-year-old
Sara Swerdlow and her best friend, a gay playwright named Adam
Langer. But by the end of the first chapter, Sara is killed in a
car accident on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Sara and Adam (who emerges from the crash with only a few
bruises) had been out buying ice cream to bring back to the friends
with whom they've rented a ramshackle summer house, as they do
every year. When the landlady refuses to refund their rent, the
survivors decide to stay on for a monthlong wake of drinking,
grieving and reminiscing.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so ``Big Chill.'' Wolitzer's cast includes Sara's friend
Maddy; Maddy's husband, Peter, and their baby, Duncan; as well as
Adam and his handsome new boyfriend, Shawn. To break up the
couples' tidy symmetry, Wolitzer introduces Sara's mother into the
mix. Natalie, a feisty travel agent, was particularly close to her
only child. Mother and daughter had been almost inseparable since
Natalie's divorce, when Sara was small. Now Natalie hopes to find
solace in the place where her daughter spent so many carefree days.
</P>
<P>
   Wolitzer's strategy is to stage the strange, fierce jealousies
over the newly dead as an intergenerational conflict. She describes
``a heated, furious competition, and the theme of it was: Who owned
this broken girl now, her mother or her closest friends?'' Yet
she's so eager to explore this tension that she coasts past Sara's
actual death, thereby cheating the reader of a central emotional
episode. Natalie is allowed just a few brief sentences as she views
her dead daughter. Then, after a sketchy funeral, she's prompted to
seek out the ``kids'' her daughter knew.
</P>
<P>
   The easygoing 30-year-olds obligingly include Natalie in their
parties, clubbing, drug taking and even some late-night romantic
fumblings, all the while persisting, with oddly adolescent
propriety, in calling her Mrs. Swerdlow.
</P>
<P>
   After some uneven scene setting, the ensemble piece begins, and
here Wolitzer finds her pace. Adam has been called ``the gay Neil
Simon,'' and Wolitzer shares her character's knack for wry comedy.
Her comfort with gay-straight friendships brings to mind the
affable novels of Stephen McCauley. She is easy and astute in her
cultural observations, whether on the strains of creative life (the
Broadway success that inhibits Adam and inspires envy in Shawn),
the neuroses of new mothers (Maddy is tormented by a guilt-inducing
book called ``The Upbeat Baby'') or a friendship between Natalie
and a rediscovered girlhood friend, now rich. ``If you ever want to
talk,'' she tells Natalie helpfully, ``or if you want a helicopter
ride, or a facial or anything at all, I am here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolitzer's amiability proves something of a liability, however,
given the novel's somber theme. Even her lines on grief have a
punchy quality, as when she remarks, ``Grieving parents never found
their footing, never found their feet, never even found their
shoes, but simply stayed in bed forever.'' Wolitzer is adept at
banter, but she stumbles into awkward, implausible dialogue at
moments of crucial revelations or during heart-to-heart talks.
</P>
<P>
   And Sara remains blurry. This, of course, is partly the point:
to examine how each of these characters needed and in some sense
created her. We know that Sara was beautiful and sexy and smart (a
graduate student in Japanese history), but only because we are told
she was. The occasional flashbacks don't bring these qualities to
life.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Sara's mysterious melancholy seemed to be her
near-oppressive closeness to her mother _ their secret salute,
``Surrender, Dorothy,'' resembling the coded song of the women in
``Friends for Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Buried within this affecting novel is the troubling question of
whether close friendships and close family ties can keep a person
from finding romantic intimacy. Wolitzer's Sara didn't live long
enough to explore that possibility. Perhaps her survivors will be
luckier.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Brownrigg's novel, ``The Metaphysical Touch,'' will be
published in June.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
