<HEADER>
A4139 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-STASI-NYTSF     05-12 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-STASI-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 STASI
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Untold Story of the East German Secret Police.
</P>
<P>
   By John O. Koehler.
</P>
<P>
   Westview Press. $28.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; A NATION OF SPIES
</P>
<P>
   By Belinda Cooper
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Following the fall of the Berlin wall in 1989, East German
dissidents fought for and won a broad right of access to the
material left behind by the East German secret police, the Stasi.
Since 1992, hundreds of thousands of people have viewed the files
of that enormous bureaucracy of espionage and internal repression.
The result has been an outpouring of books and articles in Germany,
and some in the United States and England, on numerous aspects of
the Stasi. Thus anyone announcing possession of ``the untold
story'' of the Stasi is making a large claim. Unfortunately, John
O. Koehler's ``Stasi'' fails to live up to its ambitious subtitle.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the information Koehler offers on Stasi espionage and
support for terrorism is already known. His chapter on internal
repression, the most disturbing aspect of the Stasi, covers only a
few spectacular and oft-reported stories, barely touching on the
agency's more Orwellian activities, like its use of tens of
thousands of domestic informants (though his estimate of as many as
two million informers -- one in ``any party of 10 or 12 dinner
guests'' -- is greatly exaggerated, according to the agency that
catalogues the Stasi files). While the details gleaned from Stasi
files and interviews with former officers are occasionally
illuminating, the author's readiness to take even self-serving
statements at face value detracts from his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Given the dearth of English-language literature on the Stasi,
these weaknesses might be forgiven. But more problematic are the
book's blatantly ideological underpinnings. Koehler, a former
correspondent for The Associated Press in Germany and a director of
communications under President Ronald Reagan, surrounds his
narrative with the frequently inaccurate generalizations and
cliches of the cold war.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Koehler informs us that the Stasi was ``worse than the
Gestapo,'' quoting the Nazi-hunter Simon Wiesenthal in support.
East German leaders were ``on a par with Hitler's gang,'' and Stasi
crimes were ``as brutal as those perpetrated by their Nazi
predecessors.'' In the book's melodramatic last lines, the
autobiography of the spymaster Markus Wolf ``has become a best
seller in Germany. So was Hitler's 'Mein Kampf.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which one can legitimately compare the Nazi and
Communist systems has generated extensive scholarly and popular
controversy. The secret services of dictatorships undoubtedly share
many features. But simply equating the Stasi's behavior --
intrusive and brutal as it was -- with the unrestrained torture and
murder and ultimately with the genocide perpetrated by Hitler's
security forces is patently wrong and does little to further
understanding of either.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler needs a Stasi that matches the evil of the Nazis in
order to maintain his us-against-them view of the world. If the
Stasi chief Erich Mielke can be likened to Heinrich Himmler, there
is no need to delve into the moral ambiguities of, for example, the
Allies' postwar recycling of Hitler's espionage service (which he
mentions) or the return to positions of influence of former Nazis
in postwar West Germany (which he does not). In fact, gray areas
never trouble Koehler's narrative: the African National Congress in
South Africa is ``Communist-controlled'' and ``terrorist''
(incredibly, the word ``apartheid'' never appears); it is suggested
that an American scholar who maintains personal contacts with East
German professors is a ``nave, muddle-headed, liberal academic.''
</P>
<P>
   Such simplistic language is inexcusable, regardless of one's
political convictions. The Stasi certainly deserves condemnation.
But Koehler's failure to examine, even in passing, any of the
historical, social and political contexts in which the East German
secret service flourished does a disservice to the writing of
history. It also leads to a book that avoids addressing any of the
fascinating questions the Stasi raises about the workings of
dictatorship, the reasons for collaboration, the motivations for
dissent and the factors that contributed to the Stasi's demise as
well as to that of the system it served.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Belinda Cooper is a fellow at the World Policy Institute and the
editor of ``War Crimes: The Legacy of Nuremberg.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
