<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4141 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WANDERER-NYTS     05-12 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WANDERER-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 A WANDERER IN THE PERFECT CITY
<TEXT>
<P>
   Selected Passion Pieces.
</P>
<P>
   By Lawrence Weschler.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry Mind Press. Paper, $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; CRANK CASES
</P>
<P>
   BY M. G. LORD
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Weschler, a staff writer at The New Yorker since 1981,
has the credentials of a literary insider. What makes his work
striking, however, is that he writes from the perspective of an
outsider. The subjects of Weschler's untraditional essays are
quixotic misfits, visionary flakes and a few freshly anointed
geniuses whom he managed to discover back when the world dismissed
them as cranks. The eight pieces in his absorbing new collection,
``A Wanderer in the Perfect City,'' are unpredictable in the way
that only the best nonfiction can be.
</P>
<P>
   No fiction editor concerned with plausibility would tolerate
Weschler's characters: an Indian schoolteacher who rescues a broke
Manhattan painter from obscurity; a rocket scientist who trains to
be a circus clown; a Russian music prodigy who passes his 10th
decade as a musical lexicographer in West Los Angeles. Weschler's
essays are also exquisitely written -- so perfectly and
unobtrusively organized that one can't imagine telling them a
better way. Weschler describes these essays as ``passion pieces''
about ``people and places that were just moseying down the street
one day, minding their own business, when suddenly and almost
spontaneously they caught fire . . . ending up, by day's end,
somewhere altogether different from where they'd imagined they were
setting out that morning.'' But they are united by another common
theme -- the triumph of the excluded and offbeat over the entitled
and entrenched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shapinsky's Karma,'' which opens the collection, is a landmark
of anticelebrity journalism. It details the rise of Harold
Shapinsky, a dirt-poor second-generation Abstract Expressionist,
through the efforts of Akumal Ramachander, an English teacher from
Bangalore, India -- a story, as Salman Rushdie has put it, of
``European revenge'' against the hidebound New York art world.
Although Manhattan art dealers had dug in their heels against
Shapinsky -- if he were any good, how could they have overlooked
him? -- Ramachander orchestrated a breakthrough in England,
enlisting James Mayor, a London gallery owner, who gave Shapinsky a
show; Ronald Alley, a curator at the Tate Gallery, who sent
Ramachander to Mayor; even Rushdie, who persuaded Britain's Channel
4 television to profile Shapinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Weschler has a sense of humor about his subjects -- Shapinsky's
Karma'' opens with a series of phone calls from Ramachander, which
appear to arrive at either midnight or dawn -- but he never derides
them. He does suggest, though, that Ramachander's motives may not
be as pure as Ramachander contends. The Indian's quest for
attention outside his homeland may well be a response to its caste
system, in which, despite his drive and talent, he can never be
more than a provincial English teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Weschler's best work is set in California or deals with
aspects of California culture -- for which Weschler, a native
Californian, seemingly retains affection. ``Gary's Trajectory''
exposes the inner workings of TRW, a West Coast aerospace
contractor, with which Gary Isaacs, an M.I.T.-educated rocket
engineer, grows disenchanted. Whether Isaacs is testing already
built spacecraft before launching or rescuing a satellite that
failed to deploy properly, Weschler makes his activities vivid and
comprehensible -- no mean feat with highly technical subject
matter. He does the same with the subsequent stops on Isaacs's
unlikely career path: Wall Street and the Ringling Brothers and
Barnum &AMP; Bailey Clown College in Venice, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slonimsky's Failure'' brings together another odd bunch of
Southern Californians. After his wife's death in 1964, Nicolas
Slonimsky, a Russian-born composer, conductor, pianist,
lexicographer and Slavic language professor, accepted a position at
U.C.L.A. He forged a close if improbable friendship with his
Hollywood neighbor, the rock legend Frank Zappa, performing with
him at the Santa Monica Civic Auditorium in 1981. He also came to
rely heavily on his assistants, or ``odalisques,'' a bevy of
archetypal California coeds.
</P>
<P>
   Weschler's gentle treatment of his subjects could have been
inspired by Slonimsky. Instead of accusing Leopold Stokowski of
lying, for example, Slonimsky delicately notes that the acclaimed
conductor was ``born in London in 1882 but preferred to have
entered the world in Cracow five years later.'' Weschler also
plunges into the technical aspects of music, as he did with those
of rocket engineering. He argues convincingly that to Slonimsky,
music is a ``mathematical passion,'' not a sensual one. If, as
Leibniz has conjectured, music ``is a hidden arithmetical activity
of a mind that does not know it is counting,'' Slonimsky actually
``hears the counting.''
</P>
<P>
   Weschler's most affecting portrait may be of Art Spiegelman, the
creator of ``Maus,'' before he became a certified genius. Not that
long ago, he was a mere underground cartoonist, struggling to make
sense of his upbringing as the child of Holocaust survivors.
Spiegelman's conversations with his father about his experiences,
which became the core of ``Maus,'' were not merely a part of their
relationship; they were the entire relationship. Other
communication invariably left the two ``at loggerheads.''
</P>
<P>
   While reading ``A Wanderer in the Perfect City,'' I found myself
thinking of the Bhagavad-Gita -- not that strange an association,
since Ramachander often paraphrased its tenets. What struck me was
the idea of nonattachment: when it comes to work, the joy should be
in the doing, not in the gathering of rewards. One cannot force
one's work to be successful. Fruition requires an element of
``grace,'' in its original sense of ``gratis, for free,'' Weschler
writes. ``One works and works and works at something, which then
happens of its own accord: it would not have happened without all
the prior work, true, but its happening cannot be said to have
resulted from all that work, the way effects are said to result
from a series of causes.'' Rather, grace descends and, in ways that
can be as funny as they are extraordinary, what Weschler terms
``the humdrum'' takes flight.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   M. G. Lord is the author of ``Forever Barbie: The Unauthorized
Biography of a Real Doll.'' She is working on an informal cultural
history of NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
