<HEADER>
A4142 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-UNBROKEN-NYTS     05-12 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-UNBROKEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 UNBROKEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Jessie Haas.
</P>
<P>
   185 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Greenwillow Books. $15. (Ages 10 and up)
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; SPRING CHILDREN'S BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   THE ORPHANS
</P>
<P>
   BY EMILY ARNOLD MCCULLY
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The powerful story of a resilient girl's moral awakening in the
context of family and community, ``Unbroken'' is set in 1910 in the
Vermont towns and hill farms that Jessie Haas knows to her marrow,
but it reverberates with universal meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Haas tackles themes of family responsibility, independence,
mastery, work and courage on the same small canvas in all her
books. Even her earliest chapter books for beginning readers, about
Lily and her mare Beware, are trenchant and entertaining, with
winning characters, strong plots and a wealth of expert horse lore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbroken'' -- inspired, like Haas's earlier novel
``Westminster West,'' by a real-life Vermont story -- eloquently
links the fates of 13-year-old Harriet (called Harry) and her colt,
orphaned together in 1910. After delivering Harry to school in a
buggy, her mother forces the terrified mare, Belle, to pass an
approaching car. The horse shies and they are killed. Her ailing,
widowed mother had protected Harry from knowing that there are
debts and the house must be sold. Her mother planned for Harry to
be raised on a back-country hill farm by Aunt Sarah, who Harry is
convinced hates her. Why did Harry's charming, stylish, educated
mother consign her only daughter to a deeply rural life she herself
had fled, if only to a small town?
</P>
<P>
   In Haas's ``Uncle Daney's Way,'' the title character arrives in
a wheelchair, dependent on family charity, but he's a free spirit.
A character remarks: ``That's what used to make your grandfather so
mad. He worked hard all his life at a job he hated, and Daney did
what he felt like doing and was happy.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Unbroken'' we meet Aunt Sarah, who scrubs her house with
cider vinegar and despises the values Harry has learned to espouse.
Like the grandfather who resented Uncle Daney, Aunt Sarah thinks
Harry should ``take up the life the Lord's given you.''
</P>
<P>
   The mean injustice of Sarah's ideas and her power over the girl
provoke a fury of righteous rage in Harry. Aunt Sarah dismisses the
notion of further education and taunts Harry with her own bitter
belief that Harry's mother had snagged her father in a shotgun
wedding. Harry is desperate to disprove the idea. It seems to call
into question everything she has taken as true. Furthermore, Harry
knows that without an education she is doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Her only legacy is the unbroken colt, Belle's son. If she can
train and sell him, she can pay for school. But despite all her
efforts, the colt shies, even at hens. Will she repeat her mother's
mistake and be hurt or killed?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Harry's Vermont world is not as limited as it seems.
The doctor, her friend's parents, even the driver of the car will
help her get the education she was meant to have. The challenge is
not to defy or even to overcome, but to comprehend. She realizes
that her mother, an impoverished widow, had decided to be happy
with her lot. She learns the truth about Sarah, who was also
orphaned at Harry's age and courageously raised four siblings, who
died of consumption. The knowledge brings shame and finally
reconciliation for them both.
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle Harry doesn't have to overcome is self-pity. Her
self-consciousness is a necessary means of addressing the world and
finding her place in it. She is linked by common knowledge and
common trials to her forebears. Harry experiences terrible loss and
failure before she can move on. Willful rebellion matures to
compassion. Faithful to life's struggles and richly peopled with
flinty characters, ``Unbroken'' is a wise and satisfying novel.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Emily Arnold McCully's books include ``Mirette on the High
Wire'' and ``Beautiful Warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
