<HEADER>
A4143 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-TEA-NYTSF     05-12 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-TEA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 TEA WITH MILK
<TEXT>
<P>
   Written and illustrated by Allen Say.
</P>
<P>
   Boston: Walter Lorraine Books/Houghton Mifflin Company. $17.
</P>
<P>
   (Ages 5 to 9)
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; SPRING CHILDREN'S BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   STRANGER IN HER OWN LAND
</P>
<P>
   BY MARGARET MOORMAN
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Masako is very clear about it. ``I'd rather have a turtle than a
husband!'' says the heroine of Allen Say's new picture book, ``Tea
With Milk.'' In spite of her protests, this independent young woman
is introduced to a banker chosen for her by a matchmaker. In Japan
around 60 years ago, when this story takes place, good families
proceeded with the business of love and marriage in this
time-honored way. Unfortunately, Masako has recently come to Japan
from America, where she was brought up. There she drove a car and
dreamed of college and a career in the gleaming city of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   After the failed encounter, Masako announces with vehement
indignation, ``I won't marry a moneylender!'' The next morning the
otherwise obedient daughter boards a bus for another gleaming city,
Osaka, where she talks her way into a job at a department store.
Shocking! Young ladies in Japan did not work outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, we've met this complicated individual before. In
Say's beautiful ``Grandfather's Journey,'' which won the 1993
Caldecott Medal, she was simply the grandfather's child, who in a
page or two grew up, married and produced a son -- now our highly
accomplished author and illustrator.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Tea With Milk,'' Say elaborates on his mother's story,
pursuing the sort of character he clearly understands well: a
person whose heart is divided between one home and another. ``I'll
never get used to this place,'' Masako thinks as a teen-ager, when
her parents move back to Japan, their homeland, after decades in
California -- the place they presumably never got used to. Fellow
students in Masako's Japanese school are cruel in the expected
ways, calling her a gaijin (foreigner) and refusing to befriend
her. She misses her American neighbors, who called her May and fed
her pancakes, fried chicken and spaghetti. As she learns to speak
Japanese, handle a calligraphy brush, wear a kimono, bow politely
and pour plain tea, she remembers life in America and misses tea
with milk and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tea With Milk'' turns out to be a spirited but very proper
love story. In Osaka, on her job, May meets another uprooted soul
like herself, a Japanese gentleman raised by English foster
parents. Like her, he takes his tea with milk and sugar. May's
rebellion, while tame by Western standards, has paid off --
handsomely, in fact, judging from her suitor's graceful features
and elegant bearing, as compared with the round face and large ears
of the matchmaker's spurned offering.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of Say's books have been praised more for their
limpid watercolor illustrations than for the writing, he is
actually a gifted storyteller. In a nicely ironic twist, Mr. Right
also happens to be a banker, so May marries a moneylender after
all. And the author creates a satisfying frame by beginning the
story in California, where Japanese is spoken in May's home and
English is the language of the wider world, and ending the book in
Yokohama, where May and her husband speak to each other in their
shared personal language -- English -- while committing themselves
to life in Japan. The restrained narrative is carried along on an
undercurrent of alienation, determination and romance.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast with the illustrations in many of Say's other books,
the pictures in ``Tea With Milk'' are surprisingly wan and for the
most part dull. They are not stylistically different, but they lack
warmth. A few of them clearly had their genesis in snapshots from a
family album, and the sepia tones of nostalgia creep in from page
to page. Too many of the compositions are washed in browns and
grays, and too many are wide-angle shots -- the tan facade of the
department store, with dark windows, on a street where the plain
black cars of the era dominate the traffic, or three blank-faced
elevator operators in black uniforms, standing at attention in a
setting that is, again, mostly ocher, sienna and black.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Grandfather's Journey,'' the illustrations were the point,
and the story, while equally complex, was winnowed down to just a
line or two of prose on each page, employed like captions. But even
if ``Tea With Milk'' is visually only a shadow of Say's most
sumptuous books, including ``Grandfather's Journey'' and ``The Lost
Lake,'' it probably won't disappoint his fans, who will enjoy the
elaboration of a story they almost know and accept the
illustrations as mere accompaniments.
</P>
<P>
   As recent picture books about immigration go, there are cheerier
ones, like Arthur Dorros's ``Abuela'' and ``Isla,'' with their
throbbing, jampacked pictures by Elisa Kleven. And there are others
that seem more wrenchingly contemporary, like Michele Maria Surat's
``Angel Child, Dragon Child.'' But Allen Say's family history as
told in his two companion books somehow makes for intensely
memorable reading, as he records the individual longings, losses,
compromises and triumphs of lives lived between the poles of
adventure and tradition.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Moorman's most recent book is ``Waiting to Forget,'' a
memoir.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
