<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4146 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DIXON-NYTSF     05-12 1552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DIXON-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 30
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pieces of a Novel
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   672 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Henry Holt &AMP; Company. $30.
 &UR; SLEEP
</P>
<P>
   Stories.
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee House Press. Paper, $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; S.A.S.E.
</P>
<P>
   BY VINCE PASSARO
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   One of the signal experiences of working at a literary magazine
in the 1980's was being on the receiving end of the serial
submissions of Stephen Dixon, who ranks up there in terms of
productivity with the giants of the trade, Joyce
</P>
<P>
   Carol Oates and John Updike, but who, in those days at least,
spent vastly more on postage.
</P>
<P>
   For proof, you might check the magazines credited with prior
publication on the copyright pages of Dixon's novel ``Frog''
(1991), which was nominated for a National Book Award. The journals
noted there include (starting from the top) Agni Review, Ambit,
American Letters &AMP; Commentary, Another Chicago Magazine, Asylum,
Beloit Fiction Journal, Boston Review, Boulevard, Caprice,
Confrontation and so on. Note, we have 23 letters of the alphabet
still to go here. All told, 35 literary magazines appear on this
list, and running your eyes past their names is like a brief ride
down the National Endowment of the Arts' memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   To a fiction reader working at one of these magazines, Dixon's
stories seemed to come in at a fantastic rate. They arrived in worn
envelopes, hastily addressed. The stories themselves were neatly
typed but often photocopied at odd angles, and clipped to them were
small, torn pieces of paper on which Dixon's quick and nearly
illegible scrawl appeared: ``Here's my latest -- Stephen.'' If you
didn't know who he was, you would have thought of him as an inmate
with typewriter privileges, a desperate voice from behind prison or
asylum walls, so driven and copious was the prose. Instead, Dixon
was at that time the second in command, under John Barth, at the
Johns Hopkins University writing seminars, among the most
prestigious graduate writing programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon's newest books are ``30,'' which is subtitled ``Pieces of
a Novel,'' and ``Sleep,'' a collection of stories that span some 25
years of the author's career but have not heretofore been
collected. Much of ``Sleep'' feels as old as it must be; on the
bright side, a few of the stories remind you that Dixon in earlier
years resorted more to fantasy and a Middle American magic realism
than he does in his recent work, often with strong results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other Way,'' for example, is a story about a man searching the
roadside for a body in the bushes that he thinks he may have seen
earlier, a good Samaritan effort that turns into a dizzying
phantasmagoria of shadows, strange men and uncertainty. The best
piece in the collection is the title story, in which a husband goes
to sleep the day he buries his wife and feels as if, with them both
past suffering, he is about to rejoin her.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``30,'' which the reader takes to be all recent
work, nothing about the title, on investigation, proves to be true.
The numeral refers to the number of ``stories'' in what is supposed
to be a larger structure, though according to Dixon's
have-it-both-ways subtitle, something less than a novel. Adding to
the confusion is a tricky count. There are, actually, 29 stories,
each with a title, and then another 15 stories, also with titles
but gathered together as a subcategory under a single title,
``Ends.'' Thus, quite artificially, do we get ``30.'' None of this
genre-diddling has any effect. Dixon could as easily have called
the book ``44 Stories'' with no change in the reader's perception,
except that of having been saved the effort of trying to figure out
why the author called the book ``30: Pieces of a Novel,'' or what
feature distinguished the last 15 stories to make them substories,
or why, once so distinguished, they're collectively called
``Ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Frog, the eponymous hero of Dixon's earlier ``novel,'' was a man
with a wife and children and a career as a writer and teacher.
Nowadays, Dixon's character is named Gould. His full name is Gould
Bookbinder, a rather broad-fisted metaphor, and he is not only the
hero of ``30'' but of Dixon's last book, ``Gould.'' He also is a
man with a wife and children and a career that bounces from
journalism to writing to academia. The pieces in the book span the
years from his childhood to his mid-60's, and they are adamantly
not arranged by any chronology.
</P>
<P>
   Like Frog, Gould is mildly selfish, clumsy, ill tempered and
manic. He also thinks himself a wit, but Dixon puts us in the
awkward position of wondering whether the author finds him funny or
only portrays him as self-deluded on this score; Gould's gibes and
attempts at sarcasm are blunt and slightly off in the timing, like
the embarrassing dinner jests of a drunken uncle. Even the
characters around him don't seem to find him amusing.
</P>
<P>
   If the stories in ``Gould'' and now ``30,'' and also the pieces
in ``Frog,'' are not autobiographically based, they are strongly
autobiographical in flavor. Dixon's strengths as a writer -- the
quick revelations of a rushing, exhibitionist prose -- add to the
impression. Dixon's problem is that over a long career he has
relied on these strengths too heavily and repeated them too often;
he has turned them into mere affect. The run-on sentences, the
rapid-fire but mundane stream of consciousness, the apparently
frank but merely amphetamined dialogue that goes back and forth and
back and forth within page after page of unbroken paragraphs that
stretch as far as the eye can see: these devices are no longer
energized by an author who has anything fresh to say.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a taste from a segment of ``30'' called ``The First
Woman,'' when Gould, now 64, gets involved with a 23-year-old woman
after his wife has left him: '' 'I'm sorry, I don't always mean to
direct us, but the conversation's gotten too morbid, so can we
change the subject again?' 'Do you like movies?' and he said,
'Sure, some, who doesn't? though I prefer the older foreign ones in
black and white -- late 50's, early 60's, long before you were born
-- but I bet you like the new ones a lot,' and she said, 'Only if
they're good.' Has he seen . . .? and he said no, but does she
think it's worth going to? If she does he'll make a point of it,
and she said if he's serious about that she'll go with him, since
she wouldn't mind seeing it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The pieces, most of them, go on like this for pages. One long
story Gould tells his wife from his childhood is really a debate
about whether he's told her the story before, and about what she
remembers from the earlier telling. It ends with Gould addressing a
detail she doesn't think he's related, and offering his most
representative statement: He is sure he did mention the detail,
``because otherwise there wouldn't have been any point in telling
the story.'' You read this on page 62 of a 672-page book, and your
heart sinks. Exchanges like the ones above, and there are many, are
too easily achieved -- too easily typed, even -- and they're not
challenging to the reader or to Dixon himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the thread connecting these vignettes is sex. In the
first piece in ``30,'' a young Gould walks back to a girlfriend's
house and stops to watch a teen-age couple going at it in a car.
Hot and bothered, he tries to seduce the girlfriend when she comes
back from shopping, but only manages to annoy her and gets thrown
out. Other stories have him chasing a belly dancer on a cruise ship
and linking up, inexplicably given the conversation quoted above,
with that 23-year-old, who is the daughter of an academic
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   He watches women on the street, he thinks about them constantly
and drops many hints about a life of frequent masturbation. Gould's
lascivious nature is supposed to propel these stories and give them
what little power to shock that they have. But the sexuality is
bland and unsurprising; the cleaning up, one senses, takes longer
than the act.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon is a second-tier member of what one might call the Horny
Old Men School of American literature. It's a group that dates back
to the 50's, when writers like Philip Roth, John Updike and Harold
Brodkey emerged, all of whom were horny old men even in their
youth. Especially in lesser hands, the world of the horny old man
gets reduced to two basic stories: that of wanting to bed a woman,
failing and being miserable, or of succeeding and being miserable.
The latter should make superior reading to the former, but Dixon,
even when he gives his old goat Gould a break, wearies his readers
before getting there. He drowns us in a flood of mind-numbingly
dull preparatory moments and never lets Gould, or us, enjoy the
ride.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Vince Passaro is a contributing editor for Harper's Magazine and
director of communications at Adelphi University. He is a former
fiction editor at Columbia: A Magazine of Poetry and Prose.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
