<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4149 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-TRUTH-NYTSF     05-12 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-TRUTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE WAY THINGS NEVER WERE
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Truth About the ``Good Old Days.''
</P>
<P>
   By Norman H. Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   Atheneum Books for Young Readers. $17. (Ages 10 to 14)
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; SPRING CHILDREN'S BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   THOSE WEREN'T THE DAYS
</P>
<P>
   By Christine Stansell
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This is a book of debunking. Norman H. Finkelstein believes that
kids need to be disabused of the view, pushed on them by
baby-boomer parents, that the 1950's and 60's were a golden time.
His goal is to assure children that the reverse is true; that like
a Florida condo village, the America of the 1990's offers a
splendid five-star way of life against which the postwar decades
look like a shabby tract-house development.
</P>
<P>
   In topical chapters, Finkelstein provides a counterhistory to
idealizations about how much better life used to be in the areas of
health, crime, diet and family life. Yet where, exactly, the myths
about the good old days came from and who, exactly, believes them
is never clear. Does anyone seriously tell children that ``people
were healthier'' in the 1950's, as the title of the book's first
chapter has it? Surely not the parents of the sophisticated
middle-class youngsters at whom the book is pitched. Those adults
are more likely to convey ambivalence about a period that mixed
strong doses of misery and repression with undeniable childhood
pleasures. Many, if not most, young adolescents today barely have
any fix at all on the postwar past; and what they do understand is
an amalgam of ``Grease,'' trinket-laden hippies and the angst of
the civil rights movement, more likely to provoke historical
judgments of ``weird'' than ``awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely this widespread ignorance that makes the idea of
``The Way Things Never Were'' appealing. And there are moments when
Finkelstein succeeds, especially when he focuses on some
little-known piece of the past from a child's perspective. The
chapter on health begins promisingly enough with a description of
the polio epidemic of the early 50's. Finkelstein recalls the
worried parental admonitions that encoded fear deep in the mental
circuitry of early-50's childhood: ``Stay away from crowds!''
``Don't go swimming!'' He injects his own shot of horror -- always
a useful device in history for young people -- with descriptions of
polio victims entombed in iron lungs. Anecdotes of the
duck-and-cover exercises in the atomic bomb drills and the vogue
for ``dog tags'' strung around kids' necks (name, date of birth and
address could identify the charred body after a nuclear attack)
give a sense of how the big history of the cold war filtered into
the little histories of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way Things Never Were'' also introduces more general
perspectives -- on the dreadful eating habits of the 50's, for
instance, and the ubiquity of cigarette smoking. Finkelstein, a
school librarian in Massachusetts, is good on environmental issues,
re-creating something of the happy abandon with which America
strip-mined vast reaches of the upper South and Midwest, poured
noxious gases into the air and flung poisonous chemicals into
rivers. This material is useful for inquiring young researchers
looking for odd angles and, ideally, might even provoke talk
between young readers and parents who have their own, inevitably
more mixed, memories to recount.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, the book amasses information that lends itself
to school reports rather than cover-to-cover reading or interested
questions. Many chapters repeat well-worn stories, already
available from better sources: the Montgomery bus boycott and the
civil rights movement, the advent of rock-and-roll, the events of
the cold war, the prevalence of neo-Victorian sex roles.
</P>
<P>
   But the chief problem is the monotony of Finkelstein's
relentless, invidious distinctions between the benighted past and
our unsurpassable present. In his eagerness to undercut one
mythology, he substitutes another, underwritten by a remarkably
smug belief in progress without pain. A paradigmatic example is the
tale he tells about travel in America.
</P>
<P>
   The two-lane highways of the 50's appear in this book as
``crowded, narrow roads lined with dirty gas stations, 'greasy
spoon' restaurants and primitive cabins,'' to be pushed aside
providentially by the freeways. Thus into the trash bin of history
he tosses the fabled Route 66 as well as the myriad concrete
tracks, some of them plain and workaday, some of them enchanting,
that webbed the country. Wonderful books have been written about
the visual delights, curiosities and lingering joy of these
journeys -- as well as the carsickness, itchy boredom and racial
harassment people experienced on the road. But ``The Way Things
Never Were'' sets the travel Zeitgeist moving ever upward,
presumably to reach its zenith on Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the simplicity of the idea of ineluctable progress, it
is not the best hook for teaching history to children. History
books that provoke and enthrall young readers succeed by showing
that in some way they missed out on something. Good history, for
kids as well as adults, reveals the unalterable pastness of the
past -- the past as a foreign country, with its own logic, laws,
pleasures and sorrows, woven together in an intricate pattern of
human achievement and defeat, creativity and banality. Its lesson
is that change involves shifting quotients of loss and gain.
</P>
<P>
   The history is there to be taken on its own terms, initially,
and then to be weighed and balanced: reflected upon, marveled at or
deplored. ``The Way Things Never Were,'' despite its promising
subject matter, looks at the past only as a wan and pitiful
precursor to the splendiferous present.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Christine Stansell is a professor of history at Princeton
University. Her book ``American Moderns'' will be published early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
