<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1409EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4150 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WORLD-NYTSF     05-12 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WORLD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ANOTHER WORLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Pat Barker.
</P>
<P>
   278 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $24.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; HAUNTED HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   By Barry Unsworth
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In ``Another World,'' Pat Barker follows a principle more often
favored by playwrights than novelists: that the curtain should open
on an extreme situation, that from the first words, the first
motions, we should be involved in the tensions already twisting
about on stage. This novel does not seek to inveigle us or woo us;
we are pitched straight into it.
</P>
<P>
   There can't be many fictional families that have started off in
such a state of harassment and distress. Grandfather Geordie, age
101, is dying of cancer, beset by nightmares of World War I that
have resurfaced, after 80 years, to plague him again. Geordie's
grandson, Nick, and his second wife, Fran, have just moved into a
large house in a Newcastle suburb. They are not settled in yet;
everything is in chaos. He is a daily witness to his grandfather's
painful death. She, heavily pregnant, has their 2-year-old son to
look after and is more or less permanently exhausted and resentful.
Their respective children by former marriages, Miranda and Gareth,
loathe each other and take no trouble to conceal it. Gareth is
seriously disturbed anyway; Miranda's mother has just been admitted
to a mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The weather doesn't help either, being hot and sticky. And when,
in one of the novel's many powerfully realized scenes, the parents
and the two older children make an attempt at cooperation and start
stripping down the old wallpaper in the living room, they slowly
uncover an obscene, hate-filled painting of another family, the
Fanshawes, done 100 years earlier and bearing a frightening
resemblance to themselves. In fact, they recognize themselves all
too clearly in these terrible faces.
</P>
<P>
   The impulses of hatred and violence that continue to divide us,
symbolized by the horrors of a war remote in time but still present
in its consequences: these are the central concerns of the book. In
exploring them, ``Another World'' demonstrates the extraordinary
immediacy and vigor of expression we have come to expect from
Barker -- brilliant touches of observation, an unfailing ear for
dialogue, a talent for imagery that is darting and brief but
wonderfully apt. In the opening scene, skinheads clamber and
cluster threateningly around a car, then move away ``like a blanket
of flies.'' A bit later, Nick tries to get his grandfather to talk
about the past, ``poking him between the bars of his inertia, as
you'd try to rouse a moribund animal.'' Again and again, Barker
achieves that most difficult of combinations: effects that contain
the shock of the unexpected but are at once recognized to be
exactly right.
</P>
<P>
   The story is told in a terse and vivid present tense, which
works well for moments of accelerated action or sensation, not
always so well for reflection or introspection or when some greater
fullness of response is needed. There are times when the characters
in ``Another World'' seem caged in these short sentences, in this
changeless present. Here, for example, is Nick watching the
pregnant Fran, noting her swollen body and drained face: ``The
truth is he's repelled by her, but the truth frightens him and he
sheers away from it.'' Repulsion, knowledge, fear, avoidance --
it's a lot to try to get across in one short sentence. If what is
being unfolded is Nick's awareness of his own reactions from moment
to moment, we need considerably more. If, on the other hand, the
intention is simply to provide information of a general sort, it
seems clumsy and somehow lacking in authority.
</P>
<P>
   In maintaining the tension, the sense of some impending act of
violence that will echo the violence of the past -- themes on which
the novel depends -- Barker also puts an occasional strain on our
willingness to believe. Gareth, Fran's 11-year-old son, is an
unattractive lad, as children with severe problems often are. He
has a history of sadistic bullying of smaller children; he has
undergone psychiatric treatment; he throws terrifying tantrums in
public places. In short, he is more than just difficult. And he is
due in a few weeks to go to a new school, a huge comprehensive
where he has no friends but a number of dreaded enemies. He is
living in fear, a fact well known to his mother. In these
circumstances, wouldn't the parents, both university graduates,
both belonging to a section of society familiar with its rights and
highly articulate in claiming them, inquire into alternatives for
Gareth? Or is it that, for the novel's larger purposes, he needs to
be kept frightened and vicious? Any suspicion that probability is
being sacrificed to plot is bound to put something of a crack in
the intensity of the illusion. The author always deals the cards
and they are always stacked; but we shouldn't be made too aware of
this or the cheat will fail.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of these reservations, it doesn't. The novel exerts its
grip early and, as the strands of its plot come together, past and
present show their similarly poisonous fangs. The narrative pace is
superbly maintained -- this is a novel that doesn't allow you to
miss a sentence. The beleaguered, rancorous, struggling family of
the present; the dark story of the Fanshawes; the legacy of the
1914-18 war relived in the nightmares of the dying Geordie: these
elements fuse together to form an urgent meditation on the
cruelties of experience, the mutual distortions of past and
present. To reinforce these effects, Barker takes risks, the bolder
for her being in general so naturalistic a writer. Ghosts move
through this story, some merely emblematic, like the ghost pain of
Geordie's old bayonet wound, some true phantoms, the faces and
forms of the dead. It says much for the skill and tact of Barker's
writing that these wraiths are made, without strain or contrivance,
to form part of the pattern of hauntings of which the novel is
composed.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good deal of compassion in Barker's book, but not a
lot of hope. Indeed, at times there is what seems almost a perverse
insistence on the desolation of things. Snipping away with
secateurs at the bushes around his house, lacerating his hands and
arms, Nick pulls out a nest of obscenely dead fledglings. Even the
roses in his garden have dead flies all over them, ``like caps of
gray scurf.'' We are spared none of the blood and vomit and
excrement attendant on Geordie's last days, nor the searing
humiliation of his weakness. You can be sure that when he tries to
stand up, his dressing gown will fall away to reveal a ruinous
scrotum. No reconciliation is offered and there is no real
resignation, in spite of the elegiac note sounded in the last
section, when Geordie, in his single person both victim and
murderer, is laid to rest in the churchyard with ``the innocent and
the guilty . . . side by side, under the obliterating grass.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the novel, Nick reflects that the past never
threatens anything as simple or avoidable as repetition. Of course,
our deeper fear is not that the horrors of the past will be
repeated but that they have never gone away. While ``Another
World'' does little to reassure us on this score, it is a powerful
and moving and deeply humane study of the tyranny of the past and
the quandaries of the present. The virtues it extols are those of
stoicism, endurance, dignity -- the classic virtues in the face of
a hostile universe.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Barry Unsworth's latest novel, ``Losing Nelson,'' will be
published this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
