<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4151 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-INTERVIEW-NYT     05-12 1532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-INTERVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERVIEW WITH PAT BARKER
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; OLD WAR WOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   BY ALIDA BECKER
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The most striking character in Pat Barker's new novel is a
centenarian war veteran named Geordie, who in his dying days
manages to frighten, frustrate and charm everyone who comes near
him. Geordie returned from the Great War with a bayonet wound in
his stomach and a head full of guilty memories -- memories that
readers of Barker's Regeneration trilogy will instantly recognize.
Those novels, like ``Another World,'' owe at least part of their
inspiration to Barker's childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1943, in the thick of World War II, in the industrial
northeast of England, Barker never knew her father. She was told
that he was in the R.A.F., that he had died. She and her mother
lived with her grandparents until, seven years after Barker's
birth, her mother moved out to start a new family. Barker remained
with her grandparents -- and so her grandfather's war, which had
left him with scars from a bayonet wound, became part of her own
stock of memories. So too did the memory of what it was like to
care for an invalid: after getting her university degree, Barker
returned to nurse her dying grandmother, who had herself tended her
husband for many years.
</P>
<P>
   How much of Geordie derives from this slice of Barker's personal
past? In a telephone interview from her home in Durham, not far
from Thornaby-on-Tees, the town where she was born, Barker
reflected on ``all the tributaries'' that flow into a character.
The main similarity between Geordie and her grandfather, she
decided, was that Geordie, who has cancer, is convinced that the
bayonet wound is responsible for his increasingly unbearable pain
-- a diagnosis her grandfather had earlier made for himself. ``I
was fascinated,'' she explained, ``by the idea that in each case
the man needs to believe that the war is what's killing him.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of Geordie's steely flirtatiousness? As a widower in
his late 70's, Geordie acquired a new girlfriend with an ``opulent
bosom'' and a penchant for leopard-print blouses. Over 20 years
later, as ``Another World'' draws to a close, he somehow summons
the energy to rise from his deathbed and spruce himself up for one
final meeting with an attractive university professor who has
interviewed him for a book -- a woman closer to his grandson's age,
who is definitely not immune to his charms. Barker laughed. ``No,
that's not my grandfather,'' she said. ``My grandfather wasn't
flirtatious.'' That part of Geordie put her more in mind of an
elderly Billy Prior, the character who as a young man gradually
comes to dominate the Regeneration novels.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the physical aspects of Geordie's character were derived
from yet another source, a World War I veteran Barker met on the
battlefields of France while filming a documentary for the BBC.
``He was 103,'' she recalled, ``and had perfect hearing, perfect
memory. He stood upright; he had no arthritis. He seemed physically
indestructible.'' But when she put her arms around him, she was
surprised by how fragile he was. ``You felt he could crumble away
before you, in your fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   That eye for the delicate, often puzzling balance of human
strength and weakness, both physical and mental, has been at the
core of Barker's work from the beginning. Her first two novels,
``Union Street'' and ``Blow Your House Down'' (originally published
in the early 1980's and recently brought back into print in a
one-volume paperback), were generally praised -- and generally
pigeonholed as ``regional'' and ``feminist'' -- for their gritty,
unsentimental depictions of the lives of working-class women in the
north of England. Although her next two novels, ``The Century's
Daughter'' and ``The Man Who Wasn't There'' (which Barker said
would also be combined in a forthcoming paperback), moved her
closer to the critics' idea of the literary mainstream, it wasn't
until 1991, with the publication in Britain of ``Regeneration,'' a
historical novel about mentally ill World War I soldiers, including
real-life figures like the poet Siegfried Sassoon and his doctor,
William Rivers, that her place there was staked out. With the
succeeding volumes of the trilogy, ``The Eye in the Door'' and
``The Ghost Road'' (which won the Booker Prize in 1995), that place
was firmly established. Barker appears to have found the whole
process both frustrating and satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early criticism -- that I wrote mainly for and about women
-- is an artificial one in some ways,'' she remarked. ``My early
books were published by a feminist publishing house, so naturally
they were perceived in a particular way; they got that artificial
perspective.'' When ``Regeneration'' appeared, ``I did seem to be
setting off at right angles, which wasn't actually true. The themes
in 'Regeneration' are also the themes of books like 'Union Street'
-- they're about trauma, whether it's experienced by working-class
people or aristocrats. Women were also central to the Regeneration
books, even though they didn't figure as largely in them. They are,
together with Rivers, a sort of moral center.''
</P>
<P>
   Does ``Another World,'' which takes place in the present day and
is set in the north of England, in a Newcastle still partly
blighted by industrial decline, represent a more obvious melding of
her early work with the Regeneration trilogy? ``I do think I'm
trying to knit the two strands together,'' Barker agreed. Nick, the
middle-aged schoolteacher whose point of view dominates much of the
action, is a kind of clearinghouse for a good deal of the novel's
speculation about memory and identity, but at the same time ``a lot
of the force of the book is deflected from him onto the two
generations on either side.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus Nick figures in a pair of pivotal scenes: a late-night
tussle in a garbage-strewn back alley with Geordie, who has escaped
from his bedroom and is hallucinating a return to the trenches, and
a frantic search for Nick's 11-year-old stepson, Gareth, who has
run away from home and wound up in a nocturnal wasteland of
derelict factory buildings sectioned off by barbed-wire fences.
Clearly, Barker wants us to think about how the combat of (and
with) the past is mirrored in the domestic skirmishes of the
present -- to consider, as a passage early in ``Another World'' has
it, ``the power of old wounds to leak into the present.''
</P>
<P>
   The reader is also meant, Barker said, ``to be comparing
Geordie's fantastic memory, his belief in remembering the past and
using the past as a guide to the present, with Gareth's total
ability to reinvent the past, even down to what happened the
previous day.'' Gareth, like many boys his age, is obsessed with
violent computer games. Unlike many boys his age, he shows signs of
erupting into real violence. ``The point with Gareth is that you
don't know how dangerous he is,'' Barker remarked. ``He could turn
out to be a fine, upstanding computer analyst or he could turn into
someone you read about in the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   At school, Gareth has been reprimanded for bullying and
threatening younger children. During a family outing, Barker
positions him on a cliff, hurling rocks down onto a sandy beach.
Below, unobserved by their parents, is his 2-year-old stepbrother,
Jasper. The temptation is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that beach scene,'' Barker recalled, ``I tried to make much
of the fact that Gareth sees the child from above. From up there on
the cliff, what he sees has some of the impersonality of video
games. From there, his brother looks like a piglet, not a child.
It's easy to dehumanize someone at that point.'' Writing that
scene, she was also thinking of grown-up video games, of modern
technological warfare, with its ``precision siting, puffs of smoke
behind which actual human beings are blown to pieces. The reader is
not meant to get off too lightly. I also meant the reader to be
thinking of a disturbed society.''
</P>
<P>
   What will she want readers to be thinking of next time around?
She's reluctant to talk about the novel she's working on now,
beyond saying that she has completed a first draft. ``By the end of
the first draft, it's full of wrong turnings,'' she explained. ``By
then I've seen the book I ought to have written instead of the book
I have written.'' Might it resemble the novel she talked about in
an interview in late 1995, just after ``The Ghost Road'' won the
Booker Prize? Set in a rundown housing project, the book was going
to focus on young joy riders who steal cars and then burn them to
destroy the evidence. No, Barker said, with a laugh, that one isn't
likely to make it into print. ``I had problems understanding their
feelings about cars. I just couldn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Alida Becker is an editor at the New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
