<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BONE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE WHITE BONE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Barbara Gowdy.
</P>
<P>
   330 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Books/ Henry Holt &AMP; Company. $23.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; HER NAME IS MUD
</P>
<P>
   BY SARAH BOXER
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Write a novel about a herd of female elephants and you're in
virgin territory. Who's to say what's right when it comes to
elephant thoughts, elephant speech, elephant names?
</P>
<P>
   The very first chapter of Barbara Gowdy's new novel, ``The White
Bone,'' contains a crucial and trivial event. Mud, a young female
elephant, is renamed. Why? Because a male mounts her and ``digs her
calf tunnel.'' The rule is that male elephants get to keep their
names for life ``because bulls are calves forever,'' but female
elephants, once mounted, are transformed. They are hollowed, or
hallowed, depending on which elephant you ask. And in place of
their pert noun-names they get hyphenated verb-names. Mud is
renamed She-Spurns to go with the nonvirginal names of her family,
the She-S's: She-Swaggers, She-Sees, She-Snorts, She-Soothes,
She-Screams.
</P>
<P>
   You might not think a name really matters. But try slogging
across the parched veld with a herd of verb-names and keeping them
straight while also tracking the pachyderms' memories,
hallucinations, visions, superstitions and plain old perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Gowdy has kindly supplied, in the manner of 19th-century
novelists, the family trees of five elephant families: the She-S's,
the She-D's, the She-M's, the She-B's-and-B's (a subgroup of the
She-B's) and the We-F's (who are very self-centered). She has also
provided a glossary of elephant words. The ``She-eye'' is the sun,
a ``She-he'' is a spotted hyena, the ``She-ones'' are elephants and
``the She'' is the mother of all elephants, a k a God. And she has
consulted elephant experts to insure that the migrations, sex
lives, family bonds, mourning habits and secretions are realistic.
But it doesn't always help.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God, or, as the elephants would say, thank the She, that
some of the elephants are male. Tall Time, Torrent and Swamp are
memorable because their names are nouns. And praise be the females
who manage to hold on to their maiden names. She-Spurns, true to
her name, spurns her name as well as her ardent suitor. Her name is
Mud through most of the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's narrow-minded to balk at verb-names. But Gowdy, the
author of ``Mister Sandman'' and ``We So Seldom Look on Love,'' is
the creator, ``the She,'' of these fictional creatures. She gives
the elephants their names and imagines their beliefs. She even
allows her elephants a mating cheer: ``Ready and ripe? Yes! Yes! /
Streaming rank smell? Yes! Yes! / Go then and bore the tunnel
wherein / A newborn will dwell! Yes! Yes!''
</P>
<P>
   So why does she choose a nomenclature that makes so many
sentences into ``She sells seashells''? (A simple sample will
suffice: ``As she passes She-Sees, She-Scares nudges her to come
along, and like a submissive calf She-Sees obeys.'') And why do
these elephants, who are in most respects bawdy and vile, use
phrases like ``by my troth'' and sing hymns of thanksgiving
(``Come, Thou Fount of every blessing! Fill my trunk to blare Thy
grace'')? They sound like a herd of Puritans.
</P>
<P>
   A partial answer is that they are Puritans. ``The White Bone''
is a big religious put-on, an elephantine ``Pilgrim's Progress.''
The white elephant bone at the center of the book is a relic that
everyone believes will point to the ``Safe Place.'' The elephants,
fearful that uttering the name of the bone will weaken it, call it
``the that-way bone'' (sounds like ``the Jahweh bone''). The
elephants' trek is a test of their faith in the face of drought and
bounty hunters. When Date Bed, a Christ figure, picks up a rearview
mirror in the desert, it is a lesson in vanity. And those monstrous
female names are not so different from Prudence, Piety, Chastity
and Discretion.
</P>
<P>
   You can see that the novel is plenty funny and plenty odd, but
it would have been far funnier without the verb-names. They keep
the reader from reveling in Gowdy's great gift for parody and her
even greater gift for sensual, gross-out description.
</P>
<P>
   Here is an example: ``The nurse cow eats the dung of the other
grazers, 'drought fruit,' she calls it, and exhorts the rest of
them to do likewise, and when anybody craves salt she revives her
urine-drinking campaign. . . . Roaring, 'Watch She-Soothes!' she
curves her trunk under Bent to drink his, and the little calf
wobbles on his delicate legs and shows the whites of his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sickening, sure. But in an arid land of She-ones, the reader
gulps down those salty sentences like springwater.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Boxer is a reporter for the Arts section of The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
