<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4153 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ADAM-NYTSF     05-12 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ADAM-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 EXPECTING ADAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   A True Story of Birth, Rebirth, and Everyday Magic.
</P>
<P>
   By Martha Beck.
</P>
<P>
   Times Books/Random House. $23.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; WHAT VISIONS HAVE I SEEN!
</P>
<P>
   BY SUSAN CHEEVER
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Memoir is a woman's game. A disproportionate number of memoirs
are written by women. The most controversial memoirs -- the ones
that provoke heated public argument and contemptuous reviews -- are
almost all written by women. No wonder. Women are publishing
stories that have only been told privately, in whispered
conversations and intimate diaries, for centuries. These stories
are the text of our domestic life, with all its fits and starts,
kitchen dramas and bedroom tragedies. They are stories about loving
famous men, stories of incest, stories about secret happenings in
the lives of women; most of all they are stories of marriage and
children. Childbirth, after all, is also a woman's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expecting Adam'' is a glorious example. Martha Beck is smart,
willing to confide in the reader, good at concise description and
very funny, particularly about the most serious possible subjects
-- childbirth, angels and surviving at Harvard. Parts of this story
are hard
</P>
<P>
   to believe -- psychic experiences, glimpses of metaphysical
beings -- but Beck's voice is so sympathetic and most of her
details so accurate that they frequently carry all before them. It
is hardly important that this is a story about bearing and raising
an exceptional child -- a son with Down syndrome -- in exceptional
circumstances (Beck and her husband, John, have six Harvard degrees
between them). Beck is telling it for all women who have raised
exceptional children and ended up feeling privileged, and for all
mothers who have found communities that put a high value on
material accomplishments simply unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the story of two driven Harvard academics who found
out in mid- pregnancy that their unborn son would be retarded,''
Beck explains. ``To their own surprise and the horrified dismay of
the university community, the couple ignored the abundant means,
motive and opportunity to obtain a therapeutic abortion. They
decided to allow their baby to be born. What they did not realize
is that they themselves were the ones who would be 'born,' infants
in a new world where magic is commonplace, Harvard professors are
the slow learners and retarded babies are the master teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck is also a pretty good teacher. Her chatty descriptions of
life at Harvard, combined with her humorous detailing of the rigors
of bad pregnancies and caring for her toddler daughter, Katie, are
sharp. When she begins having paranormal experiences -- she can see
her husband, who is in Japan; she is visited by ministering angels
-- she is more skeptical than anyone. ``How many times a day does
some poor hapless human really need a good supernatural protector
and fail to get one?'' she asks after she experiences being carried
-- with Katie -- out of a deadly fire in her apartment building by
strong, invisible hands. ``People are tortured and killed and raped
and pillaged on a daily basis, and if there are angels in the
vicinity, they apparently just sit around watching -- wringing
their ectoplasmic little hands, perhaps, but letting nature take
its course.''
</P>
<P>
   As Beck's life spins out of control -- when she finds out that
she is carrying a Down syndrome child, not one doctor connected
with Harvard approves of her decision to keep it -- the angels'
visits become more frequent and more visible. If this is hard to
believe, no one has a harder time with it than Beck herself.
Finally, she figures out a way to accept what is happening to her.
``Until that point, I had followed the good old Baconian logic of
refusing to believe anything until it was proven true,'' she
writes. ``Now I decided that I was willing to believe anything,
absolutely anything I heard, saw or felt, until it was proven
false. If this doesn't sound like a major life transition to you,
it's because you've never done it.''
</P>
<P>
   The story trembles on the verge of tragedy again and again, but
it has a happy ending after all. Adam is born, and Martha and John
with their young family leave Harvard and move to the Southwest,
where life is informal and a graduate school career is not
considered more important than a child. Beck, a career counselor
and columnist for Mademoiselle, is the author of ``Breaking Point:
Why Women Fall Apart and How They Can Re-Create Their Lives''; her
husband is a partner at Anderson Consulting and a professor of
international management at the University of California, Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I once spoke to an entering class of Harvard Medical School
students about my pregnancy and my decision,'' Beck recalls. ``Adam
was asleep on my lap at the time, wearing a bow tie and a dreamy
expression. After the speech, I was approached by an elderly
professor whose name I forget. He had just become the grandfather
of a little girl with Down's. As he talked to me, he stroked Adam's
soft blond hair and wept. He loved his granddaughter with
inexplicable openness, and the experience had changed his whole
life. Now there's a doctor with some real information to offer the
parents of a retarded baby. Whoever said that love is blind was
dead wrong. Love is the only thing on this earth that lets us see
each other with the remotest accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Susan Cheever is the author of nine books, including her recent
memoir, ``Note Found in a Bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
