<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4156 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-NY     05-12 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the enormous talents of the folk artist Edward Hicks
(1780-1849) are often celebrated, it was his mission as a religious
servant that inspired his illustrious allegorical series of
paintings, ``The Peaceable Kingdom.'' In THE KINGDOMS OF EDWARD
HICKS (Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Center/Colonial
Williamsburg Foundation/Abrams, $39.95), Carolyn J. Weekley,
director of museums at Colonial Williamsburg, deftly chronicles
Hicks's early training as a decorative painter, his journey into
the Quaker world and his lifelong struggle to reconcile his
spiritual beliefs with his material needs. Hicks's mother died when
he was a toddler. Unable to support the child, his father sent him
to live with family friends who raised him as a Quaker. As a
teen-ager Hicks was apprenticed to a local stagecoach shop to learn
decorative painting. He became a Quaker minister in 1811. He
received no pay for this position and supported his family with his
decorative painting, a practice that stood in direct contradiction
to the utilitarian views of the Quakers. Increasingly Hicks's views
diverged from those of the Quakers, and under the guidance of his
cousin Elias Hicks, a Hicksite faction was formed. There was much
animosity between the Hicksites and the orthodox Quakers, which had
an irrevocable effect on Hicks. His many versions of the
``Peaceable Kingdom'' paintings symbolically reflect the urgency of
that discord as well as his desire for peace between the two
divisions. Using Isaiah's prophecy ``The wolf also shall dwell with
the lamb . . .'' as a blueprint, Hicks's paintings, in varying
degrees, mirror his personal agony about religious tension. Weekley
has compiled a scholarly history of Hicks as both minister and
painter, and of the turmoil these conflicting vocations wrought on
his own kingdom. _ Amy Todd
</P>
<P>
   THE PIG FARMER'S DAUGHTER AND OTHER TALES OF AMERICAN JUSTICE
</P>
<P>
   Episodes of Racism and Sexism in the Courts From 1865 to the
Present.
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Frances Berry.
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rape cases disclose unambiguously that the prevailing
narrative used in the courts is of white male privilege,'' Mary
Frances Berry writes. ``Rape also enhances our understanding that
patriarchy is the subtext underlying race, class and gender.'' With
claims like these, Berry regrettably drowns long hours of research
in a corrosive blend of rancor, rage and cheap Foucault. Berry,
chairwoman of the United States Commission on Civil Rights and the
Geraldine R. Segal Professor of American Social Thought at the
University of Pennsylvania, maintains that American justice
systematically favors white heterosexual men over minorities, women
and homosexuals. Her argument draws heavily on cases from the Jim
Crow South, a period when most judges were Confederate veterans.
What such men thought about race equality and women's rights is
hardly surprising -- less surprising than Berry's effort to read
each and every case as a study in oppression. If courts let black
children inherit from white fathers, if they helped poor women, if
uncommon judges guarded black people's rights, all this -- Berry
scoffs -- reflects only paternalism, the ``Southern gentlemanly
tradition.'' In her focal case, from Texas in 1886, a black man,
Albert Johnson, was charged with raping a German farm girl. She
said her assailant was cleanshaven, and identified Johnson seven
weeks after the crime. Convicted and sentenced, Johnson finally
went free, thanks to six witnesses (black and white, including a
sheriff and two judges) who testified that he had always worn a
mustache. Berry attacks all parties: jurors for racism, ``elite
appellate judges'' for crediting six witnesses' testimony more than
a shaky identification -- even Johnson, for being the ``boy'' of
his ``well-to-do white patrons.'' Were Atticus Finch to stray into
these pages, he would be unmasked as David Duke. _ Allen D. Boyer
</P>
<P>
   A GOOD ENOUGH DAUGHTER
</P>
<P>
   A Memoir.
</P>
<P>
   By Alix Kates Shulman.
</P>
<P>
   Schocken, $23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I would suffocate if I didn't leave,'' Alix Kates
Shulman writes about suburban Cleveland in the early 1950's and the
stifling embrace of her family. At the age of 20, she left for New
York to become a writer, but she returned more than four decades
later to care for her aging parents, who died in 1996. In ``A Good
Enough Daughter,'' Shulman, the author of the novel ``Memoirs of an
Ex-Prom Queen,'' now 66 years old, honors connections she once felt
compelled to negate. Her portrayal is refreshingly upbeat, infused
with insight, affection and respect. Her father's congestive heart
failure and her mother's progressive dementia do not erase their
vigorous personalities. ``Trawling for secrets'' in her parents'
past, Shulman was surprised to discover herself. Her mother had an
exciting job with the Works Progress Administration and a bohemian
group of female colleagues. File cabinets stuffed with short
stories, essays and articles reflect the ``furious energy'' of her
mother's later attempt at a literary career. ``Once I launched my
own life, I somehow forgot,'' Shulman says. Nor did she associate
her mother's political activism, ``which dotted my childhood with
moments of vicarious glory,'' with her own feminism. Excerpts from
a brief autobiography, written by her father when he was 88,
display the love of language he and his daughter had always shared.
Her own occasional letters home, however, are painful; seeing them,
all carefully preserved, she writes, ``I regretted having saved so
few of hers, and worse, having often cringed to read them.'' This
memoir benefits from Shulman's unflinching honesty. ``I asserted my
difference,'' she says, ``until my past was obliterated.'' With her
independence established, Shulman is free finally to recognize her
parents' ``extravagant love'' as the source of her own strength.
``Now that their power is spent,'' she writes, ``I taste their
sweetness.'' _ Leslie Chess Feller
</P>
<P>
   ONE MORE TIME
</P>
<P>
   The Best of Mike Royko.
</P>
<P>
   Commentaries by Lois Wille.
</P>
<P>
   University of Chicago, $22.
</P>
<P>
   How do you boil down the nearly 8,000 newspaper columns that
Mike Royko wrote from 1963 until his death in 1997 into a ``best
of'' collection? His friend and colleague Lois Wille skillfully
provides the introductions to the pieces, but, of course, the joy
of ``One More Time'' is Royko in his own words -- for example, on
the unveiling of Chicago's Picasso sculpture in 1967. The statue's
eyes ``are pitiless, cold, mean . . . like the eyes of every slum
owner who made a buck off the small and weak. And of every building
inspector who took a wad from a slum owner to make it all
possible.'' The collection shows Royko's command of a range of
emotions, as in his eulogy for his wife: ``We met when she was 6
and I was 9. Same neighborhood street. Same grammar school. So if
you ever have a 9-year-old son who says he is in love, don't laugh
at him. It can happen.'' _ Mary Eileen O'Connell
</P>
<P>
   FAULKNER, MISSISSIPPI
</P>
<P>
   By Edouard Glissant.
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25.
</P>
<P>
   Edouard Glissant's ``Faulkner, Mississippi'' is a short,
ambitious and, at times, rambunctious expedition into Yoknapatawpha
County. Well translated from the French by Barbara Lewis and Thomas
C. Spear, it plunges you into the peculiar miasma of the place,
with its questions about the legitimacy of the South's foundation,
bloodlines and descendants and the role and place of blacks,
Indians, women and children. Glissant, a poet, essayist and
playwright, calls Faulkner's characteristic situation ``the
inextricable,'' and writes that Faulkner's technique for conveying
it consists of a ``gradation in disclosure'' that ``dissociates
cause and effect, delays revelation, diffracts the perception of
the real.'' He describes the progression of Faulkner's work as ``an
accumulating mystery and a whirling vertigo -- gathering momentum
rather than being resolved.'' This last characterization applies to
the way in which Glissant himself proceeds: there are no
demonstrations in his book, only observations that are slowly
accumulated, insights gradually or suddenly revealed and questions
raised -- all of which transforms an academic project (undertaken
when Glissant was teaching literature at Southern University in
Baton Rouge) into a piece of writing that is often poetic. _
Christine Schwartz Hartley
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
