<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4170 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NY     05-12 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS
 BY SCOTT VEALE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERYBODY WAS SO YOUNG:
</P>
<P>
   Gerald and Sara Murphy. A Lost Generation Love Story
</P>
<P>
   By Amanda Vaill. Broadway, $15.
</P>
<P>
   The Murphys were a dazzling, rich American couple who knew and
entertained just about everybody who was anybody in Paris and on
the French Riviera in the 1920's, from Fitzgerald to Picasso. In
1998 our reviewer, Brooke Allen, called this ``a marvelously
readable biography'' by ``a skillful and compassionate writer.''
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT A BOY
</P>
<P>
   By Nick Hornby. Riverhead, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   Will Freeman is a smug but aimless London bachelor in his 30's
who devises a dating scheme to tap the market in sexy divorced
women by pretending to be a single dad and joining a support group
full of single mothers. Before long, though, he runs into a
troubled 12-year-old boy who sees right through him, and the two
become unlikely soul mates. ``Hornby . . . combines a skilled,
intuitive appreciation for the rigors of comic structure with
highly original insights about the way the enchantments of popular
culture insinuate themselves into middle-class notions of
romance,'' Hal Espen wrote here in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A WALK IN THE WOODS:
</P>
<P>
   Rediscovering America on the Appalachian Trail
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Bryson. Broadway, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The author chronicles in breezy, good-humored fashion his
five-month struggle to hike the 2,100-mile Appalachian Trail from
Georgia to Maine. Bryson is ``a satirist of the first rank, one who
writes (and walks) with Chaucerian brio,'' Dwight Garner wrote here
last year. Searching for Yellowstone: Ecology and Wonder in the
Last Wilderness, by Paul Schullery (Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $14),
is an environmental and human history of Yellowstone National Park
by a longtime park ranger and administrator. ``Schullery . . . has
given us a refreshingly unhyperbolic look at the place he loves,''
Michael Parfit wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOMLAND
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Price. Island/Dell, $7.99.
</P>
<P>
   This novel tracks the racial turmoil that erupts after a white
woman turns up in a New Jersey city and claims her 4-year-old son
was abducted by a black carjacker. '' 'Freedomland' is infinitely
more than a detective story,'' Francine Prose said here last year.
``It aspires to the heft and weight of a 19th-century Russian
classic.''
</P>
<P>
   WORMHOLES: Essays and Occasional Writings
</P>
<P>
   By John Fowles. Owl/Holt, $16.
</P>
<P>
   This grab bag of musings by the 73-year-old English novelist
covers a lot of territory -- from autobiographical pieces to
cantankerous forays into politics and culture. ``The book is as
various, quirkily learned, beguiling, opinionated and, in parts, as
sumptuously written as Fowles's fiction,'' Roger Kimball wrote here
last year.
</P>
<P>
   THE IRON TRACKS
</P>
<P>
   By Aharon Appelfeld. Schocken, $12.
</P>
<P>
   This Israeli novel is about a concentration camp survivor who
wanders through Austria buying sacred books and other remnants of
the Jewish culture that once flourished there while searching for
the Nazi officer who murdered his parents. ``Appelfeld's controlled
fiction compresses large themes into small spaces,'' Jonathan Rosen
said here in 1998. Bronstein's Children, by Jurek Becker
(University of Chicago, $15), is another novel about the psychic
aftershocks of the Holocaust, in which an 18-year-old German Jew in
1973 stumbles onto his father and two other camp survivors as they
torture a former Nazi guard. ``Becker, writing simply and clearly
in an unstrained narrative, speaks with the voice of knowledge,''
Eva Figes said here in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   THE COLLECTED POEMS OF AMY CLAMPITT
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   Clampitt's poetry is full of restless motion and energy as she
evokes places like the Quaker village in Iowa where she was born
and Greenwich Village, where she cultivated a resolute bohemianism.
In 1997 in the Book Review, Christopher Benfey called this
posthumously published collection a testament to an ``extraordinary
life's work.''
</P>
<P>
   A BEAUTIFUL MIND
</P>
<P>
   By Sylvia Nasar. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $16.
</P>
<P>
   This biography of John Nash, the Nobel Prize-winning developer
of game theory, follows him from his early career through his
crippling bouts of schizophrenia to his recovery years later. The
author, who writes about economics for The New York Times, ``offers
a remarkable look into the arcane world of mathematics and the
tragedy of madness,'' Simon Singh wrote here in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN FIRES:
</P>
<P>
   Assault on Eden. A Novel of the Ecuadorian Rainforest
</P>
<P>
   By Marnie Mueller. Curbstone, $13.95.
</P>
<P>
   A former Peace Corps volunteer revisits the jungles of coastal
Ecuador on her honeymoon in 1969 and becomes involved in a battle
between the native people and American oil companies. ``The
characters are well drawn, and the novel has adventure, intrigue
and romance as well as politics,'' one critic said in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   HAVANA DREAMS: A STORY OF A CUBAN FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   By Wendy Gimbel. Vintage, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The lives of three unhappy women -- a wealthy bourgeoise, her
daughter and the daughter's child by Fidel Castro -- provide a
striking perspective on Cuba and its odd destiny. ``The result is a
shimmering book,'' Alma Guillermoprieto said here last year. Scott
Veale
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
