<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4171 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-CHRISTIANS-NYTSF     05-12 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-CHRISTIANS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBLE BELT NEEDS TO DISAVOW THE GUNBELT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    On the same day as the White House conference on children and
violence, the Christian Coalition ran radio spots ascribing blame
for the Littleton, Colo., school massacre.
 &HT;    What caused Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold to kill their
classmates? A government that has outlawed God. If children could
pray, they would not shoot one another.
 &HT;    Many Americans find this analysis compelling. Since the early
1960s when the Supreme Court ruled against school-sponsored prayer,
conservative Christians have made it their cause-celebre to put God
back in the classroom.
 &HT;    Nearly every social ill -- teen pregnancy, drug abuse and low
SAT scores -- can be blamed on God's banishment. Teen murder has
been added to the list.
 &HT;    God is mad for being exiled and is getting even by allowing evil
to run amok.
 &HT;    This is wrong on several counts. First, the courts only forbade
school-sponsored religious activities. Teachers and principles
could not pray or read the Bible. Even after the decisions,
students could still pray, read their Bibles, and hold religious
meetings on campus.
 &HT;    The line between school-sanctioned and personal religious
activity was sometimes difficult for local school boards to
discern. In the confusion, some wrongly disallowed constitutional
religious freedom.
 &HT;    The Clinton administration has tried to correct these abuses and
``ensure that religious freedom does not end at the schoolroom
door.'' The president's commitment to religious freedom has allowed
for an increase of student-led religious activities on campuses
across the country.
 &HT;    Harris and Klebold did not murder in a religious vacuum. Since
most of their victims proclaimed Christian faith, I suspect
Columbine High School allowed a full range of legal religious
activities -- such as Young Life and Meet You at the Pole -- for
its students.
 &HT;    Second, scholars have demonstrated that the Supreme Court
decisions were applied unevenly. In the South and West, many
schools continued to sponsor religious activities. For many
Americans, school prayer never ended. Local custom -- ``don't ask;
don't tell'' prayer policies -- prevailed.
 &HT;    Such was the case at my Arizona high school in the 1970s. At
least one teacher conducted Bible studies under the guise of a
``Bible as Literature'' course. We prayed at school events and
student council meetings. Mormon, evangelical Christian, Roman
Catholic and Jewish groups maintained a strong campus presence with
official sanction.
 &HT;    The Christian Coalition may not have noticed, but the recent
school shootings have occurred in the places where the Supreme
Court rulings were rarely enforced. Jonesboro, Arkansas. Paducah,
Kentucky. Pearl, Mississippi. Littleton, Colorado. Except for the
episodes in Oregon and Pennsylvania, these attacks happened in
America's Bible Belt. These kids did not grow up liberal, secular
humanists.
 &HT;    The problem is not God. The problem is guns, access to guns, and
conservative Christian resistance to gun control.
 &HT;    Throughout American history, Christians have vacillated in their
attitudes toward guns. For colonists and pioneers, guns were
essential for hunting and protection. But neighbors often settled
disputes with firearms. If someone offended you, shoot them.
 &HT;    As the country became more urbanized in the 18th century,
vigilante gun violence disturbed many Christians. The church,
particularly the refined Church of England, allowed for controlled
revenge -- dueling. Thus, among pious Christians, gentlemanly rules
replaced killing sprees.
 &HT;    When Aaron Burr killed the saintly Alexander Hamilton in a duel,
Christians were shocked. Their outrage fueled the most successful
gun-control movement in American history -- the anti-dueling
crusade.
 &HT;    Convinced that God frowned upon gun vengeance, the churches
campaigned to end dueling. Although it took several decades,
religious groups changed national attitudes toward dueling and the
crusade succeeded.
 &HT;    But Christian outrage at gun violence is often short-lived. Now,
conservative Christians blame killing on government for outlawing
God.
 &HT;    They should blame themselves for refusing to outlaw guns. Why is
the Christian Coalition in bed with the National Rifle Association
and other radical gun lobbies? Because deep cultural and political
prejudices keep them from seeing the truth: people using guns kill
people.
 &HT;    In the wake of Littleton, it is time for outrage again. American
religious groups need to stand up against the NRA. Denominations
should sponsor protests and boycotts -- and perhaps censure members
who support radical pro-gun groups.
 &HT;    Gun lobbies are wrong. Religious freedom is not wed to the
freedom to own assault weapons. People of faith need to see through
their facile arguments. The framers of the Constitution never
envisioned their words protecting the kind of guns wielded by the
boys at Columbine.
 &HT;    It could take decades before people of faith can change American
attitudes toward gun control. Meanwhile, a modest proposal:
American schoolchildren should start each day with prayer, ``Good
Lord, protect and deliver us from the NRA.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
