 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, May 13:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a page of coverage on the firing of
Russian Prime Minister Primakov:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Ledeall: President Boris Yeltsin
fires his prime minister, Yevgeny M. Primakov, and replaces him
with Sergei Stepashin, a longtime Yeltsin loyalist and current head
of police as Interior Minister. The move comes the day before the
Communist-dominated Parliament, which strongly supported Primakov,
takes up the impeachment of Yeltsin. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ A news analysis. The method to
Yeltsin's apparent madness of yet another government shakeup:
self-protection. His prime minister was in bed with his enemies, he
came in as political stabilizer but was unable for last three
months to control the growing impeachment drive and the conflict
with Parliament over Yeltsin's desire to remove Russia's chief
prosecutor. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-STEPASHIN (Moscow) _ A profile of Sergei Stepashin, the
new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DIPLO (Washington) _ Related developments in Washington
and reaction to the change in Russia; plus its possible impact on
the Kosovo crisis. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 pages of coverage on the continuing
crisis in Kosovo and the aftermath of the bombing of the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments on the war from NATO
headquarters. By Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Much emotion as ashes of the dead
Chinese are brought home. Demonstrations subside and James Sasser,
the U.S. ambassador, leaves the embassy. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Developments: Secretary Cohen and
General Shelton plan a 3:30 p.m. briefing.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, stories on the political
situation in Montenegro, more on refugees entering Macedonia and,
from China, a look at the roots of Anti-American sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUBIN &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a page of coverage on the resignation
of Treasury Secretary Rubin and the appointment of Lawrence Summers
to succeed him:
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-RESIGN (Washington) _ A ledeall: Robert Rubin resigns as
Treasury secretary; Clinton will name Lawrence Summers, Rubin's
deputy, to succeed him. Rubin is reported to have wanted to leave
for some time but waited until after Clinton's impeachment was
settled and the global economic situation seemed less volatile.
Plus reaction from the investment community where he was admired,
and a consideration of who will fill his role as an adviser on
economic and other issues. By John M. Broder and David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-ASSESS (Washington) _ A look at Secretary Rubin's impact
on U.S. economic policy and the economy. An analysis by Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-SUMMERS (Washington) _ A profile of Larry Summers, chosen
to replace Rubin as Treasury secretary. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-EIZENSTAT (Washington) _ A profile of Stuart Eizenstat,
who will replace Summers in the No. 2 Treasury post. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ After a 200 point drop in the Dow on the
announcement of Rubin's resignation, markets strengthened. At 1:25
p.m., Dow industrials were down 47, The S&AMP;P was little changed, and
the Nasdaq composite up 22 points. European markets were little
changed. In Asian trading, the Nikkei closed 1.22 percent higher,
and Hong Kong stocks rose 1.08 percent. On the credit markets at
midday the 30-year bond was yielding 5.81 percent. By Jonathan
Fruebringer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Russian immigrants are now the
king-makers of Israeli politics, and this group that can swing the
election either way is moving away from Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-POLITICS (Rome) _ On Thursday, the Italian Parliament will
begin selecting Italy's next president, largely a figurehead. But
rather than a dull civics exercise, the process is full of mystery
and intrigue, closely watched by Italians. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ House and Senate conferees try,
try again to hash out an emergency spending bill for war,
hurricanes, farmers and favorite causes. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CRIME (Washington) _ The Senate continues working on
the juvenile crime bill, and may take up gun-control amendments. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CRIME (Washington) _ The president's ``21st Century
Crime Initiative.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HATECRIME (Austin, Texas) _ Strange things happen to a
state legislative session when the governor is a front-runner in
the next presidential election. Everything is refracted through the
national prism, which may be why a hate crimes bill named in honor
of the black man who was dragged to death by whites in East Texas
has unexpectedly emerged as one of the most emotional, political
flashpoints of the current session. Democrats are charging that
Republicans loyal to Gov. George W. Bush are attempting to bottle
up the James Byrd Act, to kill it in committee so it would never
land on Bush's desk and force him to make a decision to either
support it, and alienate right-wing Republicans who object to the
inclusion of protections for homosexuals, or veto it and offer
Democrats a juicy issue to batter him with in the 2000 presidential
race. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Abner Louima ends his testimony
today in the police brutality trial, he will be followed by the
officer who broke the Blue Wall of Silence in the case. By Joseph
B. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COX-TCA-CABLE (Undated) _ Cox Communications Inc. plans to
acquire TCA Cable TV Inc., based in Tyler, Texas, for $3.26 billion
in cash and stock. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-CABLE (London) _ Folo on reports that Microsoft plans
to buy 30 percent of Cable and Wireless Communications, Britain's
biggest cable operator for $4 billion. With this investment and the
AT&AMP;T-MediaOne deal that gave Microsoft a 30 percent in Telewest,
Microsoft will now hold big stakes in all three of Britain's major
cable companies. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   NET-INVESTMENT-FRAUD (Undated) _ The Securities and Exchange
Commission has accused 26 companies and individuals with using the
Internet to defraud investors, in the agency's third nationwide
crackdown on Internet securities fraud. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-WIRELESS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The bidding from Europe's
phone giants for One-2-One, the British wireless phone company,
illustrates how wireless is helping reshape the European
telecommunications industry. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   LOEWEN-BANKRUPTCY (Toronto) _ The Loewen Group, a huge funeral
services company, says it will have to seek bankruptcy protection
or even liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By
Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
