<HEADER>
A4179 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRATEFUL-DEAD-HNS &LR;      05-12 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRATEFUL-DEAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADHEADS CAN SHARE TUNES ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A lawyer for the venerable Grateful Dead has
announced that concerts recorded by fans will be distributed at no
charge on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The recordings will be posted in the MP3 file format, which lets
users easily exchange near-CD quality songs over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Dead ceased performing in 1995 when its leader, Jerry
Garcia, died.
</P>
<P>
   While performing, the Dead had a longtime policy of allowing
fans to record the band's concerts. The caveat was that these
recordings could not be commercially distributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This takes the Dead's 30-year tradition and propels it into
the brave new world of the Internet,'' said Eric Doney, the lawyer
for the band. ``The members of the Grateful Dead feel this decision
is important for them and their fans to continue the spirit of that
policy of free concert recording.''
</P>
<P>
   Doney said that sites posting the home-grown recordings cannot
profit from the Dead files. They are prohibited from charging fans
to download the files, posting ads on sites containing the files,
and selling data about users who visit the sites to download the
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that the strict noncommercial aspects of
these recorded concerts are preserved,'' Doney said. ``The
remaining members of the band were adamant about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Doney emphasized that the sanctions apply only to the
fan-recorded songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go after any Web site operators that violate these
guidelines,'' he said. ``We'll consider that copyright infringement
and will proceed accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement makes the Grateful Dead one of the first major
bands to embrace the MP3 format, joining the likes of Perry Farrell
of Jane's Addiction, rapper Chuck D of Public Enemy and singer
Alanis Morissette in support of the digital movement.
</P>
<P>
   Record labels and recording industry trade groups have launched
a number of lawsuits against MP3 Web sites and makers of MP3
listening devices, fearing the technology will lead to widespread
piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the format continues to grow. Last week,
Seattle-based RealNetworks Inc., which makes industry standard
Internet audio software, debuted its RealJukebox Web music player,
which processes MP3-encoded music files.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1424EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
