<HEADER>
A4197 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-12 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELFARE OVERHAUL HURTS IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ In our boom economy that defies the
doomsayers, discussions about welfare have all but disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians _ from President Clinton to congressional leaders to
heralded Republican governors _ chortle with great satisfaction
that the Welfare Reform Act of 1996 has greatly reduced the public
dependency of our neediest countrymates, who are beginning to work
for a living. Before we all become too smug about lifting millions
of people out of poverty and into productive work, listen to Doris
Ng.
</P>
<P>
   She is a staff attorney with Equal Rights Advocates, a San
Francisco public-interest law center for women and the author of a
recent report, ``From War on Poverty to War on Welfare: The Impact
of Welfare Reform on the Lives of Immigrant Women.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the perception promoted by political pooh-bahs that
welfare recipients are getting off the dole and onto someone's
payroll, Ng's study tells a more sobering tale. Equal Rights
Advocates interviewed 75 Mexican-American women and 75
Vietnamese-American women in Santa Clara County, the heart of
prosperous Silicon Valley. The survey showed that California's new
welfare-to-work program, called CalWorks, is having little success
in moving these women off welfare and into jobs where they could
become self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrant women aren't the only people on public assistance who
are targeted to be on their own in two years under welfare reform.
But because California has a disproportionate number of legal
immigrants, the study's findings add a bracing dash of realism to
politicians' self-satisfied positive spin about reform's benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the advent of welfare reform, the outlook for poor
immigrant women has worsened,'' the study said. ``Indeed ...
welfare reform is being implemented in ways that largely ignore
immigrant women's barriers to self-sufficiency. Consequently, even
after participating in CalWorks, many immigrant women on welfare
will reach their time limits but not be better off.''
</P>
<P>
   The language barrier is a huge impediment to securing poor
welfare-dependent immigrant women a self-sufficient future, Ng
said. About half of the Mexican-American women and an astounding 86
percent of the Vietnamese-American women surveyed had poor or no
understanding of English.
</P>
<P>
   When they look for jobs, most of which require English
proficiency, ``they are unable to secure work or (they) wind up in
temporary or low-paying jobs that offer no promise of long-term
stability,'' Ng said. Other immigrant advocates tell similar tales
of welfare reform's hidden consequences. Indeed, legal immigrants
were targeted for disproportionate welfare cuts.
</P>
<P>
   While some public benefits have been restored, the attorneys who
represent immigrants say fear and confusion continue among many
legal immigrants about whether they remain eligible for welfare,
food stamps, Medicaid and Supplemental Security Income.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Park, senior staff attorney for the National Asian Pacific
American Legal Consortium in Washington, D.C., said, ``Because some
benefits like SSI have been restored for some immigrants, there is
a danger of falling into a level of complacency about the
continuing needs of some in our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress hasn't undone certain harsh provisions, such as the
ineligibility of immigrants who came legally to the United States
after Aug. 22, 1996, when the Welfare Reform Act became law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfair of our government to turn its back on these new
immigrants when they fall into a financial crisis,'' Park said.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Hwang, a staff attorney with the Asian Law Caucus of San
Francisco, said, ``Nobody understands welfare reform _ not
government workers, and not elderly immigrants who need
assistance.'' He said some immigrants who are eligible for public
benefits aren't applying, while ignorant government workers have
turned down applications of people who qualify for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
