<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SURPLUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS CALLS FOR SPENDING CHUNK OF SURPLUS ON SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Gray Davis will propose tapping an
anticipated budget surplus to expand after-school and preschool
programs, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is expected to announce Friday that California's booming
economy has created an unexpected surplus of $4 billion, giving the
governor another chance to influence the state's $78 billion
spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Davis, who is a Democrat, would
ask the Legislature to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Raise spending for after-school programs at elementary and
middle schools from $50 million per year to $85 million. The extra
money would start an additional 383 recreational and homework
programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expand state-funded preschool programs from 66,000 to 100,000
children, ages 3 and 4, who are from low-income families. The first
six months of the expansion is expected to cost $23 million, and
would increase to $69 million in the next budget year. The current
$180 million program is mostly paid for with federal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Davis doesn't want to spend any more money than is required
under Proposition 98, which mandates that at least half of all new
state revenues be spent for education. More announcements are
expected from the governor on his plans for the rest of the $4
billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The mass killings at a Littleton, Colo., high school have
renewed interest in after-school programs, which Attorney General
Bill Lockyer made a centerpiece of his campaign last year. Studies
show that most crimes committed by juveniles occur between 3 and 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   One bill before the Legislature would provide $75 million for
after-school programs in kindergarten through grade eight. Davis'
proposal would add $10 million to the K-8 programs, which one
senator said is still short of what is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually have almost double the interest and need in
California,'' said state Sen. Deborah Ortiz, D-Sacramento, author
of the measure. ``The governor is still $15 million below the need,
and that's going to continue to grow. This is just the tip of the
iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Gordon, assistant director of the California School Boards
Association, said after-school programs offering a variety of
academic and recreational opportunities are essential to student
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those resources will be put to good use by school districts
that will need them,'' he said of the governor's proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0223 </DOCNO>
