A4246 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RABBI-PURPOSE-NYTSF &LR;      05-12 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-PURPOSE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS PURPOSE IS THE ANSWER TO THE HIGH SCHOOL MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RABBI ELI HECHT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The funerals have been held for the 13 victims of the shooting
rampage at Columbine High School, and the question remains. How did
this happen?
</P>
<P>
   There are many different answers given by psychologists -- so
many theories that it is difficult to form an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the problem is guns. I agree that guns are a big
problem in our society. I do not allow a gun in my home.
</P>
<P>
   However, remember that this is America, where we have the right
to bear arms. And in earlier days on the frontier, children did not
pick up guns and shoot their parents, their teachers or their
friends.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not the availability of guns, it's that guns fall into
the hands of the wrong people.
</P>
<P>
   NRA President Charlton Heston claims that schools need armed
guards to insure the safety of the students. I wonder, does he want
our schools to turn into armed camps? Visiting a classroom will
become like visiting the state penitentiary. You would be frisked
and then go through metal detectors as you enter the cafeteria or
the school grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, even armed guards can't prevent a shooting
rampage. Columbine High School had an armed guard. Arming the staff
is no answer.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those who claim that the reason this took place
was because there is no mention of God in school. Well, whose God
are they talking about? Conflicts are taking place all over the
world in the name of God.
</P>
<P>
   So no, God cannot be the only answer to this tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Some would blame the poor. But remember, most of the school
murders have taken place in middle- to upper-middle-class white
class communities. It is not the inner-city schools and the poor
who produce violent youth -- it is our society.
</P>
<P>
   Some say, let's blame the parents. They should know and do
something about it!
</P>
<P>
   Well, that doesn't always work. Parents can't always know what
is happening. Even when they do, they may not be able to change
anything.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, 15-year-old Kipland P. Kinkel was charged with
murdering his parents and other students while wounding 18 people.
He came from a model home and supportive parents.
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported that Susan Klebold, the mother of Dylan
Bennett Klebold, one of the two boys who went on the Littleton
murder spree, said, ``There is no way I could have known this would
happen.'' She claims she had no idea of what was wrong with her
son.
</P>
<P>
   I feel there may be something wrong with the Klebolds. Any
parent with Jewish family ties knows that a child who yells out
``Heil Hitler'' while bowling a strike has a deep and obvious
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying with the worst world enemy of the Jewish people,
Adolf Hitler, is a sure sign of a major disorder.
</P>
<P>
   True, the parents supported Dylan Bennett with a sharp-looking
BMW, a $500,000 home and the latest computers. But that doesn't buy
peace or meaning in life.
</P>
<P>
   It may, however, cover up a major disorder for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Something that has been overlooked in recent years is our lack
of a religion that teaches the universal religious purpose of life.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's time to find a common denominator in all religions
based on the Noachide laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish world Chassidic leader, the Lubavitcher Rebbe, Rabbi
Menachem Mendel Schneerson (1902-1994), stated early in the 1970s
that in order for the American school system to succeed it must
allow a moment of silence for religious and moral contemplation.
</P>
<P>
   He asked that the Noachide laws be distributed. Students would
have a moment for prayer or contemplation to think about a higher
purpose and meaning for life. This could be achieved through the
seven divine laws that preceded the three world religions, Judaism,
Christianity and Islam.
</P>
<P>
   The Almighty God gave us, the children of Noah, seven divine
laws by which to live. These are the prohibition against adultery,
idolatry, blasphemy, theft, murder, sexual ambiguity, acts of
cruelty and last, but not least, the obligation of courts and
justice for mankind.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that by observing the Noachide Laws we would have
fewer differences between people. We would not shoot one another,
because it trespasses a Noachide Law. We would not commit cruelty
to animals and to our fellow human beings, because God said not to.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be wonderful if we were truly one family? We would
be compassionate, caring about the world as family members.
</P>
<P>
   We would look for similarities among people and not differences,
and work together in securing a healthy present, and be more
optimistic about our future.
</P>
<P>
   We would recognize the athlete for what he is, a gifted person
with athletic qualities. We would give respect to those who are
inclined to the world of technology and computers. Those musically
inclined would have their place in society. Jocks, nerds and spacey
music people would have acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   A reason why Eric David Harris and Dylan Bennett Klebold killed
so many people on the day of Hitler's birthday stemmed from the
fact that they did not feel themselves to be important members in a
world of law and order. They took matters into their own hands and
destroyed the real world around them in the name of others who had
done the same, like Hitler. There is no God, they claimed.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Colorado feels that the parents should be
charged as accomplices. He may have a point in looking for
collective responsibility. We may all be guilty!
</P>
<P>
   As a school administrator I am told to give the children space.
When we are dealing with a troublesome teen-ager, the sage advice
is, ``Let them do what they want in their rooms and garages. At
least you know where they are. If you ask too much they will run
away from home.''
</P>
<P>
   If that be the case, then how will we ever know our kids?
</P>
<P>
   Educators are instructed to keep prayer and the mention of God
out of the school system. It is interesting to note that during the
killings almost all the kids prayed.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't that tell us that we may have it all wrong?
Seventy-thousand people attending the funerals is a sign that we
must change the way we are doing things.
</P>
<P>
   As a parent and educator, I believe we must be interested in
everything our children do. We should allow a moment of prayer or
silence in our school system. We should not wait for a crisis to
allow the students pray.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif.)
</P>
