<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOWTOWING TO CHINESE IS EGREGIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's lucky for the American people that John McCain and Pat
Buchanan are running for president. If they weren't, there might be
no U.S. political leader with the gumption to stand up to China.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some other politicians or officials have stepped up to the
plate in reaction to China's outrageous temper tantrum over the
accidental bombing of its embassy in Belgrade _ but if they have, I
haven't heard or read their remarks.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the folks who ought to be telling China to
pipe down and back off have instead been licking the commie thugs'
boots. The list of bootlickers begins with _ big surprise _
President Clinton. As of Tuesday afternoon Central Daylight Time,
Clinton had apologized at least three times for NATO's mistake in
dropping bombs on the Chinese Embassy instead of the intended
Yugoslav military target.
</P>
<P>
   These multiple apologies go to a country, it must be noted, that
has yet to apologize for stealing U.S. nuclear secrets, for handing
over nuclear technology to Pakistan and Iran, for trying to
influence U.S. elections, or even for slaughtering its own citizens
in Beijing's Tiananmen Square a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Clinton could take a brief respite from banking his
Chinese campaign contributions and begging China's forgiveness for
a purely unintentional intelligence error and explain to his own
constituents why the greatest nation on the planet should be
kowtowing to one of the most consistently lawless governments in
the history of the world.
</P>
<P>
   We made a mistake. We apologized. End of story.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it should be the end of the story. But mere apologies
won't satisfy the arrogant criminals who run the show in China.
They want abject remorse. They want the United States to beg for
absolution.
</P>
<P>
   And we've all but done it, thanks to a commander in chief who
would generate a lot more respect among his countrymen if he would
stand up to China the way he has stood up to this two-bit dictator
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   So. Thank goodness for McCain and Buchanan, both of whom
criticized China in no uncertain terms for encouraging violent
demonstrations against the U.S. Embassy in Beijing and for its
continuing insistence on further apologies.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what McCain said, as reported by The Associated Press:
``I would call up the premier of China and say: `Stop it, and stop
it right now. We have apologized, it's tragic, now it's over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, according to the AP, ripped China as ``an antagonistic
and hostile regime spoiling for a quarrel.''
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be terrific if the president could be so resolute?
</P>
<P>
   You'd think, at the very least, that Clinton could tell the
Chinese that if they don't shape up, he's going to cut off their
spies' unfettered access to U.S. nuclear labs.
</P>
<P>
   It's perfectly obvious why the Chinese are making such a big
deal out of this accident, of course: They see it as an opportunity
to distract the world from their endless list of misdeeds. A CNN
reporter who works the State Department suggested that some
officials are speculating that the devious dictators in China are
throwing a fit over the bombing in order to put U.S. officials on
the defensive and thus extract concessions in future negotiations
on other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Which reminds me: Do you suppose Bob Dole would be
groveling at the feet of the Chinese tyrants if he were president
of the United States?
</P>
<P>
   Not on your life.
</P>
<P>
   We wouldn't be in this mess, needless to say, if Clinton hadn't
committed the grievous misjudgment of involving the United States
in a European civil war that is none of America's business. Never
mind that the CIA can't separate the legitimate targets from the
innocent bystanders; we shouldn't be bombing Yugoslavia in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe something good will come of it, though. Maybe the
unfortunate bombing of that embassy will cool American enthusiasm
for getting chummy with the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   After this mess, even Clinton should be able to figure out that
China is no friend of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
