<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, May 13:
</P>
<P>
   NY-VILLAGE-APARTMENT (New York) _ Question: How long does it
take to put together a three-bedroom, two-bathroom apartment in the
heart of Greenwich Village, with three working fireplaces and a
terrace, overlooking an Italianate inner garden _ and all for a
total of $234,000? Answer: 21 years. The woman who created the
space, Diane Shea, 45, is notable not merely for perseverance. She
also represents a classic New York tale. By Mark Kristal.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   SENIOR-FURNISHING (Undated) _ Home furnishing design is having a
senior moment. Knitted afghan throws, crocheted pillows, chenille
spreads and tufted pom-pom quilts are appearing like silver hairs
in youthful catalogues like Garnet Hill, stores like Pottery Barn
and Crate and Barrel and collections like Ralph Lauren Home and
Nautica. There are also rag rugs, rocking chairs, pressed glass,
ginghams and gussy floral prints that are blooming on everything
from bedding to china. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Gardening questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   PRUNING-PLANTS (New York) _ ``It's a matter of finding the tree
in the tree,'' said William Miller, 41, an arborist who started a
tree business on Long Island 13 years ago and does what amounts to
behavioral analysis on each plant he prunes. ``When we first look
at a tree, we look for what to encourage, what to discourage,'' he
said. ``We want to accentuate forms, allow them to stand out. And
we're also manipulating light.'' By Mac Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
