<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAG-VIGNETTES-ART(2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CITY STRUGGLING DAILY FINDS TIME TO LAUGH, WORSHIP AND LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES)-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq _ During one of our first meetings with
humanitarian workers in Iraq, we were told that economic sanctions
have not only caused the deaths of thousands of children each
month, but have created a breakdown of the family structure, with
many children now forced to help with the family income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are too important to become a pawn of politics,''
Anupama Rao Singh, the United Nations Children's Fund
representative in Iraq, told us.
</P>
<P>
   We had seen children dying in the hospitals of the city.
Elsewhere we saw the effects of the family breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   Walid, 14, and his brother Ramy, 15, have been working the
streets of Baghdad for eight years, the same length of time
sanctions have been in place. They live in a dark two-room
apartment with three younger stepbrothers and their mother and
father.
</P>
<P>
   An ancient TV droned on in the background while their mother
explained their situation, which she blamed on poor economic
conditions as a result of the U.N. sanctions imposed after the 1991
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The father, who was a butcher, lost his shop shortly after the
Persian Gulf War and hasn't worked since. The mother had an
untreated thyroid condition and couldn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The father sent the younger boys to school, but Walid and Ramy
are his stepchildren and didn't go to school.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the older boys shined shoes on the streets around the
Palestine and Sheraton hotels to support the family. Walid and Ramy
both were quick to make friends among the members of the Washington
Physicians for Social Responsibility delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Walid had a wide smile and he could sing _ in English _ ``My
Heart Will Go On,'' the theme song from the movie ``Titanic.'' Ramy
was slower to smile, but, with his freckles, he conjured up an
image of Huck Finn.
</P>
<P>
   Not a day went by that the boys couldn't be found shining some
delegate's shoes at 50 cents a pop, making them, for a while
anyway, among the highest paid workers in Baghdad. The delegates
often got two shoeshines a day. Baghdad is a dusty city.
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   The orphanage in downtown Baghdad was clean and bright and the
children, who ranged from week-old infants to 5-year-olds, wore
identical colorful pajamas. There were almost as many women
volunteers as children on view.
</P>
<P>
   The number of orphanages in Iraq is growing along with the
divorce and suicide rates, and as more families abandon children,
according to humanitarian workers in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The facility, appropriately called Government House Orphanage,
had government showcase written all over it. Its director, Bayon
Hasui Ali, a woman with six years of experience working at
orphanages, said the volunteers were all women because this kind of
work required a woman. She said many Iraq and foreign officials had
visited her orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   The orphanage was supported by the government and by wealthy
donors, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ali, whose job it is to escort members of the news media
wherever they want to go during their stay in Baghdad, translated
while the orphans sang songs of welcome to the visiting
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our father Saddam Hussein shows us how to be a teacher,'' the
children chanted in unison, with one little boy stepping out and
shaking his fist emphatically to the last words of the verse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our father Saddam Hussein shows us how to be a farmer,'' the
children chanted, and another little boy stepped out from the group
and shook his fist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our father Saddam Hussein shows us how to be a soldier,'' the
children chanted. This time an older girl stepped out from the
group and said, ``And we will kill the American invaders.'' The
children smiled and clapped their hands.
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   Not long after we arrived in Baghdad, Hans von Sponeck, the
United Nations Humanitarian Coordinator for Iraq, told us that the
sanctions ``are turning the social structure upside down.'' We
didn't have to go far to see what he meant.
</P>
<P>
   On the street along the Tigris River, not far from the Palestine
Hotel, a nervous-looking man approached me, thinking I was a member
of the WPSR delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to ask your help,'' he said, speaking softly in perfect
English. ``I'm a doctor, and I'm fed up with working in this
country. I want to leave. I'm thinking about leaving my
profession.''
</P>
<P>
   When he learned he was talking to a reporter, he said I must
never use his name or where he worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would kill me and my entire family if they found out,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he couldn't live here watching people die, with his
family suffering as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the father of a baby boy,'' he said, ``but I'm not happy
because I can't imagine his future.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor blamed the sanctions, but his No. 1 concern, at the
moment, was whether I would help him if he and his family got out
of the country. I said I didn't know what I could do, but I gave
him my business card, and he said I would hear from him very soon.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter probably lasted less time than it took to write
about it.
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   At a school not far from the Palestine Hotel last month, dozens
of smiling students welcomed American visitors warmly, then sang
songs about Saddam Hussein and about killing American invaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a picture of Saddam Hussein,'' a bright-eyed cherub
chanted. ``I like it very much, very much.'' Nothing personal was
intended; it was just the morning ritual.
</P>
<P>
   In an art class, several student paintings showed boys and girls
firing guns at warplanes bearing U.S. ensignias. One picture showed
tombstones with a caption written in Arabic that said, ``Martyrs
are better than us all.''
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   In a quiet residential district, a single-story building built
around a large courtyard served as a military training school for
members of the Baath Party, Iraq's ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, for two hours a day, for one month, every member of
the party, male and female, is required to learn how to fire an
AK-47 assault rifle, administer emergency first aid, and march in
formation. The training session we observed, at least the women's
class, seemed to require a lot of marching in formation.
</P>
<P>
   The women, all looking quite healthy and prosperous in
fashionable dresses, high-heels and makeup, watched carefully while
male soldiers showed them how to aim the rifles. Then each woman
practiced pulling back the bolt and aiming at an imaginary enemy
across the courtyard. In this class, the target was often the
Post-Intelligencer photographer or reporter. We assumed the rifles
weren't loaded.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the soldiers said more than 1 million members
of the Baath Party went through this militia training last year.
The party wants everyone to be prepared, he said, in case Iraq is
invaded.
</P>
<P>
   As the women did a modified goose-step around the courtyard,
they sang a verse or two from a song that roughly translated as,
``Saddam Hussein will always remain in power no matter what the
Americans do.''
</P>
<P>
   As the troop of women marched by, one rather tall, heavily made
up, husky-looking woman in a masculine-looking suit-dress winked at
me, and her dark red lips broke into a wide grin. I laughed, but I
was flattered. And I knew then it was time to go home.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers gathered them together for one last group photo,
with the carefully coiffed women holding their AK-47s high in the
air, and we said goodbye. My new friend broke formation long enough
for a little wave.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
