<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4274 &Cx1f; tth-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAG-VIGNETTES-ART-2N     05-12 1807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAG-VIGNETTES-ART-2NDTAKE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD,IRAQ: for a little wave.
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   In an upper-middle-class neighborhood in Baghdad, a woman said
she was trying to persuade her brother, a well-known surgeon, to
leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can only survive here because my mother gives him money,''
she said as her eyes filled with tears. ``All of our inheritance is
being used up; we will have nothing for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, whose 10-year-old Toyota was one of the few cars I'd
seen in Iraq that didn't have crumpled fenders and a cracked
windshield, said her two young children would have the opportunity
to get advanced degrees here if they wanted to, but they would have
nothing to look forward to after they graduated.
</P>
<P>
   A painting on the wall of her clean, modern house traced her
husband's family tree back to the prophet Mohammed. The woman was a
college graduate and her family came from a long line of
intellectuals _ her father obtained an advanced degree in the
United States. Her husband, who ran a business, came from a family
of soldiers and merchants. He had spent four years on the front
lines during the war with Iran.
</P>
<P>
   She wore modern dresses, but covered her head with a scarf, a
nod to tradition that kept her from getting a decent job in
business, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (modern businessmen) want younger women who dress in
short skirts,'' she said. Even her daughter, she said, refuses to
wear a scarf.
</P>
<P>
   The woman said she had heard so much about the new diseases
making a comeback under the sanctions that she worried about her
children's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least, if my brother goes abroad, he can make money and
help us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   We had come to Iraq expecting that suspicious government
officials would watch our every move. We feared people would hate
us because we came from the country whose warplanes were bombing
some part of their country almost daily. But we found that most
people were warm and friendly. The first thing people wanted to
know was where we were from. After hearing we were from the United
States, the next thing they said was ``welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   And we found that amid the death and destruction, the squalor
and deterioration of Baghdad, that life _ and love _ go on.
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   The Palestine Hotel, the Baghdad home for the Washington
Physicians for Social Responsibility delegation, was the host to 51
wedding parties on a Thursday night. Friday is the only day off for
most Iraqis (Christians also get Sundays off) so Thursday has
become the day of choice for getting married. The one-day honeymoon
beats no honeymoon at all.
</P>
<P>
   Marriages in Iraq are almost always arranged by families. The
couple is accompanied to the hotel, and often right up to the room,
by a crowd of relatives and other well-wishers and by musicians
playing horns and drums. Most of the couples wore Western-style
wedding clothes _ the women's outfits were especially elaborate
with large hoop skirts and long veils.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was repeated across the road at the Sheraton, and
according to the Palestine Hotel manager, similar celebrations were
going on at several other of the nicer hotels around Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   One wedding party took over the Palestine Hotel ballroom for the
night, and filled it with about 400 wedding guests.
</P>
<P>
   Several young men standing at the door of the ballroom waved us
in and showed us to the center of the room where the bride and
groom were seated on a stage while relatives and friends crowded
around them for photo opportunities. The groom even invited his new
guests up on stage to pose for wedding pictures with himself and
the bride.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the young men formed a line and danced for us. Their
wild gyrations and laughter suggested that the Muslim prohibition
of alcohol might have been temporarily suspended for this occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol is sold openly by stores in Baghdad, but it can be
consumed only in private.
</P>
<P>
   The groom's brother, Amar Karim Kitan (we spoke in Spanish) said
the couple could afford the lavish celebration _ a dinner for all
the guests and a live band _ because Hadi, the new husband, was a
car dealer. His brother was a very modern man and would take only
one wife, although four wives are allowed, Amar said.
</P>
<P>
   The party lasted all night. The Post-Intelligencer's reporter
and photographer didn't.
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Abu Ali, the journalists were allowed into two large
mosques in Baghdad. After checking our shoes at the entrance of the
first mosque, Abu Ali made a path through the worshipers to the
front of the mosque.
</P>
<P>
   An Iraqi TV crew had already set up its camera and microphone.
It was Friday, the Muslim holy day, and we were shown to an area of
the mosque that was packed with men. The women and children,
according to custom, worship separately.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtyard outside the mosque, we were warmly welcomed by
the clerics but inside, at the front of the room, the atmosphere
was less welcoming. The religious leader's sermon was animated and
the word America seemed to pop up frequently, and when it did, many
eyes shifted our way.
</P>
<P>
   It felt good to get outside, in the courtyard, again. But on the
way out, the man who gave the sermon, broad-shouldered and more
than 6 feet tall, suddenly appeared with an entourage of disciples
and asked where we were from and who we were. After learning we
were journalists from the United States, he said, ``You are
welcome.'' Then he instructed us to send him a copy of whatever we
do. He wasn't the kind of man who would take no for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at the second, more historic Golden Mosque, we decided to
wander through the immense courtyard surrounding the inner-prayer
hall. Pilgrims were sprawled along the outer walls. Entire
families, some with sickly looking infants, appeared to have taken
up residence there.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ali said many families were waiting for their relatives to
return from the annual Hadj pilgrimage to Mecca, in Saudi Arabia, a
trip every Muslim is required to make at least once in their lives
if it is economically possible.
</P>
<P>
   There were many soldiers visiting the Golden Mosque, and we were
challenged several times, but each time, Abu Ali flashed his ID and
we were free to continue our visit.
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   Nestled on the banks of the Tigris River across from the
Palestine Hotel, the tea house became a late-night ritual for many
members of the WPSR delegtion. For a few cents, you could sit among
crowds of Iraqis _ men on the inside, women and men outside _ and
drink heavily sugared hot tea and smoke flavored tobacco from a
large water pipe.
</P>
<P>
   For a few cents more, the waiter would bring dominoes, which
seemed to be widely popular. The low murmur of conversations was
frequently interrupted by the click, click, click sound of the
wooden domino rectangles as they slapped against the tables to
cries of victory or defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Tea was served in small, clear glasses nearly one-third filled
with roughly-granulated sugar. The water pipe, with a choice of
peach-, apple- or berry-flavored mild tobacco, was more than 3 feet
tall, and was usually placed to one side of the table, with only
the hose passed among the smokers. The combination of sweet tea and
flavored tobacco was such a relaxing treat that even non-smokers
often shared the pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Street children often hovered in the background, eager to run
errands or shine shoes, and often some of the children would join
us at the table for a treat _ a Pepsi or the big splurge, a Coke.
Pepsi was produced in Iraq; Coke was imported.
</P>
<P>
   On one occasion, a couple of women from the WPSR delegation
broke the taboo on having women inside the tea house, but the men
there seemed non-plussed. The waiters served them and eventually
the boredom of it all drove them back outside with the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   With the stars overhead and good company at hand, we talked of
mundane things throughout the night. Malnutrition, dying children
and the sanctions that fully occupied our days were rarely
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   -- -- --
</P>
<P>
   Sabehna Jasim smiled and straightened her black robe and warmly
welcomed us into her home.
</P>
<P>
   We had come looking for a better vantage point to photograph the
farmers' market that ran along the street on one side of her
building. Her second-story apartment overlooking the intersection
of two streets was perfect. Abu Ali, whose job is to assist foreign
journalists, conveyed our request and translated during our visit.
</P>
<P>
   Jasim took us out onto the balcony for a better view. After
reluctantly acquiescing to our requests to pose for photos, she
insisted on making us tea.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other members of the family lived there in three small
rooms. In the hallway, a retarded woman sat on the floor and helped
one of Jasim's granddaughters shell peas. She smiled and murmured
softly each time we passed her in the hall.
</P>
<P>
   In a place of honor, dominating the living room wall, was a
photo of a young officer in uniform. It was Jasim's first-born son.
He had been killed by U.S. forces during the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The officer's widow smiled shyly at the guests and helped serve
tea.
</P>
<P>
   Singh, the UNICEF representative, in Baghdad, said economic
sanctions have caused a breakdown of the family structure, with
many children now forced to help support their families and
dropping out of the educational system.
</P>
<P>
   We had seen some evidence of these problems _ street children
begging for handouts, shoeshine boys working late into the night,
children sitting on the floors of underfunded classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   But in Jasim's home, the family remains strong. The children go
to school. A son and a daughter have jobs. And it was clear that
the strong-willed 70-year-old Jasim was the driving force.
</P>
<P>
   We spent an hour taking photos and talking. Times are hard,
Jasim said. The U.N. food rations always run out at least a week
before the end of the month. There is work, but little pay. The
sanctions are no good, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hated President Bush, and when reminded that he was
no longer president, she said President Clinton was just as bad.
</P>
<P>
   Jasim said she had no hard feelings for Americans. She said she
blamed the government of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are the same everywhere,'' she said. ``Only governments
are different.''
</P>
<P>
   When we left, Jasim told us we were always welcome in her home.
So, just before leaving Baghdad, we went back, taking the family a
present in gratitude for their help and hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   Jasim excitedly ushered us into her apartment, and informed us
with great satisfaction that we had, by our last visit, made her
the toast of her little part of the town.
</P>
<P>
   And, once again, despite our pleas, she insisted on serving us
tea, cheese and bread that a grandson fetched fresh from a nearby
bakery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
