<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOINGGREEK-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GO GREEK: FUSION FOOD FIT FOR THE GODS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The food of Greece may be the world's first fusion cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Until around 3500 B.C., Greeks ate what their Mediterranean
neighbors ate _ a simple diet of grilled meats, fish, and found
greens and fruit. But as the Minoan civilization developed on the
Crete and Santorini islands of the Aegean, a wider variety of food
became available.
</P>
<P>
   Trade with North Africa brought dates and onions, and clearing
of forests lead to olive groves and planted wheat. By the time the
Greeks were holding forth from their civilized world, the
preparation of good food was considered an important part of life.
</P>
<P>
   Today, following the ascension of Rome, occupation by the
Ottoman Empire and the introduction of New World ingredients, that
early Greek diet of olives, wheat, figs, grapes, wild greens, fish
and some meat has been brightened by non-native ingredients such as
lemons, potatoes, eggplant, tomatoes, spinach and okra. This hot,
rocky country serves up a treasure of culinary ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Fruits and vegetables still play an important role in the diet,
as do olives and olive oil. Yogurt and cheese are the primary dairy
sources and lamb is the predominant meat. And all of this is bathed
in the sun of Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   So sit on your deck, pour a little ouzo, dally with some olives
and cheese triangles, and transport yourself to the warmth of a
white and blue village.
</P>
<P>
   LETTUCE DOLMAS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 heads lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds ground lamb
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped dill
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raw rice
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 to 2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Select lettuce with leaves suitable for stuffing. Clean
carefully and separate leaves. Bring pot of water to boil, add
leaves, a few at a time, cook just until they wilt. Remove
immediately and spread on platter. If they are too large, cut in
half before stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Place meat, onions, parsley, dill, rice, egg whites, 2
tablespoons butter, salt and pepper in bowl. Knead well to mix.
Place about 1 teaspoon of mixture on a leaf and bring up sides
toward center, then roll up like a cigar. Place stuffed leaves,
open side down, in layers in pot. Add a little salt and pepper and
rest of butter and enough water to half cover. Lay a plate on the
dolmas; cover pot. Simmer slowly and when they have absorbed almost
all the water, add milk. Allow to cook a few minutes longer until
approximately 1 cup liquid remains. Beat egg yolks, add lemon juice
to them, then blend in liquid from pot. Return sauce to pot. Shake
over low heat for 2 to 3 minutes. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 344 calories, 24 grams fat, 15
grams carbohydrates, 17 grams protein, 138 milligrams cholesterol,
195 milligrams sodium, 63 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Greek Cookbook'' by Sophia Skoura (Crown, $9.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TZATZIKI
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3-4
</P>
<P>
   2 cups plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 medium cucumber, peeled, seeds removed, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2-3 teaspoons fine olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in glass or earthenware bowl and chill
to allow flavors to penetrate the cucumber. Serve as a dip, or on
lettuce leaves as a salad, or with fried zucchini, eggplant or
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 99 calories, 6 grams fat, 7
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 14 milligrams cholesterol,
114 milligrams sodium, 55 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Food of Greece'' by Vilma Liacouras Chantiles (Fireside,
$14)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHEESE TRIANGLES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8 as entree, 20 as appetizers
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk, scalded
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped dill
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound (approximately) phyllo
</P>
<P>
   Oil, melted butter or other shortening for brushing phyllo
</P>
<P>
   Melt 3 tablespoons butter, add flour and stir well to blend.
Slowly add hot milk, stirring constantly to make a thick, creamy
sauce. Remove from heat. Add salt and pepper and continue to stir
until sauce is just cool. Crumble cheese into small pieces and add
them to sauce. Add eggs, stir well, then add dill and mix until
well-blended.
</P>
<P>
   Cut each of the sheets of phyllo lengthwise into 3 strips. Take
1 strip at a time (keep others covered to prevent their drying
out). Holding strip horizontally, brush with melted shortening. Put
a teaspoonful of filling in the lower-left corner, then fold corner
over to make a triangle along the strips. Fold upper-left corner
over to close triangle. Continue to fold phyllo over and over until
strip has become a small (about 3-inch) triangle of pastry. Brush
top with butter. Continue to prepare all of the ``pittas'' like
this. Place triangles on lightly buttered baking sheet and bake in
preheated 300-degree oven for 15-20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 139 calories, 8 grams fat, 11
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 64 milligrams cholesterol,
308 milligrams sodium, 51 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Greek Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SPANAKORIZO
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons clarified butter or olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup long-grain white rice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup canned tomato sauce or tomatoes, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds fresh spinach, washed, drained, stems removed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs fresh mint, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   3 slices bacon, crumbled, optional
</P>
<P>
   4 hard-cooked eggs, sliced, optional
</P>
<P>
   Lemon wedges, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter or oil in enameled pan, then add onion and cook
until soft and transparent. Add rice and saute for a few minutes,
stirring constantly, then add tomato sauce or tomatoes and water,
cover pan and simmer until rice is almost tender (about 10
minutes). Uncover and stir in spinach, parsley, mint; season with
salt and pepper. Partially cover pan and continue cooking, stirring
with a wooden spoon until spinach has wilted. Grate a little nutmeg
over top and continue cooking until all liquid has been absorbed
and the dish is tender, not mushy. Remove from heat and drape with
a dry towel until ready to use. Transfer to warm serving dish,
sprinkle with bacon bits, if you like, and garnish with sliced eggs
and lemon wedges. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
