A4283 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOINGGREEK-2ndTake-TE     05-12 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOINGGREEK-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Serve warm. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with bacon and without
hard-cooked eggs: 155 calories, 8 grams fat, 15 grams
carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 108 milligrams cholesterol, 176
milligrams sodium, 45 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Food of Greece''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GREEK COUNTRY SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   1 pound feta cheese cut into small cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 English cucumbers or 3 regular cucumbers, peeled and
thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 medium ripe tomatoes, cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red onion, thinly sliced and separated into rings
</P>
<P>
   Dressing, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   12 large romaine lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   8 anchovy fillets, optional
</P>
<P>
   16 kalamata olives
</P>
<P>
   12 green olives
</P>
<P>
   Place cheese in large bowl. Add cucumbers, tomato wedges and
onion rings to cheese. Pour dressing over cheese mixture and toss
gently until well mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the lettuce leaves on a large platter. Spoon cheese
mixture over lettuce. Lay anchovies over salad and garnish with
olives.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The lettuce can be torn into bite-size pieces, if you
prefer. In that case, you'll need about 6 cups of torn lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   Periyali dressing:
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 2 tablespoons regular olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon minced fresh thyme or 1/8 teaspoon dried thyme
leaves, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon minced fresh oregano or 1/8 teaspoon dried oregano
leaves, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced chives
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Pinch white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Bring broth to boil in small saucepan. Reduce heat and simmer
until reduced by half, to about 2 tablespoons. Remove from heat and
pour into a medium bowl; set aside until just warm. Stir in
vinegars and lemon juice. Begin adding mixture of the oils, drop by
drop at first and then in thin, steady stream, beating constantly
with wire whisk until mixture thickens. Beat in herbs, salt and
pepper. Cover and store in refrigerator. Bring to room temperature
and beat lightly to remix before using.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 570 calories, 54 grams fat, 12
grams carbohydrates, 13 grams protein, 67 milligrams cholesterol,
1,545 milligrams sodium, 85 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Periyali Cookbook'' by Holly Garrison (Villard, $24)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SQUASH STUFFED WITH CHOPPED MEAT
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   2 3/4 to 3 pounds medium zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1 pound chopped meat
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound ripe tomatoes, peeled and seeded
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   Water as needed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raw rice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup toasted bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   Cut stems from squash and scrape off the skins. Wash and scoop
out flesh leaving a quarter-inch shell.
</P>
<P>
   Brown meat and onion in half the butter, crumbling with a spoon.
Add tomatoes, salt, pepper, parsley and 1/2 cup water. Boil for 15
minutes. Add 1 cup hot water; as soon as it boils, add rice. Cover;
simmer 10 minutes. Remove from heat. Add cheese and bread crumbs.
Cool mixture slightly, then add lightly beaten egg whites. Mix
well. Stuff squash with mixture and carefully place in a pot. Add
remaining butter and 1 more cup water. Bring to slow boil and cook
until only a small amount of liquid remains. Beat egg yolks with
lemon juice. Add some liquid from pot, beating constantly. Pour
sauce into pot. Shake pot constantly until sauce thickens. Serve
hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 581 calories, 44 grams fat, 24
grams carbohydrates, 24 grams protein, 212 milligrams cholesterol,
532 milligrams sodium, 68 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Greek Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BAKED SHRIMP AND FETA IN SHELLS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   2 pound large shrimp, shelled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 onion or shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil or butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup canned tomato sauce plus 2 to 3 tomatoes, peeled,
chopped and drained
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh basil or dill
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   Fresh basil leaves, or parsley, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Wash and drain shrimp, then sprinkle lightly with lemon juice.
Heat the oil or butter in a frying pan and cook onion until soft.
Add tomato sauce, herbs, garlic, and salt and pepper to taste.
Simmer for 25 minutes, then remove from heat and strain.
</P>
<P>
   Butter large scallop or other shells, or individual ovenproof
dishes, and spoon a little sauce into each. Fill with shrimp and
spoon the sauce over, then crumble feta over top. Set into baking
pan and bake for 15-20 minutes in 350 degree oven or until shrimp
is cooked and cheese melts. Garnish with fresh basil or parsley and
serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 338 calories, 18 grams fat, 7
grams carbohydrates, 37 grams protein, 263 milligrams cholesterol,
774 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Food of Greece''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Glossary:
</P>
<P>
   Baklava: A classic dessert of sheets of very thin pastry
(phyllo) layered with honey syrup and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Dolmas: Generally, grape leaves stuffed with meat and rice and
rolled into cylinders. You can make these yourself, or purchase
them ready-made in cans. Drain, pat dry and serve with lemon
wedges. Popular on meze plates.
</P>
<P>
   Feta cheese: This crumbly, salty white cheese can be made with
cow, sheep or goat milk, with the first being the mildest. Store
the cheese for long-term use in brine in the refrigerator. (If no
brine comes with the cheese, make your own by dissolving 3
tablespoons of salt in 4 cups water.)
</P>
<P>
   Gyros: The national street food of Greece, these sandwiches are
a substantial, plate-size piece of flat bread topped with shaved,
roasted lamb topped with onions and a cucumber sauce. (In America,
these meat is shaved from a cone of compressed beef and lamb.)
</P>
<P>
   Meze: A grand selection of little bites that can be served as an
appetizer or a whole meal. This tradition is popular throughout the
Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Olives: In Greece, olives are a regional specialty, with each
area preparing its own variety in time-honored fashion. Kalamatas,
large black briny olives, are the most well-known in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Ouzo: Anise-flavored liquor.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllo: Thin ``leaves'' of pastry dough that is sold in 1-pound
packages in the frozen-food section of nearly all supermarkets.
Allow dough to thaw in refrigerator, then bring to room
temperature. Take care not to let dough dry out while working with
it by laying a damp cloth or towel over the stack of dough not
being used at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Retsina: The process for making this Greek wine is more than
3,000 years old and involves treating the wine with pine-tree
resin. The wine has a strong smell and flavor that takes some
getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   Souvlaki: Marinated lamb.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
