<HEADLINE>
KEY EVENTS SINCE IRAQ'S INVASTION OF KUWATI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   _Aug. 2, 1990: Iraq invades Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   _Aug. 6: United Nations imposes sweeping trade sanctions on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   _Jan. 17, 1991: U.S.-led coalition launches air war against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   _Feb. 28: Cease-fire announced.
</P>
<P>
   _March 2: U.N. Security Council lays down conditions, including
elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, that must be met
before sanctions are lifted.
</P>
<P>
   _Since the 1991 Gulf War, U.S. and British planes have been
enforcing a northern no-fly zone in Iraq to protect rebel Kurds
from the Iraqi air force. A southern zone protects Shiite rebels.
</P>
<P>
   _1996: The United Nations begins the oil-for-food program in an
effort to counter the devastating effects of sanctions on Iraqis,
particularly children.
</P>
<P>
   _February 1998: U.S., British increase military presencePersian
Gulf after Iraq refuses to allow weapons inspections of
presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
   _Feb. 23: U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan works out agreement
with Iraq, defusing crisis.
</P>
<P>
   _Oct. 31: Iraq halts U.N. weapons monitoring work; United
States, Britain warn military strikes are possible.
</P>
<P>
   _Nov. 14: U.S. naval ships in gulf about to attack Iraq when
President Clinton orders a stand down, tentatively accepting Iraqi
pledge to allow resumption of inspections.
</P>
<P>
   _Nov. 18: U.N. inspection work resumes.
</P>
<P>
   _Dec. 15: U.N. reports Iraq has not met promises of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   _Dec. 17: U.S.-British forces begin a four-day bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _Dec. 21: U.S.-British pilots begin operating under relaxed
rules for attacking Iraqi radar and missile sites. Since then,
Iraqi units have been hit almost daily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
