<HEADLINE>
QUICK FACTS ON IRAQ,ITS PEOPLE, GEOGRAPHY, POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEOGRAPHY: Land area consists of about 167,000 square miles,
with the country divided into four major regions: desert in west
and southwest; rolling upland between upper Euphrates and Tigris
rivers; highlands in north and northeast; and alluvial plain in
central and southeast regions.
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE: Approximately 22 million. Arabs make up 75 percent to 80
percent of the population; 15 percent to 20 percent are Kurdish;
and 5 percent are Turkoman, Assyrian or other.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR CITIES: Baghdad, the capital, with a population of
approximately 5 million; Basra, in the south, with a population of
approximately 2.5 million; and Mosul, in the north, with a
population of approximately 1.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION: Officially Islam, as Muslims form 95 percent of the
population. Christians make up the largest non-Muslim religious
group.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT: Officially a republic, with power in the hands of
the Revolutionary Command Council, which is responsible for the
election of the president from among its members. The National
Assembly, with a membership of 250, is elected every four years.
Saddam Hussein has been president since July 16, 1979.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
