<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEXIBILITY IS KEY TO REACHING PEACE WITH MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 16)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S.-led NATO plan is quite clear in its goal
of ending the airstrikes against Yugoslavia and leaving that
tortured land once Kosovo has been made safe for the return of a
million or more ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic understands the basic principles of the plan
and has had it in his power to end the conflict since before the
air assault began March 24. But he has chosen to play the stubborn
martyr, knowing full well that his treatment of the Kosovar
Albanians has been barbarous.
</P>
<P>
   Once the furor over NATO's accidental bombing of the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade subsides and peace negotiations resume in
earnest, flexibility will be the key word as NATO officials spar
with Milosevic over the intricacies of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   That is the way peace accords usually are achieved. It has been
rare for the United States, with all its vast power, to get all it
wants at the peace table.
</P>
<P>
   We settled the Korean conflict in 1953 by agreeing to an
armistice that has remained in effect ever since, maintaining a
tenuous and often unstable peace between the communist north and
the democratic south.
</P>
<P>
   After years of devastation in Vietnam, America's Henry Kissinger
and North Vietnam's Le Duc Tho concluded a peace settlement in 1973
and were jointly awarded the Nobel Peace Prize that year.
</P>
<P>
   But the accord was short-lived. By 1975 North Vietnamese armed
forces had overrun South Vietnam. One of the bleak memories of that
decade is of American diplomats and Vietnamese nationals scrambling
to board helicopters that would transport them to safety away from
Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its allies emerged triumphant from the
Persian Gulf War of 1991. Iraqi troops were forced to retreat from
Kuwait to Baghdad. But when it was all over, Saddam Hussein
remained in power in Iraq and continued to be a threat to security
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   World War II was a mighty exception to the rule that the West
does not totally prevail at the end of a long and bloody armed
conflict. In 1943, Franklin D. Roosevelt decreed that he and his
allies would settle for nothing less than ``unconditional
surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what they got, although in accepting Japan's surrender,
they did agree to let Emperor Hirohito remain on his throne.
</P>
<P>
   But that unconditional surrender had its critics, who claimed
that the war in Europe was prolonged because Nazi Germany knew it
could not soften peace arrangements. There was no chance that Adolf
Hitler would get the treatment accorded Kaiser Wilhelm at the end
of World War I when he fled to the Netherlands for nearly a quarter
century of peaceful exile.
</P>
<P>
   One such critic was the late Edward Folliard, a Pulitzer
Prize-winning reporter who covered the White House for the
Washington Post from the days of Roosevelt to those of Richard
Nixon. Folliard contended that Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower, who
commanded the allied forces that conquered Germany, shared his
view.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after the war had ended but before Eisenhower became
president, he got an opportunity to ask the general his view on
``unconditional surrender.'' Ike said he opposed it because German
propagandists had used it to strengthen German morale and spur Nazi
military forces to fight to the bitter end.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out that Ike had ambivalent feelings on the
subject. In a letter to his wife Mamie in August 1944, he said,
``The end of the war will come only with complete destruction of
the Hun forces.'' A month later, he wrote: ``There is still a lot
of suffering to go through. God, I hate the Germans.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitler, having witnessed the destruction of his evil empire and
knowing that the allies would put him to death, took his own life
just before Germany's surrender in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ike said the demand for ``unconditional surrender'' had
lengthened the war, it was because of action he took in 1942 that
Roosevelt felt compelled to declare such a policy.
</P>
<P>
   When Eisenhower took command of U.S.-English efforts that year
to drive the Germans from North Africa, he began searching for a
French military leader who could persuade French forces to break
with Germany and support the allies.
</P>
<P>
   After considering several French generals, he sought the
cooperation of Adm. Jean Darlan, commander-in-chief of the Vichy
French armed forces fighting on Germany's side.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ike's biographer, Stephen Ambrose, ``The admiral's
record was odious. He was a fascist, an eager collaborator with the
Nazis, author of Vichy's anti-Semitic decrees, and violently
anti-British.''
</P>
<P>
   When word got out that Eisenhower had signed an agreement with
Darlan, according to Ambrose, a ``tremendous storm of criticism''
crashed around Eisenhower and almost cost him his job.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt supported him, but to quiet his critics in England and
the Soviet Union as well as at home he announced his
``unconditional surrender'' policy. That announcement assured his
allies, including Winston Churchill and Josef Stalin, that ``we
will have no truck with fascism in any way, shape or manner.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be great if Clinton and his NATO colleagues could apply
the same rule to Milosevic's brutal ethnic cleansing. But they may
have to agree to less stringent terms in the name of peace.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert E. Thompson can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
