<HEADLINE>
WITH MUCH AT STAKE, U.S. BUSINESSES PUSH FOR SANCTIONS REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The turning point in the debate over economic
sanctions came last fall, when India and Pakistan tested nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The tests triggered automatic U.S. sanctions against the two
countries, mandated by a nuclear non-proliferation law
overwhelmingly passed by Congress just a few years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But the sanctions caused an uproar when it became clear that a
primary victim would be Northwest wheat farmers, for whom Pakistan
represents the largest export market.
</P>
<P>
   So Congress acted to grant President Clinton permission to waive
the sanctions, at least for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Now Congress, and the White House, are poised to take broader
action to change U.S. sanctions policy.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering several pieces of legislation that would
bar sanctions on food and medicine, require cost-benefit analyses
before new sanctions could be imposed, and require the president to
periodically report to Congress on new sanctions. Any new
unilateral economic sanction must expire after two years unless
Congress or the president acts to reauthorize them.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate measure, sponsored by Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., has
attracted 31 co-sponsors, including Sens. Slade Gorton, R-Wash.,
and Patty Murray, D-Wash. The House measure, sponsored by Rep.
Philip Crane, R-Ill., has 68 co-sponsors, including Republicans
Jennifer Dunn, Doc Hastings and George Nethercutt and Democrats
Brian Baird and Adam Smith, all of Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though one could probably justify individually almost all
of the sanctions bills that have been passed, when you look at the
impact of them all combined, it's overwhelmingly negative on our
economy, and it does not seem to have any measurable foreign policy
plus,'' Gorton said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton recently acted to make it possible for some
food and medicine to be exported to Iran, Libya and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's point man on sanctions, Undersecretary of
State Stuart Eizenstat, said the administration wants to go
further: ``We would like to have comprehensive sanctions reform,''
Eizenstat said.
</P>
<P>
   USA Engage, the coalition of 674 business groups pushing for
sanctions reform, is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot more support than we did last year at this time,
and the mood is very strong,'' said Frank Kittredge, vice chairman
of the coalition. ``On the other hand, it looks as if China is
going to be a large part of the (congressional) agenda, and that's
going to require a big role by the business community, and we know
the administration is very heavily focused on Kosovo. But certainly
our congressional sponsors show no signs of being discouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   But change is far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mobilization of business groups will block a lot of new
mandatory sanctions, but I don't know that they will reverse those
sanctions already on the book,'' said Ken Rodman, chairman of the
government department at Colby College in Waterville, Maine.
Members of Congress ``don't want to look like they're supporting
Castro or the mullahs in Iran, and it's very difficult to separate
those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., recently wrote a stinging rebuke of the
business community, saying that ``what they really stand for is not
engagement but mercantilism _ an amoral foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the journal Foreign Affairs, Helms called claims of a
sanctions frenzy ``sheer nonsense'' and blasted ``the distortions
spread by this small cabal of lobbyists in the name of American
business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the lobbyists, the United States should be
hamstrung when a government proliferates weapons of mass
destruction, commits genocide or supports terrorists,'' Helms
wrote. ``But if that same government floods the American market
with cheap television sets, America should throw the book at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO is not normally a Helms ally, but on this issue the
labor union has some sympathy for his position. An official of the
AFL-CIO urged a congressional panel studying sanctions to ensure
that the United States continue to ``stand for values other than
short-term cash flow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We seldom hear an outcry from the business community that the
U.S. trade representative should refrain from imposing retaliatory
tariffs or withdrawing trade preferences when one of our trading
partners has engaged in illegal dumping or has violated
intellectual property rights agreements,'' said Thea Lee, the
AFL-CIO's assistant director for international economics. ``In the
end, objections to unilateral economic sanctions in general are not
to the efficacy of the policy tool, but rather to the unworthiness
of the cause when there is no direct economic interest of U.S.
businesses at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   The non-partisan Congressional Budget Office issued a report
minimizing the concerns of sanctions critics, suggesting that the
loss of income to businesses pales in comparison with the
gargantuan size of the U.S. economy. The Congressional Budget
Office also pointed out that most sanctions are against countries
with relatively underdeveloped economies, lessening the effect on
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And the White House has reservations about placing too many
limits on sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would take the view that a disciplined approach needs to be
imposed on sanctions, to show some reasonable balance on costs and
gains,'' said Assistant Secretary of State Alan Larson. ``But there
are clearly times when the greater good, the national interest,
calls for sanctions. Those sanctions are going to impose costs on
American companies, American citizens, and that's part of the price
we pay for protecting our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Indiana's Lugar, the leading congressional critic of
sanctions, said even without a bill, the policy is changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways it doesn't matter whether we pass the bill,
because effectively unilateral sanctions have become very
dubious,'' Lugar said. ``Instead of the enthusiasm with which these
(sanctions proposals) used to be greeted, now they're met with
skepticism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
