<HEADLINE>
WHAT U.N. OIL-FOR-FOOD RESOLUTION AUTHORIZES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Security Council Resolution 986
</P>
<P>
   _The resolution authorizes the sale of $5.2 billion (U.S.) worth
of Iraq oil for each six-month period. Every oil contract must be
approved by the sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
   _All proceeds from the sale of oil go directly into a
U.N.-controlled escrow account.
</P>
<P>
   _Thirty percent of the proceeds is transferred to a war
reparations compensation fund. Costs for other U.N. operations in
Iraq are also deducted from the escrow account.
</P>
<P>
   _All contracts for humanitarian supplies for Iraq are paid from
the escrow account.
</P>
<P>
   _The export of oil is monitored by independent inspection agents
at two exit points: the Kirkuk-Yumurtalik pipeline (to Turkey) and
the Mina al-Bakr terminal (in the Persian Gulf). These inspectors
directly inform the sanctions committee about the export of all
petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
   _The aim of the resolution is to enable Iraq to import
humanitarian supplies and to guarantee their equitable distribution
throughout its territory.
</P>
<P>
   _The United Nations has said the $5.26 billion limit, from which
about a third is deducted for U.N. expenses and war reparations, is
the minimum amount required to prevent a deterioration in the
health of the population because of U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: United Nations
</P>
</TEXT>
