<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLYING TINTED FILM TO WINDOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most windows allow cold to pass through the glass in the winter,
and heat in the summer. This can make the home uncomfortable and
drive energy bills up. In an effort to make windows more efficient,
manufacturers have introduced gas- filled tinted-glass windows.
These windows are very efficient, but they are also expensive.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is another way to make windows more
energy-efficient without spending a lot of money. You can apply a
tinted film to the glass. These window films can cut down the
amount of ultraviolet rays that penetrate into the house, and
protect furniture, carpets and drapes from fading.
</P>
<P>
   They can also keep your house cooler in the summer by blocking
the sun's visible rays, thus preventing heat gain. In the winter,
some films can help keep the home warmer by trapping interior heat.
Films can also increase visibility inside and lessen eyestrain by
reducing the harsh glare that comes from strong sunlight.
Transparent films allow more light to enter than either drapes or
shades, so the interior never becomes dark or dreary.
</P>
<P>
   Before installing window film, it is important to understand the
types available so you can select the right one for your needs.
Window films fall into three categories: reflective, nonreflective
and low emission.
</P>
<P>
   Reflective films are the least expensive, at approximately 45
cents a square foot. They are very effective in blocking out the
sun's ultraviolet and hot- visible rays. This can help keep the
house cool in the summer, but in the winter this same barrier will
keep the sun from warming the house. Reflective films can also
restrict outside visibility and give the windows a shiny,
mirrorlike look that many homeowners consider an eyesore.
</P>
<P>
   Nonreflective films cost around 55 cents a square foot. They are
not as effective for reflecting heat rays as the less expensive
reflective films, but they are as efficient in blocking ultraviolet
rays and in reducing glare. They offer greater outside visibility
than reflective films.
</P>
<P>
   Low-emission films are superior to either the reflective or
nonreflective films for controlling heat loss in the winter and for
reducing heat gain in the summer. The low-emission films are also
effective for blocking ultraviolet rays, and they offer excellent
outside visibility. But this film is expensive, sometimes costing
as much as a dollar a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Before you purchase film, figure how many windows you want to
cover -- you need film only only the large windows that face the
sun -- then calculate how many square feet of film you will need.
</P>
<P>
   Applying the film is not particularly difficult, but you must
handle it carefully to prevent wrinkles and creases; once the film
wrinkles it becomes unusable. The only tools you will need are a
squeegee, a spray bottle, a steel tape measure, a metal straight
edge, a few lint-free cloths and a utility knife with a generous
supply of sharp blades. The film will quickly dull even the
sharpest blade, and dull blades will tear, not cut the film.
</P>
<P>
   Start by thoroughly washing your windows then drying them with a
lint-free cloth. Remove all dirt and dust, because even minute
specks can keep the film from adhering properly. Next use the knife
and straight edge to cut the film approximately one inch wider than
the window pane. You can trim the film to the exact size when it is
installed.
</P>
<P>
   Spray the window with the wetting solution, which some kits
include as part of the package. With other films you may have to
prepare your own by mixing a half ounce of clear liquid dishwashing
soap in a quart of clean water. Next, separate the film from the
backing paper. Be careful not to wrinkle or crease the film as you
do this. Discard any pieces that wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the film over and spray the adhesive side with the wetting
solution, then lift it into position on the window. Then, spray the
surface of the film with the wetting solution. Use the squeegee to
smooth it and remove any bubbles. Start with a horizontal pass
across the top, then follow with a series of overlapping vertical
passes from the top down.
</P>
<P>
   Finally trim the film to fit within the window frame. Leave a
gap of an eighth to a sixteenth of an inch between the edge of the
film and the window frame. The gap will allow any heat that
collects between the film and the glass to escape. The film may
look cloudy at first, but in a few weeks it will cure and become
clear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
