<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4318 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ONLINE-TRAVEL-ART     05-12 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-TRAVEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL AGENT OR WEB SITE? BOOKING TRIPS ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before she flew to Paris this spring, Mary Shane looked for
travel help on the Internet. There, she was told (1) not to pack
such French fashion no-nos as sneakers or blue jeans, (2) that the
budget hotel she was considering was clean and conveniently located
and (3) that the best price available for a round-trip airplane
ticket was $600.
</P>
<P>
   Two out of three turned out to be true. ``In Paris, all the
women were wearing black and my hotel was, well, it was clean
enough,'' she said. But Ms. Shane, who is 53 and lives near
Olympia, Wash., found a cheaper fare off line, paying $525 for a
round-trip ticket offered by a Montgomery Ward travel service.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shane's experience typifies both the best and the worst
aspects of online travel sites. If you are willing to wade through
dozens of travel sites _ general sites for airline, hotel and car
rental reservations; travel chat rooms, and sites with tourist
information _ you may stumble upon useful information that could
save you time, money and the embarrassment of showing up at the
Eiffel Tower in Nikes. You can even be your own travel agent and
book airline tickets, hotel rooms or rental cars. There is no
guarantee that you will find a better deal on line than you find if
you walked through the door of your local travel agency, but the
simpler your travel needs, the better the chances of finding the
best prices on the Web. If your tastes run to cooking or museum
tours or high-end travel, you are more likely to need a travel
agent.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of people who visit online airline sites do so
for research. Only about 30 percent of those people end up buying
at those sites, according to a new study from NPD Online Research,
a market research company in Port Washington, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far I've always found a cheaper price off line,'' said Ms.
Shane, a retired analyst for the county health department. ``But
since I live in a little town of 3,000 people _ it really is the
sticks _ I couldn't live without the information I get from the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, more and more travelers have been booking
trips on line. Several of the sites with the most traffic reported
record sales in 1999. Over all, online sales last year accounted
for about $3 billion, about 1 percent, of the $300 billion
Americans spent on travel. But that figure is expected to climb by
the end of 2002 to nearly $12.6 billion, about 7.9 percent of what
is expected to be total travel sales then, said Fiona Swerdlow, a
digital commerce analyst at Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to potential savings, the Internet also offers a
powerful psychological benefit. At a time when travelers are so
often forced to endure the indignities of canceled flights or lost
luggage or have suspicions that the passenger in the next seat paid
$400 less for the same ticket, the Internet puts part of the
process firmly back under their control. That's perfect for the
information hound who likes to compare a number of permutations of
an air route just to save $50.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like driving your own car instead of being in the
passenger's seat,'' said Richard Gritta, a professor of business at
the University of Portland in Oregon who studies the airline
industry. ``The Internet makes you an active participant.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the larger travel sites, like Microsoft Expedia Travel
 &UR; (expedia.msn.com)  &LR; and Travelocity  &UR; (www.travelocity.com) &LR; , work
like this: customers submit itinerary information, like dates and
times of travel and departure and arrival cities. (Many sites,
however, will not give you price information if you have multiple
destinations and want to fly into and out of different cities.)
Then the site spits out a list of airplane itineraries and prices,
or hotel or car information and prices. To buy, customers type in
credit card information, and the purchase is confirmed by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are most likely to see the largest price swings _ and
largest potential savings _ for airline tickets. Most major
carriers encourage online sales because the airlines generally pay
lower commissions to online agents than to off-line travel
agencies. And many online sites have struck deals with specific
carriers to offer special deals.
</P>
<P>
   You can also find big price differences among the various travel
sites because they do not all check flights for the same set of
airlines, even though many sites seem to share databases. For
example, a recent search for a fare for three people to fly from
New York to Rome in midsummer turned up a fare of $3,084 from
Travelocity, $2,802 from Expedia and $2,814 from Skytours
 &UR; (service.skytours.de) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Many airlines also offer online reservations for their own
flights at their own Web sites, which can be good places to look
for specials. And travelers concerned about frequent-flier miles
may want to go straight to the Web sites of particular airlines.
But if you go to the general sites, you can get information from
many airlines at once. Air-fare prices can fluctuate from day to
day, largely because airlines use sophisticated yield-management
techniques to track sales and adjust prices.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the bigger travel sites have added improvements in
recent months that make them easier to navigate. Last month,
Travelocity added a Best Fare Finder feature that allows travelers
to see the cheapest ticket for any given air route. Expedia
recently introduced Mileage Miner, which will keep track of
customers' frequent-travel account balances and point them toward
new mileage offers. And Preview Travel  &UR; (www.previewtravel.com) &LR; 
beefed up its Destination Guides last month, enabling travelers to
read restaurant and hotel reviews for 202 destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Sheppard, of Nahunta, Ga., was recently able to find a
New York hotel room through Expedia, which strikes deals with
specific hoteliers and also has access to the Pegasus reservations
system, a database that contains the most up-to-date rates for
thousands of hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I found the hotel I wanted,'' Sheppard said, ``saw the price
was $160 a night, which was much less expensive than the price that
a local travel agency gave me for the same hotel, and booked it.
They sent e-mail to confirm the reservation.''
</P>
<P>
   While some sites have streamlined the purchasing process, do not
expect from travel sites the kind of one-click shopping that makes
it so easy to buy, say, books on Amazon.com. ``With travel, one
click is too quick,'' said Suzi Levine, a product manager for
Expedia. ``This is often an expensive purchase, and we want to make
it very clear to customers that here is what they are buying. You
don't want customers to have remorse. We want them to feel like
they're in control.''
</P>
<P>
   But booking on line works best for travelers who want to make
relatively simple arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the technology is ideally suited to someone who
needs a round-trip ticket on a well-traveled air route, who can
say, `I know what I want and what I'm willing to pay,''' said Gadi
Maier, chief executive of the Internet Travel Network
 &UR; (www.itn.com) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   For travelers like Lisa Myers, a mother of two who has booked
several family trips on Travelocity in the past two years, the
Internet can seem an ideal solution. ``We travel a lot to see our
family, and I'm looking for a good air fare,'' said Ms. Myers, who
lives in Houston. ``I usually have some flexibility on dates, so I
look to see when we can fly the cheapest and then I book it. I
usually do it at night, after the children are asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   But planning something more complicated, like a cruise, can
require an expert's advice. You're not very likely to find out how
old the ship is or how nice the staff is just by surfing travel
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about travel today, there are two general
categories,'' said Ms. Swerdlow, the analyst. ``There's complex
travel, which involves lots of questions to be answered, and then
there's fairly simple travel, which might require nothing more than
a point-to-point airline ticket. In the future, you'll see online
sites becoming easier to navigate, but today, the straightforward
type of arrangement is what most people would feel comfortable with
doing on line.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; One Chance At a Low Price &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers who care only about price and don't mind compromising
on departure times can check Priceline.com, a hybrid travel site
that lets you place a bid. But for each itinerary, a traveler gets
only one chance to bid _ if the first bid is too low, there is no
chance to enter a higher bid and try again.
</P>
<P>
   For a discount air fare, a customer types in bare-bones
itinerary information _ departure and arrival dates and cities _
then enters the price the customer is willing to pay for an airline
ticket or hotel room. A company spokesman said that customers had a
35 percent chance of getting a ticket if they made what he called a
reasonable offer _ an offer that is within 30 percent of a 21-day
advance-purchase price for a particular air route.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com  &UR; (www.priceline.com) &LR;  can offer those discounts
because it negotiates deals with major carriers in advance. ``If
Delta has lots of excess inventory on a given flight, of course,
they want to fill those seats,'' said Fiona Swerdlow, a digital
commerce analyst at Jupiter Communications. ``If you know the going
price for a fare, and you would be willing to pay a little less,
maybe your fare will be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   The tricky part is that the customer must agree to buy the
ticket _ and type in credit card information _ before finding out
whether the flight is available at that price. Also, the customer
must agree ahead of time to fly on any major airline that is
willing to sell a seat and to fly on any flight departing between 6
a.m. and 10 p.m. It's a service aimed at bargain hunters willing to
make a few compromises for price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines have told us they are willing to entertain these
low offers as long as they are serious, no-fooling-around offers,
which is why customers have to agree up front to buy the ticket,''
said Brian Ek, a Priceline.com spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Although Priceline's popularity has grown consistently in the
year since its debut _ in April, the site sold an average of 20,000
airline tickets a week _ the rules can be confusing to
inexperienced travelers. Charles Sheppard, a Pepsi warehouse
manager who lives in Nahunta, Ga., learned that lesson a few months
ago when he was planning a trip to New York with his wife, Julia,
to celebrate their 12th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Priceline got me a $125 round-trip ticket from Jacksonville,
Fla., to New York City, but then when I looked at the details, the
times were terrible,'' Sheppard said. ``We would have to be flying
through the middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Sheppard, when he phoned Priceline.com's customer
service department to explain the situation, ``they were very
cooperative and said, `Yes, sir, we'll cancel the order.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``But they told me not to do it again,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Internet has many travel sites. Here are a few of them: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET TRAVEL: www.budgettravel.com. A great site for travel
links, which steer you to sites with information on things like
transportation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   1TRAVEL: www.1travel.com. Bargains and travel advice.
</P>
<P>
   CHEAPTICKETS ONLINE: www.cheaptickets.com. Discount air fares
and specials on air fares and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   EAT HERE: www.eathere.com. A search engine for travelers who
loathe the idea of fast food on a driving vacation. Enter your
United States or Canadian itinerary and the site responds with a
list of roadside diners along the way. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LONELY PLANET: www.lonelyplanet.com. Charming and offbeat online
information from the people responsible for the quirky Lonely
Planet guidebooks. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WILD ADVENTURES ONLINE: www.wildadventures.com. Features
information on safaris, backpacking vacations and mountain biking
tours. &QL; 
 &QL; 
VACATION SPOT: www.vacationspot.com. A source for unusual vacation
properties, like a restored farmhouse in Provence or a castle in
Italy. Has a special section for millennium vacations. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
QUICKAID: www.quickaid.com. Information about dozens of airports in
the United States, and some abroad, from terminal maps to
transportation options. &QL; 
 &QL; 
OANDA: www.oanda.com/converter/classic. Nifty currency converter
that quickly enables you to translate foreign prices into dollars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
INTERRES: www.interres.com dc .Hotel reservations, mostly in
Southern Africa, with walk-throughs of rooms. Can find availability
and confirm right away. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
