A4329 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     05-12 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV30-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., MAY 30, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am remodeling my kitchen and will be installing a new sink
in the counter top. I had planned on a self-rimming type of sink
that overlaps or mounts on top of the counter. However, my wife
prefers the type that mounts under the countertop and has no rim or
molding of any kind sitting on top of the counter. She feels this
will make it easier to wipe off the countertop by simply pushing
crumbs, etc. into the sink. How is an under-the-top sink installed,
and is this type more difficult to install?
</P>
<P>
   A: Called an undermount sink, this type is more difficult and
more time-consuming to install (probably several hours as compared
to less than one hour for most self-rimming sinks). The
self-rimming sink merely sits on top of the counter with a layer of
putty under the rim (except for some stainless models that require
a rim). The undermount sink is held in place with a special
clamping ring that is screwed to the underside of the counter as
shown here. However, there is another problem to consider: an
undermount sink is only possible when installed on solid countertop
material (granite, Corian or similar material) because the edge of
the counter material will be exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have to repair some wooden chairs that have rungs which fit
into holes in the side of each leg. These rungs have worked loose
in a couple of places and I want to re-glue these loose joints.
What is the best way to do this?
</P>
<P>
   A. The job can only be done properly by literally taking the
chair apart and pulling the end of each rung out of the hole. You
can then scrape all old glue off the end of the rung and from
inside the hole. Coat the rung end with fresh glue, then reassemble
each joint and clamp by wrapping a long strap or rope around the
chair legs. If taking the chair apart is impractical or too
difficult, you can try pulling the end of each rung out as far as
it will go, then use a small knife to scrape glue off the end of
that rung. Spread carpenter's glue on the rung and inside the hole,
then force the joint closed and apply pressure by wrapping as
described above.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our house has windows with double-pane glass and there are
metal or plastic strips inside _ between the two panes of glass _
that divide the large panes to make them look like smaller ones.
Unfortunately, these strips seem to be falling apart. Can we fix
these windows without having to replace them?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's possible that the glass panes can be taken apart and the
strips replaced, but this will depend on how the window was made or
assembled. In any case, this is usually not a job for the
do-it-yourselfer. It calls for the services of a professional
glazier. I suggest you contact the manufacturer of that window, or
check with several local glass dealers in your community to see if
any are equipped to handle this kind of job.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We have fiberglass shingles on our roof that are still in
pretty good condition. However, I have never been happy with the
color. Is there any way to change the color without having to
replace the shingles?
</P>
<P>
   A. The only way to change the color of the shingles is to paint
them. There are special paints sold for this purpose, but they come
in only a limited number of colors and not all dealers carry them.
You can also paint the shingles with a good quality latex house
paint, but like any paint, this will have to be renewed every few
years, depending on the weather and the exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``UNDERMOUNT SINKS'' goes with this
column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Self-rimming sinks sit on top of the counter, while
undermount sinks are held in place with special clamps.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
