<P>
   TREASURY-RUBIN (Washington) _ Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, a
Wall Street favorite who is widely credited with helping to sustain
the economic boom, is stepping down and will be succeeded by his
deputy, Lawrence Summers. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   US-RUSSIA (Washington) _ President Clinton is still looking to
Russia as the go-between with Yugoslavia in the quest for peace
despite the political upheaval in the Kremlin and the threat by
Russian President Boris Yeltsin to withdraw from the negotiations.
By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ House and Senate negotiators are
hammering out an emergency spending bill to give President Clinton
at least $4.9 billion more than he wants to continue bombing
Yugoslavia. Congressional leaders are hoping to minimize the number
of side issues tacked onto the bill. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL (Washington) _ Congressional lawmakers, led by
Texas Reps. Lamar Smith, a Republican, and Sylvestre Reyes, a
Democrat, urge President Clinton to boost the number of Border
Patrol agents by 1,000 to help stem the flow of illegal immigrants.
By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-SPENDING (Washington) _ Reps. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., and
Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., former Rep. Ronald Dellums, D-Calif., and
AIDS research advocates call for higher government and industry
spending on efforts to stem the spread of HIV in developing
nations. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
