<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Thursday, May 13, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Ledeall: President Boris Yeltsin
fires his prime minister, Yevgeny M. Primakov, and replaces him
with Sergei Stepashin, a longtime Yeltsin loyalist and current head
of police as Interior Minister. The move comes the day before the
Communist-dominated Parliament, which strongly supported Primakov,
takes up the impeachment of Yeltsin. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ A news analysis. The method to
Yeltsin's apparent madness of yet another government shakeup:
self-protection. His prime minister was in bed with his enemies, he
came in as political stabilizer but was unable for last three
months to control the growing impeachment drive and the conflict
with Parliament over Yeltsin's desire to remove Russia's chief
prosecutor. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments on the war from NATO
headquarters. By Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-MILWAUKEE (Milwaukee) _ A decade ago, an eccentric band
of reformers here set out to guarantee every poor person a path
from poverty _ an assured job at a sufficient wage with child care
and health care. But as the program closes its offices this week,
an exhaustive volume of new research offers some disquieting
conclusions. Among the adults, only 27 percent managed to stick
with their subsidized jobs long enough to escape poverty. Their
average annual earnings were just $6,600. By Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-RESIGN (Washington) _ A ledeall: Robert Rubin resigns as
Treasury secretary; Clinton will name Lawrence Summers, Rubin's
deputy, to succeed him. Rubin is reported to have wanted to leave
for some time but waited until after Clinton's impeachment was
settled and the global economic situation seemed less volatile.
Plus reaction from the investment community where he was admired,
and a consideration of who will fill his role as an adviser on
economic and other issues. By John M. Broder and David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
