<HEADER>
A4354 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YMCA-RENTER-AZR &LR;      05-12 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YMCA-RENTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YMCA IS HOME FOR 32 YEARS  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS HAVE BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM LOWE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Frank Mazza remembers the day he moved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memorial Day, 1967,'' he said. ``I came down Van Buren, turned
north and walked past the YMCA. Then I turned around, went inside
the Y and got a room. Cost me a couple of bucks a day, 10 bucks a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   So he stayed.
</P>
<P>
   And stayed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he's still there.
</P>
<P>
   The rates have gone up more than 800 percent and his room number
has changed at least five times, but the YMCA in downtown Phoenix
has been his mailing address for almost 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a sleeping room,'' he said, then volunteered to
conduct a guided tour. ``Small, but it's all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Valley of the Sun YMCA has 139 rental units in the
seven-story facility. Four floors are reserved for men, one floor
for women. They're usually filled. It's one of the few Ys still in
the lodging business. Nationwide, according to a spokesperson in
Chicago, only about 120 Ys are available for sleepovers, a drastic
reduction from a half-century ago when YMCA rooms were primary
targets for tourists and men in transition who needed low-cost
rooms. There are more than 3,000 YMCAs in the United States, the
spokesperson said, and new facilities are going up every year. But
none of them focuses on rooms for rent.
</P>
<P>
   Like all the others, Mazza's room is small. Very small. Mazza
estimates it's maybe 12 feet by 18 feet. It looks smaller but it's
too crowded to pace it off. There's barely enough space for a bed,
easy chair, desk, chest of drawers and Frank Mazza. One door leads
to a tiny closet, the other door opens into the hallway. The
bathroom's down the hall to the right. His 17-inch color television
sits on the dresser and his radio and electric razor perch on a
window sill.
</P>
<P>
   Because his is a corner room, he has two windows. One looks
north at the Westward Ho, which was a pretty fancy hotel when Mazza
got here. Now it's a retirement community. Looking east from the
other window, he can see much of downtown Phoenix. Most of the
buildings in his line of vision weren't there when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Mazza was born near Pittsburgh in 1917 and spent most of his
life in the area, working as a spectograph operator in metal and
chemical plants. He served in the armed forces during World War II
and spent time in the South Pacific with a hospital unit on the
front lines. After moving to the Valley of the Sun, he worked for
Goodyear Aerospace until retiring in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I don't do anything,'' he said with a chuckle. ``That's
what I'm supposed to do. I'm retired.''
</P>
<P>
   He spends his days reading and watching television, mostly news,
weather and sports. He follows the Arizona Diamondbacks baseball
team ``because it's a local team and the only one I can watch. But
I'm still a Pirates fan.''
</P>
<P>
   And his eyes sparkled when he remembered ``that home run.''
Mazza was in the stands at Forbes Field on Oct. 13, 1960, when Bill
Mazeroski's ninth-inning home run gave the Pirates a 10-9 victory
over the New York Yankees in the seventh game of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never let anything get me real excited,'' he remembered,
``but that got me as excited as I could be.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't been to a Diamondbacks game yet, even though Bank One
Ballpark is less than a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to get to a game this year,'' he said. ``When they
play the Pirates.''
</P>
<P>
   He used to spend a lot of time walking around downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when I was more alert, I'd walk every day,'' he said.
``But now, it doesn't interest me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Phoenix was a nice place when he got here, Mazza
reflected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crowded. There were lots of shops and a restaurant on
every block, but they all moved out. Now it's mostly big office
buildings. And it's all modernized.''
</P>
<P>
   When the urge to move about strikes him now, Mazza drives there
in his 1996 Chevrolet Beretta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to the golf course,'' he said. ``Used to play quite a bit
but the old back went out. Played pretty well, sometimes in the
70s. Shot 72 once. But now I just putt.''
</P>
<P>
   His room is too small to allow formal dining or pizza parties,
so Mazza dines regularly in the Y's cafeteria. He also spends a lot
of time in the lounge, socializing and watching television on a set
with a larger screen. But although he's never at a loss for
companionship, he still gets lonely. Once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, sometimes I wish I'd got married,'' he said. ``I had
a girl back home. A couple of them. But I didn't have money or
anything to offer them, and I didn't want to start empty.''
</P>
<P>
   His only relatives are a cousin in Phoenix and a niece in the
Pittsburgh area. But he has the Y for company.
</P>
<P>
   Most YMCA tenants stay for only two or three weeks, on an
average. Frank Mazza exceeded that figure in June 1967.
</P>
<P>
   And he has no plans to move. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
