r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CHINA-AZR &LR;      05-12 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHINA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S WAR, AND MISTAKES HAPPEN  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE MAY 12 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - NATO forces are waging what looks a lot like war in
the Balkans. Yet a lot of people _ even nations _ still act
surprised at the consequences of unloading 15,000 bombs and
missiles on Yugoslavia. The erroneous bombing over the weekend of
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade was tragic, but nobody should be
shocked that such errors occur _ and will continue to occur.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton apologized to Chinese President Jiang Zemin
for the mistake, which killed three and wounded 20. But China is
having none of it. It used the mistake to fan anti-NATO protests in
Beijing and suggest that the bombing was premeditated.
Nationalistic cries of ``American imperialism'' rang again in the
streets of Beijing. China took advantage of the bombing to divert
attention from the upcoming 10th anniversary of the Tiananmen
massacre and growing restiveness in the United States over the
Chinese theft of U.S. military secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing also has had consequences for the United States and
NATO. It has set back efforts to involve Russia and China in
diplomatic efforts to end this crisis. China accused NATO of
pursuing ``absolute gunboat policy'' and has warned that, as long
as the bombings continue, there can be no U.N. solution to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   China is worried that, after the Balkans, NATO and the United
States will seek to intervene in any other countries where human
rights abuses are an issue. Today, Kosovo. Tomorrow, China? Hardly.
Given the lack of success NATO is having in the Balkans, it's
doubtful that next time around NATO could muster the will to mount
a naval blockade in a bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of the Chinese Embassy is being blamed on faulty
information from the CIA. Such information is supposed to be
checked and rechecked to avoid possible risks to civilians. The
Chinese Embassy and a headquarters for a Yugoslav arms agency
nearby (which was the intended target) were of a similar size and
shape.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of the Chinese Embassy is regrettable. But, whether
anyone wants to use the word or not, this is war. Buildings get
blown up, sometimes intentionally, sometimes not. Sometimes the
wrong buildings get blown up intentionally, as was the case with
the Chinese Embassy. The United States can certainly do a better
job of targeting, but even the world's most technologically
advanced nation can't be expected to wage a war so efficient and
sanitized that only the bad guys get killed and everyone else
escapes collateral damage.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces have little choice but to continue the bombing while
stepping up efforts to find a diplomatic way out of this mess. The
embassy bombing has set back U.S. relations with China, but the
United States has rightly sought to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, China should tone down the rhetoric and
acknowledge what was clearly an error. China needs the United
States as a trade partner. Cynics might suggest that it's also in
China's military interest to maintain ties with the United States.
After all, there are still a few more U.S. military secrets left
for China to steal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
