<HEADLINE>
A WALKMAN-STYLE PC LEADS THE IBM LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., N.Y., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer and consumer electronics manufacturers invest
considerable time and money exploring design ideas, trying to hit
on the next Palm Pilot, IBM Thinkpad or Motorola Startac cellular
phone.
</P>
<P>
   For the past couple of years, a corps of engineers and
industrial designers at the International Business Machines Corp.,
known for its blue-sky designs, has been sketching out the concept
cars of the computer world: a tiny personal computer with a
full-screen display, a versatile household computer that adapts to
any environment, the cyberphone and a dress watch that doubles as
an electronic organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Research into futuristic projects is happening in other places
as well, like the Massachusetts Institute of Technology Media
Laboratory and Microsoft, but IBM is particularly well positioned
for such projects. Its eight research centers, scattered around the
world, delve into many things, like advanced circuit design and
projection display technology.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John P. Karidis organized the designers into ``virtual
teams.'' Although the Personal Systems Group, where Karidis is a
Distinguished Engineer, is overseeing the projects, Karidis has
drawn on engineering talent from a variety of IBM groups in
Raleigh, N.C.; Tokyo; Almaden, Calif., and Yorktown Heights, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The most high-profile product idea to emerge so far is the
so-called wearable PC, a Walkman-style device designed by an IBM
team in Japan. Also referred to internally as the visionpad, the
device is a fully functioning PC, with a headpiece that contains a
virtual display as well as a speaker and a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't want to give up any of the applications
they've got on their PC today,'' said Phil Hester, chief technology
officer of the Personal Systems Group at IBM. ``PDAs and
subnotebooks all require you to give something up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at a notebook, what really determines its size
is display and keyboard. So we said, `Let's assume we can fix the
display and keyboard problem. How small and how mobile can you make
a PC without giving up any functionality?'''
</P>
<P>
   The visionpad has all the functions of an IBM Thinkpad 560E
laptop, including a chip that runs at 233 megahertz. The
translucent device, which clips onto a belt, is roughly as thick as
a deck of playing cards.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most radical departure from the computing norm is
the device's head-mounted display: a flexible headband with a
rectangular display that sits an inch or two in front of the user's
eye _ somewhat similar to the way a mirror is mounted on a bicycle
helmet. Innovative optical technology makes a 26-inch display
appear to be about six feet away. ``The image appears to float in
front of your face,'' Karidis explained, adding that the distance
is adjustable.
</P>
<P>
   For input, the visionpad depends largely on voice recognition
through a headset; in addition, a small pointing device is wired to
the belt pack. A regular keyboard can also be attached to the unit.
</P>
<P>
   Another device, but one early in development, is the cyberphone,
IBM's answer to the latest rage in mobile devices. The cyberphone,
designed by engineers in Yorktown Heights, looks much like an
ordinary cellular phone, but a tiny high-resolution image of a Web
page can be bounced off a mirror, found inside the phone's flip
cover, to generate a virtual screen image in front of the user.
</P>
<P>
   Like the visionpad, the phone uses a reflective surface to
create an image that appears to the eye to be a full-size display
at a normal reading distance. That is possible because of the
special shape of the mirror. The pointing device for the screen is
a thumb-operated track point on the side of the phone.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the cyberphone, Hester said, is to combine
regular phone functions with simultaneous access to information.
``It goes back to a human factors discussion,'' he said. ``How does
someone hold a cell phone? What is natural for you to do? To glance
down. The whole premise is that you want to be able to deliver
visual information at the same time that you're talking on the
phone in a way that's very natural.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   A third project, which IBM has nicknamed the chameleon, crosses
a notebook computer with a desktop computer. The distinguishing
features of the device, which will be slightly larger and weigh
slightly more than a notebook computer, are its A-frame structure,
a touch screen and a wireless keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Hester says the chameleon will transform itself into something
different depending on where it is in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the name. On a kitchen counter, for example, the screen
slides forward to hide the keyboard so it looks less like a
computer and more like an appliance, or television. When the
keyboard is needed, it can be pulled out like a drawer.
</P>
<P>
   A woman in her 30s, a frequent computer user who was a market
research subject for the chameleon, said she wanted to keep a
computer on her dining-room table but put it away when she had
dinner guests. The Chameleon is ``for people who need their
computer to be portable sometimes, but they don't need a
notebook,'' Karidis said. The chameleon, he said, will cost more
than a desktop computer but less than a notebook.
</P>
<P>
   Another project, which Karidis discussed in a recent speech, is
the development of a dress watch with a very high-resolution
display that doubles as a personal organizer. ``It turns out that
if you have very high contrast and brightness, most people don't
have trouble reading very small type,'' Karidis said. The goal, he
said, is to avoid the nerdy appearance of most digital watches.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four devices, the visionpad is closest to becoming an
actual product. The company plans to build 150 of them later this
year and test them with a handful of customers who have a need for
hands-free computing, like aircraft maintenance workers or law
enforcement officers. Depending on how the field tests go, the
product could be on the market in the next year or two.
</P>
<P>
   The chameleon is still in the early prototype phase, and the
cyberphone and the watch are at the concept and design stage. The
watch and the cyberphone ``both depend on the display technologies
and ultra-low-power processing, which are just starting to become
available,'' Karidis said.
</P>
<P>
   Hester agreed, especially when it came to the watch. ``Display
technology is headed there in three years,'' he said. ``But it's
beyond the state of the art in terms of producing working models.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether there's a market for these devices is another matter.
``We're trying to push the envelope of what technology and design
can offer,'' Karidis said. ``But when you're exploring the edges of
what's possible, naturally we'll come up with lots of ideas which
the market may not be ready for. Just because you can build it
doesn't mean people want it or will buy it. When you ask people
what they want, they don't always know.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Shipley, publisher of Demoletter, an industry newsletter,
has seen the IBM designs and agrees that market acceptance is
difficult to gauge. ``I don't know how comfortable people will be
flipping up a monitor in front of their face,'' she said, referring
to the visionpad.
</P>
<P>
   Hester said IBM did not plan to manufacture all the devices
itself, especially the phone and the watch. The company will seek
suitable partners that specialize in such products, he said. Ms.
Shipley agreed that such a strategy made sense. ``I'm not sure IBM
is ready to design jewelry,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
