<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4365 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-12 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCRETE EVIDENCE THAT SENTIMENTALITY DOESN'T PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I loved that sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   It's ridiculous to say, but I did. Sometimes, when I was
watering my yard, I'd look at the concrete square that was stamped
``Pacific Construction, 1930'' and envision the people who built my
house as they pushed a baby stroller over that spot, as their kids
rode a bike, or as someone stood there and cheered when World War
II ended.
</P>
<P>
   So you can understand how upset I was when I heard a jackhammer
in my front yard and saw the sidewalk buckle and split as if the
Earth was having one big, frenetic seizure.
</P>
<P>
   ``WHAT ARE YOU DOING?!'' I yelled as I marched out into the
yard.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) ``NO HABLO INGLES!'' (end ital) the jackhammer guy
yelled as panic raced over his face.
</P>
<P>
   When I took a step closer, he dropped the jackhammer and ran
across the street to his foreman, who was real busy looking at his
nostrils in the rearview mirror from the front seat of his truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a problem, lady?'' the foreman said as he walked
toward me, in a stride so brazen I briefly thought that either John
Gotti or Sammy the Bull had become a working stiff in the federal
witness-protection program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're chopping up my antique sidewalk,'' I said, being as
brave as I could without being drunk. ``It was made in 1930. Says
so right here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no. This is not your sidewalk. Your yard is yours,''
he said with one hand on his hip and the other waving in my face.
``But the sidewalk is the property of the city of Phoenix, and they
contracted us to make improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Improvements?'' I said, suddenly remembering that all
Liquored-Up Laurie's courage usually got me was a photo of myself
with my eyes half-closed posted next to the doorway of the bar with
the words, ``Trouble: Drunk, Mean, Angry Writer'' under it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?'' I continued. ``Are you going to cover it in
stucco, paint it pink and slap a tile roof on it? That's how the
city of Phoenix `improves' things!''
</P>
<P>
   I was dealing with an evil entity here that the Pope couldn't
handle, even with a cameo appearance by the Holy Ghost, or even
Selena.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe it's only a sidewalk, but it's always easier for the
city of Phoenix to knock something down than it is to fix it. This
is the place where progress includes demolishing hundreds of
historic homes and building a freeway or a 70,000-seat hot dog
concession stand instead. So why would I think that the city of
Phoenix would have mercy on my little sidewalk?
</P>
<P>
   There was no mercy to be had, evidenced in the chunks of a
concrete puzzle now lying where the sidewalk used to be, in the
street and in my front yard.
</P>
<P>
   In my front yard.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor was staring at me, waiting for me to shut up and
go back into my little old house.
</P>
<P>
   But you know me better than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' I said, walking over to the pile of concrete in my yard.
``If this is my yard, and my yard is my property, then I guess this
concrete (begin tial in my yard (end ital) is my property, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The contractor just kept staring at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that makes this mine,'' I said as I picked up the chunk
stamped ``Pacific Construction, 1930'' from the street and threw it
onto my grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this mine,'' as I threw another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``And THIS mine,'' as I threw another one and felt the herniated
disk in my back pop so far out of alignment that it nearly broke
the skin and sliced me in half with a big lightening bolt of pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady,'' the contractor said, still staring at me, ``it's just
a sidewalk!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah?'' I said as I hobbled back into my yard. ``For 70 years,
people have been pushing strollers on this sidewalk. Kids learned
to ride their bikes on this sidewalk. Little girls played hopscotch
on this sidewalk, writing the numbers with chalk in their tiny
little 1930s hands! Do you know how small hands were in the 1930s?
Very small.''
</P>
<P>
   I hobbled a foot closer to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And how do you know,'' I said, my voice rising almost to a
yell, ``that when World War II ended, someone didn't stand right
here and understand the real meaning of what it meant to be free?
Huh?
</P>
<P>
   ``Or that someone was on this sidewalk when they heard President
Kennedy was shot and tears of anguish and sorrow ran down their
face and splashed on the concrete!
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you know that when Neil Armstrong took his first step
on the moon, a father didn't bring his son out here to point up at
the sky and say, `That's our country up there, Jimmy, THOSE ARE OUR
BOYS!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The contractor was silent for a moment, and looked over to the
pile of cement chunks that now belonged to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you in drama, lady?'' he said. ``Or am I on `Candid
Camera' ?''
</P>
<P>
   I ignored him as I traveled, apelike, into my little old house.
I had bigger problems to solve, like explaining to my husband why
it looked like NATO had dropped a bomb in my front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like something BIG is building a nest out there!'' I
thought about saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey! A meteor almost hit the house!'' I contemplated crying.
``But it's OK because I lived! I'm alive!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't believe it,'' I decided to say, ``but I was watering
the front yard when, all of a sudden, this midget version of
Stonehenge unearthed itself! Do you think it's possible that we
live on Druid sacred ground?''
</P>
<P>
   But when he opened the front door, my husband just held up his
hand when I began to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Kravitz,'' he said, taking a deep breath, ``the next time
you see . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the hose . . .'' I started to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . any kind of workmen, guys in uniform, people with tools,
anyone in a backhoe . . .'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . the ground shook, the sky got dark . . .'' I tried to
describe.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . repaving the street, fixing a street sign and,
especially _ and I mean ESPECIALLY _ messing with the sewer . . .''
he went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . I heard chanting . . .'' I wanted to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . YOU ARE NOT ALLOWED OUTSIDE, OR TO GIVE THE WORLD WAR II
SPEECH TO ANY OF THEM!'' he concluded. ``Now, how bad does your
back hurt?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know,'' I answered, pointing to the butterfly
bandage that was keeping my spine in one piece, ``it was just a
sidewalk. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her column
to the Rep, P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or by e-mail to
laurienotaro(at)usa.net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
