<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-CABLE-BOXES. (For the Hollywood Reporter.) The
Federal Communications Commission is expected to take action
Thursday with its effort to make cable boxes more widely available
to consumers. In 1996, the Telecommunications Act required that
cable boxes be made available at commercial outlets, not just from
the cable provider. As part of that rule, cable companies were
asked to separate the part of the box that controls the channels
subscribers are able to watch (300 words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-PHONE-COLUMBINE. Police wasted precious minutes
securing the gymnasium at Columbine High School after a caller told
911 dispatchers a shooting victim was bleeding to death there. In
fact, no one in the gym was injured, and officials had no way of
knowing the call -- a prank -- came from a wireless telephone
outside the school. The shootings have drawn new attention to
problems that occur when people use wireless telephones to call for
help. (600 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   IDAHO-GUN-CONTROL. As the Senate began a contentious debate on
juvenile crime and gun control, Sen. Larry Craig offered an
amendment that would provide private dealers with temporary
licenses or a special register at gun shows (400 words.) Robin
Brown
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-OIL-GAS. Whatever good will existed between the
Clinton administration and Sen. Mary Landrieu on major federal
oil-and-gas revenue legislation appears to be over. At a Senate
hearing Tuesday, the Louisiana Democrat sharply criticized a White
House plan to spend $1 billion on the environment. Landrieu said it
failed to solve a ``glaring inequality'' in the way the federal
government allocates offshore oil drilling royalties to Louisiana.
(400 words.) By Mark Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN-WASH-MONUMENT. Call it an inside-the-beltway example of
tilting at windmills. Better make that tilting at obelisks. At the
very least, it's a Washington cover-up that one former Michigan
resident doesn't want uncovered. Chad Allen, now living in
Washington, wants to keep the Washington Monument covered in
scaffolding. The scaffolding, designed by architect Michael Graves,
is temporary. It's intended to remain in place during the
renovation of the 555-foot stone obelisk honoring the nation's
first president. Not if Allen has anything to say about it. (500
words.) By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   MULTICHANNEL-WIRELESS-CABLE. A look at the wireless cable
industry, which is beginning to get into the high-speed Internet
access business. (1,200 words.) By Laura Maggi
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-YOUNGSTOWN-CENSUS. On Capitol Hill, a battle rages to
ensure that urban towns like Youngstown and other communities are
not short-changed in next year's census. (700 words.) By Sean
Gorman
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-BUS. The South Eastern Pennsylvania Transit
Authority (SEPTA) has the most improved safety record of all the
nation's largest bus systems, according to a national transit
association. (500 words.) By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-CENSUS-PRISON. Wisconsin is the leading exporter of
prisoners in the nation. But could counting those prisoners save
Wisconsin from losing a congressional seat after the 2000 census?
Green Bay Republican Mark Green thinks it could help. (Working.) By
Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
