<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERLYS-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERLYS IN HARMONY AGAIN, AT LEAST ON CONCERT STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There are harmony groups. Then, there are the Everly
Brothers, who basically exist on a celestial plane above everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   The shimmering blend of voices between Don Everly and his
younger brother Phil created some of the most lasting songs in
rock-and-roll history. That's one reason why the Beatles, the Beach
Boys and Simon &AMP; Garfunkel all cited the duo as an inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Few records have captured the essence of teenage yearning better
than ``All I Have to Do Is Dream.'' There was the forceful ``When
Will I Be Loved,'' the compelling ``Cathy's Clown'' and the
emotionally raw ``Bye Bye Love.'' These weren't just hit records;
they were 2{-minute mini-masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Still, something seems a trifle odd imagining 62-year-old Don
and 60-year-old Phil singing about the ache of first love. But the
eldest Everly says that the captivating combination of voices is
still there when the two perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're singing as good as ever _ maybe better,'' Don
says, driving around his adopted hometown of Nashville. ``Believe
me, before we go onstage I wonder why we're doing this. Then, when
we're out there, I'm like, `Yeah, this is what it's about.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When the duo reunited in 1983 for a pair of London concerts
after a 10-year separation, the voices sounded intact. The mammoth
success of those shows led to a series of international tours and a
recording deal with PolyGram.
</P>
<P>
   Three albums were issued between 1984 and 1989, each attracting
critical raves but less-than-spectacular sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I would love to be back in the studio, but I
don't see any recording for us in the future,'' Don admits. ``Phil
has his life out in Los Angeles, I'm here _ I just don't see it
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The duo's classic sound in the '50s and '60s combined elements
of rock and roll, rich Kentucky harmonies and a pure hillbilly
twang. The Everlys regularly crossed over to the country and R&AMP;B
charts in their heyday. The duo's '80s output even produced some
country hits (``On the Wings of a Nightingale,'' ``Born
Yesterday''), but Don doesn't think that the format now would
welcome the siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing a mix of rock and roll and country,'' he says.
``But honestly, I don't know whether there's a market for us in
country music. There's no point in doing it if no one is going to
buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they spend a few months on the road each year. And with
their amazing legacy, they can sit back and let the rewards roll
in. Box sets and greatest-hits collections are constantly
appearing. They were among the first inductees when the Rock and
Roll Hall of Fame was formed in 1986. In '97, they received a
long-overdue Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award. A musical based on
the pair's life premiered in Nashville last year.
</P>
<P>
   And although the two patched up the personal differences that
sparked the initial breakup, they don't sound particularly chummy
today. Don says they don't see each other when they're not touring.
They even travel in separate buses. It's hard to imagine that two
men who sing so closely and so beautifully live such separate
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it's good now,'' Don says. ``I think we sing closer
than we ever did, but now we have our own lives. Really, it's just
easier this way.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at randy.cordova(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
