<HEADER>
A4388 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MOTHER-GOOSE-NYT &LR;      05-12 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MOTHER-GOOSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESERVING MOTHER GOOSE ELECTRONICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When some parents and teachers bewail a loss of cultural
heritage, they're not talking about knowing when the Civil War was
or being able to pick Andrew Jackson out of a line-up.
</P>
<P>
   It's the undercurrent of sadness _ or panic _ that sets in when
children ask, ``Jack and Jill Who?'' or ``Was Georgie Porgie a rock
star?''
</P>
<P>
   A selection of posted Internet comments about the fading of
Mother Goose blamed such culprits as illiteracy, fewer grandparents
at home, the decline of storytelling, too much television and
extreme political correctness. (Hey, would you like someone to cut
off  &UR; your &LR;  tail with a carving knife?)
</P>
<P>
   That page is one of the links from the year-old Web site of the
Mother Goose Society
 &UR; (www.gbalc.org/MotherGooseSociety/index.html) &LR; , which celebrates
rhymes that never needed any extra help in previous generations.
</P>
<P>
   The site was created by a Pennsylvania author, Gloria T.
Delamar, with help from a California Web page designer, Stephanie
Stokes. Mrs. Delamar, a former kindergarten teacher, said in a
telephone interview that she created the society, and then the
page, to promote sales of her book ``Mother Goose: From Nursery to
Literature'' (McFarland &AMP; Co., 1987). Along the way, she said, she
declared May 1 as Mother Goose Day (``It's my birthday,'' she
explained) and got it listed in some published calendars.
</P>
<P>
   Her book went out of print last summer. But the Web site lives
on, with the Greater Bay Area Library Council as its host. ``We
just keep adding to it,'' Mrs. Delamar said.
</P>
<P>
   The site includes a good deal of how-to information: recipes,
finger puppets, counting-out games and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Delamar debunks a few well-known tales of nursery-rhyme
origins. The so-called original Mother Goose who is buried in
Boston is fanciful, she says. Correcting another common belief, she
writes that ``Ring Around the Rosy'' was not an allusion to the
plague. ``Little Miss Muffet'' may refer to the daughter of Dr.
John Muffet, an Elizabethan entomologist. But even that is shaky,
since the first known printed version of the rhyme, using a
different name, did not appear until 1805.
</P>
<P>
   A short but very interesting Mother Goose site on the Web
originates in Japan. The English-language site, called the ``Mother
Goose Library''
( &UR; www.sun-inet.or.jp/syasui/MotherGooseLibrary.html &LR; , introduces
the rhymes to Japanese students, explains the author's interest and
invites viewers to e-mail an application to join the host club, the
Mother Goose Society in Japan. Unlike Mrs. Delamar's Mother Goose
Society, which exists only on the Web, the 10-year-old Japanese
club issues a monthly newsletter, holds study groups and has a
national convention every other year.
</P>
<P>
   The site was created by Yasui Sadao, a high-school English
teacher for 20 years, who grew curious about odd expressions that
popped up frequently in English stories and that seemed to make no
sense when he literally translated them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I got to know about Mother Goose, the better I felt I
was able to understand English,'' wrote Yasui. ``When I introduced
some of the famous rhymes, like `Humpty Dumpty sat on a wall' or
`Jack and Jill went up a hill,' to my students, they showed keen
interest in the poems, in the illustrations, in the melodies and
the stories in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Yasui has collected more then 500 Mother Goose
books, mainly from English and American publishers. Mother Goose
rhymes, he wrote by e-mail, were first translated into Japanese in
1921 by a poet, Hakushu Kitahara. Later translations have been a
big hit, and a scholar, Keiichi Hirano, has written several books
on Mother Goose.
</P>
<P>
   Society members exchange information about research on Mother
Goose or ideas about how to teach Mother Goose to children and
students.
</P>
<P>
   A loss of children's culture is a problem in Japan, too. ``We
used to have traditional Japanese nursery rhymes but they are
`endangered species' these days,'' Yasui wrote. ``Children rarely
sing or play with them. They do TV games or computer games now!
Poor things!''
</P>
</TEXT>
