<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-VILLAGE-APARTMENT-     05-12 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VILLAGE-APARTMENT-ART-1130(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN APARTMENT TRANSFORMED: A 1990S NEW YORK DESIGN FOR LIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MARC KRISTAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Question: How long does it take to put together a
three-bedroom, two-bathroom apartment in the heart of Greenwich
Village, with three working fireplaces and a terrace, overlooking
an Italianate inner garden, and all for a total of $234,000?
Answer: 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who created the space, Diane Shea, 45, is notable not
merely for her perseverance. She also represents a classic New York
tale, in a certain time and place: a personal journey from 1970s
art student to a collaboration with a 1980s art star to a genteel,
familial bohemianism that is typically 1990s. It is equally a story
of homesteading, Manhattan-style, and how, as one woman grew with
the city, she adapted to changing times _ within her neighborhood,
the real-estate market, her apartment and her life.
</P>
<P>
   The story starts in 1974, when Ms. Shea was an art major at the
Parsons School of Design, crashing with three aspiring musicians in
an artist-in-residence loft on West Broadway and Prince streets,
then a quiet, semi-industrial zone. Each paid $85 a month for the
privilege of living in a space in which you took the elevator by
leaping into the shaft and grabbing a rope, Tarzan-style, then
scrambling out again before the car came down and crushed you.
</P>
<P>
   Tiring of the communal life, Ms. Shea decided to get a place of
her own. She found a 250-square-foot studio in a crazy-quilt
structure created from four tenements erected in the 1850s and
combined in the 1920s. The buildings had been joined but not
unified, and the results of this polygamous shotgun marriage were
evident everywhere: hallways and window lines abruptly changed
levels; closet doors opened onto unresolved bits of stairway.
Indeed, there were still two entrances and two addresses, one on
Bleecker Street, the other on West 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Her studio was a box, with a half-kitchen, and front and
bathroom doors that opened directly into the living space. The
wiring ran through the original gas lines, and the entire space
functioned at the whim of a single 15-ampere fuse. Its sole
distinguishing feature was an orange-veined, gray marble fireplace
_ more a necessity than a luxury, as the boiler was often out.
</P>
<P>
   But the studio's three windows looked onto a lush garden and
former stable, which had been converted to a loggia adorned with
found furniture. It formed a remarkable urban oasis. The
neighborhood still felt very much like the storied bastion of
bohemianism, in which free thinkers drank gin at Chumley's while
debating the evils of capital and the glories of art. And, at $175
a month, the price was right, though, Ms. Shea noted dryly, no
bargain. It was an ideal life for a 20-year-old student, enjoying
her first New York adventure.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985, when the building went co-op in that decade's
real-estate boom, Ms. Shea's life had changed. A relatively unknown
artist, Robert Longo, had engaged her to collaborate on his work,
and along the way he had become one of the brightest of the New
York art scene's supernovas. Ms. Shea had, in her own way, arrived.
Her priorities became those of a woman whose knockabout youth had
given way, at 31, to a desire for more mature satisfactions.
</P>
<P>
   With little in savings, Ms. Shea secured 100 percent bank
financing and bought her piece of the Manhattan rock for $48,000.
She also bought her next door neighbor's apartment, a
325-square-foot studio, for $68,000, also 100 percent financed,
without knowing whether she could legally or structurally combine
the two. Neither was anyone's ideal of hearth and home, but it was
an opportunity, and she wasn't going to miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Ms. Shea married Doug Sloan, a multimedia
producer-director and old school chum of Longo's. She sublet her
two studios and moved into Sloan's apartment in a cookie-cutter,
white-brick building on East 46th Street. Still, she pined for
Greenwich Village, though as a career woman and soon-to-be mother,
for different reasons. The bohemian fantasyland of her youth was
giving way to higher rents, fancier restaurants and tonier shops,
but it was still home to Public School 3, one of the city's best.
And with the Bleecker Street playground just outside the door, the
Village remained one of the most civil places in Manhattan to raise
a family. So Ms. Shea cast her eye on a third studio, this one a
whopping 500 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   There were two problems. The apartment was still occupied, by an
elderly woman who paid a two-figure, stabilized rent. The second
problem was more troublesome: the third space didn't adjoin the
others. The only direct access was through a wooden fire door and
across a tar-paper roof to another fire door.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ms. Shea urged her husband to buy the apartment
from the owner of the building, knowing that he would take much
less than if the place were vacant. They were near to closing a
deal when the tenant suddenly died _ and the price more than
doubled. Swallowing hard, Sloan ponied up $48,000. The couple now
owned three studios, for a total of $160,000, and were still living
in midtown.
</P>
<P>
   There ensued two long years, in which Ms. Shea had a second
child; worked with Robert Evans, a New York architect, to
reconfigure the 1,000-plus square feet into a space that would
afford comfort and privacy to a family of four; dealt with New
York's protracted permit procedures and the Landmarks Commission,
and through her architect hired an expediter to, as she put it,
find loopholes in the law and hang around City Hall, making sure
the paperwork got moved to the tops of the right piles.
</P>
<P>
   The expediter, John Peachy, earned his keep. He found an
obscure, Lindsay-era law stating that the total number of
apartments in tenement buildings could be decreased without need of
a new certificate of occupancy, which saved Ms. Shea an expense.
And Evans determined that a lot-line window belonging to another
building, which sat squarely in the middle of the planned hallway
that would connect apartments two and three, could be legally
covered.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shea also joined the co-op board, which helped insure that
her renovation plan would be approved. Once the permits and
permissions were in place, she hired all the craftsmen and shopped
for bargain appliances and fixtures. When money ran short, she
shrewdly used her resources, bartering most of her cache of signed,
original Longos at the height of their value to reduce her cash
outlay to roughly $70,000 from an estimate of $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1995, just in time for her elder child to begin
first grade at Public School 3, Ms. Shea and her family took up
residence. The resulting space remains a model of painstaking
planning, highlighting the architecture's best qualities, while
catering to individual and collective needs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   This is most evident in Ms. Shea's original studio, which has
been transformed into a two-bedroom children's suite and has a
ship's snug economy. Her old entrance is now a niche, containing an
antique storage cabinet used for linens. Beside it, the tiny
Pullman kitchen has been replaced by louvered closets. These are
opposite the doors to the new bedrooms; together, they form a
corridor, at the end of which is the entrance to the enlarged
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Off the corridor, the children's two bedrooms form the most
amusing and effective of the residence's spatial economies. The
original studio had three windows. Each bedroom would, of course,
receive one, but which child would get the third?
</P>
<P>
   The solution was sublimely Solomonic: the new rooms interlock
like Lego blocks before the center window, resulting in ``bunk
beds'' in which each bunk is actually in a separate room. Mica, 8,
has the lower berth in hers, while, 31 inches above, Max, 11,
sleeps in the upper in the room next door. An identical-size
portion of the original window (sealed with Plexiglas) remains at
the foot of each bed. Both spaces, which display a riot of
childhood clutter, provide roughly 50 square feet of floor space _
about the size of a dorm room, Ms. Shea noted.
</P>
<P>
   Apartment two, which is a step up from the children's suite and
in another building, serves as the couple's living
room-kitchen-dining room. The narrow kitchen, which incorporates
the old bathroom, is finished with an antique sink, which Ms. Shea
found on the Bowery, and cherry-wood-and-glass cabinets. It is open
at both ends, affording both separation and easy access from the
front door and the dining area.
</P>
<P>
   The living-dining area, though small, has three generous
windows, which overlook the garden and flood the space with
afternoon light. The area also reflects the family's priorities: no
sofa, but a substantial dining table, designed by Ms. Shea, at
which she and her children work on projects.
</P>
<P>
   For the 14-by-20-foot tar-paper roof between apartments two and
three, Evans designed a hallway that connects the spaces via their
old fire exits. It is enclosed in what Ms. Shea describes as a
little hut, raffishly clad in fire-resistant copper shingles. From
the hallway, sliding glass doors open onto a new west-facing
terrace, delightfully private and serene.
</P>
<P>
   The third apartment serves as the master suite and departs from
the others in atmosphere and architecture. With leaded-glass
windows, wide plank floors and beamed ceiling, all original, the
space sustains a literal and psychological separateness for parents
who need their privacy. Here, the kitchen was removed, and a
curved, partial wall installed to form an open walk-in
closet-dressing room. This space contains another of Ms. Shea's
droll designs for living: a pedestal sink, which taps the former
kitchen's water line. While Ms. Shea is occupied in the slightly
undersize bathroom, Sloan can shave in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ms. Shea, who still works with Longo, estimates that her
apartment is worth roughly three times its $234,000 total cost. But
the family has no plans to move on. For one thing, the feat could
not be duplicated, at least in the Village. For another, the couple
has built a post-and-beam house on 10 acres near Rhinebeck, N.Y.,
where the children can roam unrestricted.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Ms. Shea expects that as she and her family evolve,
the apartment, in one configuration or another, will always play a
part in their lives. In a tradition more usually associated with
the heartland, but no less applicable to New York, she will remain
in her first home forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
