<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     05-12 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOR PRINTERS IN COLOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the advantages of ugly, boring computers is that they
look relatively good when attached to ugly, boring peripherals,
like printers. So when Apple Computer introduced its boldly
fruit-colored line of iMac and G3 computers last year, it
brightened millions of desktops but also called attention to the
homeliness of most other peripherals in its general vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   Epson to the rescue. The company has just introduced a
fruit-colored ink-jet printer, the Color Stylus 740i, which becomes
the first _ and so far the only _ printer designed to match the
iMac and Power Macintosh G3 color schemes. The printer costs $279,
but has a $30 mail-in rebate.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the 740i is the same printer as the award-winning
740 printer that Epson introduced last year. The only changes are
cosmetic. The boring beige plastic of the 740 has been replaced by
a translucent blue and white case that matches Apple's most popular
iMac color scheme, blueberry and ice.
</P>
<P>
   For those who favor one of the iMac's current alternative colors
_ grape, strawberry, tangerine and lime _ Epson sells
color-coordinated replacement printer lids for the 740i at $15
each.
</P>
<P>
   The replacement lids will also fit on the original Epson 740
model, adding a splash of color atop the beige base. This is a nice
bonus for iMac owners who bought one of the beige 740's when it was
one of the few printer models to offer built-in support for the
iMac's Universal Serial Bus (USB) connection scheme. Now, by
flipping the lid, they can bring their 740s out of hiding.
</P>
<P>
   The Epson 740i is not only a printer of color but also a very
good color printer with a number of features that set it apart from
other ink-jet printers in its price class.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Epson printers, the 740i has a maximum print
resolution of 1,440 by 720 dots per inch, which far exceeds that of
the competition. The higher resolution makes it a good choice for
people who need a versatile printer capable of producing
plain-paper documents ranging from business letters to color
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   If printing color photos is the highest priority, however, a
better printer choice is the new Epson 750 ($299), which uses a
six-color print cartridge instead of the four-color cartridge used
by the 740 and 740i. But the 750 is slower than the 740 and is not
well suited for printing black-and-white letters or other mundane
office documents.
</P>
<P>
   If color printing is not important, the user would be better off
getting a personal laser printer, which invariably produces better
and crisper text than an ink-jet and typically prints faster, too.
</P>
<P>
   Epson achieves its high resolution in part through a technology
called micro piezo, which deposits exceptionally small droplets of
ink on the paper. The smaller the dots, the more detail can be
shown, and Epson's dots, at six picoliters each, are the smallest
in the ink-jet world.
</P>
<P>
   When it detects large areas of solid color in a photograph or
other color design that does not require sharp resolution, the
printer automatically increases the droplet size to cover the space
more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Another nice feature of the 740i is its choice of connections,
including, besides USB, traditional parallel and Macintosh serial
ports. The printer can sense which port is connected and can switch
automatically among them, which makes it particularly useful for
people who have both Windows and Mac machines in the house, or
perhaps both an older Mac and a newer iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Although most newer computers have been equipped with USB ports
for the last year, the acceptance of USB peripherals has risen
among consumers and manufacturers only recently. Apple has been
among the industry leaders in trying to establish USB as a simple
``plug and play'' replacement standard for older parallel and
serial ports.
</P>
<P>
   Apple went so far as to make USB the only connection option for
the iMac, which forced people to either buy USB-ready printers,
like the Epson, or to buy USB-to-serial adapters for older
peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   USB has a number of advantages over older serial and parallel
port technologies. It has a maximum data transfer rate of 12
megabits per second, or 1.5 megabytes per second, which is more
than 10 times the speed of parallel and serial ports but slower
than other buses like SCSI (``scuzzy'') or IEEE 1394, which Apple
calls Firewire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   As a result, USB is best suited for relatively low-speed devices
like printers, mice, keyboards, speakers, microphones and scanners,
not only because they do not need to move as much data but also
because Firewire is more expensive to build into computers and
peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   Firewire, which transfers data at speeds of 100 megabits per
second and upward, is best suited for so-called high-bandwidth
devices like digital video cameras and DVD players, which depend on
moving large amounts of data quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The practical results of USB are a reduction in chaos and
cabling on the rear end of the computer, relief from the old
problem of limited expansion slots and the ability to plug and
unplug peripherals without having to shut down the computer.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, as many as 127 different USB peripherals can be
connected to a computer's USB port, but in practice only someone
with a severe USB peripheral fetish would want to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: The Epson 740i is a nearly perfect match for the
iMac, not only in its color scheme but also in its balance of
price, performance and ease of use.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   The new Apple Powerbook G3s introduced this week are faster and
a couple of pounds lighter than the older, slower and fatter
Powerbook G3s they replace.
</P>
<P>
   The new Powerbook G3s were designed for business customers.
Prices will start at $2,499 for a 333-megahertz G3 model and $3,499
for one based on a 400-MHz chip. Both are expected in stores by May
20.
</P>
<P>
   Besides keeping their names (why can't Apple think up new names
when it significantly changes the product line?), the new Powerbook
G3s retain the sensuous curves and black skin that made previous
Powerbooks so distinctive, and the 400-MHz G3 chip is more powerful
than anything on the Windows side of the universe, desktop or
portable.
</P>
<P>
   The new models weigh six pounds with the battery and CD-ROM
drive installed, as against eight pounds for the earlier models,
and they are sleeker. Even so, they still have an impressive
14.1-inch display screen _ great for a desk, but too big for a
coach seat on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has been promising a lower-priced, lighter-weight portable
Mac for consumers and students, but it now looks like we'll have to
wait until July's Macworld trade show for more details.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Apple sorely lacks a lightweight portable that can
compete with the three- to four-pound Windows-based models that are
popular with business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Apple said the battery life of the new models was five hours,
which would be a remarkable improvement over earlier Powerbooks.
Equipped with two lithium-ion batteries, a Powerbook in theory
could run for 10 hours. Such claims are often extravagant.
</P>
<P>
   The hard disk drives are a surprisingly puny four gigabytes on
the cheaper model and six gigabytes on the expensive one. Also,
while Apple added a second USB port to the new Powerbooks, it did
not include a standard Firewire port, which is curious because it
is Apple's own technology. Sony offers Firewire on its superthin
Vaio 505TX notebook.
</P>
<P>
   Apple also released a modestly improved version of its operating
system, Mac OS 8.6. Besides bug fixes, among the incremental
advances are a better search engine for finding local hard disk or
Internet files, improved support for DVD-RAM drives and integrated
support for USB and Firewire devices. Apple asserts that OS 8.6
will also improve the battery life of Powerbook portables.
</P>
<P>
   Current users of Mac OS 8.5 can download the 35-megabyte upgrade
without charge from www.apple.com/macos, or order it on CD-ROM for
$19.95.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Apple announced that Sears, Roebuck will start selling
iMacs and iMac peripherals in more than 800 stores nationwide at
the end of the month. There is absolutely no truth to the rumor
that Sears will sell iMacs under the Kenmore brand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
