A4462 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MIDNIGHT-GAME-NYT     05-12 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MIDNIGHT-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING ART AND SOUND INTO CHILD'S PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sensuous is not a word typically applied to multimedia. On
screen, spectacle generally trumps texture and nuance. So it is a
pleasant shock to encounter Midnight Play, which has collected so
many international art prizes that its commercial doom in the
United States is almost assured.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a children's story by Kveta Pacovska, a Czech artist
and author, Midnight Play is an interactive picture book with
enough visual sophistication to satisfy any adult. If Joan Miro's
paintings met Edward Gorey's cartoons under the tent of ``Terry
Gilliam's Flying Circus,'' it would look like this.
</P>
<P>
   The story (all four sentences of it) is this: ``The theater at
night is dark and quiet. The actors are all sound asleep, until
midnight, when the moon rises above the theater. As if to say, `Is
anyone down there?' the moon looks down at the theater.
</P>
<P>
   As moonlight beams upon the stage, one by one, the actors awake
to perform all kinds of fun music, movements and tricks.'' But that
is from the box _ there are no words, written or spoken, anywhere
on the disk. As in a ballet, namely ``The Nutcracker,'' the story
is merely a premise for the visual and musical delight that
follows.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart, Midnight Play is about the qualities of drawing
and painting. After the introductory animation, you might find
yourself in a red painting whose one small figure seems content in
its multicolored box, off to the side. Swept through the box, the
cursor changes hue. Pulled across the screen, it leaves a stripe of
color in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the split-second delay, and the way the color
overlays itself with a subtle shadow, it's more like drawing with
oil pastels than with a computer paint program. The color doesn't
feel as though it's made of pure light. It feels as though it's
made of something soft, unctuous, thick and blendable.
</P>
<P>
   On this digital canvas, there is a pleasure in the gesture of
painting, in the illusion of texture, that makes the experience
into an abstract expressionist exercise whose fluid quality is
enhanced by a trance-inducing drum-and-woodwind soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Click on the moon man who appears at the edge of the painting,
and the screen fills with images of torn paper _ scraps of
stationery, graph paper, musical notebooks and labels. Drag them to
the edges and you'll hear the sharp shuffle of paper against paper
and, underneath, jingle bells ringing on the collar of a cartoon
harlequin _ the drawing buried beneath the scraps.
</P>
<P>
   Uncovered, the harlequin expands until the zigzag pattern around
his neck fills the screen and becomes yet another painting, whose
interlocking triangles correspond to the notes of a drum. When
clicked, each wedge sounds a different percussion note and changes
color, until the moon man comes along and transforms the painting's
four triangles into six colored squares, each evoking the sound of
a different art medium (charcoal, chalk or squeaky markers, paper
being crumpled) and leads to another full-screen composition.
</P>
<P>
   As you move among these images, their relationships deepen. The
multicolored squares form the waistcoat of a clown, who turns up in
a painting of a clock. From the clock, a blue circle expands into a
giant chalky moon, framing a cat on a swing in silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   Illuminated by a spotlight, the cat grins, then turns slowly,
revealing himself to be a paper cutout. The ballerina on his
reverse side dances a solo in the next painting, curtsies, then
crumples into a piece of pink paper in the patchwork sound
painting.
</P>
<P>
   The transitions are as intriguing as the images themselves. By
illustrating the links between paintings, they knit the work
together into a visual riddle _ a fractal jigsaw where the pieces
fit together in multiple ways, adjacent to one another but also
inside one another. One painting suggests a path through several
others.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't take those paths, the knowledge that they
exist creates an overlay as palpable as the illusory oil pastels.
When you've experienced the white cat's drum as a sound painting,
when you know the clown's waistcoat turns into a puzzle, you can't
look at the cat or the clown again and not see something else.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the same image a second or third or fourth time,
it's a different experience because you know where the links are.
And the links are so multidimensional and nonlinear that
understanding them becomes a delight in itself.
</P>
<P>
   Taken as a whole, the work is an exercise in nonsense logic
worthy of Lewis Carroll. But because the logic is visual, it is
accessible to even the youngest child, though like all great works
for children, Midnight Play speaks equally to adults.
</P>
<P>
   It also speaks to the possibilities of digital media. In Ms.
Pacovska's original book, the images unfold page by page. The
reader's path is one of many. In a collection of interrelated
digital images, animation weaves multiple paths through this
eccentrically rendered universe.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, this is the sort of interactive storytelling that
works only with pictures because pictures can contain one another
in ways that words cannot. Verbal stories dissipate as they branch
because they are progressive _ the only way to learn more is to go
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Visual stories deepen as they branch because they are recursive
_ you can understand something new by going back. And with images
this beautiful, the return is always a pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Midnight Play, published by Tivola; CD-ROM for Mac and Windows
95 and 98, $42. Available at the American Museum of the Moving
Image gift shop, (718) 784-4520. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
