<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, May 13, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sprawling high pressure extending from central Canada to the
Northeastern states will continue to interfere with the typical
west to east motion of weather systems. As a result a dry weather
pattern will persist Thursday over the Northeast while clouds,
showers and some thunderstorms will linger over parts of the upper
Middle West and Ohio Valley. Meanwhile, unseasonably cool air will
remain over the Northwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will be plentiful in most of the Northeast as breezes
from the north draw cool, dry air from eastern Canada, however,
patches of clouds will form over northern New England. Farther
south, a wavering front from the Ohio Valley to the Middle Atlantic
states will be the focus for clouds and scattered showers. The
heaviest rain and a few thunderstorms will occur where converging
winds lift relatively humid air from southern Ohio to the mountains
of West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered thundershowers will form from the Carolinas to the
eastern Gulf Coast as a weakening disturbance at 20,000 feet drifts
across the region. In the wake of the disturbance, sunny and warm
weather will prevail from the southern Mississippi Valley to the
eastern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled, cool weather with a mixture of clouds and sun will
prevail over the Northwest. Clouds and a few showers will dampen
the Northwest coast and some mountain slopes from the Cascades to
the northern Rockies. Most of the Southwestern will be sunny and
hot, although isolated late afternoon thunderstorms will erupt over
the Texas and Oklahoma panhandles.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Wet May
</P>
<P>
   This month is already one of the wettest Mays on record at
Bismarck, N.D. Through the first 11 days, rain totaled 5.04 inches,
leapfrogging this month into fifth place on the city's list of
wettest Mays. The average rainfall for May is about 2.2 inches. In
May, a recurrent pattern of blocking high-pressure systems over
central Canada have impeded the advance of low-pressure systems
from the Pacific. After exiting the Rockies, lows braked, allowing
protracted winds from the south ahead of them to import moisture
from the Gulf of Mexico, setting the stage for a wet early May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
