<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CALM DURING AND AFTER THE STORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release May 20)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I became a little concerned when the hail stones started
drowning out my book tape.
</P>
<P>
   The drive toward my office in Atlanta had grown progressively
more difficult as the storm front from Oklahoma moved through. Rain
fell in torrents, and the sky grew dark and ominous. Thunder boomed
so deeply it seemed to be coming out of my stereo speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers of BMWs and Mercedes were stopped under overpasses
trying to protect their car finishes from the grape-sized hail, but
also effectively blocking the road for the rest of us, whose old
minivans and outdated sedans wouldn't notice another ding here or
there.
</P>
<P>
   As I finally pulled into the parking garage, the security guard
leaned forward and said, ``Tornado just hit Lilburn. It's headed
toward Lawrenceville.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lilburn?'' I said. ``That's where I live. That's where my
children are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd give them a call,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I raced to the elevator, using my cell phone to call my husband
and trying not to panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tornado hit Lilburn,'' I told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll find out where,'' he said and hung up.
</P>
<P>
   After a quick call to Adam's elementary school and Sarah's day
care, I was reassured that they were safe and the danger had
passed. There was no one to call at our house, but it seemed of
little importance now that the children were OK. I did imagine
Star, our 11-year-old, storm-phobic German shepherd, cowering under
the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we found out a few trees were knocked down, a couple of
roofs leaked, some streets were flooded and lots of homes lost
power. But the tornados hadn't touched down, and there were no
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   From our intact, cozy living room, I watched the news reports
from Oklahoma and Kansas that night with a new sense of empathy. A
muddy 10-month-old girl had been found curled up next to a tree
after being sucked from her house by the twister's pull.
</P>
<P>
   Suffering only from a few scratches, she cried to be held as a
policeman wiped her off. Her grandmother had been killed, and her
father was in critical condition, but she was promptly reunited
with her mom.
</P>
<P>
   Adam was quiet at dinner, so I asked him what had happened at
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a twister emergency. We had to sit against the brick
wall with our heads like this,'' he said, lowering his head between
his knees, ``for an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing from his teacher that this event had lasted no more than
10 minutes, I stifled a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was anyone scared?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was,'' he said. ``I kept whispering `I hope we don't die,'
over and over again, and then I started talking about what heaven
was like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, really,'' I said, imagining that this had probably set
quite a calming tone for the other second-graders. ``And what did
you come up with?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, just that it probably has a lot of candy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How about Ms. Woods? Did she have to sit with you and put her
head down?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope. She was reading us a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that just like a second-grade teacher? A row of scared
8-year-olds, an approaching storm ... and a good book read aloud to
keep the fear at bay.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
