<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, May 13, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Here's a story I heard in
men's Sunday school last week. It was told by the teacher to
illustrate a passage from the Book of Psalms that warns against
boastfulness. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ The National Writers Workshop reminded me: It's
a privilege to write for a living. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ Rowland Nethaway's column will resume shortly.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Has state Rep. Talmadge Heflin
let his brown hair grow down to his shoulders because he's fixing
to join the World Wrestling Federation? Is the Houston Republican
sporting this very un-GOPish hairdo because he's going to begin a
new life on the Drag? Or is he wearing a hairdo that would have
gotten him thrown out of third grade because he is starting a
grunge band? It sure looks like any of those could explain why the
conservative Heflin is letting his freak flag fly. (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ A conversation with an old high school friend
about what People magazine, teenagers and Americans in general
think of when the word ``beautiful'' is used: ``Looks over
substance. And we're buying it everywhere....'' (Jefferson, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Kate White is the
editor-in-chief of Cosmopolitan magazine, a big job which means she
is in charge of instructing American women, mostly white American
women, how to do our hair, lose 10 pounds and make ourselves more
orgasmic. Not in that order, of course. She also writes books, two
so far. The title of White's newest book is 9 Secrets of Women Who
Get Everything They Want. (Minor, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-EDITORIAL _ The gabfest on youth violence which occurred at
the White House Monday was notable for the absence of two key
players: the National Rifle Association and top Hollywood
executives. Still, President Clinton used the meeting to reiterate
the gun-control package he proposed immediately after the Columbine
High School shooting massacre in Littleton on April 20. And, while
the NRA wasn't invited, the president did get support for his plan
from three major gun manufacturers and the American Shooting Sports
Council. (Daily Sentinel, Grand Junction, Colo.) MOVED.
</P>
