<P>
   TEX-SIXTIES-SYMPOSIUM _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Was the 1960's the
dawning of a new consciousness? Not the hokey ``Age of Aquarius''
of ``Hair,'' but a shift in values more subversive and pervasive,
one that opened the doors of perception and threw the very
conception of reality up for grabs? Or was it a culture collapsing
under the weight of a collective nervous breakdown? A mass ``freak
out,'' in the parlance of the age, a time when ``blowing your
mind'' was considered a good thing. For the walking wounded of the
psychedelic revolution, this was another Legacy of the Sixties. One
suspects that it's a different ``Legacy of the Sixties'' that will
be explored through this week's symposium by that name at the
University of Texas. (McNeese, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   w/SIXTIES-PANEL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ We got to wondering what the
ultimate assemblage of intellectual candlepower on the decade might
look like _ factors such as death or dementia being no deterrent.
Such as it is, here's our dream team: Moderator: Jann Wenner ,
Rolling Stone founder and poster boy for wanton boomer excess and
self-indulgence. Panel: Timothy Leary , Harvard academic and LSD
advocate; the Maharishi Mahesh Yogi , leader of transcendental
meditation movement; Mama Cass , singer, the Mamas and the Papas;
Hunter S. Thompson , gonzo journalist; Malcolm X, civil rights
activist and subject of Spike Lee bio-flick; Janis Joplin, singer;
Jimi Hendrix , musician; Lee Harvey Oswald, got some 'splaining to
do; Sly Stone, singer (absent). (Beach, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
