<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-REVIEWS-2NDTAKE-N     05-12 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-REVIEWS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
Undated: in a Dumpster.   PUBLICATION NOTES:
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THE COMPLETE NATIONAL GEOGRAPHIC'  &QL; 
(National Geographic/Mindscape; $149.95 (CD-ROM), $199.95
(DVD-ROM); Windows 3.1 and later, Macintosh 7.5 and later.)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Convey Eameses' Genius &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who were lucky enough to be in the audience for the
designer Charles Eames' 1970 Norton lectures at Harvard, where he
showed the original version of his film ``Powers of Ten'' (1968),
will never forget its impact. Moving from galaxy to proton, zooming
from the edges of the universe to the hand of a man lying on a
picnic blanket in a Chicago park and then into a carbon atom on his
hand, the film lends the viewer nothing less than a sense of the
proportions of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Eames Office, Pyramid Media and DATT Japan have produced
a CD-ROM called Powers of Ten Interactive, dedicated to expanding
on the ideas of the husband-wife design team of Charles and Ray
Eames, the film's producers. (The disk, which can be bought on line
at www.eamesoffice.com and www .powersoften.com, is based on a
second version of ``Powers of Ten,'' made in 1977.)
</P>
<P>
   Largely the work of their daughter, Lucia Dewey Eames, and
grandson, Eames Demetrios, who direct the office today, the disk is
filled with fascinating video clips of interviews with those who
worked with the Eames Office in Venice, Calif., mini-movies the
couple made as well as images and documents from their body of
work.
</P>
<P>
   An Eames revival of sorts is in progress, keynoted by a show of
the work of the Eameses, originally organized by Donald Albrecht
for the Vitra Museum in Germany and opening on May 20 at the
Library of Congress. (The show will run at New York's Cooper-Hewitt
Museum from Feb. 15 to May 15, 2000.)
</P>
<P>
   Charles Eames is best known for his furniture _ the plywood
chairs and chaise lounge he did for the Herman Miller company. But
with Ray he was also a multimedia innovator. Together, they created
some 88 short films and pioneering multiscreen and multipanel
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the Eameses was their ability to make a
difficult concept tangible: they designed perspectives and insights
as much as they designed chairs or multimedia displays. The film
``Powers of Ten,'' with its images moving closer to Earth every two
seconds by an exponential power of 10, shows this strength at work.
It is a demonstration of the scales of physics _ from star system
to atom _ that feels like a roller coaster ride.
</P>
<P>
   Navigating the ``Powers of Ten'' disk, however, proved to be a
challenge. The program slaps together portraits of thinkers on time
and space, from Descartes to Einstein, and interviews with figures
like an Australian aboriginal artist with bits of science and a
history of the Eames work. There are clips from the Norton lectures
as well as transcribed texts.
</P>
<P>
   The first warning sign of the interface difficulties comes in
the form of a bright pink label warning Windows users (the disk
runs on Mac as well) that they must set their monitors to 256
colors and must use Quicktime version 2.5. The former requires
rebooting the computer; the latter violates basic conventions of
compatibility since later versions of Quicktime won't work with the
disk. The second warning sign is the injunction to unfold a complex
set of printed instructions and set them beside the computer. A
good interface should be self-contained.
</P>
<P>
   On screen, the organizing metaphor is an odd choice: a Japanese
fish trap, a woven basket where the thematic strands of the
information are represented by colored lines. The user is most
likely to feel more like the fish than the fisherman. There are
many wonderful pieces, like a short video that takes the viewer up
a road, across a meadow and into the living room of the Eames house
in Los Angeles, a landmark of construction from off-the-shelf
industrial parts. The narrating voice is that of Ray Eames, but
nothing indicates when the clip was first shown. Several
``strands'' titled Space, Time, Tools, People, Patterns and Eames
give what few connections there are among the different pieces
found on the disk.
</P>
<P>
   This is exactly the sort of needless complexity it was the
genius of the Eameses to cut through. Charles, who died in 1977,
and Ray, who lived until 1987, might have done something
interesting with CD-ROM technology. ``Powers of Ten,'' the film, is
not interactive, but sweeps the viewer along in the hands of a
knowing guide. Such a guide could turn the material here into a
wonderful documentary, linear but exciting in its connections.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `POWERS OF TEN INTERACTIVE'  &QL; 
(Pyramid Media; $79.95; Windows 95 and 98, and Macintosh 7.1 and
later.)  &QL; 
By PHIL PATTON  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Open Window Onto Artist's Muses &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The artist Betye Saar has been enjoying a growing reputation
based on her mixed-media collages and assemblages. Through these
folk-art pastiches, Ms. Saar, who began her career in costume
design and is now represented in galleries around the world,
expresses aspects of African-American history and life.
</P>
<P>
   On this multimedia project, Ms. Saar uses the convention of the
griot, a West African storyteller, to lead the viewer down the long
and varied road of her art and life, blending her own narration and
168 pieces of her vibrantly colored art.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with an image of a ``black girl's window'' composed of
many panes, each with its own artwork and heading, like
Inspiration, Bridge of Memory and House of Dreams. The panes are
meant to be tarot cards the griot reads to tell stories.
</P>
<P>
   If you click on Secret Heart, for example, you arrive at an
arresting Saar artwork of an eagle with the word love inscribed
over it. An animated explosion dissolves the word into a beating
heart, accompanied by delicate Satie music. Move to some text, and
a narrator begins, ``My secret heart is seduced by twilight.''
Clicking on a sweetheart icon leads you to more Saar art.
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as this disk is, the artifice of the griot isn't
terribly well supported. There seem to be many voices here, many
routes to take, but not the central narrative that the griot
convention might suggest.
</P>
<P>
   I tried the House of Dreams to find a well-hidden Room of
Secrets and Sorrows. To find this room, you feel around the screen
with your mouse until the icon on the cursor changes. I had no
luck, but I stumbled upon another icon in the top right-hand corner
and landed in the Index of Images. The first artwork to pop up was
of a girl's face behind a grilled window, a nice surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the House of Dreams (determined to find the secret
room), I came upon Grandma's House, a framed assemblage of raindrop
images and swatches of faded wallpaper against a salmon-pink
backdrop, an inviting scene.
</P>
<P>
   Reverting to the window once more, I clicked on what turned out
to be the most satisfying pane of all: Inspiration. Here are the
smallest but most important treasures Digital Griot offers: a
notebook of watercolor sketchings by Ms. Saar, renderings of trips
to Paris, Brazil, Italy and South Africa. With flutey music and Ms.
Saar's soothing descriptions, the notebook reveals her sources of
ideas for things like a playground fence for a public school in
Queens. (The source was a fence in Paris.)
</P>
<P>
   What unfolds is not only a tour of exotic and gorgeous locales
but also the steps this artist takes to create and an inventory of
her simple raw material. Ms. Saar becomes so accessible through
these sketchings, you want to stay in Inspiration all day, even if
the griot is calling.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BETYE SAAR: DIGITAL GRIOT'  &QL; 
(LTI-Voyager; $29.95; Windows 3.1 and later and Macintosh 7.0 and
later.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By DULCIE LEIMBACH  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Les Line is a freelance science writer, an author and a former
editor in chief of Audubon magazine. &QL;
</P>
