<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      05-12 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOK: LOTS OF AGONY, LITTLE ECSTASY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Conn.)  (nk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phone rang, and the writer Pat Jordan was saying that the
experience of publishing his latest book, soon to be in stores, was
rather like being smote on the head with a bong starter, and while
what is happening to him was an extreme case, to be sure, it was
leaving him wobbly in the knees and the mind. All he could do, he
said, was take it with a caress of dark humor, assuring himself
that in the end authorship isn't really as horrible as book
publishing sometimes makes it.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, his experience is so unusual that it is almost at the
terminus of the terrible anxieties that can be unloaded onto an
author. But such things do happen, and a writer can be put through
a roundelay in which the work in progress can bounce like a
spaldeen from editor to editor and publisher to publisher in a way
that surely saps creative vigor.
</P>
<P>
   For Jordan it all started in 1975 with the publication of his
first book, ``A False Spring'' (Dodd, Mead), a critically acclaimed
tale of his four years as a minor league pitcher who couldn't
control his fastball, a story of sports and of coming of age in
America. Then followed eight other books, including a novel, and
magazine articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to pitch in a real game again, and I wanted to write
a sequel of `False,' '' although the two weren't really connected
in his mind, he said from his Florida home.
</P>
<P>
   So in July 1997, he wangled a pitching turn in Connecticut for
the Waterbury Spirit in the Northeast League. He was 56 years old,
and what followed were the inevitable book offers. ``Some wanted a
straight baseball book, an old guy pitching in the minors, and some
wanted to go back to a `False Spring,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the final moment Golden Books _ I then thought they only
published children's books _ called my agent, David Vigiano, and
topped the top offer by $10,000,'' he said. He got a high
five-figure advance, and he took about eight months to write ``A
Nice Tuesday: A Memoir.''
</P>
<P>
   His editor at Golden Books Family Entertainment, the company's
adult publishing group, was Robert J. Asahina, a veteran of Simon &AMP;
Schuster, where he had worked for Richard Snyder before Snyder was
discharged and took over Golden Books. ``Bob told me I could go
wherever I wanted to go in the book, that it could be as much a
memoir as a baseball book. Baseball was the thin line that held it
together,'' Jordan said. ``I had great stories. My father was a
card shark, pretty much a grifter. When I was just about finished,
I sent it to Bob. He loved it and said he was proud to publish this
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the fall of 1998. My editor is thrilled, and I'm
thrilled,'' Jordan said. His happy quivers have been few ever
since. ``All of a sudden a friend starts sending me stories from
New York about Golden Books in debt; there's an article on Snyder
that says the company's going down the tubes.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now I'm starting to panic. I'm getting punchy. This goes on
for months, and every time I call Bob he said, `No problem, no
problem, don't worry about it.' I asked my agent, should we buy the
book back and sell it to someone else, and when he presented that
to Golden Books they said, `Don't worry, we love the book, and it's
coming out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It became a publishing diptych. One panel was Golden's direness;
the other said don't worry. (Golden Books is involved in bankruptcy
proceedings.) His worst fear, he said, was that Golden would go
bankrupt just as the book was coming out and it would simply
vanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all known fears going,'' was the way the writer
described his state of mind. He started hearing that the Golden
adult division was going to be sold, which he said was a relief,
since the buyer obviously had cash, and it was clear that Golden
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   In February Asahina jumped ship and became editor in chief of
Broadway Books, a Random House division, and Jordan was assigned a
new editor, Cassandra Jones, who also had worked on his book.
Asahina said several days ago that he thought ``A Nice Tuesday'' is
``a great book that will do well.'' He continued: ``Pat is one of
those authors with a cult following.''
</P>
<P>
   In March the federal bankruptcy court approved the sale of the
adult division and its backlist and frontlist books to St. Martin's
Press, which left Jordan a bit happier but somewhat emotionally
fatigued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob, a terrific editor who would shepherd my book and who
promised me an eight-city book selling tour, is gone, but now
Cassie is telling me not to worry because she's going to go to St.
Martin's and take my book with her,'' Jordan said. ``By then it's
been printed in hard cover'' (10,000 copies), ``with Golden Books
on its spine, but it will be distributed by St. Martin's, and
Cassie will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an important moment in a book's life. A strong, engaged
editor is needed to help guide a book's marketing campaign, to stay
on top of all the events that go into publishing a book well.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones arrived for her first day's work at St. Martin's on
Monday, April 26. The following afternoon she called Jordan. He
described that insensate moment: ``She's whispering on the phone
saying, `I have something important to tell you.' I ask, `Is it
good or bad?' She's been there one day, and she whispers, `I'm
leaving St. Martin's.' My only two editors have gone off.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert B. Wallace, St. Martin's editor in chief, said he would
take over from Ms. Jones, who suddenly popped up at Regan Books, a
HarperCollins imprint, to work with Laura Yorke, who was her boss
at Golden Books and is Snyder's wife. They start their new jobs on
June 1. Asked about her one-day encampment at St. Martin's, Ms.
Jones would only say, ``It's a complicated story.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan can say the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been one thing after another, a series of bad accidents.
I won the card game and got the free ticket on the Titanic,'' he
said. ``This was a last-minute deal. I was ready to sign with
another publisher, and at 6 at night my agent said we can get
another $10,000 from Golden.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jordan, the only way Benjamin Franklin could sell
his poems was to stand on a street corner in Philadelphia ringing a
small bell. ``That's how I feel, like I'm standing on the corner
ringing a bell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't have the sang-froid of his remark. This is the
book he has been wanting to write for 25 years. It could have been
a happier experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
