<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4516 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JENNY-JONES-NYT &LR;      05-12 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JENNY-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: CURBING JENNYS AND JERRYS WITHOUT CURBING
RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Jenny Jones case is guaranteed to try the patience of
defenders of free speech. By all the rules of First Amendment
advocacy, Warner Bros., which owns ``The Jenny Jones Show,'' should
have won its case. Instead it was ordered to pay $25 million in
damages to the family of a homosexual man, Scott Amedure, who
announced during a taping of the show that he had a crush on
another guest, his friend Jonathan T. Schmitz; a few days later,
before the show was broadcast, Schmitz, who apparently is not
homosexual, shot and killed Amedure.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bizarre affair, with its tangle of personal and corporate
responsibility. Is Schmitz somehow relieved of some portion of
guilt because he was lured into an embarrassment? Do the producers
bear some blame for bringing out his fatal feelings? As if the
situation were not complicated enough, a homosexual advocacy group
has expressed concern that by blaming the show rather than the
killer, the plaintiffs were encouraging homophobia. Not, let's
hope, grounds for a class-action suit.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones gave herself and her producers an excessive benefit of
the doubt in an interview after the decision by insisting that no
one associated with the show had any responsibility for anything
untoward that its format and content might have invited or might
ever invite.
</P>
<P>
   Her practiced defense of the abysmal show, including her own
role in coaxing Amedure to reveal his graphic fantasies, was almost
enough to convict her on the spot. Yet the notion, proposed by the
plaintiff's lawyer, that a television program should have the job
of screening its guests for mental aberrations and then provide
psychiatric care is putting a slightly comical burden on the whole
shabby enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   I am left with a hunch that the jury was swept away by sympathy
for the Amedure family or just prone to socking television. In
surprising Schmitz on camera with the news of his friend's crush,
the program was being as crude as usual; that's what ``Jenny
Jones'' is all about. But finding Warner Bros. negligent for not
preventing a murder that took place three days after the taping of
a program that was never run requires a considerable leap of
judgment. And the outsize award emphatically bespeaks a disposition
to punish.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of exhibitions like those fronted by Jenny Jones, Jerry
Springer, Rikki Lake and Montel Williams, bottom feeders with a
devotion to the bottom line, see a trend here, a spreading distaste
for downscale shows, particularly the ``ambush'' encounters that
trade on exploiting people's relationships. William J. Bennett,
critic in chief, comments: ``It's a good thing for the public to
look the entertainment companies in the eye and say, `We've had
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but it is not a good thing to crack down on speech for
far-fetched reasons. If this case demonstrates anything, it is the
need for a way for ``the public'' to express itself without using
the courts or the Congress to suppress the speech of others. A more
fitting way to make Bennett's preferred point than through
government in any form is on the commercial terms that producers
and performers cannot fail to understand: a boycott of advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   For Warner Bros. and other media powers and for the tube's
Jennys and Jerrys, the ratings of such shows, which have in fact
gone down since the killing, are all that counts. So a vote by
boycott might further reduce profits without offending the
Constitution. If the shows are allowed to expire altogether, well,
that's free speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4521 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUBIN-MARKET13-COX     05-12 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBIN-MARKET13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MARKET TUMBLES, THEN RECOVERS AFTER NEWS RUBIN IS LEAVING
 &HT;    440&AMP;add. With RUBIN. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By DAVID McNAUGHTON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The stock market shrugged off news Wednesday that
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin is resigning, with the Dow Jones
Industrial Average recouping most of the 213 points it lost in
early trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow finished down 25.78 points, at 11,000.37, but the
broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index gained 0.6 percent to set a
record at 1,364. The Nasdaq composite finished up 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The initial reaction on Wall Street was attributed partly to the
uncertainty about economic policy under Rubin's deputy and
designated successor, Lawrence Summers. The news also provided an
excuse to sell for investors already worried about the market's
historically high level, said money manager Phillip M. Larkins of
Legacy South in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A third reason for the early stumble may have been due to
Rubin's relationship with Wall Street. Rubin is not only a Wall
Street alumnus _ he headed the Goldman Sachs investment banking
firm _ but like Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, is well
respected there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rubin is probably the only person who could take Greenspan's
job without upsetting the market,'' said Donald Ratajczak, director
of Georgia State University's Economic Forecasting Center in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The market's subsequent rebound came after investors had time to
reflect on three things, Larkins suggested:
</P>
<P>
   ``Rubin had indicated many times he would like to step down in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, I think people came to a conclusion that the worst
of the global turmoil is behind us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third, it's been fairly well assumed that Larry Summers would
replace him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to see him go, but the market was anticipating it,''
Larkins added.
</P>
<P>
   ``There been a lot that has happened on his watch, and most of
it has been good,'' noted economist Mark Vitner of Charlotte,
N.C.-based First Union bank. He cited the federal budget surplus
and Rubin's handling of international financial crises, first in
Mexico and then in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very protective. He was very, very determined that
financial crisis overseas would not leak back to the United
States,'' Vitner said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also noted that Summers has been the Treasury secretary's
``right-hand man. It is not likely to represent that much of a
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of viewing the news negatively, as the market did
initially, a closer look might lead to a more optimistic outlook,
Vitner said, echoing others.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may come to the conclusion that Rubin thought the world
economy is in good enough shape that he could step off the stage,''
Vitner said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Sharp declines on Wall Street are not unusual when changes are
made in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty arose in late 1994 when Rubin was picked to succeed
Lloyd Bentsen as Treasury secretary. At the time, there were
questions about how well Rubin could deal with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Even Greenspan did not enjoy an instant embrace on Wall Street.
In 1987, the stock market initially fell on the news that Paul
Volcker was stepping down as chairman of the Federal Reserve and
that Greenspan would succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street ``thought no one could replace Volcker,'' Ratajczak
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
