<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4527 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-RUSSIA-HNS &LR;      05-12 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-RUSSIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. STILL HOPES RUSSIA WILL HELP IN BALKANS DESPITE UPHEAVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is still counting on Russia to
help mediate a peace agreement with Yugoslavia despite political
upheaval in the Kremlin, U.S. officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Clinton administration officials and Russia scholars
agreed that Russian President Boris Yeltsin's surprise sacking of
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov would not imperil Russian efforts
to broker an end to the standoff between the U.S.-led North
Atlantic Treaty Organization and Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The western military alliance pressed ahead with the air
campaign against Yugoslav forces Wednesday. The onslaught began
March 24 in an effort to persuade Milosevic to accept allied
demands that ethnic Serbian forces cease murderous ethnic cleansing
of Albanian Muslims in the province of Kosovo and permit occupation
by a U.S.-led peace enforcement operation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said U.S.-Russian cooperation
is continuing despite Yeltsin's ouster of Primakov, allegedly for
failing to rescue Russia's teetering economy over the last eight
months.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials pointed to an agreement in Moscow on Wednesday
between Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and former Russian
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. The officials set up joint
U.S.-Russian working groups to map implementation of a possible
peace agreement between NATO and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said U.S. and Russian
officials were working out a precise timetable for Yugoslav troop
withdrawals from Kosovo as well as the make-up of a multi-national
military force, including U.S. and Russian troops, that would enter
Kosovo to enforce any peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott scheduled more meetings Thursday with Russian officials
to review blueprints for enforcement of a peace agreement and
civilian reconstruction of the devastated province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said the
Talbott-Chernomyrdin talks ``were not affected by the political
developments in Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin added: ``We do not discern any effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Bush, a Russia scholar at the independent Center for
Strategic and International Studies in Washington, D.C., said
Yeltsin's ouster of Primakov ``won't have much impact on
U.S.-Russian peace efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia seeks to bolster its international prestige by seizing
the role of mediator between the 19-nation western military
alliance and the Serbs in Yugoslavia, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia wants to be part of this; the United States wants
Russia to be part of this; so Russia will be a key player no matter
what the turmoil in Moscow,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   John Steinbruner, an international affairs specialist at the
Brookings Institution in Washington, D.C., predicted that the
Clinton administration would continue to rely upon Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, Rubin cited U.S.-Russian negotiations
on a peace plan that are continuing on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is not ignoring Russia's proposals _ in
fact, we're engaged in a very concrete, substantive discussion
about Russia's proposals and NATO proposals,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the U.S. apology to China for mistakenly
bombing the Chinese embassy in Belgrade is expected to ease
Beijing's resistance to an eventual effort in the U.N. Security
Council to authorize an international peace keeping force to go
into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin is reeling not only from Yeltsin's latest sacking of
a prime minister, but accelerating efforts by the
Communist-controlled Duma to impeach Yeltsin, the first
democratically-elected president of Russia in its 1,000 year
history.
</P>
<P>
   Steven R. Sestanovich, U.S. ambassador-at-large and adviser on
the former Soviet Union, told the House International Relations
Committee on Wednesday that Yeltsin's dismissal of Primakov
appeared to be motivated by the Russian president's effort to side
track the Russian Duma from voting on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma had planned to vote later this week on the five
impeachment charges leveled against Yeltsin, including launching
and then botching a war against Muslim separatists in the Russian
province of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But by sacking Primakov, Yeltsin can now submit his new prime
minister, Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin, to the Duma for
confirmation _ a process that could side track the Duma from
planned votes on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbruner said that Primakov's departure and the looming
battle over Duma confirmation of his successor only signals
deepening political instability in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changeover is dangerous _ let's hope it's not too
dangerous,'' Steinbruner said. ``Primakov was a moderate and his
ouster is a polarizing move. Let's see if the Russian political
system can keep itself together under these very dire pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Yeltsin's quest for Duma ratification of his new prime
minister will lock up Russia's political system in a prolonged
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian constitution permits the Russian president to
dissolve the Duma if the parliamentary body rejects the choice for
prime minister on three separate votes up to two months apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be political deadlock here,'' Bush said.
``We just can't even talk about political stability until this is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has fired three prime ministers in 14 months _
Chernomyrdin, who served six years; Sergei Kiriyenko, who served
less than four months and Primakov, who served eight months.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, Yeltsin's action imperils delivery of an emergency
$4.5 billion rescue package from the International Monetary Fund.
The injection of foreign assistance was designed to help Russia
stave off technical bankruptcy by making payments on the $17.5
billion in debt service due this year on a crippling foreign debt
of $143.9 billion _ $103 billion of it inherited from the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
