joins the AJC in the GAAF's lawsuit against the newspapers over the
Olympic records. (Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 6.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-WITCHES _ KILLEEN, Texas _ On the U.S. military's
largest installation , more than 40 witches, male and female,
celebrated the Rite of Spring on March 20, the day of equal
daylight and darkness that symbolizes the witches' goal of perfect
balance. Their on-post ceremony was possible because three years
ago, Fort Hood's top brass recognized Wicca as a legitimate faith,
making it the first U.S. military base to provide space for
neo-pagan rituals. It's difficult to gauge the religion's reach in
the military. Defense Department statistics on the religious
preferences of members place Wiccans under the ``other'' category,
which represents less than 2 percent of those in the armed forces.
But Pentagon officials said they believe many Wiccans are among the
28 percent who claim no preference. (Perkes, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   w/WICCA-BELIEFS (A short reader on modern-day Wiccan beliefs)
and
</P>
<P>
   WICCA-HISTORY (the necessary background to understanding the
religion.) (Perkes, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POKER _ MCCOLL, S.C._The South Carolina legislature is fighting
this week over whether to regulate video poker machines. The $2.3
billion-a-year industry is growing rapidly, sprouting in border
towns such as McColl, a small place where an estimated 15 video
poker parlors draw thousands of people, some who play for pleasure,
others who are addicted. (Burritt, Cox News Service).
</P>
