<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRUNING-PLANTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRUNING WITH A SPECIALIST'S TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MAC GRISWOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a matter of finding the tree in the tree,'' said William
Miller, 41, an arborist who started a tree business on New York's
Long Island 13 years ago and does what amounts to behavioral
analysis on each plant he prunes. ``When we first look at a tree,
we look for what to encourage, what to discourage,'' he said. ``We
want to accentuate forms, allow them to stand out. And we're also
manipulating light.''
</P>
<P>
   Trees are the biggest, oldest living creatures that people know
intimately, even if they spend hours at the zoo. Since trees are
mute, immobile and often slow growing, however, they sometimes seem
like green generalities even to their owners. Gardeners tend to
think about trees only when a limb crushes the roof of the Subaru,
branches turn brown in spring or when the hostas that were happy in
filtered light waste away in the inky shade. (In my case,
consciousness awoke when three black mulberries, trees only a bird
could love, sprouted their annual crop of disfiguring, yardlong
vertical whiskers, more properly called water sprouts, from old
cuts.)
</P>
<P>
   A good arborist can prevent or cure such problems. Most will
visit free of charge for an estimate and will offer a price for the
job, not by the hour. A work crew costs between $120 and $250 an
hour for four people, depending on experience and locality, said
Derek Vannice, who runs the certified arborists' programs at the
International Society of Arboriculture in Savoy, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   A certified arborist is one with at least three years of
experience who is licensed at the state or national level, or both.
A consulting arborist, more highly trained and a member of the
American Society of Consulting Arborists, who gets an average of
$180 an hour, is the one to call for expert witness testimony,
difficult appraisals and written reports for insurance or legal
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   You can use a certified arborist to identify species, recognize
and deal with most pests and diseases, advise what to plant,
install lightning protection on trees, remove dead specimens and
cable branches for safety and support. More earthbound tasks
include fertilizing, aerating the soil and cleaning up with a
chipper and a rake without injuring other plantings. (The last is
an end-of-the-day chore that routinely gets skimped.)
</P>
<P>
   Trees that produce yards of annual growth, like mulberries,
maples and willows, need frequent pruning in situations where
lighter shade is required. Fruit trees are pruned annually to
produce better crops. But Miller, who is not scissors-happy,
cautioned: ``If a tree is in a location to grow freely, I would
discourage pruning. But many are not. They have been pruned
incorrectly before and that's why they need it.''
</P>
<P>
   The best months for tree work are from heavy frost until the
leaves emerge, about now. But emergency pruning can be done at any
time of year. Some trees, the ``bleeders'' like silver and red
maples and pines, will run with sap when cut late in the season. It
isn't pretty, but it doesn't hurt the trees, either: it is all part
of a healing response to seal off the wound.
</P>
<P>
   The first reason to hire an arborist is to give trees the
optimum chance for long and handsome lives. ``The best way to save
a tree is to make it look good,'' said Miller of Bill Miller &AMP;
Associates in Sag Harbor, N.Y. His everyday working gear includes a
hard hat and a 17-year-old climber's saddle he made from fan belt
webbing. He has a tidy ponytail and works wearing a bow tie _
evidence that his attention to appearance does not stop at trees.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps an ideal shape in mind for each type of tree, a ``prior
vision,'' as he put it. ``But as tree people, we work with the
shape the tree is trying to go, which means moving that vision to
different circumstances for each tree,'' he said. ``Is there wind
off the ocean? Is it reaching for the sun? Is it a forest tree or a
tree growing in the open?''
</P>
<P>
   His favorite look, common in the paintings of the Hudson River
School, is the kind that comes from struggles with wind, drought
and sun. He calls it the ``krummholz look'' after the gnarled trees
that grow in the Alpine krummholz zone, where they are stunted by
high altitudes and low temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Guerino, the assistant foreman of the climber-pruners at
the New York Botanical Garden, defined the right and wrong pruning
styles. The right way is to reduce the tree's structure over all
from the outside, a process called ``crown reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McCafferty, the foreman on many of Miller's jobs, summed
up his boss' expert touch this way: ``The essence of Bill Miller is
going to the ends of the branches and cutting back _ working from
the tips in, not from the trunks out.''
</P>
<P>
   The wrong way (which requires much less climbing skill) is to
work along branches from the trunk outward. This produces what in
the trade are called ``lion's tails,'' branches with no foliage
except at the tips. Long and limber, they can whip around freely in
a storm, destabilizing the tree and making it more prone to damage.
``Limbing up,'' the standard (and often necessary) practice of
removing low limbs to admit more light to the ground and increase
air circulation, can also destabilize a tree unless the arborist
takes the overall structure into account. The widest branches
should be at the base if possible.
</P>
<P>
   One common problem in this age of instant landscape is what is
called a ``root collar.'' Nursery-grown trees are mechanically
cultivated, so inches of soil are sometimes heaped over the natural
baseline of the tree, creating a false ground line: a landscaper
can unsuspectingly replant the tree too deep. When a tree is ailing
and the trunk has that telltale telephone pole look, where the
trunk does not flare out in a natural bole at the base, an arborist
thinks, ``Root collar.'' Roots may be sprouting from the trunk
below the soil line, and will eventually strangle the tree unless
it is dug out to the right level.
</P>
<P>
   It can take years for a tree to recover from a bad pruning, and
some trees never do. Bad pruning often happens when a tree stands
on or hangs over a property line and ``grudge pruning'' has
developed, for reasons either territorial or fiscal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to have work done on a tree on your property line,
notify your neighbor,'' Miller advised, adding that both neighbors
have the legal right to prune back to the line.
</P>
<P>
   Miller does not encourage asking the neighbor to split costs,
feeling that it causes more problems than the tree itself. ``How
important is it to you that this person pays for the tree?'' he
asks his clients, ``and how much does the tree matter?''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``There's always one person who cares about the tree,
and that becomes the person who is responsible for it.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's your tree hanging over your neighbor's property, there
is no legal way to prevent him from advancing on it, chain saw
screaming. Only long-term tact and communication will work. Turning
Robert Frost's line on its head, one can only say, ``Good neighbors
make good branches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
