<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Mini-Notebooks With Ample Keyboards &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mini-notebooks that easily slip in and out of briefcases are
becoming increasingly attractive to business users and seemingly
irresistible to manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   IBM recently released its 2.6-pound Workpad Z50, a $999 personal
computer with an eight-inch screen and practically full-size
keyboard. Packed into a black, inch-thick case, the new Workpad is
hardly a Palm Pilot look-alike, its makers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers were telling us that their key needs away from
the desktop were relatively simple,'' said Bill Tsang, a market
manager for the International Business Machines Corp. ``Calendars,
contacts, to-do lists and e-mail are the top things people want.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsang said IBM customers had indicated that they felt
constricted by the relatively small screens of palm-size PCs, which
usually do not come with keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   The new Workpad Z50, which uses the Windows CE operating system,
has a keyboard that is only 5 percent smaller than a full-size one.
</P>
<P>
   Another leading maker of PCs, the Compaq Computer Corp.,
confirmed reports that it was preparing to release a lightweight
handheld computer of its own. Like IBM's handheld, Compaq's
computer will use Windows CE and is expected to cost less than
$1,000. But Compaq is not willing to disclose much about the PC,
including its name, until it is officially introduced next month.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq officials were willing to discuss how the new handheld
will feature an embedded smart-card reader. The smart card, said
Frank Varela, product manager for Compaq's handhelds, will give
users a significantly higher level of security.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Marriott &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Souped-Up Search Engine Uses a Network to Get Results &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The quest for the perfect on-line search engine got a little
more interesting recently with the release of a test version of a
new engine called Fast (www.alltheweb.com). Created by Norwegian
academics, Fast (which stands for Fast Search and Transfer) uses a
network of small Dell computers and is easier to expand to reach
more pages than other engines that operate from huge, centralized
nerve centers. The plan is to have Fast cover 200 million Web pages
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Early reviews of the new search engine were mixed. ``Over all,
Fast adds fuel to the fire that Northern Light started earlier this
year about trying to be the biggest search engine on the Web,''
said Danny Sullivan, editor of Search Engine Watch, based in
Salisbury, England. ``But size isn't everything, and right now, the
Fast demo site has a long way to go to be compelling to users.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said FAST needed to list only one page per site in its
search results (a process called clustering) and to eliminate
duplicate pages.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Sherman, a search specialist at the Mining Co.
(www.miningco.com), a human-powered search page, said Fast could
drive other search companies to expand their databases.
</P>
<P>
   According to Forrester Research of Cambridge, Mass., there are
currently 500 million to 600 million Web pages. Alta Vista
catalogues about 150 million pages, Northern Light about 120
million and Hotbot about 100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman is cautious. ``If you make the haystack bigger, the
needle is harder to find,'' he said. ``It begs the question, Is it
really important to have a Web site with Uncle Elmo's East Podunk
bowling scores?''
</P>
<P>
   Tina Kelley &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Handwritten Signatures That Can Open Digital Doors &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Silicon Valley start-up company is marketing a biometrics
system that enables you to attach your signature to digital
documents or sign your way into a secured Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The system is called Cyber-Sign, which stands for cyber
signature identifier for global network (www.cybersign.com). It
works by recording the way people provide their signatures _
recording the shape and speed of the strokes, the pen pressure and
the number of times the pen comes off the writing surface.
</P>
<P>
   To use the system, a person must first sign an input tablet
three times; the tablet is wired to a computer that is equipped
with Cyber-Sign software. The software then creates a composite
signature based on those three versions. The next time the person's
signs in, the software will compare the biometrics of the new
signature with the stored composite to verify its authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   People never sign their names exactly the same way twice, so
slight variations are taken into account. But an exact copy of the
composite version _ which might be acquired illegally _ would not
be accepted. And unlike a password or PIN, a signature cannot be
forgotten or lost.
</P>
<P>
   Cyber-Sign is now selling the system to companies like banks and
health-care institutions. If it takes off, the system and input pad
could become accessories for the home computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be used with electronic verification forms so that
paper doesn't have to be printed anymore to authenticate
yourself,'' said Chip Mesec, the company's vice president for
product marketing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Guernsey &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steamy Computer Chips Like The Touch of Refrigeration &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rush for faster desktop computers took a big leap forward
last week when the chip maker Advanced Micro Devices demonstrated a
version of its K7 computer chip running at a cool 1 gigahertz
(1,000 MHz). The computer was able to run that fast because a
special refrigeration system built by Kryotech removed most of the
extra heat that would normally have caused the computer to
malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Peeples, the chief operating officer at Kryotech, said the
new version was just a demonstration of the technology that company
currently installs in IBM mainframes and special work stations with
the Compaq Alpha chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategic plan,'' Peeples said, ``is based on the plan
that the chips that Intel and AMD are designing are getting hotter
and hotter and hotter.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer chips expend a small amount of electrical energy in
each calculation, which generates heat. Running a chip faster means
doing more calculations and that means more heat. Some of
Kryotech's systems simply keep the computer chip at room
temperature and others actively cool it to about minus 40 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Peeples said Kryotech used some of the same compressors and
coolant used in small cube-shaped refrigerators but combined them
with a proprietary design to prevent the condensation that might
short out an electrical device.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is keeping water, moisture and anything that would
condense at lower temperatures away from the chip,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Using stock parts like this means that the Kryotech cooling
system would add about $400 to $500 to the price of a desktop
system. Dropping the temperature to minus 40 degrees generally
leads to speed increases of about 25 percent to 35 percent, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Computer owners bored with their desktop machines can upgrade
them by purchasing an empty computer case with the refrigeration
equipment in place. This Kryotech product, known as the Renegade,
costs about $300 and allows computer users to speed up their own
chips _ and generally voids their warranties.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Wayner &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Family Tree Maker Software Now Has 1.5 Billion Names &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you are one of those people who has been meaning to compile
your family history since ``Roots'' was broadcast in 1977, help is
on the way. Broderbund's just-released Family Tree Maker Deluxe
Version 6.0 contains a whopping 15 CD-ROMs of genealogical
information, and the program promises access to 1.5 billion names
so you can ``Find Ancestors Guaranteed!''
</P>
<P>
   Selling for about $90, the deluxe version offers the digitized
Social Security Death Index and an International Marriage Records
Index, plus disks containing American military records, 900 years
of birth records for the United States and Europe, and 15,000
existing family trees.
</P>
<P>
   The Family Tree Maker program, which began 10 years ago as a DOS
application and has software descendants of its own, has also been
upgraded. Templates for displaying family tree information have
been added, and users can supplement their printouts with
background pictures and graphics _ a convenient way to tend to your
ancestral arboretum without leaving the house.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Biersdorfer &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
