<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANGLER-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     05-12 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGLER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTING FOR TROUT AND CATCHING A BIT OF ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at the end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For James Prosek _ prodigy fly-fisherman, skilled watercolorist,
author of two books on trout fishing (``Trout: An Illustrated
History'' and ``Joe and Me: An Education in Fishing and
Friendship'') while still a college undergraduate _ the idea was
not to have to take a summer job between his junior and senior
years at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   As he tells it in his handsome new book, ``The Complete
Angler,'' he had already proposed to the committee for the Branford
College Class of 1960 Traveling Fellowship that he fish the
headwaters of the Tigris River in eastern Turkey, the site of Eden
in Milton's ``Paradise Lost.'' The idea would be ``to glean some
great wisdom from catching trout that were descendants of those
which had witnessed man's fall from Paradise.'' But, as he writes,
the judges ``didn't bite.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he had a more serious proposal, to follow in the fishing
footsteps of Izaak Walton (1593-1683), author of ``The Compleat
Angler,'' that bible of fishing books that everybody has heard of
but few people _ not including Prosek at the time _ have actually
read. After all, he told the committee, Walton's book was the third
most frequently reprinted book in the English language, after the
actual Bible and the works of Shakespeare. It had gone through more
than 400 editions in 300 years, five within Walton's lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Once he had won the fellowship and actually read ``The Compleat
Angler,'' he was able to make a more serious case for Walton's
literary stature. Having made his fortune as a draper (he was never
Sir Izaak, despite frequent misidentifications as such), he turned
to writing and published a life of his friend John Donne, the first
of five biographies, to the art of which he introduced primary
resources and the use of dialogue, Prosek argues.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important was Walton's little book on fishing, Prosek
insists. It was published in 1653, at the height of the English
Civil War, which had caused Walton, as an Anglican persecuted by
the Puritans, to depart London, probably for his birthplace,
Stafford, in central England near the rivers Wye and Dove. Not
merely a celebration of a simpler, pastoral life, it can be read as
an allegory whose title might as well be ``The Compleat Anglican''
and whose contents promote a return to ``primitive Christianity,''
in the sense that Jesus himself and his Apostles, Galilee fishermen
and fishers of men, were primitive.
</P>
<P>
   All this Prosek conveys quite charmingly as he cruises like a
feeding trout in a heavy nsect hatch along the various trout
streams that Walton made so famous. In a particularly instructive
scene, he argues over dinner at Oxford with a group of Jesuits
dismissive of the book that in favoring the hunting of otters over
the destruction of foxes, Walton was really saying that Puritans
were more dangerous to Anglicans than Papists. The Jesuits seemed
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Prosek is less successful delivering on his promise to lay bare
the religious essence of ``The Compleat Angler.'' What his version
of Walton's message comes down to is ``be humble, be simple, be
nonconfrontational,'' which though worthy seems crashingly banal.
Far more arresting is Prosek's suspicion that Walton expressed just
a little too much humility to be credible, most likely to conceal
his lowly origins and as a way of inviting praise.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the theological shortcomings of Prosek's book hardly matter,
for he succeeds in more important respects, particularly in making
you feel what it's like to be on the loose with a fly rod in
England. It's odd that someone with such a shaky sense of grammar
can write so well, yet despite containing at least a dozen
syntactical howlers _ among them the most elaborate dangling
modifier since the opening of Norman Mailer's ``Harlot's Ghost'' _
the book's prose makes you see the special greenness of English
foliage and feel the gentle current of its streams.
</P>
<P>
   Networking with stream-owners he meets through his Yale and
fishing connections, he successfully imposes his American
sensibility on England's landscape and people. As he justifiably
boasts: ``I taught them a new cast(e) system, these strange people
in England; an Englishman couldn't have done what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he writes, ``This life and its accouterments wrapped me in
a blind contagion.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he catch any fish?
</P>
<P>
   Almost with every toss of his line, it would seem, although he
saves a detailed account of a battle for a 24-inch monster trout he
lured into casting range in the River Test by feeding it half a
cookie. But as vivid as the fish he lured are the people he
persuaded to let him fish their streams. Warm and generous, they
took him into their stately homes, made him part of their families
and thereby challenged his pretense to Waltonian simplicity. On
reflection, he came to understand Walton's conclusion that while
riches might cause ``weary days and restless nights,'' they also
``remove many fears and cares.''
</P>
<P>
   This is perhaps why Prosek concludes that ``there is no better
portrait of England and of Walton and all his ideals, there is no
better study of Walton's philosophies in vivid motion, than a man I
spent some days with on the stream in southeast England, a Sir John
Swire of Selling, in Kent just south of London.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it must be noted that not least among the attributes that
permit Sir John to be so graciously at ease in the 1,500 acres he
owns is the fact that, as his gamekeeper says, he is perhaps the
fifth richest man in England, worth about (PS)1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   As skilled at hooking big fish as he shows himself in this
beguiling volume, Prosek proves equally adept at catching big
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE COMPLETE ANGLER: A CONNECTICUT YANKEE FOLLOWS IN THE
FOOTSTEPS OF WALTON'
</P>
<P>
   By James Prosek
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 324 pages. HarperCollins. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
