<HEADER>
A4552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KRAUSE-SOFTWARE-NYTR &LR;      05-12 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRAUSE-SOFTWARE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
SOFTWARE WIZARD KAI KRAUSE TO LEAVE METACREATIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CISSY ROSS   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ Kai Krause _ self-proclaimed ``soul'' of
MetaCreations, software guru, media star and artist _ is parting
company with the once high-flying Carpinteria enterprise he helped
found.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, his odyssey the last seven years at the colorful
computer graphics software company is a reflection of how quickly
the high-tech industry changes.
</P>
<P>
   MetaCreations Corp. was among the first wave of high-tech
companies to launch a new generation of millionaire executives who,
after a lucrative public stock offering, drove snappy red Ferraris,
or in Krause's case, a white Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   They were generally younger than other CEOs and a lot more
outspoken.
</P>
<P>
   At MetaCreations, there even seemed to be a rivalry between the
two founders _ Krause, a rock star look-alike who came to the
United States from Germany originally to work in the music
industry, and John Wilczak, the former CEO who took care of the
business side.
</P>
<P>
   Just three years ago, Krause acknowledged that Wilczak ``has
done a fantastic job ... but make no mistake: This is my company. I
am the soul of this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, the company has had mounting losses.
New management is now steering the company in a new direction. But
Krause, 42, said he has other plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy,'' said Krause of the decision to leave the
company. ``There is no one to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he even generally agrees with the company's new strategy
to make software for Internet designers. But, he added, ``I don't
want to be the one driving it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the company's chief software wizard, Krause had a golden
touch. His particular talent was designing graphics programs that
the Average Joe could use which is not just for computer nerds.
</P>
<P>
   Krause helped develop a host of products emblazoned with his
name. In addition, the company sold more expensive software
packages to professional designers. He also emerged as a big draw
at high-tech conferences, teaming up with musicians like Peter
Gabriel, before large, adoring crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would waltz in there and hold a press conference for 800
people,'' recalled Krause, during an interview at his Montecito,
Calif., estate.
</P>
<P>
   And in Europe, he was even more of a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in my field they know me, but there people ask for
autographs,'' he said. ``In Europe I am the company.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, MetaCreations was ripe for its first initial public
offering, a champagne-popping affair that reaped $45 million,
giving it a pile of cash to buy other companies and grow.
</P>
<P>
   There were more heady days, as Krause hosted some of the first
chats on America Online, worked with physicist Stephen Hawkins on a
CD-ROM of ``Life in the Universe,'' and even had his own Absolut
Vodka ad in ``Wired'' magazine, created with his software.
</P>
<P>
   But the days that Krause could hole up in his estate with a
hand-picked team to design a software program were numbered. The
company had added locations in Santa Cruz, Calif., Princeton, N.J.,
and Ireland, and held weekly meetings via videoconferencing.
</P>
<P>
   Krause also said the thrill of making updated versions of his
old products is gone.
</P>
<P>
   While some people in the company grumbled he wasn't turning out
enough new work, Krause reached out in other directions, showing
his own images in museums and meeting with European officials to
discuss how they might tap more high-tech sources.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, Wilczak, the former chief executive officer,
left the company, and Gary Lauer, a former Silicon Graphics
executive, is repositioning the company as a ``creative Web''
enterprise, helping designers make eye-catching, three-dimensional
images for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company still sells Kai's consumer software tools, but the
new lineup features the company's name prominently _ MetaFlash and
MetaStream. The former is a computerized flash attachment for a
digital camera that reconstructs pictures into three-dimensional
images. The latter helps stream 3-D images over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company is still losing money. It lost $19.8 million in
1998, on the heels of a $8.2 million loss in 1997. In July the
company cut 35 jobs at the corporate headquarters here, leaving
about 90 workers.
</P>
<P>
   On April 13, the company issued a lengthy press release about
the hiring of a new senior vice president, adding near the end of
it, a one-sentence statement that Krause was leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Krause said the company plans a more formal statement, but the
brief notice was to meet its requirements as a public company to
reveal executive changes.
</P>
<P>
   He will consult with the company for a year but he's looking
forward to other plans, such as establishing a think tank in a
castle overlooking the Rhine River.
</P>
<P>
   Krause said German officials have asked him to consider the
possibility, and while he can't talk about it now in detail, he
envisions bringing more minds together than just software
designers.
</P>
<P>
   While MetaCreations' public stock offering helped make Krause a
wealthy man, he said he was already a millionaire at 26 as a result
of establishing another software company before MetaCreations.
</P>
<P>
   Krause's total MetaCreations' compensation last year, including
salary, bonuses and other benefit payments, was $268,000, according
to the company's latest proxy statement, but a lot of his net worth
is stock ownership and options.
</P>
<P>
   Krause is the third largest MetaCreations shareholder with
489,945 shares, worth about $3.4 million. (The largest shareholder
is Bert Kolde, vice chairman of the Portland Trail Blazers
basketball team and the Oregon Arena Corp.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Krause received an option to purchase 300,000 shares of
stock for the discounted price of $6.44.
</P>
<P>
   In sharp contrast to MetaCreations founders, Krause and Wilczak,
Gary Lauer, the current CEO, is low profile. He repeatedly has
declined to be interviewed since taking over in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Lauer can turn around the losses at MetaCreations with
the new Internet strategy remains to be seen. The company still has
$43.8 million in capital to help bolster its prospects.
</P>
<P>
   What seems more certain, however, is that MetaCreations, without
Krause, will be less colorful.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Rosa Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of
the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
