<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4554 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAIR11-COX     05-12 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIR11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No curl up and dye here: Beloved beauty salon still a favorite
spot for regulars to get a shampoo and a set
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Irene McCoy is rolling hair this morning, as she has
for 53 years. She parts Alaerisse Leitch's long, iron-gray strands
with a black comb, smooths them, pulls them tight, then twirls them
around a purple curler. She picks up the metal clip Leitch is
holding and secures the roller, the comb tucked in her hand all the
while. Then it's on to the next one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now these will make you hair real tight,'' Irene says, holding
up green, fuzzy curlers. ``That's why we use them on the little old
elderly ones. These,'' she holds up a purple roller, ``will make it
loose, loose, loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them likes it tight, some of them likes it loose. I
like it tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Time has changed many things at Mozelle's Hair Care, the
venerable beauty salon on 14th Street across from Georgia Tech. A
well-known Atlanta shop in the days when women went in for weekly
shampoos, sets and sessions under huge hair dryers _ think Aunt Bee
in ``The Andy Griffith Show'' _ the shop has aged, and so have its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it endures.
</P>
<P>
   More than five decades after the shop opened, women still come
here for regular shampoos and sets, partly because many other
salons no longer provide those services. Like 84-year-old Irene,
most of them are senior citizens who like their hair rolled tight.
Irene, an energetic woman with ash-blond hair, tan cigarette pants
and bronze pumps, tells customers that she's 62. Irene ran the shop
for decades with Inez Rikard, who eventually turned it over to
Irene. A few years ago Irene gave the business to Mozelle Collins,
who's worked there 40 years herself. Irene didn't stop doing hair,
though. She walks to work or gets a customer to drive her and opens
the shop soon after 6 a.m., four days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of mornings, I feel like, God, I just can't make it, I'm
tired. But then I get up, and I feel like a young girl,'' says
Irene, the daughter of a Church of God preacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has helped me. I haven't missed a day of work. I had
breast cancer, had two operations. I came straight back to work.
I've never laid out of work a day, have I?'' she says, looking over
at three women waiting their turn at the shampoo sink. They nod
their heads in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never a day I don't come up the street praising
Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   The shop is Irene's therapy, Mozelle says. The customers agree
with that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go to any cafeteria now and a lot of the elderly women
will come up and hug my neck and say `Irene, I love you,' '' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   She's shampooing Dorothy Moore of Atlanta, a customer for four
decades, talking up a storm while running her fingers vigorously
through the scalp.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful with the little elderly ones,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   The customers let this talk of elderly women go only so far.
Every time Irene brings up their ages, they fire right back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm younger than you. I'm 81,'' Moore says. ``You're 84.''
</P>
<P>
   It's getting harder to find places that do hair the way they do
it here, a time-consuming process of shampooing, rolling up,
sitting under a stationary dryer and combing out. Few people want
to spend close to two hours every week at a beauty salon; few
operators are willing to put the time into that kind of style when
they could do highlights and a blow-dry in the same amount of time
_ 90 minutes _ for at least triple the money. At Mozelle's, a
shampoo and set runs $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have people lined out the door,'' says Mozelle, a
trim woman in jeans with close-cropped hair. She's a master at
styling and teasing, her customers say. Even with a phone glued to
her ear, she rapidly combs out wet hair and twirls it into a
roller.
</P>
<P>
   Mozelle, 58, started here as an 18-year-old shampoo girl working
her way through business school.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be 14 or 16 of us working on top of each
other,'' Mozelle says. ``Business is dropping because a lot of my
customers have died or moved to nursing homes. I work four days a
week now. Used to work six.''
</P>
<P>
   On the three days a week she's not at her salon, Mozelle styles
hair at a nursing home. She's thinking of going back to school to
study computers, so she can get a job that doesn't keep her on her
feet all day.
</P>
<P>
   She's not sure what she would do with the shop. Maybe, like
Irene did, she will pass it on to someone else. Maybe by then,
there will be another stylist working at the salon who can take it
over.
</P>
<P>
   Irene reminisces about how beautiful the shop was when she gave
it to Mozelle, and what a nice big sign _ Irene McCoy's, it said _
hung outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irene, that sign was ate up with rust,'' Mozelle says.
</P>
<P>
   The shop shows the effects of time, too. One air-conditioning
unit is missing its grille, and the white laminate is cracking on
some cabinets. Plastic covers protect the backs of blue-and-green
floral chairs. A couple of chairs have the poles for stationary
dryers sticking out of their backs, but the hoods are no longer
there. The Coke machine stocks glass bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Carters, Maddoxes and a Talmadge used to come to the shop, Irene
says. Lester Maddox built a ramp so he could wheel in his wife, the
late Virginia Maddox, a customer for at least 50 years. He'd get
her a bottle of Coke to sip while she sat under the hair dryer she
liked best.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many of the customers drink Diet Cokes while they sit
under the enveloping dryers, in the front of the store by the big
window facing 14th Street. One reads the paper, one looks out at
the 18-wheelers stopped at a traffic light and another rests, her
eyes shut.
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the salon, where the dyeing and curling goes on,
it's livelier. Customers joke with Mozelle, who's divorced, about
finding a man. (Irene's a widow. Her husband, James, worked at the
salon too.)
</P>
<P>
   Irene and Mozelle keep bantering about their relationship,
drawing smiles from the customers. ``We just like an old married
couple,'' Mozelle says as she applies chestnut dye to a woman's
hair. ``One of us start a sentence, the other finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Irene on Mozelle: ``I get along with her good, and I love her,
but I don't know if it goes the other way or not. She's precious.''
</P>
<P>
   Irene fired Mozelle once for spending half a day at the Varsity
drive-in. But there were still customers in the shop when Mozelle
got back, and Irene told her she could finish out the rest of the
day. So much for being fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both just mean as the devil,'' Mozelle says. ``We're
trying to outdo each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The two of them never stop working. Irene laments how few people
are there this morning, but the six customers keep the two stylists
busy. Mozelle moves swiftly from woman to woman, dyeing hair here,
trimming there, often balancing the phone on her shoulder. Irene
shampoos and works with the rollers.
</P>
<P>
   Irene is removing curlers from Cecelia Saul's hair. It's
pulling, and Saul, a 70-something from Sandy Springs, winces.
Florence Gagliardi, 66, of Dunwoody, removes her own curlers, then
stands up and gently works the rest out of Saul's hair.
</P>
<P>
   As the morning's first group of customers finishes up, a new set
waits by the window. Louise Scheurer, 84, of Buckhead wants her
hair done before a doctor's appointment that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about Mozelle, no matter how busy she gets, she
never slights anybody,'' Scheurer says. ``I've been coming here 30
or 40 years, I don't know how long. Irene's business never goes
down, does it?''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
