<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHES OF THREE CHINESE EMBASSY VICTIMS ARRIVE HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The ashes of the three Chinese killed by NATO bombs in
Belgrade returned to China on Wednesday, carried off the airplane
by relatives who were wearing white flowers of mourning in a sad
procession shown repeatedly on national television.
</P>
<P>
   Popular anger over the bombing of the Chinese Embassy on Friday
was laced with grief. The authorities, seeking to re-channel the
outrage of the last four days, halted the raucous demonstrations
that had immobilized the American Embassy and urged students and
others to concentrate on their own work to help make China
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, the streets around the embassy were quiet,
sealed off by hundreds of police officers. Ambassador James Sasser
emerged from the American Embassy for the first time since
Saturday. Sasser and several staff members walked out the front
door, picking their way through shards of glass and heaps of
plastic bottles and chunks of concrete that protesters had heaved
against the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to give our Chinese friends a day of grief,
and then we can move on and discuss with them how to mend this
situation,'' Sasser said before visiting the families of American
diplomats who have remained all week in nearby foreigners'
compounds. Sasser later returned to work and then left to sleep
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the week, a skeletal staff will be working in
the embassy and consulate buildings, mainly to clean up. The
embassy remains officially closed.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy flags were hung at half-staff in respect for the
dead. The gesture was shown on Chinese television, another sign
that the authorities were hoping to cool passions as they sought
deeper remorse and explanations from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   China flew all flags at half-staff as the entire political
leadership paid homage to the dead, who are described as heroes and
martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   Killed in the bombing, which the United States says was caused
by a misidentification of the embassy building, were Shao Yunhuan,
47, a reporter for the official New China News Agency; Xu Xinghu,
31, a reporter for The Guangming Daily newspaper; and Xu's wife,
Zhu Ying, 27, an art director for the paper's advertising
department.
</P>
<P>
   Also brought home on the plane Wednesday were six seriously
wounded people and 20 who were sleeping in the embassy when it was
hit by at least three bombs.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shao's 19-year-old son carried her ashes. Her husband, a
diplomat, was one of the severely wounded taken off in a stretcher.
Ms. Zhu's father carried two boxes of ashes, those of his daughter
and of his son-in-law, past weeping relatives, politicians and
hundreds of representatives of social groups.
</P>
<P>
   The procession was officially met by Vice President Hu Jintao,
who was shown on television greeting a bandaged man by saying, ``On
behalf of the Central Committee of the Communist Party I welcome
you home and offer you sincere condolences.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, private memorial services were held at The
Guangming Daily and at the news agency.
</P>
<P>
   The television news Wednesday night showed President Jiang
Zemin, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji and Li Peng, who ranks second in
the Communist Party and heads the parliament, as well as three
other top party leaders, visiting the services before they began,
shaking hands with grieving relatives. Alone among the leaders, the
usually unflappable Zhu was visibly sobbing.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Wednesday there was no announcement of any larger
public service, an event that some feared might set off demands for
additional demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese and American governments have barely begun to assess
how far the bombing, and the convulsion of anti-Americanism here,
have damaged relations.
</P>
<P>
   In view of the political climate in Washington, China may be
badly mistaken if it tries to use guilt over the bombing to extract
deep concessions on vital issues. Chinese leaders have made it
clear that they still seek American trade, investment and
technology and that they still want to join the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But even before the bombing, powerful industries here had
attacked the prime minister for making too many market-opening
concessions in negotiations with Washington over the trade
organization, putting those talks under a cloud. China's leaders
surely know that after the outburst this week Congress will be in
no mood to grant special economic favors.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has it ever been likely that the Clinton administration
could give China the absolute pledge that it seeks that Taiwan will
not be included in a hypothetical missile-defense system.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese, for their part, have suspended talks on arms
proliferation and other issues that are of deep concern to the
United States, and it is unclear what it will take to get them back
to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the two countries have many shared economic interests,
and neither wants to see a costly new Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the embassy Wednesday morning, Sasser said he hoped that
``we'll move back in the direction of trying to establish a
productive and stable relationship between our two countries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
