<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      05-12 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRISTS TAKE A BATTERING IN PRE-ELECTION POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In the hard-driving politics of Israel, if you stand
in the middle of the road, you just get run over.
</P>
<P>
   This political axiom appears to be holding true once again as
Israel heads into the final days of a campaign for prime minister,
and the newly formed Center Party has dropped precipitously in
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago when the Center Party announced it would be
headed by rising star Yitzhak Mordechai, the choice of was heralded
with fanfare and great promise.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai was dramatically fired by Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in January after standing up to Netanyahu on what
Mordechai saw as strategic blunders in the peace process. Then he
took the reins of the new center party.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said some of Israel's heaviest hitters, disillusioned
conservatives and disaffected liberals, were creating a unique
middle ground to save the peace process and to heal Israel's deep
ethnic divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, an immigrant from Kurdistan, was seen as an ethnic
outsider who could bring into the fold the ``Sephardic,'' or
Eastern, Jews, deeply alienated by what they saw as an elitist,
liberal Labor Party. This center party, analysts said, was
different than others that had failed in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai and his Center Party list of candidates for parliament
have plummeted in recent polls to only 7 percent. This is down from
February polls that said Mordechai would win by 2 percent in a
direct race between him and Netanyahu. Mordechai's campaign slogan,
now embarassingly boastful, is ``Only Mordechai Can Win Big.''
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai has so far stubornly clung to a promise that he would
stay in the race until the end. But members of his own party have
urged him to throw his support behind Labor Party candidate Ehud
Barak, a move which some analysts say could clinch a victory over
Netanyahu for Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai is expected to deliver a major policy speech in
Jerusalem Thursday in which some observers believe he may decide to
pull out of the race in the interest of defeating Netanyahu and
salvaging important parliamentary and Cabinet posts for the Center
Party.
</P>
<P>
   In the May 17 general election, voters decide among the five
candidates for prime minister. Barak is beating Netanyahu by as
much as 9 percent, according to polls released Wednesday. But Barak
is not expected to win the required absolute majority and so the
two leading contenders, almost certainly Barak and Netanyahu, will
then compete in a runoff June 1.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Ma'ariv Wednesday urged Mordechai to drop out,
arguing that if he does so Barak can take the election in the first
round. The center is now watching polls that show Barak winning in
the second round, but as many analysts said that is a risky game.
Netanyahu is a consummate survivor and could come back strong in
the runoff.
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake, the center has already begun to fracture.
The Center Party's founder, Tel Aviv Mayor Roni Milo, has been
quoted in newspapers as sniping at Mordechai for letting his ego
get in the way of a potential Barak victory. And the third pillar
of the center, the popular and dashing former general and Netanyahu
chief of staff, Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, has publicly stood by
Mordechai but is privately applying pressure to pull out.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers said this kind of splitting along the seams
was true of a long list of center parties dating back to the 1955
party known as RAFI, a Hebrew acronym for Workers of Israel,
through to the 1977 DASH party, or Democratic Movement for Change,
and straight through to the 1996 Third Way Party. All of them began
with some of Israel's best and brightest politicians, but fell
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The centrifugal force of Israeli politics is so strong that
the center can't hold,'' said David Clayman, Jerusalem
representative of the American Jewish Congress and a longtime
political observer.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering DASH from 1977, he said, ``I was a true believer, a
fighter against the corrupt Labor Party and the far right Likud.
They won 16 seats, but it fell apart within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you couldn't take this center party seriously if
you've been around for a long time. They began imploding this week,
and that seemed inevitable right from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics point out that the trio of Mordechai, Milo, and
Shahak have vastly different visions on the two central issues: the
peace process and Israel's religious-secular divide.
</P>
<P>
   Avraham Diskin, a political scientist at Hebrew University and
an activist in the centrist Third Way party in 1996, said, ``Roni
Milo wanted a centrist party to put forth his antireligious views.
But in same party you have Mordechai kissing the conservative
rabbis. So which is it? Will they be about secular Tel Aviv culture
or kissing rabbis? They never made up their mind, and that is why
they fell apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1812EDT &QL; 
