A4565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-STEPASHIN-NYT &LR;      05-12 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-STEPASHIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTING PRIME MINISTER KNOWN AS POLITICALLY SAVVY YELTSIN LOYALIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-POLITICS, RUSSIA-ASSESS, RUSSIA-DIPLO) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Sergei Vadimovich Stepashin, President Boris Yeltsin's
fourth choice as prime minister in less than a year, is best known
for loyalty to his boss. But that description does not do him
justice.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin has made an entire career in the Russian internal
security apparatus. At one point or another, he has run Yeltsin's
counterintelligence bureau, directed the Federal Security Service,
which was the domestic successor to the KGB, and helped carry out
the president's disastrous war against rebels in the Chechnya
region of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, he worked simultaneously as deputy prime minister
and interior minister, and Yeltsin handed him three highly
sensitive political tasks: curbing extremism, attacking government
corruption and policing the next national elections for Parliament
and the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Given that employment history, it is perhaps surprising that
Stepashin is given good marks by many liberal, pro-democracy
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a reasonable, very cautious politician, and, I must say,
a literate politician,'' said Otto Latsis, a veteran political
commentator for the newspaper Novy Izvestia. ``Without a doubt,
he's also a democratic politician, and this is how he's made his
career _ by being one of the democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin has so far kept relatively clean hands in some
legendarily dirty businesses. Some democrats questioned his
involvement with the early stages of the Chechen War. But others
give him points for resigning from the Federal Security Service and
Yeltsin's Security Council in 1995 after Chechen rebels stunned the
government by raiding a Russian town outside Chechnya and taking
scores of hostages at a hospital. At the same time, Stepashin won
credit for directing the Russian forces that eventually freed the
hostages after negotiations with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Stepashin's Interior Ministry has skated at the edge
of a nasty battle between Yeltsin and the nation's prosecutor
general, Yuri Skuratov, who is investigating corruption in
Yeltsin's inner circle. Stepashin has supported Yeltsin's efforts
to dismiss Skuratov, and Skuratov has complained that state
security agencies under Stepashin's control have been less than
helpful in his inquiry. But Skuratov has stopped short of accusing
the ministry of directly interfering in his work.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, a young-looking 47, was born on the Soviet Union's
Pacific coast in 1952. At age 21, he graduated from an Interior
Ministry military-political school, then lectured at the school and
worked in the Supreme Soviet of the Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Yeltsin appointed him chief of security for the St.
Petersburg region and then deputy security minister of Russia. By
1994 he was head of Russian counterintelligence and director of the
Federal Security Service. Yeltsin named him justice minister in
1997, and interior minister in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin speaks English and holds a law degree. He is married
and has one child.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
