</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-BROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN SCORED THE REAL ROUNDHOUSE RIGHTS IN GAME 2 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Like a rose in a minefield, Curtis Brown's performance
was overshadowed by the gore surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   But were it not for his handiwork _ the subtle jabs between
roundhouses _ the Sabres would not have won Sunday's slugfest in
Boston, 3-1, and hence, would not have returned to Marine Midland
Arena for Wednesday night's game locked in a 1-1 tie with the
Bruins in their best-of-seven Eastern Conference semifinal
skirmish.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's first-period assist and second-period goal, both
artistic counterpoints amid the mayhem, staked Buffalo to a 2-0
lead and for all intents and purposes decked the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Just 1:51 into the game, he helped provide Buffalo with crucial
momentum when he outfought P.J. Axelsson for the puck behind the
Boston net and sent a pass into the slot that glanced off goalie
Byron Dafoe's stick and out to center Michael Peca, who converted a
fadeaway wrist shot to the far side.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our strengths is going down deep, setting up our goals
off the forecheck as opposed to the rush,'' said Brown. ``This was
one of those plays. I just threw it out to Pecks, who did a real
good job of getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5:57 of the second period came the coup de grace. Taking an
Alexei Zhitnik feed at the Boston goal line to the right of the net
during a Buffalo five-on-three, Brown deftly threaded the puck
through a pinhole opening between the pads of Dafoe, who was
preoccupied with the traffic on the other side of the crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was taking the pass away across the front of the net,''
said Brown. ``He did a good job of deterring the pass, and I
couldn't get it across. I saw a little opening in his pads. The
puck had to have eyes to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's playoff performance _ which began with the goal that won
the first-round opener and triggered Buffalo's four-game sweep of
favored Ottawa _ may be an eye-opener to the uninitiated. But it's
comfortingly familiar to coach Lindy Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's giving us in the playoffs basically what he's been giving
us all year,'' said Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   During the year, the 23-year-old center-left wing gave the
Sabres 16 goals. That total would have been far gaudier if Brown
hadn't endured a 23-game drought at the end of the season. With
40-goal scorer Miroslav Satan sidelined by an ankle injury since
Game 3 against the Senators, it was imperative that Brown shed his
slump to help provide the offense by committee Ruff is relying on
to compensate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had different guys step up,'' said Ruff. ``He's one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   During his extended exile in the scoring desert, Brown did not
despair, partly because he saw encouraging signs, partly because
that's his newfound outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never did bother me,'' he said. ``Goal scoring is finicky.
I counted it up and I hit six posts during that streak. If all
those had gone in, I'd have been the hottest guy in the league. I
was still getting the chances. If I wasn't getting the chances,
then I'd be worried.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't consider that attitude a rationalization; it is, in
fact, his revised blueprint for life. Brown has focused on
accentuating the positive for the past year and a half, since he
underwent a spiritual . . . well, you couldn't really call it a
rebirth or awakening. Perhaps realization would be the term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the Lord and the Bible,'' he said. ``If you
believe in those things, you have to go that way. Growing up, I
always believed. But if you believe, you have to take that special
leap. I wasn't a strong Christian. I wasn't sure how to be. I had
to get the right information.''
</P>
<P>
   It was provided by former Bruins goalie John Blue, an old friend
of Brown's who works with the ministry Champions. Brown asked the
questions; Blue provided the answers. It was a gradual process,
Brown emphasizes. There was no precipitating trauma, no epiphany.
And it wasn't that Brown was a confirmed hedonist before he hooked
up with Blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look around,'' said Brown, ``from the world's eyes, I
wasn't doing anything wrong. What some people don't understand is
that you don't have to hit rock bottom'' before making a religious
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   His latent awareness hasn't transformed Brown on the ice, though
Ruff said, tongue-in-cheek, ``Maybe he's taken his play to a higher
level.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, no overhaul was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to go out and play hard,'' said Brown. ``That's
what I've always done. You just have to have your eyes focused on
the right thing. I'm probably more focused now because people are
waiting for you to step out of line. I'm not perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   He was close enough in Game 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
