<HEADER>
A4569 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-TICKETS13-CO     05-12 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-TICKETS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Countdown to `Menace:' Fans snap up tickets
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Yoda once instructed, ``Do. Or do not. There is no
try.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Michael Clayton and Susan Cauthen's credo, too, as
tickets for ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' sold at a
light-speed clip Wednesday at more than a dozen metro Atlanta movie
megaplexes.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton, 29, and Cauthen, 28, both of Tallapoosa, were first in
line at General Cinemas' Parkway Pointe to snare 24 tickets to the
first showing of ``Phantom Menace'' on opening day Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got the fever and I'm impatient,'' said Clayton, who'd
arrived with Cauthen at Parkway Pointe at 11 p.m. Tuesday and
camped out on a makeshift sofa _ an opened sleeping bag draped over
two folding beach chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Theater managers reported a steady stream of walk-up buyers,
many grabbing the limit of 12 tickets each. Some 50 minutes into
the sale, Parkway Pointe general manager Larry Smith estimated up
to 500 tickets had been sold at his theater to walk-up customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is far beyond our expectations,'' Smith said. ``There are
now 100 people still out there and we expect them to continue
trickling in all day.''
</P>
<P>
   The line of walk-up buyers outside AMC's Colonial 18 in
Lawrenceville (GA.) snaked around the building about 9 a.m., some
six hours before the start of sales. In less than two hours of
ticket sales by walk-up and phone, Colonial had sold out several of
its first-day evening shows and the midnight debut, said AMC
spokesman Joe Brock.
</P>
<P>
   Long lines of a couple hundred ticket buyers were also seen at
AMC's North DeKalb Mall 16 and at United Artists Perimeter Pointe.
</P>
<P>
   In Cobb County, roughly 200 fans had lined up outside Parkway
Pointe by 3 p.m. They had spent hours playing ``Star Wars'' Trivial
Pursuit and Monopoly. Some who'd waited all night had concocted a
sing-song chant: ``We've been chain-smoking since 1 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 13 theaters _ less than half of those that will
ultimately play ``Phantom Menace'' on about 60 screens _ began
ticket sales Wednesday. The other theaters will start sales either
Monday or opening day.
</P>
<P>
   For the latest on ``Phantom Menace,'' including a list of local
theaters and showtimes:
</P>
<P>
   &QR; www.accessatlanta.com/FEATURES/movies/starwars/
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
