</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-YOUNGSTOWN-ROBIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNGSTOWN NAMES UMASS ASSISTANT HEAD COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   University of Massachusetts men's basketball assistant coach
John Robic was named head coach at Youngstown State Tuesday,
becoming the fourth assistant under former UMass mentor John
Calipari to be named a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Robic, 35, who agreed to a four-year deal at Youngstown,
replaces Dan Peters, who left for an assistant's job at Cincinnati.
Robic had been an assistant at UMass for 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Robic is the last of the three assistants from the Minutemen's
first NCAA tournament team under Calipari (1991-92) to become a
head coach. The others were Bill Bayno, now head coach at
Nevada-Las Vegas, and current UMass head coach Bruiser Flint.
Wright State coach Ed Schilling was a UMass assistant during the
1995-96 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the right time for me to do this,'' said Robic, a Western
Pennsylvania native. ``I didn't set a timetable for myself. It's
the first job I ever applied for and I like the fit. I still have
ties in Pittsburgh and Ohio, so I like the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what everybody says, there's a good nucleus of players
coming back. The Mid-Continent Conference gets one team in the NCAA
tournament every year, so we will build all our momentum for the
conference tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Robic said he will enter the program with two scholarships to
give. There is talk that former Minuteman guard Rafael Cruz, who
decided to leave UMass but has not signed on with another program,
might join Robic. ``I have to be careful about how I speak about
him,'' said Robic. ``I'd like to (sign Cruz). The decision is up to
him, but I think it would be a good fit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
