<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATIVE-AMERICAN-ART-2     05-12 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIVE-AMERICAN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS MAKING PEACE WITH MUSEUMS TO CELEBRATE THEIR CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Walls have come down at the Heard Museum, and not just
the 8-foot-high berm that long separated the white stucco arches of
this celebrated American Indian arts center from an emerging
downtown arts district along Central Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter divisions that have set American Indians against
non-Indian custodians of their culture since the arrival of the
white man are crumbling too.
</P>
<P>
   Resplendent after an $18 million expansion that nearly doubled
its exhibition and programming space, the 70-year-old Heard, with
its staff of Indian experts, is pointing the way to a new
nationwide spirit of collaboration between Indians and the museums
housing their patrimony and sometimes the remains of their
ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Indian museum has changed its face, and the Heard
was a factor in changing it,'' said John Lewis, executive director
of the Inter-Tribal Council of Arizona, which just moved into new
quarters across the street from the Heard to be closer to it.
</P>
<P>
   From small collections to the Smithsonian Institution, Indian
museums are increasingly opening their doors to a contemporary
Indian presence, a development that Lewis, a Pima and Mojave
Indian, attributes more to an evolving sensitivity than to Indian
demands. While tribes remain skeptical about how decisions are made
at the Heard and other museums, he said, a spirit of partnership is
growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took them a long time to wake up,'' said Margaret
Archuleta, the Heard's curator of fine art, who is of Pueblo and
Hispanic heritage and credits the Heard with breaking new ground.
</P>
<P>
   Still, tribal art continues to be stolen, and clashes still
erupt, as they did last year when Sotheby's auctioned Indian art
despite tribal protests about ceremonial items identified as
sacred. Nineteen objects were later withdrawn from sale and three
others were bought for repatriation to their tribes. The planned
American Indian museum on the Mall in Washington has been stalled
over contractual disagreements between the Smithsonian Institution
and the project's original architect, Douglas Cardinal, an Indian
of Blackfoot ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   But most ownership disputes are attributable to confusion, said
Elizabeth Sackler, daughter of the noted antiquities collector
Arthur Sackler and founder and president of the American Indian
Ritual Object Repatriation Foundation in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   And despite widespread fears that a recent federal law would
provoke a spate of contests over Indian holdings in museums, issues
are generally being resolved amicably, officials say. In some
cases, museum directors and Indian leaders say, tribes have even
agreed that museums are better custodians of their art and
artifacts than they could be, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   The Heard's showcases still brim with Zuni turquoise and silver,
Navajo blankets, Pima baskets, Santa Clara blackware, Apache and
Kiowa beadwork and the late Sen. Barry Goldwater's incomparable
collection of Hopi katsina dolls. (Tribal experts now favor that
spelling to the old kachina.)
</P>
<P>
   But alongside the antiquities that a wealthy couple, Dwight and
Maie Bartlett Heard, began acquiring shortly after their move from
Chicago in 1895 are new galleries of starkly modern art by
contemporary Indian painters and sculptors, work that Joe Baker, a
Delaware Indian beader and artist at the Heard, says belies the
image of American Indians as ``a people of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heard, which unveiled its bold new footprint and
50,000-square-foot expansion in February, has taken other steps to
build what its director, Martin Sullivan, calls ``a living museum,
where the objects aren't just there for esthetics but also to tell
stories about people.''
</P>
<P>
   Indians hold senior staff positions and an Indian might
conceivably end up as the new director after Sullivan leaves in
June. Indian artists serve residencies at the museum and offer
demonstrations in the galleries, Indian high school students are
trained as guides, and the staff consults regularly with Indian
artists and elders who, in many cases, are as nearby as the
19-member Inter-Tribal Council across the street.
</P>
<P>
   The Heard has also taken a leading role in complying with the
Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act of 1990,
which requires museums to conduct an inventory of their human
remains, funerary objects, sacred items and cultural patrimony and
take steps to return them. It has made at least eight such returns,
one of the largest museum repatriations proportionate to its
collection, to nearby tribes of Hopi, Navajo, Gila River
Pima-Maricopa, Salt River Pima-Maricopa and Crow. One returned urn
contained ashes from a cremation. The museum received an
unidentified Indian skull in the mail one day and turned it over to
the Southern Cheyenne for burial.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, who helped draw up the act's guidelines, was just
elected chairman of a seven-member repatriation panel that mediates
disputes, including one over whether the 9,300-year-old Kennewick
man, whose remains were found in 1996 in the Columbia River Basin
in Oregon, could be classified as Indian or Caucasoid. Sullivan is
also chairman of the Cultural Property Advisory Committee working
with federal agencies to curb the illegal trade in Indian art and
antiques worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to redefine our relationship in terms of
partnerships and an emphasis on living culture,'' said Sullivan,
who came here nine years ago from the New York State Museum in
Albany, N.Y., where he helped resolve a dispute with the Onondaga
Nation of Indians over 12 wampum belts that the museum had been
holding, some since 1898. The beaded belts, encompassing a kind of
historical charter of the tribes, were returned to the Iroquois.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the Heard has shifted emphasis from acquiring
and displaying artifacts to explaining them in what Sullivan calls
``a first-person voice.'' Significantly, in 1989 it shortened its
name from the Heard Museum of Anthropology and Primitive Art, to
the Heard Museum, with the tag line ``of Native Cultures and Art.''
The evolution is more than a fad, he maintained. ``The PC label has
been stuck on this, but I don't want to do it because it's PC. It's
just good practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the 1950s, the Heard added Indian trustees, and
Indians joined the staff in the '60s. In the '80s, under Sullivan's
predecessor, Michael Fox, the Heard took the initiative in
developing federal standards leading to the repatriation statute,
working with Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., then vice chairman of the
Select Committee on Indian Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian presence brought new sensitivities. Ms. Archuleta,
the Heard's fine art curator, said that at her behest the museum
recently took down a painting of a Hopi religious ceremony in a
kiva, or underground chamber, which is off limits to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a native staff person,'' she said, ``I make sure that
people don't see something that's not kosher.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar case was the museum's adoption of katsina instead of
kachina as its spelling for the traditional spirit dolls given to
girls of the Hopi tribe. An unwritten language, Hopi has no
transcribed form of the word, and the new spelling is said to
better reflect its pronunciation. Because of the religious nature
of the dolls, the museum consulted tribal experts and engaged
another Indian, Alph Secakuku, to write an accompanying book before
putting on a special exhibition several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Archuleta said she was proudest of the Heard's hospitality
to contemporary Indian painters and sculptors who find mainstream
museums inhospitable.
</P>
<P>
   One gallery has a show called ``Art in Two Worlds,'' a
compilation of provocative works by Indians that were exhibited in
seven invitational shows from 1983 to 1997. A second gallery is
also devoted to contemporary fine arts.
</P>
<P>
   In March the museum also started an artist-in-residence program,
sponsoring an Indian artist, Michael Kabotie Lomawywesa, a Hopi
jeweler and painter, to work and mingle with visitors. He and Joe
Baker, the Delaware Indian artist who heads the program, have works
in a new book, ``North American Indian Jewelry and Adornment'' by
Lois Sherr Dubin, published by Harry N. Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   (Similarly, in April the Eiteljorg Museum of American Indians
and Western Art in Indianapolis, Ind., announced $100,000 in
fellowships to Indian artists over the next 10 years.)
</P>
<P>
   The modern exhibits often startle visitors emerging from
galleries of traditional baskets, blankets, jewelry and katsina
dolls, but it is part of the museum's purpose to juxtapose the old
and new for maximum effect, said Rebecca Murray, the communications
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the museum is far better known for its historical
collection. Mrs. Heard, the daughter of a leading Chicago hardware
wholesaler whose business grew into today's Tru Value Hardware
chain, resettled in Phoenix with her husband after a lung ailment
sent him in search of a warm, dry climate. They became major
landowners, ranchers, developers and philanthropists, and in 1912
Heard became a publisher as well, buying The Arizona Republican
(which changed its name to The Arizona Republic in 1930). Their
estate, Casa Blanca, off Central Avenue, drew many prominent
guests, including President Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   The Heards also became avid collectors of Indian artifacts, some
of them excavated from Hohokum Indian ruins on property they bought
in Phoenix. They also sought other indigenous art on expeditions to
Egypt and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   In 1929 they built a Spanish Colonial Revival building on their
property to house their growing art collection. Heard died months
before its completion. His wife opened it to the public, although
it was unmarked and visitors had to ring the bell at Casa Blanca to
gain entry. Mrs. Heard died in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The collection grew quickly, often through purchases from Fred
Harvey Co., which began as a provider of food and lodging to the
railroads and became one of the largest dealers in Indian art and
handicrafts. In 1971 Harvey's great-grandson gave the museum about
4,000 items.
</P>
<P>
   The latest expansion of the museum has taken it to eight times
its original size, including a remodeled 400-seat auditorium and a
cafe featuring Indian specialties like Hopi corn stew and Navajo
tortilla wraps. The museum can now display about 10 percent of its
permanent collection at one time, twice as much as before. Casa
Blanca was demolished years ago, the site now occupied by a
high-rise apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   With the demolition of the berm that concealed the museum from
the main thoroughfare, Central Avenue, and the realignment of the
main portal, the Heard has gained a bolder downtown presence. The
nearby Phoenix Art Museum and the Phoenix Theater help anchor what
Sullivan, the Heard's director, says the city is striving to
develop as an arts district. In a city notorious for sprawl, ``We
need something that makes cultural life more pedestrian-friendly,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever direction the expanded Heard takes from here, Sullivan
will not be around to see it. He is leaving in June to become
director of Historic St. Mary's, a restoration of the 17th-century
capital of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   He said the list of potential successors includes Indian
curators at other museums as well as non-Indians. Being an Indian,
he said, ``is not a condition, but it would be wonderful.'' The
Heard would not be the first museum headed by an Indian; the
director of the National Museum of the American Indian at the
Smithsonian is W. Richard West Jr., a Southern Cheyenne.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis of the Inter-Tribal Council is watching the search process
closely. ``We have a great interest,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
