<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-2     05-12 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES(1,190&AMP;TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CLOSE ISRAELI RACE, RUSSIAN VOTERS HOLD THE KEY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ There is a pointed joke making the rounds in Israel:
Why don't campaign commercials have subtitles in Amharic, the
language of the Ethiopian immigrants here?
</P>
<P>
   Because, the answer goes, Russians don't read Amharic.
</P>
<P>
   As the Israeli campaign plunges into its final frenzied days
before the election on Monday, Russian immigrants are the wild card
in a close race for prime minister between Ehud Barak, the
front-runner, and Benjamin Netanyahu, the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say the immigrant community, whose support
for Barak has climbed from 15 to 40 percent in a few months, will
determine the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are this vote,'' Robert Satloff, executive director of
the Washington Institute for Near East Policy, said in an interview
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Transforming this country socially, culturally and politically,
some 740,000 immigrants from the former Soviet Union have arrived
in Israel since 1989. Unlike native Israelis, they are not born
into political parties. Although many favor the right because they
take a hard line toward conceding territory to the Palestinians,
they are, with 14 percent of the electorate, a swing vote.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 they favored Yitzhak Rabin, the Labor Party leader at
the time, and four years later they swung to the right for
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the real center,'' said Yuli Edelstein, the immigration
minister and chairman of the campaign for the Yisrael B'Aliya
party, led by Natan Sharansky. ``You will see that in this race. We
are the ones who are going to break the stalemates in this
society.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, the candidates have fixated on the
Russians above all other groups in this diverse society, sometimes
in transparently gimmicky ways.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky, who is squat and bald, has been courted with such
passion that he jokes about the Israelis finally coming to see his
inner self _ ``a handsome tall man with thick curly hair.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Both Barak and Netanyahu have faced off in chess matches against
Sharansky, a masterly player, even though he has repeatedly said he
will make no endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, the Labor Party leader, lost his match but won the photo
opportunity. Netanyahu, who hates to lose, sweated it out to a
draw, guided by chess advisers and a computer chess program.
</P>
<P>
   But peering over the prime minister's shoulders was Tommy Lapid,
a chess expert who happens to be running for parliament at the head
of an aggressively anti-religious party. So the publicity stunt,
whatever effect it had on the Russians, briefly infuriated some of
Netanyahu's supporters in the ultra-Orthodox world.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Russians and ultra-Orthodox Sephardic Jews made for uneasy
bedfellows in Netanyahu's coalition government, and tensions
between them have been exacerbated during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At one particularly low moment, Eli Suissa, the interior
minister, referred to Russians in a campaign ad for his
ultra-Orthodox Shas Party as ``counterfeiters, con men and call
girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanoch Smith, one of the more cautious pollsters, said
Netanyahu, who can probably count on 60 percent of the Russian
voters, needs 70 percent to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs that to compensate for his losses in other parts of
the population, and it doesn't look he is getting it,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Sweating out an uphill battle to hold onto his post, Netanyahu,
who leads the Likud Party, trails Barak by 6 to 8 percent in the
opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the campaign, Netanyahu bled supporters to a
new rightist party, headed by Benny Begin, his former science
minister; to the Center Party, headed by his former defense
minister, Yitzhak Mordechai; and to Barak himself.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who fled directly to Barak _ rather than defecting
first to Mordechai, then, as his campaign failed, to the Labor
Party leader _ were Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three months ago he was nonexistent in our community,''
Edelstein said of Barak. ``If he had asked me, I would have said,
`Ehud, you're a nice guy, but you don't stand a chance.' But he
invested time, lots of time, on the ground, and it has paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that Russians, who think contrarianism is a foundation
of democracy, like to vote out the incumbent. But Barak's campaign
has left no stone unturned in the Russian immigrant community.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Yisrael B'Aliya held a picnic for party workers.
No candidates for prime minister were invited; it was not to be a
politicized event.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak, a highly decorated former general, was not deterred.
He sent an unmarked car _ no loudspeakers, no bumper stickers _ to
deliver hundreds of carnations, a present that could not be
refused.
</P>
<P>
   On Russian-language radio, Barak's campaign has filled more than
two hours of advertising time in the last two weeks with
biographical tidbits about the candidate and testimonials from his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians don't have roots here, so they don't know his
story,'' said Sasha Klein, a filmmaker and Russian media adviser to
Barak. ``Our main strategy was not to go anti-Bibi, because
Russians like to vote against somebody anyway. It was to explain
Ehud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians don't like generals, but they do like heroes.
Also, he plays the piano, which is very important, and he can talk
about Rachmaninoff, Pushkin, Dostoyevsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Renata Koeppel, who arrived four years ago from Ukraine, said
she listened carefully to the Russian-language election programs. A
resident of the port town of Ashkelon, she feels she is ``not very
strong in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time they told me vote for Netanyahu, and I did,'' she
said, referring to other Russian-speaking immigrants. ``This time,
I'm just like other Israelis. I want things to change, to be
better. I'm influenced by the commercials. I think Barak.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With the advantages of an incumbent, Netanyahu has been able to
use his office to appeal to the immigrants. Last week he declared
that May 9, the date that Russia celebrates the Allied victory in
World War II, would become an Israeli holiday _ with its own
postage stamp. He also announced new benefits for the 40,000
Russian war veterans in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this spring, with an eye to the Russian vote, he and
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon traveled to Russia, giving interviews
to Russian television stations that are broadcast on cable in
Israel. It was probably the first time in Israeli political history
that politicians tried to appeal to ethnic voters by returning to
their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Raised in an authoritarian state with vast territories, many
Russian immigrants instinctively prefer Netanyahu's image as a
strong leader reluctant to turn over land to the Palestinians and
tough enough to resist the pressures of American diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They carry the conceptual baggage of a totalitarian regime,''
said Roman Bronfman, a Yisrael B'Aliya member of parliament. ``And
Netanyahu represents a more totalitarian approach, with his message
of a `strong leader for a strong nation.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, new immigrants, many of whom are workers and
small-business owners, are among the hardest hit by the rising
unemployment and stagnant economic growth of the last two years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To make inroads into what he has called ``our most precious
electorate,'' Barak has been able to take advantage of new
alliances, forged after November's municipal elections, between
newly elected Labor Party mayors and Yisrael B'Aliya
representatives who were named deputy mayors in several key cities,
including Haifa, Rishon Lezion and Akko.
</P>
<P>
   Barak also benefits from the Likud Party's weaknesses on the
ground. On Election Day, when getting out the vote will be crucial,
the Labor Party's superior organization and close relationships
with the Russians in several cities could be critical.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky's party burst onto the political scene in 1996, when
it captured seven seats in parliament. Before that victory, the
Russians played a far less visible role on the public stage. Their
votes were sought at election time, but the stakes were low:
Individuals were promised bus rides to the polling stations or
sometimes apartments that never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Russians are demanding, and the candidates are
promising, key ministries in the next government. In particular,
Sharansky has set his party's sights on the interior ministry,
which has belonged to Shas for years.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has indicated that he is more than willing to give Yisrael
B'Aliya that powerful post, breaking Shas' control of an agency
that has refused to register many Russian immigrants as Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stigma against Russians has been so bad in the last few
years that I've considered changing my name from Sasha to Shmuel,''
Klein said. ``It's interesting that we're so important in this
campaign, given that our place in the society is so
controversial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
