A4600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ADVISORY-NYT &LR;      05-12 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a page of coverage on the firing of
Russia's Prime Minister:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Ledeall: Ever the master of surprise,
President Boris N. Yeltsin abruptly fires Prime Minister Evgeni M.
Primakov, pushing Russia to the brink of a crisis that could
endanger its fragile political stability. Yeltsin's latest
government dismissal _ his third in 15 months _ came as the Russian
parliament Thursday opened what promises to be a stormy and
emotional debate on his impeachement, with the outcome of a vote
scheduled for Saturday increasingly uncertain. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ A news analysis: Encircled by his
leftist opponents and reduced almost to a cipher in opinion polls,
clearly ill and on the cusp of impeachment, Boris Yeltsin rose
Wednesday to sack a government he had never embraced and position
himself once more as Russias savior. But after eight years of
dramatic sackings, the question this time was who Yeltsin was
trying to save: democratic Russia, or himself? By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-STEPASHIN (Moscow) _ A profile: Sergei Vadimovich
Stepashin, President Boris Yeltsin's fourth choice as prime
minister in less than a year, is best known for loyalty to his
boss. But that description does not do him justice. Stepashin has
made an entire career in the Russian internal security apparatus.
At one point or another, he has run Yeltsin's counterintelligence
bureau, directed the Federal Security Service, which was the
domestic successor to the KGB, and helped carry out the president's
disastrous war against rebels in the Chechnya region of Russia. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DIPLO (Washington) _ Having invested considerable capital
in nurturing Russia as a partner in a Kosovo settlement, the
turmoil in Russia today appeared to represent another impediment to
the Clinton administration's hopes of finding a diplomatic end to
the war. After dismissing his government today, President Yeltsin
threatened to withdraw from negotiations on Kosovo, saying that
Moscow's proposals were being repeatedly ignored. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 or (212) 556-1927: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Gary McCardell.
</P>
<P>
   The evening supervisor is Pat Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   The late-night supervisor is Sam Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS: &LR;
</P>
