<HEADER>
A4603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DENVER-GALLERY-ART-NY     05-12 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENVER-GALLERY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER'S TIRELESS PATRONS ENJOY THE ART OF CITY LIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Costa Rica)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ELIZABETH HEILMAN BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Here amid the hubbub of Lower Downtown's hip eateries
and art galleries, two-and-a-half blocks from Coors Field baseball
stadium and just blocks from the daytime hangout for many of
Denver's transients, Frederick and Jan Mayer bought a parking lot
and built the first private single-family residence to rise in this
old industrial district in a century.
</P>
<P>
   Since September, when the Mayers moved from suburb to city, they
have been lauded as urban pioneers, the most visible homesteaders
in a surge of billion-dollar loft and condominium development. In a
decade this formerly seamy neighborhood bordering the freight yards
has become Denver's second most expensive neighborhood (after
Cherry Creek).
</P>
<P>
   Mayer, once named Wildcatter of the Year, made a fortune in oil
in the early 1980s and then sold his oilrigs the year before the
oil market collapsed. He is currently a director of the American
Petroleum Institute and chairman of the board of Captiva Resources,
an oil and gas exploration and production company.
</P>
<P>
   But to locals, Mayer, 71, and his wife, who is the president of
the American Federation of Arts, are mostly known as extraordinary
art patrons. For more than 40 years they have been avid collectors,
and they were among the first to explore and understand the value
of Costa Rican pre-Columbian art and Spanish colonial art from
Mexico. In 1994 the Mayers gave the majority of their pre-Columbian
collection to the Denver Art Museum, which displays more than 2,000
of those objects on the fourth floor. The Mayers' gesture is
particularly taken to heart in a rapidly changing city where half
public school children are Hispanic. The Art Museum makes a
showcase of its pre-Columbian collection, one of the nation's best.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Mayers were included in a listing of the world's
200 top collectors in Art News magazine. Their colonial Latin
American art was specifically cited, but they also collect stamps,
coins, American watercolors, 20th-century American prints and Greek
antiquities.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976 Mayer has served three times as the Denver Art
Museum's board chairman, and he is currently chairman of the
governing board of the Yale University Art Gallery in New Haven. At
both institutions he has been a proponent of ``deaccessioning,'' or
selling artworks that are stored in basements and never seen.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer the Mayers commissioned Mope, a 19-year-old graffiti
artist who frequents the Spot, a nearby nighttime center for
at-risk adolescents, to paint a mural on the plywood construction
walkway in front of their emerging town house. The 50-foot mural
was Mope's interpretation of the future of Lower Downtown, or LoDo:
in dark canyons there were flying city buses, a traffic cop
resembling an alien, and Coors Field on a precarious precipice.
</P>
<P>
   Weary of his daily predawn commute from Cherry Hills Village, a
south Denver suburb, Mr. and Mrs. Mayer began experimenting with
urban living a few years ago, staying at the historic Oxford Hotel
or borrowing a-friend-of-a-friend's loft for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mayer said: ``I was so bored walking my dog in our old
neighborhood. Every time you walk outside here it is so exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayer added: ``Our old house was built for raising three
children. We had nine collections and we had no place to show them.
We were at a stage in our lives where we thought it would be fun to
live with these things rather than keep storing them.''
</P>
<P>
   After a two-year national search, the Mayers asked Jim Olson of
Olson Sundberg Architects of Seattle to oversee the design of a
town house that could be used for displaying the Mayers' art and
for entertaining. Olson has created a contemporary three-story town
house with a courtyard on three city lots; the building is at once
a museum, a home and a response to its urban context.
</P>
<P>
   Olson explained: ``I think the Mayers really wanted to create a
Florentine-like town house in a modern setting. Everywhere I looked
in Colorado I saw red brick, red rock, red sandstone, and the
Mayers like red. In their collection of Spanish colonial art red is
frequently used, and the contemporary art they chose has a lot of
red in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The town house, which cost about $3 million to build, is called
the Red House because of its dark red facade, made of a base of
precast concrete, stucco and sandstone from India. To a passerby,
the main door of the Mayers' ``cloister'' is as imposing as the
Wizard's portal in the ``Wizard of Oz.'' A sliding security gate
opens to reveal an 11-foot door of hammered bronze, coated and
waxed with a Chinese brown patina. The entry hall extends the
atmosphere of subtle grandeur. Ceilings rise to 15 feet, and an
inner courtyard has a gently flowing fountain, strawberry plants
and a white grid sculpture by Sol LeWitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like a little private paradise, a private world
within the public world,'' Olson said. ``With the layout of the
house turning in on a courtyard, the courtyard becomes their little
secret garden.''
</P>
<P>
   The rooftop sculpture garden is visible to gallerygoers and bar
hoppers below, with a grand aluminum and steel-wire sculpture by
Kenneth Snelson jutting into the skyscape like a child's toy placed
just out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Olson said that the town house's main floor ``is about
community, about people, events,'' adding: ``The Mayers have
something going on in those spaces all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The second floor I call the nest,'' he said. ``It is really
their private space and more about creature comforts. The top floor
we call the sanctuary, and it is about spiritual, universal things.
You can look out at the mountains, look at the stars. It is about
going out beyond the immediate community.''
</P>
<P>
   On what was once skid row the Mayers have built a live-in
gallery that they frequently open to benefit some of their favorite
local institutions. Patrons of the Denver Art Museum have enjoyed
cocktails surrounded by the works of Milton Avery, Hans Hofmann,
John Singer Sargent and George Innes. In January the Mayers held a
party for supporters of the Spot, the nearby youth center.
</P>
<P>
   David DeForest-Stalls, director of the Spot, said, ``What's
wonderful is that the Mayers have reached out for the benefit of
groups like ours. The Mayers enjoy the diversity around them. They
celebrate that diversity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
