</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS URGE PRESIDENT TO HIRE MORE BORDER AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: CORRECTS word in 6th graf; it's recruits, not conscripts)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional lawmakers, led by Texas Reps. Lamar
Smith, a Republican, and Sylvestre Reyes, a Democrat, attacked
President Clinton Wednesday for failing to comply with a law
requiring him to achieve a net gain of 1,000 Border Patrol agents
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter signed by 47 other House members and 12 senators _
including Republicans Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas
and Democrats Dianne Feinstein and Barbara Boxer of California _
Smith and Reyes accused the president of surrendering to
traffickers of illegal drugs and immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cross-border drug smuggling and alien smuggling continue to
cost uncounted lives and damages each year ... yet there is no
indication that your border strategy recognizes the emergency
situation,'' Smith and Reyes wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference announcing the letter, Rep. Henry Bonilla,
R-Texas, whose district has the longest border in the country with
Mexico, said Congress is ``tired of excuses from the president.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Congress passed and the president signed the law
mandating the net addition of 1,000 new Border Patrol agents each
year through 2001. The idea was to double the force from 5,000 to
10,000 over five years.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, Border Patrol Chief Gus de la Vina told a Senate
immigration subcommittee that while his agency will hire 1,000 to
1,200 Border Patrol recruits during this fiscal year, the net
addition to the force will be only 200 to 400 agents because of a
high attrition rate of about 800 a year. The 1999 fiscal year ends
Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner
Doris Meissner announced earlier this year that the administration
will hire about 800 agents in fiscal 2000 but will have no net gain
in the number of agents. The INS is the Border Patrol's parent
agency.
</P>
<P>
   INS spokeswoman Nicole Chulick said the INS asked the
administration for a net gain of 1,000 agents in fiscal 2000 but
the White House dropped the request from its proposed budget.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said the president was ``breaking the law'' by using the
money Congress had allocated for more Border Patrol agents for
other parts of his budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to make the president comply with the will of the
people,'' he said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Other senators who signed the letter were Spencer Abraham,
R-Mich.; Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M.; Pete Domenici, R-N.M.; Slade
Gorton, R-Wash.; James Inhofe, R-Okla.; Jon Kyl, R-Ariz.; John
McCain, R-Ariz., and Olympia Snowe, R-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Chulick said the agency's failure to achieve the net gain of
1,000 agents this year results from a tight labor market. ``Like
most employers, we have had a hard time finding qualified
applicants,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., said the INS has done almost
nothing to recruit new agents, adding that other branches of
government, such as the military, have managed to attract
applicants despite similar problems.
</P>
<P>
   Chulick also said that the White House budget office chose not
to add any new agents in 2000 because it was afraid that the agency
had too many inexperienced agents working in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration felt some time was needed to give the
thousands of agents hired during the past few years a chance to
gain the experience they need to do their jobs correctly,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Reyes, a former Border Patrol sector chief in El Paso,
said several sectors along the border were staffed primarily by
``very experienced'' agents who would have little trouble training
the new personnel.
</P>
<P>
   To help the Border Patrol attract more applicants, six
southwestern senators, including Hutchison and Gramm, have proposed
legislation to raise base pay from $33,000 to $41,000 for agents
who successfully complete their probationary year. INS estimates
that the pay raise would cost $40 million to $50 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bill is designed to redress some of the pay
inequity that currently hampers the agency. The Border Patrol's
loss of about 10 percent of its 8,000-agent workforce stems in part
from the fact that agents move on to higher-paying jobs within the
INS or in other federal law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Other senators sponsoring the bill are Bingaman, Domenici, Kyl
and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
