<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4620 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFTERLIFE-FILM-2TAKES     05-12 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFTERLIFE-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSE ONE MEMORY TO TAKE WITH YOU, HE ASKS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 B. Ruby Rich is the author of ``Chick Flicks: Theories and Memories
of the Feminist Film Movement.''  
 By B. RUBY RICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The afterlife. Today it rivals Vancouver as one of the most
popular movie locations. Ever since Ernst Lubitsch sent a departed
mortal hurtling back to earth in ``Heaven Can Wait,'' heaven itself
has been fascinating Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   When Wim Wenders sent his angels earthward in ``Wings of
Desire,'' a trend was reborn. What with John Travolta, Robin
Williams and Brad Pitt all going celestial, heaven has never been
more hip. Heaven help future historians tempted to interpret this
era's spiritual proclivities from a close reading of recent movies.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, they _ and we _ now have some help from the Japanese
director Hirokazu Kore-eda. His new film, ``After Life'' redefines
our notions of what comes next in a charming fable that's as
profound as it is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Life'' asks its audience to imagine that humans, after
death, enter a sort of purgatory that resembles nothing so much as
an aging school building or government depository. There, a helpful
staff informs them one by one of their status, offers sympathy
(``So sorry for your loss'') and then provides assistance with the
task that confronts them: to choose one memory out of their entire
life to take with them for all eternity. Everything else about
their life on earth will be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Already, ``After Life'' has proved its ability to cast a spell
over its audiences, in part perhaps because of its unusual
combination of fiction and fact. What memory would you take with
you? What would you pick?
</P>
<P>
   In France, the film took the grand prize at the Nantes Festival.
In Argentina, where memory and amnesia regularly duke it out for
ownership of history, it struck a particular chord, picking up a
distributor instantly and winning awards for both Best Picture and
Best Screenplay at the Buenos Aires Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   At festival screenings in the United States, it has acquired
cult status. Even at the Sundance Film Festival, ``After Life''
managed to transfix its notoriously untransfixable crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Kore-eda seems to believe that the very essence of humanity is
memory, if his recent career is any indication. In ``Maborosi,''
the feature debut that brought him international fame in 1995, a
young widow is haunted by grief over her husband's suicide even
after a new marriage offers happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Kore-eda's contemplative regard for this character and the
exquisite gravity with which he invested his images of her memory
and sorrow captured audiences and awards.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Maborosi'' told only part of the story. Kore-eda made
eight documentaries, before and after ``Maborosi,'' exploring the
lives of Japan's outsiders, victims and renegades. The most recent,
``Without Memory,'' tracks the astonishing case of a man who was
the victim of a botched medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   He was left with his memories intact but stripped of the ability
to form new ones. In effect, he remains condemned to an eternal
present excavated by continual forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   The third of this trio of memory pictures, ``After Life''
synthesizes the lessons learned along the way. Whereas ``Maborosi''
was a polished fictional construct, this time Kore-eda decided to
retain his documentary style and process. He investigated the
nature of memory by visiting temples, parks and homes for the
elderly to pose his question: If they could carry only one memory
with them after death, which would they choose?
</P>
<P>
   After 6 months and 500 interviews, Kore-eda came to an
unexpected realization. ``Originally, I intended to `steal' their
stories,'' he said through a translator at the Sundance festival.
``But I was so compelled by the authenticity of those stories, and
their facial expressions as they told them, that I realized I could
never beat them and just decided to cast them as they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The director's willingness to learn from his own process made
``After Life'' a hybrid in which scripted actors and nonactors are
filmed in the act of actually retrieving their own memories.
Kore-eda eschewed big-movie techniques in favor of natural light,
16-mm cameras and extended shots to avoid unsettling his
nonprofessionals. It's risky , but it pays off brilliantly.
</P>
<P>
   One woman particularly captivates audiences. She recalls a
joyous girlhood moment, when her favorite brother bought her a red
dress to wear to a special dance and then showed her off to his
friends afterward. All these years later, she's still intoxicated
by the memory. Other characters recall other memories: the taste of
rice balls cooked in a bamboo grove, the feel of a breeze blowing
in the window of a tram, the sight of clouds in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Life'' is hardly a sober film, however. Its purgatory
staff, for instance, assists the dead by filming their memories,
for their reliving as well as for the collection they solemnly call
``the archives.''
</P>
<P>
   In one hilarious scene, they even order up a lifetime of
surveillance videos for a man who needs a refresher course on his
own life. A documentary filmmaker all his life, Kore-eda cannot
resist poking fun at the film production process itself while
gently considering the relationship between a film crew and its
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is memory and its unreliability, its vagaries and
gaps, that fascinate Kore-eda. ``I developed this idea, at a young
age, that you forget everything, and then you die,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He forged such beliefs in his own childhood, living with a
grandfather who started losing his lucidity, then developed
dementia and senility as Kore-eda grew up. Alzheimer's had not yet
been named.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, he no longer recognized our faces,'' Kore-eda
recalled. ``Finally, he could not recognize his own.'' Haunted by
this experience, Kore-eda imagined an alternative: ``What if you
got to hold onto one thing?'' Out of this idea, first conceived 10
years ago, Kore-eda developed ``After Life.''
</P>
<P>
   His film continually challenges viewers to sift and sort
artifice from authenticity, yet the line between the fictional and
the factual can never be entirely clarified. One character, for
example, recalls her life of prostitution, then chooses to remember
a tender encounter that was the exception to the rule. Or was it?
</P>
<P>
   Her story changes drastically as she gets deeper into its
telling. Surely she must be an actress with a script? Not quite.
Now an actress, she was once a well-known Japanese porn star.
</P>
<P>
   Kore-eda noted how the film's production was shaped by unusual
transformations: ``There was a script, but the actors on the set
were so moved by the stories of the real people that they began to
insert their own lives into the script. She wanted to tell this
story.'' It's not surprising to learn that the film's title was
suggested by a Japanese vaudeville expression meaning ``neither
here nor there.''
</P>
<P>
   If audiences wonder to what extent ``After Life'' reflects
Japanese attitudes toward life after death, Kore-eda avoids
grandiose claims. Asked about whether the bells heard tolling in
``After Life'' are a reference to the 108 chimes at Japanese New
Year for the 108 sins of man, he said, ``I think I just like the
sound of bells.''
</P>
<P>
   He happily discusses a range of Japanese faiths: that there is a
heaven and hell; that there is nothing after death, according to
scientific empiricism; that the divide between the brain and the
objective world is no longer clear. He links this last view to
Oliver Sacks' study ``A Leg to Stand On,'' which has had a great
influence in promoting the idea of mind-body connection in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In Kore-eda's films, what stands out most is the compassion with
which characters are imbued. This is a director who is infinitely
patient, prepared to wait and to listen. Perhaps this capacity for
empathy was forged in childhood, when his family experienced
Japan's postwar economic boom of the 1960s within the confines of a
poor Tokyo neighborhood called Gumma.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family was very poor,'' he said. ``We drew our water from a
well, our bath was heated with firewood. It was hardly evocative of
metropolitan Tokyo life.''
</P>
<P>
   If his grandfather lost memory, his father retained it: ``He was
in the military. He became a prisoner of war in Manchuria and spent
two years at hard labor in Siberia. I believe that the deaths of
his fellow POWs and friends in the camps in Siberia had a major
impact on his life.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, in turn, loved to watch Hollywood movies on
television, especially ``those starring Joan Fontaine or Ingrid
Bergman,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It is out of this mix of pleasure and deprivation, trauma and
memory, that Kore-eda has emerged as one of Japan's most original
cinematic talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Life'' taps into a wellspring of emotion in audiences
drawing on intensely different public and political histories. In
Japan, its sold-out screenings are a striking phenomenon for a
culture that prefers to dismiss its memories. As Kore-eda points
out, ``The Japanese, after all, at the end of every year have a
bonenkai, literally, a year-forgetting party, in which all the
events of that year are put aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a party is unimaginable, of course, in American culture,
where memory can be malleable or marketable, exposed on daytime
television or sold on the memoir circuit, rewritten or restored,
but never discarded.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, ``After Life'' has riveted audiences. People leave
the theater strangely silent, caught up in revery, perhaps
reviewing the events of their life. Kore-eda, by fashioning a story
of death and memory, has slyly delivered a movie that reaffirms
life _ and the magic of movies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
