<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4622 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-0513-     05-12 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-0513-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YELTSIN FIRES PRIMAKOV, SETTING UP ANOTHER SHOWDOWN WITH DUMA
 &HT;    850&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By JULIA SHARGORODSKA 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin plunged the country
into political turmoil once again Wednesday, firing Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov and replacing him with Interior Minister Sergei
Stepashin, a longtime ally.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination of a new prime minister, the fourth in fourteen
months, sets the stage for yet another showdown with the
Communist-controlled State Duma, the lower house of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The sacking of Primakov, who was popular with the Duma, comes on
the eve of the start of impeachment hearings against Yeltsin in the
lower house -- which Speaker Gennady Seleznyov said would go ahead
as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma will attempt to muster the 300 votes needed to impeach
Yeltsin, while the president threatens to dissolve the Duma if it
does not confirm his choice of prime minister in three votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If yesterday about 300 could have voted for his impeachment,
now there will be 400 of them,'' Seleznyov predicted, adding that
confirmation hearings on the new prime minister wouldn't begin for
a week -- the maximum time frame allowed under the Russian
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are busy with another procedure right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Zakharin, deputy general director of the Policy
Foundation, a Russian think tank, said dissolving the Duma could
make the country spiral into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currency markets and stock markets could fall, and Russia's
role as a negotiator in the Yugoslavia would have to start from
zero,'' he said. ``The IMF would again have to rethink its
relations with the government. And if the government doesn't
receive the ($7.5 billion in foreign loans), the ruble falls and
the situation in Yugoslavia becomes worse, it could cancel Duma
elections on the premise that there isn't any money.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about the popular Primakov's sacking have been
circulating for weeks, as Yeltsin grew more disapproving of
Primakov's cooperation with the Communist dominated duma. Three
weeks ago, Yeltsin ceded Primakov's negotiating powers in the
Kosovo crisis to former prime minister Victor Chernomyrdin, who
would report directly to Yeltsin. It was clearly a slap in the face
for Primakov, who had served as Foreign Minister before his
appointment as prime minister last September -- replacing
Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   While Primakov's powers have been eroding, Stepashin's have been
on the rise. On April 27, Yeltsin brushed aside Primakov's
right-hand man and appointed Stepashin first deputy prime minister
in addition to his duties as Interior Minister.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov tried to put a positive light on the situation in his
farewell address to the Cabinet Wednesday, which was met with a
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our government has nothing to be ashamed about. We performed
our responsibilities professionally and well,'' Primakov said. He
said he would remember his eight-month tenure in the government
``with great pleasure and joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, who was also deputy prime minister, said Yeltsin's
appointment came as a surprise to him. He praised the government
for stabilizing the economic and political situation in the
country, and said he would continue the economic course and fulfill
all agreements reached with the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's dismissal sent the Russian stock market sharply
lower, and trading was suspended twice over the course of
Wednesday's session.
</P>
<P>
   But on the streets of Moscow on Wednesday, news of the
government turnover was met with little reaction. People riding the
subway continued to read Tuesday's newspapers and do crossword
puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the same to me who (is prime minister),'' said a 40
year old teacher, who refused to give her name. ``There was
something of a beginning of stability. I think the president did it
so it wouldn't get too boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, in a televised address to the nation, gave
contradictory reasons for firing Primakov. While praising Primakov
for stabilizing the economic situation following the August 17
crisis, Yeltsin criticized Primakov for not doing enough to spur
economic growth in the country.
</P>
<P>
   He said Primakov's government ``fully accomplished their
tactical assignment'' although ``we are still tapping in place in
the economic sphere.''
</P>
<P>
   There is currently ``no basis for serious and stable economic
growth,'' Yeltsin said, adding that the decision couldn't be
postponed until the Duma elections -- scheduled for December.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a feeling that the entire economic activity of the
government is linked only to negotiations with the IMF,'' Yeltsin
said, ``as if the treatment of the Russian economy depends solely
on the extension of Western credits.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMF had tentatively agreed to give Russia $4.5 billion in
new loans, and the World Bank had promised an additional $3 billion
loan for Russia, which is now on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just about to try and conclude our arrangements for a
$3 billion package,'' World Bank President James Wolfensohn said in
Washington. ``But now we don't have a government to deal with, and,
until there is a new government, clearly there is nothing more we
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   An IMF spokesman in Washington said nothing had been decided so
far on implementing the loan. The IMF is in contact with the
Central Bank and technical experts in the Russian government, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   (ED: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts and Duma deputies strongly criticized Yeltsin's
move, saying
</P>
<P>
   it set the stage for a new political crisis as the Duma seeks to
carry out impeachment before Yeltsin dissolves it.
</P>
<P>
   Zakharin, of the Policy Foundation, said the real reason behind
Primakov's firing is that in Yeltsin's opinion, he didn't do enough
to protect his interests in the Duma. While the lower house is
moving ahead with an impeachment vote, the upper house recently
voted to reinstate Prosecutor General Yury Skuratov, whom Yeltsin
tried to fire after Skuratov was allegedly found in a sauna with a
group of prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was a matter of disapproval with the economic course, he
would appoint a prime minister with an economic orientation, and he
doesn't know Stepashin's economic plan,'' Zakharin said.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Deputy Prime Minister Valentina Matvienko said Primakov
plans to resume work at the Russian Academy of Sciences and write a
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life goes on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
