<SLUG> BC-RUBIN-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a page of coverage on the resignation
of Treasury Secretary Rubin and the appointment of Lawrence Summers
to succeed him:
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-RESIGN (Washington) _ Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin,
whose insistence on deficit reduction early in the Clinton
administration helped propel the American economy to its strongest
performance in generations, announced today that he was resigning.
Clinton said he would nominate as Rubin's successor Lawrence H.
Summers, currently the deputy secretary of the Treasury, a longtime
ally of Rubin's and the day-to-day manager of a succession of
international financial crises that have rocked the global economy
over the past three years. By John M. Broder and David E. Sanger.
(1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-ASSESS (Washington) _ There is a case to be made that his
approach exacerbated the global financial crisis of the last few
years. He could be politically tone deaf, as when he initially
resisted efforts in Congress to overhaul the IRS. At times he was
stubborn and turf conscious, traits on display in his continuous
battle with the Fed's Alan Greenspan to preserve the Treasury
Department's powers as a bank regulator. But the enduring fact
about Robert E. Rubin is that he was consistently the most
influential voice in shaping economic policy through more than six
years in which the economy performed remarkably well, bringing
great benefits to the United States and incalculable political
advantage to his boss, President Clinton. An news analysis by
Richard W. Stevenson. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-SUMMERS (Washington) _ A profile of the Treasury
appointee: He arrived in Washington six years ago with a reputation
for brilliance and an equal reputation for intolerance. But in the
past year or two, a new Larry Summers has emerged _ one who has
tamed his sharp-edged wit, who regularly solicits key congressmen
and senators for their advice, who now occasionally admits to
errors of political judgment. As he trained to take over the most
visible job in the world economy, he has become, one close
associate at the Treasury said recently, ``more Rubin-esqe.'' By
David E. Sanger. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-EIZENSTAT (Washington) _ A profile of Stuart Eizenstat,
who will replace Summers in the No. 2 Treasury post. By Stephen
Labaton. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ After a 200 point drop in the Dow on the
announcement of Rubin's resignation, markets strengthened. At the
close, the Dow industrials were down 25, the S&AMP;P was little
changed, and the Nasdaq composite up 39 points. European markets
were little changed. In Asian trading, the Nikkei closed 1.22
percent higher, and Hong Kong stocks rose 1.08 percent. On the
credit markets at midday the 30-year bond was yielding 5.81
percent. By Jonathan Fruebringer.
</P>
