<HEADER>
A4627 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT &LR;      05-12 0287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 pages of coverage on the continuing
crisis in Kosovo and the aftermath of the bombing of the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments on the war from NATO
headquarters. By Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Much emotion as ashes of the dead
Chinese are brought home. Demonstrations subside and James Sasser,
the U.S. ambassador, leaves the embassy. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Developments: In their daily
briefing, Pentagon officials say that in the eighth week of
bombing, NATO attacks have damaged but not broken the Yugoslav
military's ability to fight. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ A look at the roots of
anti-American sentiment and the competing emotions that color the
way most ordinary people in China see the United States: admiration
and suspicion, hope and fear, love and hate. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ A reporter's notebook of vignettes
of ordinary life in the Kosovo capital amid the fighting. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, see also Washington RUSSIA-DIPLO, by Jane Perlez, on the
impact of Russian developments on the prospects for a diplomatic
solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
