<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER13-COX     05-12 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWMAKERS SCOLD CLINTON ON BORDER PATROL HIRING LAG
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers from both parties charged Wednesday that
security is deteriorating along U.S. borders and scolded President
Clinton for failing to hire 1,000 new Border Patrol agents a year
as required by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In an escalation of grumbling from Capitol Hill, the members
protested that only about 200 new agents will be hired this year
and that no additional agents are planned for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meanwhile, cross-border drug smuggling and alien smuggling
continue to cost uncounted lives and damages each year, and
terrorists may enter the United States at any time,'' said a letter
to Clinton signed by 49 representatives and 12 senators, most of
them from border areas.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, who chairs the House subcommittee on
immigration, blamed an ``apparent lack of interest in protecting
Americans'' and ``bureaucratic bungling'' for the failure to
recruit the additional agents.
</P>
<P>
   He said the current 8,000 border agents, fewer than the police
force of Chicago, was not nearly enough to guard the nation's 4,000
miles of southern borders and 2,000 miles of border to the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no sense of urgency'' about the problem, said Rep.
Silvestre Reyes, D-Texas, a 26-year veteran of the Border Patrol.
``There is no serious effort by the (Immigration and Naturalization
Service) to comply with this mandate'' to hire more agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're missing is will,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
who said that Clinton ``wants to spend this money on other
things.'' His fellow Texas Republican, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,
echoed that view, saying that border areas were being treated as a
``stepchild.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the lawmakers spoke in the U.S. Capitol, the
president was in the Rose Garden announcing $95 million in new
grants as part of his signature program to hire 100,000 community
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration offered no assurance that it would
meet the congressional demands.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Chulick, spokesperson for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said the agency was ``challenged in meeting
this goal'' of finding 1,000 qualified new agents because the
booming economy offers too much competition for qualified
applicants. ``It's the same as in the military,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has added a toll-free number in the past week and
stepped up visits to military bases and colleges, she said, but the
ranks of agents is still expected to grow by only 200 to 400 this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Border patrol agents are paid less than drug enforcement
officials, but the administration has the authority to raise pay
and has not done so. Chulick said INS Commissioner Doris Meissner
``has been studying that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Attorney General Janet Reno told Congress early this year
that the INS has hired new agents so rapidly that the service has
too high a proportion of new recruits. She urged a temporary halt
in hiring in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   That idea was rebuffed by lawmakers on Wednesday. ``We cannot,
as some have suggested, take a break in our fight against illegal
immigration and drug trafficking,'' Reyes said. ``Border
communities deserve full, complete attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-Texas, said the dangers along the Mexican
border are reaching the critical stage. He said some ranchers in
his border district check their cattle in the evening only with
their wives accompanying them with a gun as protection from drug
smugglers. ``We're tired of excuses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
