   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, May 13. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
ECOKOSOVO (Phoenix) - Sen John McCain, R-Ariz., and other senators
are hanging amendments on military spending bills, including the
$13 billion supplemental appropriation for the Kosovo conflict.
These riders would halt enforcement of the Endangered Species Act
and make permanant the Air Force's control of the Barry M.
Goldwater Gunnery Range in Arizona. By STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ADOPT-CHINA (Phoenix) - The Jacobs family, confined to a hotel in
China during anti-American demonstrations stemming from the bombing
of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, returns to Phoenix with a newly
adopted daughter. By MIKE CLANCY. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) - For small-business man Scott Fader,
competing head-to-head with the Arizona Diamondbacks has been like
a Little Leaguer squaring up against Randy Johnson. Now, the team
has raised the stakes, making Fader's life like facing Randy
Johnson _ blindfolded. Holding a 10-pound bat. With one arm tied
behind his back. By E.J. MONTINI Story will move in the ``A'' and
``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EVERLY-MUSIC (Phoenix) - There are harmony groups. Then, there are
the Everly Brothers, who basically exist on a celestial plane above
everyone else. The shimmering blend of voices between Don Everly
and his younger brother, Phil, created some of the most lasting
songs in rock-and-roll history. That's one reason why the Beatles,
the Beach Boys and Simon &AMP; Garfunkel all cited the duo as an
inspiration. By RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
YMCA-RENTER (Phoenix) - Frank Mazza remembers the day he moved in.
``Memorial Day, 1967,'' he said. ``I came down Van Buren, turned
north and walked past the YMCA. Then I turned around, went inside
the Y and got a room. Cost me a couple of bucks a day, 10 bucks a
week.'' So he stayed. The rates have gone up more than 800 percent
and his room number has changed at least five times, but the YMCA
in downtown Phoenix has been his mailing address for almost 32
years. With PHOTOS. By SAME LOWE. Story moved in the ``A'' and
``L'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - I loved that sidewalk. It's ridiculous to
say, but I did. Sometimes, when I was watering my yard, I'd look at
the concrete square that was stamped ``Pacific Construction, 1930''
and envision the people who built my house as they pushed a baby
stroller over that spot, as their kids rode a bike, or as someone
stood there and cheered when World War II ended. So you can
understand how upset I was when I heard a jackhammer in my front
yard and saw the sidewalk buckle and split as if the Earth was
having one big, frenetic seizure. By LAURI NOTARO. Story will move
in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Phoenix) - The Lexus LS 400 and GS 400: Both are built
by the same luxury-car division of Toyota Motors. Both are
expensive, have four doors and are powered by nearly identical V-8
engines. Yet they are as different as Abbott and Costello.
Embargoed for Saturday, May 15. By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the
``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EDIT-CHINA (Phoenix) - NATO forces are waging what looks a lot like
war in the Balkans. Yet a lot of people _ even nations _ still act
surprised at the consequences of unloading 15,000 bombs and
missiles on Yugoslavia. The erroneous bombing over the weekend of
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade was tragic, but nobody should be
shocked that such errors occur _ and will continue to occur. Story
moved in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
