<HEADER>
A4632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-POLITICS-340&AMP;AD     05-12 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-POLITICS-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY WATCHES PRESIDENTIAL RACE, FOR INTRIGUE MORE THAN ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ On Thursday, the Italian Parliament will begin selecting
the next president of Italy, a largely ceremonial figure.
</P>
<P>
   But for Italians, the back-room process is not a dull civic
exercise; it is the nation's equivalent of David Lynch's bizarre
television series, ``Twin Peaks.'' Months in advance, newspapers,
politicians and soothsayers keep track of elliptical signs and
veiled political maneuvering, and the only certainty is that things
are not what they seem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election of the Italian president is a game played behind
closed doors in which some oligarchs choose their doge according to
a secret pact,'' Sergio Romano, a former Italian ambassador,
explained in a recent column for Corriere Della Sera, a Milan
daily. ``The political parties never declare their full intentions
and limit their exchanges to elusive messages.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not the only Italian to wax indignant about a process that
seems a throwback to Venetian court intrigue. But actually, the
baroque exercise may be a way for Italians to purge their passion
for dietrologia _ the Italian science of seeking the hidden motives
behind an act _ on an election that while significant, does not
determine the fate of the nation. The seven-year term of the
current president, Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, 80, expires this month.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, no major political party had put forward an
official candidate. Transparency in the presidential race is
considered unseemly and politically obtuse.
</P>
<P>
   But Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema hopes to set a precedent. In
an effort to avoid delaying tactics and the appearance of back-room
politics as usual, D'Alema Wednesday held a flurry of meetings with
key leaders in his majority and the opposition, and persuaded all
of them to back his choice. That was Treasury Minister Carlo
Azeglio Ciampi, 78, who is widely credited with securing Italy's
entry into the European Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no guarantee that the deal would stick once
voting, by secret ballot, begins on Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There are several other figures who had been described as
front-runners, particularly on talk shows or elaborate newspaper
charts. One is Nicola Mancino, 67, the president of the Senate,
whose small Popular Party, a Catholic movement, has provided
crucial support to the governing center-left coalition of D'Alema.
</P>
<P>
   But the Popular Party has also been lobbying on behalf of Rosa
Russo Jervolino, 62, the minister of Interior, a Catholic who
fought against the legalization of divorce in the 1970s. She has
told reporters that she is not worthy of the office, and that
display of reticence instantly convinced Italy's political class
that she was a serious candidate.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one candidate openly running for the office, Emma
Bonino, 51, the European Union's humanitarian aid commissioner. In
a brazen departure from tradition, her followers have set up voter
petition drives, raised funds by selling ``Emma for President''
T-shirts, and sent campaign letters to all elected officials who
can vote in the presidential race, a lack of delicacy that
political experts view as sealing her doom.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, Italy has tried to reform its unwieldy
and chronically unstable political system, with only moderate
success. At least 16 political parties have seats in Parliament.
Last month, a national referendum to put an end to proportional
representation and move toward a two-party system narrowly failed
to attract enough voters to pass.
</P>
<P>
   In June, however, Parliament will have a chance to debate a bill
to allow voters to directly elect the president.
</P>
<P>
   For now, presidents are elected by 1,010 grand electors, made up
of senators, members of the lower house of Parliament and 58
leaders from regional councils.
</P>
<P>
   Italian presidents mostly unveil plaques and greet foreign
dignitaries, but one reason political parties work so passionately
behind the scenes is that presidents also have the right to
dissolve Parliament when a government collapses.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, D'Alema said his effort to reach a consensus
was a ``sign that shows the sense of responsibility of our
political forces.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
