<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Thursday, May 13, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact David Brady at the Daily News, (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   BRUSH-FEE (Los Angeles) _ While thousands of mostly suburban San
Fernando Valley-area homeowners are being dunned $13 to pay for
city brush clearance inspections, at least two public agencies had
thousands of acres inspected free of charge by the Los Angeles Fire
Department. The Santa Monica Mountains Conservancy and Caltrans,
both state agencies, are immune from such inspection fees by law.
By Deborah Sullivan. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   STAR-WARS-TICKETS (Los Angeles) _ At theaters across the galaxy,
``Star Wars'' fans lined up Wednesday to buy tickets for the
``prequel'' that opens Tuesday at midnight. At Mann's Chinese
Theatre in Hollywood, fans were camped out on sidewalks. In
suburban Burbank, where two megaplexes within blocks of each other
downtown were selling tickets, police set up barricades and braced
for traffic jams. By Robert Monroe. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``e'' entertainment news files.)
</P>
<P>
   STUDIO-COMPLEX (Orlov) _ The Los Angeles City Council considers
approval of a developer's plan to build television and movie
studios in suburban North Hollywood in the city's San Fernando
Valley.By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``n'' California news
files.)
</P>
<P>
   PAINT-POLLUTION (Los Angeles) _ Air quality regulators on Friday
will consider sweeping changes in the way a variety of paints can
be made in an attempt to reduce pollution. Opponents claim the new
rules could drastically limit the choice of paint products availibe
to consumers, making such tasks as painting houses and walls more
costly and expensive. By Gregory J. Wilcox. (Will move in the ``f''
financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BDE-STOCK (Los Angeles) _ Wall Street has finally taken notice
of Brilliant Digital Entertainment, the Woodland Hills,
Calif.-based software developer with the gimmick of offering
customers movies with multiple plot choices. Shares rocketed 35
percent Wednesday after Brilliant announced a quintet of
high-profile investors have purchased 18 percent of the company's
outstanding stock. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f''
financial news file.)
</P>
