<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PILOT-0513-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRAINING FOR APACHE HELICOPTER PILOTS IN ALBANIA 'MENTALLY'
TOUGH
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAWK BASE, Albania _ Flying an Apache helicopter leaves Matt
``absolutely exhausted,'' he says, not so much from physical
demands but from the mental concentration of flying the gun- and
missile-laden aircraft at low altitudes, at night, over hilly
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Threatening terrain -- like that not far from this gathering
point for America's Apache helicopters near the Kosovo border.
Enemy terrain -- like that not far from the green drab colored
tents that are home to Matt and the other Apache pilots between
simulated attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Matt -- military censors would not allow him to be identified
any further -- is from the West Point class of 1996, husky, single,
of medium build, easy going and for the last 15 months the
``driver,'' as he calls it, of one of America's most lethal killing
machines -- the AH-65 Apache attack helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   He belongs to the ``Pale Riders'' troop of the Six Shooters
Squadron of the 12th Aviation Regiment from Illesheim, Germany.
Most squadrons have their own personality, and his is made up of
mostly single guys who like to party. But the squadron patch on the
shoulder of their grey flight suits underscore the serious nature
of their jobs: Ducit Amor Patriae -- ``For Love of Country.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt spent four months last year on ``peacekeeping'' duty with
the Apaches in Bosnia. Now, with some four dozen other Apache
``drivers,'' he is training for attacks in the event that NATO
deploys the killer choppers against Yugoslav forces in embattled
Kosovo province. The Apache force sees itself as ``the tip of the
spear'' in any ground assault on Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   The training takes place mostly after dark, so Matt tries to
sleep in his tent in the daytime. The sun is murder, though, and
sleeping is nearly impossible in the heat and mud and tension of
Task Force Hawk. Even so, ``no matter how bad it gets here, it can
never be as bad as it was in the first year at the Academy,'' Matt
told reporters Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after every training mission and the post-mission
de-briefing, Matt tries to force himself to sleep, even though he
is still keyed up. ``I don't want to be drowsy when I'm flying,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Matt's tent could hold up to 12 people, but he shares it with
only one other pilot. Out back is a small patch of grass on which
is set up a wash stand and a mirror for Matt and his neighbors.
Trips to the latrine require everyone to ``saddle up,'' that is,
don pistols and vests.
</P>
<P>
   Training is dangerous. Two Apache crew members died last week in
the crash of their aircraft during a training exercise. They were
friends of Matt. ``They died doing what they wanted to do,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the training crash, Matt said he has ``total
confidence'' in the Apache. ``I think the aircraft is absolutely
safe,'' he said. ``I think the Apache is an extremely rugged
aircraft . . . I don't think you could pick a safer aircraft to
fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Or a helicopter as lethal. The twin-engine chopper carries 16
Hellfire missiles -- eight on each side. And under the fuselage is
mounted a 30-millimeter machine gun capable of firing 625 rounds a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't do a whole lot physically when you are actually in
the aircraft,'' Matt said. ``But your mind is working a thousand
times an hour to keep up with what's going on. So when you pull
yourself out of the cockpit at the end of the night, you are
absolutely exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   The darkness in which the Apache usually operates also adds to
the tension, as do the craggy cliffs and sharp valleys leading up
to northernmost Albania -- the Apaches's practice flight path.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there is the occasional Albanian who is curious about
all the helicopters flying around and hits them with a spotlight
just to see what is making all the fuss. Such an incident occurred
during one of Matt's training exercises this week. His cockpit
filled with light just as he and his co-pilot were about to land
the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared us both a little bit at first, but I realized it was
probably a curious person who was trying to figure out what we were
doing in his front lawn,'' Matt said with a chuckle. ``I can
imagine . . . if we landed in somebody's yard in Michigan, they
probably would have shot at us.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
