<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS CLOSER TO PASSING KOSOVO FUNDING BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House and Senate negotiators moved toward agreement
Wednesday on giving President Clinton nearly $11 billion in
emergency funding for the war against Yugoslavia, but the White
House warned of a veto if lawmakers insist on attaching extraneous
spending measures to it.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators hoped to reach a compromise Wednesday night that
would win passage in both chambers and have the bill on Clinton's
desk by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But there were substantial differences between a House-passed
bill authorizing nearly $13 billion for the Kosovo funding measure
and a package favored by the Senate that would provide $10.9
billion for U.S. military operations and refugee relief connected
to the NATO operation.
</P>
<P>
   Both are way above the $6.05 billion request Clinton sent to
Congress several weeks ago when he asked for supplemental funding
for the U.S. portion of the allied campaign through Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate insisted on adding billions more to cover
the cost of a military pay raise and numerous other Defense and
State Department-related programs. The Senate also decided to merge
the Kosovo bill with another emergency spending measure that would
provide about $1 billion for hurricane relief in Central America,
$372 million for victims of the recent Oklahoma and Kansas
tornadoes, and $570 million for financially troubled farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the negotiation process between House and
Senate conferees are efforts by a few senators to add additional
spending and other provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, is insisting that language
be included in the final bill that would allow unrestricted use by
the states of $246 billion to be paid by the tobacco industry as
part of its agreement to settle lawsuits brought by the states. The
administration opposes the provision, which would prevent the
federal government from claiming a share of the tobacco money to
cover Medicaid and Medicare reimbursement costs.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., is demanding that a $1 billion
loan guarantee program be included in the emergency package to help
U.S. steel companies and other businesses hard-hit by foreign
competition.
</P>
<P>
   As the House and Senate negotiations continued Wednesday, White
House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart signaled that Clinton would veto
the final bill if it contains ``extraneous political issues''
unrelated to prosecuting the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can't be seen as a positive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart stressed, however, that Clinton supports the idea of
merging the aid to hurricane and tornado victims into the Kosovo
package.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a true emergency, both Central America and the Kosovo
operations. We ought to get this through. We ought to leave out
other people's political agendas and pass it,'' Lockhart said,
adding that the tobacco provision and other issues should be
debated later on this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still believe that the very important funding for this
Kosovo operation should not be held hostage to other political
agendas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to head off a possible veto, House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
urged colleagues not to load up the Kosovo bill with ``nondefense''
spending seen as benefiting only a handful of special interests.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that both men would like to see Byrd's loan program
left out, along with a provision that would prevent gas producers
from having to pay interest on $200 million in customer
overcharges.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the two leaders are lobbying hard to keep
Hutchison's tobacco settlement provision in the final bill.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had hoped to have a ``clean bill'' free of
riders, or add-ons, on the president's desk sometime this week. But
in addition to the tobacco, steel and gas issues, House and Senate
conferees are arguing over a dozen smaller items that members would
like attached.
</P>
<P>
   They include an effort to keep the Alabama sturgeon from being
added to the endangered species list; an attempt by Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., to overturn a court ruling preventing mining
companies from expanding their milling operations on public lands;
and a proposal to create a $500 million loan program for
financially depressed oil and gas companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
