<SLUG> BC-SATELLITE-JACKPOT-560&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS GROUPS PROTEST JURY'S $581 MILLION AWARD IN FRAUD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By TOMMY STEVENSON   
 The Tuscaloosa (Ala.) News   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAWYERVILLE, Ala. _ George Merriweather said he was ``mad as
hell'' when he realized he had been cheated on installment payments
for a television satellite dish he and his wife, Velma, bought in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   A Hale County jury sympathized and last week awarded $581
million to the 80-year-old retired foundry worker, his wife and
their daughter, Barbara Carlisle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we won't get that much when it's all over, and I'm
still mad about what they did to us,'' Merriweather said. ``Money
doesn't excite me.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, have grown excited.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy between the relatively small amount of fraud
involved and the state-record $581 million award sparked an outcry
from business associations, politicians and lobbying groups such as
Alabama Voters Against Lawsuit Abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ridiculous, ruinous, revolting and graphic proof that
our civil justice system is out of whack, out of control and out of
common sense,'' said Lewis Fuller, chairman of the tort reform
advocacy group's board of directors. ``This crazy verdict is
obviously not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The award has provided new vigor for passage of proposed tort
reform laws that seemed all but dead in the waning days of the
state legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Merriweather spoke during a news conference in the
yard of his small, pre-fabricated home off a dead-end road about
100 miles southwest of Birmingham. Four television cameras,
including two from the ABC and NBC nightly news programs, pointed
his way, while a half dozen reporters took notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I want the world to know, the public to know, is how
I've been cheated, how I was cheated out of my earnings so they
won't cheat nobody else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict rendered Friday against Whirlpool Financial National
Bank includes $975,000 in compensatory damages along with $580
million in punitive damages. Whirlpool is appealing the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Methvin, the Montgomery lawyer who represented the
plaintiffs, said salesmen came to the Merriweather and Carlisle
homes and tricked them into the credit agreement, which carried an
interest rate of more than 300 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony showed Carlisle and the Merriweathers were told by
Gulf Coast Electronics that the dishes, which cost about $1,000,
would cost them $34 a month for three years. But the contract ran
for 4 1/2 years, costing the three an additional $612 in payments.
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool, a former subsidiary of Whirlpool Corp., is now owned
by TransAmerica Bank. Whirlpool provided the financing for the
satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-day trial last week, Methvin suggested a $6.9
million verdict to the jury. When it was suggested that the huge
judgment might backfire against law firms like his by giving new
life to tort reform issues, he disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the appeals courts are going to lower it down,
and the jury was very sophisticated and I think they realized that
too. They were just trying to call national attention to the
problem, and that is why they made it so large,'' Methvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted the whole country to know that some segments of
corporate America and Wall Street, who are behind these credit
schemes, are coming into the living rooms of the illiterate and the
elderly and the blind, and they are fleecing them out of thousands
of dollars each, and the total fleece is in the millions,'' Methvin
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Merriweather has a third-grade education.
</P>
<P>
   Methvin organized the media circus in the Merriweathers' yard in
rural Hale County. He closely monitored the interviews conducted
with his clients, at one point admitting that he was worried they
might express an opinion about how much they would really be
willing to accept in a negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he put such a settlement at about $5 million. On
Monday, however, he had estimated that he and his clients would
probably receive less than $1 million after the appeal process,
which could go all the way to the Alabama Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it and decided I had it too low on Monday,''
he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Methvin said the amount a law firm takes as payment in such a
case is typically one third of the award or settlement.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Merriweathers and their daughter seemed to
have no illusions about actually receiving in excess of half a
billion dollars, nor did they seem to be making any big financial
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're not going to get that much money,'' said
Carlisle, a 40-year-old who works for an apparel company in
Greensboro, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Velma Merriweather, 60, who works the midnight shift at Peco
Foods in Tuscaloosa, said she has given no thought to spending the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just tired,'' she said as she posed beside the satellite
dish at the corner of her vinyl-sided home. ``I didn't get off
until 8 this morning, drove all the way home, and I couldn't go to
sleep because I knew all these people were coming here. I just want
to get some rest.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Tuscaloosa (Ala.) News is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
