<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MUSICALS-ART-2TAKE     05-12 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MUSICALS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SECOND ACT FOR THE TV MUSICAL? PRODUCERS BET ON IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Nearly 25 years ago Neil Meron, a senior at Brooklyn
College, invited Craig Zadan, a writer who had just completed a
book about Stephen Sondheim, to present a lecture to students about
Sondheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I spoke, Neil said he was looking to get into the
musical theater and did I know anyone who could give him a job,''
said Zadan. ``I said, `How would you like to be my assistant?'''
</P>
<P>
   The two men, who soon began working for Joseph Papp's Public
Theater, eventually forged a producing partnership that has taken
them to television, where they have revived a form of entertainment
that executives had given up for dead: Hollywood's version of the
musical comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Once a studio mainstay, musicals are almost extinct in films and
never established much of a beachhead on television. In recent
years Meron, 44, and Zadan, 50, have begun to turn this around. In
1993 on CBS they produced a three-hour version of ``Gypsy'' with
Bette Midler that won high ratings. In 1997 on ABC, they produced
``Rodgers' and Hammerstein's `Cinderella,''' with Whitney Houston,
Bernadette Peters and Brandy, for ``The Wonderful World of
Disney.'' Reaching over 60 million viewers, the show gave ABC one
of its highest ratings in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday at 9 p.m. the producing team's newest musical,
``Double Platinum,'' with Diana Ross and Brandy, will be on ABC.
Ms. Ross and Brandy sing original songs from their solo albums in
the production. Ms. Ross plays a diva who has sacrificed motherhood
for stardom, and Brandy plays the daughter whose success threatens
Mom.
</P>
<P>
   Future plans include the Sondheim-John Weidman ``Assassins,''
directed by Barry Levinson, for HBO; ``Annie,'' starring Kathy
Bates as the harridan Miss Hannigan, to be broadcast next year on
ABC; ``The Music Man,'' and ``Mame.'' They have also signed Judy
Davis to portray Judy Garland and lip-synch her songs in an
adaptation of the autobiography ``Me and My Shadows: A Family
Memoir,'' by Lorna Luft, Garland's daughter. Zadan and Meron are
also producing an original television musical, ``Heavens to
Betsy,'' in which Dolly Parton will star and direct.
</P>
<P>
   Zadan and Meron have tapped into their contacts in the musical
theater to shape ``Double Platinum,'' which was written by Nina
Shengold and directed by Robert Allen Ackerman. The producers, who
said they have been friendly with Ms. Ross for years, came up with
the mother-daughter idea and pitched it to the two women, who
immediately agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing a musical for television is doing something very
fragile,'' Zadan said during an interview with the two men in the
living room of his home in the hills above Sunset Strip. ``The
first criteria is that it has to be dramatic, it has to be
emotional. The second is that it has to have very, very strong
characters. And the third is that you have to have event casting:
you have to have stars.''
</P>
<P>
   They said musicals had been given a bad rap in films and
television by executives who insist that younger audiences are not
interested in the genre. Zadan and Meron disagree. ``Actually this
generation has been brought up on MTV and VH-1,'' said Zadan.
``They're used to seeing superstar videos of people like Madonna or
Michael Jackson that tell stories through singing. They're actually
like musicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Where movie musicals have gone wrong, said Meron, citing
``Star,'' ``Hello, Dolly,'' ``A Chorus Line,'' ``Mame,'' ``Dr.
Doolittle,'' ``Annie'' and ``Newsies,'' is in miscasting (Lucille
Ball in ``Mame'' and Barbra Streisand in ``Hello, Dolly,'' for
example) and poor filmmaking. ``They blame the genre rather than
the film itself,'' said Meron.
</P>
<P>
   Zadan and Meron recall attending Broadway musicals as
star-struck children. Zadan, who used to write about the theater
for New York magazine, quit his job to work Off Broadway after
writing his book ``Sondheim and Company'' in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Their partnership evolved after Meron graduated from Brooklyn
College, and they produced shows at the old Ballroom in Soho
featuring evenings devoted to such musical comedy composers and
lyricists as Sondheim, Andrew Lloyd Webber, Sheldon Harnick and
others. Joseph Papp, the theater impresario, had asked them to work
at the Public and help develop musicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had just done `Chorus Line,' the money was pouring in and
it was the most vibrant time in the history of the Public
Theater,'' Meron said. What they learned from Papp was that ``when
we wanted to do a show he'd say, `Do you love it?''' Zadan said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Do you absolutely love it?' '' he said. ``If you don't love
it _ if you like it _ I don't want to do it.' He also said, `Don't
ever be afraid to fail.'''
</P>
<P>
   The shows they worked on at the Public Theater include
``Runaways,'' ``I'm Getting My Act Together and Taking It On the
Road'' and an adaptation of ``The Umbrellas of Cherbourg.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s Zadan moved to Hollywood to work for the
producer Peter Guber, who was running Casablanca Records and Films.
Meron stayed in New York to develop plays and musicals for Guber.
The team later split up for several years to work for other
producers until Zadan made his successful producing debut in 1984
with the movie musical ``Footloose,'' directed by Herbert Ross and
starring Kevin Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   They produced or were co-producers on nonmusicals as well,
including ``Serving in Silence: The Margarethe Cammermeyer Story,''
which was based on the Army colonel who challenged the military's
policy on gay enlisted personnel. But it was ``Gypsy'' that cleared
the path for Zadan and Meron on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fluke,'' said Meron. ``One day I was on the phone
with Shirley Bernstein, who represented Arthur Laurents and who is
Leonard Bernstein's sister, and she said, `How would you feel about
doing ``Gypsy'' for television?' I said, `Absolutely.' '' Laurents
created the Broadway classic show with Jerome Robbins, Jules Stine
and Sondheim.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sagansky, then a top executive at CBS, promptly agreed to
make the television movie if the men could find a top star. It took
months of pressure to secure the services of Ms. Midler, who had
told them she was worried that the part was too closely associated
with Ethel Merman and that a leap into television might not benefit
her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally said to her: `Is ``Gypsy,'' not one of the greatest
musicals? Is it not one of the greatest roles for a female?' and
she said, `Yes.' And we said, `So what's your problem?' And she
said, `OK, I'll do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Midler won a Golden Globe for best actress for ``Gypsy,''
which was one of the year's top-rated programs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not all their efforts have ended happily. They yearn to put
``Dream Girls'' on television, but the rights are owned by David
Geffen and Warner Brothers, whose plan to make the musical was
recently scrapped. They were planning to make a film version of
Sondheim's ``Into the Woods,'' but John Calley, chairman of Sony
Pictures Entertainment, dropped the project. These musicals and
others are viewed in Hollywood as too risky and too expensive.
Numerous other musicals are unavailable because estates that own
the rights often decide that a television presentation would hurt
the future income of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there is the history of failure of so many movie
musicals. ``If an action film fails, no one says, `Let's stop
making action films,''' said Zadan. ``But if a musical fails, it's
like cutting our throats.''
</P>
<P>
   Meron agreed. ``We're crazy to keep wanting to do musicals,'' he
said. ``They're so fragile. There are so many problems. But when
they succeed, there's nothing like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
