<SLUG> BC-SEC-INTERNET-FRAUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC SUITS CITE ILLEGAL INTERNET SECURITIES SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Securities and Exchange Commission has filed civil
cases against several companies and individuals for allegedly
selling fraudulent securities on the Internet, SEC officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each case involved outrageous or baseless promises to
investors, in some instances guaranteeing annual profits in excess
of 500 percent,'' said James B. Adelman, associate Boston district
administrator of the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   The commission alleged that Bruce W. Lynch, of Brookline, and a
Long Island, N.Y. company called Neurotech Enhance Resources, Inc.
created an Internet offering of $15 million in notes in August 1998
to finance the construction of hospitals in Turkey. No such
hospitals were being built, according to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch went beyond representations made to him by Lawrence M.
Artz, of Roslyn, N.Y., an official of Neurotech, by publishing
revenue and earnings projections for completed hospitals ranging
from $4 million to $27 million.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC is seeking a cease and desist order in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also filed a complaint against Richard J. Briden,
of Ashland, and two corporations he founded, Empowerment Funding
Group LLC and Infopro Group Ltd., asserting that they conducted a
fraudulent offering of so-called ``prime bank'' notes on the
Internet, and that they sold interest in another bank-trading
program to seven investors.
</P>
<P>
   Briden allegedly used Web sites to offer purportedly risk-free,
high-yield investment opportunities to people with a minimum of $1
million to invest. The SEC also alleges that Briden convinced the
seven people to invest $295,000 in a program called Mutual Assets
Limited, promising the investors a return of 640 percent per
40-week period.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC is seeking permanent injunctions prohibiting Briden and
his companies from further violations of specific provisions of
securities law and a civil monetary penalty to be determined by the
court.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also filed a civil complaint against a former
Gloucester resident, Jason R. Rosenthal, currently of Dunedin,
Fla., alleging that he violated federal securities law when he
solicited investors to purchase unregisterd securities in companies
that would sell software for operating commercial Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   According to the commission, the securities were issued by a
company known as VentureLink Capital Corp. or one of its
affiliates, and Rosenthal's solicitation falsely projected
investment returns of 500 percent to 2,000 percent within two year.
Rosenthal also allegedly misrepresented the offering as an
opportunity to invest in a company that had obtained millions of
dollars of start-up capital from venture capitalists who had
financed Microsoft Corp. and Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is seeking a permanent injunction prohibiting
Rosenthal from further violations of specific federal securities
law, the disgorgement of his gains, prejudgment interest on the
gains and a civil fine.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants could not be reached Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
