<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
Aug. ??. If you have any questions, please call Dennis Boone on the
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4758.
</P>
<P>
   SAM _ Sen. Sam Brownback, Kansas Republican, has found himself
well-placed for a publicity coup. As a critic of violent song
lyrics, the conservative Republican is now the talking head in
demand when talk turns to culture. A Senate hearing and White House
meeting are helping him gather steam. By David Goldstein.. Story
will move in the ``w'' category.
</P>
<P>
   BEEF _ Tomorrow is the deadline by which European countries must
start accepting hormone-treated beef from the United States. For
business. By David Goldstein. Story will move in the ``w''
category.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY13 _ Kansas City school board members accuse the state of
reneging on a promise to provide $38 million in replacement revenue
for the withdrawn desegregation payments. But because of the way
the state applied the school foundation formula, the district will
only get $28 million. In addition, the district expects to lose $4
million in revenue because charter schools that open this fall will
siphon off students. The $14 million shortfall is 5 percent of the
district's budget. Officials say making up that loss on top of $60
million cut last year will be painful. By Phil O'Connor. Story will
move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   CIG _ Closing arguments today in the Charles Steele family
lawsuit against Brown &AMP; Williamson in Kansas City federal court.
The family says Kool cigarettes gave Steele cancer and killed him.
The tobacco company says Steele knew the risks of smoking and
working in a foundry gave him cancer. The family is asking for more
than $25 million. The tobacco analysts are watching the case
closely in light of the industry's win this week in Memphis and two
loses in West Coast cases earlier this year. By Mark Morris. Story
will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH _ A new program offers protection and peace of mind for
elderly or disabled Kansas City residents. The Senior Watch Program
started in January in the police department's East Patrol Division,
but could spread to the rest of the city. Program members provide
police with their phone number, medical history, family contacts
and the name of someone nearby who can let police into their home
in an emergency. The information is entered into a computer, and
accessed only by the police. Since January, 280 people have joined
the program. Malcolm Garcia. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   CRISIS _ In the wake of the Littleton shooting, Swope Parkway
Health Center and Truman Medical Center Behavioral Health Network
form a school-based crisis team. The team will begin a pilot
project at Central High School and Central Middle School.
Eventually, the program will expand to as many as 12 Kansas City
School District schools. By Tanika White. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   EVOLUTION _ Kansas Board of Education delays a decision on new
science standards that proclaim evolution as one of the unifying
principles of science, hearing an alternative proposal to include
creationism as a theory. Kate Beem. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   ION (Business) _ Sprint shows off its new Integrated On Demand
Network, the amazing fiber-optic, high-speed, big bandwidth service
that it hopes will revolutionize American life. By Ted Sickinger.
Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   BAKE (Business)_ Interstate Bakeries didn't do everything it was
supposed to do when it acquired Continental Grain, Dept. of Justice
says. Jennifer Mann Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   STAFFORD (Business column) _ About 6!}illion workers who have
been quietly struggling with infertility are becoming more vocal.
They want their employers' health insurance plans to help pay for
infertility treatments. After all, they say, infertility is a
medically recognized disease and should not be discriminated
against. They also proclaim protection as disabled workers under
the Americans With Disabilities Act. At Work column by Diane
Stafford. Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   AQUILA - Aquila Energy is building a gas-fired electricity
generating plant in Cass County, Mo. By Rick Alm. Story will move
in the ``f'' category.
</P>
