<P>
   RUBIN-SUMMERS (Washington) _ Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers, who was nominated on Wednesday to succeed Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin, arrived in Washington six years ago with a
reputation for brilliance and an equal reputation for intolerance
of those he considered slow to grasp the dynamics of an unforgiving
global economy. But in the past year or two, a new Larry Summers
has emerged _ one who has tamed his sharp-edged wit, who regularly
solicits key congressmen and senators for their advice, who now
occasionally admits to errors of political judgment. By David E.
Sanger. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Display)
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-ASSESS (Washington) _ By the time he announced his
resignation Wednesday as treasury secretary, Robert Rubin stood
second only to the Federal Reserve chairman as the embodiment of
American economic solidity in a world that has been roiled by
financial instability and accompanying political upheaval. By
Richard W. Stevenson. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-MARKET (New York) _ Wall Street flinched, but then quickly
brushed off Wednesday's announcement that Treasury Secretary Robert
E. Rubin was resigning and being replaced by Deputy Treasury
Secretary Lawrence H. Summers. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   (Both are scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom Right)
</P>
<P>
   CONAGRA-LAYOFFS (Chicago) _ Conagra Inc., one of the world's
largest food companies, said late Wednesday that it would layoff up
to 9 percent of its workforce, or about 7,000 employees, and close
dozens of production, distribution and storage facilities as part
of a major restructuring effort aimed at reducing its costs and
bolstering its lackluster earnings. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom Left)
</P>
<P>
   COX-TCA-CABLE (Undated) _ In the latest consolidation deal by a
cable company preparing to offer telephone, Internet and
interactive services as well as ordinary television to its
subscribers, Cox Communications on Wednesday announced it was
acquiring TCA Cable TV Inc., for $3.264 billion in stock and cash.
By Lawrie Mifflin. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HERE ARE TONIGHT'S OTHER REGULAR FEATURES:
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ When Pepsi-Cola Co. first said it
would sell Storm, a lemon-lime carbonated drink, in a handful of
markets nationwide, many analysts thought the company would be
challenging 7-Up and Sprite. That was last year. This year, Storm
has displayed little, if any, punch. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The Securities and Exchange
Commission on Wednesday took enforcement action against 18
individuals and eight companies in 14 cases of fraud _ the agency's
third sweep in seven months of Internet investment scams. This
latest action focused on bogus offerings of securities. By Edward
Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   MINIMUM-WAGE-ECONSCENE (Undated) Whatever the political
attraction of a higher minimum wage, does it make economic sense? A
growing number of economists say yes, though there is reason for
Congress to move cautiously, perhaps even creatively. By Michael M.
Weinstein.
</P>
