<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4664 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUBIN-0513-Cox     05-12 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBIN-0513-Cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PUTS SUMMERS IN THE SPOTLIGHT, SALUTES RUBIN FOR SERVICE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Softening the loss of outgoing Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin, President Clinton named Rubin's top deputy to replace
him and assured the nation Wednesday there would be no shift in
policies that have helped guide the strongest American economy in a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the difficult act he must follow, Deputy Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers pledged to stay the course of fiscal
moderation and global integration at the heart of an economic
strategy that has driven eight years of uninterrupted growth and
impelled the stock market to dizzying heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right course has been set,'' said Summers, 44, ``and the
challenge is to carry on.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to build further on the theme of continuity, Clinton
named Stuart Eizenstat, undersecretary of state for economic
affairs, to replace Summers in the No. 2 job at the Treasury
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hailed Summers, a former Harvard professor and one-time
chief economist at the World Bank, as a ``brilliant'' strategist
who has served for six years in senior positions at the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely has any individual been so well prepared to become
secretary of the Treasury,'' said Clinton. ``He has always been Bob
Rubin's partner in many, many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no attempt, though, to disguise the fact he is
losing his most trusted economic aide, an ideological soul mate and
one of the most respected cabinet members of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will miss his cool head and steady hand, his sharp mind and
his warm heart,'' Clinton said during a White House ceremony at
which Rubin's resignation was announced. ``Everybody believed as
long as he was secretary of the Treasury, nothing bad could
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, the Lincolnesque millionaire who used his Wall Street
instincts and progressive politics to help steer Clinton's economic
policies, said he planned to leave by early July.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a yearning to return to public life in New York, where
he spent 26 years as an investment banker with Goldman Sachs. But
Rubin, who has written extensively on the need to broaden economic
opportunity to take in widening numbers of the nation's poor,
announced no specific plans for his life after public service.
</P>
<P>
   The news Rubin is leaving initially made Wall Street shudder.
The Dow Jones industrial average plunged nearly 2 percent in early
trading before rebounding to close down 25.78 points for the day,
at 11,000.37.
</P>
<P>
   That's more than three times higher than the close of 3,241.95
on the day Clinton first took office, Jan. 20, 1993, with Rubin
close at hand.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year before that, Clinton the candidate had summoned
Rubin to the Arkansas governor's mansion in Little Rock to discuss
economic policy. Convinced that Clinton was serious about trying to
balance the federal budget and helping the country's disadvantaged
at the same time, Rubin signed on as a key adviser and important
link to wealthy Democrats in New York.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton took office, he named Rubin as the first director
of the newly created National Economic Council, responsible for
overseeing economic matters ranging from tax and budget to trade
and commerce, and coordinating the efforts of various departments
with economic responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought it all together,'' Clinton said during his Rose
Garden remarks Wednesday. ``He got us to work as a team. He worked
for consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, 1995, Rubin succeeded former U.S. Sen. Lloyd Bentsen
as Treasury Secretary. One of the most influential economic
position in the world, the job pays $99,500 a year -- a fraction of
what Rubin once earned engineering mergers and acquisitions at
Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin took the helm amid a crucial test of Clinton's commitment
to the global marketplace: the collapse of the Mexican peso, which
threatened to bring down emerging markets worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Despite polls showing the public strongly opposed, Rubin
convinced Clinton to back a multi-billion-dollar bailout package
for the peso. Rubin later told the New York Times that was one of
the most nerve-wracking gambles of his high-stakes career.
</P>
<P>
   The gambit paid off: Mexico paid back to the Treasury more than
$12 billion in currency support loans -- with interest and ahead of
schedule. The deal was seen as staving off long-term recession in
Mexico and as a hallmark of Rubin's ability to balance U.S. risks
and interests in the global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Those skills have been tested and retested in recent years, as
Rubin has traveled the world as Clinton's chief economic diplomat,
working to stave off financial collapse from China to Russia to
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   He's also jawboned the Japanese into adopting long-promised
economic stimulus aimed at lifting the world's second-largest
economy out of a decade in the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   What Rubin seemed proudest of, though, was his role in the
administration's deficit-reduction efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The administration inherited federal budget deficits topping
$250 billion a year. This year, buoyed by strong growth in tax
revenues, the budget is projected by the White House to show a
surplus in excess of $80 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While the country's total debt has risen from $4.4 trillion to
$5.4 trillion under the Clinton administration, the White House has
reduced the privately-held portion of that debt -- the amount the
government owes to bankers and global investors - from $3.1
trillion in March, 1997, to $2.8 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the debt, and the interest paid on it, is
essentially money the government owes itself.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's departure comes at a difficult moment for Clinton, who
is riding out one of the most challenging sets of foreign policy
problems of his career.
</P>
<P>
   As much of the developing world struggles to recover from the
economic crash that shattered the promise of emerging markets two
years ago, Clinton is leading NATO in a war against Yugoslavia that
has left a deep chasm between the United States and two global
giants -- Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin has worked extensively to build U.S. economic partnerships
with both of those countries.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
