<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS DIVISIVE TIMORESE VOTE NEARS, A CRITICAL VOICE IS SILENCED 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ The editor was in New York, covering the
signing of an agreement to end a generation of war in his small,
remote homeland. But his articles never saw print. While he was
away, thugs bent on scuttling the agreement destroyed the office of
his newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Because they did not like the newspaper's brand of journalism,
one side in the conflict here in the territory of East Timor
decided to close it down.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper, Suara Timor Timur, has been the only independent
daily in this former Portuguese colony, where rebels have resisted
annexation by Indonesia since 1975. Until recently, it published
six days a week, for a circulation of 7,500.
</P>
<P>
   Renewed violence has swept the territory in recent weeks as new
civilian militias, backed by the military, try to block moves for
independence before a referendum on East Timor's future set for
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that Suara Timor Timur represents an
eloquent voice of attempted reason and logic in that horrid
situation,'' said A. Lin Neumann, the Bangkok-based consultant on
Southeast Asia for the Committee to Protect Journalists in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There couldn't be any clearer indication of the barbarism of
those militias than that they would choose that institution to
destroy. The CPJ thinks this is absolutely one of the key
institutions if East Timor is going to have any chance of a
successful transition.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper's reports have irritated pro-Indonesian authorities
since it began publishing in 1993, challenging what the managing
editor, Aderito Hugo da Costa, calls ``the culture of lies, always
covering things up.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported the official versions of events in East
Timor, statements from the opposition and the results of its own
reporting. Officials accused it of favoring anti-government
insurgents.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the slaughter at Liquica town, the government said five
people were dead,'' Hugo said, offering an example of the paper's
coverage. ``In my reporting I got more than 10. That's the kind of
thing we've been writing in our paper. We do our own reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   Though his number was higher than that given by the government,
it was also lower than the 25 reported by pro-independence forces.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper was accustomed to vandalism and threats, but it is
suffering from the stepped-up violence of what may be a final phase
in East Timor's independence struggle. Several of the paper's 18
journalists have received death threats and have gone into hiding.
Both Hugo and the editor, Salvador Soares, have left East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper was one of the targets in a three-day rampage
through the capital of Dili that began on April 17 and took as many
as 30 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours before, Hugo said, he received an assurance from
military officials that his paper would be safe. Then, he said,
more than 100 young men arrived in three trucks and two vans at the
office, which was closed because it was a Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Brandishing guns and bamboo spears, they broke down the door,
crowding into the tiny office. Two office boys who were there hid
under tables in the darkroom.
</P>
<P>
   The men threw computers and fax machines to the floor, ripped
out telephones and smashed printing presses. Someone with a machete
slashed a couch. Someone bludgeoned a hole in a reception desk.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Liquica killings in early April and other recent
attacks, Hugo and his reporters could describe in detail the
destruction of their office. But this time, like their editor in
New York, they had nowhere to publish a report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 1939EDT &QL; 
