u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-AGING-GENE-NYT &LR;      05-12 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AGING-GENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GENE MAY PROVIDE KEY TO AGING PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The microscopic roundworm Caenorhabditis elegans, studied by
many biologists as a model organism, does not live very long: a
mere three weeks if amply supplied with its favorite food,
bacteria. But the little creature has become of keen interest to
students of longevity because it will live up to four times as long
when mutations are engineered in certain of its genes.
</P>
<P>
   A longevity gene, even one that works in worms, might give clues
as to how to make people live longer, too. But skeptics have noted
that most of the life-lengthening mutations are in genes that
control the worm's hibernation and may be of little relevance to
species, like people, that do not hibernate. The worm prudently
enters a dormant stage when food is scarce or when too many other
worms are around.
</P>
<P>
   But discovery of a new worm gene, reported in Thursday's issue
of Nature, now suggests a possible link between those
life-lengthening genes and a leading theory of human aging, the
belief that cells age through stress as reactive chemicals, such as
free radicals, attack DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The new gene, discovered by Dr. Martin Chalfie, James Taub and
colleagues at Columbia University, is one that breaks down reactive
chemicals, like the hydrogen peroxide often formed when fat is
metabolized. At least two of the previously known life-lengthening
worm genes must work by turning on the newly discovered gene,
called a catalase gene, because when it is disabled, the other
longevity genes fail to prolong life as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Chalfie believes the catalase gene is normally switched on in
hibernating worms to keep their cells healthy. The life-lengthening
genes found by other biologists, which are mutations of normal
genes, probably work by causing the catalase gene in adult worms to
be unusually active, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Evolutionary biologists have strong theoretical reasons for
doubting the existence of any longevity gene, however. One is that
natural selection increases fitness up to reproductive age but not
beyond, because organisms living to a greater age than that would
not leave extra descendants. Also, a crowd of post-reproductive
animals would compete for food with their own progeny.
</P>
<P>
   Chalfie does not dispute these arguments but notes that the
normal role of the catalase gene is to protect the hibernating
worm, increasing its lifespan before reproduction, just the kind of
property that natural selection would be expected to favor.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the worm's genes have recognizable counterpart genes in
humans, despite the millions of years since the two organisms last
shared a common ancestor. Chalfie has searched through the public
data banks that record the human DNA sequences known so far, but
has not yet found a counterpart to the catalase gene. ``Maybe it is
only expressed when people are starving,'' he said, meaning that it
might not have been picked up by biologists searching for active
genes in the cells of well-fed people.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Ames, an expert on DNA damage in aging, who works at
the University of California, Berkeley, said the result was
important because it confirmed the idea that aging in animals
resulted from accidental damage to DNA, like that caused by free
radicals, and not from a genetically directed clock.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Ruvkun, a worm biologist at Massachusetts General
Hospital, said the new finding could prompt ideas for intervening
in human aging, perhaps by using a hormone to turn on the human
counterparts of the suite of genes that includes the new catalase.
But if increasing protection against reactive chemicals like those
known as free radicals is good for us, why don't we do it all the
time?
</P>
<P>
   One reason may be that the body's immune system generates free
radicals to attack bacteria. ``People who lack the enzymes that
make free radicals have terrible bacterial infections,'' Ruvkun
said. Hibernating animals can step up protection against free
radicals ``because if you're hibernating you are not exposed much
to bacteria. I don't think there's a free lunch _ if people want to
live a long time they're going to have to be a little sedated,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
