<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-ART-N     05-12 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: KOSOVARS BECOME MEDIA CONSCIOUS AS WAR DRAGS
ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Stojan and Gordana Antic were asleep in
their house in the Kosovo village of Lipljan about 11 p.m. last
Wednesday when the missile came through the bedroom above their
heads.
</P>
<P>
   As the walls and roof collapsed, injuring them and two of their
children, the missile knocked a hole in the wall of the new house
next door before bouncing back into the garden to lie amid the
yellow and red tulips and purple pansies of late spring.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, when the press arrived, the village was gaping
and gossiping, standing around the beige remnants of the projectile
as if a cow had dropped down from the moon. Some people kicked at
the missile, presumably aimed at the nearby airport at Slatina, the
way they might a dead snake.
</P>
<P>
   Aleksandara Antic, the couple's 12-year-old, who was unharmed,
was describing how she awoke with her mouth and nose filled with
dust and smoke.  &QC; She was young enough to be enjoying the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Milenko Djokic, 65, who lives next door, seemed quite outraged,
pointing repeatedly to the hole in his house and taking journalists
on tours. Cveta, his wife, 63, said she nearly died of fright
thinking of her grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the room, lifting the blanket to get into bed, when
it happened,'' she said, holding her heart. ``The house was
shaking, and all the windows shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   She was clearly frightened. But when a television camera
appeared, even this Kosovo villager went into speech mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we guilty?'' she asked with dramatic effect. ``We
think nothing bad about anyone. But what should God do to these
people? Let Clinton's daughter be under a broken roof like the
children next door.''
</P>
<P>
   No Gas? He'll Have to Stay
</P>
<P>
   Although it was difficult to secure the permission of the
Yugoslav authorities to visit Kosovo from Belgrade, it was possible
with the correct papers to travel freely in a private car through
the province without an escort _ so long as one had gasoline, which
is essentially unavailable for private purchase in Kosovo, even on
the black market.
</P>
<P>
   But there are foreign journalists based in Pristina, nearly all
of them Greek. Even though Greece is a NATO member, it makes little
secret of its pro-Serb orientation, and the Greeks have been
quickest to provide needed relief assistance _ both medicine and
food _ to the Serbs and Albanians who are living in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   There are also various Serbian journalists who work for the
Serbian media or for Western news agencies; a Turkish journalist,
who largely covers the Turkish minority in Kosovo; and one
Canadian, Paul Watson of The Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Watson managed to drive back to Pristina after having been
expelled, with other Western journalists, in March. Having shown up
at the dreary Grand Hotel in the midst of chaos, his car was
rapidly stolen or confiscated. So Serbian officials let him stay,
said Milivoje Mihajlovic of the Media Center, based at the Grand,
mostly because they had no car or gasoline with which to expel him
again.
</P>
<P>
   In the wonderful ways of bureaucracies, even during a war, his
presence here has now been institutionalized.
</P>
<P>
   A Holdover From the '60s
</P>
<P>
   Wartime Kosovo also receives puzzling official visitors. Last
week, it was Regis Debray, a French intellectual of the 1960s who
promoted the wit and wisdom of Che Guevara. Debray has moved
ideologically over the years, becoming an adviser to President
Francois Mitterrand and something of a nationalist, and he said he
would consult with French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
   Debray also stayed at the Grand, asking questions and meeting
officials, including a puzzled Mihajlovic, who is also the editor
of the local state radio station. After their meeting, Mihajlovic
wondered, ``Does he know where he is?''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing Against Brooklyn
</P>
<P>
   There is enormous destruction throughout Kosovo, with thousands
of Albanian houses and shops looted and burned, and many bridges,
buildings and other public works bombed from the air. Amid the ash
and the fear, there is also a sort of gallows humor. One Albanian
man, pointing to the taped glass of the Corso cafe in central
Pristina, said, ``Here we call this Windows '99.''
</P>
<P>
   Albanians have always frequented the Corso, and they continue to
do so. But they don't go to the Brooklyn Bar, about 100 yards away,
where Serbs tend to sit under a modernist wall hanging that depicts
the Brooklyn Bridge. The main problem is the outdoor terrace, where
Serbian soldiers and police officers tend to gather for midmorning
espresso and mineral water.
</P>
<P>
   Two Views of the Future
</P>
<P>
   Albanians and Serbs, interviewed separately, endlessly chew over
the possible future of Kosovo. Surprisingly, perhaps, in view of
their pain, the Albanians seem to have more confidence in the
long-term future and seem ready to try to live again with the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   After all, an Albanian named Rahim said, many more Albanians
still live in Kosovo than Serbs, ``and we have NATO on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   Official Serbs strut through the cities with confidence. But
many Serbs privately worry about how a future can be shaped after
so much violence. Many say if members of the Kosovo Liberation Army
are installed at the center of a new police force, as a Western
draft peace plan would carry out, many Serbs would be unwilling to
remain. Few Serbs here regard the rebel group as anything but a
terrorist organization committed to killing Serbs and winning
Kosovo's independence.
</P>
<P>
   Mihajlovic, a practical man, thinks that an east-west partition
of Kosovo, with the Serbs' retaining Pristina and points east and
the Kosovar Albanians' taking Pec, Prizren and the Albanian border,
may be the best long-term solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been so many bad things on both sides, maybe too
many to live together,'' he said in a dark moment. ``There are no
simple rights and wrongs in this story, no good solution. Too much
has happened for the West's social engineering. We should do
something to insure that this doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what form of solution is reached now, Mihajlovic said,
``the KLA will do whatever it can to get rid of the Serbs in
Kosovo, and some Serbs feel the same way about the Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the Balkans, he said, where nationalities have struggled
for dominance for centuries. Western plans for shared sovereignty
and minority rights ``may look like a balance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm afraid there is no balance here,'' he said. ``There is
only another recipe for war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
