<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POKER13-COX     05-12 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POKER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Casinos boost S.C. town's odds of economic survival
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCOLL, S.C. _ The White Sands video gambling parlor closed 2
1/2 weeks ago, giving hope to opponents of the casino operators
encircling this economically embattled town.
</P>
<P>
   But the victory appears to be fleeting. White Sands plans to
reopen early next week, joining eight other parlors flourishing on
the outskirts of McColl. With three more casinos under
construction, this town of 2,750 suddenly finds itself hooked on
video gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the parlors, prosperity is as rare as rolling lucky
sevens in this swampy patch of South Carolina. Squeezed between the
Great Pee Dee River and the North Carolina state line,
industry-starved McColl lost its last factory last year.
</P>
<P>
   Casino operators are making big money along South Carolina's
northern border, luring gamblers from North Carolina. Once
dependent upon cotton and textile mills, McColl is now debating the
virtues and vices of its new growth industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go in and say, `Next time I'm going to win,' but they
wind up with all their paycheck for the week in that machine,''
said the Rev. Joe Elvington, interim pastor of First Baptist Church
in McColl.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition from preachers and ambivalent support from
McColl's mayor haven't slowed the spread of video gambling, which
flourishes at convenience stores in McColl as well as in the
casinos outside the city limits. Just a block from First Baptist,
an old gas station is reopening with 10 machines.
</P>
<P>
   That will put video gambling on three of the four corners of
McColl's busiest intersection. At the other corner sits a blue and
white metal building, most recently home to the Sunrise Church of
Jesus Christ, but now vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Perched on a stool in Nic's Pic Kwik, accountant Bob Jones, 52,
lights a Winston, sips a cup of coffee and slips more bills into a
machine. He plays a game called Superball Keno, flashing $6,551.77
as the jackpot prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it is a source of pleasure and relaxation,'' Jones
said. ``People have a choice of whether or not to play. Their arms
are not being twisted.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Columbia, 100 miles to the southwest, conservative
Republican legislators are calling for stiff regulation of the
fast-growing, $2.5 billion industry. It seems, though, that the
most ardent gambling opponents are holding a losing hand.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the state House of Representatives takes up
legislation, passed last week by the Senate, calling for a
referendum in November 2000 to let voters decide whether to ban
video gambling. In the meantime, winnings per hand of black jack,
poker or other video games would be capped at $900. Some House
members have proposed a $600 cap.
</P>
<P>
   At present, state regulations limit daily winnings to $125 per
player. The industry largely ignored that law until a federal judge
recently ordered five major operators to abide by it. The judge
ruled in response to a lawsuit by addicted gamblers who say the
advertisement of large jackpots is an unlawful inducement.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the operators _ including one at Interstate 95 tourist
attraction South of the Border _ said they're laying off 400
workers as they shut down video gambling machines rather than abide
by the judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   Balking at the Senate proposal, the House last week passed a
bill calling for tougher restrictions, including a $125 daily limit
on winnings. But Gov. Jim Hodges backs the Senate version, and he
has threatened to convene a special session next month if the House
and Senate don't agree to regulations.
</P>
<P>
   With big contributions from the video gambling industry, Hodges,
a Democrat, ousted incumbent Republican David Beasley in November's
gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regulation is coming,'' said Robert Huckabee III, who is
building a casino on the outskirts of McColl. He is hurrying
construction, just in case legislators enact a law banning the
opening of new gaming halls.
</P>
<P>
   Huckabee's company, Southland Gaming Corp. of Wilmington, N.C.,
is building on a tract next to a swamp dotted by yellow-flowering
lily pads.
</P>
<P>
   The eight casinos around McColl employ more than 300 people,
most earning about minimum wage. Many welcome those jobs in
Marlboro County, where the unemployment rate tops 10 percent and
the median family income of $32,000 trails the state average of
$40,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are as poor a town as there is anywhere,'' said McColl
Mayor Lynn Bisbee, who swears off video gambling, but not its
economic boost. ``It does furnish a lot of jobs.'' McColl officials
are tossing around the idea of annexing the casinos clustered along
U.S. 15/401 between the town and North Carolina. The town would
collect property taxes and licensing fees while providing police
protection to the brightly lit strip of casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Even some staunch opponents, such as longtime First Baptist
Church member Edna Guilherme, can't escape the economic reach of
video gambling.
</P>
<P>
   After a recent Wednesday night prayer meeting at First Baptist,
Guilherme, 75, denounced the casinos as ``terrible.'' Yet just
three weeks ago, she and her husband, Albert, sold a 10-acre tract
where Huckabee is building the casino near the state line.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Guilhermes had dreamed of building a house in the
piney patch they had owned since the 1950s. Huckabee approached the
couple about selling three acres. They agreed, if he'd buy all 10
acres. The couple concluded the spot was no longer suitable for a
house.
</P>
<P>
   Edna Guilherme is still stirred up from what she called an
``agonizing decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wish any of them any bad luck,'' she said. ``No, I
take that back. I wouldn't care if everyone of them went broke.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
