A4686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYCOS-USA-BOS &LR;      05-12 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-USA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS LEADER LOOKS AHEAD AFTER COLLAPSE OF USA NETWORKS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Bob Davis, chief executive of Lycos Inc., was
disappointed but upbeat as he confirmed reports Wednesday that the
deal to merge Lycos with elements of USA Networks Inc. had
collapsed three months after it was struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lycos was a good business three months ago,'' Davis said.
``Lycos is a great business today.'' Davis vowed Wednesday to
continue making deals that would further expand the audience for
Lycos' Web sites, which now trail only America Online Inc. and
Microsoft Corp. in total Internet audience. And the Associated
Press, citing an unnamed source, said late Wednesday that Lycos
nest week will announce a partnership with a software company that
could put a direct link to Lycos on millions of desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spoke at a press conference to officially announce the
deal's demise. Davis had hoped to merge Lycos, one of the most
popular Internet portals, with several broadcast, on-line, and
retail assets of New York-based USA Networks, which is owned by
Barry Diller. The resulting company was to have been an electronic
retailing powerhouse, with $1.5 billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
   But Lycos shareholders rebelled against the terms of the deal,
saying that their share of the new company would be too small.
Lycos shares lost a third of their value the week the deal was
announced in February. Worse yet, Lycos board member David
Wetherell, chief executive of the Internet venture firm CMGI Inc.
in Andover, reversed his earlier support for the merger. Because
CMGI holds almost 20 percent of Lycos' outstanding shares,
Wetherell was able to kill the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Conn, CEO of Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch, one of the
USA Networks assets that was to have been merged, said that the
failure of the merger has left a residue of bitterness between
Lycos and CMGI. ``I'm sure there was animosity on many fronts about
that and I'm sure there'll be more of that over time,'' said Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Davis. ``Our relationship with Dave is cordial,''
he said. ``Dave was a partner of ours for a good long time and
provided the seed money to get this venture started. And life is
too short for this to be anything other than a good, cordial
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   CMGI officials did not respond to requests for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the merger proposal, the deal could only be
called off by mutual consent. In negotiations that lasted until
early Wednesday morning, the two firms worked out a separation
agreement that gives Lycos many of the benefits it hoped to gain by
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   For example, USA's CitySearch Web service will be linked with
Lycos to information on events and tourist attractions in
communities throughout the United States. People who purchase
tickets through Ticketmaster will receive materials promoting
Lycos. And Lycos also will be promoted on USA Networks' television
properties, including the USA Network and the SciFi Channel.
</P>
<P>
   These arrangements are non-exclusive, leaving Lycos free to
pursue other merger or acquisition opportunities after a
``standstill'' period that ends on July 15. Davis said that Lycos
is very interested in making additional acquisitions of other Web
companies, though he didn't cite any by name. ``We're interested in
more of the same,'' said Davis. Lycos attained its present size
through a series of acquisitions of major Web sites such as Tripod,
HotBot, WhoWhere, and Wired News.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said that Lycos will soon be free to use the
``pooling of interests'' method to acquire companies by swapping
shares of stock. Accounting rules barred the use of this method
because CMGI formerly owned more than half of all Lycos stock. But
CMGI reduced its stake in 1997, which entitled Lycos to use the
pooling method after two years had elapsed. The deadline passes on
October 9. After that date, Davis said, Lycos will be able to
acquire companies without having to write off goodwill expenses, a
practice that reduces the firm's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said that there are still many major media firms that
may be interested in doing a partnership with Lycos. He cited Time
Warner Inc., News Corp., CBS Corp., Viacom Inc., and the German
publishing house Bertelsmann. Davis rejected the view that Lycos
was desperately in need of a hookup with one of these firms. ``If
anything,'' said Davis, ``I think we can look at it and say media
companies need us.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Lycos, of Waltham, Mass., closed Wednesday up 8 3/4 to
107; CMGI lost 4 15/16 to close at 239 3/4; Ticketmaster-CitySearch
closed up 3 7/16 at 36 1/16; and USA Networks gained 3 9/16 to
close at 39 7/16, all on the Nasdaq stock exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
