<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOL-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OKS BILL BANNING OPEN CONTAINERS OF ALCOHOL IN VEHICLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The House on Wednesday approved a bill that
would ban open containers of alcohol in vehicles, and a Houston
proponent of the measure predicted it has a 75 percent chance of
survival in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Rep. Ron Wilson said the Senate would support the ban
mainly because the state can gain access to about $120 million in
federal highway funds if a strict ban is approved.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's bill included an array of strong anti-drinking
proposals, but some of them were expected to be watered down in the
Senate before it becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, hoping to end a long string of defeats, proponents of the
tough new sanctions were advancing some of the same proposals in
free-standing bills. In addition to a separate open container bill,
another back up measure that excludes minors from bars is on
today's House calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, common sense is going to prevail,
although it didn't look like it yesterday,'' predicted Rep. Harold
Dutton, D-Houston, who opposed the package of anti-drinking
proposals approved late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really getting to a point where we're criminalizing
drinking, and that's not what I think we should do,'' he said.
``All that stuff is going to come off in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's amended package, House Bill 3555, which won final
approval Wednesday and was sent to the Senate, would ban open
containers in passenger compartments of vehicles on public roads,
ban minors from bars and outlaw liquor sales in topless bars.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Nixon, R-Houston, who offered the amendment to Wilson's
bill that would preclude liquor sales at sexually oriented
businesses, said he's already been told his proposal will be
discarded.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Rep. Leo Alvarado, D-San Antonio, said he's doubtful
his amendment banning minors from bars will pass muster in the
Senate. But Thursday he's offering the same concept in a separate
bill _ just as he has in the past four biennial sessions. His goal
is ``to protect the little children from themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite existing laws that ban alcohol sales to those under age
21 and require minors to be hand-stamped in bars so they won't be
sold liquor, Alvarado said the laws are often and easily
circumvented. He claimed that not only do illegal sales occur, but
drug- and alcohol-selling ``predators'' prey on youths going into
bars, ``selling them half pints of whiskey, crack cocaine, Ecstacy
and marijuana to get their buzz outside so they can have fun
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when they come back out,'' Alvarado continued, ``they get
in cars they can barely drive and either kill themselves, somebody
they love or some poor guy coming home from work.''
</P>
<P>
   His proposal probably won't become law because even if it passed
Thursday, it would arrive in the Senate too late to win both
committee and floor approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had support. It's just that one or two people kill
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the open container proposal is likewise uncertain.
On Wednesday, the House approved Wilson's bill that included the
ban and then approved a similar measure, House Bill 487 by Rep.
Fred Hill, R-Richardson, that included fewer exemptions and
potential loopholes. Generally, both would outlaw open containers
in passenger compartments, except in locked glove boxes or behind
the vehicle's last fixed seat.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's bill included the open-container ban, but the other
controversial features were added by other members. Dutton said the
additions were allowed because of the wide range of regulatory
topics the original bill addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever a bill starts to bleed a little bit, the sharks start
to circle, attack and feed,'' Dutton said. Proponents of the
anti-drinking amendments, who helped approve a lowering of the
legal intoxication threshold this week as well, commandeered
Wilson's, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They represent the radical view, not me,'' Dutton said. ``If
the premise is to make sure the streets are safer because we don't
want people drinking and driving, then outlaw drinking and
driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutton unsuccessfully proposed a lowering of the intoxication
level from the current .10 percent blood alcohol content to zero.
The House on Tuesday approved a .08 percent threshold.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person is sitting in a bar on Dowling Street, how are
they supposed to know what level they're at?'' Dutton asked,
adding, ``We're sending the wrong message to Texans that we're
somehow making the streets safer.''
</P>
<P>
   He advocates stiffening penalties for existing liquor-related
laws instead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
