<SLUG> BC-EXP-KOREA-WOMEN-JOBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SOUTH KOREA, CRISIS CAUSES MORE WOMEN TO GET INVOLVED IN
BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ As Choi Yang Sook saw it, her place was in
the home, cooking for her husband and cleaning up the house and
raising their children.
</P>
<P>
   But the Asian economic crisis changed all that, virtually
destroying her husband's architectural design business and forcing
Mrs. Choi to look for ways to make money herself. So now she is
enrolled in a course on how to run a flower shop, and she expects
to start her own flower business this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time that women seek jobs,'' said Ms. Choi, a
mother of two teen-agers. ``Some of our husbands have lost jobs,
some have had cuts in salaries, and businessmen have had a hard
time. So women want to help their husbands and maintain the
household.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Asian crisis was particularly harsh on women,
and in South Korea many companies, cutting costs, laid off women
while keeping male employees. But the crisis has also forced women
into the job market alongside their husbands. And the eventual
outcome may be more entrepreneurs and even business executives who
are women.
</P>
<P>
   Among Asians, Korean women have been among the most traditional
of wives and mothers. A few hundred years ago, when a girl was
born, her parents frequently named her Gutsuni, or Last Girl, in
hopes that she would be the last girl born to the family. Even
today property is still generally handed down mostly through men.
</P>
<P>
   These days, young women frequently work after high school or
college, but it is common for them to quit after marrying or having
children. Very rarely have women pursued high-powered careers while
also marrying and raising children.
</P>
<P>
   Now with family finances crimped, those traditions are fading
and women are acquiring greater economic significance in South
Korea. Discrimination against women is at least as intense as ever
in the business world, but women are nonetheless emerging from the
home to help their husbands run start-up restaurants, do the
banking for a new business, or keep the books for the old company
when workers are let go.
</P>
<P>
   Park Ai Ja, a 55-year-old former housewife, was in the office of
Sae Ki Trading Co. the other day. It is her husband's company,
importing chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Park seems a stabilizing force in the business. The company
is struggling, and none of her three sons will take it over. But
she says she and her husband are happy because he still has an
office, while many of her husband's friends have been forced out of
their salary jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just maintaining the company, and maintaining our
health, which is important,'' Ms. Park said. The office, she added
with a wink, is really for her husband's pride. ``If you don't have
a card, if you don't have a title, people may look down on you.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAYTHEON-SUIT-BOS &LR;      05-12 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON   UNIT SETTLES INDUSTRIAL SPYING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Fla., Ala.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Aerospace Co., a subsidiary of the Lexington,
Mass.-based Raytheon Co., has agreed to settle allegations that it
used a security firm to spy on a small competitor in Alabama three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On March 30, days before a lawsuit was to go to trial, Raytheon
agreed to pay $16 million to AGES Group, of Boca Raton, Fla., to
settle allegations that it had engaged in at least three days of
industrial spying that included video and audio surveillance and
thefts of documents. Raytheon also agreed to make an undisclosed
amount of future purchases from AGES, which sells aircraft engines
and parts and services them.
</P>
<P>
   A security firm that Raytheon allegedly employed to undertake
the surveillance, Wackenhut Corp., agreed to pay AGES $5 million to
settle the claims.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual aspect of the case, Raytheon and Wackenhut's offer
for a judgment to be entered in favor of AGES on all of its claims
did not disclaim liability, as is customary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filed a complaint alleging industrial espionage and both
the plaintiff and defendants decided to avoid going to trial in a
case in which the plaintiffs were seeking substantial amounts of
monetary damages,'' said the lawyer for AGES, Mark Lawson, of the
Birmingham, Ala. firm of Burr &AMP; Forman.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Raytheon Wednesday denied that the company had
done anything illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to emphasize that there has been no evidence of
criminal wrongdoing in the case, and that's about all we can say on
the record,'' said David Polk, a spokesman for Raytheon, the
third-largest defense contractor in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Wackenhut did not respond to requests for comment
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The judgments, entered by US District Judge W. Harold Albritton
3d, marked the end of a 2 1/2-year suit connected with a
competitive bid for a government contract worth about $450 million,
according to court papers. The contract was for the servicing of
the US Army C-12 aircraft, a military transport. Raytheon
eventually was awarded the contract.
</P>
<P>
   AGES had hired a company in Slocumb, Ala., The Libertatia
Associates, to help prepare its bid.
</P>
<P>
   AGES alleged in the lawsuit that Raytheon hired Wackenhut to
send private investigators to spy and eavesdrop on Libertatia while
it was preparing the bid. AGES asserted that investigators
illegally monitored and intercepted communications from
Libertatia's office, using sophisticated electronic eavesdropping
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the case said that officials of both Raytheon
and Wackenhut denied that such activity occured during the
discovery phase of the trial, prior to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But AGES had assembled eight eyewitnesses who asserted that they
saw vehicles with specialized equipment, like parobolic microphones
and a tape recorder, as well as people leaving the Libertatia
offices who were later identified as Wackenhut employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
