<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLOVAKIA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MECIAR ONCE AGAIN FIGURES IN SLOVAKIA'S ELECTION  

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia _ Six months after dumping Vladimir Meciar
as prime minister and putting their small Central European country
back on track for membership in the European Union and even NATO,
Slovaks are again tussling over whether Meciar should have a share
of power.
</P>
<P>
   Meciar's surprise entry last month into Slovakia's presidential
election on Saturday has again confronted his country, created
after the peaceful split of Czechoslovakia in January 1993, with
the choice of continuing democratic reform or sliding back into
international isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning heavily on Slovaks' distaste for NATO's bombing of
Yugoslavia, the maverick Meciar kicked off his presidential
campaign on April 15 by announcing that he had invited President
Slobodan Milosevic to Slovakia ``for a rest and some hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   He added in this waggish vein that the Yugoslav leader had
declined the invitation on grounds that there had been enough
bloodshed. Meciar also compared the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia to
the invasion of Czechoslovakia by the armies of the Warsaw Pact in
1968, claiming that the Serbs are now going through ``what we
experienced in 1968.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that most Slovak voters, while opposed to a military
solution to the Kosovo conflict, have grown wary of Meciar's brand
of populism. Although 65 percent of Slovaks polled say they oppose
the NATO bombing, about the same number hold Milosevic responsible
for the tragedy of Kosovar Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   With Meciar as prime minister from 1992 to 1998, with a
nine-month hiatus in 1994, Slovakia lost its chance to join NATO,
and was not designated a prime post-Communist candidate for the
European Union. Under the coalition that defeated Meciar six months
ago, however, the country has emerged from its isolation. The new
administration hopes that Slovakia will join Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic in the first wave of candidates for membership
at the European Union summit meeting in December in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   The current election is one attempt to allay any lingering
European Union doubts over Slovakia's democracy. When the term of
Michal Kovac, independent Slovakia's first president, expired last
May, the deeply divided Slovak Parliament was unable to agree on a
successor, and Meciar assumed some presidential powers.
</P>
<P>
   Then in September, a four-party coalition led by the current
prime minister, Miklos Dzurinda, defeated Meciar in parliamentary
elections. The coalition's candidate for president, Rudolf
Schuster, leads opinion polls in a crowded field of 10 candidates.
A runoff between the top two finishers is likely on May 29.
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, 65, turns off some Slovaks because of his past in the
Communist Party, which he joined in 1964. He was the last Communist
chairman of Slovakia's Parliament before the ``Velvet Revolution''
of 1989 ended 41 years of Communist rule in Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   He left the Communist Party in 1990, and then served as the
Czechoslovak ambassador to Canada. For the last five years, he has
been mayor of Kosice, turning the isolated eastern Slovak town into
a lively urban hub. He makes no excuses for his former Communist
affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been an aparatchik _ I always served the
citizens, not the party,'' Schuster said in a recent interview. ``I
entered the Communist Party out of conviction as a young man. I
don't have the slightest regrets about my past.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuster has donated most of his campaign budget to hospitals
and orphanages. He runs only one simple television ad and has
almost no billboards throughout the country, relying largely on
backing from the prime minister, who appears at his side at rallies
and news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Meciar on the campaign trail has tended to pose with children
for a few select journalists. Meanwhile, officials are looking into
some of the worst alleged scandals of Meciar's time in office. The
police are investigating his former interior minister for having
scuttled a 1998 referendum on direct presidential election and NATO
membership. Meciar's former secret service director was detained
for alleged complicity in a number of crimes, including the 1995
kidnapping of the son of former President Kovac.
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls show Schuster with 34 percent support and
Meciar with 26 percent. Showing 19 percent support is an
independent candidate, Magda Vasaryova, a popular former actress
and a former Czechoslovak ambassador to Austria who appeals to
younger, urban and more educated voters.
</P>
<P>
   Her chances of advancing to the runoff on May 29 slumped with
Meciar's entry into the race. In a runoff pitting Schuster against
Meciar, Ms. Vasaryova's backers are likely to back the Kosice
mayor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
