A4696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EIZENSTAT13-COX     05-12 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EIZENSTAT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Relentless' mastery of policy to be expected from Eizenstat
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta native Stuart Eizenstat has been an all-around
global troubleshooter for the Clinton administration for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat, 56, was named by President Clinton on Wednesday to
take over as the No. 2 official at the Treasury Department,
succeeding Larry Summers, who is moving up to replace Robert Rubin
as Treasury secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat, a one-time Henry Grady High School All-America
basketball star, got his first exposure to national politics in
1976 when, as a young attorney with the Atlanta law firm Powell,
Goldstein, Frazer &AMP; Murphy, he went to work for Jimmy Carter's
Atlanta-based presidential campaign as issues and policy director.
After the election, Carter named the then-34-year-old as his top
White House domestic policy director.
</P>
<P>
   After Carter lost his 1980 re-election campaign, Eizenstat
returned to Powell, Goldstein as director of the firm's
high-powered Washington office for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   It was from there that President-elect Bill Clinton plucked
Eizenstat to become ambassador to the European Union in Brussels in
1993. At the time, he faced intractable trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Eizenstat began his long march upward through the
Clinton administration's economics/foreign policy ranks.
</P>
<P>
   First, he was named undersecretary of commerce for international
trade. He was sworn in two days after Secretary Ron Brown was
killed in a plane crash in Croatia. Brown's successor, Bill Daley,
assigned Eizenstat to de-politicize the department's overseas trade
missions.
</P>
<P>
   He also took the lead on the administration's politically
explosive decision to boycott World Trade Organization proceedings
on the legality of Washington's 35-year-old economic embargo of
Cuba. Eizenstat was given a special White House assignment to
negotiate repatriation of gold seized from Holocaust victims by the
Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   When Madeleine Albright was named secretary of state in 1997,
she summoned her friend of 20 years to join her inner sanctum on
the seventh floor of the State Department as undersecretary of
state for economics, business and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard-trained lawyer, who had also graduated from the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, said he viewed the
post as an opportunity to ``bring an economic dimension'' to
foreign policy decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But he continued his assignment on Nazi gold, persuading three
Swiss banks to return $1.6 billion to Holocaust survivors. He also
continued the thankless task of defusing allied objections over
U.S. policy toward Cuba, even getting pelted with eggs from Mexican
protesters at one point.
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, he took on global warming and the crises
surrounding the India-Pakistan nuclear arms race. His efforts
earned him the sobriquet, ``Undersecretary for Impossible Issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat is known as a skilled negotiator and relentless master
of complicated policy issues. ``Stu is the most dedicated,
relentless sort of master of the policy process that I think I've
ever worked for,'' said Assistant Secretary of State Al Larson.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat spent 10 years flying to Boston to lead weekly spring
semester seminars on presidential decision-making at Harvard's
Kennedy School of Government. That training, he has said, helped
prepare him for his government assignments, in particular on the
importance of keeping Congress informed. Eizenstat, father of two
grown sons, returns to Atlanta regularly to visit his family, which
is active in Atlanta's Jewish community. He has said his
86-year-old mother, Sylvia, has ``the cheapest room in town.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
