u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALVADOR-SUITS-BOS &LR;      05-12 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVADOR-SUITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-SALVADORAN GENERALS SUED BY FAMILIES OF MURDERED CHURCHWOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly two decades after Salvadoran national
guardsmen murdered four American churchwomen, the families of the
victims have filed a lawsuit against two former Salvadoran generals
who have been granted residency in Florida despite evidence that
they covered up the internationally publicized crime.
</P>
<P>
   The case is expected to highlight the growing problem of
suspected human rights offenders who have taken refuge in the
United States in recent years. Human rights advocates and relatives
said they hoped the suit would force US officials to take action
not only against the two ex-generals but also a number of suspected
human rights criminals whose presence in the United States was
documented in a Globe series earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought this suit, not for the money, but to draw attention
to these people and to get them to come out from the rocks under
which they've been hiding,'' said William P. Ford, a New York trial
attorney whose sister Ita, a nun, was among those slain in the 1980
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   The case was one of the most notorious crimes of the 13-year
civil war in El Salvador, which ended in 1991. The churchwoman --
Ford, Maura Clarke, Dorothy Kazel and Jean Donovan -- were
kidnapped by the national guardsmen, taken to a remote location,
raped, then shot to death. The case was solved only after US
authorities circumvented a widespread coverup by the Salvadoran
military.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint filed in US District Court in Miami, the families
charge that Jose Guillermo Garcia, the minister of defense at the
time of the murders, and Carlos Eugenio Vides Casanova, who
directed the National Guard, ``initiated, organized, orchestrated,
directed and implemented a coverup of the Salvadoran National
Guard's responsibility for the crimes under their command.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit echoes the 1993 findings of a United Nations Truth
Commission, which concluded that Garcia had failed to adequately
investigate the murders and that Vides ``knew that members of the
National Guard had committed the assassination and...had
facilitated the concealment of facts, obstructing the respective
judicial investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit is expected to help clarify the vaguely defined role of
US courts in prosecuting human rights crimes committed abroad. The
faimlies charge the two ex-generals with overseeing extrajudicial
killing, torture and crimes against humanity. The former generals
are being asked to pay unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights, a New
York-based group, discovered last year that the two ex-generals
were living in Florida. Garcia lives in Plantation, a suburb of Ft.
Lauderdale. Vides lives in Palm Coast, about 45 minutes north of
Daytona Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Neither could be reached for comment Wednesday. But in a recent
interview with the Globe, Vides adamantly denied his involvement in
the murders or the coverup. He said he entered the United States
through normal channels and had received his visa from a US
consular officer in San Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Citing privacy restrictions, both the State Department and the
Immigration and Naturalization Service have refused to discuss the
cases publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates said they have been stymied in their
efforts to find out why the two ex-generals were granted residency
in the US despite the allegations. US Rep. James McGovern, a
Massachusetts Democrat who has led efforts to press the government
for information about the case, said he planned to send a letter to
President Clinton requesting that all documents relating to the
case be released to the relatives of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about the murders of four American women who
were brutally raped and killed by members of the Salvadoran
National Guard,'' said McGovern. In conversations with US officials
involved in El Salvador over the past several years, he said,
``everybody agrees that Vides Casanova and Garcia were involved in
the coverup, if not worse. Given that reality, how the hell did
they get here?''
</P>
<P>
   US Rep. J. Joseph Moakley, a Massachusetts Democrat who also has
been involved in human rights issues in El Salvador, said he was
upset when he heard that the two former generals had been granted
residency. ``Here are the heads of organizations that were involved
in the killing of the churchwomen and they get residency status? I
know people down there that have never done anything wrong and they
can't get out of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   R. Scott Greathead, a member of the Lawyers Committee for Human
Rights, which helped prepare the case, said he hoped that the suit
would help bring human rights offenders to justice. ``I think it's
enormously important to pursue the notion that the commander who
orders the crimes or who presides over the institutions that are
responsible for this kind of criminal activity are criminally
culpable for their acts,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
