<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4701 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HATE-CRIME-ART-     05-12 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HATE-CRIME-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HATE CRIME BILL GIVES GOV. BUSH TWO PERILOUS POLITICAL
CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rm) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Strange things happen in a state legislative
session when the governor becomes his party's front-runner in the
next presidential election. Everything is refracted through the
national prism, which may be why a hate crimes bill named in honor
of the black man who was dragged to death by whites in East Texas
has unexpectedly emerged as one of the most emotional flash points
of the current session.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats said that Republicans loyal to Gov. George W.
Bush were attempting to bottle up the bill, the James Byrd Jr. Act,
to kill it in committee. That way, it would not land on Bush's desk
and force him to either support it, and alienate right-wing
Republicans who object to the inclusion of protections for gays and
lesbians, or veto it and offer Democrats a juicy issue to batter
him with in the 2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all being driven by emotion, not logic,'' said Sen.
Rodney Ellis, the Houston Democrat who is sponsoring the hate
crimes legislation. ``And when I say emotion, I mean politics. The
Republicans are worried that if they pass the bill and if the
governor signs it, the religious right, the ultra-right, will seek
political retribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some Republicans say it is the Democrats who are
playing politics with the bill, trying to find an issue in Austin
that they can use against Bush in the presidential election. And
what better than painting him as a politician who is not solidly
against hate?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's surprising for everyone that this bill has turned
into a political football, but it's the Democrats who have chosen
to make this a divisive issue for us,'' said Sen. Florence Shapiro,
a Plano Republican. ``I believe they are trying to hurt the
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   At the opening in January of the 140-day session of the Texas
legislature, the last before the 2000 presidential campaign,
everyone had their list of pending bills that were considered most
likely to dominate the session's debate _ Bush's proposed $2
billion in tax cuts, utility deregulation, parental notification
prior to abortions for teen-agers, a pilot program of school
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Expanded hate crimes legislation was on nobody's list.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush's proposed tax cuts are likely to become the
dominant issue of the session before its close on May 31, it is the
hate crimes bill that has stirred the most passionate debate in
Austin in recent weeks. This is partly because the brutal death of
Byrd has given the issue added momentum this year. But politicians
in both parties, while blaming members of the other party for the
situation, acknowledge that it is largely the prospect of a Bush
presidential campaign that has pushed the issue to the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overdramatic standoff over the hate-crimes bill has little
to do with reality or the bill's content, yet it's coming to
dominate the legislative session,'' said a lead editorial in
Wednesday's Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   A vote in the Senate Criminal Justice Committee, the body
charged with deciding whether to forward the bill to the full
senate, was postponed after several hours of behind-the-scenes
negotiations Wednesday night during which members haggled over new
language that might make the bill agreeable to committee
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A new vote is set for Thursday, whether the new language can be
worked out or not, Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   But even so, there is no assurance that the bill would pass the
senate. And if it fails in the committee, supporters say they have
several more tactics to bring it up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to give up,'' Ellis said, though he denied that
he was trying to find a political advantage for national Democrats
in 2000. ``I've been trying to pass this bill since 1990, that's
why I'm doing it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has declined to say whether he favors the bill, only that
he would consider it if it lands on his desk. Nor has the governor
or members of his staff been drawn into the discussion of the
issue's ancillary political implications, even as far as
speculating whether Democrats are attempting to seize on the issue
as a fertile one to use against the governor in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the natural tendency sometimes is to magnify an issue
by bringing in the issue of the governor's national aspirations,''
said Karen Hughes, the governor's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   But there is, at the very least, ``a widely help perception in
the capitol that the governor does not want this bill to reach his
desk,'' said Sen. Eliot Shapleigh, an El Paso Democrat. ``And in
politics, the perception is the reality.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats have charged that high-ranking state Republicans
have been working, behind the scenes, to scuttle the hate-crimes
bill, including perhaps even the governor and his staff. Not true,
Hughes said. And Shapiro said that she had not received a single
call from the governor or anyone on his staff on the subject,
though hers was one of the critical votes on the senate committee
looking at the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ellis said he is inclined to believe Bush has not pushed to
kill the bill _ ``I think I can take my governor at his word,'' he
said _ but he is not so sure that other Republicans in Austin have
decided that it would be best for the party and their governor for
the issue to quietly disappear.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in a fund-raising visit to Austin last week,
met with members of the Byrd family and called on legislators to
pass the hate-crimes bill. Former Sen. Bill Bradley, who is seeking
the Democratic presidential nomination, has also weighed in,
calling at least one Republican legislator and urging her to
support the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flabbergasted when he called,'' Shapiro said. ``I
couldn't imagine why he would ever make the call. I'm afraid I was
rather cool to him, I thought someone was pulling my leg. Then I
realized that the call was coming on the same day the president was
in town and met with the Byrd family. I think this really is
pressure form the Democrat side to turn this into a potential
national issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's office issued a statement Wednesday urging the Texas
legislature to pass the hate-crimes bill, and a spokesman said he
had called Shapiro at the request of Texas Rep. Senfronia Thompson,
a Houston Democrat who sponsored the bill in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Texas already has a five-year-old hate-crimes law, though it
does not specify which groups _ minorities, gays, women, etc. _ are
covered. Opponents of the current bill say it is unnecessary, that
the existing law is satisfactory, that it has even been
strengthened in recent legislative sessions.
</P>
<P>
   But Ellis and others have been trying for the last five
legislative sessions to pass a bill that does specify groups who
might be targets of hate crimes. In past sessions, the debate has
usually been over the inclusion of sexual orientation among the
hate categories. This time, though, that has not emerged as an
issue, at least publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the other senators during the hearing on this bill that
I was glad, at least, that we had progressed to a point in Texas
where opponents of the bill do not feel able to say out loud the
real reason that they oppose it,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Buchanan, a professor of government at the University of
Texas who specializes in presidential politics, agrees that the
governor's national role has had a tendency ``to elevate certain
issues like this that otherwise would not have gotten as much
attention.'' But he thinks there is something a little deeper at
work, too, that the Democrats may have found a way to highlight a
certain predilection in the governor toward playing his cards close
to his vest.
</P>
<P>
   ``People smell a reluctance in the governor to be smoked out,''
Buchanan said, especially on controversial, hot-button issues.
``And they see something like this as significant for that
reason,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of more interest, he said, is that years of bipartisan
cooperation in the legislature _ something that the governor has
often pointed to with pride and sometimes taken partial credit for
_ appeared to be fraying in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   The vote to pass the bill in the house was largely along part
lines, and the breakdown in the senate committee appeared to be
breaking in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes to the very heart of Bush's national appeal, that
he's just what the doctor ordered for Republicans trying to get
over Gingrich and Company,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
