<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, May 16,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PIANO-RECORDING-HISTORY (Undated) _ Is it possible to sum up the
vast recorded legacy of the piano? One answer has begun to arrive
in recent months. Philips has been releasing the first volumes of
Great Pianists of the 20th Century, which it says is the largest
recording project ever. It may well be: so far, 60 two-CD volumes
have been released, and when all 100 volumes become available by
the end of October, they will include 15,006 minutes of music. If
that number is a little difficult to comprehend, you might do the
math this way: figuring on a 35-hour-per-week listening schedule,
which allows time off for lunch and weekends, you would need nearly
two months to hear everything. By Michael Kimmelman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ANDRE-DINNER-FILM (New York) _ ``My Dinner With Andre,''
directed by Louis Malle, was a surprise success in 1981 and quickly
became a cult movie favorite: a virtuosic colloquy between two old
friends, Andre Gregory and Wallace Shawn, whose wide disparities
were philosophical as well as personal. Last fall, the movie was
shown as part of an archival series of classic films at the
Hamptons International Festival, and it has just been re-released,
beginning with an exclusive engagement at the Lincoln Plaza Cinemas
in Manhattan. This seemed a propitious time to bring the two
together for another conversation _ about the film, questions of
art and reality, and what has happened to them since that first
``Dinner.'' By Mel Gussow. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERLIFE-FILM (Undated) _ The Japanese film ``After Life'' by
Hirokazu Kore-eda, redefines our notions of what comes next in a
charming fable that's as profound as it is simple. ``After Life''
asks its audience to imagine that humans, after death, enter a sort
of purgatory that resembles nothing so much as an aging school
building or government depository. There, a helpful staff informs
them one by one of their status, offers sympathy (``So sorry for
your loss'') and then provides assistance with the task that
confronts them: to choose one memory out of their entire life to
take with them for all eternity. Everything else about their life
on earth will be forgotten. By B. Ruby Rich. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PERFORMING-SPACE-THEATER (New York) _ Performing Space 122 in
Manhattan over the years has presented more that 5,000 artists and
commissioned hundreds of new plays and dance works. Increased
financial support, critical accolades from the mainstream press,
and an audience that grew more discerning as it increased all
combined to turn P.S. 122 into what its longtime executive
director, Mark Russell, calls ``the Carnegie Hall of performance
art.'' By Steven Drukman. (Moved). Photo
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARSONS-DANCE (New York) _ The Parsons Dance Company has
attracted large audiences, in locations as diverse as Brazil,
Italy, Australia and St. Louis, Mo. And its two-week engagement at
the Joyce Theater, starting Tuesday, is nearly sold out. ``Almost
all the music will be live,'' said David Parsons, 39, the
dancer-choreographer. In the troupe's lineup is Parsons newest
work, ``Fill the Woods With Light,'' which had its world premiere
at the American Dance Festival in Durham, N.C., last summer, to a
commissioned score by the jazz composer Phil Woods, who will play
it at the Joyce with his Little Big Band. To Woods's mix of funky
rock-and-roll, blues and bossa nova, Parsons created, according to
the composer, ``a warm dance, sort of down and dirty.'' By Valerie
Gladstone. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WOZZECK-OPERA (Undated) _ Two operas are closely linked:
``Wozzeck,'' a devastating success; ``Moses und Aron,'' a failure
of epic stature. The pupil, Alban Berg, wrote the first; the
teacher, Arnold Schoenberg, the second. Perhaps no opera since
Mozart feels as complete as ``Wozzeck.'' ``Moses und Aron'' lies
unfinished, although its first two acts were written some 20 years
before the composer's death in 1951. The words for a third act
awaited only the music for them. Both works played at the
Metropolitan Opera this season, showing us two minds going in
opposite directions. By Bernard Holland. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TOM-ZE-BRAZIL-MUSIC (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ In Brazil, where
leading songwriters routinely cite concepts from anthropology and
pay homage to avant-garde poets, Tom Ze, 62, comes across as a man
who's passionate about ideas. A conversation wandered from his
childhood in Irara, a poor rural town in Bahia in northeastern
Brazil, to his education in contemporary classical composition at
the University of Bahia's school of music, to his tour with the
band Tortoise (which comes to Irving Plaza in Manhattan on
Wednesday) to the Council of Trent, in the mid-16th century. By Jon
Pareles. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIBETAN-ART (New York) _ The art exhibition ``Worlds of
Transformation: Tibetan Art of Wisdom and Compassion,'' is now
showing at Tibet House in Manhattan. Many of the art works suggest
ways to tame the violence in the human mind. By Kay Larson.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ENCAUSTIC-ART (Undated) _ Leave it to modern artists to find
intriguing beauty _ and expressive power _ in the gooey textures of
waxy buildup. New materials and techniques have always attracted
the avant-garde, but paradoxically, during certain periods in the
20th century, an ancient method of image making seized the
imagination of many experimental artists. The results of some of
those experiments are on view from Sunday through Aug. 15 at the
Montclair Art Museum in Montclair, N.J., where ``Waxing Poetic:
Encaustic Art in America'' examines its theme in more than 70 works
by modern and contemporary artists, including Arthur Dove, Jasper
Johns, Lynda Benglis and Michelle Stuart. By Edward M. Gomez.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-DARIA (Undated) _ Daria the character made her debut on MTV's
less verbal animated series ``Beavis and Butt-head'' in 1994.
``Daria'' the show had its premiere in March 1997, when the title
character transferred to a new school. ``I like to think that I've
helped her come out of her shell,'' says Glenn Eichler, who created
the original character and is co-creator, with Susie Lewis Lynn, of
the series. The secret of Daria's popularity (everywhere but in her
own home and school) may be our collective alienation. By Anita
Gates. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TV-CHEADLE (Los Angeles) _ Don Cheadle, who won a Golden Globe
Award for his betrayal of Sammy Davis Jr., in the HBO movie ``The
Rat Pack,'' will play Grant Wiggins in HBO's ``Lesson Before
Dying'' (Saturday at 8 p.m.), based on the 1993 novel by Ernest J.
Gaines. Here Cheadle is a proud and snobbish man eager to break out
of a dirt-poor black community in the South of the 1940s, where he
teaches shoeless children in overalls. By James Sterngold. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-BOOKS-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ Frank T. Siebert's American
Indians book collection will be auctioned in two parts at Sotheby's
in Manhattan, in a sale estimated to total about $7 million. The
first 550 books, which focus on the tribes east of the Mississippi,
will go on view Sunday and be offered for sale on Friday; they are
expected to bring as much as $3.4 million. The rest of the books,
on those of the South and the West, will be auctioned in October.
By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
