<SLUG> BC-CALIF-FUR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL TO PUT DETAILS OF ANIMAL DEATHS ON FUR COATS DEFEATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Beverly Hills voters have overwhelmingly
rejected a proposal to require that fur coats sold here carry a tag
describing the grisly ways that animals used to make them may have
been killed.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, the sole issue in a special election on Tuesday
that drew roughly a quarter of the city's 20,473 registered voters,
was defeated by 63.8 percent to 36.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition A, the Consumer's Right to Informed Choices Act of
1999, would have required that furs, and products with $50 or more
worth of fur on them, carry a tag saying, ``Consumer notice: This
product is made with fur from animals that may have been killed by
electrocution, gassing, neck breaking, poisoning, clubbing,
stomping or drowning and may have been trapped in steel-jaw
leg-hold traps.''
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting the measure, Beverly Hills voters deflected a
direct attack on a symbol of the city's image of glamour and
wealth. Beverly Hills, with its exclusive furriers and department
stores and Rodeo Drive boutiques, is one of the largest fur retail
markets in the United States, according to trade association
figures, and the city's name alone conjures images of wealth and
power.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters said they resented their city's being used as a
stage to attract national attention to the plight of animals killed
for their pelts.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides raised more than $150,000 to press their causes.
The proposal's backers cast the issue as one of truth in
advertising, contending that fur sellers misled consumers by
routinely assuring them that animals were humanely killed for their
pelts. The advocates forced the city to hold a special election by
gathering signatures from more than 15 percent of the voters in
support of a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal drew the backing of some Hollywood stars, including
the comedians Buddy Hackett and Sid Caesar and the actor Jack
Lemmon, who sent a mailer to voters on his own stationery asking
them to consider approving it. About 5,000 homes also received a
videotape with graphic images of animals' being killed. The effort
to win passage drew vast publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set out to educate a few consumers here in Beverly Hills
about how fur animals are killed by clubbing and electrocution, but
we succeeded in educating millions of people around the world,''
said Luke Montgomery, the 25-year-old campaign manager for Yes on
A. ``So if our intent was to educate people about these killing
methods the fur industry uses, we certainly did our job.''
</P>
<P>
   Some voters said they had opposed the proposition because they
felt that it would mean an undue burden for Beverly Hills furriers
and that the tag's wording _ that the animal ``may have been''
killed in a painful manner _ would have been too vague.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
