<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4710 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-CRIME-NYT &LR;      05-12 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REJECTS BACKGROUND CHECKS AT GUN SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: An expanded version of this story is scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET) 
(rm) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Wednesday narrowly defeated a
Democratic measure that would have tightened regulations on the
sale of firearms at gun shows, a clear illustration of lawmakers'
limited appetite for gun control even in the aftermath of the
school shootings in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, senators approved a rival Republican measure that would
create a voluntary system for unlicensed dealers at gun shows to
conduct background checks on their customers. Under current law,
only licensed gun dealers are obliged to do so, and while the
Democratic proposal would have changed that, the Republican
alternative does not. It was a major setback for gun control
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures were put forward as amendments to a broader
juvenile justice bill whose fate has yet to be decided, and the
votes split largely along party lines, with the Republican majority
electing the voluntary measure and the Democratic minority
preferring the mandatory one. The National Rifle Association
lobbied heavily in support of the Republican position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the NRA lives in here,'' grumbled Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., as she left the Senate floor after the votes.
``I find it extraordinarily discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that their measure took into account the rights
of the law-abiding citizens who represent the majority of
participants at gun shows, while the Democrats' amendment was
unduly meddlesome.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, called the Democrats' amendment ``too
costly, too burdensome and too bureaucratic. We all know this is a
much more complex problem than guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had considered their gun show amendment to be the
single item in a package of 10 gun control amendments with the best
shot at garnering enough bipartisan support to pass. Its failure
created serious doubt that any of the rest of their proposals on
gun control would succeed, and it suggested that the political
ground on gun control had not shifted all that much since the 15
deaths at Columbine High School three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have put forward a few modest gun control proposals
that, like the voluntary measure they passed Wednesday, are clearly
intended to deflect any criticism that they are soft on guns and
too cozy with the NRA. But gun control advocates said the
Democrats' amendments, which are themselves quite limited in scope,
are more substantive and potentially effective.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the shootings at Columbine, Republicans have fixed
their attention not on guns but on the cultural realities that may
be influencing violent behavior among children.
</P>
<P>
   That focus was reflected Wednesday in the passage of a
Republican amendment to the juvenile justice bill that would
authorize federal studies into the marketing of violent imagery to
youth and encourage the makers of movies, video games and other
entertainments to enter into voluntary codes of conduct. Democrats,
too, supported the measure, which passed unanimously, 98-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
