<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LARRY-FLYNT-NYT &LR;      05-12 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LARRY-FLYNT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYNT PLEADS GUILTY IN OHIO OBSCENITY CASE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ohio)  (nk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Larry Flynt, who has been battling legal authorities
in Cincinnati for two decades, pleaded guilty Wednesday to two
counts of pandering obscenity in a deal that allows him to avoid
any jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt, publisher of Hustler magazine, and his brother, Jimmy,
partners in an adult gift shop in downtown Cincinnati, agreed to
stop selling sexually explicit videos and pay a $10,000 fine. In
return, 13 obscenity charges against the two were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The Flynts, who were indicted last year on charges of selling
obscene videos to a 14-year-old boy, could have each faced
sentences of up to 24 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said they got the better of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is,'' Flynt said, ``we accomplished
what we wanted. And that is, Hustler magazine can be sold and
distributed in Cincinnati and throughout Hamilton County.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to remove these videos from Hamilton County,''
said the county prosecutor, Mike Allen. ``And that has been
accomplished. It was never our goal to incarcerate the Flynts.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynt had predicted that the trial would demonstrate the
changing mores of society. He had said that contemporary community
standards, a cornerstone of the constitutional definition on
obscenity, had changed sharply since he was convicted of pandering
obscenity in Cincinnati in 1977. But in making his plea agreement
in the third day of jury selection, Flynt chose not to test his
theory.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of First Amendment scholars, Flynt did not win the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flynt's point was that standards have changed in 20 years _
now we'll not know,'' said William Marshall, a law professor at
Northwestern University and a constitutional expert. ``If he still
sees himself as somebody who's carrying the torch on the limits of
obscenity and pornography, I think he lost.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Flynt's lawyers, Lou Sirkin, insisted the plea deal gave
the 56-year-old publisher a way out of the case that leaves him
``without any real scars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients are off the hook,'' Sirkin said. ``Sometimes,
there's an advantage to closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynt had opened his store near the city's gleaming Fountain
Square because, he said, he was angered by crackdowns in Cincinnati
that were making it difficult for him to sell his magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati officials have announced plans to acquire the store
and adjacent properties as part of a development of a new arts
center. If owners of the properties are unwilling to sell, city
officials have indicated they will seek to invoke the powers of
eminent domain.
</P>
<P>
   The trial had been delayed twice because Flynt, an Ohio native,
needed surgery for a urological problem related to his paralysis,
and had developed pneumonia. Flynt has been in a wheelchair since
being shot in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection had been moving slowly, with some potential
jurors in this conservative county saying they found the videos too
distasteful to bear.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors asserted that the images in videos, which often
featured violence against women, were much more profane than those
in Flynt's magazine.
</P>
<P>
   After being convicted in 1977 on pandering obscenity charges,
Flynt served six days of a 7- to 25-year sentence and was released
pending appeal. The conviction was overturned in 1979. The
prosecutor, Allen, promised Wednesday to prosecute Flynt if he
again attempted to sell explicit videos in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does, we will be back in court,'' Allen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
