<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-LAWSUIT13-COX     05-12 0250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LAWSUIT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attorney general joins suit to open Olympic records
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Attorney General Thurbert Baker filed a motion
in Fulton County Superior Court on Wednesday to intervene in a
lawsuit over the sealed Atlanta Olympic bid records.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general is joining the litigation as a co-defendant
with The Atlanta Journal-Constitution in the suit filed by Olympic
officials in their quest to keep bid records closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have upped the ante in my continuing effort to make the
Olympic records public,'' Baker said. ``I'll do everything I can do
as attorney general to move this issue forward and argue the case
for openness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation, which owns the
records, filed suit against the newspapers last week seeking a
judgment that the documents are not subject to the Georgia Open
Records Law.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and the newspapers contend that the Olympics were a
public-private enterprise and that records pertaining to the bid
and the staging of the Games should be accessible.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has made nine boxes of records available to the
public by appointment at the Atlanta History Center, but it
maintains that information related to staff, volunteers and
contributors to the bid effort are private and may be purged from
the files. Some documents were removed from the nine boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
