<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-STEPASHIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE TOUGH-TALKING SPYMASTER REPLACES ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ By replacing Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov with
Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin Wednesday, President Boris N.
Yeltsin substituted one tough-talking former spymaster for another.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is in loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, 69, the outgoing premier who spied for the KGB in the
Middle East and later headed Russia's foreign intelligence agency,
was a survivor who built his own support base among Yeltsin's
Communist opponents and often clashed with an increasingly jealous
president.
</P>
<P>
   In that way, Stepashin, 47, could not be more unlike his
predecessor. He has faithfully served Yeltsin, including a term as
the head of the KGB's domestic successor.
</P>
<P>
   It was in that capacity, in 1994 and early 1995, that Stepashin
was in charge of intelligence operations in Chechnya, where Russia
fought a war that failed to put down a separatist rebellion and
cost tens of thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is well known for his successful work in the government, in
law enforcement bodies, for his active work in Russia's `hot
spots,' '' Yeltsin said of Stepashin in a televised address.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin said Stepashin would give a jump start to an economy he
said had stagnated under Primakov's eight-month tenure, and
Stepashin himself pledged to accelerate market reforms. Amiable and
approachable, Stepashin is a master networker but expresses no
individual political ambitions, all of which could be plusses for
his candidacy as premier.
</P>
<P>
   But Stepashin's reputation for unswerving loyalty to Yeltsin,
and his past role as head of Russian security agencies, have some
lawmakers concerned that he may use the country's second most
powerful post to orchestrate a crackdown against Kremlin opponents.
Other observers agree.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin could ``without fear or reproach break up the
parliament,'' wrote the Moscow daily Izvestia recently.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin joined the Interior Ministry troops in 1973 and from
1980 to 1992 taught at a military academy. In 1986, he earned a
doctorate, defending a thesis with the title ``Party Leadership in
Leningrad's Fire Brigades During World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   He got Yeltsin's attention as head of the defense and security
committee of the Supreme Soviet, the legislature whose power
struggle with the Kremlin ended in street fighting in 1993.
Throughout the conflict, Stepashin sided with Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   That, plus his reputation as a reformist with ideas for
modernizing the security service, led Yeltsin in 1994 to name
Stepashin head of the Federal Counterintelligence Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin played a key role in the Chechnya conflict, first
organizing a botched attempt to overthrow the separatist government
of Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev, then leading the Kremlin's
campaign to ``liquidate illegal bandit groups'' and ``restore
constitutional order.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have said flawed intelligence from Stepashin's
agency persuaded Yeltsin to order the disastrous December 1994
invasion of Grozny that started the war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 he was fired after a mismanaged attempt to solve a
hostage crisis that arose when Chechen guerrillas raided the
southern Russian town of Budyonnovsk. But Stepashin went on in 1997
to become Justice Minister and after April 1998 headed the Interior
Ministry, which oversees Russia's police and internal security
army. In that job, Stepashin has made no noticeable headway in
fighting crime and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he has closed Russia's border with Chechnya and
pledged to have troops shoot ``bandits'' on sight. That solidified
his reputation as a tough talker, but also won praise from Yeltsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
