<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-TCA-CABLE-ART-560     05-12 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TCA-CABLE-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COX COMMUNICATIONS TO BUY TVA CABLE TV  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Ga., La., Pa., Texas, Va.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest consolidation deal by a cable company preparing to
offer telephone, Internet and interactive services as well as
ordinary television to its subscribers, Cox Communications &UR;  &LR; Inc.
announced Wednesday that it was acquiring TCA Cable TV &UR;  &LR; Inc. for
$3.264 billion in stock and cash.
</P>
<P>
   The deal moves Cox up the ladder of the nation's largest cable
companies from No. 5 to No. 4, behind Time Warner &UR;  &LR; Inc.,
AT&AMP;T &UR;  &LR; Corp. (new owner of Telecommunications Inc.) and
Comcast &UR;  &LR; Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, based in Atlanta, will have almost 5 million cable
subscribers upon the completion of two deals _ Wednesday's with
Texas-based TCA, which has 883,000 customers mostly in Texas,
Arkansas and Louisiana, and its recent $1.4 billion acquisition of
Media General Inc., of northern Virginia, with 264,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company was the last attractive takeover candidate among
the publicly traded cable companies,'' Fred Moran, an analyst with
ING Baring Furman Sels, said of TCA. Moran's company was among
several investment firms that gave TCA a ``buy'' rating recently.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation trend that began with enormously expensive
acquisitions by the three biggest cable companies is now spreading
to middle-sized companies, analysts said. Cable companies need to
acquire more systems and subscribers to achieve economies of scale
in building costly new networks capable of delivering telephone and
Internet and interactive digital television to homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox-TCA transaction is valued at $63.89 a share, with Cox
offering TCA shareholders $31.25 in cash and 0.3709 share of Cox
common Class A stock for each TCA share. Cox will also assume $736
million in debt. The transaction has been approved by both
companies' boards.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said that the deal translated to a multiple of roughly 20
times TCA's estimated cash flow in the current fiscal year, which
ends Oct. 31, or a value of about $4,100 a subscriber. He described
that price as ``right in line with other recent transactions in the
industry and very rewarding for TCA shareholders because they get
both cash and stock in Cox, which is one of industry leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T paid about $4,600 a subscriber when it agreed to acquire
MediaOne Group Inc., last week.
</P>
<P>
   Another large multisystem operator, Adelphia
Communications &UR;  &LR; Corp. of Coudersport, Pa., has made three
acquisitions, each for more than $1 billion, of small cable
companies in the last two months. The latest was its purchase of
privately held Harron Communications in April.
</P>
<P>
   James Robbins, Cox's president and chief executive, said his
company planned to make further acquisitions, calling TCA ``the
cornerstone of our plans to offer advanced services in
middle-market communities.''
</P>
<P>
   TCA reaches 74 percent of the homes in its markets, well above
the industry average of 67 percent. And Robbins said it had several
other attributes important to Cox, including what he called ``a
powerful commitment to customer service, a solid management team, a
strong balance sheet and a technologically advanced network.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Cox and TCA are both well ahead of most other cable
companies in making many of the technological improvements needed
to enable cable lines to provide advanced services and digital
television. Both have also been aggressive about deploying new
services to customers relatively quickly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Half of TCA's systems and more than 65 percent of Cox's have
two-way capability for data and telephone services. TCA offers
high-speed Internet access to about 2,300 customers now in
partnership with At-Home Corp. and digital-cable television service
to about 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cox currently has almost 100,000 digital television subscribers,
in eight markets, and provides high-speed Internet access via cable
modem to 88,900 customers; it also provides digital telephone, but
to only about 42,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cox stands today as the most technologically sophisticated
cable operator, already,'' Moran said. ``And TCA, as a
well-positioned Southwestern property, complements Cox perfectly
because they, too, have been aggressive in deployment of new
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the transaction is completed, Cox Enterprises Inc., will be
the majority shareholder of the new company, with 67.2 percent of
the equity and 76.8 percent of the voting power in Cox
Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Following the announcement, Standard &AMP; Poor's placed debt of Cox
Enterprises Inc. and Cox Communications Inc. on CreditWatch with
negative implications, apparently because the Media General and TCA
deals will require substantial financing. While it has an extensive
investment portfolio that includes equity in AT&AMP;T and At-Home, Cox
has not announced a definitive financing plan.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Cox Communications fell $1.9375, to $8.625. TCA Cable
gained $7.96875, or 15.31 percent, to $60.03125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
