<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REJUVENATED SUTTON IS PLAYING AS WELL AS EVER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)  (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The PGA Tour is in Texas this week, which means
Hal Sutton is a good bet to play well.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton will enter the opening round of the GTE Byron Nelson
Classic on Thursday with confidence, playing in a state that has
been good to him. Sutton won last year's Westin Texas Open, he tied
for second at last year's Byron Nelson and he tied for second
earlier this month at the Shell Houston Open.
</P>
<P>
   That success has been part of a resurgence that has rejuvenated
Sutton's career. During the early 1990s, Sutton fell from being one
of the tour's top players to being a player who was embarrassed to
hit balls on the driving range.
</P>
<P>
   His low point came in 1991, when he won only $39,234, finished
185th on the money list and wondered if he should find a different
line of work. But last year, Sutton came back, winning a
career-best $1.83 million, and capping his season with a dramatic
victory at the Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked No. 21 in the world, Sutton is 10th on this year's money
list ($849,070), and at age 41, his game is as good as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been driving the ball really well, my iron game has been
good and my short game is right there,'' said Sutton, the winner of
the 1983 PGA Championship, who has 10 career victories on tour.
``I've never won the Byron Nelson, but this course seems to fit my
game. I'm looking forward to this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The field has six of the world's top 13 players _ Tiger Woods,
Mark O'Meara, Nick Price, Justin Leonard, Phil Mickelson and Fred
Couples. On Thursday and Friday, players will be divided between
two courses at the Four Seasons Resort and Club _ the TPC at Las
Colinas and Cottonwood Valley. The final two rounds will be played
at Las Colinas.
</P>
<P>
   For Sutton, every tournament during the next few months will be
significant because he is trying to secure a place on this year's
U.S. Ryder Cup team. Sutton is currently eighth in the Ryder Cup
points standing, and the top 10 players will make the team, along
with two players selected by this year's captain, Ben Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton made the Ryder Cup team in 1985 and 1987, but both times,
the United States was beaten by Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would very much like to be on the Ryder Cup team,'' Sutton
said. ``I was a part of two teams, and I would like to make that a
brighter spot on my career.''
</P>
<P>
   This has already been a special year for Sutton and his wife,
Ashley, who became the parents of twins, Sadie and Sara, in
January. Sutton skipped the year's first three events, making his
season debut at the Phoenix Open, yet he already has five top 10
finishes in 11 starts. And considering his past success in Texas,
Sutton had reason to feel confident this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's a reason for it, other than maybe
being from Louisiana, Texas is close to home,'' Sutton said. ``A
lot of my friends come over here for the tournaments. Maybe that
has something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of ways, I think I'm a better player than I ever have
been. Experience is both good and bad, depending upon what kind
you've had. But physically and mentally, I feel good. I'm looking
forward to some good things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
