<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      05-12 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: YELTSIN, HIS BACK TO THE WALL, TAKES HIS BRASHEST RISK 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-POLITICS) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Encircled by leftist opponents and reduced almost to a
cipher in opinion polls, clearly ill and on the brink of
impeachment, President Boris Yeltsin rose Wednesday to dismiss a
government he had never embraced and to try once again to position
himself as Russia's savior.
</P>
<P>
   But after eight years of such dramatic sackings, the question
this time was who Yeltsin was trying to save: democratic Russia, or
himself?
</P>
<P>
   In a political career distinguished by bold risks, Yeltsin took
one of the brashest Wednesday. On the eve of a parliamentary vote
on his impeachment, he fired a popular prime minister and dismissed
a government fashioned to mollify the same legislators who are
about to rule on his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin said that Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, the only
leader on whom reformers and Communists could agree after Russia's
economic collapse last August, had gone from stabilizing the nation
to stagnating it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of economic strategy, even today, nine months
later, is still open,'' Yeltsin said, speaking laboriously and not
always clearly, in a broadcast address. ``I am convinced that
procrastination and delay is the most serious blow today to
stability in the economy and the social sphere.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Yeltsin was seeking a return to stability and prosperity,
Wednesday's actions seem likely to lead to precisely the opposite
end. By dismissing a coalition government, Yeltsin may well have
assured his impeachment by an angry lower house of Parliament later
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he lighted the fuse on a political and constitutional
crisis that could easily immobilize Moscow for months, with the
Parliament refusing to approve an impeached president's new
government, and the president dismissing the Parliament in return
and calling new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin also has thrown into limbo the fate of several billion
dollars in loans that the International Monetary Fund has
tentatively pledged to Moscow, and which seem critical to Russia's
fiscal and political stability.
</P>
<P>
   Russia needs the fund's money merely to avoid defaulting on its
existing foreign debt and choking off its access to credit for
years to come. The fund agreed last month to make the loans, but
only if Russia's Communist-controlled Parliament enacts unpopular
tax increases and budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   With Wednesday's dismissal of Primakov, Yeltsin has yanked away
the only politician who could give the Communists the political
cover they need to vote for belt-tightening and against their own
party's economic ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Just what Yeltsin stands to gain in return is not completely
clear. The Parliament is unlikely to confirm his new prime
minister, Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin, and even if he were
confirmed, Stepashin's economic and social proposals would be dead
on arrival in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin could be angling to call new elections in the lower
house of Parliament, betting that voters would sweep out the
Communist plurality and install friendlier legislators. But even
the quickest elections could not present Yeltsin with a new
legislature before September, barely nine months before his term in
office expires and hardly enough time to pass any bold initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, many analysts say, is that Yeltsin was faced with
the very real prospect of political irrelevancy: a drawn-out
impeachment effort in Parliament's lower house, the crumbling of
his support in the upper house, which rejected his firing in April
of Russia's controversial chief prosecutor, and Primakov's own
rising popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has never brooked challenges to his authority, as his
repeated reshufflings of government show. Yeltsin shelled
Parliament in 1993 to put down a Communist uprising. Less
dramatically, he has run through five prime ministers in just the
last year, one of them _ his current envoy in the Yugoslavia
crisis, Victor Chernomyrdin _ twice.
</P>
<P>
   It is commonly believed that Chernomyrdin was first dismissed
because he appeared too eager to succeed Yeltsin as president.
Primakov has repeatedly denied any ambitions for Yeltsin's job, but
opinion polls suggested that he was the most trusted _ and
electable _ politician in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin may have believed, when he accepted Primakov and two
Communist ministers in his government last September, that he had
bought harmony and new support for his policies. What he got was
the renewed pursuit of his impeachment by Communists and steady
nibbling at his authority by Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin looks like a bear in his den which doesn't see any
hint of light around him,'' said Otto Latsis, the veteran political
commentator for the newspaper Novy Izvestia. ``But this is a real
bear. This bear is not scared in such a situation. On the contrary,
it's on the offensive. He is simply showing his political character
hasn't changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
