<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAINS SEEN IN CONSUMER PRIVACY ON INTERNET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study of consumer privacy on the Internet shows that
nearly two-thirds of all commercial Web sites display some type of
warning if they collect personal information, a sharp increase
since last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a remarkable improvement, but there is still work that
needs to be done,'' said Robert Pitofsky, chairman of the Federal
Trade Commission, which has been waiting for the results of the
industry-financed survey before completing a report to Congress on
whether to regulate online privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Industry groups said the findings, made public Wednesday, showed
that new federal regulations were not warranted, but consumer and
privacy advocates said most sites' practices left much to be
desired.
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted by Mary J. Culnan, a business professor
at Georgetown University, at the request of the FTC.
</P>
<P>
   A similar study by the commission last year showed that only 14
percent of Web sites warned consumers how their private information
was being collected, prompting warnings from Pitofsky that he would
push for new regulations in Congress this year if industry efforts
at self-regulation did not yield improvements.
</P>
<P>
   He said the new study would play a central role in the FTC's
recommendations to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which looked at 364 commercial Web sites in February,
found that 93 percent collect some type of personal information. Of
those, 65.7 percent warned that businesses were collecting personal
details from visitors, including names, postal and e-mail addresses
and even likes and dislikes.
</P>
<P>
   While most commercial Web sites now explain how those personal
details are used, just 10 percent of those sites had what the FTC
and industry experts consider comprehensive privacy policies. Those
sites notified consumers, gave them the chance not to have their
personal information collected, allowed customers to review their
information and explained how to contact the company with
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the largest companies on the Web, including IBM, America
Online, Microsoft, Compaq and eBay, paid a total of $60,000 for the
study. They have also formed new trade associations and
certification and monitoring groups like BBB Online and TrustE to
assure consumers of their commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Varney, a former FTC commissioner who is now a
consultant for one of the groups, the Online Privacy Alliance,
called the study an ``absolute vindication'' for those trying to
make self-regulation work.
</P>
<P>
   But privacy advocates noted that few sites offered comprehensive
privacy policies and said that finding underscored the need for a
legal framework establishing basic practices. ``It's clear that
data collection is clearly the norm, yet one-third posted no
privacy practices at all,'' said Beth Givens, director of the
Privacy Rights Clearinghouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
