<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4728 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREASURY-RUBIN-BOS &LR;      05-12 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREASURY-RUBIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY CHIEF RUBIN TO STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin, architect of the Clinton
administration's remarkably successful economic policies at home
and its controversial response to unprecedented financial crises
abroad, submitted his resignation Wednesday after four years in the
post.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton confirmed that Rubin would be leaving the
administration on July 4 and nominated Rubin's trusted top aide,
Deputy Secretary Lawrence Summers, to take over as Treasury
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Washington pundits and Wall Street economists do not expect big
shifts in trade and budget policies if Summers' nomination is
confirmed by Congress. The stock market, after an initial jolt,
recovered Wednesday from news of Rubin's departure.
</P>
<P>
   But his resignation in the midst of war in Kosovo may be
ill-timed for an administration seeking to ensure the continuation
of this country's longest peacetime expansion. Rubin, a former Wall
Street financier, has presided over Treasury during a period of
tremendous growth that saw the benchmark Dow Jones industrial stock
index nearly triple in value.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will miss his cool head and steady hand,'' Clinton said.
``He cares very deeply about the impact of abstract economics on
ordinary people. I can tell you that for all these years, he has
always been one of the administration's most powerful advocates for
the poor and for our cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also praised Summers, a distinguished former professor
of economics at Harvard University who was instrumental in dealing
with Asia's financial crisis last year, as a ``brilliant'' member
of his team. ``Rarely has any individual been so well-prepared to
become secretary of the Treasury,'' the president said at a Rose
Garden ceremony under a bright blue sky. Also attending were
members of his Cabinet and the Congress and Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said he would nominate Stuart Eizenstat,
undersecretary of state for economic affairs, to succeed Summers as
deputy treasury secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, who is 60, said he found it difficult to leave because he
was committed to the administration. Rumors swirled that he may be
a candidate to replace Greenspan when his tenure ends in June 2000,
though administration sources said that was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining his decision to resign, Rubin said his 6 1/2 years in
Washington had been ``all consuming'' and that it was time to
return to his wife in New York, Judith Oxenberg Rubin, who remained
there during his entire tenure and rarely flew to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a truly extraordinary experience,'' Rubin said. He
was first assistant to the president for economic policy from the
beginning of Clinton's first administration in 1993 through 1994
and was appointed the nation's 70th secretary of the Treasury on
Jan. 10, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Rubin will go down in history as one of the handful of
great secretaries of treasury in our country's history,'' said US
Representative Edward J. Markey, a Democrat from Massachusetts.
``Every American with a job should be grateful for his wise and
steady service.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Price, chairman of Franklin Mutual Advisors Inc., which
manages about $24 billion of assets, credited Rubin for keeping
``investor confidence at a very high level, and because of that the
markets have done very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Before entering politics, Rubin amassed a fortune estimated to
exceed $100 million during 26 years as an executive at one of New
York's most prestigious investment banks, Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. He
was co-chairman of the firm when he left.
</P>
<P>
   A Goldman spokesman said Rubin cashed out his equity position in
the firm and ``did not participate'' in the firm's recent public
offering of stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street veteran was widely viewed as possessing a rare
mix of loyalty to the Democratic party _ he raised millions for the
Democrats during the Clinton campaign _ and Wall Street shrewdness
in dealing with Congress and international currency traders.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1995 and 1996, when Congress faced a crisis on the
federal debt limit, Rubin found creative ways to continue funding
of essential government functions.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Munnell, a former assistant secretary of the Treasury for
economic policy who is now a professor at Boston College's School
of Management, said Rubin ``deserves a lot of credit'' for
advocating early in Clinton's first term that ``if you want to
restore confidence you have to get this deficit under control.''
</P>
<P>
   As Treasury secretary, Rubin later found himself the
administration's point man during a string of financial emergencies
that threatened a worldwide recession or worse. They ranged from a
Mexican debt crisis in 1996 to a plunge in Thailand's currency in
1997, which spread throughout Asia and into Russia and threatened
to destabilize Brazil's _ and the world _ economy.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Rubin's Wall Street experience served him well
in dealing with the unprecedented crises. When the yen was going
into freefall last summer and threatening to further destabilize
economies in southeast Asia, he oversaw a US-government led
intervention to buy yen and prop up the currency and followed up
with strong prescriptions for Japanese economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not you want to credit the US Treasury for
arranging that or the Japanese government itself coming to its
senses, the fact is, within short order of the intervention in June
'98, the Japanese government did change course,'' said Adam Posen,
a senior fellow at the Institute for International Economics in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   More controversial under Rubin's term was the administration's
backing of stiff conditions required by the International Monetary
Fund for aiding Russia and Thailand last year. Some critics believe
that the IMF-administration bailout packages worsened, rather than
eased, the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is that problems in Asia and risks to the world were
made worse for a time by the methods applied'' by the IMF and by
the administration, said Allen Sinai, chief global economist for
Primark Decision Economics based in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But, Sinai added, the trio of Greenspan, Rubin, and Summers
ultimately played a major role in calming markets by deciding to
cut interest rates in the United States. ``I have no doubt'' Rubin
was involved in those discussions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers is expected to be confirmed by the Senate Finance
Committee. A spokeswoman for Senator Phil Gramm, Republican of
Texas and chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, said he plans
to hold hearings on the appointment as well.
</P>
<P>
   Summers, a prickly academic who is said to have become wiser in
Washington's ways while working under the low-key Rubin, is
expected to continue his policies. Analysts, for example, expect
Summers to support Rubin's strong-dollar policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Summers, who has written extensively on an array of topics
as an economist, may go further afield in his policies than Rubin
did, said Robert Litan of the Brookings Institution in Washington.
``He might get involved in things you didn't expect _ things like
global warming, for example, because it involves tax policy,''
Litan said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers left the podium in the White House Rose Garden barely
able to contain his emotions. ``I'd like to thank the people who
made it possible for me to be here today,'' he said. ``My teachers,
my parents, my wife, my children. . . . Mr President, thank you for
this opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
