<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-MAYORAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PHILADELPHIA MAYORAL CONTEST, RACIAL ISSUES EMERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It was the kind of day politicians locked in a
close race only dream of. John F. Street, the former City Council
president who is one of five Democrats running for mayor of
Philadelphia, awoke on Tuesday morning to a long and ``heartfelt
endorsement'' in the city's largest newspaper, The Philadelphia
Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   The editorial endorsement not only urged Philadelphians to vote
for Street in the primary next Tuesday but also begged them _
``please, please'' _ to not vote for one of his closest
competitors, Marty Weinberg, a wealthy lawyer who was once an
adviser to Frank L. Rizzo when he was mayor from 1972 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In a stinging rebuke, the endorsement called Weinberg the worst
candidate in the field, based on his association with the
controversial Rizzo.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Street appeared at a news conference with
construction union leaders, who presented him with a check for
$100,000. Opening the envelop, he looked genuinely surprised. ``I
knew it was going to be a check,'' Street said. ``This is
unbelievable.'' He said it was the largest single donation he had
ever received.
</P>
<P>
   In a rough-and-tumble campaign to succeed Mayor Edward G.
Rendell, a popular Democrat who is barred by the city charter from
serving a third consecutive term, Street, 55, appears to be sailing
along as the front-runner, little concerned by the efforts of four
other Democrats and one Republican to overtake him. Altogether, the
six candidates have raised nearly $15 million, a record for
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Under Rendell's leadership for the past eight years,
Philadelphia has reinvented itself as a vibrant city that has grown
in sophistication without losing its characteristic grit and
feistiness. Chronic budget deficits of previous administrations
have turned into annual surpluses, and economic development
abounds.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of Philadelphia's progress, the Republican Party
plans to hold its national convention in this overwhelmingly
Democratic city next year.
</P>
<P>
   In general, all the Democratic candidates have campaigned on the
urgent need to continue the progress of the Rendell administration
by improving the public schools, maintaining fiscal restraint,
expanding economic development into the neighborhoods and lowering
crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sam Katz, who is trying to become the city's first
Republican mayor since 1952 and faces no opposition in the primary,
is making the same points.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, the race for the Democratic nomination
seems to be tightening a bit, based on a number of polls.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mayor's strong support of Street, Weinberg, 62, and
John White Jr., 50, who once led the city's public housing agency
and the Pennsylvania Department of Public Welfare, appear to be
narrowing Street's lead.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Dwight Evans, 44, and Happy Fernandez, 60, a former
council member, are widely viewed as long-shot challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not coincidentally, the campaign dynamics began changing
last month, when the candidates began broadcasting a flurry of
attack ads, the most caustic from Weinberg's campaign. They
underscore how close to the surface the issue of race is in a city
where voters often cast ballots along racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   As the only white candidate among the three leading contenders,
Weinberg is counting heavily on a strong turnout among what he
describes as ``row-house voters,'' essentially, white working- and
middle-class residents who constitute about half the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   It is Weinberg's calculation that if the three black candidates
_ Street, White and Evans _ split the black vote, he can prevail.
Ms. Fernandez, who is white, is not expected to win enough white
voters to affect Weinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on that equation, Weinberg began running television
advertisements that use 18-year-old filmed images of Street, then a
young councilman, shoving a television reporter to the floor. In
another advertisement, Street is shown throwing water in the face
of a City Council administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Each advertisement asks: ``John Street for mayor? You decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg has also run commercials that cite Street's past
financial problems, including bankruptcy, and ask voters, ``Does
this sound like someone who should be in charge of a $2.7
billion?''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Weinberg said of his advertisements: `'I'd like
to view them as informational. These are things voters should know
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg's target audience is also reflected in his promotional
brochure that shows a series of five photographs of the candidate
and voters, only one of whom is black, a little boy.
</P>
<P>
   As the front-runner, Street has resisted being drawn into any
personal attacks. He has not denied the financial problems cited in
the Weinberg commercials, but he has refrained from responding
except to to call on Weinberg to avoid negative campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desperate people do desperate things,'' Street said in an
interview, referring to Weinberg's tactics. ``He is a candidate who
is drowning, failing in almost every way. I consistently said I am
not interested in doing anything negative.''
</P>
<P>
   White was drawn into the advertising wars only after Katz, the
Republican, began broadcasting commercials last week that attacked
the credibility of Weinberg and the managerial skills of White as a
way to prop up Street. Campaign aides in several camps say Katz,
49, would have an easier time defeating Street, especially if the
vote breaks along racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg has virtually ignored Katz's foray into the Democratic
campaign, but White responded to Katz's criticism by calling his
contentions ``Republican lies'' in his own commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by polls showing him gaining on Street and pulling about
even with Weinberg, White said the race was now ``wide open,
anyone's to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm discovering that if the candidates can be viewed at all
objectively, there's a certain comfort level voters have discovered
with me,'' he said in an interview. ``For us, that's a big plus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
