<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4732 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-12 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING STEPPED UP; RUSSIAN CRISIS CLOUDS PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO stepped up its attacks on Yugoslavia
Wednesday, dropping bombs on assorted targets during one of the
busiest 24-hour periods for the air campaign, as political
instability in Russia intruded on diplomatic efforts to find an end
to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides reported unusually heavy bombing in Kosovo, the
southern Serb province that is seeking independence. Yugoslav media
said the bombs struck several civilian targets in both Kosovo and
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic acknowledged that the
military had suffered casualties on the eve of Security Day, which
honors the country's police and security forces. He paid tribute to
the ``many members'' of the country's forces killed in the Kosovo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Yugoslav troops stormed two northern Albanian
villages in an offensive aimed at cutting supply lines of the
Kosovo rebels, in one of their deepest incursions yet from Kosovo,
according to international observers.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, during a visit to the
Albanian capital, Tirana, said the alliance would not allow attacks
that pulled Albania into the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conflict is not going to be sent into Albania,'' he said.
``I want to reassure the people of this country that NATO will not
tolerate any action against this country stemming from the presence
of NATO forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Solana said two dozen US Apache helicopters deployed in Albania
would go into action ``very soon'' against the Yugoslav Army and
police accused of purging Kosovo of hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the alliance had
launched 327 airstrikes, ``the highest number of strike sorties to
date.'' Allied warplanes struck five airfields, eight bridges,
armored vehicles, a missile launcher, barracks, command posts,
ground troops and destroyed five MiG-21 aircrafts on the ground in
raids late Tuesday and early Wednesday, NATO said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our campaign to pin down, cut off and take out Serbian forces
is gathering pace,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   As the air strikes intensified, Russian Prime Minister Boris
Yeltsin warned that his country may pull out of Yugoslav peace
talks and cease its shuttle diplomacy if its proposals are not
given more consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's special envoy for Kosovo, ex-premier Viktor
Chernomyrdin, said without elaborating that Yeltsin's dismissal of
the government ``will cause us special difficulties,'' Interfax
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Solana played down the significance of developments in Russia
for Kosovo diplomacy, telling a Spanish state radio during a brief
interview: ``I am sure that whatever the final result of the change
of government in Russia is, the diplomatic process will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   --Defense Secretary William Cohen said the air strikes were
having an impact far beyond degrading Serb military forces. He said
Pentagon officials are now getting reports that senior military
leaders have joined the elite in Yugoslavia in sending their
families out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic may not admit that he is taking his country down the
road to ruin _ politically, economically and militarily _ but his
top leadership is apparently more realistic,'' the secretary said.
He added that Yugoslav leaders ``are now seeing the handwriting on
the wall, and it's not a forgery.''
</P>
<P>
   -- As the ashes of three Chinese journalists killed in the NATO
bombing of Beijing's embassy in Belegrade returned to Peking in an
emotional welcome, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, on a
16-hour visit to China, said he had apologized for the accident,
but China refused to soften demands that NATO halt its air war. He
said he had come to Beijing to try to persuade China to play a
constructive role in the search for a solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   -- The United Nations refugee agency, UNHCR, said new donations
from the United States and Canada will help it cope with a cash
crunch that threatened to disrupt getting help to Kosovo refugees.
The Geneva-based office of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees
had appealed for money to cover the Kosovo crisis for the first six
months of this year. Since warning of the cash crisis,the UNHCR
said it had received donations of $5 million each from the United
States and Canada. But officials said the money crisis is not over.
</P>
<P>
   The military buildup also continued. The 104th Fighter Wing in
Westfield, Mass., joined two units in other states being called to
active duty for the Kosovo operation.
</P>
<P>
   The other two units are the 124th Fighter Wing, in Boise, Idaho;
and the 110th Fighter Wing, in Battle Creek, Mich. All three will
depart from Barnes Air National Guard base in Westfield as a joint
force under one commander.
</P>
<P>
   Defense officials said the units will take six A-10 attack jets,
low-flying tank-killing planes also known as Wart Hogs, that have
been put to use recently over Kosovo, as well as crews, maintenance
and support personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Those officials refused to say how many troops will go, when
they might go or how long they might be gone, saying such
information was confidential.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, 47 members of the 260th Air Traffic Control
Squadron was ordered to report Wednesday to Pease Air National
Guard Base to provide help in the conflict. Though the date for
their departure or where they will be going was not known, they
were expected to serve for 270 days.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest airstrikes, explosions boomed Wednesday afternoon
across Nis, a frequent target in central Serbia, and cluster bombs
rained down on the eastern sector of the city, reported Tanjug, the
state news agency.
</P>
<P>
   The city is the headquarters of the army group responsible for
operations in Kosovo. Eight missiles struck the Kosovo capital,
Pristina, Wednesday morning, hitting the local airport and two
suburbs, the Serb-run media center there reported.
</P>
<P>
   An ``unspecified'' number of people were killed in an attack on
a Serb collective farm in Svetlje, housing Serb refugees from
northern Kosovo and two nearby villages, Yugoslav media reported.
Two people were wounded in airstrikes near the central Serbian town
of Kraljevo.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people, all reportedly civilians, were killed in the
preceding 24-hour heavy bombardment, the Yugoslav media said.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary's sole remaining rail link with Yugoslavia, a 20-mile
route running between the Hungarian town of Szeged and the Yugoslav
town of Subotica, was cut by a bombed overpass that collapsed on
the track, the Hungarian State Railways said. Other links have
already been bombed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is demanding a total withdrawal of Milosevic's forces from
Kosovo, the return of refugees and the deployment of an
international peacekeeping force before it halts the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff reporter Anne E. Kornblut contributed to this report.
Wire service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
