<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DIPLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKEUP IN RUSSIA ADDS UNCERTAINTY TO KOSOVO TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-POLITICS) 
(sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The turmoil in Russia on Wednesday appeared to
represent another impediment to the Clinton administration's hopes
of finding a diplomatic end to the conflict in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   After dismissing his government, President Boris Yeltsin
threatened to withdraw from negotiations on Kosovo, saying that
Moscow's proposals were being repeatedly ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our calls and repeated suggestions are clearly not reaching
somebody,'' a Kremlin spokesman quoted Yeltsin as saying. Without
calling specifically for NATO to halt its bombing as he has in the
past, this appeared to be Yeltsin's point.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which has tried hard to make Russia a partner
in the search for a Kosovo settlement, said the changes in Moscow
were internal matters. American officials also said they hoped the
Russian special envoy to the Balkans, Victor Chernomyrdin, would
continue in his role as a shuttle diplomat with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But several officials said they worried that the Russians'
wrangling could sideline a peace settlement, or shift the emphasis
away from one, at least in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis unfolded as Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott
met in Moscow with top Russian officials, for the second time in
three weeks, to try to work out details on an international
security force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Among the officials Talbott met with was Igor Ivanov, the
foreign minister. But because of the shakeup in the Russian
government on Wednesday, Ivanov only held the post as acting
minister and his future was uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov has become a key contact for Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who has spent up to two hours on some days talking to him
during the Kosovo crisis as she tried to insure that he understood
NATO's positions.
</P>
<P>
   She met with Ivanov in Oslo a month ago to set the stage for
bringing Russia into the administration's orbit on Kosovo. Last
week the seven richest industrial countries and Russia agreed on a
joint statement of principles for ending the war, the most
far-reaching agreement between NATO countries and Russia on Kosovo
so far.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott also spoke on Wednesday with Chernomyrdin. Chernomyrdin
does not hold a government position, and his role as envoy was
probably not threatened, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Chernomyrdin remained as involved in the diplomacy
as he has in the past several weeks, his platform within Russia
could well be eroded by internal politics.
</P>
<P>
   A special adviser to Albright, Stephen Sestanovich, acknowledged
at a congressional hearing on Wednesday that it was unclear how the
Russian envoy would be affected if Sergei Stepashin, Yeltsin's
choice for prime minister, assumed the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rather hard to tell at this stage,'' Sestanovich said.
``We know Mr. Stepashin; we don't know whether he will have a
mandate to pursue different policies from Mr. Chernomyrdin.''
</P>
<P>
   With the mistaken bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade
having created difficulties for a diplomatic solution,
administration and NATO officials said they hoped the upheaval in
Moscow would have only a limited effect on the process.
</P>
<P>
   The French president, Jacques Chirac, arrived in Moscow on
Wednesday to talk to the Russians about their role in ending the
war. The French, who view the Russians as an essential element in
solving the Kosovo conflict, said they would persist in working
with the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The groundwork was laid last week by the G8 in Bonn, and our
objective is to resolve this conflict,'' said Hubert Vedrine, the
French foreign minister, in alluding to the agreement between the
Group of 7 and Russia last week.'
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian foreign minister, Lloyd Axworthy, said on Wednesday
that Ivanvov told him in a telephone conversation on Wednesday he
could be reappointed as foreign minister if Stepashin was confirmed
by the Duma. But given Ivanov's closeness to Yevgeny Primakov, the
dismissed prime minister, it was not a certainty that Ivanov would
remain foreign minister, other officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sestanovich, the adviser to Albright, gave a careful view of
what the Russians could accomplish in Kosovo, when he appeared at
hearings of the House International Relations Committee. ``Their
objectives, if we look at what they say, are to end this
conflict,'' Sestanovich said. ``They say that it has to be ended on
a basis that protects the territorial integrity of Yugoslavia. And
with that we can agree.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sestanovich cautioned: ``If Russian objectives are to solve
this problem in Kosovo, and instability in the Balkans more
generally, in a way that is simply aimed at hampering American
policy, then we won't be able to cooperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott left Moscow on Wednesday night for Helsinki where he was
to meet with the Finnish president, Martti Ahtisaari. The
administration and other NATO countries believe that Ahtisaari may
be a suitable negotiator with the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan
Milosevic, when NATO gets to the point of presenting a cohesive
plan concerning an international security force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari heads a country that is not a member of NATO _ a plus
in the mind of Milosevic. But the Finnish president has been
outspoken against the the reports of atrocities and forced
expulsions against ethnic Albanians, a position that benefits NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Finland is scheduled to take the chair of the European Union in
July for six months, a position that would give Ahtisaari extra
clout as a negotiator with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian envoy, Chernomyrdin, was also expected to visit
Ahtisaari on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has stressed that there is still a lot of
work to do with the Russians on bringing their and those of NATO
closer together on the key elements of the international force that
is planned to secure Kosovo and take back refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Russia would like to diminish NATO's role in such a force, but
if agreement can be reached, Milosevic would be presented with the
plan, administration and NATO diplomats said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
