<HEADLINE>
HOUSE TENTATIVELY OKS CAMPAIGN FINANCE PACKAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With the blessing of top legislative leaders,
the House on Wednesday tentatively approved new rules for reporting
political contributions that should make it easier for the public
to decipher a campaign's backers and activities, including
last-minute infusions of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with a separately approved bill to put the information
on the Internet, proponents of the reforms said Texas is on the
verge of eliminating secretive contributions of cash and corporate
``soft money'' into state officials' campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In a concession to candidates, House Bill 5 by Rep. Pete
Gallego, D-Alpine, increases from $50 to $100 the amount of
contributions and expenditures that must be itemized in reports
filed with the Texas Ethics Commission. But its main features are
aimed at allowing public scrutiny of campaigns for governor, judge
and the Legislature, the author said.
</P>
<P>
   If finally approved by the House on Thursday, Gallego's bill
goes to the Senate, where key supporters are prepared to press it
through the legislative process in the session's waning days. The
biennial lawmaking session ends May 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly significant for the fact that for the first
time, we do some innovative things like soft money reporting,''
Gallego said. Soft money is the unlimited money that corporations
or others can give to political parties rather than individual
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a provision that requires corporations to report the
amount of money they spent ... on administrative expenses for
political action committees that wasn't there before,'' Gallego
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of sunshine on the political process, it makes a big
difference,'' he said. The bill was crafted during months of
meetings that involved candidates, elected officials, political
parties and advocacy groups. Only provisions that both major
parties agreed to in advance were included in the package, Gallego
said.
</P>
<P>
   One key improvement, he said, would be a new requirement to
report direct expenditures of more than $5,000 that aren't funneled
through a campaign, such as when a benefactor buys airtime for a
candidate's commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a big contributor to causes, particularly if you're
doing it in the last few days of a campaign, within 24 hours you
have to file either by fax or telegram a report with the ethics
commission what you've spent,'' Gallego said. ``That's a good thing
because it lets you know who's doing what in the final days of the
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposals should work well with a previously approved
requirement for electronic filing of campaign finance reports, the
author said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday is the last day for the House to give initial approval
to its own members' bills, so the chamber is expected to work until
midnight if necessary. But most of the measures approved this week
face uncertain fates in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In other action Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   The House approved new safety regulations for the state's 500
body piercing studios, including a mandate to obtain a parent's
written consent before piercing is done to anyone under age 18.
</P>
<P>
   The measure controls piercing of noses and navels, but not ear
lobes, which rarely produce consumer complaints, said sponsoring
Rep. Ron Clark, R-Sherman. After being changed to prohibit piercing
of an intoxicated person, Senate Bill 61 by Sen. Frank Madla, D-San
Antonio, was headed back to the originating chamber for
reconsideration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
