<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4745 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-ART-2     05-12 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ANOTHER GOVERNMENT SHAKEUP, YELTSIN FIRES PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also RUSSIA-ASSESS, RUSSIA-DIPLO, RUSSIA-STEPASHIN)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Ever the master of surprise, Russian President Boris
Yeltsin abruptly fired Prime Minister Yevgeni Primakov on
Wednesday, pushing Russia to the brink of a fresh political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's latest government shakeup _ his third in 15 months _
comes on the eve of the what promises to be a stormy and emotional
debate on his impeachment in the Russian parliament on Thursday,
with the outcome of a vote scheduled for Saturday increasingly
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Although the danger of his being removed from office is slight,
Yeltsin _ weakened by poor health and isolated politically - has
already succeeded in throwing Russia's future into uncertainty,
jeopardizing a pending package of badly need foreign credits and
increasing the chances of early parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised statement Wednesday, the 68-year-old president
said he had taken the ``difficult decision'' because Primakov,
whose coalition cabinet included Communist ministers, had failed to
pull Russia out of its economic crisis by putting too much emphasis
on political consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The premier's caution, his readiness to take only those
measures that get maximum approval and support are now beginning to
cause damage,'' said Yeltsin, whose face looked pallid and puffy,
and whose speech was labored. ``The time of soothing talk is over,
the turn of vigorous action has long come.''
</P>
<P>
   To replace Primakov, a former foreign minister appointed eight
months ago as a compromise candidate, Yeltsin named Interior
Minister Sergei Stepashin, a Yeltsin loyalist and a veteran of
Russia's security services whose own views on Russia's troubled
economic reforms are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Russian parliament's rebellious mood, Stepashin's
confirmation is by no means assured. Liberal deputies hold him
accountable for his role in the bloody Chechen war, while
Communists, overlooking his law and order credentials, might vote
him down as a Yeltsin appointee. His rejection would open the
possibility for Yeltsin to make his next surprise move _ a
disbanding of the lower house, followed by early parliamentary
elections, perhaps by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by the president's decision to fire a government that
had their support, Yeltsin's Communist opposition Wednesday called
for an emergency meeting of the parliament's upper house to review
Primakov's dismissal, and ordered its supporters out onto the
streets in protest.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's sudden announcement topped a week of steady
speculation about Primakov's coming fall from power. Yeltsin, in
recent appearances, has seemed to go out of his way to snub his
prime minister. In private, the president's aides described
Primakov as an unreconstructed Communist, who if left in office,
would slowly lead the country back to its authoritarian past.
</P>
<P>
   With parliamentary elections now due in December, and his own
presidential term expiring in the summer of 2000, Yeltsin, Russia's
first democratically elected president, is concerned about the
survival of a legacy that includes the introduction of a fledgling
market economy, freedom of the press and the return of Russia to
the circle of Western democracies, aides say.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's mounting irritation with Primakov has also
been linked to his apparent frustration over the prime minister's
independence, popularity and above all, his close ties to the
Communists. Primakov may have signed his government's death warrant
Tuesday night when he once again reassured his left-wing allies
that he would resign rather than accept the dismissal of his top
Communist deputies, Yuri Maslyukov and Gennadi Kulik.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, a Middle East expert and former intelligence chief who
once served as a top diplomatic adviser to Soviet leaders, was
widely credited with calming Russia's political turbulence after he
took office last fall. Ever the cautious diplomat, he avoided any
grand schemes for economic recovery but managed to avoid the
hyperinflation, and total economic disaster that many experts had
predicted for Russia after last August's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   According to opinion polls, Primakov soon emerged as Russia's
most trusted politician, even as economic statistics showed a
steady rise in the number of Russians living below poverty levels.
In a recent poll by the Center for International Sociological
Studies of 4,730 russians, 82 percent credited Primakov with
stabilizing the political situation in the country, while 77
percent approved of his domestic policies. But the same poll showed
only 40 percent in favor of Primakov's foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
   At a farewell meeting with his cabinet Wednesday, Primakov said
his team had nothing to be ashamed of, listing his government's
success at paying back debts to pensioners, and at preventing the
collapse of the currency. After packing up his office, Primakov,
69, spent the evening watching a European soccer championship at a
Moscow stadium.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although Primakov repeatedly denied any presidential ambitions,
his name inevitably surfaced as a plausible candidate to succeed
Yeltsin next year. But without the authority that comes with power,
it is not clear whether Primakov, who suffers from a back ailment,
will pursue a political career of his own.
</P>
<P>
   With the Russian economy crippled by debt, corruption and
mismanagement, Primakov's lack of any economic program become more
and more of a liability. ``Last fall, Primakov did a great thing
when he managed to stabilize the situation,'' said Mikhail Berger,
editor of the newspaper Sevodnya in a radio interview Wednesday.
``Brakes are an important part of any car. You cannot drive a car
without brakes. But if you apply the brakes all the time, it is no
longer a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Russian politicians _ including Moscow Mayor Yuri
luzhkov, the leading presidential candidate _ had recently stepped
up their criticism of Primakov, accusing him of marking time as
economic stagnation set in. But the timing of his dismissal _ on
the eve of a highly charged impeachment debate _ was greeted with
almost universal dismay.
</P>
<P>
   Grigori Yavlinky, leader of Yabloko, Russia's largest liberal
party, compared Yeltsin's move to a chess player who overturns the
chessboard, throwing the pieces, and his opponents, into disarray.
``It is a typical radical move,'' said Yavlinsky who was the first
to float Primakov's nomination during Russia's last political
crisis which followed Yeltsin's dismissal of the short-lived
government Sergei Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
   Yavlinsky had harsh words for Primakov's economic performance
but he was even more pessimisstic about the prospects for the
Russian economy during the coming period of political instability.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov called Primakov's firing ``unjust and unjustified,''
while several regional governors lamented the onset of another
period of political inactivity, as a new government puts together a
new team and new policies.
</P>
<P>
   Without a fully functioning government, the Russian parliament
is unlikely to give prompt approval to a package of politically
unpopular measures set by the International Monetary Fund as
conditions for the staggered delivery of an $4.5 billion credit,
earmarked for payment on Russia's outstanding IMF loans.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's political disarray has also raised concerns about
Moscow's ability to follow through on its diplomatic initiatives in
the search for peace in Kosovo. At a press conference Wednesday
held jointly with U.S. assistant secretary of state Strobe Talbott,
Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's special Balkans enovy, admitted that
frequent changes in government ``create certain problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, the biggest concern is over a potential
constitutional clash that could develop if the parliament's lower
house votes on Saturday to start impeachment, and subsequently,
votes to reject Stepashin's nomination as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian constitution, drafted by the Yeltsin Kremlin and
adopted in 1993, gives the parliament's lower house three chances
to approve the president's nominee for prime minister. If the
nomination fails on the third try, the president is obligated to
disband the parliament and set early elections.
</P>
<P>
   However, the same constitution forbids the president from
disbanding the parliament once an impeachement vote is taken. If
both events take place, then Russia could face another
constitutional clash like the one that led to the street violence
and shelling of the old parliament by army tanks in October 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five charges brought against Yeltsin in the indictment
pending in parliament, only one _ accusing him of waging of an
illegal war in the breakaway region of Chechnya from 1994 to 1996 _
has a chance of collecting the 300 votes needed for passage in the
450-seat lower chamber. The difference will be made up by members
of Yavlinsky's Yabloko faction which on this charge alone, is
prepared to join the Communist-led opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Before a russian president can be ousted from office, the
impeachment charge must be cleared by both the Constitutional Court
and the Supreme Court, and finally must be approved by the Council
of Federation, the parliament's upper house. The process could take
months, and could be easily tripped up by legalities at any step.
</P>
<P>
   A successful impeachment vote Saturday would deliver another
devastating blow to Yeltsin's dwindling authority. In recent
months, he has already seen his once-assured support in the Council
of Federation _ made up of regional governors and legislative
leaders _ chipped away in a battle over the Kremlin's efforts to
force Russia's chief prosecutor, Yuri Skuratov, out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts argued that Yeltsin's gamble may pay off, with the
restoration of a balance of power between the presidency and the
parliament. ``Tthe president suddenly realized that the price being
paid for Primakov's support in the Duma was too high,'' said Vitaly
Tretyakov, editor of the Independent Newspaper, a Moscow daily.
``He realized that in this triangle two is company, but three is a
crowd, and he was the odd man out. He couldn't bear it, and fired
Primakov to restore the balance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
