<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     05-12 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TEAM EFFORT SUREST WAY TO WIN TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A decade ago, a continent away, a basketball team was
practicing and a rookie guard was penetrating and the players with
him on offense were observing. The coach, by reputation the
creative wizard of the day, watched the pint-size point man dribble
into the lane, into traffic, leave his feet and throw the ball to
... no one.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson's face became contorted with disgust, and he shouted
his Golden State Warriors to a halt. He marched over to Tim
Hardaway and placed his hand on the new kid's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentlemen,'' Nelson said, ``we have ourselves a special talent
here. But for him to do what he does best, which is make all of you
look better, you're going to have to put yourself in position for
him to pass you the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Practice continued. Later that day, Oct. 17, 1989, an earthquake
fractured the San Francisco Bay area. For its pro basketball team,
which was loaded with offensive weaponry and had lightning-quick
Hardaway at the trigger, the aftershocks would last for years.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, by the time the structural core had collapsed for
Nelson and Golden State and Hardaway wound up with Pat Riley in
Miami, he was an All-Star with a surgically repaired knee, a gunner
in his own right who took one look at the undistinguished players
around him and decided they were all his license to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he first got here, I don't think he trusted the other
guys,'' said Bob McAdoo, a Riley assistant who fired up a few
forced jumpers in his own playing days. ``He's had to learn to
trust them, to not think he has to take every big shot.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the story of Game 2, Heat versus Knicks, Miami's
desperate push for an extended first-round playoff series. Whether
the Heat could win a game at Madison Square Garden, Wednesday night
or in Game 4 Friday, and take the series back to Miami was likely
to depend on the Heat's ability to make the Game 2 story a
serieslong theme.
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Mourning aside, could Hardaway continue to trust the
likes of Keith Askins, Jamal Mashburn and P.J. Brown? Could he
count on Riley's commonplace supporting cast to keep making the
shots?
</P>
<P>
   There are no sure things in playoffs this season, now that the
Bulls dynasty has run its course, and that means every flawed team
has its share of insider intrigue. So while the evolving Knicks
have struggled to define themselves in relation to Patrick Ewing,
their longtime 7-foot franchise player, here is the Heat,
top-seeded in the Eastern Conference, still trying to decide how
best to use its 6-foot shooting point guard.
</P>
<P>
   That's the inherent appeal of the pro playoffs, as opposed to
the one-and-out college tournament. The best-of-5 or best-of-7-game
series allows for adjustments in strategy and attitude. Every game
can be a new season, which is why no declarative statements should
be made until the word elimination is attached to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got on Tim about getting better shots after the first game,
about not always settling for the long jumper,'' McAdoo admitted
before the Miami shoot-around Wednesday at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway had taken 19 shots in Game 1, made four. His right knee
is hurting, though he threatens to terminate any interview in which
he is asked how much. Whatever. As much as Hardaway has tormented
the Knicks from afar, he has had his share of games when,
completely healthy, his shots seemed magnetically drawn to the rim,
front and back. With all due respect to this electric player, no
team ever won a championship on the strength of a little man
hoisting jumpers from 23 feet.
</P>
<P>
   McAdoo said Hardaway's instructions for Game 2 were to not
surrender his dribble to the Knicks' pressure, get into the teeth
of the defense, create a medium-range game, as opposed to always
looking for a Mourning dunk or a 3-point shot. Hardaway took five
shots and the Heat won by 10. He was back in that practice gym,
distributing the ball the way Nelson envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``A win is a win,'' he said Wednesday night. ``I'm not worried
about getting off my shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has always said the same thing, but the proof of
conviction is how ego mixes with team when the season is on the
line and the cast starts clanking its shots. Out West, Hardaway had
the young Mitch Richmond and Chris Mullin around him, and then
Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Knicks, who have other perimeter scorers, there is no
one of comparable ability on this Heat team, built in the combative
image of its celebrity architect.
</P>
<P>
   Four years and counting in Miami, this is Pat Riley's team. If
it wins, he gets the glory. If not, then he, not Hardaway, takes
the heat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
