<HEADER>
A4753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUBIN-MARKET-ART-NYT &LR;      05-12 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBIN-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER INITIAL JOLT, MARKETS REBOUND FROM RUBIN NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUBIN-RESIGN, RUBIN-ASSESS, RUBIN-SUMMERS,
RUBIN-EIZENSTADT, EDIT-RUBIN, RUBIN-TEXT) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on Dow and trade balance is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street flinched, but then quickly brushed off
Wednesday's announcement that Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin was
resigning and being replaced by Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks did fall on the news, with the Dow Jones industrial
average plunging more than 200 points in the morning. Bond prices
dipped and the dollar, which was rallying in Europe because of the
sudden dismissal of the Russian prime minister, gave up some gains.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't take long for traders and investors to realize
that the resignation news was not that bad and the three markets
began to rebound almost immediately. Indeed, Russian President
Boris Yeltsin's dismissal of Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov had
more impact, but it was still muted. While the dollar moved as some
investors sought a haven, bond and stock prices fell only
moderately in key emerging market countries.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the day in the United States, stocks were
mostly higher, the dollar rose against the euro and bond prices
were little changed.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the rebound is that Summers is respected, though
his bluntness might mean some volatile trading days when he speaks
his mind. Additionally, Clinton administration policy initiatives,
including support for a strong dollar, open markets and its focus
on the repair of global financial markets, are not expected to
change. The U.S. economy is in good shape and the world financial
crisis has subsided.
</P>
<P>
   But more importantly, Wall Street was prepared. Rumors of a
Rubin-Summers switch have been circulating for so long that the
only uncertainty was the timing of the change. The Treasury went to
great lengths to prepare financial markets and investors for the
change, even insisting that the cover photograph for a Time
magazine article on the taming of the global financial crisis
include Summers with Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a move that had long been contemplated,'' said John
Lipsky, the chief economist at Chase Manhattan Bank. ``And there is
no sense that Summers is untried in directing policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Wien, the U.S. investment strategist at Morgan Stanley,
Dean Witter, said the change in leadership at the Treasury would
not have an effect on his outlook for the stock market. But he did
say there would be a ``vacuum in the Cabinet'' because Rubin's
contributions included more than his Treasury duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``His influence and his wisdom covered geopolitical areas and
areas of public policy well beyond financial, and that is what will
be sorely missed,'' Wien said.
</P>
<P>
   He also argued that with ``the credibility of the Clinton
administration damaged, Rubin was the one person who had the
respect of Congress and the respect of our partners abroad. And it
will take a while for Summers to grow into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Fand, the senior foreign exchange strategist at
BankBoston Corp., suggested that the appointment of Summers might
even give an extra upward push to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dollar will benefit from his frankness on the problems
with the Japanese and European economies,'' said Fand, because his
comments will presumably make it clearer to investors why they
should be investing in the United States rather than Europe or
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Fand also said that ``the dollar is likely to be more volatile
because Summers will be less controlled with his remarks.''
</P>
<P>
   In the stock market, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 25.78
points, to 11,000.37. Two oil companies _ Exxon, off 2 9/16 a
share, to 79 1/16, and Chevron, down 3], to 94 11/16 _ accounted
for most of the Dow's loss as the price of oil fell to $17.57 a
barrel, dropping for the fourth time in the last five trading days.
</P>
<P>
   The other major stock indexes ended higher. The NASDAQ composite
index rose 39.86 points, or 1.55 percent, to 2,606.54, led by Cisco
Systems, which reported better-than-expected earnings for its third
quarter and announced a 2-for-1 stock split. Earnings jumped 33
percent and the stock rose 6~ a share, to 118}.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks set a new closing
high, finishing at 1,364.00, up 8.39 points. The Russell index of
2,000 smaller-company stocks climbed 2.45 points, at 449.26.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff that greeted the Rubin announcement was a reflection
that traders cannot take time to assess important news. If it
appears to be bad, they have to sell immediately to protect
themselves from serious losses. If the news proves to be less
worrisome, they can always buy again, even profiting from the
decline.
</P>
<P>
   Bond investors remained nervous Wednesday ahead of reports on
producer and consumer inflation, set for release Thursday and
Friday respectively, and on retail sales Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's Treasury auction of 10-year notes went much better
than Tuesday's five-year note auction, giving the bond market a
little lift. The new 10-year note was auctioned at a yield of 5.51
percent; by the end of the day that slipped to 5.50 percent as the
price, which moves in the opposite direction, rose.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond was up 4/32, to 91 30/32, while
the yield slipped to 5.82 percent Wednesday. A poor five-year
auction Tuesday had raised the yield on the 30-year bond to 5.83
percent, its highest in almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar strengthened against the euro, with the euro ending
the day at $1.0653, from $1.0715 on Tuesday. The dollar was off
slightly against the Japanese yen, at 120.95 yen compared with
120.97 Tuesday. The dollar did rebound from the intraday low
against the yen after the Rubin announcement.
</P>
<P>
   In emerging markets, the Bovespa stock index in Brazil dropped
nearly 1 percent, while the Bolsa index in Mexico fell 1.74
percent. The difference _ or spread _ between the yield on Russian
bonds and comparable U.S. Treasuries jumped to 42.73 percent, which
reflected a 10 percent drop in prices, according to J.P Morgan
Securities. But the moves in Latin American bond markets were much
smaller. In Brazil, the spread widened less than a quarter of a
percentage point to 8.88 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
