r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYCOS-SFCHRON &LR;      05-12 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 USA Networks, Lycos Officially Call Off Merger
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Officially throwing in the towel on a controversial deal that
shareholders opposed and Wall Street doubted, Lycos Inc. yesterday
scotched its $22 billion merger with USA Networks by mutual
consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disappointment,'' Lycos chief executive Bob Davis said
in a conference call with reporters and analysts. ``We had a very
difficult time explaining the value of this deal'' to the financial
community.
</P>
<P>
   In February, USA Networks agreed to buy Lycos of Waltham, Mass.,
and combine it with the cable TV network's Home Shopping Network
cable channel and Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch Inc., a ticket
agency and online entertainment directory.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos _ the third-most-popular site on the Web _ is in a race
with America Online, Yahoo, Excite and others to reach the most
consumers with an all-in-one commercial Web site. Such super sites,
or ``portals,'' combine online shopping, news, Web searches, e-mail
and chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The quashed merger will have ``absolutely no bearing'' on Lycos'
proposed $83 million buyout of San Francisco's Wired Digital, Lycos
officials said. The long-planned deal to acquire the online news
service, which employs 160, should be completed next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people wondered how a leading content provider like Wired
Digital fit into the same company that owns Home Shopping
Network,'' said a Wired Digital employee, who asked not to be
named. ``The question was: What is our role in this beautiful
e-commerce machine?''
</P>
<P>
   Those views evidently were shared by many on Wall Street, who
balked at the idea of an Internet company and cable TV network
melding operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were misgivings about this hybrid Internet-electronic
retailing company that was not a pure Internet or media
transaction,'' said Barry Parr, e-commerce analyst at International
Data Corp. in Mountain View. ``There was a fair amount of
disconnect between two companies with far different selling styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the market wanted (for Lycos) was a deal with a major TV
network, like NBC,'' Parr said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last-minute negotiations Tuesday night, USA Networks CEO
Barry Diller and Davis abandoned plans to create an e-commerce
behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   New York's USA Networks offers cable TV programming available in
70 million homes. Its Home Shopping Network handles more than 1
million telephone transactions every day, and Ticketmaster sells 70
million tickets a year. Lycos, meanwhile, reaches about 32 million
people each month _ nearly half of all domestic online users _
through a network of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Media mogul Diller couldn't win over an army of day traders who
own a major piece of Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Investors chafed at the deal, flooding Internet chat rooms and
message boards with caustic remarks about the deal, Diller and
Davis. Many wanted Lycos to remain a pure Internet company and
avoid melding operations with a traditional retailer like Home
Shopping Network.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more damning, Diller also failed to keep the support of
Lycos' largest shareholder, CMG Information Services, a Boston
investment firm that owns about 20 percent of Lycos. CMGI initially
supported the deal, then retreated after Lycos shares plummetted.
CMGI went so far as to hire investment banker Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter to help find another suitor to challenge Diller's bid.
</P>
<P>
   David Wetherell, CMGI chief executive and a Lycos board member,
said Lycos can now turn its attention to developing online assets.
``We are gratified that Lycos shareholders will now have new
avenues to realize appropriate value for their shares,'' Wetherell
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Early bets are that Lycos will renew merger talks with a media
partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of eligible bachelors is as large as it's ever
been,'' Ron Sege, Lycos executive vice president, said in a phone
interview. ``Time Warner, Viacom, AG Bertlesmann, CBS and Fox are
presumably looking. There are lots of potential spouses out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lycos lost a potential mate on Monday, however, when NBC
announced it is teaming with online community Xoom.com and
Snap.com, an NBC-Cnet joint venture that provides news and
searching, to create a super Web site called NBC Internet, or NBCi.
Industry watchers already peg the value of that enterprise at $3.5
billion to $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its termination agreement with USA Networks, Lycos is
required to pay the cable TV network $35 million if it agrees to be
acquired by someone else before July 15.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also agreed to feature Ticketmaster and CitySearch
on Lycos' phalanx of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   News of the deal's demise sent the stock of both companies
soaring. Lycos shares jumped $8.75, to $107. USA Networks shares
improved $3.56, to $39.44.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
