<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4755 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON &LR;      05-12 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Pac Bell Inside Wiring Ruling
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
State regulators today will likely approve Pacific Bell's request
for a rate increase on inside wiring insurance but deny the
company's application for rate increases on other services such as
collect calls and calling cards.
</P>
<P>
   Customers now pay 60 cents per month for Pac Bell's ``inside
wiring repair'' plan. Those who pay the monthly fee can get phone
wiring problems inside their homes fixed for free by Pac Bell.
Those who don't have the plan can either pay Pac Bell for repairs
or hire an electrician.
</P>
<P>
   The state Public Utilities Commission will vote on two proposals
today: A PUC administrative law judge has proposed raising the
inside wiring fee to $1 a month, and PUC Commissioner Henry Duque
has proposed raising it to $1.20.
</P>
<P>
   Duque's proposal, unlike the $1-per-month proposal, could result
in more increases down the road because it also would recategorize
inside wiring as a fully competitive service. Pac Bell can raise
rates more easily on competitive services than on regulated ones.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have balked at Duque's proposal, saying that
inside wiring services are not competitive and that Pac Bell should
not be allowed to charge much more than $1 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there's much competition for this service,''
said Paul Stein, an attorney for The Utility Reform Network. ``A
huge percentage of Pacific's customers subscribe to inside wire
repair.''
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of Pac Bell customers pay for inside wiring
insurance. Pac Bell must repair outside wires, but inside wires are
the responsibility of the homeowner.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell officials support Duque's proposal. Pac Bell spokesman
John Britton said customers can get their wiring repaired by dozens
of companies other than Pac Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are ads in the phone book for companies that will do
this. It's been fully competitive for quite a while,'' Britton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals agree on this point: Pac Bell should not be
allowed to increase its rate caps on services such as calling card,
collect and person-to-person calls.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell had asked the PUC for permission to set higher rate
caps on these services, but both proposals under consideration
rebuff that request. The company wanted to raise the maximum fee on
a collect call to $1.60 from 95 cents and on a person-to-person
collect call to $4 from $2.95.
</P>
<P>
   However, both the judge's and Duque's proposal would reclassify
some operator-assisted services as fully competitive.
</P>
<P>
   If they are reclassified, Pac Bell could raise rates on those
services more easily than it can now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
