<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-ENVOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SETTLES ON ADMIRAL TO REPLACE CHINESE AMBASSADOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ending a six-month search, President Clinton plans
to nominate Adm. Joseph Prueher to be the next ambassador to
Beijing, a choice that the administration hopes will signal the
importance of working with China on critical national security
issues dividing it from the United States, White House officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the same week that NATO warplanes mistakenly bombed the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade, sparking demonstrations throughout
China, the administration finally selected a replacement for the
departing ambassador, James Sasser.
</P>
<P>
   The administration had failed to persuade at least six former
officials to accept the post. Many were put off by the prospect of
having to manage a deteriorating relationship with Beijing,
enduring a potentially difficult confirmation process and serving a
short term for a lame-duck president.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the White House bypassed the diplomatic corps and chose
Prueher because of his high-profile military background and because
he was ``the most seasoned statesman we could find,'' said David C.
Leavy, spokesman for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Prueher, who was commander of the unified Pacific Command until
March, gained a reputation as a tough military statesman who
improved military ties with the Chinese but also sent U.S. warships
into the Straits of Taiwan to warn China not to use war games to
disrupt the 1996 elections in Taiwan. It is unusual, but not
unheard of, to name a military official to an ambassadorial post.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very well respected in Congress, in the White House and
in China,'' said David J. Rothkopf, a former senior Clinton
administration official. ``He is viewed as a real grown-up who
won't give away the store at a time when what's needed is a
soldier-statesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Although entry in the World Trade Organization remains an
important issue for China, the emphasis in relations has shifted
toward national security concerns as Congress investigates China's
acquisition of American military secrets and China condemns the
NATO air campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Prueher, 56, retired from the military on May 1, after learning
he was being considered for the post. Although he has strong
backing in the White House _ National Security Adviser Sandy Berger
formally offered him the position _ the admiral was not the first
person approached for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the winter, the Clinton administration contacted at
least six former officials _ including two former members of
Congress, a former National Security Adviser, a former secretary of
defense and Gen. John Shalikashvili, former chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff _ all of whom politely declined.
</P>
<P>
   Shalikashvili said that when he was approached about the post he
strongly recommended Prueher. ``He would be the best man for the
job,'' the general said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Some candidates were reluctant to undergo a confirmation process
in the Senate that could become a forum for attacking Clinton
administration policies and China's record on espionage, human
rights and trade.
</P>
<P>
   Prueher's formal nomination is expected to be sent to the Senate
in two weeks, and a hearing is expected in June, White House
officials said. Sasser had planned to leave China this month,
before he and several other diplomats came under siege by Chinese
protesters angered by the Chinese embassy bombing in Belgrade last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials hope Prueher's confirmation process
will go smoothly, despite anti-China sentiment in Congress, because
he received confirmation as commander of Pacific forces in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   During his previous confirmation, he was questioned about his
role as commandant of midshipmen at the Naval Academy from 1989 to
1991, when he oversaw the investigation of a sexual harassment case
against eight midshipmen who chained a female midshipman to a
urinal.
</P>
<P>
   The woman eventually resigned from the academy over what she
said was Prueher's leniency toward her assailants. At his Senate
hearing, Prueher said he regretted some of his decisions in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   While commander of Pacific forces from 1996 through March 1999,
he visited China seven times, promoting military ties between
senior through junior officer ranks. In an address at China's
National Defense University in 1997, he warned that if the United
States and China failed to establish a ``partnership based on
mutual security,'' they could end up in another ``Cold War based on
mutual suspicion, where both sides lose, and neither side gains.''
</P>
</TEXT>
