<HEADER>
A4759 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON &LR;      05-12 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Web Site Making Ethnic Media Accessible to the Mainstream
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
They're the most popular newspapers you've never heard of _ but
that could change.
</P>
<P>
   California's ethnic media, covering local events in a babel of
languages, are organizing to put their English translations online.
</P>
<P>
   So now, when a bomb falls on a Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, you
can get more than just the mainstream U.S. news perspective. You
can see what the California editions of the Chinese language press
_ the Sing Tao Daily, the World Journal and the China Press _ have
to say.
</P>
<P>
   Those papers are among 150 news organizations that have a new
home at New California Media Online.
</P>
<P>
   The site, at  &LR; www.ncmonline.com &LR; , aims to be a ``Web portal''
for California's ethnic media, and it's easy to see the concept
spreading nationwide and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   It's the brainchild of Sandy Close, the executive editor of the
Pacific News Service since 1974 and winner of a MacArthur
Foundation ``genius award'' in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be in business and be operating in the world economy now
and to be a monolingual American like myself is to be at a
tremendous disadvantage,'' Close said. ``The parochialism of the
American media desperately needs the voices accessible through the
ethnic media.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Close established New California Media, a coalition of
news and civic groups dedicated to raising the profile of ethnic
media. It puts out news on the Pacific News Service wire, it stages
an annual awards banquet, it earned desks in the City Hall press
room for ethnic media, and on May 27, it's leading a New California
Media Expo at Pier 35.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's launched a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The site is run by Steven Chin, a former San Francisco Examiner
reporter who now runs his own Web design firm in Multimedia Gulch
called Monkey King Media.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to have historic implications for how we see and
do journalism in California,'' Chin said. ``It's potentially of
huge value because you're able to transcend the boundaries you're
limited with in television, radio and print.''
</P>
<P>
   Chin runs the nonprofit site as a paid contractor, with two of
his employees working half time. Ten translators take stories
originally written in Chinese, Japanese, Korean, Vietnamese,
Spanish and, occasionally, Arabic and post them on the site in
English.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The site is updated several times a week and more frequently
when there's major breaking news, such as the Chinese Embassy
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Close and Chin hope that the site ultimately will reap a
financial reward for the ethnic media by connecting them to
advertisers; at the moment, they're trying to build traffic by
placing links on other ethnic Web sites, like Latino Link and Net
Noir.
</P>
<P>
   The NCM Online site now is packed with stories, summaries, links
and chat, as well as searchable and in-depth information on all the
major participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a former mainstream reporter, I wish I had had this site,''
Chin said. ``It's the best news tips you'll ever get. It's a whole
new level of information.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FATHERS AND SONS: &LR;  One of Texas governor and putative presidential
candidate George W. Bush's best friends in Silicon Valley just
freed some more time for fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Red Herring Communications founder Tony Perkins has relinquished
the chief executive's job.
</P>
<P>
   He'll stay on as chairman _ he owns more than 50 percent of the
company _ and as editor-in-chief of the firm's flagship business
technology magazine.
</P>
<P>
   His business partner Chris Alden last week assumed the reins as
interim CEO, and they're looking for what Perkins called a
``world-class media executive'' who can take the company public.
</P>
<P>
   They reached the decision over dinner one night two weeks ago.
Oddly enough, the fateful meal was at the Duck Club at the Stanford
Park Hotel in Menlo Park, which Alden's father owns. It was through
the elder Alden that Perkins met his young partner seven years ago,
when Chris was a wet-behind-the-ears Dartmouth grad with an
entrepreneurial zeal.
</P>
<P>
   Alden had a new Mac as a graduation present, and they started
the company in his Woodside home. Now, they employ 100 people in
the Hamm's Building in San Francisco's Multimedia Gulch, and
Perkins says the company eked out a profit on revenues of nearly
$18 million last year. He expects sales to top $25 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   It's another father-son connection that led Perkins to Bush,
this going back a generation. It started with William Draper, a
longtime venture capitalist and an old pal of former President
George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Draper raised a lot of money during Bush's 1980 campaign and
held some prestigious appointments in the Reagan administration,
Perkins said. His son, Tim Draper, also is a venture capitalist in
Silicon Valley, and he is a lifelong buddy of Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Draper led Perkins to the younger Bush. But the
appeal was not just personal: The valley businessmen like the Texas
Republican's views on labor, immigration and the free market.
``Clearly, he's one of us,'' Perkins said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Perkins was in Austin speaking at a conference and
meeting with Bush's handlers, promising to raise $2 million from
2,000 technology entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   He ought to know how to do it. He's heard enough startups try to
pry cash from tight-fisted bankers over the years; why should
political &UR;  &LR; fund raising be any different?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE PREZ: &LR;  Cnet named its first president yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Marino, currently president and CEO of International Data
Group's PC World Communications, will oversee the San Francisco
Internet media firm's online publishing and television units, as
well as sales, marketing and human resources.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet co-founder Halsey Minor remains chairman and CEO, and
co-founder Shelby Bonnie, the chief operating officer, also will
become vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Marino, 50, will focus on actually running the company, leaving
Bonnie to look more toward acquisitions and freeing up Minor to
operate on a strategic level.
</P>
<P>
   After nine years at San Francisco's PC World, will Marino help
create a Cnet print product?
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' Bonnie said, ``but I doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CHANGE AFOOT: &LR;  I don't have any inside scoop, but I can't help
wondering: If 4-year-old Internet auctioneer eBay can buy
134-year-old Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield, could some upstart media
firm _ like 7-year-old Cnet _ buy the 134-year-old Chronicle?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know, but here's my candid take on Halsey Minor's hiring
of Rich Marino: absolutely brilliant. As usual.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The San Francisco Chronicle.
Send buzz, dirt, tips and comments to fostd(AT SIGN)sfgate.com,
call (415) 777-6004 or fax (415) 543-2482. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
