<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4763 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVENT-LAWSUIT-NYT &LR;      05-12 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-LIVENT CHIEF SAYS HE WAS TOO BUSY TO BE INVOLVED IN ACCOUNTING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)   By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garth Drabinsky, the Canadian impresario who founded Livent
Inc., said in court papers filed Wednesday that he had been too
caught up in the details of producing Broadway musicals like
``Ragtime'' to have had time to help keep the company's accounting
books, which have been found to be false.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky was responding to a suit filed against him last year
in Toronto by the company's new management team, led by Michael
Ovitz, the Hollywood talent agent. The new managers contend that
Drabinsky helped direct an accounting scheme under which the
company recorded more than $60 million in false profits and then
had to file for protection from its creditors in bankruptcy court
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The papers were Drabinsky's first detailed response to the
accusations of Ovitz and the company's other new executives, who
took over the theater company last June.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan and the Securities and
Exchange Commission made similar accusations in January when they
charged Drabinsky and his longtime partner, Myron Gottlieb, with
orchestrating a criminal financial fraud. The two have refused to
turn themselves in and instead have remained in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In the court papers, lawyers for Drabinsky, who was Livent's
chief executive and chairman until June, said that his main role
had been that of theatrical producer. They said he was not an
accountant and did not have the training necessary to establish the
company's accounting procedures or internal financial controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not and could not micro-manage a complex accounting
system staffed by a myriad of employees and managed by senior
officers and employees, many of whom were chartered accountants,''
the papers said.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky's lawyers also said the company's accusations that he
and Gottlieb had given themselves $7.5 million in ``kickbacks'' by
funneling corporate money to another company in the early 1990s
were ``false and misleading.'' The lawyers said Livent was not a
public company at the time the checks were written and therefore
could not have caused a loss to public shareholders. At the time of
the payments, the company was owned by a private partnership
between Drabinsky and Gottlieb.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nathan, a spokesman for Livent, said Wednesday that there
was plenty of evidence contradicting Drabinsky's new court claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the SEC's lawsuit, which describes Garth
Drabinsky's conduct as `a multifaceted and pervasive eight-year
fraudulent accounting scheme' and the 16-count criminal indictment
by a U.S. grand jury makes perfectly clear Drabinsky's
culpability,'' Nathan said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the SEC's complaint against Drabinsky, Livent's top
four executives, including Drabinsky and Gottlieb, would often meet
at the end of a quarter to discuss the company's financial results
and what adjustments needed to be made to increase the profits that
would soon be reported to shareholders. The regulators said
Drabinsky had directed his top financial executive to make the
adjustments to the accounting books.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb has also denied the accusations and says he did nothing
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman in the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan said
Wednesday that prosecutors intended to begin proceedings to arrest
the two Canadians and bring them to the United States to face the
criminal charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
