<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-`SURPRISE'-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONLY `SURPRISE' HERE IS HOW THIS SHOW MADE IT ON THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surprise! Kathie Lee Gifford hasn't lost her phony sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, viewers won't be subjected to it Friday night. A
CBS entertainment special titled ``Surprise, Surprise, Surprise!''
will air as scheduled, but a mawkish and maudlin segment requiring
Gifford to go sincere on us has been lifted.
</P>
<P>
   In its place, viewers will no doubt see something just as
manipulative of the tear ducts, but, ideally, more tasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprise, Surprise, Surprise!'' is a little bit ``Candid
Camera,'' a little bit ``Ted Mack's Original Amateur Hour'' and a
little bit ``Queen for a Day.'' It's more than a little bit awful,
too, but CBS is testing it to see if it might become a series. It's
from the same company that produces ``Kids Say the Darnedest
Things.''
</P>
<P>
   But where ``Kids Say'' retains a smidgen of honesty born of a
child's unpredictability, ``Surprise'' is about as honest as the
telemarketers who call at dinnertime to say you've won a free trip
to Reno. The premise is simple: Someone gets surprised on the air
and we, the audience, share in the amusement, amazement, etc. The
possibilities run the gamut from reuniting long-lost relatives to
fulfilling a cherished dream.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, for example, a woman who loves karaoke and has
dreamed of singing on TV gets her chance. Her rendition of Gladys
Knight's ``Midnight Train to Georgia'' is enhanced by the pipes of
the Pips, but the whole thing is as spontaneous and surprising as
Al Gore. Still, it's the best part of the show.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Kathie Lee is on the slippery slope to slop, and she
falls right in. The low point comes when a woman in the audience
``surprises'' her wrestling-obsessed husband with his own bizarre
World Championship Wrestling fantasy/punishment, featuring herself
and his twin brother tussling on the mat, plus some WCW grapplers
in spandex standing around as the surprisee laughs awkwardly. Even
the impression that the producers had taken the guy's living room
furniture out of the house and reassembled it on stage is phony. In
spite of photos purporting to show the moving men moving, a voice
at the end of the segment advises that the stage set is ``a
duplication'' and that the guy's real furniture ``remains at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprise!
</P>
<P>
   The excised segment involved a woman who survived the 1980 fire
at the MGM Grand Hotel in Las Vegas, in which 84 people died. She
had been rescued by construction workers and said she'd been trying
to find them in order to bring closure to the ordeal. As footage of
the awful blaze played on the screen, Gifford made references to
the ``inferno'' and the ``death trap.'' Finally, the woman got to
meet one of her rescuers _ the other has since died _ in an
uncomfortable scene that ought to be private, not witnessed by
millions. Luckily, some people with good sense at the network
decided to have the segment pulled before it aired. Too bad they
stopped there.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the show, Gifford says, ``I guarantee we will
surprise you.'' Alas, the only surprise is that a monumental
embarrassment like ``Surprise, Surprise, Surprise!'' made it on the
air at all.
</P>
<P>
   Odds 'n' ends
</P>
<P>
   Just when you thought there couldn't possibly be another awards
show on TV, The WB announces creation of The WB Radio Music Awards.
The two-hour fall special will recognize musicians and bands in six
genres and also pay tribute to radio talent across the country...
Just when you thought The WB Radio Music Awards would be the last
word in awards shows, E! Entertainment Television announces that it
will televise the annual American Fashion Awards ceremony June 13
at 9 p.m....Just when you thought I couldn't come up with another
awards-related item, MTV announces that Lisa Kudrow will host ``The
1999 MTV Movie Awards,'' airing June 5, and probably about 200 more
times before the end of the millennium.... Next Tuesday, American
Movie Classics presents ``Hollywood Goes to Court,'' a one-hour
special that looks at Hollywood's depiction of the courtroom
through the years. Prominent attorneys, including Johnnie Cochran
and Gloria Allred, take part.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
