<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV FORCES WEAKENED BUT STILL CAPABLE OF FIGHTING, PENTAGON
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-NATO) 
(sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senior NATO and Pentagon officials said on
Wednesday that after the most intense 24 hours of bombing so far,
NATO had weakened Yugoslavia's armed forces but still not broken
their ability to fight and resist.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
said that the attacks had exacted ``a significant toll on Serb
forces in Kosovo and throughout the rest of Yugoslavia,'' including
half of the Yugoslav air gorce and a quarter of tanks and other
armored forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia acknowledged on
Wednesday that the NATO attack has caused the deaths of ``many
members'' of its army and police forces.
</P>
<P>
   But Shelton conceded that Milosevic's forces could continue
operations for weeks. ``It is possible that a force like the one
Milosevic is using for ethnic cleansing and terror in Kosovo could
hold out for quite some time,'' he said at a Pentagon briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton appeared on Wednesday with Secretary of Defense William
Cohen to offer a fairly detailed _ and upbeat _ assessment of
NATO's war in the Balkans, which continued for a 50th day with no
sign of nearing an end.
</P>
<P>
   With clear skies, American and allied fighters and bombers have
been attacking in wave after wave. Officials said NATO aircraft
carried out 327 strikes over the 24 hours leading up to early
Wednesday, hitting eight bridges, an air-defense command center in
the Belgrade suburb of Rakovica, an oil production center in
Sombor, in northwestern Serbia on the border with Hungary, and five
airfields, where they destroyed a MiG-29 and five MiG-21s.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's military spokesman, Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz, described
seven ``packages'' of aircraft conducting virtually uninterrupted
strikes over the previous 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   It began early Tuesday with a wave of 36 American A-10s and
F-16s, British Harriers, French Etendards and Jaguars and others
attacking military vehicles around Suva Reka, in south central
Kosovo. And it ended just before dawn on Wednesday with a wave of
24 fighters and bombers, including B-52s, striking a number of
sites in Kosovo, including the airfield in Pristina, the provincial
capital, and forces around Junik and Stimlje.
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO's campaign has done nothing to reverse the
expulsion of much of Kosovo's ethnic Albanian population, NATO and
Pentagon officials have portrayed the attacks as successful. Faced
with sharp questions about the progress, they insist the attacks
are steadily whittling away Yugoslavia's military capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would simply say that the game's not over yet, quite
frankly,'' NATO's spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, said on Wednesday when
asked to assess the progress so far. ``And I don't think we should
start writing the history books until the final results are in.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Brussels and here in Washington continue to report
an erosion in morale among Yugoslavia's military leaders, though
they provided little hard evidence of that, and other officials
have played down the psychological impact of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that Yugoslavia's senior military leaders had sent
their families out of the country in what he said was a sign of
waning support for Milosevic and his political leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic may not admit that he is taking his country down the
road to ruin _ politically, economically and militarily _ but his
top leadership is apparently more realistic,'' he said. ``And at
the very least, they are hedging their bets by hiding their assets
and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Cohen's aides said they did not have the names of
commanders who had sent their families out of the country. Nor
could they quantify how many families they believed to have left.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Shelton vowed to press the attacks _ soon with
additional aircraft based in Hungary and Turkey and, perhaps, with
Apache helicopter gunships in Albania, which Shelton indicated were
at last ready for combat. Two Apaches that crashed have been
replaced, bringing the total back to 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
