<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REJECTS NEW LIMITS ON GUN-SHOW SALES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate defeated a measure Wednesday that would
have required background checks for those purchasing firearms at
gun shows, a sign that the Colorado high school shootings have not
moved the Republican majority to embrace more gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, tacked to juvenile justice legislation now being
debated by the Senate, was killed by a vote of 51-47, with all but
six Republicans opposing the measure and all but two Democrats
supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was pushed by Democrats as a response to the recent
Columbine High School shootings, where investigators said some of
the weapons used in the killings were purchased at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Two students opened fire with several weapons inside the
Littleton, Colo., school, killing 13 before killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The April 20 massacre reinvigorated several gun control
initiatives that had languished in Congress over several months,
but one of the measures most discussed was the tightening of
oversight on gun show sales.
</P>
<P>
   In a loophole to the Brady law requiring background checks of
gun purchasers, unlicensed sellers at gun shows do not have to
conduct such background checks.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was a victory for the National Rifle Association, which
has staunchly opposed all gun control measures and came under
criticism after the April school shooting for suggesting that
better law enforcement, not gun control, was the proper response.
</P>
<P>
   It represented a defeat for the Clinton administration, which
had hoped the public outrage over the Colorado tragedy would prod
Congress to approve stronger gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said during debate that the unwillingness by
Republicans to strengthen gun control laws was an indication of the
NRA's lobbying power.
</P>
<P>
   The failed amendment's sponsor, Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.,
complained about how easy it is to procure firearms at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tens of thousands of firearms are sold at these events with no
background checks or record keeping,'' he said. ``You can just walk
into a gun show, put down your cash and walk away with a gun,
semiautomatic or any other deadly weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, joined with the state's
senior senator, Phil Gramm, R-Texas, in opposing the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gramm and Hutchison supported a Republican alternative that
makes instant background checks available to unlicensed sellers and
promoters at gun shows but does not mandate such checks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The GOP amendment was approved 53-41, with one Democrat
supporting it and three Republicans opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Hutchison had said Tuesday that she supported instant
background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Republican version would not require such
checks, a Hutchison spokesman said the senator believed that the
GOP alternative ``was a more effective approach to getting
compliance with the federal law.''
</P>
<P>
   The sponsor of the Republican provision, Sen. Larry Craig,
R-Idaho, said that the Democratic amendment would impose
restrictions ``on private citizens who come to gun shows and engage
in discussion with other private citizens and decide to exchange or
sell their guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig said his provision contains incentives to gun sellers to
conduct background checks because such checks would mean limited
protection from liability in future lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Several gun control provisions remain before the Senate, but
only one appears likely to be approved: A youth convicted of a
crime would be banned as an adult from buying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine shooting prompted President Clinton to advocate
several new measures, including background checks at gun shows,
trigger locks for all guns and new restrictions on handgun
ownership. But Clinton's gun control proposals have fared poorly in
Congress since the Republicans took control in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The measure requiring background checks at gun shows was
recently considered and rejected by a Texas House legislative
committee. Texas Gov. George W. Bush said he supported the
legislation even though committee members said he did nothing to
ensure its passage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
