<HEADER>
A4792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZMAGS13-COX     05-12 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft keeps one step ahead of Justice Department
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bill Gates apparently isn't waiting for the Justice
Department to break up Microsoft, according to Business Week (May
17).
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Vision 2,'' the Microsoft leaders have launched a
plan to break the software giant into eight groups, ``each with
unprecedented decision-making power and a sharp focus on
customers.'' Gates, co-founder of the company, is executing this
scheme with Steven A. Ballmer, Microsoft's new president.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the magazine says the company is facing ``more
challenges than ever before. ... Perhaps the biggest threat is the
Justice Department's antitrust trial, scheduled to kick off again
later this month.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate article, Business Week says U.S. corporations have
gotten a second wind from surprisingly strong first-quarter
earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Observers had fretted that economic problems in Asia and Latin
America, combined with exhausted U.S. consumers, would cut short
the eight-year run of U.S. earnings growth in the first quarter.
But foreign economies appear to have stabilized, and consumers
haven't yet worn out their plastic,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff was a surprisingly strong 12 percent gain in net
profits in the first quarter, and an 8 percent rise in operating
profits, based on the magazine's survey of 900 corporations. That
was in contrast to the 2 percent decline in profits in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The new environmentalism
</P>
<P>
   Interface, an Atlanta-based manufacturer of carpet tiles used
mainly in commercial buildings, gets favorable mention in Harvard
Business Review (May-June).
</P>
<P>
   The magazine looks at the growth of ``natural capitalism,'' or
the use of natural resources in new ways that extend product life
further than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Interface developed Solenium, a floor covering that lasts four
times longer than ordinary carpets and uses 40 percent less
material, the magazine says. Interface is one of a number of
companies cited for manufacturing techniques that improve the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
