<HEADER>
A4793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-DISCRIMINATION13     05-12 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-DISCRIMINATION13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plaintiffs in suit against Coca-Cola to meet company in court
 &HT;    By Henry Unger and Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. emphatically denies that it racially
discriminated against one former and three current employees who
have filed a federal lawsuit against the company.
</P>
<P>
   In its legal response to the suit, Coca-Cola said Wednesday that
its actions toward the four African-American plaintiffs ``were in
no way motivated by race ... but instead were based solely on
legitimate, nondiscriminatory business reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides will be in federal court in Atlanta today to argue
whether the soft drink company should be allowed to discuss the
merits of the case with its employees, since some of the
communications could reach African-Americans who might become
members of a class action.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company has employed 23 defenses to try to
rebut allegations of systematic discrimination against blacks in
pay, promotions, performance evaluations and terminations.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are seeking class-action status so they can
include another 1,500 salaried U.S. black employees in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola said the plaintiffs ``have failed to plead a
proper class action and the named plaintiffs' claims are not
legally or factually proper for class-action treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard Story will decide whether to grant
class-action status. That decision could take anywhere from a few
months to two years, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   In its lengthy response, the company said the lawsuit did not
fairly describe salaries at Coca-Cola. The company, however, did
not specifically provide statistics to refute some of the figures
provided by the plaintiffs. For example, the suit alleges that
there was a $26,830 gap in median pay between blacks and whites in
1998 at Coca-Cola's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Robert Baskin said a more detailed response to
the allegations will be made during the course of the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's filing is a first step in the process that will show
that the Coca-Cola Co. does not tolerate discrimination,'' Baskin
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that the pay for one of the plaintiffs, Linda
Ingram, was below the salary range for her position as an
information systems analyst. But the company denied that it was the
result of any discrimination or illegal action.
</P>
<P>
   The other plaintiffs are administrative assistant Motisola
Malikha Abdallah, security officer Gregory Allen Clark and former
director Kimberly Gray Orton.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers for Coca-Cola and the plaintiffs will argue
before Story today whether a court rule prohibits the company from
writing memos, e-mails or other communications to employees who
might be potential class action members.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, in the aftermath of the suit filing, Coca-Cola
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer M. Douglas Ivester sent two
e-mails to workers to defend the company's employment and personnel
policies. In one message, Ivester alleged the lawsuit had
``significant errors of fact.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' lawyers contend federal court rules for the
Northern District of Georgia prohibit this kind of communication
with potential members of a class action.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed in federal court late Wednesday, the plaintiffs'
attorneys say they have no blanket objection to communication
between the company and employees ``at this juncture.'' They
contend, however, that Coca-Cola should make clear in messages that
officers are giving only company views. They say Coca-Cola should
also tell employees they may contact the plaintiffs' attorneys
about the complainants' position.
</P>
<P>
   The petition also asks that the court limit communications to
employees such as African-Americans who could become members of a
class alleging discriminatory treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' attorneys ask that Ivester send out a ``corrective
notice'' following up on his recent e-mails on the case.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Coca-Cola defends its rights to communicate with
employees, saying the other side's lawyers are engaging in ``legal
maneuvering.''
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed last Friday, Coca-Cola said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The relief plaintiffs seek would impose an unconstitutional
prior restraint on Coca-Cola's right to free speech, require
Coca-Cola to segregate and discriminate against its own employees
_the very employees plaintiffs seek to represent _ and punish
Coca-Cola for having African-American employees in positions of
significant authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
