<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4794 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-TCACABLE13-COX     05-12 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TCACABLE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In bid to grow larger, Cox scouts smaller markets
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In its quest to grow larger, Cox Communications has
shifted the focus of its acquisition strategy from cable TV systems
in big metro areas to those in smaller cities.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is twofold. For one, there aren't many big systems
available. And the few up for sale are expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest in mid-market opportunities is a combination of
price and what's available,'' said Jim Robbins, Cox Communications'
president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications' strategic shift is evident in the
Atlanta-based company's latest purchase. The company announced
Wednesday that it would pay $4 billion in cash and stock to buy TCA
Cable TV, based in Tyler, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   TCA has 883,000 subscribers in systems in small- to mid-sized
towns across Texas, Louisiana and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   What Cox Communications likes about TCA's systems is that, while
small, they are well-clustered. Indeed, TCA has almost completed
integrating its systems into one digital system that can
efficiently provide new services such as high-speed access to the
Internet and telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins said that TCA's management team, which would remain in
place, would help his company identify other small to midsized
systems that might be good buys for Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   He added, though, that Cox Communications would remain cautious
about purchases. ``We'd screen for quality and management,'' said
Robbins. ``Our interest is only in companies with a level of
quality and strategy similar to our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications traditionally has placed a big emphasis on
customer service. It also has been an industry leader in rolling
out the new services enabled by digital technology. Many of its
systems are now offering high-speed access to the Internet, local
telephone service and the sharp images of digital television.
</P>
<P>
   TCA was looking to do the same thing within its small systems
but began to feel it lacked both the engineering expertise and
capital to upgrade quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was a cable TV company in the country that
didn't step back and look itself after the AT&AMP;T deal,'' said Fred
Nickols, TCA's president and chief executive. He was referring to
AT&AMP;T's tentative purchase of MediaOne for $62 million, making it
the largest cable operator.
</P>
<P>
   What Nickols saw was his company could not quickly offer local
telephone service. ``Cox Communications will bring us an expertise
we are lacking in the telephone area,'' he said. ``We can now do in
one year what would have taken us up to three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
