<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PILOTS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta pilots lower 777 pay demand
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The pilots union at Delta Air Lines cut its pay demand
to fly the new Boeing 777, saying the move will test management's
``willingness to come to an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Line Pilots Association's new proposal seeks about
$287,000 a year for a 777 captain, based on an hourly rate of $319
and a standard 75-hour work month.
</P>
<P>
   That's down 8 percent from an initial demand of $346 an hour, or
nearly $312,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still well above Delta's last offer of $239 an hour, or
about $215,000 a year before overtime and other add-ons.
</P>
<P>
   The union made its proposal in a negotiating session this week,
spokesman Andy Deane said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immediate reaction from company negotiators was to offer a
counter at the same rate as their (previous) offer,'' Deane said.
``This was not the movement we hoped for.''
</P>
<P>
   While Delta did not sweeten its pay proposal, the company said
it offered work rule improvements and remains hopeful of an
agreement ``as soon as possible.'' More talks are set for next
week.
</P>
<P>
   The pay dispute has cast doubt on Delta's plans for the giant
777, a premier international jet already flown by several of the
Atlanta-based airline's rivals. ALPA has said it will invoke its
right to refuse to fly the plane on Nov. 1 if a pay agreement isn't
ratified by then.
</P>
<P>
   Delta now has two 777s in service, but canceled four future
orders last month, citing the risk that the fleet might be
grounded. It also said five deliveries scheduled for later this
year are in jeopardy, depending on the progress of talks. The
airline says an agreement must be in place by midsummer so it can
confidently add the planes to its fall and winter schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the 777 pay issue will set the tone for new
contract talks that start this fall, in which rates and work rules
for all pilots and aircraft will be on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
