A4797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYCOS-HOMESHOPPING13-     05-12 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-HOMESHOPPING13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lycos saves a part of doomed deal
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the end, the Lycos deal was worth more dead than
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Web directory site Lycos and Barry Diller's USA Networks
officially bailed out of their complicated and controversial merger
agreement Wednesday, but Lycos hung on to the all-important
cross-media advertising and promotion pieces of the deal deemed so
crucial to a Web site's success.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos stock was up $9.12 1/2 to $107.50 after Lycos Chief
Executive Officer Bob Davis officially announced the deal was
kaput. It seems that stockholders and investors didn't like the
idea of their highflying Internet stocks being dragged down to
earth by Barry Diller's traditional companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal did make sense,'' says Forrester Research analyst
Chris Charron. ``At some point the market has to understand that
long-term strategic value is not necessarily provided by pure
Internet plays. They are clearly punishing companies for online and
offline alliances and rewarding online-only alliances like Yahoo!,
GeoCities and the NBC deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, the fact that a major shareholder
torpedoed the deal, and the delay and uncertainty over the last
four months, has put Lycos in a tough position in the portal race.
The portal space is moving too fast to move in limbo for six
months. They should have cut the cord a bit sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be wrong to say this deal was doomed from the start. As
Davis pointed out in February when the merger was first announced,
the money and assets of the USA Network seemed too good to pass up.
Diller, who has always been something of a maverick and a
visionary, clearly saw the potential of the Internet and Lycos in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, currently ranked the most-visited portal site on the Web
by Media Metrix, has also been gradually acquiring companies such
as Wired Digital and the Tripod community Web site in an effort to
assemble the Web's most popular and profitable hat trick: content,
community and commerce. The plan was working well before Diller
dangled the golden carrot of electronic commerce infrastructure and
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Davis would have done well to stick to his original plans. He
admits now that nobody _ not Diller and certainly not David
Wetherell, who heads CMGI, Lycos' largest shareholder _ understood
how the market would respond to the deal. Although there is
speculation about serious disagreements between Davis and Wetherell
about the direction Lycos should take, Davis is reluctant to say
Wetherell was the one who killed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos stock plunged 26 percent when the deal was announced. As
dazzling as the deal and Diller's reputation and clout as a media
visionary are, the stone-cold fact is that Web valuations sink
faster than you can say ``Titanic'' when you attach them to a
real-world venture such as Diller's cable enterprises. Why? Because
alone, Lycos can move up with the rising Internet bubble in the
market. But it would be buried within the organizational chart of
Diller's outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Diller's acknowledgment that he was an Internet speculator
probably didn't do much to warm the hearts of Lycos shareholders
either.
</P>
<P>
   Davis stressed that future plans for the company were to put the
ill-fated USA Networks deal behind them and concentrate on growth
through acquisition instead of billion-dollar mergers with
companies that may not want to stick around when the going gets
rough.
</P>
<P>
   Diller was conspicuously and uncharacteristically silent
Wednesday, but his remark to the Jupiter Internet conference last
March, ``Who told me to come in here and muck everything up?''
seems oddly prophetic now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
