<SLUG> BC-SEARS-MARTINEZ13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sears to sell large appliances online beginning today
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a significant move to beat other retailers to the
Web, Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. will start online sales today of
refrigerators, freezers and other large appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Six major brands of appliances will be for sale at www.sears.com
this afternoon, after Chairman and Chief Executive Arthur Martinez
addresses shareholders at the company's annual meeting today at the
Apparel Mart in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman Estates, Ill.-based Sears has moved aggressively with
its Internet strategy as one way to regain market share lost to
discounters and fast-growing retailers such as Home Depot and
Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse. Atlanta-based Home Depot plans
to start selling products online this year but is still working out
pricing and shipping issues. And it's still deciding which products
are best suited for the Web. Lowe's sells some tools online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a significant advantage in our infrastructure,''
Martinez said in an interview Wednesday. ``In home delivery alone,
we make 4 million to 5 million deliveries a day. We've got the
people and the trucks on the road already.''
</P>
<P>
   Sears already sells Craftsman tools and appliance parts online.
Later this year, customers will be able to schedule deliveries,
repairs and installation on the Web site as well, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is trying a number of initiatives to revitalize the
company. The retailer's turnaround stumbled in 1998 as apparel
sales slowed in the second half of the year. Revenue of $41.32
billion was flat, and earnings were hurt by losses from the sale of
its Western Auto stores and its HomeLife furniture chain.
</P>
<P>
   In apparel, Martinez is cutting prices on basic items,
eliminating marginal lines and trying to send a more focused
fashion message to customers. In other areas, Sears is taking on
Home Depot and other housing-related retailers as it scales back
its so-called softer side and beefs up traditional strengths in
home goods.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said the company is back on track with growth plans for
the Sears Hardware Stores, a neighborhood format that will compete
directly with the new Villager's Hardware concept by Home Depot.
Sears has digested its 1996 acquisition of the Orchard Supply
Hardware chain in California and will open up to 30 hardware stores
this year. It plans to end 1999 with 290 hardware stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll pick up the pace in 2000 and the following year. I'd
like to get to a point where we're building 60 to 75 stores a
year,'' Martinez said. Home Depot will open its first hardware
store next month in East Brunswick, N.J. Home Depot is not a threat
to Sears' hardware stores because Home Depot typically takes a
cautious approach with new concepts, Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a 300-store lead on them, which we intend to
extend,'' Martinez said. ``We'll be marching across the country at
a rapid rate with a proven concept while they're testing a few.''
The likely threat is to independent hardware stores as large chains
like Sears and Home Depot roll out smaller formats.
</P>
<P>
   Sears also is treading in territory that Home Depot has staked
out as well. Last year, Sears launched a home interior superstore
in Denver dubbed the Great Indoors, a distant cousin to Home
Depot's Expo Design Center. This year Sears will open its second
Great Indoors in Scottsdale, Ariz., and will start building another
in Dallas. A fourth store is on tap, and Sears may expand its
growth plans for the concept later this year, Martinez said. Home
Depot operates eight Expos and plans to have 200 in the next five
to seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
