<SLUG> BC-U.N.-WEATHER-AGENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. WEATHER AGENCY CHIEF'S RE-ELECTION OPPOSED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A contentious campaign is under way over who will head
the U.N. agency that tries to predict global weather disasters,
with accusations of mismanagement and cronyism surrounding the
current secretary-general's bid to secure another term.
</P>
<P>
   Godwin Olu Patrick Obasi, 65, of Nigeria is seeking a new
four-year term at the agency, the World Meteorological
Organization, which he has headed for 16 years. For the first time
since his 1984 election, he has opposition: Manuel B. Dengo, 53, a
Costa Rican diplomat and hydrologist, and Gordon A. McBean, 55, who
heads Canada's weather services.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates from the 185 member countries are meeting in Geneva to
select a leader on Friday for the agency, known as the
authoritative voice on the ozone layer, climate change and major
weather phenomena such as El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that some delegates say was intended to spare Obasi
some embarrassment, the delegates agreed during a testy,
closed-door debate to allow the candidates to present their visions
for the agency but the men will not be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the potentially embarrassing issues concern severe staff
morale problems and accusations of hiring cronies.
</P>
<P>
   Obasi denies any cronyism. ``I believe I have been very fair,''
he said, pointing out that ``there are only 28 African staff
members.''
</P>
<P>
   His opponents simply say that it is time for a change. ``There
needs to be better weather services and better predictions'' to
contend with the increasing number of weather disasters, McBean
said. Dengo advocates reaching out to the public sector to help
boost the flagging finances of the agency, which has a $90 million
annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   The United States opposes Obasi's re-election and supported a
resolution, approved by delegates last week, to limit the
secretary-general to three terms. But that does not take effect
until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Obasi says that serving four more years, a 20-year tenure, would
be no big deal, and points to his predecessor, who served 24 years,
leaving only when he was defeated for a seventh term, and, to the
recently retired head of the World Intellectual Property
Organization, who had 24 years in office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
