A4812 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SEATTLE-FESTVIAL     05-12 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SEATTLE-FESTVIAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE FILM FESTIVAL HAS KEPT ITS UNIQUENESS OVER THE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This year's Seattle International Film Festival, which
kicks off on Thursday night, is being billed as the silver
anniversary edition _ and SIFF '99 will be celebrating a quarter
century of itself throughout its crowded, 25-day schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But, as all regular festivalgoers know, it's actually not the
25th at all. It's the 24th. The running gag is that back in 1988,
when the time came to have a 13th edition, the festival powers
decided to skip that unlucky number and, like an elevator, move
directly from the 12th to the 14th floor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no matter how we do the math, this year's Seattle
International Film Festival is geared up for nostalgia, with
revivals of its greatest hits, a special silver anniversary
souvenir booklet and, no doubt, much teary-eyed looking back over
the spring movie classic's extraordinary run.
</P>
<P>
   And, for me, the tongue-in-cheek playfulness with which the
decision to skip the 13th was made is somehow wonderfully
appropriate for a festival that has always taken itself seriously,
but never too seriously: it has steadfastly embraced both the
idealism and the fun of movies.
</P>
<P>
   No other film festival in the world has better kept the faith of
the golden age in which it was born: the great, post-``Easy
Rider,'' pre-``Star Wars'' period of the '70s when a generation
embraced the religion, art and glamour of cinema as at no time
before or since.
</P>
<P>
   The SIFF story actually begins in 1974, when two young members
of that generation _ Dan Ireland and Darryl Macdonald _ brashly
waltzed into town from Canada, leased the old Moore Theater,
painted it in an Egyptian motif, and reopened it as the
Moore-Egyptian: Seattle's first ``movie-palace art house.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in the staid Seattle movie community of the time thought
``the boys'' would last long, especially when they impulsively
decided to host, with no municipal support, a festival of films
``that normally wouldn't be found outside the city limits of New
York, L.A. or San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   When that first festival was finally ready to go in 1975 _ a
two-week, 26-feature lineup, opening with ``The Lost Honor of
Katharina Blum'' _ Ireland had a hard time convincing the Seattle
press that it wasn't a joke. ``We're hoping people will realize
we're serious,'' he told the Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   But that first SIFF was an immediate hit, and for the second
edition in 1976, the bar was raised to 19 days and 30 films. For
the third edition, the lineup was 20 days and nearly 50 films. The
fourth SIFF was 28 days and 83 movies and it hasn't stopped growing
since.
</P>
<P>
   The late '70s were an amazing time for foreign films and, within
five years, the fledgling festival made a national name for itself
as an innovative showcase for New German Cinema, New Australian
Cinema and particularly New Dutch Cinema, which it single-handedly
popularized in America.
</P>
<P>
   It also developed an unusually loyal following by making SIFF a
``high-touch'' festival that brought festivalgoers up close and
personal with visiting filmmakers, offered free matinee series,
added screenings of sold-out films to accommodate its fans... you
name it.
</P>
<P>
   And it developed a joyful, campy character all its own. When
actor Harry Dean Stanton canceled his in-person tribute, it held a
``Tribute Without Harry Dean Stanton.'' If Cannes had its Palm d'Or
and Berlin its Golden Bear, Seattle would have its Golden Space
Needle.
</P>
<P>
   When the festival couldn't lure a Diane Keaton or Jane Fonda to
Seattle in the late '70s, it made a Seattle star out of Monique van
de Ven, ``The Marilyn Monroe of Holland.'' During its first five
years, that magical Dutch actress and her films were invariably the
festival's biggest draw.
</P>
<P>
   The '80s brought some tough new challenges. The number of film
festivals had grown like Topsy, the better foreign films were
suddenly hard to snag, and the video revolution was making it
possible for people to have a film festival in their own home any
time they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Also in that decade, Ireland _ the boundlessly enthusiastic
public relations genius of the fest founders _ left Seattle to
pursue a career as an agent, producer and director in Hollywood.
Thus, in subsequent years, the spiraling SIFF problems fell into
the lap of one man, Macdonald.
</P>
<P>
   To maintain a special identity in the brave new movie world of
the '80s, Macdonald decided _ wisely, it turned out _ to go for
volume, to be no less than the biggest film festival in America.
And to support such a massive event, he had to expand his venues
and draw an audience from many demographic groups.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, he put together an extraordinary moviegoing
coalition of Capitol Hill gays, suburban young professionals,
dedicated film buffs, hip college students and various ethnic and
national communities; and each spring he simply overwhelmed the
city with celluloid.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to give Macdonald too much credit for the
survival of SIFF and its explosion in the '80s _ the sheer
administrative skill with which he met the funding and logistical
nightmares of importing 100-plus films and dozens of temperamental
filmmakers each year from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Year after year, he's consistently managed to find the hottest
new European filmmaker, the most promising new Asian film, a
pristine print of some delicious Hollywood silent classic, some
unexpected movie star to drop by, some world-class director to
tribute, some new feature or twist to the festival.
</P>
<P>
   As he maintained an iron grip over the festival, Macdonald often
made enemies, and his staff came and went, often bitterly. But even
the most bitter of them will grudgingly admit that he's proven
himself to be a true visionary and one of the world's great film
festival organizers.
</P>
<P>
   A staffer who unhappily left the festival in 1994 told me,
``Darryl is not the easiest man to work with, but there's just no
disputing his dedication to the festival, his willingness to make
any personal or financial sacrifice to maintain its quality, or his
skill.... He's a master politician.''
</P>
<P>
   In the later '90s, Macdonald's skill and vision would be sorely
tested. With most foreign film industries in steady decline and the
new Hollywood openly hostile to festivals, he's had to increasingly
rely on the booming American Independent Cinema to fill his slots,
and many of its films have been of marginal quality.
</P>
<P>
   To a certain extent, his old coalition of festivalgoers began to
crumble, as much of the straight audience began to feel the
festival was ``too gay,'' the older audience felt it was ``too
young,'' and the mid-'90s generation of college students showed
little interest in non-Hollywood films.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Macdonald was harshly ctiticized by this (at the
time) grumpy and sensory-overloaded film critic who was worn down
by insipid indies and _ longing for the days when the festival
showed 20 good foreign films _ called the just-concluded 24th
festival the nadir of the event.
</P>
<P>
   But Macdonald has bounced back with a festival that is not only
the biggest ever (206 features) but potentially one of its best: a
festival with major Hollywood films, 12 fewer American indies,
countless auspicious foreign films, tributes, special features and
reminders of its glorious past.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the '90s, the cloudy moviegoing climate also seems
to be improving for SIFF. Hollywood is suddenly more
festival-friendly, foreign-film industries are on the rebound
everywhere, and the new college generation seems to have discovered
the marvels of the art cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Every indication is that the Seattle International Film Festival
will survive its pressing financial and demographic problems and
retain its special character well into the new millennium. I
certainly hope so. A Seattle moviegoing future without it is simply
unimaginable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
