<HEADLINE>
THE PREAKNESS FIELD IS FULL WITH 14 HORSES AND SOME QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ A full but fragile field of 14 horses was entered
Wednesday in the Preakness, including two fillies from Bob
Baffert's barn who were promptly installed as second and third
choices to Menifee, who missed winning the Kentucky Derby by a
neck.
</P>
<P>
   The field was fragile because one of the fillies,
Silverbulletday, drew the No. 14 post position on the far outside,
and it seemed likely that Baffert might decide to run her instead
in the Black-Eyed Susan Stakes for fillies on Friday, the day
before the Preakness. The filly, who has won 10 of her 11 starts,
has drawn the No. 1 slot for the Black-Eyed Susan. Her stablemate,
Excellent Meeting, fifth in the Derby, drew the seventh spot for
the Preakness and was considered certain to start.
</P>
<P>
   The Preakness will be run Saturday at Pimlico Race Course with
such a wide-open field that Charismatic, the long shot who won the
Derby at odds of 31-1, could command no better odds than 6-1,
making him fourth choice in the early betting line. But Charismatic
will start from the No. 6 gate, prompting his trainer, D. Wayne
Lukas, to say, ``We're in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee, who has won five of his seven starts with two seconds,
got the fourth pick in the process and his trainer, Elliott Walden,
cheerfully took the fifth hole in the gate, a decided improvement
over the No. 18 he got for the Derby. ``The 18th spot in the Derby
didn't help,'' Walden said. ``But then, Charismatic came out of No.
16 and won.''
</P>
<P>
   The Preakness, at a mile and three-sixteenths, is one-sixteenth
of a mile shorter than the Derby and five-sixteenths shorter than
the Belmont Stakes, which may explain why it has drawn more fillies
than any other Triple Crown race: 51. Also, the most winners: four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
