u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONAGRA-LAYOFFS-520&AMP;A     05-12 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONAGRA-LAYOFFS-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONAGRA ENLISTING IN THE MARCH TOWARD A LEANER FOOD INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Conagra Inc., one of the world's largest food
companies, said late Wednesday that it would lay off up to 8.4
percent of its work force, or about 7,000 employees, and close
dozens of production, distribution and storage sites as part of an
effort to reduce costs and bolster lackluster earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which sells everything from Butterball turkeys and
Wesson cooking oil to Swiss Miss chocolate drink mix and Peter Pan
peanut butter, is the latest food giant to announce a major
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, food companies have posted weak earnings and
have largely missed a stock market boom because of slowing demand
from Asia, tough price competition at home and, in many cases,
inefficient operations.
</P>
<P>
   These problems have led to similar cutbacks at H.J. Heinz Co.,
Kellogg Co. and Sara Lee Corp. Now, Conagra, which had sales of
almost $24 billion last year, says it too is moving aggressively to
cut costs and reconfigure a company that has long been wedded to a
decentralized operating structure. Although it plans to keep its 80
divisions, it intends to require more cooperation among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a conglomeration of a lot of companies that have long
operated as islands,'' said Bruce Rohde, the chief executive at
Conagra, which is based in Omaha. ``We've never operated as a team,
but now we're going to operate as a team. We're going to be 11
people with a playbook rather than 11 people with 11 playbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts largely praised the announcement but said
Conagra would have to prove that it could effectively lower its
costs and then find a way to increase its sales at a time when many
food companies are experiencing flat sales growth and low profit
margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can only be a positive,'' said Tim Ramey at Deutsche Bank
Securities. ``They can accomplish the belt tightening, but can they
grow the business? I think the market's going to take a
wait-and-see attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Conagra announced the revamping shortly after the stock market
closed. Its shares gained 18.75 cents Wednesday, to $24.8125, on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1997, shares of Conagra and other large food
companies have been trading in narrow ranges because of weak
earnings growth and even weaker sales growth, largely because food
prices have been flat at supermarkets and elsewhere. As a result,
Conagra has finally been forced to react.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like everyone else in the industry, they are recognizing that
to get more growth, you have to be more efficient and then try to
stimulate growth,'' said Nomi Ghez, an analyst at Goldman Sachs.
``The question from here is more often the success of the
execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Conagra said the changes would begin next month. It did not
indicate which operations it would close, but it did say that it
would eventually save about $600 million a year by shutting at
least 15 production plants and 70 storage, distribution and
processing sites and by exiting 20 small noncore businesses. Half
of that money, Rohde said, will go to earnings and the other half
will be used to spur sales growth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The company also said that because of the revamping, pretax
profit margins (which Rohde acknowledged were well below that of
other food companies) were expected to grow 50 percent, to about
6.5 percent, in the next three years, and that it expected earnings
per share to grow by about 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the restructuring, which is called Operation
Overdrive, would result in a charge against earnings of about $810
million that would be spread over the next three years. It said it
would pursue further restructuring efforts over the next two years
that would produce an additional $400 million charge against
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   John McMillin, an analyst at Prudential Securities, said,
however, that many Wall Street analysts had been urging the company
in recent years to divest itself of several unprofitable businesses
or to consider spinning them off. And so while the announcement
Wednesday was positive in terms of cutting costs, he said some
analysts were still worried that the food giant, which has more
than 80,000 employees worldwide, was too large to operate
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think they're trying to juggle a lot of balls in the
air,'' McMillin said. ``Now they're saying we're going to juggle
many balls with fewer hands. I think the applause on Wall Street
would have been greater if there had been divestiture.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts remain concerned about such underperforming
businesses as refrigerated foods and meats, including pork, beef,
chicken and turkey processing.
</P>
<P>
   But Rohde said in an interview that his focus was on creating
more teamwork and that executive pay at Conagra would be tied to
the success of the team approach.
</P>
<P>
   As for Conagra's divesting itself of the meat division or any
other large core business, Rohde said: ``It's always easy to pick
the cylinder that isn't working and say jettison it. We're in good
businesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
