<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4819 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-CRIME-1STLD-     05-12 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CRIME-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REJECTS BACKGROUND CHECKS AT GUN SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: subs 7th graph to add details of other amendments; 2nd take
is new)  
(rm) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Wednesday narrowly defeated a
Democratic measure that would have tightened regulations on the
sale of firearms at gun shows, a clear illustration of lawmakers'
limited appetite for gun control even in the aftermath of the
school shootings in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, senators approved a rival Republican measure that would
create a voluntary system for unlicensed dealers at gun shows to
conduct background checks on their customers. Under current law,
only licensed gun dealers are obliged to do so, and while the
Democratic proposal would have changed that, the Republican
alternative does not. It was a major setback for gun control
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures were put forward as amendments to a broader
juvenile justice bill whose fate has yet to be decided, and the
votes split largely along party lines, with the Republican majority
electing the voluntary measure and the Democratic minority
preferring the mandatory one. The National Rifle Association
lobbied heavily in support of the Republican position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the NRA lives in here,'' grumbled Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., as she left the Senate floor after the votes.
``I find it extraordinarily discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that their measure took into account the rights
of the law-abiding citizens who represent the majority of
participants at gun shows, while the Democrats' amendment was
unduly meddlesome.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, called the Democrats' amendment ``too
costly, too burdensome and too bureaucratic. We all know this is a
much more complex problem than guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had considered their gun show measure to be the single
item in a package of 10 Democratic gun control amendments, from
requiring child safety locks on handguns to raising the minimum age
for handgun ownership to 21 from 18, with the best chance for
garnering enough bipartisan support to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Its failure created serious doubt that any of the rest of their
proposals on gun control would succeed, and it suggested that the
political ground on gun control had not shifted all that much since
the 15 deaths at Columbine High School three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have put forward a few modest gun control proposals
that, like the voluntary measure they passed Wednesday, are clearly
intended to deflect any criticism that they are soft on guns and
too cozy with the NRA. But gun control advocates said the
Democrats' amendments, which are themselves quite limited in scope,
are more substantive and potentially effective.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the shootings at Columbine, Republicans have fixed
their attention not on guns but on the cultural realities that may
be influencing violent behavior among children.
</P>
<P>
   That focus was reflected Wednesday in the passage of a
Republican amendment to the juvenile justice bill that would
authorize federal studies into the marketing of violent imagery to
youth and encourage the makers of movies, video games and other
entertainments to enter into voluntary codes of conduct. Democrats,
too, supported the measure, which passed unanimously, 98-0.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While Republican leaders could have used parliamentary tactics
to block Democratic gun control amendments, they did not, a sign
that they were indeed sensitive to the potentially shifting tides
of public opinion about gun control.
</P>
<P>
   In another tiny concession, Republican leaders agreed, without a
full vote by the Senate, to add to the juvenile justice bill an
amendment by Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-California, that authorized a
federal study into the gun industry's marketing to children.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of that bill, aimed at reducing crime among children,
creates about $1 billion in federal grants to toughen enforcement
of juvenile crime while also, to a lesser extent, enhancing
programs and efforts to prevent it and help troubled children.
</P>
<P>
   Of the scores of suggested amendments the bill has attracted,
the Democratic gun control measures were guaranteed not only to be
the most contentious, but also to be the best measure of any
fluctuation in the political temperature on Capitol Hill, where
most Republicans and a number of Democrats have long resisted new
gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' gun show amendment, whose chief sponsor was Sen.
Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., would have made background checks of all
buyers at gun shows mandatory. It also would have broadened the
definition of a gun show and imposed new regulations on the
promoters of shows.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing for it on the Senate floor, Lautenberg asked, ``When
will the public's rage finally reach into this place?''
</P>
<P>
   He rejected the claim by Republicans that his amendment trampled
on people's rights. ``There's a freedom that overrides all the
others, and that's the freedom to live,'' Lautenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   But his amendment was defeated by a vote of 51-47. While six
Republicans broke party ranks to support Lautenberg's amendment,
two Democrats opposed it and another two Democrats were absent.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican alternative, whose chief sponsor was Sen. Larry
Craig of Idaho, passed by a vote of 53 to 45. Three Republicans
broke party ranks to oppose it, while one Democrat supported it and
two were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Craig and other Republicans who spoke in support of his
amendment said that the country was already awash in gun
regulations that were not being sufficiently enforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rememember, there are 40,000 gun laws in America today _ city
laws, county laws, state laws,'' Craig said. ``Forty thousand,'' he
repeated.
</P>
<P>
   He also disputed Democrats' characterization of gun shows as
places that, because they were liberated from some of the
regulations governing stores, attracted criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five million people are clandestine criminals going to gun
bazaars across the nation?'' Craig asked, referring to annual gun
show attendance in this country. ``I doubt that very much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration had supported Lautenberg's amendment,
which mirrored one of its own proposals. So did gun control
advocates, who said that the fine print in Craig's amendment
actually relaxed some gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said, ``It's a bad day for the
American people, as well as for the Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
