A4823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RJR-ANNUALMEETING13-C     05-12 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-ANNUALMEETING13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Tobacco down, but not out, RJR declares
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. _ Executives told RJR Nabisco shareholders
Wednesday that the company's beleaguered tobacco business
anticipates better times, despite legal threats, declining
cigarette consumption and stiffening competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to be as resilient and competitive as possible in
this new environment,'' said R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. Chief
Executive Andrew Schindler.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Reynolds will become an independent, publicly traded
company following its spin-off by parent RJR.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the first time since 1970 that Reynolds has traded on
the New York Stock Exchange. Its headquarters will be in
Winston-Salem, the company's birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, RJR said it had completed the sale of Reynolds'
international division to Japan Tobacco Inc. for $7.8 billion.
After taxes, an estimated $6 billion in proceeds will be used to
slash RJR's $6.5 billion in debt left over from the high-stakes
1989 leveraged buyout of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover fight, played out partly in Atlanta, where RJR was
based at the time, saddled the company with $30 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, RJR has been burdened by annual debt
payments of $700 million to $800 million a year, money that
otherwise would have been reinvested in the company, RJR Chief
Executive Steven Goldstone said.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds has also suffered from the threat of mounting
health-related lawsuits against Big Tobacco and the growing
strength of Philip Morris, the nation's biggest cigarette maker.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the industry has been squeezed by declining
consumption, which Schindler said could be as low as 8.5 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall's $206 billion national tobacco settlement spared the
major tobacco companies from potentially devastating lawsuits by
states' attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette companies still are vulnerable to suits by individual
smokers and their relatives. But Goldstone said the slashing of
Reynolds' debt will improve the company's odds of surviving a court
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally believe that Reynolds is doing quite well, as is
the industry, in this litigation,'' Goldstone told more than 200
shareholders attending RJR's last annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Several anti-smoking advocates accused RJR of failing to take
sufficient steps to curb youth smoking and to stop the illegal
smuggling of cigarettes. But Melrose Stocks, a retired
Winston-Salem schoolteacher whose deceased husband had worked for
Reynolds for 31 years, defended the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a shame,'' she said to loud applause, ``that no
one has attacked the alcohol industry with the same amount of vigor
that the tobacco has been attacked with.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
