<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS expands aviation electronics program
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service is renaming and expanding its
aviation electronics subsidiary, II Morrow, which makes navigation
and communications systems.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidiary will be called UPS Aviation Technologies, and
financial and management muscle will be added to boost its presence
in the avionics industry, UPS said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't apply the UPS name lightly,'' said Tom Weidemeyer,
president of UPS Airlines, in announcing the change Wednesday at
the Aircraft Electronic Association convention in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS Aviation Technologies plans to triple its business over
the next three years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weidemeyer said the push is part of UPS's belief in investing in
high-tech enterprises related to its core businesses _ in this
case, aviation.
</P>
<P>
   UPS acquired Salem, Ore.,-based II Morrow in 1986 to design and
build mobile communications and tracking gear, including the
hand-held devices used by drivers to collect package information.
</P>
<P>
   It also makes a range of avionics equipment, including Apollo
navigation units for small aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's biggest recent project has been the development of a
next-generation collision-avoidance system for large jets. The
system was recently certified by the Federal Aviation
Administration and is undergoing tests on UPS and other cargo
airline jets.
</P>
<P>
   UPS and other carriers are pushing the new system, based on
global positioning satellite technology, as a cheaper but more
capable alternative to TCAS, or Traffic alert and Collision
Avoidance Systems, now required on passenger aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
