<HEADER>
A4827 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOM-ZE-BRAZIL-MUSIC-A     05-12 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOM-ZE-BRAZIL-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, ADDING ART NOTE)  
 WEAVING A COUNTERPOINT OF IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16)  
 (af)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Tom Ze had just moved into a new apartment,
and he apologized to a visitor for the disarray. The room he uses
for a home recording studio was a jumble of cords, guitars,
microphones and old recording equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Boxes awaited unpacking in the hallways; walls were bare. But
the books were already on the shelves in neat rows: fiction and
history and philosophy from Brazilian and Portuguese authors
alongside Faulkner and Nero Wolfe mysteries by Rex Stout. ``Of
course the books came out first,'' said Ze's wife and sometime
translator, Neusa.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Brazil, where leading songwriters routinely cite
concepts from anthropology and pay homage to avant-garde poets, Ze,
62, comes across as a man who's passionate about ideas. A
conversation wandered from his childhood in Irara, a poor rural
town in Bahia in northeastern Brazil, to his education in
contemporary classical composition at the University of Bahia's
school of music, to his tour with the band Tortoise (which comes to
Irving Plaza in Manhattan on Wednesday) to the Council of Trent, in
the mid-16th century.
</P>
<P>
   While purifying Catholic doctrine, the council banished musical
elements considered lascivious or impure; it set out to define
correct compositional practice for all of Europe. ``It was more
important than the most important composers in Western music,'' Ze
contended.
</P>
<P>
   The Council of Trent wouldn't have approved of Ze's songs, which
are terse little musical contraptions. Drawing at whim from the
great reservoir of Brazilian rhythms and melodies and from his own
instinct for angularity and dissonance, Ze assembles meticulous but
aberrant patterns of rhythm and counterpoint: steely webs of
guitars, percussion and voice.
</P>
<P>
   His lyrics move from tenderness to sarcastic satire to word
games; one song, ``Sem a Letra `A,''' considers what the world
would lose without the letter A, including ``amor.'' The songs are
sly, prickly and ingenious, and they rarely last more than three
minutes because Ze is determined not to bore anyone, especially
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate tedium,'' he said. ``To be a composer is to have
courage. And I don't understand how a composer dares to make a
living through music simply by repeating things that have been done
before.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not a commercial attitude, as Ze could testify. In
Brazil, Ze, whose original name was Antonio Jose Santana Martins,
had his moment of pop glory in the 1960s, when he and a coterie of
fellow musicians from the state of Bahia _ including Caetano
Veloso, Gilberto Gil, Gal Costa and the band Os Mutantes _
transformed Brazilian pop with a movement they called Tropicalia.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing Brazilian traditions and imported rock, the Tropicalists
celebrated the collision of tradition and modernity. Ze's
contribution to ``Tropicalia,'' the movement's 1968 manifesto of an
album, was ``Parque Industrial,'' which put lines from the
Brazilian national anthem alongside advertising jingles and the
English-language refrain ``made in Brazil.'' That same year, he won
a televised song contest with the sardonic ``Sao Sao Paulo, Meu
Amor.''
</P>
<P>
   But his dry voice and smart, playful, unsentimental music
weren't appreciated by a mass public. Nor was his continuing urge
to experiment. By the late 1970s, he was using household appliances
in his arrangements, playing an instrument that triggered assorted
blenders and vacuum cleaners with a keyboard made of doorbells. His
audience dwindled; his recording contract ended in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Ze played for college audiences and scraped by; in the late
1970s, he worked for an advertising agency. ``That was when we
could afford to eat in restaurants sometimes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, David Byrne of the Talking Heads was browsing in a Rio
de Janeiro record store and picked up a copy of Ze's 1976 album,
``Estudando o Samba'' (``Studying the Samba''). Delighted and
startled by the music, Byrne tracked down Ze. Byrne's label, Luaka
Bop, issued a compilation, ``The Best of Tom Ze,'' in 1990,
followed by new albums in 1992 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Luaka Bop has just released ``Postmodern Platos,'' an EP of
remixes of Ze's songs by John McEntire of the Chicago instrumental
band Tortoise, the neo-psychedelic band the High Llamas, Sean
Lennon, the disk jockey Amon Tobin and other Tom Ze fans. The
acclaim from abroad has helped Ze find a new Brazilian audience
too.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Ze begins a United States tour, backed by Tortoise
along with the regular guitarist from his Brazilian band. In some
ways, it's an incongruous match; Ze's songs are quick and
intricate, while Tortoise's music ambles along. But Ze is a
Tortoise fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't make songs that just follow section A with section
B,'' he said. ``They go divagating, as if you were floating lightly
in the clouds. It's like a musical survey, with a mathematics that
turns algebra around.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tortoise, meanwhile, is learning the convolutions of Ze's songs.
``Most of the tunes are pretty standard in that verse-chorus-verse
sense,'' McEntire said. ``But there are lots of little things,
little rhythmic twists and turns that make you say, `How'd they do
that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ze described his method of composing as ``embarrassingly
simple.'' He has recordings of samba and baiao rhythms in three
different tempos; above them he works out patterns on upper strings
of his guitar, mimicking the cavaquinho, the miniature guitar that
accompanies sambas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a surgeon that opens a belly, that's how I live with
samba,'' he said. ``I have this intimacy, this cohabitation with
samba. I try to find a phrase that repeats, an ostinato, that
decays or degenerates the rhythm of the samba. I try to create a
very consistent counterpoint with the phrases of the cavaquinho,
and when this counterpoint satisfies me, it has a peculiarity _ it
permits me to almost escape tonality. ``The cavaquinhos are like
two walls topped by a ceiling. And this ceiling, to get the
structure to stand upright, must have interesting elements and also
must have a subject to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, Ze stood his visitor's Portuguese dictionary on
end, parallel to a box of low-calorie sweetener; those were the
cavaquinhos. Then he balanced a knife across the tops: the melody.
``The melody is a cradle that makes the words have more meaning,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Ze described his music as an extended misunderstanding.
``In truth, I am a composer of only one piece,'' he said. ``I try
to repeat a song I listened to as a child, the song of the
washerwomen in Irara. That was the first music I heard. But every
time I make the attempt to write it, I keep making mistakes, so I
keep trying again. And I keep finding something that moves the
atomic nucleus of my desire to make music.''
</P>
<P>
   Ze delivered that explanation with a touch of irony, but as in
many of his songs, there was sincerity behind the wit. ``They say
that Faulkner's writing speaks about the loss of an Edenic world,''
he said. ``I lost a world just like his, the world of my
grandparents in the country, a world of justice and ethics. I'm
trying to revive this world all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ze doesn't usually listen to other people's music. ``If you look
to the newspaper and to radio and to television, you become
crazy,'' he said. ``Because every day something is happening in
music in the world, and something is taking your attention. And if
you stay in your small room with your small problem, sometimes it
is more important, because you can contribute to the music of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The landscape of creation is a place where you're deeply
alone,'' Ze said. ``A person who's creating has to throw out
everything that he knows and everything that he's seen. So I have
to throw out serialism and tonality, throw out bossa nova and so
on, Tropicalismo, sambas, rock, blues and folkloric music. I have
to reach that lonely place where, if I'm able to reach a syllable,
I'm in the genesis again. That is loneliness, but I can't say that
it would be called pain. On the contrary, I see it with much joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten used to going into that room of emptiness,'' he
continued. ``From time to time the room is full of water, and I'm
like a fish arriving at the shore. I'm an animal that decided not
to develop my wings but to develop my legs. And when the room is
full of fire, that's not a problem because I become a salamander.
And I could think of an apocalypse, like in the Bible, or remember
the folkloric dances of my youth, where I saw these fires in the
distance. But they lit up my heart, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
