<HEADLINE>
THE CHANGING FACES-IN-CHIEF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   How outraged should the Chinese be about NATO's bombing mistake
this week? Reading  &UR; George Stephanopoulos &LR; ' ``All Too Human''
(Little, Brown; $27.95),  &UR; Eric Umansky  &LR; came upon the former
Clinton aide's description of the president's reaction to the
killing of six American soldiers in Mogadishu, Somalia. ``When
people kill us,'' said Clinton, ``they should be killed in greater
numbers. I believe in killing people who try to hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Meanwhile, the Beauty and Barber Supply Institute has
announced that Stephanopoulos will present the keynote address at
the institute's annual convention this summer in Las Los  &LR; Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. In related news, facial reader  &UR; Rose Rosetree  &LR; told
Ladies' Home Journal that ``the scandals through his presidency
have bonded''  &UR; Bill  &LR; and  &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to 1992,'' says the Journal, ``both had curved lower
eyelids, revealing an openness to meeting people. Today, their
eyelids are straight, meaning they're reluctant to welcome new
acquaintances into their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICAL PETTING ZOO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Because every president since  &UR; Grover Cleveland &LR;  has had a pet,
candidates in every party are cramming their Web pages with
pictures of themselves with their dogs and cats and birds. Among
the Republicans:  &UR; Elizabeth &LR;  and  &UR; Robert Dole &LR; 's late schnauzer,
Leader, has a site of his own;  &UR; Dan Quayle &LR;  has a Labrador
retriever;  &UR; Steve Forbes  &LR; has two poodles;  &UR; George W. Bush &LR;  has a
springer spaniel and three cats.
</P>
<P>
   Senator  &UR; John McCain &LR; , R-Ariz., has 16 pets, including three
dogs, four cats, a rabbit and various snakes, lizards and fish.
``We win,'' an aide to McCain told U.S. News &AMP; World Report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE SCENE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Frances Peavey  &LR; and  &UR; Jan Hartsough &LR; , members of the grassroots,
nonprofit Crabgrass group, are just back from helping refugees in
Kosovo, where they were issued identification tags by the United
Nations High Commission on Refugees. The tags, which they wore
during their entire stay, identified them as members of
``Grabass,'' a designation that drew few comments from generally
non-English-speaking Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEYMAKERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The cosmetics company L'Oreal has paid $130,000 for the
renovation of the steeple of Memorial Church in Berlin, in return
for hanging on it huge banners featuring the face of  &UR; Claudia &LR; 
 &UR; Schiffer &LR;  and other supermodels. Berlin newspapers said that the
banners, which went up Monday, are ``tasteless'' and
``sacrilegious,'' but Lutheran Church Bishop  &UR; Wolfgang Huber &LR;  said
the money was needed.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the interests &LR;  of family harmony, May 17 has been declared
Don't Do Dishes Day. Also in the interests &LR;  of commercialism: The
declarer is Dixie, the company that makes disposable plates and
cups.
</P>
<P>
   _ New York magazine reports that trendy moms in New York are
carrying gingham diaper bags by  &UR; Kate Spade &LR; , which cost a cool
$245; and according to the Washington Monthly, all future grave
sites at the Green River Cemetery in East Hampton, on New York's
Long Island _ ``popular as a grave site among the rich and famous''
_ have been taken.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TECHNOSPHERE EXPERIMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Four human guinea pigs are ``marooned in cyberspace,'' says the
Times of London, in an experiment conducted by a researcher at the
University of Herfordshire.
</P>
<P>
   The four, two men and two women, were locked in solitary
confinement on Monday, dressed in bathrobes and possessing only
credit cards and access to the Internet. Their aim will be to
clothe, feed and entertain themselves for 100 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Internet users can follow their progress at www.msn.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `I'm going to tell her she needs better advisers. (The skits)
were in poor taste. She should have gone on and not made any
references to the president at all. She's not conducting herself as
well as she could.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Camryn Manheim, who just a few days before was Monica
Lewinsky's gal pal, on Lewinsky's ``Saturday Night Live''
appearance. Manheim, who was quoted by the New York Daily News, is
in the middle of a publicity push for her new book, which may have
something to do with her use of Lewinsky as a vehicle to call
attention to herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Monica) is lovely, warm, honest and candid. I just want to
support her in any way I can. She did a great job. And she was fun
to watch. I actually stayed up to watch her.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Manheim a day later. Her press representative said that
Manheim's opinion stood: that Lewinsky's appearance was ``both well
done and ill advised.''
</P>
