<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4839 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-HNS &LR;      05-12 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is painfully clear now to the top-seeded San Antonio Spurs
that the eighth-seeded Minnesota Timberwolves are worthy of NBA
playoff competition.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-71 upset by the Wolves on Tuesday at the Alamodome showed
the Spurs just how tough their first-round opponent can be.
</P>
<P>
   With the best-of-five series even at one game each entering
tonight's Game 3 at the Target Center in Minneapolis, San Antonio
must win at least one of the two games at Minnesota to avoid a
shocking early exit from postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gut check for us,'' said San Antonio point guard
Avery Johnson. ``I kept telling the team that Minnesota played hard
to get to the playoffs, just like us. They are NBA players, and
they can win if we don't put out a maximum effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have to win there, and it will be a good test for us.
I'm looking forward to see how we respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Center David Robinson said the team needs to respond by
realizing Minnesota put out a better effort than the Spurs in Game
2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did everything better than we did,'' Robinson said.
``They were better in every aspect of the game. We didn't shoot
well, we didn't rebound, we didn't go after loose balls, and we
didn't defend.
</P>
<P>
   ``After watching what happened to Utah (a Game 2 loss at home to
Sacramento), I thought we would have been sharp. I don't understand
why we weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio missed all eight 3-point shots it attempted in Game
2. Guard Mario Elie, who has been the team's top outside threat,
made only two of his 12 field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I let the team down, and I blame myself for a lot of
what went wrong,'' Elie said. ``I had a lot of open looks and
couldn't put the shot down. When Tim (Duncan) and David are being
double-teamed, we have to make those shots. I also missed a couple
of defensive assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to Minnesota's success Tuesday was forward Kevin
Garnett, who had 23 points, 12 rebounds and six assists. The battle
between Garnett and Duncan, two of the league's premier players,
has been the focus of attention in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Duncan is really good, and I'm not taking anything away
from him,'' Garnett said. ``But I'm pretty good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The two had words in Game 1 when Duncan scored 26 points, but
Garnett took Round 2 by scoring 10 fourth-quarter points Tuesday to
hold off a San Antonio comeback attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both good players,'' Duncan said. ``We're both going to
go out there and compete and do the best we can for our teams, but
that's where it ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie said Garnett set the tone of the game early Tuesday when he
was called twice for goaltending in the first quarter. It gave the
Spurs two baskets, but Elie said it paid off for the Wolves in the
long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garnett established a presence right away,'' Elie said.
``Later he got a block on one of my shots right on the glass. The
ref was standing right there and didn't call it. But Kevin Garnett
is a marquee player, and I'm just Mario Elie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves also showed they would get physical when center
Dean Garrett was called for a flagrant foul as he clotheslined
Johnson when Johnson drove in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avery had been driving to the hole in the first game, and
nobody had really stopped him,'' Garrett said. ``I didn't intend to
hurt him, and Avery knows that. We live two minutes from each other
(in Sugar Land). But these are the playoffs, and I don't want to go
home yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wolves feel confident entering tonight's game because they
are 18-7 at home this year, including three consecutive victories
and nine wins in the past 11 games at the Target Center.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs had the best road record in the NBA this season at
16-9, winning three in a row away from home to close out the
regular season and five of the last six.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't lost our confidence,'' Elie said. ``We play well on
the road. I've been in these situations before, even in a Game 7.
We'll be back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
