<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT &LR;      05-12 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS CONDEMN DELAY IN SEARCHING OF SCIENTIST'S COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators told the top Energy Department lawyer on
Wednesday that they were baffled and appalled at the long delay in
authorizing a search of the work computer of a scientist at Los
Alamos National Laboratory suspected of spying for China.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Energy and Natural Resources Committee, Sen.
Frank Murkowksi, R-Alaska, said at a hearing that the episode was
``a classic case of bureaucratic bungling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke's 130-year-old secret is more secure than our nuclear
weapons research,'' Murkowksi said. A Democrat on the committee,
Sen. Blanche Lambert Lincoln of Arkansas, said the failure to
quickly search the computer ``still angers me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Supposedly everybody was watching, and in reality no one was
watching,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The department's general counsel, Mary Anne Sullivan, told the
committee she agreed that the legal and bureaucratic obstacles to
the search ``produced an unfortunate result.'' She noted that
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson announced tighter security
measures on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sullivan said the department had twice offered to search the
computer but had backed off because of concerns that an espionage
investigation might be jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   Requests by the FBI for permission to obtain a search warrant
for the scientist, Wen Ho Lee, were rebuffed twice in 1997 by the
Justice Department. It was not until March of this year, after
obtaining Lee's consent, that investigators examined his computer.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say they discovered then that Lee had improperly
transferred huge amounts of classified nuclear secrets into an
unsecure system and then tried to delete them in February, two days
after he failed a lie detector test.
</P>
<P>
   No information has surfaced to suggest that the delay in
searching Lee's computer harmed national security. Lee has not been
charged with any crime, and his lawyer says his client did nothing
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But the difficulties of gaining access to a computer at a
government-owned weapons laboratory prompted senators to complain
on Wednesday about how security concerns could be improperly
subordinated to privacy protections or the demands of espionage
investigations, most of which never result in prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sullivan and her aides said the Energy Department may search
someone's computer if there is a reasonable basis to suspect
work-related misconduct. But a search in a criminal case requires a
higher standard, probable cause that a crime has been committed.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Energy Department may forgo its right to search _ as
it did in the case of Lee _ if it fears that a defendant may
legally challenge the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   This legal caution can create a dilemma in which no one is
charged with a crime, yet national security may be harmed because
no one does a search.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, in the same closed hearing room, the Senate
Select Committee on Intelligence heard from Attorney General Janet
Reno on many of the same issues. Afterward, the committee's vice
chairman, Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said that most committee members
believed that the Justice Department should have approved the FBI's
request for warrants to search the computer.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's chairman, Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., said the
attorney general ``defends what happened but doesn't know what
happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
