<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE TALKS WITH GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- He may not be a quick fix for the Galaxy's scoring
problems, but coach Sigi Schmid met with former UCLA All-American
Seth George on Wednesday and said he hopes to have the talented
striker in training camp this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy drafted George in the second round (13th overall) of
the 1999 Major League Soccer college draft, even though they knew
he was heading to Europe to test his skills.
</P>
<P>
   George signed a temporary contract with 1860 Munich of the
German Bundesliga. He had been training there since January but
recently returned to his Mission Viejo home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we'll get some progress on that today,'' said
Schmid, who admits he's had conversations with George since he
returned. ``If (his signing) happens today he will be here
tomorrow. If it gets resolved tomorrow, then he'll be here the next
day. We're very, very close.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy General Manager Sergio Del Prado was cautiously
optimistic about signing George. However, George could be invited
to work out as soon as today as a non-roster player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get him here,'' Del Prado said. ``Seth had the
opportunity to use an option with his German club but chose not to.
At this point, we are finding out if there are any transfer fees or
any other obstacles out there before signing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Sigi would like to get him here as soon as possible to
see how he fits with the team, but we'll just have to wait at this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   George finished third in the voting for the college soccer
Player of the Year award last fall. He led the Bruins in all
offensive categories, scoring 15 goals and eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation since Schmid replaced Octavio
Zambrano last month that George would return to play for his former
college coach.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, George led the Bruins to their third national title
under Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a talented player,'' Schmid said. ``But at this point I
better keep things quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   George would be a welcome addition to a Los Angeles team that
has scored only five goals in eight games. Still, the Galaxy is
continuing to look at other strikers in an attempt to bolster their
front line.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy public relations coordinator Luis Garcia confirmed that
the team is inviting strikers Alejandro Sequiera and Mickey Trotman
to training camp next week.
</P>
<P>
   Sequiera, formerly of Tampa Bay and a Costa Rica native, could
replace seldom used El Salvadoran Jaime Caicedo as the Galaxy's
fourth foreign player.
</P>
<P>
   Trotman, released by Dallas, has shown signs of becoming a
talented scorer in the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid said he likes Caicedo, but carrying him is more of a
burden than an asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a talented player, but he's only 18,'' said Schmid.
``When you're only allowed four foreign players, it's important
that all those foreign players are making an impact on your team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to attribute the Galaxy's success last season to
Welton and Cobi Jones. Jones led the team in scoring with 19 goals
and 13 assists. Welton finished second with 17 goals and 11
assists.
</P>
<P>
   One can just as easily attribute the team's 4-4 start to the
same duo. Welton is scoreless this season and Jones has just one
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're more disappointed than anybody,'' Schmid said.
``I'm sure Cobi and Welton would like to have more goals at this
point. Welton had two good chances and Cobi had one very good
chance last week against Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles lost, 2-1, scoring on a beautiful Danny Pena
one-touch volley from 30 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it seemed those chances were falling for them and
it's our job to continue to get them looks,'' Schmid said. ``We did
shooting yesterday and this afternoon. You just have to get those
two feeling confident in front of the goal and that's what we're
working on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
