<HEADER>
A4851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMES-SCENE13-COX     05-12 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMES-SCENE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For game designers, expo a chance to soar - or crash
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Video game makers from and around the world will
convene here today with their eyes on the future and their heads
filled with visions of the most hallowed of toy shrines: The
holiday shopping cart.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Electronic Entertainment Expo (E3 to those in the
business), in Los Angeles through the weekend, is the event for
video game makers, ranging from the smallest of design companies to
the biggest of conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of their size, their hopes are the same _ to be among
the hottest of games this holiday shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   But before that happens, game designers such as Origin Systems
Inc., Digital Anvil Inc. and Blue Byte Software _ all in town from
Austin, Texas, for the trade show _ have to face an even tougher
audience: The media, industry executives and some hard-core gamers
who via the Internet could pronounce a game D.O.A. just minutes
after it leaves the show floor.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes at E3, a digital playground where speed, hype and
killer graphics (both figurative and literal) can generate buzz for
the lucky companies that deliver the goods.
</P>
<P>
   This year's expo comes at a time when Austin's gaming community
is getting more notice than ever, and Austin will be
well-represented in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Central Texas companies are expected to unveil some of the most
anticipated games at the expo, and a few local companies are
planning some surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The strong showing this year reflects the growing Austin game
community, much of it centering around Origin Systems, the veteran
Austin software company owned by Electronic Arts Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Origin, which produces the popular Ultima and Wing Commander
series of games, will be part of a large presence by Electronic
Arts. But it also plans to debuting its latest project _ Ultima:
Ascension, Ultima creator Richard Garriott's long awaited
single-player game.
</P>
<P>
   David Swofford, a spokesman for Origin, said Austin's gaming
community is growing quickly, and was born from the area's
connections to art and music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's created a good mix for the interactive entertainment
community,'' Swofford said. ``That's one of the reasons Garriott
game down here in the '80s. There's tons of creativity in the
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Origin, which employs about 200 workers in Austin, has also
worked with other Austin game companies including Digital Anvil,
the game company formed by former Origin executive Chris Roberts.
Roberts, who piloted the ``Wing Commander'' game series for Origin,
co-wrote and directed a film version of ``Wing Commander'' that was
released in March.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' company plans to debut three games at E3, to be
published by Microsoft Corp., and the expo will be the company's
unofficial coming out party after more than a year of quiet work on
the games.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Davies, president of Digital Anvil, said the reasons his
company decided to open up shop in Austin are the same reasons many
are attracted to move here _ quality of life and a talent pool of
creative workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gaming is very much like movies _ there are high production
values,'' Davies said. ``Austin is a very heavy center for artistic
talent, both in music and for visual artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Origin and Digital Anvil's high-profile projects have created a
buzz for Austin's game industry, said Vince Broady, editorial
director of GameSpot, an online gaming magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Austin community is well-regarded in the PC/videogame
industry, as is Texas in general,'' Broady said via e-mail. ``I
think its general atmosphere, proximity to UT and freethinking
reputation make it a natural incubator for game software
development, and I think it will only get bigger over time.''
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of gaming and the abundance of computer-savvy
residents (throw a rock in a University of Texas computer lab and
you'll hit an ``Quake II'' deathmatcher) has also attracted new
game companies to the area. In the past few years, Iguana Software,
owned by Acclaim Entertainment, has started designing games _
including ``South Park,'' ``Turok: Dinosaur Hunter'' and ``All Star
Baseball 2000'' _ for the Sony PlayStation and the Nintendo 64
console systems.
</P>
<P>
   Bootprint Software, a division of GT Interactive, has also set
up shop in Austin. Bootprint has yet to release any games, but has
actively been recruiting programmers and others.
</P>
<P>
   Austin has also made a believer out of European game developer
Blue Byte Software. Based in Germany, the company has all but made
Austin its base of operations. Thomas Hertzler, chief executive of
Blue Byte, said the company has found the Austin office keeps the
company closer to U.S. gaming trends.
</P>
<P>
   After releasing its latest game recently, ``Settlers 3,'' the
company plans to make a big splash at E3 by revising a game
classic. The company is expected to announce today that it is
working with the creators of the arcade game ``Dragon's Lair,'' to
release a new version called ``Dragon's Lair 3D'' next year.
</P>
<P>
   Don Bluth, the legendary artist who designed ``Dragon's Lair,''
will be at the company's booth alongside the designers of the
company's other new title, ``Shadowpact.''
</P>
<P>
   For every new kid on the gaming block, however, there are others
that don't make it in the industry. Austin's Crack.com, for
instance, was busily working on a game called ``Golgotha'' before
it went out of business last year.
</P>
<P>
   But game watchers like Broady say they think the game community
in Austin, led by the larger design companies, will continue to
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I hope so,'' San Francisco-based Broady said. ``I
need an excuse to come down and get some decent Tex-Mex.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
