<HEADLINE>
KINGS ANNOUNCE AFFILIATE AGREEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might not seem as pressing a matter as the still-vacant
coaching position, but the Kings' organization took a significant
step forward Wednesday with the announcement of a two-year
affiliation agreement with the Lowell (Mass.) Lock Monsters of the
American Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings will send 12 prospects to Lowell next season and 18
the year after, and will hire the Lock Monsters' coaching staff. It
means that after two years of piecemeal arrangements with other AHL
teams, the Kings will have complete control over how their
prospects are developed and what style of hockey they will play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will make the transition easier for players coming
up (to the Kings),'' General Manager Dave Taylor said. ``We'd like
to establish a winning organization at both levels. When both teams
are playing the same style, it's easier for players to come up and
down. The best example of this is what New Jersey does with their
team in Albany (N.Y.), and Buffalo has been very effective with
their affiliate in Rochester. Calgary and Montreal for many years
groomed players at the AHL level to step in.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who returned to Los Angeles earlier this week after
attending the World Championships in Oslo, Norway, said it is
likely the Kings will continue their limited affiliation with the
Long Beach Ice Dogs of the IHL for at least one more year.
</P>
<P>
   The Lowell affiliation is the first move in what promises to be
a busy summer for Taylor. High on the agenda is the hiring of a
coach to replace Larry Robinson, who was fired on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing new there,'' Taylor said. ``I've been
in Europe and I haven't interviewed anyone yet. I haven't asked any
teams for permission (to interview their coaches). I have a list
and a number of teams I want to talk to. In the next few weeks,
we'll be moving forward with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also faces a deadline to sign 1997 draft choices Matt
Zultek (left wing/center) and defenseman Richard Seeley. If they
are not signed by June 1, they go back into this year's draft, on
June 26 in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to sign them,'' Taylor said. ``But it has to be
within reason or what we think is appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he expects to speak with Zultek's agent, Larry
Kelly, this weekend at the Memorial Cup (Canadian junior hockey's
championship tournament) in Ottawa. Taylor also said he will speak
with Kelly about defenseman Aki Berg, who played in Finland this
season after he and the Kings could not reach contract terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched (Berg) play a couple of times (at the World
Championships),'' Taylor said. ``I didn't speak with him. We'd like
to sign him.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also said he is preparing to make a contract proposal to
24-year-old Finnish defenseman Jere Karalahti, a 1993 draftee who
is close to being ready to play in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he feels he's ready for the opportunity,'' Taylor
said. ``The question will be his skating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
