<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GOVERNOR MOVES TO ELIMINATE NEW YORK CITY COMMUTER TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki and legislative leaders
promised unexpectedly Wednesday to eliminate a 33-year-old income
tax for many suburban residents who hold jobs in New York City,
disregarding Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's contention that those workers
should help shoulder the cost of police and other city services.
</P>
<P>
   The move would deprive the city of at least $210 million
annually, and represents a striking attempt by lawmakers to appeal
to suburban voters, a crucial constituency in the balance of power
in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   In places like Nassau and Westchester Counties, the tax has long
been one more aggravation of the commuter lifestyle, as resented as
clogged highways and delayed trains. It has also stoked tensions
between suburban officials and their city counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 800,000 people pay the tax, which the state collects for
the city and which ranges from .45 percent of taxable earnings, for
most of those covered, or $180 annually on $40,000 of net income.
The proposed repeal would immediately affect only those who live in
New York state, about 58 percent of the people who pay the tax. But
the proposed measure stipulates that if it is overturned in court
on the ground that it discriminates against out-of-state residents,
then the tax will be eliminated for everyone. The city would as a
result lose another $150 million, bringing the total cost of the
repeal to $360 million.
</P>
<P>
   The tax was not on lawmakers' agendas until earlier this month,
when it arose suddenly in the maneuvering over a special election
for a state Senate seat in Rockland and Orange Counties, northwest
of the city. The two major contenders proposed repealing the tax, a
politically popular move in the district, and both Republican and
Democratic legislative leaders responded in an effort to bolster
their standard-bearers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commuters feel that they pay enough in all kinds of
taxes,'' said Assemblyman Samuel Colman, a Rockland Democrat, who
argued that the city could handily afford the tax cut because it
has a $2 billion surplus. .
</P>
<P>
   The politics could linger even after the tax is gone: if
Giuliani runs for the U.S. Senate next year, he could come under
attack in suburban areas for backing the tax. One of Giuliani's
potential rivals for the Republican nomination, U.S. Rep. Rick
Lazio of Long Island, quickly issued a statement Wednesday night
praising the proposed repeal.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has been a vocal proponent of cutting city taxes, but
has often asserted that city officials should have the right to
choose which taxes are lowered, not Albany, which has the final say
over most local levies. Speaking Wednesday afternoon, Giuliani
assailed the Legislature for seeking to end the commuter tax,
saying that if anything, it should be higher. He noted that city
residents pay a far higher local income tax, roughly 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the political realities, it can't be increased even
to a level that would be considered maybe somewhat more equitable
in light of the services,'' Giuliani said of the commuter tax.
``Commuters to the city are very important, I value them as much as
I do in many ways residents. They make a tremendous contribution to
the city. But in fact, the city has to have extra services as a
result of that, extra fire services, extra police services, extra
medical services.''
</P>
<P>
   After Pataki announced Wednesday night that he would sign the
legislation if it is approved by the Legislature as expected next
week, Giuliani's spokeswoman said he would sue the state to retain
the tax. The spokeswoman, Sunny Mindel, said pointedly that the
mayor would not change his position because of a possible U.S.
Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should think that because of politics, the mayor would
abandon New York City,'' Ms. Mindel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
