<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/12/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT61) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- NY-GARDEN-SALE, 5-12 --
Olean For, 78, presses her hands together in gratitude when she
hears that her community garden on East Third Street will be
preserved. The $1.2 million purchase of 51 lots by the New York
Restoration Project - arranged by the singer and actress Bette
Midler - provided a vital piece in the city's negotiations with
environmental groups. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT60) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
WOZZECK-OPERA, 5-12 -- John Tomlinson and Philip Langridge in
Schoenberg's opera ``Moses und Aron,'' at the Met. The production
illustrates with sets and costumes a conversation going on within
the composer's head. The people on stage, not least the elaborate
and powerful chorus, are a public outlet for private thinking.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT59) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
PARSONS-DANCE, 5-12 -- David Parsons, left, Robert Battle and the
Parsons Dance Company during a rehearsal of Battle's ``Rush Hour,''
which is to have its premiere at the Joyce Theater. ``Lately, every
time I start a new project, I get unnerved,'' says Parsons. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT58) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
PERFORMING-SPACE-THEATER, 5-12 -- Mark Russell, the executive
director of P.S. 122, in his words, ``the Carnegie Hall of
performance art,'' in the larger of his East Village theater's two
spaces. ``I feel like I have a new job this year,'' says Russell,
who is trying to keep P.S. 122 cutting-edge by presenting emerging
talent while also providing space to the established artists who
came of age with some of the audience. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT57) SAO PAOLO, Brazil -- May 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
16 -- TOM-ZE-BRAZIL-MUSIC, 5-12 -- Tom Ze, who begins a United
States tour this week, at home in Sao Paolo. Even in Brazil, where
leading songwriters routinely cite concepts from anthropology and
pay homage to avant-garde poets, Ze, 62, comes across as a man
who's passionate about ideas. ``To be a composer is to have
courage,'' he says. (Jon Pareles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT56) PHILADELPHIA -- May 12, 1999 -- PHILLY-MAYORAL-2, 5-12
-- One of front-runner John F. Street's rivals in the Democratic
primary for mayor of Philadelphia is Marty Weinberg, a white
candidate in a city that often votes along racial lines. Weinberg,
a wealthy lawyer, was once an adviser to Frank L. Rizzo when he was
mayor from 1972 to 1980. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT55) PHILADELPHIA -- May 12, 1999 -- PHILLY-MAYORAL-1, 5-12
-- John F. Street, the front-runner in the Democratic primary for
mayor of Philadelphia, is startled when he receives a campaign
check for $100,000 at a rally on Tuesday. In a rough-and-tumble
campaign to succeed Mayor Edward G. Rendell, a popular Democrat who
is barred by the city charter from serving a third consecutive
term, Street, 55, appears to have the edge. (Laura Pedrick/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT54) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- May 12, 1999 -- CALIF-FUR-2,
5-12 -- Beverly Hills voters have overwhelmingly rejected a
proposal Wednesday (the wording for which is shown) to require that
fur coats sold here carry a tag describing the grisly ways that
animals used to make them may have been killed. In rejecting
Proposition A, the Consumer's Right to Informed Choices Act of
1999, Beverly Hills voters deflected a direct attack on a symbol of
the city's image of glamour and wealth. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT53) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- May 12, 1999 -- CALIF-FUR-1,
5-12 -- David Meyer, left, and Luke Montgomery led the drive to
require that furs sold in Beverly Hills carry a tag describing the
grisly ways that animals used to make the coats may have been
killed. The measure was overwhelmingly rejected Wednesday. ``We set
out to educate a few consumers here in Beverly Hills about how fur
animals are killed by clubbing and electrocution, but we succeeded
in educating millions of people around the world,'' says
Montgomery, 25. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT52) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CONGRESS, 5-12 --
The chief negotiators on the military spending bill, Sen. Ted
Stevens, left, and Rep. C.W. (Bill) Young, R-Fla., want $11 billion
for the armed forces. Ignoring their leaders' wishes to hold own
the spending, Congressional negotiators on Thursday tentatively
agreed on a $11.6 billion emergency bill to finance the fighting in
Yugoslavia and pay for a myriad of Pentagon programs. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT51) AVIANO, Italy -- May 12, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NATO, 5-12 --
Lt. Gen. Michael Short, NATO's top air war commander, during an
interview on Wednesday. Despite the success allied warplanes are
having against Serbian forces in Kosovo, the alliance needs to
renew its attacks against the Yugoslav leadership in central
Belgrade to force Slobodan Milosevic to give in to NATO's demands
Short said during the interview. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT50) RISHON LEZION, Israel -- May 12, 1999 --
ISRAEL-POLITICS-2, 5-12 -- Candidates for Prime Minister in Israel
are courting Russian immigrant voters. In Rishon Lezion, Russian
and Hebrew posters back the incumbent, Benjamin Netanyahu. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT49) SAWYERVILLE, Ala. -- May 12, 1999 -- SATELLITE-JACKPOT,
5-12 -- Barbara Carlisle, left, and her parents Velma and George
Merriweather stand next to their satellite dish on Tuesday. George
Merriweather said he was mad when he realized he had been cheated
on installment payments for a television satellite dish they
purchased in 1995. A Hale County jury sympathized and last week
awarded $581 million to the 80-year-old retired foundry worker, his
wife and their daughter, Barbara Carlisle. (Porfirio
Solorzano/Tuscaloosa News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT48) ATLANTA -- May 12, 1999 -- COX-TCA-CABLE, 5-12 -- James
Robbins, Cox Communications' president and chief executive, in the
company's Atlanta offices. In the latest consolidation deal by a
cable company preparing to offer telephone, Internet and
interactive services as well as ordinary television to its
subscribers, Cox on Wednesday announced it was acquiring TCA Cable
TV Inc., for $3.264 billion in stock and cash. (Phil
Skinner/Atlanta Journal Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT47) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-SUMMERS-3, 5-12 --
From left, Stuart Eizenstat, an undersecretary at the State
Department, Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, Treasury
Secretary Robert E. Rubin and President Clinton at a Rose Garden
ceremony Wednesday during which Summers is announced as the new
treasury secretary. As he entered the home stretch of his training
for the most vital job in managing the world economy, he has
become, one close associate said recently, ``more Rubin-esqe.''
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT46) LIPLJAN, Yugoslavia -- May 12, 1999 -- KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
5-12 -- Milenko Djokic points to a hole in a house caused by debris
from a missile, presumably fired by NATO forces. The village is
near an airport which was apparently the target of the weapon.
(Steve Erlanger/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT45) DENVER -- May 12, 1999 -- DENVER-GALLERY-2, 5-12 --
Frederick and Jan Mayer in the foyer of a home they built on a
former parking lot in Denver. Last year the Mayers were included in
a listing of the world's 200 top collectors in Art News magazine.
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT44) DENVER -- May 12, 1999 -- DENVER-GALLERY-1, 5-12 -- The
home built by Frederick and Jan Mayer on a former parking lot in
Denver. It is the first private single-family residence to rise in
this old industrial district in a century. (Kevin Moloney/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT43) HOLLYWOOD -- May 12, 1999 -- TV-MUSICALS, 5-12 -- Neil
Meron, left, and Craig Zadan, producers of the TV musical ``Double
Platinum,'' in Zadan's living room in the hills above Sunset Strip
in Hollywood. ``Doing a musical for television is doing something
very fragile,'' says Zadan. ``The first criteria is that it has to
be dramatic, it has to be emotional. The second is that it has to
have very, very strong characters. And the third is that you have
to have event casting: you have to have stars.'' (Marissa Roth/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) PHOENIX -- May 12, 1999 -- NATIVE-AMERICAN-ART-2, 5-12
-- A katsina doll made by Hopis from cottonwood tree roots at the
Heard Museum in Phoenix. Resplendent after an $18 million
expansion, the 70-year-old Heard, with its staff of Indian experts,
is pointing the way to a new nationwide spirit of collaboration
between Indians and the museums housing their patrimony and
sometimes the remains of their ancestors. (Jeff Topping/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) LEDYARD, Conn. -- May 12, 1999 --
CIR-SWEEPSTAKES-ONLINE-2, 5-12 -- Wendy Limauge enters so many
sweepstakes that she has a bar chart of her winnings. Online
contests have allowed her to cut her postage bill sharply. ``People
think I'm super lucky or I'm crazy,'' says Ms. Limauge, 38, of
Ledyard, a full-time computer instructor and mother of three who
owns a company called The Computer Lady. ``I get to win things I
would never, never buy, or couldn't afford to buy.'' (George
Ruhe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) PIKESVILLE, Md. -- May 12, 1999 --
CIR-SWEEPSTAKES-ONLINE-1, 5-12 -- Norman Posner, a sweepstakes
enthusiast, won his first contest in 1969, a trip to Miami Beach
for his wedding, with Bob Hope as his best man. Posner has won
cars, cruises, trips to Europe, television sets and T-shirts
galore. He says he's lucky, yet he still adds that he believes that
gimmicks help. (Ann Grillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) SOMERS, N.Y. -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-IBM-FUTURE-2, 5-12
-- Russell A. Budd, an IBM engineer, helped develop a ``wearable
PC.'' Also referred to internally as the visionpad, the device is a
fully functioning PC, with a headpiece that contains a virtual
display as well as a speaker and a microphone. (Joyce Dopkeen/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) SOMERS, N.Y. -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-IBM-FUTURE-1, 5-12
-- The cyberphone combines a phone with access to the Web. Though
it looks much like an ordinary cellular phone, a tiny
high-resolution image of a Web page can be bounced off a mirror,
found inside the phone's flip cover, to generate a virtual screen
image in front of the user. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-EIZENSTAT, 5-12 --
Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, foreground, and Stuart
Eizenstat, an undersecretary at the State Department, during a
White House ceremony announcing Summers as the new Treasury
secretary. Eizenstat was chosen to replace Summers as second in
command at Treasury. (Stephen Crolwey/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-RESIGNS-5, 5-12 --
Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers is congratulated by
President Clinton as Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright look on, Wednesday at the White House.
Clinton announced that Summers would be taking over the post
vacated by Rubin who announced his resignation on Wednesday.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-BEAUTY-KIOSK, 5-12 --
The interactive beauty kiosk at Bloomingdale's and Macy's. With its
Cyber Beauty Advisor, a California-based makeup company called
English Ideas has toned down the hard-charging counter clerk,
infused her with information and put her inside an interactive
touch-screen kiosk. (Susan Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) PITTSBURGH -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-ROBOTS-2, 5-12 -- Cye,
which Probotics sells for $695, can be trained to wheel around on
its own. It can also be programmed to ``learn'' the floor plan of a
house and, with an accompanying wagon, it can tow up to 10 pounds.
(Gary Tramontina/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-ROBOTS-1, 5-12 -- Aibo,
a $2,500 robotic dog from Sony, can wag its tail, chase a pink
plastic ball and get around at about six yards a minute. Aibo
(pronounced eye-BO) is Sony's answer to the 20th-century quest for
a relatively intelligent robot that gets around on its own. (Philip
Greenberg/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-ART-DICTIONARY-3, 5-12
-- Samuel Sachs II, the technophilic director of the Frick
Collection, is enthusiastic about the online version of the Grove
Dictionary of Art. ``It's handy for a lot of things,'' says Sachs,
who keeps a computer at his side in his richly paneled office on
Fifth Avenue. ``If you suddenly can't remember Masaccio's middle
name, you don't have to get up and go to the Frick reference
library.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) CHICAGO -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-ART-DICTIONARY-2, 5-12 --
For Jack Brown, the director of libraries at the Art Institute of
Chicago, buying the online version of the Grove Dictionary of Art
was an easy call. ``I bought it sight unseen,'' he says. ``It's
clearly the essential and definitive tool for art history at this
point, and I wanted to distribute access to it.'' (Todd
Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-ART-DICTIONARY-1, 5-12
-- The Grove Dictionary of Art, shown here at the Frick Collection
in Manhattan, is available online. The 34-volume print version,
26.3 million words written by 6,802 experts and published in 1996,
weighs 168 pounds and takes up five feet of shelf space. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- May 12, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 5-12 --
To make windows more energy-efficient without spending a lot of
money, you can apply a tinted film to the glass. These window films
can cut down the amount of ultraviolet rays that penetrate into the
house, and protect furniture, carpets and drapes from fading.
(Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- NY-VILLAGE-APARTMENT-2, 5-12
-- Diane Shea combined three undersize studios into a smoothly
functioning home for four. The dining room, with a rare Robert
Longo triptych, was previously apartment No. 2H. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- NY-VILLAGE-APARTMENT-1, 5-12
-- Diane Shea, in her building's communal garden, combined three
undersize studios into a smoothly functioning home for four in the
heart of Greenwich Village. Today, Ms. Shea, 45, estimates that her
apartment is worth roughly three times its $234,000 total cost.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- SENIOR-FURNISHING-2, 5-12 --
Saks Fifth Avenue windows featuring Anna Sui clothing and her
collection of vintage throws and pillows that inspired it. Home
furnishing design is having a senior moment. Knitted afghan throws,
crocheted pillows, chenille spreads and tufted pompom quilts are
appearing like silver hairs in youthful catalogues like Garnet
Hill, stores like Pottery Barn and Crate and Barrel and collections
like Ralph Lauren Home and Nautica. (Barbara Alper/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- SENIOR-FURNISHING-1, 5-12 --
A Pottery Barn quilt in a tufted pom-pom pattern. Home furnishing
design is having a senior moment. The less-is-more of modern design
may be making itself disappear, as consumers realize that the style
can be as unsympathetic to live with as it is stunning and spare.
(Pottery Barn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) JERUSALEM -- May 12, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS, 5-12 -- A
Russian World War II veteran wears his medals from the former
Soviet Union. Russian immigrants are now the king-makers of Israeli
politics. Recent polls show that this group, who can swing the
upcoming Israeli election either way, are moving away from
supporting Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. (Rina Castelnuovo/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- May 12, 1999 -- PRUNING-PLANTS, 5-12
-- William Miller tending to a mulberry tree. ``It's a matter of
finding the tree in the tree,'' says Miller, 41, an arborist who
started a tree business on Long Island 13 years ago and does what
amounts to behavioral analysis on each plant he prunes. ``When we
first look at a tree, we look for what to encourage, what to
discourage. We want to accentuate forms, allow them to stand out.
And we're also manipulating light.'' (Maxine Hicks/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) CEGRANE, Macedonia -- May 12, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-FLOATER-2, 5-12 -- Young ethnic Albanian refugees
play a wooden structure which was constructed for them to play on
at a refugee camp on Wednesday. More than 30,000 ethnic Albanian
refugees who fled the violence in Kosovo are living in tents at the
camp which is currently the largest in Macedonia. (Tyler Hicks/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) CEGRANE, Macedonia -- May 12, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-FLOATER-1, 5-12 -- German army soldiers throw candy
to young ethnic Albanian refugees at a refugee camp on Wednesday.
More than 30,000 ethnic Albanian refugees who fled the violence in
Kosovo are living in tents at the camp which is currently the
largest in Macedonia. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-SUMMERS-2, 5-12 --
Deputy Secretary of Treasury Lawrence Summers in 1997. Summers will
replace current Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin who announced his
resignation on Wednesday. (Carol Powers/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) PHOENIX -- May 12, 1999 -- NATIVE-AMERICAN-ART, 5-12 --
Five figures titled ``Intertribal Greeting'' by Doug Hyde outside
the Heard Museum. Resplendent after an $18 million expansion, the
70-year-old Heard, with its staff of Indian experts, is pointing
the way to a new nationwide spirit of collaboration between Indians
and the museums housing their patrimony. (Jack Topping/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- May 12, 1999 -- ART-AUCTION, 5-12 -- At left,
Henri Matisse's ``Nature morte devant la fenetre ouverte Nice,
Place Charles-Felix,'' and Vincent van Gogh's ``La Roubine du
Roi.'' Both paintings are part of Christie's 19th-century and
Impressionist auction sale this season. (Christie's/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- CLINTON-CRIME, 5-12 --
President Clinton walks with Attorney General Janet Reno towards a
Rose Garden ceremony on Wednesday honoring police officers. Making
good on a pledge to pay for 100,000 police officers, President
Clinton announced at the ceremony a new round of grants allowing
communities to hire cadets and urged Congress to support his
anti-crime package. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-RESIGNS-4, 5-12 --
President Clinton, flanked by aides including White House Chief of
Staff Erskine Bowles, left, talks with Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin, facing camera, in the Oval Office in April, 1998. On the
president's desk, at left, is a gift commemorating the North
American Free Trade Treaty which includes the U.S., Canada and
Mexico. Rubin, idolized on Wall Street for the policies many credit
with spurring the record U.S. economic boom, is stepping down, it
was announced on Wednesday. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-RESIGNS-3, 5-12 --
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin during a briefing at the White
House in October, 1998. Rubin, idolized on Wall Street for the
policies many credit with spurring the record U.S. economic boom,
is stepping down, it was announced on Wednesday. (Shana Raab/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-SUMMERS, 5-12 --
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Deputy Secretary Lawrence
Summers, right, during a briefing at the White House in October,
1998. Summers will replace current Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin,
idolized on Wall Street for the policies many credit with spurring
the record U.S. economic boom, is stepping down, it was announced
on Wednesday. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-RESIGNS-2, 5-12 --
From left, Britain's Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown,
German Finance Minister Theo Waigel, Minister of Economy and
Finance of France Dominique Strauss-Kahn, Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin, Italy's Minister of the Treasury Carlo Ciampi, Japan's
Minister of Finance Hikaru Matsunaga and Canada's Minister of
Finance Paul Martin gather for a group photo at Blair House in
Washington on April, 1998. Rubin, idolized on Wall Street for the
policies many credit with spurring the record U.S. economic boom,
is stepping down, it was announced on Wednesday. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-RESIGNS-1, 5-12 --
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin talks to an aide before a meeting
with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, left, at the Treasury
Department in April, 1998. Rubin, idolized on Wall Street for the
policies many credit with spurring the record U.S. economic boom,
is stepping down, it was announced on Wednesday. President Clinton
will nominate his deputy, Lawrence Summers, to succeed him.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-SANCTIONS-SPI,
05-11 -- A worker polishes a mosaic of a grimacing George Bush at
the entrance of the Al Rasheed Hotel in Baghdad. ``Even though one
could probably justify individually almost all of the sanctions
bills that have been passed, when you look at the impact of them
all combined, it's overwhelmingly negative on our economy, and it
does not seem to have any measurable foreign policy plus,'' says
Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-DOCTOR-2-SPI,
05-11 -- Delegation member Ramzy Baroud, a Palestinian writer from
Seattle, breaks down after seeing the tiny body of Nemya, a
2-year-old girl who died from meningitis just minutes earlier.
``The poor, the children, the innocent are paying the price of the
sanctions,'' Baroud says. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-DOCTOR-1-SPI, 05-11
-- Gerri Haynes, who organized the Washington Physicians for Social
Responsibility trip to Iraq, is confronted by Um-Hafiz Saleemah at
the Dijlah School, an all-girls school. Saleemah wanted to know how
Americans could sit comfortably in their homes and allow the
bombing of Iraq to continue. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-VIGNETTES-4-SPI,
05-11 -- A fly crawls on the face of malnourished Ahiam Fazel,
19-months old, at the Al Mansour Hospital in Baghdad. Each month
thousands of infants are dying of malnutrition-related illnesses
that many believe would not be a problem except for the sanctions
restricting or bogging down the shipment of food and medicine. (Dan
DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-VIGNETTES-3-SPI,
05-11 -- A worshipper kisses the huge wooden door as she enters the
Mosque of Al-Imam Ul- Kazem, or Golden Mosque, in Baghdad. (Dan
DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-VIGNETTES-2-SPI,
05-11 -- Sabehna Jasim, 70, lives in a three-bedroom apartment in
Baghdad with seven other family members. Her first-born son was
killed in the Persian Gulf War. Times are hard, she says. The U.N.
food rations always run out at least a week before the end of the
month and although there is work, it pays very little. (Dan
DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-VIGNETTES-1-SPI,
05-11 --Family and friends dance and sing in celebration of a newly
married Muslim couple as they arrive at the Palestine Hotel in
Baghdad. Thursday has become the day of choice for getting married
as most iraqis have Friday off. More than 50 couples spent their
first married night together at this hotel. (Dan DeLong/Seattle
Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-4-SPI, 05-11 --
Tattered pieces of corrugated cardboard are the book cover for a
student at Am Jad Al-Qadeseh, a primary school in impoverished the
area of Baghdad known as Saddam City. Many classrooms in Baghdad
are over very overcrowded and lack necessities such desks, text
books, paper and pencils. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-3-SPI, 05-11 --
Sitting on the floor of a classroom, second-graders listen to a
lesson at Am Jad Al-Qadeseh, a primary school in Saddam City, the
poorest section of Baghdad. Many classrooms in Baghdad are
overcrowded, with two or three students sharing one desk and others
forced to sit on the floor. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-2-SPI, 05-11 -- An
Iraqi girl waits in line with her mother at a United Nations food
distribution center in Saddam City, a poor area of Baghdad, Iraq.
This tiny center serves 392 people. ``Malnutrition in Iraq is not
just epidemic, it is endemic,'' says Hans von Sponeck, the United
Nations Humanitarian Coordinator for Iraq. (Dan DeLong/Seattle
Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-1-SPI, 05-11 --
Jazwan Sulamin, 4, is held by his weeping aunt, Seeta Mohammed, in
the Al Mansour Hospital in Baghdad. The boy has had a high fever
for more than a week and, although results were inconclusive, his
doctor believes he has typhoid. Incidents of typhoid were almost
nonexistent before the sanctions. (Dan DeLong/Seattle
Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
