<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOEWEN-BANKRUPTCY-NYT     05-12 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOEWEN-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOEWEN GROUP REPORTS 77 PERCENT DROP IN PROFITS FOR FIRST QUARTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., La., Canada)   By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Loewen Group Inc., North America's second-largest
funeral home and cemetery operator, reported a 77 percent drop in
first-quarter profit Wednesday and warned that without an
improvement its creditors may force the sale or reorganization of
the company under United States or Canadian bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing extreme difficulties with our highly leveraged
balance sheet and the resulting negative cash flow, which is
impeding our ability to improve the operations of our company,''
John Lacy, chairman of the Burnaby, British Columbia based company,
said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   Reading that sort of language, investment analysts said the
probability of bankruptcy had increased. ``They're letting the
Street know that they're contemplating a bankruptcy filing,'' said
Debbie Anne Downey, a bond analyst at Miller Tabak Hirsch &AMP; Co. in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have new management and they've made some changes,'' she
said. If the second-quarter performance improves, she said,
``there's a slim chance they can renegotiate with their
bondholders.''
</P>
<P>
   But the next two quarters are historically not very strong in
the funeral business, said Bill Burns, an analyst at Johnson Rice &AMP;
Co. in New Orleans, ``so their cash flow is probably not going to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   While some assets have been sold to begin paying off $2.3
billion in debt, Burns said, he thought it would be difficult for
the company to raise cash that way.
</P>
<P>
   A critical date for Loewen Group is Sept. 15, when $300 million
in notes must be refinanced. The way the business is going now,
Burns said, Loewen will likely seek bankruptcy protection before
then.
</P>
<P>
   Loewen operates more than 1,100 funeral homes and 400 cemeteries
and does almost 90 percent of its business in the United States.
Its breakup has been considered a possibility since last September
when the founder, Ray Loewen, was removed as president and chief
executive at the insistence of impatient bankers and institutional
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation increased when Lacy became chairman in January. He
is well known in Canada for patching up and selling companies, in
whole or in parts, having done that previously with Scotts
Hospitality, a restaurant chain, WIC Western International
Communications, a broadcaster, and Oshawa Group, a food retailer.
</P>
<P>
   For the first quarter of 1999, Loewen earned $7 million or 6
cents a share, down from $30 million or 38 cents a year earlier.
Revenue totaled $311 million, unchanged. Last year the company lost
$599 million.
</P>
<P>
   Loewen first warned of the possibility it would seek bankruptcy
in documents filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission in
Washington last month, saying ``there is no guarantee that it can
continue to operate as a going concern for the foreseeable
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in Loewen is remarkable for a company that was
routinely described by investment analysts just a few years ago as
having nowhere to go but up. Demographics and an aging population
were on its side. Like its rival, the No. 1 Service Corp.
International of Houston, Loewen was expanding quickly by buying up
small family owned funeral homes. Its stock, which once traded at
more than $40 a share, is now worth $1 because of a series of
missteps. In 1995, a small Mississippi funeral parlor operator won
a breach of contract lawsuit against Loewen and a jury awarded the
plaintiff $500 million. Although the figure was cut to $175 million
in a settlement, Loewen's stock tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Service Corp. offered $3.1 billion to buy Loewen at a
handsome premium. But Loewen rejected the offer and plunged the
company into debt.
</P>
<P>
   Last November the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce seized 10
million of Loewen's shares as collateral for a $145 million loan.
The bank is now the largest single shareholder, with 13.6 percent
stake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
