camp which is currently the largest in Macedonia. (Tyler Hicks/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) CEGRANE, Macedonia -- May 12, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-FLOATER-1, 5-12 -- German army soldiers throw candy
to young ethnic Albanian refugees at a refugee camp on Wednesday.
More than 30,000 ethnic Albanian refugees who fled the violence in
Kosovo are living in tents at the camp which is currently the
largest in Macedonia. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-SUMMERS-2, 5-12 --
Deputy Secretary of Treasury Lawrence Summers in 1997. Summers will
replace current Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin who announced his
resignation on Wednesday. (Carol Powers/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) PHOENIX -- May 12, 1999 -- NATIVE-AMERICAN-ART, 5-12 --
Five figures titled ``Intertribal Greeting'' by Doug Hyde outside
the Heard Museum. Resplendent after an $18 million expansion, the
70-year-old Heard, with its staff of Indian experts, is pointing
the way to a new nationwide spirit of collaboration between Indians
and the museums housing their patrimony. (Jack Topping/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- May 12, 1999 -- ART-AUCTION, 5-12 -- At left,
Henri Matisse's ``Nature morte devant la fenetre ouverte Nice,
Place Charles-Felix,'' and Vincent van Gogh's ``La Roubine du
Roi.'' Both paintings are part of Christie's 19th-century and
Impressionist auction sale this season. (Christie's/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- CLINTON-CRIME, 5-12 --
President Clinton walks with Attorney General Janet Reno towards a
Rose Garden ceremony on Wednesday honoring police officers. Making
good on a pledge to pay for 100,000 police officers, President
Clinton announced at the ceremony a new round of grants allowing
communities to hire cadets and urged Congress to support his
anti-crime package. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-RESIGNS-4, 5-12 --
President Clinton, flanked by aides including White House Chief of
Staff Erskine Bowles, left, talks with Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin, facing camera, in the Oval Office in April, 1998. On the
president's desk, at left, is a gift commemorating the North
American Free Trade Treaty which includes the U.S., Canada and
Mexico. Rubin, idolized on Wall Street for the policies many credit
with spurring the record U.S. economic boom, is stepping down, it
was announced on Wednesday. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-RESIGNS-3, 5-12 --
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin during a briefing at the White
House in October, 1998. Rubin, idolized on Wall Street for the
policies many credit with spurring the record U.S. economic boom,
is stepping down, it was announced on Wednesday. (Shana Raab/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-SUMMERS, 5-12 --
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Deputy Secretary Lawrence
Summers, right, during a briefing at the White House in October,
1998. Summers will replace current Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin,
idolized on Wall Street for the policies many credit with spurring
the record U.S. economic boom, is stepping down, it was announced
on Wednesday. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-RESIGNS-2, 5-12 --
From left, Britain's Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown,
German Finance Minister Theo Waigel, Minister of Economy and
Finance of France Dominique Strauss-Kahn, Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin, Italy's Minister of the Treasury Carlo Ciampi, Japan's
Minister of Finance Hikaru Matsunaga and Canada's Minister of
Finance Paul Martin gather for a group photo at Blair House in
Washington on April, 1998. Rubin, idolized on Wall Street for the
policies many credit with spurring the record U.S. economic boom,
is stepping down, it was announced on Wednesday. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-RESIGNS-1, 5-12 --
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin talks to an aide before a meeting
with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, left, at the Treasury
Department in April, 1998. Rubin, idolized on Wall Street for the
policies many credit with spurring the record U.S. economic boom,
is stepping down, it was announced on Wednesday. President Clinton
will nominate his deputy, Lawrence Summers, to succeed him.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-SANCTIONS-SPI,
05-11 -- A worker polishes a mosaic of a grimacing George Bush at
the entrance of the Al Rasheed Hotel in Baghdad. ``Even though one
could probably justify individually almost all of the sanctions
bills that have been passed, when you look at the impact of them
all combined, it's overwhelmingly negative on our economy, and it
does not seem to have any measurable foreign policy plus,'' says
Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-DOCTOR-2-SPI,
05-11 -- Delegation member Ramzy Baroud, a Palestinian writer from
Seattle, breaks down after seeing the tiny body of Nemya, a
2-year-old girl who died from meningitis just minutes earlier.
``The poor, the children, the innocent are paying the price of the
sanctions,'' Baroud says. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-DOCTOR-1-SPI, 05-11
-- Gerri Haynes, who organized the Washington Physicians for Social
Responsibility trip to Iraq, is confronted by Um-Hafiz Saleemah at
the Dijlah School, an all-girls school. Saleemah wanted to know how
Americans could sit comfortably in their homes and allow the
bombing of Iraq to continue. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-VIGNETTES-4-SPI,
05-11 -- A fly crawls on the face of malnourished Ahiam Fazel,
19-months old, at the Al Mansour Hospital in Baghdad. Each month
thousands of infants are dying of malnutrition-related illnesses
that many believe would not be a problem except for the sanctions
restricting or bogging down the shipment of food and medicine. (Dan
DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-VIGNETTES-3-SPI,
05-11 -- A worshipper kisses the huge wooden door as she enters the
Mosque of Al-Imam Ul- Kazem, or Golden Mosque, in Baghdad. (Dan
DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-VIGNETTES-2-SPI,
05-11 -- Sabehna Jasim, 70, lives in a three-bedroom apartment in
Baghdad with seven other family members. Her first-born son was
killed in the Persian Gulf War. Times are hard, she says. The U.N.
food rations always run out at least a week before the end of the
month and although there is work, it pays very little. (Dan
DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-VIGNETTES-1-SPI,
05-11 --Family and friends dance and sing in celebration of a newly
married Muslim couple as they arrive at the Palestine Hotel in
Baghdad. Thursday has become the day of choice for getting married
as most iraqis have Friday off. More than 50 couples spent their
first married night together at this hotel. (Dan DeLong/Seattle
Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-4-SPI, 05-11 --
Tattered pieces of corrugated cardboard are the book cover for a
student at Am Jad Al-Qadeseh, a primary school in impoverished the
area of Baghdad known as Saddam City. Many classrooms in Baghdad
are over very overcrowded and lack necessities such desks, text
books, paper and pencils. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-3-SPI, 05-11 --
Sitting on the floor of a classroom, second-graders listen to a
lesson at Am Jad Al-Qadeseh, a primary school in Saddam City, the
poorest section of Baghdad. Many classrooms in Baghdad are
overcrowded, with two or three students sharing one desk and others
forced to sit on the floor. (Dan DeLong/Seattle Post-Intelligencer
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-2-SPI, 05-11 -- An
Iraqi girl waits in line with her mother at a United Nations food
distribution center in Saddam City, a poor area of Baghdad, Iraq.
This tiny center serves 392 people. ``Malnutrition in Iraq is not
just epidemic, it is endemic,'' says Hans von Sponeck, the United
Nations Humanitarian Coordinator for Iraq. (Dan DeLong/Seattle
Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BAGHDAD, Iraq -- May 12, 1999 -- IRAQ-1-SPI, 05-11 --
Jazwan Sulamin, 4, is held by his weeping aunt, Seeta Mohammed, in
the Al Mansour Hospital in Baghdad. The boy has had a high fever
for more than a week and, although results were inconclusive, his
doctor believes he has typhoid. Incidents of typhoid were almost
nonexistent before the sanctions. (Dan DeLong/Seattle
Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
