<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/12/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT61) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- NY-GARDEN-SALE, 5-12 --
Olean For, 78, presses her hands together in gratitude when she
hears that her community garden on East Third Street will be
preserved. The $1.2 million purchase of 51 lots by the New York
Restoration Project - arranged by the singer and actress Bette
Midler - provided a vital piece in the city's negotiations with
environmental groups. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT60) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
WOZZECK-OPERA, 5-12 -- John Tomlinson and Philip Langridge in
Schoenberg's opera ``Moses und Aron,'' at the Met. The production
illustrates with sets and costumes a conversation going on within
the composer's head. The people on stage, not least the elaborate
and powerful chorus, are a public outlet for private thinking.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT59) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
PARSONS-DANCE, 5-12 -- David Parsons, left, Robert Battle and the
Parsons Dance Company during a rehearsal of Battle's ``Rush Hour,''
which is to have its premiere at the Joyce Theater. ``Lately, every
time I start a new project, I get unnerved,'' says Parsons. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT58) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
PERFORMING-SPACE-THEATER, 5-12 -- Mark Russell, the executive
director of P.S. 122, in his words, ``the Carnegie Hall of
performance art,'' in the larger of his East Village theater's two
spaces. ``I feel like I have a new job this year,'' says Russell,
who is trying to keep P.S. 122 cutting-edge by presenting emerging
talent while also providing space to the established artists who
came of age with some of the audience. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT57) SAO PAOLO, Brazil -- May 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
16 -- TOM-ZE-BRAZIL-MUSIC, 5-12 -- Tom Ze, who begins a United
States tour this week, at home in Sao Paolo. Even in Brazil, where
leading songwriters routinely cite concepts from anthropology and
pay homage to avant-garde poets, Ze, 62, comes across as a man
who's passionate about ideas. ``To be a composer is to have
courage,'' he says. (Jon Pareles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT56) PHILADELPHIA -- May 12, 1999 -- PHILLY-MAYORAL-2, 5-12
-- One of front-runner John F. Street's rivals in the Democratic
primary for mayor of Philadelphia is Marty Weinberg, a white
candidate in a city that often votes along racial lines. Weinberg,
a wealthy lawyer, was once an adviser to Frank L. Rizzo when he was
mayor from 1972 to 1980. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT55) PHILADELPHIA -- May 12, 1999 -- PHILLY-MAYORAL-1, 5-12
-- John F. Street, the front-runner in the Democratic primary for
mayor of Philadelphia, is startled when he receives a campaign
check for $100,000 at a rally on Tuesday. In a rough-and-tumble
campaign to succeed Mayor Edward G. Rendell, a popular Democrat who
is barred by the city charter from serving a third consecutive
term, Street, 55, appears to have the edge. (Laura Pedrick/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT54) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- May 12, 1999 -- CALIF-FUR-2,
5-12 -- Beverly Hills voters have overwhelmingly rejected a
proposal Wednesday (the wording for which is shown) to require that
fur coats sold here carry a tag describing the grisly ways that
animals used to make them may have been killed. In rejecting
Proposition A, the Consumer's Right to Informed Choices Act of
1999, Beverly Hills voters deflected a direct attack on a symbol of
the city's image of glamour and wealth. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT53) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- May 12, 1999 -- CALIF-FUR-1,
5-12 -- David Meyer, left, and Luke Montgomery led the drive to
require that furs sold in Beverly Hills carry a tag describing the
grisly ways that animals used to make the coats may have been
killed. The measure was overwhelmingly rejected Wednesday. ``We set
out to educate a few consumers here in Beverly Hills about how fur
animals are killed by clubbing and electrocution, but we succeeded
in educating millions of people around the world,'' says
Montgomery, 25. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT52) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CONGRESS, 5-12 --
The chief negotiators on the military spending bill, Sen. Ted
Stevens, left, and Rep. C.W. (Bill) Young, R-Fla., want $11 billion
for the armed forces. Ignoring their leaders' wishes to hold own
the spending, Congressional negotiators on Thursday tentatively
agreed on a $11.6 billion emergency bill to finance the fighting in
Yugoslavia and pay for a myriad of Pentagon programs. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT51) AVIANO, Italy -- May 12, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NATO, 5-12 --
Lt. Gen. Michael Short, NATO's top air war commander, during an
interview on Wednesday. Despite the success allied warplanes are
having against Serbian forces in Kosovo, the alliance needs to
renew its attacks against the Yugoslav leadership in central
Belgrade to force Slobodan Milosevic to give in to NATO's demands
Short said during the interview. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT50) RISHON LEZION, Israel -- May 12, 1999 --
ISRAEL-POLITICS-2, 5-12 -- Candidates for Prime Minister in Israel
are courting Russian immigrant voters. In Rishon Lezion, Russian
and Hebrew posters back the incumbent, Benjamin Netanyahu. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT49) SAWYERVILLE, Ala. -- May 12, 1999 -- SATELLITE-JACKPOT,
5-12 -- Barbara Carlisle, left, and her parents Velma and George
Merriweather stand next to their satellite dish on Tuesday. George
Merriweather said he was mad when he realized he had been cheated
on installment payments for a television satellite dish they
purchased in 1995. A Hale County jury sympathized and last week
awarded $581 million to the 80-year-old retired foundry worker, his
wife and their daughter, Barbara Carlisle. (Porfirio
Solorzano/Tuscaloosa News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT48) ATLANTA -- May 12, 1999 -- COX-TCA-CABLE, 5-12 -- James
Robbins, Cox Communications' president and chief executive, in the
company's Atlanta offices. In the latest consolidation deal by a
cable company preparing to offer telephone, Internet and
interactive services as well as ordinary television to its
subscribers, Cox on Wednesday announced it was acquiring TCA Cable
TV Inc., for $3.264 billion in stock and cash. (Phil
Skinner/Atlanta Journal Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT47) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-SUMMERS-3, 5-12 --
From left, Stuart Eizenstat, an undersecretary at the State
Department, Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, Treasury
Secretary Robert E. Rubin and President Clinton at a Rose Garden
ceremony Wednesday during which Summers is announced as the new
treasury secretary. As he entered the home stretch of his training
for the most vital job in managing the world economy, he has
become, one close associate said recently, ``more Rubin-esqe.''
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT46) LIPLJAN, Yugoslavia -- May 12, 1999 -- KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
5-12 -- Milenko Djokic points to a hole in a house caused by debris
from a missile, presumably fired by NATO forces. The village is
near an airport which was apparently the target of the weapon.
(Steve Erlanger/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT45) DENVER -- May 12, 1999 -- DENVER-GALLERY-2, 5-12 --
Frederick and Jan Mayer in the foyer of a home they built on a
former parking lot in Denver. Last year the Mayers were included in
a listing of the world's 200 top collectors in Art News magazine.
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT44) DENVER -- May 12, 1999 -- DENVER-GALLERY-1, 5-12 -- The
home built by Frederick and Jan Mayer on a former parking lot in
Denver. It is the first private single-family residence to rise in
this old industrial district in a century. (Kevin Moloney/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT43) HOLLYWOOD -- May 12, 1999 -- TV-MUSICALS, 5-12 -- Neil
Meron, left, and Craig Zadan, producers of the TV musical ``Double
Platinum,'' in Zadan's living room in the hills above Sunset Strip
in Hollywood. ``Doing a musical for television is doing something
very fragile,'' says Zadan. ``The first criteria is that it has to
be dramatic, it has to be emotional. The second is that it has to
have very, very strong characters. And the third is that you have
to have event casting: you have to have stars.'' (Marissa Roth/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) PHOENIX -- May 12, 1999 -- NATIVE-AMERICAN-ART-2, 5-12
-- A katsina doll made by Hopis from cottonwood tree roots at the
Heard Museum in Phoenix. Resplendent after an $18 million
expansion, the 70-year-old Heard, with its staff of Indian experts,
is pointing the way to a new nationwide spirit of collaboration
between Indians and the museums housing their patrimony and
sometimes the remains of their ancestors. (Jeff Topping/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) LEDYARD, Conn. -- May 12, 1999 --
CIR-SWEEPSTAKES-ONLINE-2, 5-12 -- Wendy Limauge enters so many
sweepstakes that she has a bar chart of her winnings. Online
contests have allowed her to cut her postage bill sharply. ``People
think I'm super lucky or I'm crazy,'' says Ms. Limauge, 38, of
Ledyard, a full-time computer instructor and mother of three who
owns a company called The Computer Lady. ``I get to win things I
would never, never buy, or couldn't afford to buy.'' (George
Ruhe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) PIKESVILLE, Md. -- May 12, 1999 --
CIR-SWEEPSTAKES-ONLINE-1, 5-12 -- Norman Posner, a sweepstakes
enthusiast, won his first contest in 1969, a trip to Miami Beach
for his wedding, with Bob Hope as his best man. Posner has won
cars, cruises, trips to Europe, television sets and T-shirts
galore. He says he's lucky, yet he still adds that he believes that
gimmicks help. (Ann Grillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) SOMERS, N.Y. -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-IBM-FUTURE-2, 5-12
-- Russell A. Budd, an IBM engineer, helped develop a ``wearable
PC.'' Also referred to internally as the visionpad, the device is a
fully functioning PC, with a headpiece that contains a virtual
display as well as a speaker and a microphone. (Joyce Dopkeen/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) SOMERS, N.Y. -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-IBM-FUTURE-1, 5-12
-- The cyberphone combines a phone with access to the Web. Though
it looks much like an ordinary cellular phone, a tiny
high-resolution image of a Web page can be bounced off a mirror,
found inside the phone's flip cover, to generate a virtual screen
image in front of the user. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) WASHINGTON -- May 12, 1999 -- RUBIN-EIZENSTAT, 5-12 --
Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, foreground, and Stuart
