<P>
   (NYT34) PITTSBURGH -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-ROBOTS-2, 5-12 -- Cye,
which Probotics sells for $695, can be trained to wheel around on
its own. It can also be programmed to ``learn'' the floor plan of a
house and, with an accompanying wagon, it can tow up to 10 pounds.
(Gary Tramontina/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-ROBOTS-1, 5-12 -- Aibo,
a $2,500 robotic dog from Sony, can wag its tail, chase a pink
plastic ball and get around at about six yards a minute. Aibo
(pronounced eye-BO) is Sony's answer to the 20th-century quest for
a relatively intelligent robot that gets around on its own. (Philip
Greenberg/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-ART-DICTIONARY-3, 5-12
-- Samuel Sachs II, the technophilic director of the Frick
Collection, is enthusiastic about the online version of the Grove
Dictionary of Art. ``It's handy for a lot of things,'' says Sachs,
who keeps a computer at his side in his richly paneled office on
Fifth Avenue. ``If you suddenly can't remember Masaccio's middle
name, you don't have to get up and go to the Frick reference
library.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) CHICAGO -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-ART-DICTIONARY-2, 5-12 --
For Jack Brown, the director of libraries at the Art Institute of
Chicago, buying the online version of the Grove Dictionary of Art
was an easy call. ``I bought it sight unseen,'' he says. ``It's
clearly the essential and definitive tool for art history at this
point, and I wanted to distribute access to it.'' (Todd
Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- CIR-ART-DICTIONARY-1, 5-12
-- The Grove Dictionary of Art, shown here at the Frick Collection
in Manhattan, is available online. The 34-volume print version,
26.3 million words written by 6,802 experts and published in 1996,
weighs 168 pounds and takes up five feet of shelf space. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- May 12, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 5-12 --
To make windows more energy-efficient without spending a lot of
money, you can apply a tinted film to the glass. These window films
can cut down the amount of ultraviolet rays that penetrate into the
house, and protect furniture, carpets and drapes from fading.
(Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- NY-VILLAGE-APARTMENT-2, 5-12
-- Diane Shea combined three undersize studios into a smoothly
functioning home for four. The dining room, with a rare Robert
Longo triptych, was previously apartment No. 2H. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- NY-VILLAGE-APARTMENT-1, 5-12
-- Diane Shea, in her building's communal garden, combined three
undersize studios into a smoothly functioning home for four in the
heart of Greenwich Village. Today, Ms. Shea, 45, estimates that her
apartment is worth roughly three times its $234,000 total cost.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- May 12, 1999 -- SENIOR-FURNISHING-2, 5-12 --
Saks Fifth Avenue windows featuring Anna Sui clothing and her
collection of vintage throws and pillows that inspired it. Home
furnishing design is having a senior moment. Knitted afghan throws,
crocheted pillows, chenille spreads and tufted pompom quilts are
appearing like silver hairs in youthful catalogues like Garnet
Hill, stores like Pottery Barn and Crate and Barrel and collections
like Ralph Lauren Home and Nautica. (Barbara Alper/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
