<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4907 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-12 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE Lakers'starters outscored the Rockets' starters 81-36 Tuesday
night. That's ugly.
</P>
<P>
   But take away Charles Barkley's nice if inconsequential second
half, and the best the Rockets' starters would have done against
even the cross-town Astros on Tuesday night would have been a tie _
19-19.
</P>
<P>
   And that's hideous.
</P>
<P>
   That's why what might be in order now as the Rockets look
themselves in the mirror and face elimination is a complete
makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Change it all. Change it head to toe. Change the makeup of this
team. Take off a little here, redo this. Add that. And don't forget
the implants _ heart implants, that is.
</P>
<P>
   That's what you have to do when things get this hideous. That's
how desperate you have to be when you get this sick and embarrassed
over what you've paraded in front of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like we were ready to play,'' Rockets forward Scottie
Pippen said. ``I don't know why, but we weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets need a change, and they need it fast _ one of those
Oprah or Jenny Jones kinds of makeovers, where some tepid and
homely person ducks backstage at the beginning of the show and
moments later emerges looking gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   But where to begin?
</P>
<P>
   Game 1's ugliness in this Lakers series was limited mostly to
the final few moments.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 was like looking at some nasty morphed image of Don
King's hair, Elvis Costello's glasses, Karl Malden's nose, John
Elway's teeth and Dom DeLuise's chins.
</P>
<P>
   The individual parts were ugly, sure. But looking at it
collectively, you practically had to shade your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to change, and don't think Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich isn't considering it.
</P>
<P>
   Through 50 mostly mediocre regular-season games, Tomjanovich was
subtle and discriminating with how he handled the new-look Rockets.
He defended Pippen's troublesome adjustment to life as a Rocket,
even changing things regularly to better accommodate the former
Bulls star.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich brought the entire team along slowly and patiently,
considering the lack of a training camp and so many new faces. But
these are drastic times, and that means drastic measures.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing the rookies, Michael Dickerson and Cuttino Mobley,
with Brent Price and Sam Mack in the starting lineup might be the
most obvious move.
</P>
<P>
   The kids have a future, all right. But they've struggled
mightily in this series, while Price and Mack have showed veterans'
guile. They combined for 38 points and six assists Tuesday night,
most of the work coming in the second and third quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're here for,'' Mack said. ``We're the veterans.
We've been in these situations before.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tomjanovich of the possible change: ``We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   At the least, Mack and Price should find themselves on the floor
much earlier in today's Game 3 and likely hang around much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in this ugly mess, perhaps the Rockets finally have
realized something otherwise unfathomable. Hakeem Olajuwon needs
help.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon, speaking candidly and showing all the class that has
made him an NBA warrior, admitted as much in the quiet Rockets
locker room Tuesday night. He's overmatched by Lakers monster
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has been our strength strength inside,'' Olajuwon said.
``But he is too big. Against San Antonio or Minnesota, we play this
game and we beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   But against O'Neal, Olajuwon has been pushed deep into the lane
on several occasions, often to the point that his head is directly
under the basket and he's forced to foul like just another Stanley
Roberts. Tuesday night, O'Neal touched the ball on the low post on
13 of the Lakers' first 17 possessions. They scored on nine of
those possessions, including two off of Olajuwon fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad matchup for us,'' Olajuwon said. ``He creates so
many possibilities with his size advantage. We have to change how
we defend him.''
</P>
<P>
   And of course, most of all, the Rockets have to get the ball out
of Pippen's hands when they're bringing it upcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen has long demanded that the offense run through him. But
let's look at how this Rockets offense has performed against the
Lakers. While Pippen has gone 5-for-20 from the field, the offense
has stagnated to near playoff death.
</P>
<P>
   It is too late to be patient. It's too late to coddle Scottie,
be patient with the rookies and hope Olajuwon can match O'Neal
bucket for bucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to win or go home,'' Olajuwon said. ``We have run
out of excuses. We just have to get better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
