<HEADER>
A4908 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTUS-HARASS-BOS &LR;      05-12 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-HARASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-LOTUS MANAGER ALLEGES SEXUAL BIAS   BY EXECUTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A former manager at Lotus Development Corp. alleges in
a complaint that she and other women were discriminated against by
the company's president, Jeffrey Papows, and his executive
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint by the former executive, Arlene Greene, is among
three ongoing sexual-bias cases against the software company
pending before the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus denies the charges, although it acknowledges that it
disciplined a manager in response to one of the cases. The filings
provide details about the company's response to the sexual
harassment complaints and, in Greene's case, raise questions about
Papows' conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Greene alleges that before he became chief
executive, Papows bragged about missing the company's mandatory
diversity training programs. He also allegedly maintained a ``long
term intimate relationship'' with his secretary and top aide,
Sharon Ricci, the complaint states.
</P>
<P>
   Empowered by that relationship, Ricci ``repeatedly targets
female employees such that they either leave `voluntarily' as a
result of the harassment'' or are discharged, according to Greene's
complaint, which was filed on April 16.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint alleges that Ricci exerted influence within the
Cambridge company ``to a degree far in excess of her qualifications
and job responsibility'' and that ``Mr. Papows apparently defers to
Ms. Ricci.''
</P>
<P>
   The MCAD has not ruled on any of the three complaints and Lotus
has yet to file its response to the agency. Company spokesman Bryan
Simmons said that Green's case ``has no merit'' and said that
neither Papows, Ricci or a third executive cited in Greene's
complaint would respond to questions.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that many top Lotus officers are women, including its
chief finanicial officer and its general counsel, Simmons said,
``The message here is it doesn't seem that Jeff Papows has trouble
working with women.'' He said the number of sexual-bias cases
pending against the company with the MCAD is not unsual considering
that Lotus has 4,000 employees in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In their filings, Greene and two other women allege they were
removed from their jobs after they complained about their
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's complaint was first reported Wednesday by The Wall
Street Journal. Greene has previously declined to comment about her
allegations. She could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints are likely to increase scrutiny of Papows, who
has made no specific responses to an earlier Journal article
suggesting he may have fabricated details of his military service
record and educational background.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, now 52, joined Lotus in 1987 as a senior database
development manager. She says in her filing she was wrongfully
terminated last October, supposedly as part of a layoff.
</P>
<P>
   But instead her job was assigned to a younger woman who was less
qualified. Green also claims that she was subjected to
discriminatory treatment ``including being shunned'' by her direct
supervisor, Joseph McLaughlin, who was also named in her complaint.
His actions, Greene claims, were in keeping with the company's
practice of ``targeting female employees'' during a round of
layoffs last August and October.
</P>
<P>
   Greene says further that in February she made her concerns known
to Lotus' parent organization, IBM Corp., where its senior vice
president of human resources, William Matson, told her in March
that it would take no remedial action.
</P>
<P>
   Matson did not return a telephone message and an IBM spokesman
declined to comment, citing the pending complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Another case involving a former employee is that of B.L. Supeno,
who worked for the company about a year until her temporary
position was eliminated at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   According to her complaint, Supeno charges the mid-level manager
who supervised most of her work in the Organizer Group subjected
her to ``a series and pattern of sexual harassment.'' The manager,
Peter Forkes, routinely used sexually offensive language and wasn't
disciplined by other managers even after she complained, Supeno's
filing states.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response, Lotus concedes that in 1997 Forkes joked
about ``the best place to put a tattoo on a woman's body,'' and
posted a sign on his office door, partly in Greek, reading that
``The Spermologist is in.'' In addition, Lotus says, Forkes sent
around around a sexually-explicit e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus says Forkes was reprimanded that year for the actions and
told that he would be disciplined if there were another similar
occurence. Forkes, who still works at Lotus, declined to comment
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to its filing, Lotus says further that Supeno also
sent ``crude and sexual e-mails'' herself, which ``strongly
undercuts her claim that she found this (Forkes') behavior to be
unwelcome sexual harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   The third sexual-discrimination case involves a woman, Darlene
Hulteen, who says she was terminated in April because of a
complaint she filed with the MCAD at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Hulteen, formerly a programmer-analyst at the company's
Information Systems Web Solutions Group, charges she wasn't given
challenging work assignments because of her gender and age, 48,
while two younger men hired at the same time were given more
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   In a second complaint to the MCAD, Hulteen wrote she was
terminated ``in retaliation for filing a complaint so they could
get another individual for my position.''
</P>
<P>
   Her experience suggests the company's efforts at diversity
training aren't effective, Hulteen says. ``They preach something
only in order to say it in a legal sense,'' she said. ``There's
definitely a discrepancy between the image and the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Lotus declined to discuss the specifics of Hulteen's complaint.
Simmons, the spokesman, would say that ``We've always recognized
that maintianing a healthy, diverse workplace is hard work and it's
a job that's never done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that our work toward that goal has been more visible
than other companies but we've never taken the posture that we are
superior to other companies in our efforts or our results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
