</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-U.S.NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE RAGE AT U.S. IS SIGN OF DEEPER ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Most ordinary people in China have a double-barreled
view of the United States, filtered by sharply competing emotions:
admiration and suspicion, hope and fear, love and hate.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful surge of anti-American sentiment was unleashed after
last week's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, sending
rocks, bottles and slogans at the U.S. Embassy here. The protests
grew to become the largest anti-foreign demonstrations since the
Cultural Revolution in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Led by students, fanned by a government eager to take advantage
of nationalist emotion, the demonstrations reflected a society-wide
resentment toward the United States that feeds on China's mixture
of wounded pride, desire for influence commensurate with its size
and shame at its nagging poverty and intractable politics.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20 years since China began its reform program, many
Chinese people have openly cited American democracy, wealth and
technology as models they want to follow. Yet during those same
years, and long beforehand, the same people have harbored grave
suspicions about the United States, often seeing anti-China
conspiracies and often taking deep offense at what they regard as
signs of disrespect.
</P>
<P>
   Students, businessmen and government employees agree that the
surge of anti-Americanism is more than just an emotional reaction
to the killing of three Chinese citizens in the bombing. Instead,
it represents an attempt to rally national pride, set off by a
widespread belief that the embassy bombing was an intentional
effort by the United States to cow China into submission for not
supporting NATO's campaign in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a very old and traditional nation,'' said Wang Yizheng,
a 44-year-old government employee. ``If you do not show us respect,
we will hate you.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, Wang seems to have a drastically divided position
toward the United States. He is proud that his 18-year-old daughter
led her classmates in a demonstration outside the U.S. Embassy, and
yet he seemed equally proud that she plans to apply to study in the
United States next year.
</P>
<P>
   Is that not hypocritical?
</P>
<P>
   Wang was not fazed by the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will tell you they are demonstrating to send a message
to America,'' he said. ``In reality, they are demonstrating to feel
good, to respect themselves. Going to America to study, I don't see
any contradiction.''
</P>
<P>
   China's state-run news media, rarely so in tune with popular
opinion on a strident political issue, has encouraged general
outrage at the United States, rather than urging calm. The most
sensitive and effective heartstring the news media seem able to
pull is the issue of national pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese people cannot be bullied,'' People's Daily wrote in an
editorial that was published Wednesday. ``China is a sovereign
country and its dignity is not easily infringed upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most pungent symbol of China's wildly fluctuating
views of the United States is President Clinton, who was lionized
before and after his visit here last year. Clinton was admired in
part for his support of an engagement policy toward China against
stiff opposition from Congress, but also, many Chinese say, for his
good looks. In several popular books that appeared last year,
Clinton was roundly praised by Chinese historians as one of the
greatest American presidents ever.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Clinton is being likened to Hitler, denounced by
protesters as a fascist and an imperialist. This turnaround appears
to have less to do with Clinton personally than it does with his
role as the commander in chief in a military action that ordinary
Chinese generally see as unjustified and misguided.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the seeds for this week's explosion of public outrage
were sown in recent weeks by NATO's bombing campaign. Unable to see
what direct benefit the United States can gain from opposing
Serbian aggression in Kosovo, many Chinese seem convinced that the
United States has broader military aims.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is acting like an arrogant bully,'' said Mou Jianmin,
a former reporter for the New China News Agency who now runs a
computer company. ``I've been talking with many friends about it,
and we are asking: What is America's real aim? Is it really to
protect Kosovars? Or is it to strengthen NATO? Or is it really a
way to get at Russia?''
</P>
<P>
   Though China's news media have offered carefully filtered
accounts of the war, reporting that the sufferings of the Kosovo
Albanians had largely been caused by NATO bombing, Mou insisted
that China's limited news media were not a major factor in shaping
the resentment and anger many people now feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some Westerners think we are only acting this way
because we have limited information, but that's ridiculous,'' Mou
said. ``We feel very strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the surprising aspects of the demonstrations was the way
some students chanted ``Long Live Chairman Mao!'' during the
demonstrations. The authorities have a deeply ambivalent attitude
toward Mao, fully repudiating his fanatical politics while praising
his dominant role in modern Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to students trying to rally national pride, Mao represents
the Communist Party leader with the most courage and flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mao was the only Chinese leader who really dared to stand up
to anyone,'' said Han Weiping, an economics student from People's
University. ``He was afraid of no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant to directly criticize today's leadership, Han chose
instead to praise Mao.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just saying that Mao was great,'' he said. ``He was very
anti-American.''
</P>
<P>
   Although few Americans in Beijing have been the victims of
violence, many who have witnessed demonstrations were challenged or
threatened by boisterous crowds. Many gave false nationalities when
asked where they were from or to taxi drivers who refused to take
American passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes so little to scratch the surface and bring out
xenophobia in this country,'' said a Chinese businesswoman who has
lived in the United States. ``I feel it, too. It's my first
impulse, before I stop and think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As with any highly emotional political issue, it is entirely
unpredictable where the current surge in anti-Americanism will
lead. Yet this businesswoman said she fears that the sentiment is
so deeply felt and so widely spread that it will have an
immeasurable effect on the role of foreign businesses in China.
</P>
<P>
   Lu Xun, perhaps China's best-known essayist of the 20th century,
once wrote that in a country that was isolated for centuries, that
suffered at the hands of foreign aggressors, and that carried a
deep sense of its own lost greatness and of envy for modern powers,
it may be unavoidable that many ordinary Chinese people have
trouble seeing foreigners evenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look up to foreigners as gods, or down at them as animals,
but never equally, as people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
