<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-NEESON13-COX     05-12 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-NEESON13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Liam Neeson, larger than life
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Given his recent statements that he was retiring from
film because it had become a directors' medium that treated actors
like puppets, one could easily assume that Liam Neeson was
referring to ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace,'' in
which the Irish stage actor and Academy Award nominee plays Jedi
Knight Qui-Gon Jinn opposite a host of computer-generated
creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Neeson might have been referring to ``The
Haunting,'' an effects-driven summer horror movie from ``Speed''
director Jan De Bont, in which he plays a psychic researcher who
invites a team of people to investigate a New England mansion
possessed by supernatural powers. Both films are a far cry from the
historical and human drama of ``Les Miserables,'' ``Michael
Collins,'' ``Rob Roy'' and ``Schindler's List,'' which earned him
an Oscar nomination for best actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be a sheep herder in Tibet, that's the real
reason,'' Neeson joked during an interview Sunday at the Regency
Hotel. He was kidding, too, when he told several publications that
he was going to retire from making movies. ``It was something said
in jest and anger that snowballed,'' Neeson said. ``It's a long,
boring story, but it's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``The Phantom Menace,'' opening Wednesday, and
``The Haunting,'' due July 23, the tall, ruggedly handsome actor
will be seen this summer in ``Gun Shy,'' in which he plays a drug
enforcement agent who has lost his nerve. He is preparing to
co-star with his wife of five years, Natasha Richardson, in an
adaptation of Patrick McGrath's novel, ``Asylum.'' Then he plans to
take a hiatus from film to concentrate on the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business, it's feast or famine, so sometimes I find
myself doing a series of films back-to-back,'' Neeson explained.
``And it comes a point, you think, I really need the injection of a
live audience to do something where you start at 8 o'clock and you
finish at 10:30 and you're in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old Northern Ireland native made his professional
stage debut in 1976 at the Lyric Player's Theatre in Belfast,
having supported himself as a boxer and forklift driver for the
Guinness brewery. He was discovered playing Lennie in ``Of Mice and
Men'' at Dublin's Abbey Theatre by film director John Boorman and
cast as Gawain in the 1981 Arthurian epic, ``Excalibur.''
Supporting roles in such films as ``The Bounty,'' ``Suspect'' and
``The Dead Pool'' followed, before his first starring role as the
disfigured protagonist of Sam Raimi's cartoonish 1990 thriller,
``Darkman.''
</P>
<P>
   Neeson's breakthrough came after director Steven Spielberg saw
his acclaimed 1992 Broadway debut in ``Anna Christie'' and cast the
actor as Austrian industrialist Oskar Schindler in his Academy
Award-winning Holocaust drama, ``Schindler's List.''
</P>
<P>
   The strapping yet soft-spoken Neeson said his penchant for
playing larger-than-life heroic figures is happenstance. He
describes his latest such role, the sage but rebellious Qui-Gon
Jinn, as a cross between Alan Ladd in ``Shane,'' Takashi Shimura in
``The Seven Samurai'' and ``Star Wars'' creator George Lucas. ``I'm
not the kind of actor who needs to know what (the character) had
for breakfast last Tuesday,'' Neeson said. ``The backstory for me
was Episode 4, the first Stars Wars, believing in that world and
believing in Sir Alec Guinness' personification of an older Jedi.''
</P>
<P>
   Neeson sought out the role because of Lucas, who he's admired
since 1973's ``American Graffiti.'' Through a representative, he
sent out feelers to see if the director might be interested in him.
``Not because necessarily I was a huge, mega-Star Wars fan,'' he
said. ``I just really wanted to work with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas originally envisioned Qui-Gon as a much older character to
be played by an American actor, but was impressed with Neeson's
skills and presence. ``I'm always looking first and foremost for
very accomplished actors, people who are extremely talented and
know their craft very well,'' Lucas said. ``And then next I'm
looking for people who have the stature and, more importantly, the
demeanor of the characters. Liam just seemed ... born to play that
role. He's very quiet; he's very big; he's very powerful; but he's
very contemplative.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor's physicality was important for his fierce lightsaber
battles with ``The Phantom Menace's'' villain, Darth Maul, played
by martial arts expert Ray Park. Neeson previously crossed swords
in ``Excalibur'' and ``Rob Roy.'' ``I love doing that stuff,'' he
said. One complicated fight sequence took nearly a month to film,
with Neeson, Park and Ewan McGregor, who plays young Obi-Wan
Kenobi, dueling, leaping and somersaulting across three sets.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger challenge was interacting with digital characters who
were added to scenes during post-production. ``Acting for me is
about reacting, so it's very, very difficult,'' Neeson said. ``It's
hard to act with something that isn't there, and yet there is a
technique to it. My main consideration was I didn't want to be like
those early, early science-fiction films where you would see the
hero with a glassy-eyed stare trying to fight some huge ant.
Subconsciously as an audience member you say, well that guy's not
looking at anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace'' features nearly 2,000 special-effects
shots _ more than three times the 500 used in ``Titanic.'' As for
his other summer special-effects movie, Neeson said, ```The
Haunting' is a dawdle compared to this.''
</P>
<P>
   And how does the pop adventure of ``Star Wars: Episode 1''
compare to films that depend more on character-driven performances
than, well, puppets?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, at the end of the day you have to _ be it acting with
Jar Jar Binks (in `The Phantom Menace') or Aidan Quinn in `Michael
Collins' or something, there's something you still have to convey
and share,'' Neeson said. ``Be it, `Where's the nearest space
craft? Let's get out of here,' to whatever. It's the actor's job to
convey whatever it is _ in that scene, in that genre. Don't take it
lightly and ... try never to overplay it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
