<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-ECONSCEN     05-12 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: MANEUVERING MINIMUM WAGE BANDWAGON CAREFULLY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress will almost certainly raise the minimum wage this year,
probably to $6.15 an hour from $5.15, phased in over two to three
years. Democrats, as always, are in full support. So, too, are at
least 20 moderate House Republicans anxious about next year's
election. But whatever the political attraction, does a higher
minimum wage make economic sense?
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of economists say yes, though there is reason
for Congress to move cautiously, perhaps even creatively.
</P>
<P>
   The main purpose for raising the minimum wage is to make it
possible for all full-time workers to earn enough to lift their
families out of poverty. The current minimum wage falls short. By
2000, according to calculations by Isaac Shapiro of the Center on
Budget and Policy Priorities, the combination of earnings at $5.15
an hour, $3,600 in food stamps and the earned income tax credit _ a
provision of the tax code that has the Treasury send a check of up
to $3,880 to low-wage workers _ would bring the annual income of a
family of four to about $16,100: $1,400 short of the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   But at a wage of $6.15, the family would fall short by about
only $450.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, like Prof. David Neumark of Michigan State, say further
increases in the minimum wage would make some low-wage workers too
expensive to hire. Teen-agers are especially vulnerable. Neumark
concludes, ``the net effect of minimum wages is an increase in the
proportion of poor families.'' Other critics say that the minimum
wage showers help on the wrong people, for example, teen-agers from
wealthy families.
</P>
<P>
   But most studies show that none of these problems loom large.
Based on widely accepted estimates, a $6.15 minimum wage would
likely take jobs away from fewer than 64,000 of the 3.3 million
teen-agers now working. Very few adults would lose work. Jared
Bernstein, an economist at the Economic Policy Institute,
challenges the argument that the benefits of the minimum wage go to
nonneedy families.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 percent of the beneficiaries of minimum wage
increases in 1996 and 1997 were adults, about half of whom worked
full time and typically accounted for more than half of their
families' earnings. The 20 percent lowest-paid workers reaped about
35 percent of the benefits of the wage increase even though they
accounted for only 5 percent of total earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Many economist who concede that a higher minimum wage would not
destroy many jobs oppose raising it because, they argue, there is a
better way to help low-wage workers: increase the tax credit.
Because the credit does not hit employers, it does not strip
workers of jobs. But the problem with this argument, many other
economists point out, is that the tax credit has its own problem.
To control the cost of the credit, it is phased out as family
income rises above $12,500. The credit is scaled back by 21 cents
for every extra dollar the family earns. The claw-back operates
like an extra 21 percent tax on additional earnings. The most
effective antipoverty program, Bernstein says, ``would artfully
combine the tax credit and minimum wages.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is reason to proceed with caution. In the next few
years, women who have exhausted benefits under the 1996 welfare law
will be forced to enter the labor force. These women, many of whom
will have poor or nonexistent work records, will be pressed to find
jobs. Making employers pay an extra dollar an hour will not help.
There is, then, reason for Congress to consider permitting
employers to pay $5.15 for recent welfare recipients for, say, the
first six months or so.
</P>
<P>
   Congress might even venture a bit further. Small companies are
dropping health insurance for their workers. To reverse the trend,
Congress might consider permitting companies to apply some of the
money they spend on health benefits toward their obligation under
the minimum wage bill. There are problems with this approach _
young workers are likely to prefer higher wages to health insurance
_ but it could also help ease a pressing and growing social
problem. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0488 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4915 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FINALES13-COX     05-12 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FINALES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Series ride into the sunset
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's goodbye _ and perhaps good riddance _ to
four long-running TV series as the season comes to an end this
month.
</P>
<P>
   All were distinctive and popular in their prime, but the years
have seen ratings and freshness fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nanny,'' which ended its six-season run Wednesday, fell
the farthest, winding up with nasal Fran Drescher married to her
boss and giving birth to twins. The swan song was light years away
from the show's original concept, contrasting the blue-blood,
English-born Broadway producer and his blue-collar, live-in baby
sitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad About You,'' which started out seven seasons ago as a
romantic comedy about newlyweds Paul (Paul Reiser) and Jamie (Helen
Hunt), lost its edge with the birth of baby Mabel at the end of the
'97 season. ``Home Improvement,'' a family sitcom based on Tim
Allen's pseudo-macho standup routine, has stayed on so long the
cute kids have turned into semi-adults.
</P>
<P>
   Only ``Melrose Place,'' the definitive sexy sudser that helped
nail Fox's reputation as a hip, young network, remained true to its
original mission. But in its seven-year run, the show has seen
every imaginable coupling, uncoupling and betrayal. Not even Aaron
Spelling, the king of soapy melodrama, could further heighten
Heather Locklear's vixen stature.
</P>
<P>
   Evolution is inevitable. Perhaps so is fatigue. Nothing lasts
forever, certainly not TV characters or the actors who play them.
</P>
<P>
   But even when long-running series grow weary, they often do
better in the ratings than new shows, which have increasingly high
mortality rates. So far this season, there hasn't been a single
break-out hit on any commercial network. Established series are
extremely important to the health of a network. That's why some are
encouraged to stay on far past their prime.
</P>
<P>
   ```Mad About You' has been a tremendous source of pride,'' said
Bob Levy, vice president of prime-time series for NBC. ``And
besides making us proud, it has pulled enormous weight on our
schedule. It's been in six time periods in seven years. After a
slow start, it has performed well for us wherever it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad About You'' was the cornerstone of two of NBC's
``Must-See'' nights: Thursday and Tuesday. Its success helped
launch ``Friends'' and hastened the demise of ABC's ``Roseanne.''
Until Mabel arrived, ``Mad About You'' was a sophisticated comedy
that had all the right ingredients to attract a large and
demographically desirable audience.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the key to turning a good series into a long-running
series?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we knew that we'd have a lot more legendary shows,'' Levy
said with a chuckle. ``I think largely it's the alchemy of various
factors: the right concept, the right stars, excellent writing and
directing. Nobody can really predict it or control it.''
</P>
<P>
   When a series does click, it forms a bond with viewers that
keeps them coming back week after week. With ``Mad About You,'' it
was the romance, the humor and viewers' ability to relate to the
characters. Memories of the better, early years will be recalled in
the hour-long finale, which airs May 24 at 8 p.m. and will have a
flash-forward with Janeane Garofalo playing a grown-up Mabel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Improvement'' was an instant hit when it came along eight
years ago. Tim Allen's wacky cave man standup was the basis for the
domestic sitcom that was crafted to suit his talent, and it became
one of the few family comedies that remained focused on the parents
instead of the children. The middle son, played by Jonathan Taylor
Thomas, became something of a teen heartthrob, but Allen and
Patricia Richardson (who played wife Jill) were the heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taping that final episode was extremely emotional,'' said
executive producer Bruce Ferber. ``The show meant more to Tim than
anybody else because it was his life. Pat and Tim had a
relationship that was like a real marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute finale, which airs May 25 at 7 p.m., includes a
half-hour of highlights, a half-hour episode in which Tim quits his
cable TV show, ``Tool Time,'' and Jill is offered a teaching job in
Indiana, and a half-hour of bloopers. In the last segment, the
actors chat with the audience and each other about their memories
of the show. Everybody except Thomas, who was invited back but
declined, is on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of the end of an era,'' Ferber said. ```Home
Improvement' is the last comedy about a functional family that's
been given a prime slot on a major network.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly. ``The Hughleys'' is about a nuclear family,
and other families are bound to arrive in the fall. The family
sitcom has been declared dead many times but always resurrects
itself.
</P>
<P>
   But the end of ``Home Improvement'' is a big loss to ABC. Of the
four long-running series departing this month, ``Home Improvement''
leaves with the healthiest ratings, frequently appearing in the
Nielsen Top 20. There's no question it was a franchise show for
ABC, successfully anchoring Tuesday nights through much of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Tim's decision to quit,'' Ferber said. ``He wanted to
go out on top. And creatively, we'd been every place we needed to
go. ... History is going to be kind to this show. It captured the
male-female conflict in the country, the differences between men
and women and how we continue to try to get along. It was a show
about something, and that was a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the departing series has been as controversial or
influential as ``Melrose Place,'' created by long-time fluffmeister
Aaron Spelling (``Dynasty,'' ``Charlie's Angels''). Young viewers
flocked to ``Melrose'' by the millions, laughing at its outrageous
sexiness and imitating its fashion and hairstyles. Amanda's
short-skirted, long-jacketed suit (worn with cleavage instead of a
blouse) became the ``power suit'' of the '90s and a forerunner of
Ally McBeal's micro-mini outfits of today. The young actors
regularly pop up in the pages of People and In Style magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has definitely been a signature show for this network,''
said Craig Erwich, vice president of drama programming at Fox.
</P>
<P>
   A lightning rod for criticism, too. Older viewers and critics of
the medium decried the wanton sexual escapades that are a regular
part of each episode. Bed-hopping was a phrase that could
accurately be used to describe just about every character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Organically, that was part of the show,'' Erwich said. ``When
you have stories about young, beautiful people, certainly there
will be a sexual energy. Doing something steamy, sexy and
distinctive is never discouraged here. It was the first prime-time
soap to wrest the crown away from the older, monied worlds of
`Dynasty,' `Dallas' and `Falcon Crest' and give it to younger
people. It took an established genre, which had been on its last
legs, and breathed new life into it.''
</P>
<P>
   But on May 24 at 7 p.m., ``Melrose'' will have its last gasp.
Not surprisingly, Fox is mum on details. A tersely worded press
release says it will be ``an explosive ending, complete with a
wedding and a funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   So, is there a natural life expectancy to any series? Probably.
With all the choices available to viewers today, it's harder and
harder to grab and keep an audience and equally hard to keep them
interested.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the four series bowing out this month, the
creativity and growth of earlier years is gone. Although we'll miss
some of the characters, it's time for them to go.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
