<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ROCKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IT'S NOT ROCKET SCIENCE, MAYBE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, May 13: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Space experts are scratching their heads over a paralyzing
series of rocket failures that have disrupted both military and
civilian launches. In the last nine months there have been six
serious failures of American rockets that have destroyed or
nullified some $3.5 billion worth of intelligence, imaging and
communications satellites. Four of the failures occurred in the
past five weeks. This is the most serious launching crisis since
the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger and other rocket
failures in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   At first impression, there appears to be no common thread in the
accidents. The string of failures may simply be a run of bad luck
with no long-range significance. Or it may signify far deeper
problems, ranging from sloppy quality control to poorly written
software to design errors or manufacturing defects. One worrisome
possibility is that the launching industry is suffering from a
shortage of experienced engineers and technicians at a time that it
is under great pressure to fly more rockets more cheaply to keep
pace with foreign competitors. ``It's manufacturing and quality
control,'' one private expert contended. ``Not a lot of this is
real rocket science.''
</P>
<P>
   High-level reviews by the military and the aerospace industry
may find an answer to the puzzle. Meanwhile it is sobering to
realize that, even now, more than 40 years into the space age,
launchings remain a risky and unforgiving business. Those hoping to
be rocketed into space by commercial entrepreneurs, or who consider
rockets a dandy way to dispose of nuclear and toxic wastes in
space, might take note.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
