<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BOWERY-DEVELOP-ART     05-12 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOWERY-DEVELOP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWERY ARTISTS' BARGAIN LOFTS THREATENED BY URBAN RENEWAL PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Forty years ago, decades before stretch limousines
choked the Bowery, discharging luminaries lured to the Bowery Bar,
long before it was remotely hip to live on the Lower East Side,
much less Skid Row, Kate Millett moved to what she dubs the
``street of sorrows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When my mother first visited me, she stepped out of the cab,
over the bluejeaned hippies and the drunks passed out on the
sidewalk and wept,'' Ms. Millett, the feminist author and artist,
recalled recently, her gray, shoulder-length hair brushing her face
as she laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Millett sat in a wooden chair in the kitchen of her second
Bowery residence, a 2,400-square-foot loft the city moved her to 26
years ago after her previous rental was condemned. The massive
fifth floor apartment is where she lives; her art studio, also
2,400 square feet and awash in white, is two floors down.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Millett was chain-smoking Marlboros. ``I adore where I
live,'' she said, lighting up. ``I love nesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't? She rents both lofts from the city for the
impossible sum of $500 a month.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Millett, 64, may find herself in a new dwelling soon.
The building at 295 Bowery, also home to two other artists, a
curator and two children, is scheduled to be razed and its tenants
relocated because the city wants to tear it down to make room for
an urban renewal project that has been in the works since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Having slowly acquired chunks of property during the last 25
years over a large swath of the Lower East Side, the city is
finally poised to select a developer at the end of the summer for
the Cooper Square Urban Renewal Project, which would cover three
and a half acres. The project would include 450 market- rate
apartments, 150 low-income dwellings and a 30,000-square-foot
community center with a gymnasium and a pool.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Ms. Millett and the other residents are not
moving without a fight. Having failed to win landmark status for
the 136-year-old building _ which has quite a storied history, in a
sordid sort of way _ the tenants are looking into gaining
historic-district designation for the entire length of the Bowery,
from Confucius Plaza at its south to Cooper Square at its
northernmost end. And they have submitted to the city an
alternative development plan that would spare 295 Bowery. In
addition, the city also has yet to find replacement housing for
them, a process that could drag on.
</P>
<P>
   That the city's ambitious plans may hinge on, or at the least be
inconvenienced by, 295 Bowery could be viewed as either curious or
fitting, given the transformation of the thoroughfare and the small
building itself.
</P>
<P>
   The building had been a hotel during the Civil War, catering to
returning soldiers. By the 1890s it was a brothel and a dive where
it is said that a half-dozen destitute courtesans drank carbolic
acid and died. John McGurk, the owner of the saloon on the ground
floor, then capitalized on the notoriety of the place by renaming
it McGurk's Suicide Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Later, beginning in World War I and continuing into the 1950s
and early '60s, it was a flophouse for Skid Row veterans. In the
mid-'60s it was converted into artists' studios.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this colorful past, the city's Landmarks Preservation
Commission denied landmark status to the building, finding that it
did not have sufficient historical, cultural or architectural
merit.
</P>
<P>
   But the neighborhood is a far cry from what it was when Ms.
Millett and her neighbors first moved in. Real estate there is
ablaze. The area is dripping with funky shops, restaurants and
night spots, and the price of apartment rentals rivals that of
other Manhattan neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   So the loft-dwellers of 295 Bowery are not evoking much
sympathy. Councilwoman Kathryn Freed, who represents the area, said
the building's tenants knew when they moved in that they would one
day have to vacate because the property was part of a project born
28 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate to see this proposal fall flat because of a few
people,'' Ms. Freed said. ``They put a lot of money in their lofts,
but they knew it was not their property.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outside, the building looks like any other dowdy
tenement, with its faded brick facade and a touch of graffiti. But
inside, the rambling lofts have been transformed by their artists
in residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here, it was dark and dirty, with no windows in
the front, just openings covered with tins; no bathroom except for
a toilet, no heat and no kitchen,'' said Ms. Millett, whose living
quarters now are filled with three Franklin stoves, a wealth of
antiques, and shelves upon shelves of books.
</P>
<P>
   The Housing Preservation Department says it will relocate the
tenants, but exactly where is not yet known. The city is obligated
to move the residents into comparable space, and a statement
released by the housing agency says the new dwelling must be
``decent, safe and sanitary.'' But it is not required that the rent
remain the same, nor that the apartment be in the same condition.
Tenants, the statement said, can get rental assistance if they meet
eligibility requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Millett's downstairs neighbor and longtime friend, Sophie
Keir, denied that she and her neighbors knew that the building
would one day be leveled. Ms. Millett moved in after her former
residence on the Bowery was razed. ``Why would they put her in a
building that was going to be demolished, too?'' asked Ms. Keir, a
sculptor and furniture maker who has lived for 20 years in the
second-floor loft.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She added that artist Michael Bakaty _ who lives on the fourth
floor with his wife, Yvonne Muranushi, and two young sons, Zoli, 5,
and Kaz, 2 _ was living in the building 30 years ago when it was
privately owned.
</P>
<P>
   The Bakatys, who pay $300 a month for rent, have erected a
warren of rooms in their apartment. ``I love this place,'' said Ms.
Muranushi, a curator. ``Both my children were born here with a
midwife right there on the sofa.''
</P>
<P>
   But the HPD says the Cooper Square project is moving forward. It
will issue a request for proposals sometime this spring and expects
to have a developer chosen by the end of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, 400 households were relocated temporarily or
permanently because of the urban renewal plan, said Valerio
Orselli, a member of the Cooper Square Committee, an arm of the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Orselli said that five years ago the tenants of 295 Bowery were
shown alternative spaces at 267 Bowery, which they rejected.
Residents say they were shown the space with a flashlight because
there was no electricity. ``We asked to see it in daylight,'' Ms.
Millett said. ``That never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Orselli said the city planned to renovate 267 Bowery. ``We were
going to put in solid wood floors, windows, everything,'' he said.
Other artists have since purchased it.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the city will also demolish commercially
occupied buildings at 291, 293 and 311 Bowery. That worries Sam
Kahn, a co-owner of Stanton Trading Corporation, a restaurant
supply company. ``There's no good end to this for us,'' said Kahn,
whose business occupies 291 and 293 Bowery and the ground floor of
the loft building. ``We're in something of a pickle.''
</P>
<P>
   The housing committee of Community Board 3 passed a motion that
any proposals for new construction should contain space for Stanton
Trading, which has been on the Bowery for 40 years, Kahn said.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, Ms. Keir presented her own proposal to the
community board. Under her plan, the 600 apartments planned by the
urban renewal project would be built, but 295 Bowery would be
spared. The board unanimously passed a resolution urging the
housing department to examine the plan as a possible alternative
when proposals flow in. Ms. Keir has also presented the plan
directly to the housing department.
</P>
<P>
   And the residents are still researching the street's unsavory
past, hoping to be designated a historic district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate not to have a Bowery address,'' said Ms. Millett.
``It's the street of truth, so to speak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
