<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-BAKER13-COX     05-12 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-BAKER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Original R2-D2 actor is `on a roll'
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Kenny Baker is a singular anomaly in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   An internationally known movie star, he's yet to utter a line of
dialogue in his best-known role.
</P>
<P>
   His character's one-word name is an icon of pop culture _ like
Cher or Sting _ but few know what he looks like out of costume.
</P>
<P>
   And although he stands just 3-foot-8, he's a giant in movie
history.
</P>
<P>
   R2D2.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Baker goes for another spin in the ``Star Wars'' whirlpool
next week when the latest movie in the science-fiction serial,
``Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' opens in the United States on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Baker spent 12 weeks reprising his role in ``Menace'' as the
chirping, beeping sidekick to Anthony Daniels' C-3PO character. The
two were the only characters carried over to the ``prequel'' from
the original three movies. (His favorite was the second in the
series, ``The Empire Strikes Back.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``We used the same R2 unit we used the last time,'' Baker said
by phone from his home in Manchester, England. ``It even had the
same boots inside that I wore for stability in the first three
movies. I half thought there would still be scorpions from the last
time we shot in the Tunisian desert.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah yes, the desert. Director George Lucas shot action scenes for
``Menace'' in the same Tunisian desert seen in the opening
sequences for ``Star Wars'' in 1976. Temperatures in the 120s.
Wicked sand storms that wrecked entire movie sets. And the
aforementioned critters. All of which is all fine if you're a young
man.
</P>
<P>
   But Baker is 64 now. He's highly claustrophobic, battles asthma
and had difficulty dealing with temperatures that went as high as
127. Doesn't help that his R2D2 costume is only 3-feet, 10-inches
tall and has no cooling system and just a small hole at the bottom
to let in air.
</P>
<P>
   And as acting gigs go, R2D2 is no Hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't move very far. I wobble it around and look one way or
another, or react to dialogue, look from left to right, that sort
of thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, it was an exciting feeling to be in same kind of film,
with the same sort of sets and some familiar people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After finding stardom with ``Star Wars,'' Baker went on to
perform in such films as ``Time Bandits,'' ``The Elephant Man'' and
``Amadeus.'' A lull hit after the last ``Star Wars'' film, ``Return
of the Jedi,'' but these days his schedule is filled.
</P>
<P>
   He is represented by a Florida-based talent agency that books
him to appear at science fiction conventions around the country,
along with several other minor ``Star Wars'' characters. For four
years, he's played arguably the most lovable dwarf of all time,
Dopey, in a London stage play. And he has a few other gigs lined up
before he retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often say, I'm the luckiest dwarf in Europe,'' he said. ``My
house is paid for, I've got a Rolls Royce. There are two more `Star
Wars' movies to do, another in Sweden and a show in London that
could lead to other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really on a roll at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   R2D2 Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   You don't get to talk to R2D2 eery day. So we asked Kenny Baker
a few questions we were curious about.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Ever pop a wheelie in the R2D2 robot?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm very rarely in the mobile shots. No, the robot that moves
falls over occasionally. Hits a stone or goes into a ditch. All my
model does is wobble and turn it's head.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is furrier, Chewbacca or George Lucas?
</P>
<P>
   A: George has only got it on his face, as far as I know. Chewie
is much hairier. Peter Mayhew, who plays Chewbacca, is quite hairy
himself, though.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who would win in a fight: Darth Vader or the new meanie,
Darth Maul?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know. I wasn't there for battle scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How about a fight between Chewbacca and, say, Boba Fett?
</P>
<P>
   A: Boba Fett's the bounty hunter. He's quite popular. He's got
this power pack on his back and armor and it's a quite attractive
costume. Jeremy Bullock, the guy inside, is very likeable and
speaks very clear English. He and I do quite well on these
conventions we appear at. Who would win, though? Chewie is a little
bit slow and thinks a lot slower. I'd have to give it to Boba Fett.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Ever get the urge to knock Anthony Daniels over when he says
something snotty as C-3PO?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've knocked him over a few times by accident, but he's more
inclined to knock me over. I'm not sure if it's on purpose but I
suspect not. He has quite a lot of dialogue, but when he looks at
me, nothing really happens. I don't move quite at all in relation
to dialogue. Anthony has been pretty pissed off at me on occasion.
As an actor, how do react to a robot? I can't raise an eyebrow or
do things normal actors would do. He must get pretty frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You played a cuddly, furry Ewok in the third film. Ever go
out in public dressed like that?
</P>
<P>
   A: The costumes at the time were a pain to work with. Very
uncomfortable. Very hot. I vowed never to be an Ewok again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
