<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4931 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      05-12 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The visitors' locker room at the Great Western
Forum was almost empty when Charles Barkley made his way back from
the shower to his corner. A small boy waited and almost whispered
his request for the Air Jordans that Barkley gives away after every
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, I already gave them away tonight,'' Barkley said.
``Come back Monday after we kick their butts in Houston, and
they're yours. I'll see you on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   But returning the series to Los Angeles will take more than
Barkley's unsinkable confidence and unwavering bravado.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a half-hour earlier, when he was surrounded by media
members searching for answers to explain the Rockets' 2-0 hole in
their best-of-five series with the Lakers, Barkley said he would
not dissect his team.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to. The Lakers already had. Tonight, back home
but facing elimination, the Rockets find out what is inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's all heart,'' Rockets backup center Antoine Carr
said. ``All the X's and O's don't mean anything unless you go out
there and give it your all. If you think, `I'm a pretty boy, I'm
going to get pub,' you need to sit your butt down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first year with this team. We have a lot of new
players. I don't know if they have the mentality. I know a few of
us do, but I'm not sure about everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The depth of that mentality among the Rockets remains uncertain
at a time when it is needed most. After doing almost everything
they could to blow the home-court advantage down the stretch of the
regular season, they're paying for it immediately in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Needing to step up in the final eight seconds Sunday, they fell
down. With a chance to even the series Tuesday, they were routed
from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Now facing elimination, they insist they have the fortitude to
come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the experience of a team that knows what it's like to
be in the playoffs,'' Rockets center Hakeem Olajuwon said. ``We're
down 2-0; it doesn't mean it's over. We can't believe it's over.
The playoffs are not just the skill; it's the mental.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding the position realistically, they held serve. The
pressure is on us to take care of the home-court advantage to stay
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where the team character is tested.''
</P>
<P>
   One defeat away from ending their season, the Rockets cannot
even lean on their once-remarkable history when pushed to the
brink. The Rockets are 11-4 in elimination games under coach Rudy
Tomjanovich. But they have lost three of their past four
elimination games since the championship years.
</P>
<P>
   They have gone into a 2-0 hole 15 previous times, winning the
series twice. In best-of-five series they have been in a 2-0 hole
three times, losing all three, including twice to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past doesn't have anything to do with the present,''
Barkley said. ``We have to play well tomorrow and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   But one can learn from the past, and Barkley did bring the 1993
Suns back from a 2-0 hole, which was made deeper because the Suns
took that perilous situation to Los Angeles before sweeping the
next three games to win the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nerve-racking when your back is against the wall,''
Barkley said. ``You can't worry about it. You just have to go out
there and play, and play well. You don't have any room for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did what they had to do. Now we have to do what we have
to do. The pressure is always on the home team to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The key, the Rockets said, is striking the balance between panic
and intensity, urgency and desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're backed into a corner,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We've got to
pull really close together. We're going home. They've held serve.
We've got to get our confidence back. We can't get into a
depression. They've played very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't panic. You have to come out with a sense of urgency.
It can't be desperation. It can't be panic.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the Rockets have characterized the Lakers'
2-0 start, including their magnificent performance Tuesday, as
little more than taking care of their home court. The Lakers played
so well, they said, that the Rockets couldn't be fooled into
believing themselves outmatched.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers made 45 of 83 shots (54.2 percent) Tuesday, with a
remarkable 10 of 18 on 3-pointers, burning the Rockets for the
double-team attention they had to pay Shaquille O'Neal. O'Neal was
at his best, finishing with 28 points, nine rebounds, seven assists
and five blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they shoot the ball like that, crown them NBA champs,''
Rockets forward Scottie Pippen said. ``You have to respect the fact
we have to double down on Shaq. Somebody is going to be open. They
made us pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than them shooting the heck out of the ball, we feel
good about what we're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen added, however, that one change he believes the Rockets
will need is more offense from him. Pippen was 0-for-7 and made
three first-half free throws Tuesday. In four games this season in
the Great Western Forum, Pippen has made 15 of 56 shots.
</P>
<P>
   But in the one regular-season meeting with the Lakers at Compaq
Center, Pippen made eight of 15 shots and led the Rockets with 26
points in a 22-point win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know last night was not the type of game I would like to
have,'' Pippen said. ``I came out to try to be aggressive and get
us going early. But if you're taking the ball out of the basket
every time down the court, it's hard to make a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give this team more offense. I have to be more
aggressive offensively. I don't want to force shots, but it may
come down to that. I have to be more aggressive and get more
opportunities for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said he would continue to consider changes in
schemes or strategies that could help. But few seem likely.
</P>
<P>
   Of Pippen's offensive troubles, Tomjanovich said, ``I don't
think you put it on one person. I'm not putting it on him at all.
Collectively, we have to get into our game. When we're into our
game, we have balance out there.''
</P>
<P>
   With few changes likely, the Rockets have focused on a mindset,
an attitude and confidence. They have pointed to Game 1 _ when they
played well, could have won and insist they should have won. And
they will hope the return to their home court will give them
another chance to test themselves on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're playing a different team,'' Rockets guard
Brent Price said. ``We know what they do. We've gone over the X's
and O's. We know how we're supposed to rotate. We know what all the
tendencies are. We know all those things. All of it now is about
what's inside. We've got to come out clawing and fighting and
scratching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to find out what we're made of. Who knows? I don't
think we can really tell until Thursday night.''
</P>
<P>
   A dissection will provide such answers, especially for a
franchise that not long ago celebrated its heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can go in there and concede,'' forward Othella Harrington
said, ``or we can have some guts and play our hearts out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
