<HEADLINE>
WEALTH OF OPTIONS CONCERNS PGA TOUR BOSS
</HEADLINE>
 By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ PGA Tour Commissioner Tim Finchem said Wednesday
he has concerns about several factors that threaten to limit
widespread participation of elite players at future tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, Finchem said, are the emergence of the World Golf
Championships, the proliferation of appearance fees awarded PGA
Tour stars to compete in European Tour events and the creation of
more special events similar to the Aug. 2 exhibition match between
David Duval and Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Duval, the game's top-ranked players, are scheduled to
compete for a $1.5 million purse on a Monday night as part of
prime-time programming on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are things we have to monitor,'' Finchem said. ``I feel
good about where we are. But if things start going in the other
direction, we'll have to make some adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   On a case-by-case basis, Finchem dealt with all three topics:
</P>
<P>
   If another World Golf Championship event is added to the tour
calendar before 2002, its purse will not count as official earnings
on the PGA Tour money list, Finchem said. The tour added three WGC
events to the 1999 calendar, each with a $5 million purse and the
potential to drain the quality of fields at tournaments played in
surrounding weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we need to take a deep breath, let the public
enjoy these events and see if we need to make adjustments in a year
or two,'' Finchem said. ``If we do, we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Five elite tour players _ Tiger Woods, Nick Price, Mark O'Meara,
Ernie Els and Jesper Parnevik _ will accept six-figure appearance
fees next week to compete at a European Tour event in Germany
rather than play at the MasterCard Colonial. Each player had to
receive a conflicting-event waiver from the PGA Tour to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We carefully monitor the number of releases. But once in a
while, we still have a blip on the screen generated by big
appearance money,'' Finchem said. ``I think this is an isolated
incident. If things get too bad (in the future), we won't grant
releases beyond a certain number.''
</P>
<P>
   Although sanctioned by the tour, Finchem predicted future
special events like the Duval-Woods exhibition will be few and far
between during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of thing that doesn't make a lot of sense to do
a lot,'' Finchem said. ``Do we want to set up made-for-TV matches
during the official earnings season on a regular basis? I don't
think so. But this is a unique set of circumstances. It's a match
people want to see and we're thinking it will promote the game to a
wider viewing audience.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
