<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENTATIVE ACCORD REACHED ON EMERGENCY MILITARY SPENDING BILL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Calif., Fla., Ill., Kan., Miss., Nev., Okla., Wis.)  (rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ignoring their leaders' wishes to hold down
spending, congressional negotiators tentatively agreed Wednesday on
a $11.6 billion emergency bill to finance the fighting in
Yugoslavia and pay for a myriad of Pentagon programs.
</P>
<P>
   In a game of political poker that began with President Clinton's
bid for $6 billion for the bombing in the Balkans, the House-Senate
conference committee was far from showing its hole cards.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, committee members had not agreed on how
to pay for the emergency bill, or whether to rid it of amendments
and riders favoring special interests. The negotiations continued
into the night.
</P>
<P>
   After days of intense bargaining, Democratic senators still
sought billions in farm aid and school safety programs. Republican
senators wanted hundreds of millions for mining, gas, oil, fishing
and other business interests _ not everyone's definition of an
emergency, as Democrats pointed out. Conservatives remained furious
that most of the $13 billion on the table would come out of the
Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Other emergency spending measures, for Central American and
Caribbean countries hit last year by hurricanes, seemed likely to
grow to include $500 million for disaster victims in this country,
including Oklahomans and Kansans, who lost so much last week in
tornadoes, and about $400 million more for American farmers hurt by
falling food prices.
</P>
<P>
   That would bring the total emergency package headed for the
House and Senate to more than $13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The chief negotiators, Sen. Ted Stevens of Alaska and Rep. C.W.
``Bill'' Young of Florida, both Appropriations Committee chairmen,
read and then tossed aside pleas from the majority leader, Sen.
Trent Lott of Mississippi, and the speaker, Rep. J. Dennis Hastert
of Illinois, to hold the military spending to $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and Rep. Jerry Lewis of California, the head of the
House Defense Appropriations Subcommittee, briefly argued about the
meaning of the $11 billion figure in the leaders' letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleven billion is a ceiling, not a floor,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis responded, ``It was a floor.''
</P>
<P>
   That set the tone for the conference, which veered Wednesday
from deadly serious to nearly madcap.
</P>
<P>
   Proceedings halted for nearly an hour as Stevens and his fellow
Alaska Republican, Sen. Frank Murkowski, argued for a measure aimed
at keeping the Glacier Bay National Park open to commercial
fishermen. Young said the House would block the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The conference also took time to discuss Stevens' proposed $3
million program to help Alaskan reindeer ranchers protect their
herds. ``You can call it my Santa Claus amendment, if you want,''
the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments ground on over another amendment, sponsored by the
Republican senators from Kansas, Sam Brownback and Pat Roberts,
that would let natural-gas producers avoid repaying $235 million in
penalties and interest they owe to overcharged consumers in 23
states _ ``a straight special-interests versus public-interest
issue,'' said Rep. David R. Obey of Wisconsin, the ranking Democrat
on the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Some members wondered aloud what such provisions were doing in
an emergency spending bill to help finance NATO's air war. ``The
question of whether it's a emergency or not is in the eye of the
beholder,'' Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., said with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   But the conference did tentatively agree on the biggest item
before it: how much money to add to the military spending measure,
which was originally intended for this country's share of the air
war.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and Lewis, the chief appropriators, agreed on $11.55
billion, or $5.5 billion more than Clinton requested. They added
$2.25 billion for military operations and maintenance, $1.84
billion for a military pay increase, $300 million for aircraft,
$475 million for construction at overseas bases, $250 million for
missiles and munitions, $200 million for the Coast Guard and $100
million for military recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   They also added $46 million to Clinton's request for assistance
to war refugees from Kosovo, bringing the total to $678 million.
</P>
<P>
   The conferees have also agreed to spend $687 million for the
Caribbean and Central American hurricane victims and $100 million
to shore up Jordan's role in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest stumbling blocks remained. Moderate
Republicans need to persuade conservatives to pay for the package
with money from the Social Security surplus. House members need to
keep twisting Senators' arms to persuade them to drop amendments
benefiting home states and pet interests.
</P>
<P>
   Unless that happened, Obey said, the bill would resemble ``not a
Christmas tree, but a Christmas tree farm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
