<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4935 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-BRYANT-LAD     05-12 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BRYANT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT FRUSTRATES PIPPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Kobe Bryant, impetuous youth that he is, waits for
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the NBA, which he entered at age 18. Not for
responsibility, which he embraced when he took the final shots, as
a rookie, in the Lakers' 1997 playoff loss to Utah. Not for a
starting job, which he forcibly took this season at age 20.
</P>
<P>
   So it should come as no surprise that Bryant demanded to guard
the great Scottie Pippen in the Lakers' playoff series with the
Houston Rockets. Bryant knows what he wants, and more often than
not, he gets it.
</P>
<P>
   That trait is serving him and his team well at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are up two games to none in this best-of-five series,
and at the core of their success is stifling defense. And at the
core of that defense is Bryant, shutting down one of the 50
greatest players in NBA history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what,'' said Lakers veteran Derek Harper, ``that's
the key to the series. What he's done in this series against
(Pippen). Because he's truly taken Scottie out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In two games, Pippen has made 5 of 20 field goals, is averaging
8.5 points and 3.0 turnovers and has been almost invisible on the
court. That's a far cry from his 18.1-point career average in 11
postseasons, during which he won six championships with Michael
Jordan's Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   To be certain, Pippen is a less active part of the Rockets
offense than he was in Chicago. But there's no mistaking that
Bryant is blossoming as a defender at the expense of one of his
role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt that Pippen was the second-best player in the
world, because of everything that he brings to the table and how he
does it,'' said Bryant, who grew up watching the 12-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Ironic, too, that Bryant patterned much of his own defensive
style on what he observed in Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always admired him for his defensive effort,'' he said.
``Everybody always talked about Mike (Jordan) and how great he was.
Pippen, to me, was always the key to the team, because of all the
little things that he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's admiration of Pippen, and the desire to challenge
himself against the best, led him to strike a deal with coach Kurt
Rambis. Two weeks ago, late in a Lakers rout of Portland, Bryant
wanted to get back in the game. Rambis said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `That's fine, man. You give me Scottie,' '' Bryant
said. ``So it was a nice little tradeoff. I was more than happy to
sit on the bench for the remainder of that game.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Rambis could only laugh. The conversation did take
place, but the coaches had already decided Bryant would get the
assignment, switching with Glen Rice, who shifted to covering the
shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kobe can be a defensive stopper for our team,'' Rambis
said. ``I think he's done a pretty good job on Pippen, I think he's
putting a maximum effort into it, I think he's taking the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rambis is quick to point out that Houston's
offense is going through Charles Barkley and Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt about Bryant's ability now to dominate
both ends of the court. He entered the league in 1996 as a flashy
18-year-old with ankle-breaking moves and made-for-SportsCenter
dunks. Always the student, Bryant has not settled for being a
20-point scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher, drafted the same year as Bryant, noticed his
dedication to defense starting in last year's playoffs. At the
time, Pippen was shutting down Indiana Pacers point guard Mark
Jackson, and it was the talk of the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was something that Kobe took notice to,'' Fisher said,
``and I believe he started to really want to become a better
defender, not necessarily because of that, but I believe he saw how
a guy like Scottie Pippen, at his size, could affect a game
defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   So Bryant started asking to guard Lakers point guards in
practice to hone his skills.
</P>
<P>
   Then on opening night this season, inserted out of necessity
into the starting lineup against Houston, Bryant took on Pippen,
and the world saw the first indication that Bryant was no
one-dimensional star. He outscored Pippen 25-10 and held him to
4-of-18 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant had a long ways to go as an NBA defender, which was
clear when he moved to shooting guard at midseason and struggled to
slow the likes of Cleveland's Wesley Person and Philadelphia's
Allen Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   So he listened to veterans like Harper, he learned, he worked.
And improved immeasurably by season's end, finishing with 1.44
steals per game, fourth best among the league's top off-guards.
</P>
<P>
   Harper, veteran of 16 seasons and twice named to the
all-defensive second team, said Bryant has the ability _ and the
desire _ to be a first-teamer. Rambis agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``Kobe has taken all of the
constructive criticism that we've been giving him all year long and
used it. He wants to be the best basketball player possible. . . .
But he, like our team, hasn't even begun to play his best
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said he'd like to have a reputation like Jordan's, as a
complete player, though he realizes his offensive pyrotechnics will
prevent most people from recognizing his defense. For now, he's
just soaking up the moment, relishing every trip up the court
against Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun, it's challenging. Plus you learn a lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And all the more satisfying because of who he's shutting down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying to you,'' he said, ``if I said it didn't taste
good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
