<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ORIOLES-RIPKEN-NY     05-12 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-RIPKEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CAL RIPKEN, THE LAST HURDLE IS THE TOUGHEST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, Wayne Gretzky, John Elway . . . Cal Ripken?
</P>
<P>
   No, Ripken said, he is not ready to join those other great
athletes in retirement, but their retirement has caught his
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to be faced with retirement; you're going to be
faced with the same issue,'' the baseball member of that renowned
quartet said. ``It'd be great to sit down with those guys and
compare notes about some of the feelings you had leading up to it.
Ultimately what helped them make their decision.''
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 38 and saddled with a chronic back condition that
put him on the disabled list for the first time in his 18-year
career, Ripken may be forced to make his decision sooner rather
than later. But now is not the time, he said. Now is the time to
find out what a physically and mentally healthy Ripken can do for
the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by a two-game minor-league rehabilitation assignment,
Ripken stands poised to begin playing in the major leagues again.
He will rejoin the Orioles in Texas, eager to show the skeptics
that the Cal Ripken they saw in his first eight games of the
season, the one who batted .179 and made five errors, is not the
one they will see from here on.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the popular feeling in baseball circles is that
Ripken is nearing the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what you're picking up, everybody thinks he's just about
done,'' said one general manager, who like the others asked for
their assessment spoke on the condition that they not be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's on his last legs,'' another major league
executive said. ``As a productive player I don't think he has
anything left.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no 38-year-old player can perform the way he did as a
young man, and another general manager warned that Ripken has been
written off before and ``he's come back and played well.'' He
remains strong-willed, determined and focused, and he may be able
to get by on his experience and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ripken faces a significant physical hurdle. His condition
has been diagnosed as stenosis, or narrowing, of the spinal canal.
The pain that became the most disabling injury of his career
stemmed from a bone spur growing in the canal and irritating the
spinal cord. If the problem recurs, Ripken could need surgery,
which could end his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the injury is thrown in there and you're faced with that,
then all of a sudden your future becomes a little bit more
uncertain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken has the rest of the season to see how he progresses
physically, and determine if he wants to or can continue playing.
The Orioles don't have that luxury. They have two months to make a
critical decision. Ripken's contract has an option for next season
at a $6.3 million salary, and the Orioles must act on the option no
later than the All-Star Game, which is July 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles have Ryan Minor, their third baseman of the future,
waiting, but if they exercise the option rather than pay Ripken a
$2.5 million buyout, the Orioles, in effect, will commit themselves
not only to pay Ripken's salary but also to play him next season.
Some general managers believe they will exercise the option, but
only with the idea of paying Ripken for past services. However, no
talks have been held on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really haven't gotten into that,'' Frank Wren, the Orioles'
general manager, said Tuesday. ``That will be a big decision, one
we're not going to take lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ripken's mind, retirement talk is premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on a fair evaluation of my skills and my health prior to
the season, I thought I could count on a couple years,'' he said
one day last week, sitting in the dugout at Camden Yards. ``You
don't know until you actually do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this spring Ripken suffered a double blow in a short
period. His father, Cal Sr., died of lung cancer, and he had the
back injury. The combination, he said, contributed to his poor
performance in the early games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to arm yourself with your tools and go out there and
find out,'' he said, discussing the ability that might remain.
``Then you'll know yourself. You're being judged in front of all
these people, but nobody can make that judgment except you. A lot
of people have opinions. They think you should do it; they think
you shouldn't do it. But you're the one who has the expertise, and
you're the one who will ultimately make the judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken indicated that his chances of reaching 3,000 hits _ only
21 players have done it _ will not influence his decision. A
routine season would easily have catapulted him onto that plateau,
but in mid-May having only 5 hits of the 122 he needed does not a
routine season make.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers I look at now are pretty remarkable in my own
judgment,'' he said. ``I say I did all that and I'm still playing?
So I'm very satisfied with what has gone on. I've never had that
feeling that I had to get to 3,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers, he added, will end up where they end up, and he
won't look back with regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran into a lot of players toward the end of their careers
and I would ask do you have any regrets,'' Ripken said. ``Most of
them said I wish I would have taken care of myself better, I wish I
had played more, I wish I had taken it more seriously. Those are
the three things I definitely will not say when I'm done.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly does not need that credential to be elected to the
Hall of Fame. Another number, 2,632, will be recommendation enough.
That was the record number of games he played consecutively, of
course; it is the streak for which he will be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was proud of the streak, Ripken said: ``I'm proud of
what the streak symbolizes. Nobody can win a game by himself. You
rely on your teammates. The thing about playing every single day is
your teammates can count on you to be there. I feel extremely proud
that my teammates can count on me to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   How much longer they will be able to do that is the question of
the moment. When Ripken talked about Jordan, Gretzky and Elway, he
said he did not feel sad for them, that their careers were over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt sad for me, for the people that watch them,'' he said.
``I've thoroughly enjoyed watching them play. They've been able to
live their lives as full in their sports as they can. Everybody
should be envious of that. It's sad for the people who enjoyed
their talent and won't be able to see them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he feel flattered if, after he retires, people told him
they were sad? ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``What that would mean is
you did your hard work, your dedication, your perseverance, your
passion for the sport and you made an impression and somebody liked
watching you do what you do. That is one of the highest forms of
flattery.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
