</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DUKE-RESEARCH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHICS LAPSES AT DUKE HALT DOZENS OF HUMAN EXPERIMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By PHILIP J. HILTS with SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ Dozens of human experiments at Duke University
came to a halt Wednesday, surprising many members of the medical
staff as they arrived on a warm and flowering spring morning at the
huge medical center here.
</P>
<P>
   Duke on Tuesday became the third major research institution in
six months to have its research halted because of failure to meet
federal ethical rules. And Wednesday, the Office for Protection
from Research Risks, the agency that suspended the research,
expressed concern about another experiment last summer in which a
volunteer was injured.
</P>
<P>
   In that experiment, a volunteer briefly lost consciousness
during a space walk simulation at the university, prompting NASA,
which paid for the research, to suspend the study for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   A subsequent ethics review, a copy of which was provided to The
New York Times by NASA, raised serious questions about whether the
study subjects were adequately informed of the risks. ``We
investigated the protocols, procedures and we took corrective
actions,'' said Dr. Arnauld Nicogossian, NASA's associate
administrator in charge of life sciences research.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Dr. John Faletta, a pediatrician and chief of
the institutional review board that oversees the safety and ethics
of each human experiment proposed at Duke, said he did not know
that the volunteer's injury was supposed to have been reported to
the Office for Protection from Research Risks.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency's director, Dr. Gary Ellis, said Wednesday that
the reporting is required and described the omission as ``a serious
breach.'' Ellis said he had not been aware of it when the shutdown
was ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sort of revelation is consistent with the picture of
human subjects protection at Duke University Medical Center that
OPRR has pieced together through the last five months,'' Ellis
said. His office's decision to suspend Duke's federal license to
conduct medical research is only the fourth such move by the
government in nearly a decade. While Ellis cited a wide variety of
oversight lapses in experiments on human subjects, Duke officials
have characterized the problems as mostly administrative.
</P>
<P>
   The violations at Duke come at a time when there is a huge
increase in the number of experiments that need to be monitored, at
the same time universities are under strong budget pressure. As a
result, many universities have found themselves without the proper
manpower to thoroughly review each of the hundreds to thousands of
experiments conducted every year.
</P>
<P>
   In American research with human subjects, studies are proposed
by scientists and reviewed for safety and ethics at the university
or medical center by an institutional review board. The work of the
review boards is guided by federal regulations that define what
risks human may be subjected to and what kind of consent must be
obtained from the subjects, and what factors the boards must
consider in approving experiments.
</P>
<P>
   The Office for Protection from Research Risks is the federal
watchdog agency that checks up on human experiments and oversees
work of the review boards. But it has the equivalent of only three
investigators to cover the tens of thousands of experiments in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   At Duke alone, some 2,000 clinical experiments are being
conducted. Wednesday, all experiments stopped accepting new
patients, and each of the 2,000 experiments was being reviewed to
determine whether it should be halted altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators said that all experiments should be halted
unless they were giving significant therapeutic benefits to
patients during the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ralph Snyderman, the chief operating officer of the Duke
University Medical Center, said he did not yet know just how many
experiments would be stopped temporarily. Instead, he was working
to try to get the federal order reversed. He is to meet Thursday in
Maryland with officials of the the federal protection office.
</P>
<P>
   Snyderman said he would present a report to the office that
hoped would get the suspension lifted. He said the report would say
that the medical center was moving quickly to meet all the
potential violations of federal ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
   Snyderman said the problems cited at Duke are not just paperwork
or housekeeping. ``There was a serious misunderstanding on our part
of what they wanted and how fast they wanted us to do it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Duke and NASA officials emphasized Wednesday that the injury
during the space simulation experiment was not connected to the
government shutdown. But Ellis said that, in his mind, it ``raises
a concern about the possible nonreporting of other unanticipated
problems at the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   The injured man, who suffered a severe case of decompression
sickness, known as the bends, was in his 30s; his identity was not
disclosed. He signed up for a research experiment at the Center for
Hyperbaric Medicine and Environmental Physiology, an arm of the
Duke medical center.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment, which is also being conducted at two other
medical centers, one in Houston and another in Canada, is designed
to determine how much oxygen an astronaut would have to breathe
prior to taking a space walk, according to Dr. Richard Vann, the
principal investigator of the study at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Vann said the study subject had been
inside a hypobaric chamber, designed to simulate a space suit, for
two hours at a pressure equivalent to 30,000 feet above sea level
when he began to experience numbness and tingling in his legs. The
researchers took the man out of the chamber and treated him with
pure oxygen and he improved, but after the treatment he became
``briefly semiconscious,'' Vann said. He was treated again, and
then hospitalized overnight for observation, and has fully
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Decompression sickness occurs when nitrogen bubbles enter the
tissue and the bloodstream, causing a number of different symptoms,
usually mild joint pain., ``This was atypical in that he had
symptoms in his brain,'' Vann said. He said experts did not know
what caused the reaction, but that it was reported immediately to
the Duke Institutional Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   Vann described the incident as an ``unusually serious incident
of decompression,'' and said it was rare and unexpected. After it
occurred, NASA decided to stop the experiments at all three centers
and conduct a review of the study. In the report, a panel of
ethicists raised ``very serious'' concerns about the research,
including questions about whether it was adequately reviewed before
it began and whether the subjects were properly informed of the
risks.
</P>
<P>
   The study resumed in January, with new informed consent forms
and additional physical screening, including lung function tests,
for the participants.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said the investigation at Duke began last year when he and
and his staff began talking about the institutional review boards
at the 15 research universities that receive the most federal
money. Typically, these panels have frequent contact with Ellis'
agency, which oversees them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked the staff, can you vouch for these 15?'' he said,
adding, ``In 14 of the 15 institutions, the staff had had regular
contact.'' The fifteenth was Duke.
</P>
<P>
   So investigators scheduled a site visit for last December. They
cited a litany of problems, from questions about whether a quorum
was present when the panel passed judgment on medical experiments
to an apparent conflict of interest: one of the members voting on
the ethics of research was the Duke official responsible for
securing the grant money paying for the experiments.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators also found that, despite special requirements
to protect children involved in research, there was no evidence
that the review board had given any special consideration to
studies involving youngsters. And they found that the review panel
members were overwhelmed with work.
</P>
<P>
   The research protection agency asked Duke to take a number of
steps to correct the problems. But, Ellis said, ``their plans and
progress were simply inadequate,'' and so he decided to shut down
all federally-sponsored research programs at the university.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the collision between federal investigators and
the Duke research system, Faletta, the head of the Duke IRB and the
person who worked most with OPRR since the investigation began in
December, 1998, said he believed that the sense of urgency to
correct the problems at Duke did not hit home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably guilty of not being as articulate as I should
have been to the top administration at Duke; in pointing out the
need for change here,'' he said. His attempts to alert top
management at Duke went astray, because ``they were clearly not
attended to, and were not attended to because, I suspect, of
competing priorities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
