<HEADER>
A4944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-GIANTS13-C     05-12 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-GIANTS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves fall to ex-teammate, drop second series in row
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It came in a different setting _ wind-blown on
the California coast _ but this was a familiar foe.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Brock joined Paul Byrd and Jason Schmidt as ex-Braves to
beat their former team this season. Brock pitched 5.1 scoreless
innings in a 5-1 Giants win on Wednesday, struck out a career-high
six batters and brought the Braves' record against starters who are
former teammates to 3-4 on the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(San Francisco manager Dusty Baker) told me not to get too
excited, not to try to do anything I couldn't do,'' said Brock, who
was a question mark to start after battling the stomach flu on
Tuesday. ``Just pitch my game and that's what I tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock frustrated the Braves because he allowed eight baserunners
but none scored. Atlanta had seven hits off Brock and his fellow
Giant pitchers and drew eight walks, but left 13 runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a little bit of a sneaky fastball,'' said Braves
second baseman Bret Boone, whose career-long 14-game hitting streak
ended with an 0-for-3 day, including two strikeouts against Brock.
``Not that hard but he got some misses. He must have been doing
something right. He held us to what four hits? We've got to get
back to playing the way we were playing. We're in a little bit of a
lull.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have lost back-to-back series, after starting this
road trip without a series loss on the season. This was first time
they'd lost a series to the Giants since July of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Brock spent most of six years pitching as a starter in the
Braves' minor-league organization but never made a lasting
impression on the front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody made a big deal about it, but I'm more excited about
being in this rotation every fifth day,'' Brock said. ``I don't
have any problems with that team. They just didn't have any spots
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock gave up back-to-back walks to open the game but made his
statement for the game by striking out the heart of the Atlanta
order to end the inning. Ryan Klesko prevented a second shutout of
the season _ and second in four days _ with a solo homer in the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
