A4946 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES13-CO     05-12 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adjusting hitting stance aids C. Jones
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Chipper Jones' performance Tuesday night was
significant in a couple of ways. First, it was his hit that started
the Braves' 12th-inning rally and his run that scored on the
ensuing single from Andruw Jones to give the Braves their 9-8
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it was confirmation that some of the adjustments he made
in his swing in batting practice before Tuesday's game were paying
off. Jones, who had been struggling from the left side, said his
front leg had been collapsing, causing him to hit weak ground
balls. So with a little work in the cage, Jones was back out making
good contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was encouraging,'' said Jones, who finished the game with
two hits, two runs scored and one RBI. ``I hit the ball hard five
times.''
</P>
<P>
   He also decided to wear clear glasses _ as many of the Giants do
_ to help battle the wind. Jones, Andruw Jones and Brian Jordan all
wore them on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Monday night) it was unbearable, trying to hit Robb Nen with
your eyes watering,'' Jones said. ``It's a tremendous disadvantage
to have the wind blowing in your eyes when you're trying to focus
on something 60 feet away for 10 seconds. That's why you see guys
stepping out (of the batter's box) all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Double dose
</P>
<P>
   It's abundantly clear that this umpiring crew and the Braves are
not seeing eye to eye.
</P>
<P>
   Both manager Bobby Cox and Jordan spent the better part of
Tuesday night's game in the clubhouse _ Cox was ejected in the
first inning for throwing up his arms in reaction to a balk call.
He still was upset over a strike call on a checked swing. Jordan
was ejected four innings later after a confrontation with home
plate umpire Bruce Dreckman.
</P>
<P>
   Cox had been thrown out in the fifth inning on Monday night for
arguing a call on the basepaths. Cox has seen only six of the first
21 innings of the first two games of this series. He'll pay the
National League several hundred dollars in fines.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged it off Wednesday morning and promised to keep quiet
in the dugout for Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty warm in here, boys,'' Cox said laughing, as his
coaches complained about Tuesday night's wind and cold.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jordan's third ejection of his career. He said he was
upset because Dreckman stared him down a half-inning after his
complaint over a strike call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd made a little comment to him and it's over,'' Jordan said.
``Then I'm going out on the field, and he's staring me down. That's
(showing me) disrespect.''
</P>
<P>
   O. Perez after the fact
</P>
<P>
   Cox said Odalis Perez's nine-day layoff between starts did not
play a factor in his poor outing Tuesday night, when he gave up six
runs in the first inning to become the first Braves starter to do
that since Steve Avery in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balls down the middle, location _ he got hit,'' Cox said.
``Just like their guy.'' The Giants' Shawn Estes gave up four runs
in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Perez has had two poor starts in L.A. and San Francisco after
getting skipped in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to do my best; I was keeping the ball up, and
they were hitting it,'' said Perez, whose ERA climbed from 3.70 to
5.46. ``Ten days without pitching, it's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez was rescued by some good relief pitching; the bullpen
pitched 8 1/3 innings and gave up one run. Rudy Seanez walked in
the only run, and later said the windy conditions bothered him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get a good release point (on my breaking ball),''
Seanez said. ``But after that, instead of being down, we were fired
up, that we still had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Speier pitched 1 1/3 scoreless innings; Mike Remlinger
was charged with the one run on his two walks; Kevin McGlinchy
pitched three scoreless innings, and John Rocker dominated in the
11th and 12th to pick up his second victory.
</P>
<P>
   Matos debut
</P>
<P>
   Pascual Matos, called up as a backup catcher in Javy Lopez's
absence, made his major-league debut on Tuesday night as a pinch
hitter to lead off the 11th inning and struck out against Felix
Rodriguez. ``I felt OK in that situation,'' Matos said. ``I was a
little nervous. . . . I was looking for a slider, and he threw me a
fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
