<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leagues ending with flourish
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Manchester United drew a step closer to its fifth
English Premier League title of the 1990s in a scoreless draw with
lowly Blackburn Rovers on Wednesday, but also left the door open _
albeit slightly _ for defending champion Arsenal to reclaim the
crown.
</P>
<P>
   United picked up a point to go to 76 on the season, one more
than Arsenal, which stumbled in a 1-0 loss to Leeds on Tuesday. The
Red Devils can clinch with a win at home Sunday in the season
finale against Tottenham Hotspur. The best-case scenario for
Arsenal is to beat Aston Villa at home and hope for a United loss
or tie. Wednesday's result also relegates Blackburn, the 1995
champion, into the first division next season.
</P>
<P>
   The top five leagues in Europe are winding down with a flourish.
Bayern Munich wrapped up its 15th Bundesliga title Sunday and
Barcelona is closing in on the Primera Division crown in Spain, but
competition for Champions' League spots in both countries is
fierce.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, Lazio and AC Milan continue their winning ways, with
only a point separating them at the top of Serie A with two games
to go. Lazio has the tougher schedule, in league and out. After
playing at Fiorentina on Saturday, the Rome club meets Mallorca
next Wednesday in the Cup Winners' Cup final in Birmingham,
England. AC Milan has no such distractions, being out of Europe,
and on Saturday hosts relegated Empoli.
</P>
<P>
   Mallorca jumped into second place in Spain last weekend but must
play all three teams chasing it for automatic Champions' League
qualification _ Celta Vigo, Valencia and Real Madrid. Hertha
Berlin, Borussia Dortmund and FC Kaiserslautern are in contention
for the last two places from Germany after Bayer Leverkusen nailed
down second.
</P>
<P>
   Olympique Marseille can concentrate on its French first-division
title hopes after losing 3-0 to Parma on Wednesday in the finals of
the UEFA Cup in Moscow. Hernan Crespo and Paolo Vanoli scored
within 10 minutes of each other in the first half, and Enrico
Chiesa got a goal 10 minutes after halftime. Marseille, which
trails Girondins Bordeaux by a point with two weeks left in the
season, will get back four regulars who sat out the UEFA final
because of suspensions. Parma won its second UEFA Cup title in four
years; it was the eighth time an Italian team has won the
competition in the last 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   England: $1 million for Keegan
</P>
<P>
   Interim England manager Kevin Keegan, who initially said he
would remain loyal to second-division Fulham, is ready to sign a
deal with the Football Association worth an estimated $1 million a
year. Fulham president Mohamed Al-Fayed, the owner of Harrod's
department store, reportedly will be seeking $816,000 in
compensation. ... Bradford City qualified for the English Premier
League with a 3-2 win Sunday over the Wolverhampton Wanderers and
will be returning to the top flight for the first time since 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Inter Milan president resigns
</P>
<P>
   Inter Milan President Massimo Moratti, who has a 70 percent
stake in the club, resigned last week. Even though Moratti has gone
through four managers this season, Inter did not qualify for
Europe. Watch for a major roster overhaul with the exception of
Ronaldo, who said he wants to stay. ... Juventus midfielder
Zinedine Zidane underwent season-ending knee surgery Wednesday and
will miss France's next two Euro 2000 qualifying matches. He is
expected to return fully by August.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Playoffs begin
</P>
<P>
   A goal by Carlos Hermosillo on Sunday sent Necaxa into the
Mexican Torneo Verano playoffs that begin later this week. Necaxa,
which tied Tigres 1-1, joins Cruz Azul, Guadalajara, America,
Morelia, Atlas and either Santos or UAG in chasing favored Toluca,
which has the league's top goal-scorers. Jose Manuel Abundis and
Jose Saturnino Cardozo each collected 14 in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Africa: 2006 bids withdrawn
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria has followed Ghana and Egypt in pulling out of the
bidding for the 2006 World Cup to improve South Africa's chances,
but Morocco will stay in the hunt. FIFA boss Sepp Blatter favors
sending the event to Africa for the first time. England, Germany
and Brazil also have submitted bids. A decision will be made early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   MLS: Stadium unveiling on tape
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest events in the young history of Major League
Soccer won't be seen on live television because of the Stanley Cup
playoffs. ESPN2 has bumped its airing of Saturday night's
Columbus-New England game, which marks the opening of the Columbus
Crew Stadium, to an 11 p.m. tape-delay slot. The stadium is the
first major facility built specifically for soccer in the United
States in 77 years. ... The Crew will be missing U.S. national team
striker Brian McBride, who is out three to six weeks with a
fractured cheekbone. ... Kansas City, which won its first game of
the season last week, has scored just four goals. Two of them have
come from defender Alexi Lalas, an unlikely scoring source if there
ever was one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
