<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw)  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEC SWEEP UNCOVERS STOCK FRAUDS ON INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Companies are using the new medium of the Internet for the
old-fashioned task of separating investors from their money,
promising profits that seem too good to be true, and are according
to the Securities and Exchange Commission. Their practices were
revealed in an SEC enforcement action against 18 people and eight
companies in 14 cases of fraud _ the agency's third sweep in seven
months of Internet investment scams.
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD HEALTH PLANS ON THE MEND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oxford Health Plans has backed away from the brink of bankruptcy
by shedding thousands of loss-making members and raising premiums
for its customers. Dr. Norman Payson, Oxford's chief executive,
promises profits later this year, after operating losses in the
first six months. But even he says the makeover is a ``work in
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT IS SHAPING BRITISH CABLE
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is positioning itself as a dominant player in the
contest to revolutionize Britain's cable industry for the
oft-foretold era when the television cable delivers not just shows
but high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   DRABINSKY RESPONDS TO LIVENT SUIT
</P>
<P>
   In his first detailed response to the suit filed against him,
Garth H. Drabinsky, who founded Livent, said in court papers that
he had been too caught up producing Broadway musicals to have had
time to help keep the company's books, which have been found to be
false.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR 2000 LIABILITY BILL ADVANCES
</P>
<P>
   The House approved legislation to limit lawsuits arising from
Year 2000 computer failures. Although President Clinton has vowed
to veto the measure, the vote keeps the issue, and a possible
compromise, alive.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT RISES AT FEDERATED AND KMART
</P>
<P>
   Federated Department Stores, which owns Bloomingdale's. Macy's
and other department stores, and Kmart, the nation's second-largest
discount retailer, said that their first-quarter profits rose as
they sold more clothes and home furnishings and held down costs.
Shares of Federated rose $3.3125, to $54.3125, while shares of
Kmart fell 43.75 cents, to $17.125.
</P>
<P>
   BIDDING WAR ERUPTS FOR ONE 2 ONE
</P>
<P>
   Britain's smallest mobile phone company, One 2 One, has ignited
a bidding war between Europe's biggest telecommunication companies,
even though it has yet to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   LOEWEN IN BANKRUPTCY WARNING
</P>
<P>
   The Loewen Group reported a 77 percent drop in profit and warned
that creditors might force a sale or reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   USA NETWORKS ENDS BID FOR LYCOS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   USA Networks, the media company run by Barry Diller, officially
dropped its plan to buy Lycos, the Internet search service, because
of opposition from Lycos shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   MINIMUM WAGE INCREASE EXPECTED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congress will almost certainly raise the minimum wage this year,
probably to $6.15 an hour from $5.15, phased in over two to three
years. But does a higher minimum wage make economic sense? A
growing number of economists say yes, though there is reason for
Congress to move cautiously.
</P>
</TEXT>
