<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTION WITNESS PIERCES `BLUE WALL OF SILENCE'
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL) 
 (nk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The prosecutors called their next witness. Detective
Eric S. Turetzky entered the courtroom, an FBI agent at his side,
and nodded at the five defendants, all fellow New York City police
officers, who knew that what he was about to say might help send
them to prison for years.
</P>
<P>
   They did not return the greeting.
</P>
<P>
   The primary defendant, Officer Justin A. Volpe, the man accused
of thrusting a stick into the rectum of a handcuffed suspect,
smirked and shook his head as Turetzky raised his hand and swore to
tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky, 28, a thin, angular man with a narrow face, protruding
ears and a long mustache, had a pen neatly tucked away in his shirt
pocket. As he began his testimony, his responses were clear, crisp,
confident _ all business, all routine.
</P>
<P>
   But within 30 minutes, it was clear that Turetzky's appearance
Wednesday was more than just an electric moment in a sensational
case. It also marked a historic chapter for a Police Department
with a long record of ostracizing and mistreating officers who
report wrongdoing by their brethren.
</P>
<P>
   To his friends and family, Turetzky walked into the federal
court in Brooklyn to strike a blow against the ``blue wall of
silence.'' To them, he is an honest officer who could not close his
eyes to Abner Louima's pain and suffering, who felt compelled to
tell 12 jurors that Volpe walked through the 70th Precinct station
house after the alleged assault waving a broken stick ``like it was
a sword.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very, very proud of him,'' his grandmother, Anne
Rosenblum, 75, said in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support him for his courage and his honesty,'' said Sgt.
Eric Finkelstein, president of Shomrim, a society of Jewish police
officers to which Turetzky belongs. ``He told what he saw, and
that's what he's supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But to the defendants and their lawyers, Turetzky is an
opportunistic careerist. Marvyn M. Kornberg, a lawyer for Volpe,
made this clear as he began his cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detective Turetzky,'' Kornberg said, his voice loaded with
sarcasm. ``You have a gold shield now, don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   And how quickly, Kornberg asked, was he promoted to detective
after he cooperated with Internal Affairs? ``Eighteen months.''
</P>
<P>
   A Police Department spokeswoman disputed any suggestion that
Turetzky's promotion was linked to his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman, Officer Cheryl Cox, said Turetzky was
transferred from his patrol job in the 70th Precinct to a position
in the Internal Affairs Bureau soon after the alleged assault in
August 1997. Under department rules, Cox said, Turetzky was
automatically entitled to his promotion, in March, after completing
18 months as an Internal Affairs investigator. He has not received
any commendations or disciplinary complaints since transferring,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Turetzky did not respond to requests for comment made
through his family, his friend, Finkelstein, said the detective
never coveted a job in Internal Affairs but was sent there to
protect ``the integrity'' of the Louima investigation. Indeed, in
the weeks after Turetzky first emerged as a witness, he was placed
under police protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's doing the police work he's wanted to
do,'' Finkelstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The detective's friends and relatives said they did not know of
any reprisals against him.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, though, it appeared unlikely that Turetzky would
escape this case unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, Kornberg suggested to jurors that assignments
to Internal Affairs were reserved for officers of demonstrated
skill, experience and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about integrity,'' Kornberg said, starting a series
of questions about an incident early in Turetzky's career in which
he took a police motor scooter without authorization and then
crashed it. The detective acknowledged that he had failed to
mention this incident to his superiors in Internal Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   This followed an even more troubling admission. The night Louima
was arrested outside a Brooklyn nightclub, Turetzky was among the
police officers sent to control the unruly club crowd. At one
point, the detective testified, a woman refused his order to move
on. Laughing, she told him that he would never arrest her because
she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The detective recalled his ``foolish'' response: ``Arrest you?
I'll kick you in the stomach. Just move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers did not get a chance before day's end to
question Turetzky about this remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's your hero cop _ threatening to kick a pregnant woman
in the stomach,'' said Robert Volpe, the defendant's father.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
