r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DAVIS-LADN     05-12 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DAVIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS TO LEAVE UCLA FOR NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What was possible six months ago and probable two
months ago became official Wednesday, when UCLA sophomore guard
Baron Davis declared himself eligible for next month's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA has always been a dream,'' Davis said. ``One of my
dreams was to win a national championship. It hurts my heart to
leave that behind, but the NBA's there, and it's calling.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by his grandmother, Lela Nicholson, his sister, Lissa
Davis, and Bruins coach Steve Lavin, Davis told a large gathering
inside UCLA's Morgan Center that he struggled with the decision
until early this week.
</P>
<P>
   However, sources close to Davis said the unofficial decision
came months ago, in midseason, with his surgically reconstructed
left knee the only possible obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Davis came through with a dazzling stretch run that culminated
against Washington in the home finale, when he waved goodbye to the
crowd in the final seconds. He was named third-team All-American,
averaged 15.9 points and 5.1 assists, and delighted NBA scouts with
his energy, athleticism and skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus among the (NBA) people I talked to was Baron
could go as high as second (in the draft) and probably no lower
than sixth,'' Lavin said. ``I wouldn't want to be the general
manager that passes on him.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be a top-five pick next month, he'll become a millionaire
this summer, and he could land in Los Angeles. Both the Clippers
(through the draft) and the Lakers (through a trade) want him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to play for the Clips,'' he said. ``You all can get
tickets, you all can be at the games. As long as I'm there (in the
NBA), it doesn't matter where.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' departure leaves the sophomore-dominated Bruins with a
difficult schedule _ DePaul, Purdue, Gonzaga, Syracuse, North
Carolina _ and no proven point guard. Juniors Earl Watson and Ryan
Bailey will run the club, but neither has Davis' size and skill.
They're best-suited to a half-court attack, not the frenetic,
94-foot chaos Davis orchestrated last season.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' decision was no surprise to his teammates, who were
hoping for a return but anticipating a goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baron had to do what was best for Baron, and the timing was
right,'' Bruins forward Sean Farnham said. ``If you can be a
lottery pick, the money's too good to pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting update: The Bruins are close to signing Spencer
Gloger, a wing player from Santa Margarita High School.
</P>
<P>
   They also have emerged as a finalist for Artesia High forward
Jason Kapono, who was on campus Wednesday and attended Davis' press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two transfers, Duke center/forward Chris Burgess
and Oklahoma forward Ryan Humphrey, are considering UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, our recruiting emphasis is on frontcourt depth and
shooters to complement our inside players,'' Lavin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
