<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-12 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Scottish, Welsh Legislatures Convene
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish Parliament and the Welsh National Assembly, two new
legislatures whose members were elected last Thursday, convened in
Edinburgh and Cardiff. It is the first legislature ever in Wales
and the first since 1707 in Scotland. David Steel, leader of the
Liberal Party from 1976 to 1988, was chosen speaker of the Scottish
Parliament, but discussions on a similar post in Wales are still
going on
</P>
<P>
   Ireland: Apology For Abuses
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bertie Ahern issued a ``long overdue'' government
apology to victims of child abuse in Irish state and religious
institutions for ``our collective failure to intervene.'' The
apology and legislative proposals to regulate youth homes and
provide victims with forums for lodging complaints and seeking help
followed the broadcast of a television series documenting incidents
over four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: Catholic is Shot
</P>
<P>
   A 39-year-old Catholic was shot and seriously wounded as he
arrived for work at a construction site in a Protestant
neighborhood in County Antrim. The attack was attributed to
dissident Protestant paramilitaries opposed to the peace settlement
between Northern Ireland's warring religious communities.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey: New Problem for Lawmaker
</P>
<P>
   A Member of Parliament who was not allowed to take her oath of
office because she was wearing a Muslim head scarf was confronted
with a new obstacle. Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said the
legislator, Merve Kavakci, had been found to hold an American as
well as a Turkish passport and said it was now ``legally
impossible'' for her to enter Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Member Of Salinas Family Ends Appeal
</P>
<P>
   Paulina Castanon, the wife of Raul Salinas, brother of former
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari _ dropped an appeal of
witness-tampering charges against her and paid a $2,040 fine to
close the case. Mrs. Castanon insisted she was innocent but was
forced to accept her conviction because she needs treatment abroad
for hepatitis. A judge had barred her from leaving Mexico until the
case was settled.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil: Rights Advocate's Body Found
</P>
<P>
   A week after his disappearance was first reported, a leader of
the militant national movement of landless peasants has been found
shot to death in Para state, in the Amazon. Shortly before dropping
out of sight, Agripino Soares da Silva had led protests against the
government's land-distribution policy in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Gain for Independent Unions
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court struck down labor regulations prohibiting the
formation of independent unions at workplaces already represented
by an official union. Labor law experts called the ruling a blow to
Mexico's contract system, which has allowed employers to prevent
formation of more vigorous independent unions by signing secret
collective bargaining agreements with representatives of spurious
unions to block rival organizing drives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Students Step up Strike
</P>
<P>
   Student strikers who have shut down much of Mexico's National
Autonomous University, Latin America's largest institution of
higher learning, for three weeks threw up human blockades around
off-campus buildings where thousands of students are scheduled to
take final exams. The strikers are protesting a tuition increase.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan: Petition For Journalist Rejected
</P>
<P>
   A Lahore court dismissed a challenge to the arrest of Najam
Sethi, a prominent journalist who was taken into custody Saturday,
saying the case was outside its jurisdiction because Sethi was
detained by the army. An official statement said Sethi, an
outspoken critic of the government, had been charged with
``anti-state activities.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: Students Commemorate Killings
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of students rallied peacefully at Parliament and at
Trisakti University to commemorate the first anniversary of the
shooting deaths of four students at the university. The killings
set off riots that helped force the resignation of President
Suharto on May 21. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Philippines: Mummy to be Returned
</P>
<P>
   The elaborately tattooed and mummified remains of a 500-year-old
priest named Apo Annu will be returned next week from a Manila
museum to a cave in Benguet province from which it was stolen in
the 1920s. Tribal elders are preparing a feast and ritual that will
include the slaughter of dozens of pigs, chickens and carabao. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
