u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-1STLD     05-12 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER TESTIFIES AGAINST HIS PEERS IN BRUTALITY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS lede to reflect that defense has questioned Turetzky's
honesty.) 
 (nk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first police officer said to have come forward
with information about the Abner Louima case provided a vivid
account Wednesday of the scene at a Brooklyn station house,
testifying that one of the officers on trial emerged, agitated and
brandishing a stick, from a restroom area where prosecutors say
Louima was brutalized.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing as one of the prosecution's most important witnesses,
Detective Eric Turetzky said Louima's pants were ``down below his
knees'' as Officer Justin Volpe, his uniform in disarray and
holding a stick nearly three feet long, escorted Louima from the
restroom area of the 70th Precinct station house in Flatbush, where
Turetzky was an officer at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe took Louima to a holding cell, and ``frowning and hunched
over,'' walked by other officers and began swinging the stick
``like it was a sword and hitting it against the wall,'' Turetzky
testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just holding the stick and displaying it to us, waving
it in the air and banging it against the wall,'' Turetzky said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have said that Turetzky broke what they feared
would be a blue wall of silence by being the first to come forward
with significant information against the officers suspected of
being involved in the August 1997 incident.
</P>
<P>
   Four officers are accused of violating Louima's civil rights by
beating him in a police car. Two of them _ Volpe and Charles
Schwarz _ are also accused of torturing Louima, a 32-year-old
Haitian immigrant, in the restroom by ramming the stick into his
rectum and then his mouth, inflicting severe internal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky's statements Wednesday ended a day of testimony that
included the wrap-up of questioning of Louima, and the appearance
on the stand of a cousin of Louima who was at the scene outside a
Flatbush nightclub where Louima was arrested in a street brawl.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Turetzky said that Volpe did not speak to him
or to other officers after he came by waving the stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was very unusual,'' because normally Volpe was
``very outgoing and usually, like, the center of attention,''
Turetzky, 28, said in brisk, steady tones in federal court in
Brooklyn, as Volpe and the other officer on trial watched him,
expressionless, from the defense table.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Turetzky said, he saw Volpe walked back toward
the restroom and toward some unused cells near it, and that when
Volpe returned, he no longer had the stick, which Turetzky
described as part of a broken broom or mop handle, dark green or
blue.
</P>
<P>
   The stick has not been found. Prosecutors say Volpe used it to
tear Louima's rectum and rupture his bladder, and that Louima
required two months in the hospital and three operations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Turetzky was not inside the restroom when Volpe
allegedly attacked Louima with the stick while Schwarz allegedly
held him down, his account places both officers with Louima around
the time of the alleged attack.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky also gave major testimony incriminating Schwarz, who,
like Volpe, denies that he took part in any assault on Louima in
the station house restroom or, as the prosecution also charges, in
a police car.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky said that he had seen Schwarz leading Louima to the
restroom area not long before he saw Volpe taking Louima away from
there.
</P>
<P>
   He said that at the time Schwarz was taking Louima toward the
restroom area, Louima appeared to be bleeding from his lip and
possibly from a second facial cut, and his pants were already
``down below his knees,'' where they had fallen while Schwarz had
searched him at the station house's main desk.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that Louima's hands were cuffed behind him, Turetzky said
that Schwarz was raising the prisoner's ``rear-cuffed'' hands so
that Louima's arms were behind him in what Turetzky described as
``chicken wing fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Louima was tiptoeing and being shuffled along,'' the
witness told the jury under questioning by one of the prosecutors,
Loretta E. Lynch, chief assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution says that the two other officers on trial,
Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese, joined Volpe and Schwarz in beating
Louima in the patrol car between his arrest outside the nightclub
and the time he was brought into the 70th Precinct station house.
The prosecutors say that the officers mistakenly thought that
Louima had punched Volpe during the melee.
</P>
<P>
   A sergeant, Michael Bellomo, is also on trial, charged with
trying to cover up the alleged beating in the police car. The
officers and the sergeant all say that the charges against them are
untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the late hour when Ms. Lynch ended her questioning of
Turetzky, Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn M. Kornberg, had time for
relatively few questions as he began his cross examination.
Kornberg suggested that Turetzky had been motivated by ambition to
give his account, noting that he had recently been promoted to
detective after only four years on the police force.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among other police officers expected to testify as witnesses are
Officer Mark Schofield, who has reportedly told investigators that
on the morning of the alleged attack, he had lent Volpe a pair of
gloves that were returned to him soiled.
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of his two and a half days on the witness
stand, Louima was cross-examined by Wiese's lawyer, Joseph
Tacopina, and Bellomo's, John Patten. They brought up various
discrepancies in the accounts Louima has given to federal and state
investigators since his encounter with the officers, and Patten
suggested that Louima had continued lying to investigators even as
he tried to undo a major lie that he has admitted to.
</P>
<P>
   The lie, he testified last week, had been his statement that
during the alleged attack, one of the officers had told him, ``It's
Giuliani time!''
</P>
<P>
   When he acknowledged the lie while on the witness stand last
week, he said the statement had not been made and that he had been
advised to say it by a supporter. But Wednesday Patten asked Louima
if he was aware that the supporter ``denies he told you about
`Giuliani time.' '' Louima repeated that the man had given him the
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Louima's cousin, Yves Nicholas, testified that he, not Louima,
had punched Volpe during the street brawl that began the chain of
events, saying he acted because he believed Volpe had pushed Louima
to the ground and was arresting him without justification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
