<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-LOUIMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: ONE CLIENT NO ONE WANTS TO DEFEND: THE LAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL, NY-LOUIMA-SCENE) 
 (nk) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Abner Louima case has inspired diverse emotions,
but there is one feeling shared by New Yorkers of every race, class
and political persuasion. We all cringe at the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers defending the police officers charged with
brutalizing Louima suggested to the jury that Louima's internal
injuries resulted from homosexual sex, but they studiously avoided
giving Louima, a married father of two, a chance to address that
claim on the stand this week. Their other questions to him were so
aggressively boorish that they were repeatedly admonished by the
judge.
</P>
<P>
   They further burnished their profession's image by accusing
Louima's former lawyers of inventing the lie he once told about a
police officer's telling him, during the alleged attack, that it
was ``Giuliani time.'' Completing the courtroom spectacle were
Louima's current lawyers, whose previous tactics in defense of O.J.
Simpson appalled so many people, and who are now rewarded with a
chance to make millions from Louima's civil suit.
</P>
<P>
   No one, of course, is surprised by anything lawyers do. The
public expects even less of lawyers than of journalists. In a
Gallup/CNN/USA poll last October, only 14 percent of Americans gave
lawyers high marks for honesty and ethical standards, which ranked
them below every other category except insurance salesmen,
advertising practitioners and car salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers don't have such miserable reputations in other
countries, and they weren't always so reviled in the United States
either. Two decades ago, a Gallup poll rated them more honest than
most other professionals. What's changed?
</P>
<P>
   ``The public resents the money and power that lawyers have
gained,'' said Scott Turow, the criminal lawyer and best-selling
writer whose next novel is about a corrupt litigator. ``People now
march into the courtroom to resolve ethical and moral conflicts
that used to be decided in churches and schools and communities.
Cases like Louima's become forums for resolving social problems,
and when people are unhappy with the outcome, they blame the
lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter K. Olson, a senior fellow at the Center for Legal Policy
at the Manhattan Institute, has analyzed several common hypotheses
for lawyers' unpopularity, starting with what he calls the dentist
theory: because lawyers are required to deal with disputes and
other unhappy situations, people associate lawyers, like dentists,
with pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the dentist theory is that dentists actually
aren't that unpopular,'' said Olson, the author of ``The Litigation
Explosion'' (1991). ``They do much better than lawyers in polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Another hypothesis is what Olson calls the bartender theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyers say they have to behave badly because their clients
demand it,'' he said. ``According to this theory, criticizing
lawyers for the ugly tactics in the Simpson or the Louima cases is
like blaming a bartender for serving drinks to customers who are
falling off their stools. If he didn't do it, they'd just take
their business to another bar.''
</P>
<P>
   There's some truth to this theory, Olson believes, but it
doesn't explain the rising public anger with lawyers. He attributes
that anger chiefly to laws and procedures adopted since 1970 that
give lawyers new chances to sue and new weapons in court. President
Clinton's outrage at the questions he was forced to answer during
Paula Jones' sexual harassment case has been shared by countless
other Americans affected by new laws and liberalized discovery
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyers have more power than ever to ruin your life,'' Olson
said. ``They can come up with the most fantastic excuses to sue.
They can make outrageous charges in court without worrying about
libel. They can bankrupt you with endless motions and depositions
and demands for files. There's no constraint on their
viciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers in most other industrialized countries are constrained
by rules forcing the loser of a case to pay the other side's
expenses. America's lawyers have fought off attempts to impose a
loser-pays policy here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you think of any other occupation with that kind of
immunity for mistakes?'' Olson said. ``If you're a lawyer, you can
cost someone a fortune and ruin their reputation and cause them
sleepless nights for five years. Then, when they finally prove they
never did anything wrong, you don't owe them anything. You can just
stroll away to look for someone else to pick on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
