<SLUG> BC-OXFORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OXFORD HEALTH'S TURNAROUND IS STILL A WORK IN PROGRESS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a year on the turnaround track, Oxford Health Plans has
backed away from the brink of bankruptcy by shedding thousands of
loss-making members and raising the premiums paid by the customers
who remained. But the big managed care company is still reporting a
substantial cash-flow loss on operations and still struggling with
the dysfunctional computer systems that nearly sank the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not out of the woods yet,'' said Arun Kumar, a
health-care analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Norman Payson, Oxford's upbeat chief executive, promises
shareholders profits later this year, after operating losses in the
first six months. With the sale of its New York Medicaid business,
the company reported a small profit. But even Payson, who was named
chairman Wednesday, says the makeover is still a ``work in
progress'' on several important fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Oxford has to fix its computer systems, which still
don't talk to each other and require expensive human intervention
to match clients' claims with the three-year-old ``new'' system
that tracks everything else. The stakes are enormous: the danger of
``mistakenly mispricing premiums,'' was the worst case example
cited by Payson, 51, in an interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another hazard could be overpaying some bills. Oxford is still
trying to recover more than $100 million of the $276 million it
advanced to hospitals and doctors in the dark days of 1997 when it
completely lost control of its accounts. Payson said Oxford
intended to improve its existing information systems, rather than
start over or contract out the work. It has added 140 software
``enhancements'' this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The health maintenence organization raised its premiums 9.8
percent, on average, for the big employers whose year started Jan.
1. It seeks similar increases from small businesses and
individuals, helped by an industrywide upswing in rates. But
consultants say Oxford's rates are already above its competitors,
reflecting the costs of dealing with its huge network of more than
45,000 doctors and 200 hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford has to walk a tightrope, raising rates to cover costs and
profits without becoming too expensive and losing customers.
Membership has dropped by 400,000 to 1.69 million from 2.1 million
in the 12 months ended March 31. That was both good news and bad
news, financially. Most of the attrition was in its unprofitable
Medicaid and Medicare business plus 50,000 nongovernmental
customers spread thin in states Oxford no longer serves. But the
company also lost 100,000 members in its core business in New York,
New Jersey and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, costs are a moving target. ``Most managed care
companies' costs are growing 5 percent or 6 percent,'' said Kenneth
C. Abramowitz, an HMO specialist at Sanford C. Bernstein. ``If you
are raising premiums 10 percent, you're in pretty good shape. But
you have to make sure costs for hospitals, physicians and drugs are
growing only 5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   All the HMOs are engaged in tough negotiations with the
hospitals. Payson said some hospitals had agreed to work more
closely with Oxford on deciding when a patient is ready to be
discharged. ``We are not all exactly of one mind frame,'' he said.
Hospital officials say there has been a steep increase in the
number of denials of payment by Oxford and other big managed care
companies in New York.
</P>
<P>
   As for the doctors, Oxford is in arbitration with 14
associations of New York physicians, headed by the New York County
Medical Society, on complaints about late or inadequate payments.
The state insurance department has fined Oxford twice for late
payments under a new law.
</P>
<P>
   Payson said Oxford had made ``extraordinary progress'' in paying
doctors and hospitals promptly. ``With 70,000 claims a day, it is
easy to have difficulty with certain categories,'' he said.
Payson's progress reports have helped revive Oxford's share price,
and that has been good for him as well.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford slipped 3.125 cents a share Wednesday to $20.96875, but
that is more than triple its low of $6.81 last August. When he
accepted a four-year contract a year ago, he invested $10 million
at $15.52 per share, when the market price was over $18. Last
August, when the stock hit bottom, Payson began buying again _ two
million shares at $6 to $8 each.
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, Oxford awarded him two million options, which
can be exercised at $15.52 each and one million more at $6.0625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
