<SLUG> BC-NY-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC UNIONS FIND VOICE IN MARCH BY CITY HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In one of this city's biggest labor rallies in
decades, tens of thousands of union members marched past City Hall
on Wednesday to demand that the city and state spend part of their
budget surpluses on higher wages and on programs that help working
families, like education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   The rally sought to signal Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov.
George Pataki _ at a time that both appear to be showing interest
in higher office _ that they will have a huge fight on their hands
if they do not revamp their budgets more to labor's liking.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration, held on Broadway, 150 yards west of City
Hall, also sought to send a strong message that New York's labor
movement is alive, newly vocal and united after years of disarray
and an embarrassing corruption scandal at District Council 37, the
city's largest municipal union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is just a beginning,'' said Denis Hughes, the new
president of the State AFL-CIO. ``We are going to mobilize this
movement like never before. We are going to be in the streets like
never before. We are going to be on the phones like never before.
They're going to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the demonstration, which sometimes resembled a pep
rally, aimed to show union members _ and not just politicians _ how
strong labor can be. Officials with the New York City Central Labor
Council, the umbrella group representing all the city's unions,
estimated that 50,000 union members participated, while the Police
Department put the figure at 25,000 to 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   But union leaders and the police both said it was hard to count
the crowd because thousands of workers were still marching toward
the rally at 6 p.m., as thousands of others were leaving for the
subways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to see today not as the culmination of our effort, but
as the beginning of a movement,'' said Dennis Rivera, president of
the city's largest union, a 150,000-member grouping of health-care
workers known as 1199. ``We have to be about the business of
changing the political agenda in New York so that the working
people and families of our state come first.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders and foot soldiers alike complained that city workers had
made considerable sacrifices, like taking a two-year pay freeze.
But now that the city has a $2 billion budget surplus and the state
a $3 billion surplus, they said, the workers should share in the
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Loudspeakers lined Broadway from Park Row to Canal Street, and
for more than 90 minutes union members inched south, often 10
abreast, slowed by a maze of metal police barricades.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of teachers wore blue T-shirts reading, ``All Roads
Lead to a Fair Share for Working Families.'' Signs carried an array
of messages: ``Zeros won't feed my kids,'' ``Fed up, Stand up,''
and Pataki ``cuts $2.1 billion out of health care to pay for tax
cuts for billionaires.''
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders said the rally had the broadest support of any New
York City labor demonstration in at least 15 years, since it
brought together police officers _ who rarely demonstrate with
other unions _ teachers, construction workers, bridge painters,
nurses' aides, correction officers, transit workers and the
120,000-member District Council 37.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker after speaker said the mayor and governor should use
their budget surpluses not for tax cuts for the rich but instead
for better wages for government workers and for programs that help
middle-class families. Several labor leaders, as well as several
Democratic politicians at the rally, asserted that the city and
state should not be stingy with government workers after they
sacrificed to help create the budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McLaughlin, the president of the Central Labor Council,
insisted that the rally should put forth a positive agenda and not
attack the mayor or governor. But other leaders ignored those pleas
and lambasted both men, saying that the mayor and governor should
reconsider proposed cuts in projected education spending and that
Pataki should rescind contemplated health-care cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Randi Weingarten, president of the 95,000-member United
Federation of Teachers, said: ``Mr. Mayor and Mr. Governor, don't
talk to us about budget cuts and tax cuts and work-force cuts. We
heard enough of that when times were bad. But times aren't bad
anymore. So what's your excuse now? It's time to give our families
their fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news briefing Wednesday, Giuliani insisted that the city
should give raises only if unions agree in return to do extra work
or increase productivity in some other way. He said it was wrong
for elected leaders to give things away to unions without getting
anything. ``The age and the day of the giveaway should be over,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
