<SLUG> BC-COLO-MOSQUE-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO MAN IS SUSPECTED OF PLANNING MOSQUE ATTACK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A 39-year-old man who the police say intended to
``incinerate'' Colorado's largest mosque, was arrested Wednesday
after fleeing the site in a car loaded with bomb-making materials,
four guns and 1,000 rounds of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an enemy against the Islamic nation, and I was going to
take care of business,'' the Arapahoe County Sheriff's Office
quoted the man, Jack M. Modig, as saying.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Modig has expressed support for the far-right,
anti-government philosophy espoused by the Freemen group in
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Modig tried to ram three police cruisers during
a seven-mile chase from the suburban mosque to his rooming house in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   When taken into custody, Modig was dressed all in black _
``black T-shirt, black trouser and black combat boots,'' according
to a press release from the sheriff's office. In his car, he had a
black ski mask and black military-style clothing _ a vest and a
coat, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the mosque, Talib Syed, said the mosque, which
is called the Islamic Center and is located southeast of Denver,
drew about 500 people every Friday for prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Modig was charged with possession of explosive devices, carrying
concealed weapons, eluding a police vehicle and three counts of
attempted vehicular assault. He is being held on $500,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   The police said a search of Modig's car turned up two
semi-automatic pistols, a shotgun, a rifle, two machetes, a
survival knife and ample ammunition for all the firearms, as well
as bomb-making materials including three 10-gallon cans filled with
gasoline, bleach, electrical tape, flares, batteries, electrical
wiring and ``cheese cloth for fuses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our belief, based on our investigation, that he was
going to incinerate the Islamic Center,'' Capt. Phil Spence, the
sheriff's spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's office said Modig had a history of contacts with
law-enforcement agencies in Colorado. In 1992, he volunteered to be
an informant in four homicide investigations in western Colorado.
Last summer, he was ``escorted'' out of the State Capitol after he
tried to contact Bill Owens, who was then state treasurer. Last
fall, Owens was elected governor. Three months ago, Modig was
charged with driving under the influence and possession of narcotic
equipment in Gilpin County, 30 miles west of here.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1995, Modig was one of the first of about 150
Coloradans who signed a petition supporting the formation of a
``common law court'' in northern Colorado. The political movement
for these unofficial courts reached its apex the following summer
with the siege of the Freemen's compound in northern Montana.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver area has experienced several nativist attacks on
immigrant Muslims and the mosque in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In separate attacks over the last 18 months, gangs have killed
two immigrant men who prayed at the mosque. The police labeled the
killings hate crimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
