<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REED HANGS TOUGH AND METS' BATTERS HELP CHASE THOMSON TO THE
MINORS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The pitching line was not particularly pretty. Nor was
the bruise above Rick Reed's right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed on Wednesday became the Mets' first starting pitcher in
four games to allow fewer than eight earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   And because the Mets scored six runs in the first two innings
off John Thomson, a pitcher who was optioned to the minor leagues
after the game, the four runs in five innings that Reed was charged
with were hardly enough for the Colorado Rockies to catch the Mets
in a 10-5 victory at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, their second in the last eight games, enabled the
Mets to avert a three-game sweep at the most dangerous park to
pitch in in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   It was also good enough for Reed to pick up his third victory in
four decisions, coming only three days after he had surrendered
eight runs in one and two-thirds innings of an 11-6 loss in Arizona
on Sunday, the outing that led to the string of eight-run starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always hurts when you lose,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in this case, sometimes even when you win.
</P>
<P>
   Reed took a second-inning line drive just above his right
hamstring. He recovered in time not only to throw out Angel
Echevarria at first base, but also to pitch five solid innings.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McRae also took one for the team, running face-first into
a portion of the fence in right-center field in the fifth inning
while hanging on to Todd Helton's blast. McRae played three more
innings before leaving the game.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, both Reed and Manager Bobby Valentine credited
McRae's amazing catch, which saved a run, with helping to save the
game, even though the score was 10-2 after the drive resulted in a
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The question was, who hurt more, Reed or McRae?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably him,'' Reed said. ``He ate half that pad on the
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick,'' McRae countered. ``He got bruised. I don't have
bruises.''
</P>
<P>
   As a team, the Mets have a lot of bruises. Bobby Bonilla and
Rickey Henderson are on the disabled list, and the Mets (19-15)
announced Wednesday that Bobby Jones would take an extra day of
rest and next pitch on Monday, not Sunday, because of a tender
right elbow. Orel Hershiser gets the start Sunday instead.
</P>
<P>
   Jones allowed eight earned runs on Tuesday night, as the Mets
dropped their third straight game. After their starters had allowed
33 runs in 241/3 innings over the first five games of this
nine-game trip _ 33 runs in 181/3 innings, excluding Masato
Yoshii's six scoreless innings last Saturday _ the Mets were
looking for a lift from Reed on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It helped when the Mets scored three runs in the first inning on
a run-scoring single by Mike Piazza and a two-out, two-run double
by Robin Ventura. It helped even more when they scored three runs
in the second on a two-run double by Edgardo Alfonzo and a
run-scoring double by Piazza to give Reed a 6-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno, who had four hits, scored in the first and second
innings and scored three runs in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Reed pitched well enough and long enough to take a 10-1 lead
into the fifth inning, when he allowed three runs, the last two on
Dante Bichette's home run, his fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a really good day,'' Valentine said of his
right-hander. ``Pitching lines here are really difficult to
judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed agreed. ``Under the circumstances, I thought I pitched
pretty good,'' he said. ``It seems like every start I have they
give me a lead to work with, which to me is awesome, especially
here. This is a place where you can't score enough runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza said: ``He was aggressive. He got touched for a couple of
home runs, but that happens here. It was a great game, actually.
I've seen some games here I just can't describe.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed found it difficult to describe the pain he felt when
Echevarria's liner smacked his right buttock where it meets the
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby asked me if the ball was OK,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hina, the Mets' trainer, said: ``All Rick said to me was:
`Get away, Fred. There ain't nothing you can do.' I said, `I know,
but at least I can give you a few minutes to let the sting wear off
a little bit.' And then Rick said, `I think that one's going to
leave a mark.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could afford a couple of laughs as they made their way
to Philadelphia for a three-game series that starts Friday night.
They had driven in runs early, and received enough pitching, to win
for only the second time in six games on this trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
