<SLUG> BC-NJ-OFFICER-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ADMITS SLAYING NEW JERSEY POLICEWOMAN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ The fourth man taken into custody in the
turbulent investigation into the shooting death of a policewoman
last month pleaded guilty Wednesday to the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Condell Woodson, 25, also pleaded guilty to robbery and weapons
possession charges. Sentencing was set for June 29.
</P>
<P>
   The plea was an abrupt conclusion to the case, which has
provoked a tangle of lawsuits and state and federal investigations
stemming from the alleged beating of the first man arrested, who
turned out to be innocent, and the death of another man taken in
for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said off the record that Woodson had confessed to
relatives that he had shot Officer Joyce Anne Carnegie when she
stopped him on the street in Orange in connection with a robbery
investigation. The investigators also said that a 9-millimeter
pistol used in the shooting belonged to Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Krakora, one of Woodson's lawyers, said that the plea
agreement would probably result in a sentence of life in prison
without the possibility of parole. Without that plea agreement, he
said, Woodson would ``inevitably'' have faced the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement announcing the plea, Essex County Prosecutor
Patricia A. Hurt said the plea agreement ``mandates'' that Woodson
will not be eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   In pleading guilty, Woodson told Judge Betty Lester that his gun
had gone off accidentally when Carnegie stopped him and tried to
arrest him for a spate of robberies around downtown Orange. Police
investigators said at the time that Carnegie was shot in the
abdomen and the head in the confrontation and had not had a chance
to draw her weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson, the son of a career military man, grew up on military
bases in New Jersey, Hawaii and Virginia. He was an honor student
and gifted athlete at Orange High School. But in later years he
struggled to hold jobs and was convicted of a variety of drug,
weapons, robbery and assault charges. In recent years he lived in
Cordele, Ga., and last year was sentenced to three months in a
Georgia boot camp for robbery and assault.
</P>
<P>
   In March, he returned to Orange, where his mother lives.
</P>
<P>
   In the hunt for the killer, investigators first arrested
Terrance Everett, 24, and held him for six days before concluding
that he was innocent. Everett, who suffered bruises and a black eye
when he was arrested, has said he plans to sue the law enforcement
agencies and the town.
</P>
<P>
   Another man, Earl Faison, 27, was picked up because he bore a
resemblance to descriptions of Carnegie's killer. He died while in
police custody, and his family, too, is preparing a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state agencies are investigating both arrests.
</P>
<P>
   James Coker, 29, was also picked up during the investigation. He
was subsequently cleared of any involvement in Carnegie's shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
