<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLIN-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLIN SELLING CAPITALS AND SHARE OF THE WIZARDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (rk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Abe Pollin, who poured millions of dollars into
sports franchises that usually let him down by season's end,
announced Wednesday that he was selling outright his hockey team,
the Washington Capitals, and a minority interest in his other
holdings, which include the Washington Wizards basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   The price was not disclosed _ ``We never talk about money,''
Pollin said at a news conference _ but it appeared that a
partnership that will make the purchase was investing $200 million
now with more to come in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Pollin, who is 75, said that both his health and personal
finances were in good shape but that his two sons had told him they
did not want to follow him into the sports business. The recent
basketball lockout did not affect his decision, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The principal member of the partnership that is making the
purchase, Ted Leonsis, is a billionaire Internet executive and
sports buff who has a full-size basketball court at his house.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he was making the investment, Leonsis said: ``Because
I can. I love competition. I went to Georgetown University. I was a
Hoya.'' He is a sports fan from Brooklyn who used to root for the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Leonsis is an executive at America Online, but he said that
there would not be any connection between his sports and computer
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Pollin and his wife, Irene, have been known in Washington for
their community activity and he said that the sale would allow them
more time _ and more money _ for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have decided to spend a little less time with sports and
more with folks less fortunate than I am,'' Pollin said at the news
conference, which was held on the Wizards' practice court in the
MCI Center, an arena he built two years ago with $200 million of
his own money in downtown Washington. His immediate concerns, he
said, were a major campaign by Unicef for relief in Kosovo and
helping Washington's homeless.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he was selling now, he answered, ``First, we did
not want a repeat of the mess the Redskins went through with their
transition.''
</P>
<P>
   His reference was to the disposition of the Washington football
team after the death of its owner, Jack Kent Cooke. The trustees of
the Cooke estate sold the team to one group, only to have the deal
fall apart when it became clear that the owners in the NFL would
not approve the buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither Pollin nor Leonsis would say how much the
partnership was paying, Leonsis was asked if it was $200 million
and he answered: ``That's a good number.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Leonsis' partners, Jonathan J. Ledecky, confirmed the
$200 million estimate and, after Leonsis had declined to provide
the breakdown of the new partnership, Ledecky suggested that
Leonsis' share was 60 percent, his own 30 percent and that of Dick
Patrick, president of the Capitals, 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pollin remains the majority partner in Washington Sports, which
owns the Wizards and the MCI Center, and said he hoped to bring
another basketball championship to Washington. He said that he
expected the new partnership to eventually invest enough to obtain
full ownership of his properties _ the two teams, the MCI Center
and Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Pollin's son Robert, a professor of economics at the University
of Massachusetts, Amherst, confirmed later that neither he nor his
brother, Jim, who runs a travel business, wanted to follow Pollin
as the teams' owners.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his father's holdings made economic sense, he
said: ``Yes. He's got a lot of debt, but he's doing OK''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
