A5129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-BERENDES-NYT &LR;      05-12 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BERENDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINZ WERNER BERENDES, 74, PIONEER IN CARE OF NEWBORNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   (bl)  
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Heinz Werner Berendes, a pediatrician and medical
epidemiologist for the National Institutes of Health who pioneered
studies of birth-control safety and the care of newborns, died May
6 at the NIH Clinical Center in suburban Maryland. He was 74 and
lived in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was prostate cancer, said the National Institute of
Child Health and Human Development, where he was a senior
investigator. Berendes directed the perinatal research branch and
the groundbreaking Collaborative Perinatal Project, the largest
such effort this country.
</P>
<P>
   The project spawned hundreds of research papers 40 years ago,
and remains an important source of data on pregnancy and child
development. Berendes also led more recent studies for the World
Health Organization and made evaluations intended to improve the
care of expectant mothers and their newborns in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Dortmund, Germany, Berendes earned medical doctorates at
the Universities of Goettingen and Munich. He started a career as a
child psychiatrist in Germany but came to this country in 1953 and
later added a master's degree in epidemiology from Johns Hopkins
University.
</P>
<P>
   After joining the institutes of health in 1960, he was chief of
the perinatal branch from 1960 to 1973 and headed the contraceptive
evaluation branch from then until 1979. He successively held top
positions in contraceptive evaluation, the epidemiology and
biometry research program and, until last year, the Division of
Epidemiology, Statistics and Prevention Research.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, he took over the epidemiology and statistics program.
Under his direction, the program grew into a world leader in the
field of reproductive epidemiology.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he held academic appointments at Howard University
Medical School, Johns Hopkins and George Washington Universities.
He served as a consultant to numerous agencies, published some 120
scientific papers, sat on many committees and task forces and was
on the editorial board of the American Journal of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   Berendes is survived by his wife, Dr. Michele Forman; their son
David M., also of Bethesda; a son and daughter by an earlier
marriage, Christoph M., of Washington, and Andrea Harmer, of
Novato, Calif., and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
