<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NIGHT THE KNICKS DID EVERYTHING PERFECTLY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pat Riley was staring off into the distance as he sat
quietly on the bench. The Heat had imploded at the feet of the
cackling Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a surreal 32-2 run that began at the end of the second
quarter and carried over into the third, the Knicks overwhelmed the
Heat to take Game 3, 97-73, Monday night at Madison Square Garden.
The Heat, which missed its first 17 3-pointers, is on the verge of
elimination as the Knicks took a 2-1 lead in this
three-of-five-game playoff series. Game 4 will be at the Garden on
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell led the Knicks with 20 points. Allan Houston
shook off flu symptoms and added 18 while Patrick Ewing chipped in
15. Alonzo Mourning led Miami with 18.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere was electric as the game began. The Knicks
matched the crowd's intensity and generated their own craziness as
they ended the first half on a 12-0 run and held a 45-37 lead at
the break. That run extended to 19-0 as the third quarter began and
the Knicks led by 18 points. Incredibly, the Knicks just kept on
coming and took a 63-39 lead with 6:30 left in the third to cap a
mind-blowing 32-2 run.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat, falling apart at the seams, had scored just one field
goal in 12 minutes until Jamal Mashburn hit a jumper with four
minutes left in the third. The Heat managed to find a couple of
baskets but that was hardly enough as the Knicks overwhelmed them
to take a 73-48 lead after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was clicking to absolute perfection for the Knicks.
Although Houston spent most of the day in bed with flu symptoms,
taking Advil and swilling fluids, he shook off his ills and hit
four of seven shots to score a team-leading 11 points in the first
half. And although Ewing was in obvious pain from his sore
Achilles' tendon and was limited in defending against Mourning, who
scored 13 first-half points, he found his groove and scored 9
first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   The turn of events in this game was a reminder of Game 1. While
the Heat were missing its shots and mired at 30 percent from the
field in the first half, the Knicks were taking apart the Heat's
suddenly soft defense in transition and shooting 50 percent. Often,
those points were coming off long rebounds that came as the Heat
missed 3-point attempts, going 0 for 12 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   That pattern continued in the second half. The Heat tried to
catch up by hitting 3's instead of pecking at the Knicks from
inside. Two 3-point misses and a turnover later, and the Knicks
were ahead by 52-37, with 10 minutes left in the third. By that
point, the Knicks' run was at 19-0.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, it was the Heat that was executing. The Heat
methodically quieted the Garden and went ahead, 11-4, to start the
game before the Knicks livened up and tied the game on a 12-5 run.
Then the tightness and intensity that this series promised began to
surface.
</P>
<P>
   There was Ewing, who was irate at official Mike Mathis, drawing
a technical foul in the first quarter. There was the spindly Marcus
Camby, showing he could physically hold his own against the Heat by
diving on the floor for a loose ball in the second quarter. There
was Sprewell, taking a charge with the bulky Mourning galloping
toward him.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever edge on intensity the Heat had in Game 2, the Knicks
were pouring onto the floor for this one. After losing the
rebounding edge in the first 4 minutes of the game, 7-1, the Knicks
began to muscle their way around the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Although they were leaving the Heat open for 3-pointers, Dan
Majerle, Jamal Mashburn and Terry Porter were missing, missing,
missing. With 3 minutes left in the third quarter, the Knicks took
a 3-point miss by Porter. On the possession, Ewing ended up with
the ball and tossed it to an open Sprewell who nailed a 3-pointer
to give the Knicks a 40-37 lead. They were not about to let it go.
</P>
<P>
   That play started the Knicks' 12-0 run to end the half. Two
possessions later, after Camby and Childs dived to the floor for a
loose ball and P.J. Brown was called for the foul, the Garden
erupted.
</P>
<P>
   The fans began twirling their orange towels over their heads
like helicopter blades, and the place nearly lifted off its
foundation. They hit new decibel levels when Houston drove through
the lane and into a crowd and hit his runner with 1.4 seconds left
to give the Knicks a 45-37 halftime lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
