<HEADLINE>
NO THIRD DEGREE FOR THE QUINDLENS 
`MONICA'S STORY': THE THRILL IS GONE 
A PLACE IN THE SUN FOR HUMBLE FINNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.) (rk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH ERIC V. COPAGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anna Quindlen will not become the third member of her family to
receive an honorary degree from Villanova University after all.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quindlen, a novelist and former reporter and columnist for
The New York Times, had been invited to be the commencement speaker
and follow in the footsteps of a great-uncle and an uncle. But she
said that she told the president of Villanova, the Rev. Edmund J.
Dobbin, that she was bowing out after opponents of abortion
threatened to protest her appearance by walking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing this solely for the sake of the graduates and their
families,'' she said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I said to Father Dobbin, if I had been asked simply to give
a speech at Villanova, I would still be giving the speech, and he
would not have accepted my withdrawal,'' she said. ``But the
commencement speaker is only a collateral part of graduation. The
most important part is the students. I don't want to do anything
that would disrupt the ceremony for them. You don't want a whole
mess of seniors to walk away thinking, `My graduation was the one
where there was this huge disruption.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Clement, a spokeswoman for Villanova, said that
objections to Ms. Quindlen's appearance had come from ``a small
minority of people,'' including an anti-abortion group on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quindlen said that she had not planned to mention the
abortion issue in her speech. ``It would never occur to me to speak
about reproductive rights at a college commencement,'' she said.
``The nuns always taught me to be appropriate, and I am.''
</P>
<P>
   `MONICA'S STORY': THE THRILL IS GONE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica's Story'' has gone the way of all books about scandals
past, like the page turners about the O.J. Simpson case. ``Monica's
Story,'' Andrew Morton's briefly best-selling book about Monica
Lewinsky, has been remaindered.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher, St. Martin's Press, hopes to clear out ``maybe
50,000'' hardcover copies and clear the way for 500,000 copies of
the mass market paperback edition to be shipped by August, said
Jamie Brickhouse, a spokesman for St. Martin's.
</P>
<P>
   Remaindering allows bookstores to sell ``Monica's Story'' for
half its $24.95 cover price.
</P>
<P>
   The initial, 350,000-copy printing of ``Monica's Story'' sold
out, Brickhouse said, and another 150,000 copies were sold. It was
No. 1 on the New York Times best seller list for three weeks and
was on the list for six weeks. &UR;  &LR; Wednesday it was No. 4,459 on the
sales list of Amazon.com. Another Clinton-related book, ``All Too
Human'' by George Stephanopoulos, was No. 78.
</P>
<P>
   A PLACE IN THE SUN FOR HUMBLE FINNS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quick. When you think of Finland, what comes to mind? Paavo
Nurmi, the Flying Finn, who shattered the world record for the
mile?
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1923. Try again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finns are shy, humble people,'' said Paivi Samilham, who works
for Finlandia Vodka and was schmoozing at Studio 54 the other night
in the hope that her country might find a spot in the limelight.
``We are good at producing products, but not too aggressive at
promoting them.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ms. Samilham said, Nokia, the world's largest cell
phone company, is Finnish, not Japanese. And Marimekko is Finnish,
not Japanese or Swedish.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing push, one of a series of Finnish coming-out
parties, began in December 1997 with five main events, including a
series of concerts of music composed by Jean Sibelius at Lincoln
Center and a retrospective of designer Alvar Aalto at the Museum of
Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, companies didn't want to be identified with any
particular country,'' said Petra Tuomi of the Swedish Consulate.
``They wanted to be global.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to be competitive, we had to change. We want Finland to be
associated with high technology and high design, not just
reindeer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
