</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUNWAY-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CEMENT SYSTEM REINS IN RUNAWAY PLANE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A twin-engine commuter plane that touched down too
close to the end of a runway at Kennedy International Airport was
stopped from plunging into a tidal bay by a prototype ``arresting
system,'' a kind of flypaper for runaway airplanes. Federal
officials said Wednesday that it saved the lives of the people on
board.
</P>
<P>
   The incident on Saturday morning marked the first operational
use of the system, installed two years ago after a jumbo jet went
off the end of the same runway, forcing passengers to swim to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually saved lives with this,'' said Jan M. Brecht-Clark,
the deputy director of aviation research at the Federal Aviation
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, an American Eagle flight arriving from Baltimore,
chewed up 248 feet of the arrestor bed, a newly developed,
crushable cement; its wheels were mired to a depth of 2{ feet and
the plane, a SAAB 340 turboprop, stopped about 150 feet short of
Thurston Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the 27 passengers was hurt, suffering a twisted
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and other officials said that engineers at the National
Transportation Safety Board said they did not believe the plane
could have stopped without the special system.
</P>
<P>
   At the same spot in February 1984, an SAS Scandinavian Airlines
DC-10 overshot the runway and landed in the frigid water and some
of the 177 passengers had to swim to shore or paddle life rafts
with their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same runway, same place, same Thurston Basin and the aircraft
lands and is arrested,'' said a Port Authority spokesman, Bill
Cahill.
</P>
<P>
   The SAS accident prompted the FAA to demand that runways have a
1,000-foot overrun area ``where practicable,'' but there is no
space for such an area at Kennedy. That led the Port Authority of
New York and New Jersey, working with the FAA and private
companies, to develop the system that got its first real test with
the American Eagle flight.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the system, called the Engineered Material
Arresting System, say there are 350 runway ends at busy airports
around the country that cannot meet the 1,000-foot standard. Those
airports do not have to comply with the FAA ruling unless they are
rebuilt or undergo other major construction.
</P>
<P>
   Only two runways have an arresting system now: the one at
Kennedy and one at La Guardia Airport. The Port Authority is
planning at least one more bed at each of its three airports,
Kennedy, La Guardia and Newark.
</P>
<P>
   And Minneapolis will install such a system soon, according to
Michael Rioux, of Joseph Del Balzo Associates, a Washington
consulting firm involved in marketing the system.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons that are not yet clear, the plane flew 6,500 feet,
or about a mile and a quarter, beyond the beginning of the runway,
and touched down just 1,900 feet from the runway end, according to
a preliminary analysis. Stopping distance is usually more than
3,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Visibility at the time was a quarter mile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
