<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOK, WATSON WILL BE PRESSED TO REPEAT VICTORIES IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Their names are inscribed on granite at PGA Tour
stops in Fort Worth-Dallas. But recent history suggests that John
Cook and Tom Watson will be hard-pressed to defend their respective
titles over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   No defending champions have repeated at PGA Tour events this
season and none has prevailed at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic since
1980. Cook will attempt to break that streak beginning with
Thursday's opening round at the Four Seasons Resort and Club.
</P>
<P>
   For Watson, reigning champ at next week's MasterCard Colonial,
historical evidence suggests the challenge will be even greater.
Ben Hogan was the last repeat winner in Fort Worth, way back in
1953.
</P>
<P>
   Players cite a variety of reasons why victories by defending
champions are going the way of the persimmon driver on the PGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   More time demands are placed on the defending champion during
tournament week, for both off-course functions and media
interviews. There is heightened parity among today's players.
Better manicured courses, coupled with advances in equipment, help
level the playing field for all competitors.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget intangibles such as course familiarity, blind
luck and ever-changing weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent pool out here is so deep, you have to have
everything go right just to win once, much less twice,'' said Cook,
41, who shot a closing 65 to win the 1998 Nelson by three strokes.
``You can't have any bad rounds. You can't have any mediocre
rounds. And you still have to have a couple of things go your way.
You're not going to have that happen for you very often. That's
why, every year, it gets that much tougher to win more and more
tournaments out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Witness the fact that David Duval remains the last person to
successfully defend a PGA Tour title, at the 1998 Michelob
Championship at Kingsmill. None of the four major championships has
seen a repeat winner in nine years, and the PGA Championship has
not had one in the stroke-play era. You have to backtrack to 1937,
when Denny Shute shot down the field for a second consecutive year
in a match-play format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when I played, it seemed like that happened everywhere.
But we very seldom get repeaters any more,'' said Byron Nelson, 87.
``There are so many factors that can make a difference that players
can't control. Wind and weather changes can make two strokes worth
of difference in how hard a course plays at different times on the
same day.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching the right conditions can spell the difference between
repeating a title and abdicating a throne because of increased
parity. For those who question that fields are more tightly bunched
today than a generation ago, consider this finding by Dr. Scott
Berry, a Texas A&AMP;M statistics professor:
</P>
<P>
   After studying 13,792 rounds at 197 major championships
contested between 1935-97, Berry concluded today's elite player has
improved by only one-quarter shot per day from his peer from the
1950s. During the same stretch, however, the median player has
improved by 1.25 shots per day and golfers from the bottom 10
percent of the money list have improved by 2.75 strokes per round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely tough to repeat out here. I've never
successfully defended as a pro,'' said Tiger Woods, a seven-event
winner who won three consecutive U.S. Amateur titles before joining
the PGA Tour in 1996. ``A lot of it depends on where you feel
comfortable. It's tough to win back-to-back if you're not familiar
with the course.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, the Nelson's last repeat champion (1978-80), agreed. But
he considers something else more significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is so cyclical, you've got to strike while the iron
is hot,'' Watson said. ``And there's no rhyme or reason to that. If
it happens during the same week for two consecutive years, you've
got a chance to repeat. If not, you don't.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
