<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-DEALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT MAKES THREE DEALS IN THREE NATIONS IN ONE DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Microsoft Corp. on Wednesday continued its rapid and
sweeping expansion beyond the personal computer market, making
simultaneous moves on three competitive fronts in as many
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Redmond, Wash.-based software company agreed to help Sony
distribute music and videos over the Internet, while at the same
time pursuing a stake in a British cable company and buying a
Swedish software maker.
</P>
<P>
   While Wednesday's agreements indicate Microsoft will be a tough
competitor in the cellular Internet and cable arenas, a move it
made last week indicates it will also cooperate with its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In the musical arena, Sony Music Entertainment of New York City,
one of the nation's five largest music companies, said it will use
Microsoft's Windows Media Technologies 4.0 to create and play
copyrighted singles and music videos by Sony's most popular
artists. Due out this summer, Windows Media is a bid by Microsoft
to best a similar product from another Seattle company,
RealNetworks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said its Media software will comply with
portable-device standards being developed by the Secure Digital
Music Initiative, a recording-industry group. Such compliance is
widely viewed as critical to the growth of the market for
copyrighted music that can be downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   The online music market ``is likely to be a billion-dollar
industry'' by the year 2003, up from about $1 million today, said
Mark Hardie, an analyst with Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Britain, Microsoft continued talks to buy up to 30
percent of Cable &AMP; Wireless Communications PLC, which would give it
a stake in each of the three largest cable companies in the United
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   No agreement has yet been reached in the deal, which may be
worth as much as $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Comprehensive as usual, Microsoft this winter agreed to invest
$500 million for a 5 percent stake in the number-one British cable
company, New York-based NTL Inc. Last week, Microsoft agreed to buy
29.9 percent of Telewest Communications PLC, the third major cable
operator in Britain, for an undisclosed price.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has become a battleground for the sale of the operating
systems within the set-top boxes used with cable television, and
for server software used to host the Internet sites accessible over
cable.
</P>
<P>
   Network Computer Inc., a rival company owned by Oracle Corp. and
America Online Inc., has already made sales to all three British
cable companies, and Microsoft is seeking to dislodge that company.
</P>
<P>
   In Sweden, Microsoft agreed to buy Sendit AB, a maker of
Internet software for cellular phone networks, for $120 million in
cash.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase will give Microsoft access to Internet Cellular
Smart Access, software for browsing the Internet and receiving
e-mail, all from a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   In a cooperative gesture, last week Microsoft officially joined
the Wireless Application Protocol Forum, a move many saw as
effectively heading off a microbrowser war. Microbrowsers _
software for accessing the Internet from devices other than PCs _
are key to accessing the Internet access cell phones, and several
vendors make them.
</P>
<P>
   Many see a time when all wireless phones will be manufactured
with Web browsers included, and few wanted a standards war that
would pit Microsoft, backed by the software developer industry,
against the Wireless Forum, backed by wireless-industry players,
said WCR, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's entry means application developers can write to one
common standard, which will likely kick-start the smart-phone
market, the publication said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding $2 billion each quarter to its $22 billion cash reserve,
Microsoft can afford the kind of spending spree it's been on
lately. In recent weeks, the company has moved quickly to ensure it
holds the same dominant position in cable TV set-top box operating
systems and wireless-phone microbrowsers that it now enjoys in
personal computer operating systems and applications.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Microsoft agreed to invest $5 billion in AT&AMP;T Corp.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T will become the largest U.S. cable TV company after it
completes its acquisition of MediaOne Group Inc., and it has said
it will use Microsoft's CE operating system in as many as 10
million set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Microsoft said it will invest $600 million in wireless
telephone company Nextel Communications Inc., giving it a toehold
in the emerging market for wireless Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   Material from Bloomberg News was included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
