u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPSI-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-12 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AD CAMPAIGN HOPES TO BOOST PEPSI'S NEWEST SODA BRAND
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be named Storm, but it hasn't had much effect on the
soft-drink landscape.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pepsi-Cola Co. first said it would sell Storm, a
lemon-lime carbonated drink, in a handful of markets nationwide,
many analysts thought the company would be challenging 7-Up and
Sprite.
</P>
<P>
   That was last year. This year, Storm has displayed little, if
any, punch. Sales are too low to make any mark on the national
consumption meter, and brand image is practically nonexistent.
Pepsi, a unit of Pepsico Inc., has not expanded the number of
markets _ Denver, Northern California, and Philadelphia are among
them _ where the drink is sold, even though many analysts and
industry experts expected the company to do so by early this year.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of things happened on the way to Storm's landfall. One
was the company's national introduction of Pepsi One, the diet cola
made with Ace-K, which was completed in October and is thought to
have cost Pepsi about $100 million in marketing and promotion
expenses. Another was the huge marketing effort for Pepsi-Cola,
which culminated in March with the ``Joy of Cola'' theme, replacing
``Generation Next.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Pepsico's spinoff and public offering of its
bottling division, completed at the end of March, which also
secured U.S. distribution rights for 7-Up, made by the rival
Cadbury Schweppes PLC.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-Up agreement came about because Cadbury, which also owns
the Dr Pepper brand, insisted on security for 7-Up if the bottler,
now known as Pepsi Bottling Group, was going to continue to
distribute Dr Pepper. The spinoff constituted a change in
ownership, and Cadbury thus had no obligation to continue its
franchise agreements with the bottler, said Bill Pecoriello, an
analyst for Sanford Bernstein &AMP; Co. Dr Pepper is a perennial
moneymaker for bottlers, while 7-Up's fortunes have been in decline
for years, losing market share to Sprite, which is owned by the
Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potentially, PBG was going to drop 7-Up for Storm, and now
they've agreed to keep 7-Up,'' Pecoriello said. ``It came down to
the leverage Cadbury had with Dr Pepper. The spinoff turned out to
be a fortunate event for 7-Up.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Pepsi is putting some money into advertising in hopes of
creating a personality for Storm that has been lacking so far. The
ads, two television spots created by the BBDO New York unit of BBDO
Worldwide, part of Omnicom Group, depict the same 20-something man
in humorously uncomfortable situations. Storm, with its smooth
taste, is supposed to be the antidote to such situations.
</P>
<P>
   In the first commercial, which started running last week, the
lead character, Pete, sits in an executive's office waiting to hear
whether he has landed a job. Next to him is Lisa, clearly waiting
to hear about the same job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize it is a bit unorthodox, but given that we have only
one position available, I felt compelled to deliver my decision to
both of you, together,'' says the executive, a study in pomposity.
The job goes to Lisa, who throws her arms around her new boss and
shrieks, ``Thank you, Daddy!''
</P>
<P>
   The announcer intones: ``Life isn't always so smooth.
Fortunately, there's a lemon-lime that is.'' The tag line follows,
with ``Make the move to smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   The second spot shows Pete and a girlfriend embracing in an
apartment. The telephone rings, and the answering machine kicks in.
A sultry female voice is heard, saying she wants to come by and
will use her key if necessary. The girlfriend hears this,hisses,
``Creep!'' and whacks Pete in the head on her way out.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the voice is seen next, and she turns out to be the
cleaning lady. ``Pick up your feet,'' she coos, ramming the vacuum
cleaner at Pete, who sarcastically thanks her for coming over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted to appeal to 20-somethings and college
kids,'' said Bill Bruce, a creative director at BBDO, who worked on
the ads. ``We wanted to be relevant to them and their world.''
</P>
<P>
   Doris Cassar, another BBDO creative director, said: ``Storm is
the next level of lemon-lime for that user. It's a little more
sophisticated, more grown-up in terms of its taste and the way it
goes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi officials insist that Storm is a smoother drink than its
competitors. ``This makes it clear how we are different from Sprite
and 7-Up,'' said David DeCecco, a Pepsi spokesman. ``There's less
carbonation in Storm and a different flavor profile, and this will
make that clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Storm is also the only lemon-lime drink that contains caffeine,
in an amount comparable to a cola, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi plans to offer coupons in newspapers and set up
free-sample tables at colleges and music festivals this summer and
fall, DeCecco said. There will also be cans with ``Star Wars''
themes, like other Pepsi products.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the majority of cities where we're testing it, we've
reached our share goals,'' he said. ``In some, we haven't. We are
doing better in convenience and gas station stores than in grocery
stores.''
</P>
<P>
   The company was hoping for ``awareness'' _ the measure of how
well people recognize the name of a new product _ of 60 percent and
got 83 percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But is Storm going to intensify, or will it wind up a distant
third like Slice, Pepsi's earlier attempt at a lemon-lime soda?
</P>
<P>
   ``Long term, we'd like this to be our competitor in the
lemon-lime category,'' said Scott Moffitt, senior marketing manager
for Pepsi. ``This is part of the plan, to do a long, extended test.
Our whole effort now is more aggressive than last year, and it's
very much a priority for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
