<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0534 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5143 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUNS-EXECUTED-SUIT13-     05-12 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUNS-EXECUTED-SUIT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suit filed against ex-generals `to get to bottom' of nuns'
murder
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Two former generals from El Salvador now
living in Florida were sued Tuesday over the 1980 murders of three
nuns and a social worker, a case that drew international attention
at the time and raised questions about U.S. support for that
country's government.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in federal court in West Palm Beach, says the
murders of the four women were ordered by high-ranking officials in
the Salvadoran military and covered up by its leaders: Jose
Guillermo Garcia, the former defense minister, and Carlos Eugenio
Vides Casanova, the director-general of the Salvadoran National
Guard.
</P>
<P>
   For years the families of the victims believed the killings were
part of a larger campaign to silence ``subversives'' in El
Salvador, particularly church members, who were critical of the
military-led government for human rights abuses during its 12-year
civil war with leftist guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The women _ Sisters Ita Ford, 40, and Maura Clarke, 51, both of
New York; Sister Dorothy Kazel, 42, of Cleveland; and social worker
Jean Donovan, 32, also of Cleveland _ were among the critics. The
women worked at a Catholic refugee center in the Central American
country.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 2, 1980, they were accosted at a road block by soldiers
who later raped and shot them, leaving their bodies along a dirt
road.
</P>
<P>
   Though five members of the Salvadoran National Guard were
convicted in the killings (three of whom were released from prison
last year), the families still don't believe the case was fully
investigated. They hope to shed more light on it in a West Palm
Beach courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The families want to get to the bottom of it,'' said Bob
Kerrigan, a Pensacola attorney who represents the families with
West Palm Beach lawyer Bob Montgomery. ``How far up does this go?''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, reached Wednesday at his Plantation home, said he never
tried to cover up the deaths, but asked the FBI to help in the
investigation that resulted in the five arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are they doing this?'' he asked. ``I don't understand the
intention when this was already handled in El Salvador. And it was
already established who was responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   The families are seeking damages under the Torture Victim
Protection Act, an 8-year-old federal law that allows victims of
human rights abuses to sue their alleged assailants in U.S. courts.
</P>
<P>
   The suit doesn't say how much money the families are seeking,
but $75,000 is the minimum in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The case was filed in Florida because Garcia, 65, and Casanova,
61, now live here. Casanova lives in Palm Coast, near Daytona
Beach. The two were served with the lawsuit simultaneously Tuesday
night so one could not tip off the other.
</P>
<P>
   A second lawsuit was also filed Tuesday against the generals by
West Palm Beach attorney Jim Green. That suit has been sealed, and
Green would not name the plaintiff or discuss the nature of the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers had to file the suits by Wednesday, the 10-year
anniversary of Casanova's entry into the United States, Montgomery
said. Lawsuits under the victim protection act are barred after 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   One question the families' lawyers hope to answer is why the two
men were allowed to emigrate to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Casanova could not be reached for comment Wednesday night, but
last year he told a Cleveland Plain Dealer reporter he was not
involved in the killings and knew nothing about them.
</P>
<P>
   The governments of both El Salvador and the United States
maintained for years that the investigation ended with the soldiers
who were convicted. But in 1993, a United Nations commission found
that both Garcia and Casanova tried to cover up the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations in the suit could be buoyed by information found
by the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights, a New York-based group
that represents the families and asked Kerrigan and Montgomery to
take the case. (Kerrigan and Montgomery were two of the lawyers
hired by Florida in its $13 billion lawsuit against the tobacco
industry.)
</P>
<P>
   Last year, four of the convicted soldiers told a comittee lawyer
that they were acting on orders from superiors. But their sergeant
who received the order refused to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Documents declassified by the State Department last year show
that Garcia told a U.S. ambassador in 1985 that he suspected a
member of his high comman ordered the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some suspicions,'' Garcia acknowledged Wednesday. ``But
it's one thing to suspect and another to confirm. I had no
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The families have pushed for a deeper investigation in El
Salvador, to no avail. In 1993, the Salvadoran government declared
amnesty for political crimes from the war.
</P>
<P>
   Such difficulties are common for the victims of atrocities, who
must turn to American courts for a semblance of justice, said Patti
Blum, a law professor at the University of California at Berkeley
who helped prepare the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   No more than 20 such lawsuits have been filed in the United
States against suspected war criminals, and only two have gone to a
jury, Blum said. The suits often are more symbolic than anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Garcia and Casanova stands out because they
have established roots in the United States, so they have more at
stake, Blum said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said he doesn't have any money and wonders whether the
lawsuit is an effort to embarrass him.
</P>
<P>
   Blum said such lawsuits are part of a more aggressive effort by
human rights groups to hold suspected criminals responsible for
their actions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Amnesty International established the Center for
Justice and Accountability in San Francisco specifically to pursue
these cases; the group has filed three lawsuits since August.
</P>
<P>
   Staff researchers Sammy Alzofon and Lynne Palombo contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
