<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION BILL COMPROMISE UP FOR A VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
and KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A long-awaited compromise on a parental-notice
bill for minors seeking abortions, backed by Gov. George W. Bush,
awaited a vote from a key committee late Wednesday while talks on a
hate crimes bill fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   The substitute for Senate Bill 30, the parental notification
bill sponsored by Republican Sen. Florence Shapiro of Plano, was
drafted by Rep. Steve Wolens, a Dallas Democrat who has been little
trusted by anti-abortion forces in the past. It was Wolens' State
Affairs Committee that was expected to approve the bill, which has
been the subject of intensive negotiations for the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wolens delayed the vote first by announcing his
committee would instead take up a complicated electric deregulation
bill, with 80 to 100 amendments on the table. Republican leaders in
the House, the governor's office and activists on both sides of the
abortion debate insisted that an agreement had been reached with
Wolens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked with legislators and developed a strong and
sound parental notification bill that the governor supports and
hopes the House will as well,'' said Bush spokesman Scott
McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   After negotiations deadlocked last week, Bush's office entered
talks on Mother's Day that were said to have lasted into early
Monday morning. Bush, a front-runner for the GOP presidential
nomination, has promised social conservatives in his party that he
would push passage of a parental involvement bill this year.
</P>
<P>
   But efforts to agree on a hate crimes bill have had less
success. Bush has not said where he stands on the measure, despite
pleas for his backing from the relatives of James Byrd Jr., the
black man in Jasper who was dragged to his death behind a pickup
truck last June.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, President Clinton also challenged Bush to support the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Despite several hours of closed-door negotiations on the hate
crimes bill Wednesday, Democrats and Republicans failed to forge a
compromise to get the issue to a floor debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hopeful that after members get a chance to talk some
more and reflect on the discussions that have been had, we can come
to some middle ground Thursday,'' said Senate sponsor Rodney Ellis,
D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would toughen penalties for those convicted of
crimes motivated by prejudice against certain categories of people,
has been stalled in the Senate Criminal Justice Committee because
of Republican opposition to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, who is pushing passage of parental notification as its
Senate sponsor, is one of four Republicans on the committee. She
has said her objections to the bill stem from its specified
categories of people who would be protected from hate crimes. She
also has insisted that her opposition is not purely because of
protections for gay citizens.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ellis said the protection of gays is the major sticking
point, and he will not support a bill deleting that language. ``The
second largest category of hate crimes committed in Texas has been
on the basis of sexual orientation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With only 19 days remaining in this legislative session and a
Friday deadline for Senate committees to complete their work,
lawmakers have been scrambling to find ways to pry their bills out
of committee. But Ellis and others said they have offered no deals
on parental notification or other measures to get the hate crimes
bill moving.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the substitute parental-notice bill expected to gain
approval from Wolens' committee contains trades neither side fully
likes.
</P>
<P>
   A two-day waiting period was waived for young women brought for
abortions by parents to undergo the procedure, pleasing abortion
rights supporters. In return, anti-abortion forces won their fight
to make sure only a judge could bypass the parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty bad when the only way you can say `I told you so'
is when a young woman ends up badly hurt,'' said Margot Clarke,
spokeswoman for Planned Parenthood of Austin. ``It just makes you
hurt because it's bad. It's bad law.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Patricia Gray, D-Galveston, is expected to offer an
amendment to allow other adult family members, psychologists and
psychiatrists to be notified instead of parents.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Marchant, R-Coppell, said the compromise includes an
agreement that Republican leaders will plead with party members to
respect the compromise on the House floor, where he expects it to
land within a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very, very happy with the bill. In fact, if that becomes
the law, it's going to be OK,'' he said. Marchant is a House
Republican leader and sponsor of a similar measure killed last
session.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Price, president of Texans United for Life, said
anti-abortion activists who pushed for the bill are not happy with
the deal struck by their staunchest Republican allies in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have real problems being able to support it,
especially if a deal has been made that we can't amend it on the
floor,'' Price said. He added his group, along with the Christian
Coalition, was told by Republican negotiators that they'd have to
``take it or leave it.''
</P>
<P>
   The compromise also softens a parent-notice bill that passed the
Senate by allowing relatives, psychologists, psychiatrists and
others to offer moral support and act as advocates for young women
in their dealings with attorneys and judges. It also offers the
doctor stronger defenses against criminal misdemeanor charges that
could result in a maximum year in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Price said anti-abortion forces fear the bill's definition of
abortion will make the law ineffective or unconstitutional. He also
perceives it could offer too much protection for doctors from
criminal sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Those who oppose abortion have held high hopes this year that a
parental notice bill would pass, and abortion rights advocates
conceded they would have difficulty stopping it. Even though Texas'
anti-abortion movement has proposed parental involvement bills
since Roe vs. Wade legalized abortion in 1973, the most intense
efforts began in the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
