<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TMS' GOSSAGE BACKS IRL FOR LONG HAUL
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight days in the seat of a Harley-Davidson, on the long and
winding road from coast-to-coast, affords a man plenty of time to
think things through.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the 3,100 miles he logged between Fontana, Calif.,
and Trinity, N.C., as a member of Kyle Petty's Charity Ride Across
America last week, Eddie Gossage reached a conclusion about the Pep
Boys Indy Racing League and its fit at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   As advertised, the IRL's Longhorn 500 remains booked for
Saturday night, June 12, at the 1.5-mile racetrack with the
daunting 24-degree banked turns in Fort Worth. Same as it was
before the accident that killed three spectators and injured eight
during the IRL's VisionAire 500 at Lowe's Motor Speedway in
Concord, N.C., on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never once been any conversation about not running
that race on June 12,'' said Gossage, TMS' executive vice president
and general manager, dispelling reports the event here was in
jeopardy. ``We race. That's what we do. They're going to run the
Indianapolis 500 on May 30, and the winner and the rest of them
will come to Texas. And we'll go racing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days since a three-car crash launched a wheel and
assorted debris over a 15-foot fence and into the Turn 4
grandstands at LMS, the future of open-wheel, oval-track racing has
come into question. Rightly so, because the most recent accident
occurred only nine months after a similar incident killed three
spectators and injured six during a CART FedEx Championship Series
race at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Those are staggering statistics when multiplied by the family
members and friends affected. Count Gossage among those calling for
an accelerated look at how open-wheel race cars traveling in excess
of 220 mph can be made safer for driver and spectator alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're calling on the IRL to address the cars quickly, and make
some changes there,'' said Gossage, who anticipates the fences at
TMS will be raised approximately 41/2 feet and further extended
over the racing surface before the June event. ``There's no way you
can guarantee total safety at any sporting event, whether it's race
cars, hockey pucks or foul balls. All we can do is everything we
can do to make this place as safe as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRL's fate at LMS ultimately rests with Bruton Smith, the
founder of Speedway Motorsports Inc., and H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler,
the track's president and Smith's confidant. Some have suggested
that Wheeler _ the sport's promoter extraordinaire _ was so shaken
by the deaths of the fans that he may be leaning toward ending LMS'
association with Tony George's fledgling IRL.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Humpy' has an autonomy that those of us who don't have 25
years in the company don't enjoy,'' Gossage said of his mentor. ``I
can't tell you what `Humpy's' going to do. But I can tell you that
we're going to run Indy cars this year, next year and from there
on. I'll sign a sanctioning agreement tomorrow for another three
years. And we will. Our fans approve of the IRL. It's a great
product.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no hesitation in my mind. I'm in it for the long haul.
I had 3,100 miles to think about it.''
SPOTLIGHT ON...
Nelson takes level look at Winston Cup parity
</P>
<P>
   As NASCAR Winston Cup Series director, Gary Nelson is
responsible for maintaining a level playing field among the
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The job requires thick skin and working knowledge of the wind
tunnel, especially when one of the factories is preparing to debut
new or updated sheet metal.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, introduction of the 2000 Chevrolet Monte Carlo
originally was scheduled for the Coca-Cola 600 at Lowe's Motor
Speedway on May 30. However, the new Monte Carlo will not appear
until the 2000 season after a round of ``wind tunnel politics''
involving the car's aerodynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson admittedly dabbled in the ``gray area'' of the NASCAR
rulebook en route to 21 victories as a Winston Cup crew chief, and
the 1983 championship with Bobby Allison. But Nelson has been
working the other side of the fence since 1992, his first season as
Winston Cup technical director.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with that background _ and his experiences from the
introduction of the ``four-door'' Ford Taurus in 1998 _ Nelson has
maintained a hard-line on the 2000 Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it hits the racetrack, we want it equal,'' said Nelson,
comparing the Monte Carlo to the competing Taurus and Pontiac Grand
Prix. ``Down the road, we don't want to cut it to get it equal.
Basically, what we're saying is let's do all the development we can
before the car hits the racetrack and know as much as we can about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we learned a lot with the Taurus being a new car,
and being equal when we approved it. Then it got better by the time
three or four races went by, and we had to cut two inches off the
\Rrear\S spoiler to get it equal again. Given that history, we know
that a new-model car gains the most in the first few months. Then
it kind of levels off. Then it becomes an issue of, well, how many
races does that take?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to avoid that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the data collected at the Lockheed-Martin wind
tunnel in Marietta, Ga., in mid-March proved to NASCAR officials
that the current Monte Carlo, Taurus and Grand Prix are aerodynamic
equals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to work to make sure the \R2000\S Monte Carlo
will be competitive when it hits the track,'' Nelson said. ``I
think the car is really neat-looking. Dimensionally, it's a work in
progress. When the car is to the point where everybody feels it
will race competitively, then we will approve it and say, `Here's
your templates, go build your cars.' ''
INSIDE THE NUMBERS
STUCK AT 236 MPH
</P>
<P>
   Billy Boat won the pole position for last year's Indianapolis
500 with a four-lap average speed of 223.503 mph in an
Oldsmobile-powered Dallara. Following preseason tests at the
2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway last month, Boat predicted the
1999 pole-winner will need a four-lap (10-mile) average of 225-plus
mph on May 22. Here are the four-lap qualification records at IMS
during this decade: Year Driver Chassis/engine Speed 1990 Emerson
Fittipaldi Penske/Chevy Indy V-8 225.301 1992 Arie Luyendyk
Lola/Ford-Cosworth V-8 229.127 1992 Roberto Guerrero Lola/Buick V-6
232.482 1996 Davy Jones Lola/Mercedes-Ilmor V-8 232.882 1996 Tony
Stewart Lola/Menard V-6 233.100 1996 Scott Brayton Lola/Menard V-6
233.178 1996 Arie Luyendyk Reynard/Ford-Cosworth V-8 236.986 1996
was the last year for turbocharged engines in the Indy Racing
League. Since 1997, IRL cars have been powered by normally
aspirated, production-based Oldsmobile Aurora and Nissan Infiniti
Indy V-8s.
QUICK HITS
ISC-PENSKE ROLL DICE
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's version of ``Monopoly'' has become more than just a
retro board game.
</P>
<P>
   The merger agreement announced between International Speedway
Corp., and Penske Motorsports, Inc., on Monday has left us with two
major players in the control of big-time motorsports facilities and
race dates _ the realigned ISC and Speedway Motorsports Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Upon completion of the transaction, ISC will operate 10
facilities across the country that play host to 14 of 34 races on
the current NASCAR Winston Cup schedule. SMI chairman Bruton Smith
owns six speedways that are operating with nine Cup dates.
</P>
<P>
   Bill France Jr., the chairman and chief executive officer of
ISC, also is president of NASCAR in his spare time. Tom Thomson, an
analyst with First Union Capital Markets, told The Charlotte
Observer that the size of the new ISC will prompt NASCAR to be
``extremely careful about doing things that might be considered
detrimental to Speedway Motorsports.'' FORMULA ONE DATE SET
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway are anticipating a
crowd of 200,000 fans for the inaugural U.S. Grand Prix at
Indianapolis Formula One race on Sept. 24, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the first F1 race in the United States since 1991
are scheduled to go on sale later this year. Fans interested in
receiving an order form for tickets should send a postcard with
name and address to U.S. Grand Prix at Indianapolis, P.O. Box
24916, Speedway, In., 46224, or call (800) 822-4639. Forms also may
be obtained by e-mail at tickets &LR; brickyard.com. ALLEN PACKS POWER
</P>
<P>
   Pro Stock driver Bruce Allen of Arlington heads into qualifying
for the NHRA's Advance Auto Parts Nationals at Atlanta Dragway this
weekend with plenty of horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta will mark the first race of the year where we will
have our No. 1 and No. 2 race motors up to speed, and our car in
good working order,'' said Allen, driver of The Outlaw Fuel
Additives Pontiac Firebird. ``Finally, we should be able to see
what we're truly capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen and crew chief David Reher advanced to the final of this
race last year before losing against Mark Osborne. INJURED GIRL
IMPROVES
</P>
<P>
   The condition of 9-year-old Haley McGee was upgraded for the
first time _ from critical to serious _ at Carolinas
Medical/Children's Hospital in Charlotte, N.C., Wednesday. McGee
suffered brain and lung injuries when struck by flying debris
during the IRL's VisionAire 500 at Lowe's Motor Speedway on May 1.
Fans may send cards or toys to McGee in care of the hospital at
1000 Blythe Blvd., Charlotte, N.C., 28203. LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people get stuck in a rut and never get to do the things
they dream about. I was lucky enough at 25 _ not 45 _ to have my
mid-life crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Greg Ray, IRL driver, preparing to begin practice for the Indy
500 on Saturday
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
