<SLUG> BC-ART-AUCTION-ART-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GOGH STARS AT CHRISTIE'S AUCTION
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Christie's inaugurated the main salesroom in its new
Rockefeller Center home Wednesday night with an auction of 40
Impressionist and 19th-century artworks that was so strong it
surprised even the most seasoned experts.
</P>
<P>
   The sale totaled $65.9 million, well above its $63 million low
estimate. Of the 40 works on offer, only four failed to sell. The
sale surpassed Sotheby's auction of Impressionist and modern art on
Tuesday evening, at which 48 works sold for a total of $55.5
million and 18 failed to find buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The high prices paid Wednesday night for what were a mixed bag
of paintings, drawings and sculpture had the audience baffled. Some
said the scarcity of top-quality works for sale this season had
buyers scrambling to get what they could.
</P>
<P>
   Others said buyers could have been seduced by the glamor of
Rockefeller Center. Still others speculated that Christopher Burge,
the chairman of Christie's in America and the evening's auctioneer,
exhibited an uncanny talent for gently but effectively coaxing
buyers to keep bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Christopher Burge inspire a willing suspension of
disbelief?'' asked a London dealer, Ivor Braka.
</P>
<P>
   By far the evening's star painting, van Gogh's ``Canal With
Washerwomen'' (or ``La Roubine du Roi'') of 1888, a vividly colored
landscape that captures the spot where the women of Arles did their
laundry. The painting was for sale at Sotheby's in 1984, when it
sold for $1.7 million. Wednesday night the painting was bought by
Joseph Albritton, a Washington collector, for $19.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's took a gamble. Before the sale it had offered a
guarantee (a minimum sum promised to the seller regardless of a
sale's outcome) and estimated it would sell for $20 million. That
was not far off. (Final prices include the auction house's
commission, 15 percent of the first $50,000 plus 10 percent of the
rest. Estimates do not reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   That a buyer was bidding for himself in the salesroom was
unusual. While collectors raised paddles in the 1980s, the practice
has disappeared in the less conspicuous '90s, but it was
surprisingly in evidence Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Another throwback from the boom years of the '80s was an Asian
man taking pictures of the bidding. (Christie's officials said no
Asians were buyers last night.) And a couple in their 30s, who held
hands during the auction and identified themselves only as from
Venezuela, kissed after each of the two lots they bought.
</P>
<P>
   A large number of works offered Wednesday night were from Japan,
where banks that collected feverishly during the boom of the 1980s
are now in financial distress. Christie's has many paintings owned
by the Lake Co., the Japanese consumer-loan concern that was bought
last year by GE Capital, the financial services arm of General
Electric. Lake sent Christie's about 500 works valued at $250
million that they plan to sell over the next several years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Up for sale Wednesday night was Braque's ``Landscape at
l'Estaque'' (1906), a Fauve landscape that was expected to fetch
$1.5 million to $2 million. It was bought by a telephone bidder
identified only as a European collector for $2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lake was also selling Monet's ``Garden of Vetheuil'' (1881),
which sold at Christie's in 1990 for $4.9 million. Wednesday night
it carried an estimate of $2.5 million to $3.5 million. It fetched
$2.7 million and was also bought by a telephone buyer after five
bidders tried to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   This week every sale has been littered with Monets. (Thirteen in
all have been on offer.) Christie's was selling eight, and all but
one sold. Among the best: ``Bridge in Monet's Garden'' (1895-96),
thought to be the first view of his newly constructed Japanese
bridge, had four bidders hopping. Estimated to bring $7 million to
$10 million, it sold to an unidentified telephone buyer for $5.9
million.
</P>
<P>
   Another telephone bidder spent $5.2 million for Monet's
``Antibes, Seen From the Salis Gardens'' (1888). It had been
estimated to sell for $3.5 million to $4.5 million. One of the
sale's casualties, Monet's 1899 view of Charing Cross Bridge in
late afternoon light, was thought to fetch $5 million to $7
million. No buyer was willing to pay $3.8 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
