<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREASURY-RUBIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBIN QUITS TREASURY JOB AS DEPUTY TO GET NOMINATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, who over the
last four years has presided over one of the most remarkable
economic performances in American history, said Wednesday he will
resign in July.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton quickly announced that he will nominate Larry
Summers, a former Harvard University economics professor and the
deputy treasury secretary, to take over the Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   The president also will name Stuart Eizenstat, the
undersecretary of state for economic, business and agricultural
affairs, to succeed Summers.
</P>
<P>
   A product of Wall Street, Rubin, 60, leaves office as the
nation's 70th treasury secretary as the U.S. economy continues to
churn ahead in the longest economic expansion in peacetime history.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's unemployment rate remains low, inflation is
well-tamed, and the federal government is racking up its first
budget surpluses in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a Rose Garden ceremony, hailed Rubin ``as the most
effective treasury secretary since Alexander Hamilton'' at the
founding of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who along with Rubin
and Summers is credited with keeping the American economic
juggernaut steaming ahead, called Rubin ``one of the most effective
secretaries of the treasury in this nation's history.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rubin described his years at the White House as
``all consuming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is time for me to go home to New York,'' Rubin
said. ``In doing so, I am absolutely confident that this
administration will not miss a beat with respect to the economic
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   When word of Rubin's resignation first broke Wednesday morning,
the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 213 points. But the stock
market quickly rebounded as those early reports were confirmed by
the White House and as investors realized Summers would be
succeeding his longtime boss.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow ended the day down 25.78.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as the news was confirmed, the market came back,''
said Bryan Jordan, economics analyst for Banc One Investment
Advisors in Columbus, Ohio. ``It's really uncertainty that's the
enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   A former co-chairman and 26-year veteran of the New York
investment banking firm Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., Rubin joined the White
House in January 1993 to head the National Economic Council.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he succeeded Texan Lloyd Bentsen as treasury
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin took over just as the Clinton administration had decided
to help bail out Mexico after that country's disastrous peso
devaluation. He would later help steer the country as an economic
and currency crisis would swirl around the world, bludgeoning
economies from Thailand to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, Rubin was an advocate for budget discipline,
a strong dollar and U.S. support for the International Monetary
Fund, the world's emergency bailout organization.
</P>
<P>
   When Rubin took over as treasury secretary, the Dow was hovering
around at 3,800 and the dollar was trading for about 84 Japanese
yen. On Wednesday, the market closed above 11,000, with the dollar
trading at nearly 121 yen.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin had made no secret of his desire to leave the
administration and return to New York, where his wife, Judy
Oxenberg Rubin, has continued to live.
</P>
<P>
   But he stayed on as the world economic crisis rage and as the
impeachment trial brought official Washington to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many economists viewed Rubin's announcement
Wednesday as an indication the White House believes the economic
and political crises of the last few years have finally stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rubin ... waited for the moment when at least he saw the
crisis subsiding,'' said David Jones, chief economist for the New
York securities dealer Aubrey G. Lanston. If he wanted to resign
``this is probably the best time.''
</P>
<P>
   On Republican-controlled Capitol Hill, Rubin's resignation was
met with regret.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Rubin ``intelligent and sincere,'' Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, noted: ``Of all
the officials in the Clinton administration, he has had more
credibility with me and, I think, with Congress than any other
official.''
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Houston,
called Rubin ``a strong and sometimes solitary voice within the
Clinton administration for open markets and fiscal discipline,''
while Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Houston, called Rubin ``an exemplary
public servant, the best a country could ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his predecessor, Summers, 44, does not bring market
experience to the job. Instead, Summers hails from academia. In
1983, Summers became the youngest tenured professor in Harvard's
history, and a decade later was named the nation's outstanding
economist under the age of 40.
</P>
<P>
   From 1991 to 1993, Summers served as chief economist at the
World Bank. In April 1993 he joined the Treasury Department as
undersecretary for international affairs. He was named deputy
treasury secretary in August 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Summers ``as brilliant, able, a critical part of
our economic team during the entire life of this administration,''
while Greenspan described him as ``a person of extraordinary talent
and judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   During the world economic crisis, Summers was frequently the
administration's point man during negotiations with the
International Monetary Fund and the troubled economies around the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   Summers, however, has gained a reputation for having an abrasive
personality, while Asian leaders during the economic crisis
complained of what they described as a condescending tone, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Summers and Eizenstat _ who has spearheaded the
administrations' efforts to help Holocaust survivors retrieve
assets stolen half a century ago _ will have to be confirmed by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the Senate signaled Wednesday that Summers
would likely face a fairly warm reception on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., who as chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, will oversee Summers' confirmation, said in a prepared
statement his committee ``has had a good working relationship with
Mr. Summers in his current post,'' while Senate Majority Trent
Lott, R-Miss., noted that since Summers had been through the
confirmation process once already he did not anticipate substantial
problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
