r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-HOTRODS-LADN     05-12 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-HOTRODS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOLERS FISH LIKE VETERANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A light touch with the trolling motor inched the
bass boat closer to the shadowy targets only he could see.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fish are up there for one reason, for me to catch 'em,''
said the steely fisherman behind the polarized shades.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence belied the age of the expert. Wise beyond his years,
15-year-old Greg Glogow of Valencia has made thousands of casts
like those taken on a recent Thursday afternoon at Castaic Lagoon.
And with uncanny skill, the Hart High sophomore has landed more
trophy largemouths than most bass anglers his age _ or any age, for
that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I don't even see the fish,'' said Glogow's No.1 fishing
partner, Steve, his dad. ``I'll say, `What are you throwing at? And
he'll reel in the fish and say, `This fish.'''
</P>
<P>
   Glogow's five 10-plus-pound bass have turned the heads of
professional guides and area bass fanatics, and his personal-best
13-pound, 1-ounce bruiser caught at the lagoon in March is a
pending junior world record for boys ages 11 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obsessed with bass fishing. I had a goal to set a world
record,'' explained Glogow, who is on the water twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising words from someone so young. But upon closer
examination, occasionally other high schoolers share an
overwhelming passion for the rod and reel, so much so that they
often think of little else. By the accounts of family, friends and
fellow anglers, it's a healthy infatuation that keeps them out of
trouble, keeps the family together, keeps spawning new anglers and
keeps producing big fish. Call them hot rods.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom says I've got fish on the brain, and that's about it,''
said Steve Greanias, 17, of Granada Hills. The Crespi High senior
has kept a detailed fishing log of weekly trips since 1996, founded
his school's angling club and enjoys helping others hook up nearly
as much as he likes to himself. ``I haven't gone completely
overboard; I'm on the rail.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Glogow and Greanias are destined to be big-shot anglers,
Long Beach's Charlie Shane is going to make sure they play by the
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make a living out of being on the water,'' said
Shane, 15, a freshman at Lakewood High who fishes weekly in the
summer, preferring to pursue yellowtail, and aspires to be a game
warden. ``I want to keep fish numbers high so we can still catch
them for years to come. Besides, I'd like to be able to fish while
I work.''
</P>
<P>
   Some may express concerns over teens becoming so entirely
immersed in one interest, perhaps at the expense of other important
issues, such as family or school.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Greanias' father, Chris, puts it: ``Steve's an excellent
student (honor roll, 3.8 grade point average) and while I think he
could do even better if he dedicated more time to his studies, kids
this age are going to be obsessed with something; I'm glad it's
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, fishing crosses generational lines. It draws the
family closer because it's something we can all do together.''
</P>
<P>
   Glogow's mother, Lisa, echoed the sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really pleased about it. I think that it keeps Greg out of
trouble, off the streets and away from hanging out with the wrong
crowd. I think it's a real clean sport,'' she said. ``I think all
kids need to find something that they are good at, and I think he
has found that something.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the importance of the accomplishments of such
adolescent anglers, the International Game Fish Association added
in 1997 to its record keeping a category for junior world records.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just as good as an adult record,'' said Doug Blodgett,
records secretary for the IGFA in Dania, Fla. ``It shows that (a
record holder) is a younger person and they can do something as
exceptional, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Greanias has a raging case of fishing pox. He's such a
regular on the Ellie-M charter boat out of Oxnard's Capt. Hook's
Sportfishing that he volunteers to assist other anglers, cleans
fish and scrub the boats, much like a pinhead, or apprentice
deckhand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an avid fisherman,'' said Mike Dantona, a manager of Fish
'n Fools tackle shop in Granada Hills. ``He knows the routine as
well as any adult, or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Greanias' largest fish to date is a 25-pound dorado. He caught
and released 45 trout in two hours on Robinson Creek out of
Bridgeport last year, and once in a day boated 20 barracuda and a
like number of sand bass, returning them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure that when I have kids I can take them out
there and they can catch 20 sand bass in a day,'' said Greanias,
who graduates this month and wants to attend Moorpark College next
year and then go on to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   A chronic tinkerer who makes lures, bass plugs, rod holders and
gaffs in the garage, his favorite part of fishing may be ensuring
others have as much fun as he does. ``He tends to help other
fishermen and fish less for himself,'' Dantona said. ``There's not
enough people like that.''
</P>
<P>
   With braces on his teeth, baggy pants and a 5-foot-1 frame, the
green-eyed Glogow doesn't fit the image of a bass freak, yet he
eventually wants to fish the professional circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of myself as a little kid, but, I mean, I'm
definitely getting better at it as far as catching big fish,'' said
the understated Glogow. ``In general, yeah, I hold my own.''
</P>
<P>
   His success speaks for itself, with his first behemoth _ 11
pounds, 13 ounces _ coming at age 11. The finicky 13-pounder was a
story in itself. It finally bit on a live waterdog after Glogow
took it upon himself to walk to a nearby tackle shop and buy
6-pound line after realizing the fish was too line shy to approach
the 10-pound monofilament he had on. Dad netted the brute on the
first scoop; ``He knew it was life or death,'' Glogow said.
</P>
<P>
   Castaic carpenter and bass-fishing guide Pat Buckley admires
Glogow's quick learning and persistence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll work on one fish, like that 13-pounder, that most people
would have gave up on,'' said Buckley, whose best bass is a
14-pounder. ``It's a great accomplishment for a guy his age. It
would be a great accomplishment for anybody.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TIPS FROM THE MAN, ER, THE TEEN
</P>
<P>
   Bass-angling phenom Greg Glogow offers five easy tips for
targeting Southland largemouths:
</P>
<P>
   Light line, small baits: Try 6-pound line and a 3-inch plastic
worm, with a size No.5 or 7 split shot secured 24 inches above the
bait.
</P>
<P>
   Sun up, wind down: It's the best combination to improve odds for
success when sight-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Be in tune with the equipment: Make sure the reels drag (and
spool tension for a baitcaster reel) is set according to the type
of bait. If unsure, inquire at a tackle shop.
</P>
<P>
   Have patience: When in an area where fish have been spotted,
stay until you catch one or exhaust your options. Some anglers move
to new spots too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Have a plan and stick to it: There are only so many good hours
of fishing _ mainly from 6 a.m. to 9:30 a.m., and 4 p.m. to 7 p.m.
_ so don't waste your time changing technique in haphazard fashion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-12-99 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990512.0541 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-12 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-1STLD-     05-12 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MISSISSIPPI LEARNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 5th graf, I decided ..., to delete phrase `which is not
even a town' after Robinsville.) 
 (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUNICA COUNTY, Miss. _ I stood beside the cotton field in the
morning quiet of the Delta and listened to the echoes of the
tortured souls from years and decades and centuries past. To enter
Mississippi has always been, in my view, to descend to a lower
place, a world of fanatical race hatred in which blacks were
condemned by whites to a perpetual state of humiliation and often
gruesome suffering.
</P>
<P>
   I'm told that Mississippi is changing. Casino gambling has
flooded some areas with money and jobs and is threatening to lift
at least part of the state into the 20th century. Many of the jobs
have gone to blacks, and many of the gamblers are black. This has
been hailed as great progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go into a casino and sit down and play blackjack,''
said C. Penn Owen Jr., a 63-year-old white man and one of the most
powerful farmers in the Delta, ``I may be sitting next to my _''
This was during an interview in Owen's office. He stopped, looked
up and then started again. ``Very often there are colored people in
this community that I know well,'' he said, ``and it's kind of fun
to mix and mingle.''
</P>
<P>
   A mechanical planter, pulled by a tractor, moved slowly along
the field. Now a yellow plane, a crop duster, came into view,
flying low, and the stillness of the moment was lost. The cotton
field, which belongs to Owen, is in Robinsonville, an
unincorporated area of northern Tunica County, one of the most
rural parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to come here because something strange is going on.
There are only 8,500 people in the entire county, which is spread
over 460 square miles and consists mostly of cotton fields, soybean
farms and vacant land. Most of the people are black, poor and
poorly educated. There is only a tiny handful of children, nearly
all of them black and desperately poor, in the vicinity of
Robinsonville. And yet the movers and shakers at the local, county
and state levels want to build a brand new $8 million elementary
school for 500 pupils in Robinsonville. And only in Robinsonville.
</P>
<P>
   A new school in the middle of nowhere. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Robinsonville is just south of the largest and most successful
cluster of casinos in the state. The entire area is remarkably
empty except for the casinos. Most of the casino workers commute
from other parts of the state and from Memphis, just a few miles
farther north.
</P>
<P>
   The land for the proposed school was sold to the county Board of
Education by none other than Owen. And Owen is planning to build an
upscale residential development that will begin practically on the
school grounds and then fan out in a series of progressively wider
arcs.
</P>
<P>
   He needs the school to serve as a magnet for the upscale
families he wants to draw to his development. Those families will
almost surely be white. Hardly any of the black people in Tunica
County, not even those employed by the casinos, will be able to
afford to buy or rent a home in Owen's development.
</P>
<P>
   For many years a small number of black families have lived in
dreadful shacks on property in Robinsonville that is owned by Owen.
One by one they are being forced out, and as they leave the shacks
are bulldozed and the rubble burned.
</P>
<P>
   Penda Hair, a Washington lawyer who is working with a group of
black Tunica residents who are angry about the plan, put the matter
plainly: ``They are attempting to create an all-white, or virtually
all-white, enclave with its own school,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with stiffening opposition, proponents of the
state-of-the-art school are now saying most of its first students
will be black youngsters drawn from miles around, but that white
students will be added as white families move into Robinsonville.
What appears to be happening is grander than the simple creation of
a white enclave. Owen is not the only wealthy plantation owner
(yes, they still call them plantations) who is planning to build in
Robinsonville. There are others, and their goal seems to be nothing
less than the creation of a powerhouse, upscale, incorporated
community _ in other words, a prosperous, largely white town in an
overwhelmingly black county that has always ruthlessly exploited
its majority population.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Mississippi.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
