<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COMMUTER TAX GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 1st graf, 3rd sentence to add heated state Senate
contest in Orange County, as well Rockland.) 
 (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, May 13: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, New York's politicians outdo themselves
with acts of destructive one-upmanship. It is happening again, as
the state legislature moves toward repealing the New York City tax
imposed on commuters, blowing a deep hole in the city's finances.
The repeal of the tax is to be rammed through Albany next week
because both Republicans and Democrats think it will help them win
a heated state Senate contest in Rockland and Orange Counties.
Democrats are also eager to embarrass Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. They
want Giuliani, a Republican, to beg to keep the tax on the very
suburbanites whose support he will be seeking in his campaign for
United States Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The commuter tax, enacted in 1966 and raised in 1971, is paid by
nearly 800,000 people who work in the city but live outside it.
Since these workers benefit enormously from the city's police,
fire, sanitation and transportation services, it is only logical
for them to shoulder part of the burden of paying for them. The tax
is only about an eighth of the income tax that city residents pay,
and it has remained stable while city taxes have gone up.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani says he opposed repealing the commuter tax, but he has
been slow to mount a full-scale attack. This, however, is no time
to let political niceties stand in the way of the city's interests.
If the commuter tax is repealed for everyone, it would cost the
city $360 million in revenues. If it is repealed only for residents
of suburbs in New York state, it would cost $208 million. A partial
repeal would also be challenged as discriminating against New
Jersey and Connecticut residents.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled state Senate took the initiative on
the tax, and plans to pass it next week. Joseph Bruno, the Senate
majority leader, supports Giuliani's Senate campaign and may think
he is doing the mayor a favor by handing out a bonus to
suburbanites. Giuliani must say ``no thanks'' and threaten a legal
challenge to the legislature's acting in defiance of the city
council. He should also make his opposition clear to the
Democratic-controlled assembly and to Gov. George Pataki, who no
doubt is amused at the mayor's political predicament but should
still side with him in opposing the repeal. Everyone in this battle
right now is playing games. But if the tax is canceled, New York
City will be in trouble. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
