<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOAN-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
33 CHARGED IN BANKER'S FRAUDULENT LOAN SCHEME
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He was a former loan officer at NatWest with a
master's degree in finance. But federal prosecutors say that Gary
J. Confredo became a sham artist, helping clients who lacked credit
_ including a part-time dancer at Chippendales _ to obtain $20
million in illegal loans from 11 banks.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on his own expertise, Confredo arranged to have phony
loan documents prepared and submitted on behalf of his clients, who
owned plumbing and heating companies, an adult bookstore, a law
firm, a dental lab, a caviar bar and a delicatessen, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story on the street,'' said an associate of Confredo's,
according to court records, was that he ``could get a loan for a
homeless person.''
</P>
<P>
   Confredo, 36, was ultimately arrested, and pleaded guilty in
February to five counts, including bank fraud and making false
statements. He is in jail awaiting sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, federal prosecutors in Manhattan said they had
charged 33 others in the scheme, including business owners who had
obtained the illegal loans and three accountants and one lawyer who
assisted in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the charges, U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White said that
many of the illegal loans went quickly into default, resulting in
losses to the institutions of $10 million to $15 million. The
defendants had used the money in some cases to pay for such
personal expenses as home improvements, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally hundreds of false loan applications were made to New
York area banks,'' Ms. White said, including more than 100
fraudulent applications to Citibank alone.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities Wednesday displayed copies of documents that
they said were altered as part of the scheme. One bank statement,
for example, showed that a photography business in Melville, N.Y.,
had bounced checks and that at the end of May 1997 had a negative
balance of $157, a Federal prosecutor, Jennifer M. Moore, said.
</P>
<P>
   But records show that one of Confredo's associates doctored the
document in a computer, creating a forged version showing no
bounced checks and a positive balance of about $27,000. The owner
eventually was granted a $75,000 loan, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said in court papers that Confredo shared his
expertise with others, including his ``understanding of how to
abuse the commercial loan process.''
</P>
<P>
   His associates referred to him as ``the Wizard,'' said Kevin
Donovan, of the FBI's New York office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confredo repeatedly boasted to his business associates that
crime pays,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Confredo's lawyer, Howard R. Leader, had no comment Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
